   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SONOMA-WINES (Sonoma, Calif.) _ Residents of Sonoma County will
say this much about their neighbor to the west: Napa is better
known and has better restaurants. That said, they wouldn't dream of
living there. They would have to give up their wild and spectacular
coastline. They would have to abandon their magnificent fruits and
vegetables, superb cheeses and foie gras, prize-winning olive oil,
succulent lamb and pristine oysters. They would have to leave the
low-key atmosphere that attracts fascinating (some would say
eccentric) characters. And, of course, they would have to give up
bragging rights on those Sonoma pinot noirs and chardonnays, wines
they would put up against Napa's any day. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DOGS-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Manhattan isn't a particularly
dog-friendly place, but there are a surprising number of
restaurants that welcome dogs _ with bowls of water, biscuits,
special menus, reserved tables and more. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   GAS-MEGA-GRILLS (Undated) _ It seems like every day the mail
carrier delivers another brochure touting a new gas mega-grill.
These gleaming stainless steel behemoths, which can cost as much as
$5,000, are nothing less than fantasy kitchens reconfigured for
outdoor use. There are just two problems. First, these grills are
no fun; and second, you can cook better food on an oven rack
perched on three bricks over a charcoal fire. By John Willoughby &AMP;
Chris Schlesinger.
</P>
<P>
   WATERMELON-DRINKS (Undated) _ For hot weather, Watermelon
drinks. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   FANCY-FOOD-SHOW (New York) _ Chefs may want to get you into
their restaurants, but now more than ever, they have their eye on
your pantry shelf as well. The chefs, and their product lines, were
out in force at this year's Fancy Food Show, the annual trade show.
By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
