<HEADER>
A5001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMER-EDUC-ART-2TAKES     07-01 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMER-EDUC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEADING A CASE FOR THE CHILD: EDUCATOR STRESSES DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Miss., Ala., Ind., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (af)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ To this day, the winnowing process from his
own youth still gnaws at him: how he was able to make it, while so
many equally intelligent peers who grew up in less nurturing
environments could not.
</P>
<P>
   That memory informed the educational model that made James Comer
one of the most celebrated school innovators of his time: his
approach begins and ends with the notion that, rather than
intelligence and will, the experiences children have growing up,
good and bad, determine who wins and loses in school and life.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this should be James Comer's moment, with
education near the top of the national agenda and a White House
passionately committed to his view of it. He is a hero to many
education advocates, not the least of them Hillary Rodham Clinton,
who introduced him at a recent tribute and symposium at the Yale
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   They were there to celebrate the 30th anniversary of his School
Development Program, a nonprofit project of the Child Study Center
at the Yale Medical School that advises schools on the use of his
theories.
</P>
<P>
   But at 63, Comer (pronounced KOH-mer) finds himself not so much
a symbol of how education has changed as a marker of where the
fault lines are drawn. He is one of the most consistent critics of
the ascendant countermodels for school reform: tougher standards,
high-stakes tests and experiments with privatization or vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   For all the success of his approach, which is used in more than
450 schools in 17 states and several foreign countries, Comer is at
least as aware of the winds blowing away from him as the ones
wafting in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, my voice has been heard, and I have had some
influence,'' he said, reflecting on his career at his office at the
Yale Medical School, where he is associate dean and a professor of
child psychiatry. ``But in the one area that's most critical, the
role of child development, people are still not paying attention.
Our moment is going to come, but right now most of the attention
seems to be on things like charters and vouchers that don't do
anything for the vast majority of children.''
</P>
<P>
   Few educators have looked so hard and long at how children's
lives relate to educational achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before it was a major field of study, Dr. Comer recognized
that learning in school, before school and after school is tied to
a child's level of development,'' Mrs. Clinton said in her
introductory remarks. ``Before charter schools or magnet schools
became household words, Dr. Comer was busy designing schools in
which parents were involved in everything from curricular
development to social activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Comer's education model centers on the idea that many children,
minority-group children in particular, struggle in school because
their level of social, intellectual and cultural development is far
behind that of more affluent students.
</P>
<P>
   Schools, he says, have to focus on the developmental needs of
children, or even the best teachers and most sophisticated
curriculum will not be effective. That means bringing counselors,
psychologists, parents and others into the learning process _
rather than just depending on teachers _ and tailoring lessons to a
child's background.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at Isadore Wexler Community School in inner-city
New Haven, one school Comer works with, Shelia Brantley
incorporates child development into her third-grade reading
curriculum. Thus, the program is not just about reading. It might
include a trip to the supermarket so students who have never seen
an avocado can learn what the word means, a lesson suburban
children might not need.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions are predicated on the children's learning to
communicate complex thoughts and ideas they might not be exposed to
at home. And the whole teaching and learning experience is based on
social skills _ listening, sharing information, expressing clear
points of view _ that transcend the individual lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The schools Comer works with are organized around three
principles: problem solving rather than blaming; consensus
decision-making, and collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it sounds uncontroversial. But Comer's program begins
with the unfashionable idea that in a country of growing
disparities between the haves and have nots, education has to begin
by addressing the disparate needs and backgrounds of children so
they can learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even my friends in education still begin by talking curriculum
and instruction,'' he said. ``All those things are important, but
where's the kid? What's the kid like? What's going on with the kid?
All of American education has left the development of the child out
of it. We may pay it lip service, but for a whole number of
reasons, the needs of the kid get ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   His perspective in many ways goes against the ingrained American
belief that each individual can determine his or her own destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest problem with education is we see learning as a
function of intelligence and will,'' he said. ``If you have the
intelligence and will, you will learn. If you don't, you won't.
Well, it's not that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   To critics, particularly advocates of vouchers, charter schools
and tougher standards and tests, Comer's agenda, while well
meaning, is not systematic enough to create real change in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a soft kind of model that's very Clintonesque,'' said
Chester Finn, a prominent education analyst and a senior fellow at
the Hudson Institute. ``It says things a lot of educators find
appealing, but I'm not persuaded that it can be counted on to
produce improved student achievement. It doesn't change the power.
It doesn't change the control of resources.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't change the ground rules. It doesn't change who's in
charge. It doesn't change what we mean by a public school, and it
doesn't have the combination of uniform standards, tests and
consequences I believe you need for real change.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that there were approaches other than Comer's richly
empathetic model to help inner-city students. He cited the ideas of
Thaddeus Lott, a Houston principal recently profiled in Policy
Review magazine who uses ability grouping, intensive drill, rote
learning and other traditional teaching methods to extraordinary
result at his Wesley Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   Comer is singularly unimpressed by most of the ideas advocated
by Finn and others. Unlike some educators, who see charter schools
as a way to develop distinctive, innovative schools, he sees them
as little different from voucher proposals that he thinks would
skim off the best students, leaving most to fester in schools that
have been largely written off.
</P>
<P>
   Comer likes to cite his life story as a microcosm of his view of
education. His mother grew up poor in Mississippi, with little
formal schooling but a passionate belief in the importance of
education. His father, a steel mill laborer, grew up in rural
Alabama with a sixth-grade education. Their five children went on
to earn 13 bachelor's and graduate degrees between them.
</P>
<P>
   Comer grew up in East Chicago, Ind., in an integrated
neighborhood with integrated schools. He may have been poorer than
some of his white classmates, but his parents were able to
inculcate the values, attitudes and discipline that he believes
allowed him to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   It taught him two lessons. The first was that education was the
key to success and was open to everyone. The second was that
influences on children mean more for their chances of success than
does innate intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Comer received his undergraduate degree from Indiana University
and his medical degree from Howard University. But his work with
poor communities soon convinced him he could have the most impact
by working with schools.
</P>
<P>
   Like proponents of most reform models, he can provide research
showing dramatically improved results, like the McLeansville Middle
School in Guilford County, N.C., where the percentage of eighth
graders reading at a competent level rose from 65 to 85 between
1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But he says that of the schools he has worked with, only about a
third had dramatic results, a third showed some modest improvement
and a third were little changed.
</P>
<P>
   But all in all, he says, those are pretty good results.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play baseball those results will put you in the Hall of
Fame, and this game's tougher than baseball,'' he said. ``You're
working against the very undesirable condition of the society:
racism, economic adversity, social marginalization, the effects on
parents and teachers of dealing with kids who people believe have
no future. That's what schools serving low-income and minority kids
are always up against. You bat .333 against that, and you feel
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Comer has handed off much of the daily operation of the program
to others, like the executive director, Edward T. Joyner. But he is
not slowing down. He continues to expand his activities.
</P>
<P>
   He now works with districts as well as individual schools. He
has joined Project Atlas, a new effort in which a consortium of
theorists advises schools on a range of issues. The consultants are
Comer; Theodore Sizer, the retired head of the Coalition for
Essential Schools; Howard Gardner, the Harvard education theorist,
and Janet Whitlaw of the Education Development Center.
</P>
<P>
   Schools can tap parts of all four theorists' approaches. These
include Comer's ideas on how to draw diverse influences into a
school's daily life; Gardner's on tests and student assessments;
Sizer's on approaches to learning and curriculum, and Ms. Whitlaw's
on teacher preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Comer began his work with the idea that education reform was a
long, slow struggle. Nothing in his career has led him to think
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mentality of the moment is to look for the quick fix,'' he
said. ``But if we try to gloss over the depth, severity and
difficulty of the problems, we will never address the depth,
severity and difficulty of the problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
