<HEADLINE>
UNITED WAY OF TRI-STATE SEES FUND-RAISING SURGE AFTER 6-YEAR SLIDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (nk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reversing years of declining support, United Way of
Tri-State will report Tuesday that it raised $103 million in the
last year, up 4.5 percent over the previous year after adjusting
for inflation, the first real increase this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The growth is the first since United Way of America was rocked
by a scandal six years ago that sent its president to prison for
stealing charity funds and the local United Ways saw their support
drop.
</P>
<P>
   Donations have also suffered from downsizing at major
corporations, slow wage growth and less interest in giving to
health and human services agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the increase, contributions by the 137 large companies
and their workers in the New York metropolitan region that give
through Tri-State is still 15 percent below the 1991-92 figure,
when pledges totaled $121.4 million, adjusted for inflation as are
all figures reported here.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in pledges should translate into small increases in
allocations in the next 12 months to many of the health and human
services agencies that depend on United Way for support.
</P>
<P>
   Typically about 6 percent of pledges are not fulfilled, often
because people switch jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Tri-State is the largest of the 1,300 United Ways, but is little
known because it does not directly allocate money to agencies.
Instead, Tri-State divides the money it raises among 30 local
United Ways in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut, with 41.5
percent of the money going to United Way of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Wendt, chairman of the 1997-98 Tri-State campaign, noted
that the 4.5 percent increase in pledges is significantly higher
than the 3 percent average increase reported so far by 11 other
large United Ways across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt said he would like to see an increase in giving by the
high-income residents of New York City, including those employed on
Wall Street, where bonus checks are booming but giving through the
United Way is modest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wendt pointed to one investment bank that was generous, Merrill
Lynch, ``which had more $10,000 givers than any other company in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendt, the chief executive of GE Capital, a financial subsidiary
of General Electric Corporation based in Stamford, Conn., set a
goal for his company and its employees of $1.35 million, 20 percent
above the previous year. Pledges exceeded the goal at $1.43
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Tri-State results, and the preliminary figures from the New
York City campaign, indicate that the federated fund-raising
organization is doing much better at winning support here than in
the nation's second- and third-largest metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, United Way Inc. in Los Angeles reported
pledges of $59 million, up a half of 1 percent over last fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Giving to the United Way serving Los Angeles County is still 46
percent below its peak seven years ago, when pledges totaled $108.8
million, and has been essentially flat since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Donors may have been turned off this year by a radio advertising
campaign that chided Los Angeles residents for spending money on
breast implants and caffe lattes, but not on gifts to United Way.
</P>
<P>
   In Ventura County, a booming area northwest of Los Angeles,
allocations to 59 member agencies had to be slashed 30 percent in
May because United Way of Ventura County's deficit had grown to
$1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts came on top of a 7.5 percent cut the previous
September.
</P>
<P>
   In the third-largest city, the Chicago United Way/Crusade of
Mercy raised $95.1 million, up 3 percent from the previous year,
but still 22 percent below its $121.8 million peak six years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
