u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TAXI-INDUSTRY-665&AMP;     07-01 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXI-INDUSTRY-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXI FLEETS FIGHT NEW RULES, BUT FIND INFLUENCE EBBING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW and ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As City Councilman Noach Dear geared up last fall to
run for Congress, a group of taxi executives wrote a letter to its
members urging them to contribute generously to ``our good
friend,'' saying that without Dear's help, ``our taxi industry
might not exist today as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Dear held a fund-raising dinner two weeks ago, many
taxi and livery owners stayed away, fuming that the Brooklyn
Democrat had all but abandoned them in their time of need.
</P>
<P>
   As the owners of yellow cabs and car services fight to reverse
tough new safety standards imposed by the Giuliani administration,
they have found that the political might they built with generous
campaign contributions and powerful lobbyists has waned.
</P>
<P>
   With taxi accidents having increased by 40 percent since 1990,
taxi safety has attracted a rare amount of public attention, making
it more risky for politicians such as Dear, chairman of the City
Council Transportation Committee, to defend the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's best hope now lies in court, where it is
challenging the regulations, which include sharply higher insurance
requirements and more severe penalties for bad drivers. A state
judge has indicated that he might nullify the rules as early as
this week because, he said, the Taxi and Limousine Commission
violated state open-meeting laws when it approved the rules in May.
</P>
<P>
   While the industry's declining influence could be temporary _
the result of public attention to recent accidents and electoral
politics _ it is hurting taxi owners' ability to respond to Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. Since Giuliani proposed the new regulations in
April, Dear has declined even to hold a hearing for the owners to
air their complaints, much less help them combat the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the industry is disappointed in the City Council in
general,'' said Neil Greenbaum, a medallion broker who helped form
the New York City Committee for Taxi Safety, a top industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Dear, whose committee oversees the taxi industry, has been its
most visible champion. An analysis of campaign finance records
shows that he has banked $170,000 in donations over the last five
years from taxi and livery interests, including tens of thousands
of dollars that came in just as he took steps to help the industry.
</P>
<P>
   City Council Speaker Peter F. Vallone, who is running for
governor, and his political organizations have gathered more than
$55,000 over the same period from people affiliated with taxi
operations.
</P>
<P>
   But both Dear and Vallone are caught up in their own political
races at a time when cabbies are not especially popular. Dear is
also seeking the mayor's endorsement in the hotly contested race to
succeed Rep. Charles Schumer _ who is seeking the Democratic
nomination for the U.S. Senate _ and taxi executives complain that
Dear will not do anything to jeopardize that support.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum and his family have contributed $18,000 to Dear's
races since 1993, and his group sent out the fund-raising appeal
for Dear last fall. But, Greenbaum said last week, ``I don't know
if we can count on him as much as before.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear said he tried to mediate between the mayor and the industry
to ``help save havoc'' when taxi drivers were holding
demonstrations last month, but he was forced to back off by some of
the most vehement driver groups.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the campaign donations, he said, ``My support for
the industry or against the industry is not based on who supports
me or who doesn't support me.'' He added, ``I am no one's stooge,''
and said that he supports some, but not all, of the new
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel F. Del Valle, a former Taxi and Limousine Commission
chairman who is now a lawyer for a coalition of car-service owners,
said he believed that ``the problem that the industry really has
goes beyond politics and is partly just public relations'' on
safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have an image problem they've been ignoring,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Del Valle also said that some taxi executives were incensed that
Giuliani, who got $50,000 from the industry in his re-election
campaign last year, would go after them so hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these guys are really Republicans who supported
Giuliani,'' Del Valle said. ``They gave him their support because
he was for law and order and he'd make the `bums' on welfare go to
work. So they are in a state of shock that he is coming after them.
They've found that their vision of who the bums are _ and
Giuliani's _ didn't quite jibe.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear, 44, is widely known as one of the Council's most
aggressive fund-raisers, and also was a top national fund-raiser
for President Clinton's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   City records show that Dear has often accepted donations from
businesses that his committee regulates, including bus companies
and tow-truck operators. Taxi and livery interests have been
particularly generous, donating $90,000 to his City Council
campaigns since mid-1993 and about $80,000 of the $1.2 million he
has raised for his current House race.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the donations, Dear said there have been a number of
times when his actions upset parts of the taxi industry. He noted
that he endorsed Giuliani's sale of 400 new medallions, approved in
1996, and fought for more taxi inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also stood up for taxi owners. For instance, when the
taxi commission passed a rule in 1996 requiring medallion owners to
buy new cars every four years at most, Greenbaum's group appealed
to Dear. He responded quickly, introducing a bill to prohibit the
commission from disqualifying a taxi based on its age or prior use.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, records show, Greenbaum and other taxi
executives contributed more than $15,000 to Dear, who said his goal
was simply to ``help the small car owners, the mom-and-pop guys''
who could not afford new cars.
</P>
<P>
   The commission eventually agreed to let independently owned cabs
stay on the road for five years instead of four and made other
concessions that saved the owners an estimated $20 million. ``He
made it livable,'' Greenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum and Andrew Murstein, Alvin Murstein's son, were among
the sponsors of a June 17 fund-raising dinner. Giuliani was the
featured speaker, and industry executives said they had to scramble
to find fewer than a dozen taxi owners who were willing to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say their contributions are not bringing results,''
Andrew Murstein said. ``It just shows that money helps you buy
access, not results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
