<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-BICKLEY-AZR &LR;      07-01 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY SAMMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO - The greatest month ever has come to an end, and just
like that, Sammy Sosa has joined the ghostbusters. Another
candidate, another face for the microscope, another slugger
enlisted to chase down Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   No. 33 disappeared Tuesday night, deep into the Wrigley Field
bleachers, halting a minor drought and rekindling the imagination.
Maybe it won't be Paul Bunyan in St. Louis or Junior launching
bombs up in that user-friendly garage in Seattle. Maybe history
will belong to the smiling Cub who pounds his chest and blows
kisses to the fans, a kid who didn't pick up a bat until he was 14
and now looks like Roberto Clemente on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa smiles. Already, he is getting a little squeamish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only guy who can break the mark is Mark McGwire,'' Sosa
said. ``He's the man. I'm just another kid trying to play good.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Sosa sat at his locker, unwrapping gifts,
fully aware that no other man has ever posted a freak streak like
this. He is finishing up an unprecedented barrage, a month where
he's turned 20 baseballs into souvenirs. And as he peers at his
latest Player of the Week bounty _ the second Bulova watch he's
received in 14 days _ he is getting a whiff of the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the air can get pretty thin when you're flying after
legends. McGwire has become edgy over the circus tent of batting
practice. Ken Griffey Jr. won't partake in the All Star Game's
longball contest, fearing it will throw his swing out of whack. And
as Sosa keeps up an improbable pace, he is staring at his watch,
hoping he can suspend time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't try to compare me to anyone,'' Sosa pleaded. ``If I
start listening to all that stuff, it might take me out of my plan.
We've got three more months. I've got to keep going strong.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Sosa is seduced by the attention, tantalized by the
challenge. And there is little doubt he can make a strong push if
the pressure doesn't smother him first.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Sosa homered 40 times in 124 games. The following
spring training, he hit bombs with such regularity that he was
asked about the prospect of 60 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty?'' Sosa answered. ``Why not 70?''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's breakthrough season, it seems, was simply delayed. Last
year, the Cubs roared to an 0-14 start, and Sosa was exposed in a
lineup with little protection. He was distracted by contract
negotiations, which finally resulted in a four-year, $42.5 million
extension. And while he finished respectably, the season was a
wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time up,'' Sosa said. ``I was trying to hit two home runs
with one swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sosa has reached the halfway point in staggering fashion.
Aside from McGwire, no other National Leaguer has reached 30 home
runs by July 1. Since May 25, he has hit 10 home runs in a
nine-game span . . . twice.
</P>
<P>
   With another hot streak, Sosa could easily produce 29 home runs
in his final 80 games.
</P>
<P>
   But for a kid who once worked for $4 a day selling orange juice,
cleaning shoes and washing cars in the Dominican Republic, the
spotlight is getting a little warm.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he told a Nike representative he didn't like his new
batting gloves, requesting the old model he wore out during his
torrid streak. The Nike rep smiled, unwilling to tell Sosa the old
model has been out of date for a year. He was so desperate to keep
the flame burning that he's been experimenting with different bats,
the latest belonging to pitcher Mark Clark.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed with his latest missile, and clearly, Sosa's
streaky nature could work for him as much as it does against him.
He has 35 more games at Wrigley Field, nine more against
Diamondbacks pitching and a four-game set on tap in Colorado. Harry
Caray is in heaven, the Cubs are overdue for some good karma and
Sosa has the tools to make it interesting in September.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Sosa is ready for some elite company. A few months ago,
the president of the Dominican Republic asked Sosa if he could talk
Michael Jordan into a little visit. Armed with a video of his
homeland, Sosa approached Jordan, and the global icon actually
seems interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got everything ready, and I've got hope that he's going
to do it,'' Sosa said. ``I'll play golf if he wants. But I'm not
any good. I practiced once and hit everything foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his day job, where for one magical month, everything has
been straight and long and out of reach. And with some luck, maybe
he'll be the man of history, a man who won't need Jordan to boost
the native morale. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
