<HEADER>
A5025 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENKINS-5SFIXES &LR;      07-01 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-5S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS WOULD EMBRACE MORE COLORFUL GAME 
BY   
 BRUCE JENKINS
</HEADLINE>
 FIXES   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ It's either the end of the world or the
dawning of a new day in tennis, take your choice. Pete Sampras has
put out the call for Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't really Pete's idea. Pete's idea is to play
emotion-free tennis, check a few racket strings, then move
unnoticed through the crowd. If every other player acted the same
way, he wouldn't mind at all.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras can be sensitive to the growing criticism of men's
tennis. He really doesn't give a damn, to be honest, but if the
subject comes up in a press conference, he'll dive in. He had just
beaten Frenchman Sebastien Grosjean 6-3, 6-4, 6-4 on Wimbledon's
Court 1 Tuesday when he was asked about the marketing of tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the tour could do a lot better job,'' he said. ``Nike
has really marketed Andre (Agassi) and myself over the years, but
it's nothing like the NBA or some of the other major sports. It's
sad but true: The game needs a little controversy. It needs a
little bit of a Dennis Rodman kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, for one thing, there's only one Dennis Rodman ``kind of
guy.'' There's not much middle ground between Jan Siemerink and an
orange-haired guy wearing eye makeup. But this is a huge
breakthrough: An active player addressing the abject boredom of
today's game. The No. 1 player in the world, for heaven's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game was successful,'' said Sampras, ``you had four
of the guys in the top five playing themselves in the semis and
finals of all the Slams. They were all different personalities.
</P>
<P>
   And they all hated each other.''
</P>
<P>
   So we need a little more hatred?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, ``a hatred, or whatever you want to call it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a vague reference Sampras made to the tennis boom of
the late '70s and early '80s. He was definitely talking about Jimmy
Connors and John McEnroe; filling out the list of four, you'd guess
Bjorn Borg and Ivan Lendl, or perhaps Guillermo Vilas. Strictly
speaking, they didn't all hate each other. But there was a
palpable, contagious tension in the air _ the kind you don't get
from Davide Sanguinetti-Francisco Clavet or Richard Krajicek-Wayne
Ferreira, two of Tuesday's matches with quarterfinal spots at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   There is an interesting progression at work here. First, a few
writers and TV broadcasters popped off about the men's game. They
were ridiculed as outsiders who didn't really love the sport. But
then some key figures weighed in. ``Spectators love emotion,'' said
Boris Becker, ``but most of the players now are like machines. They
show nothing. They have forgotten that it's not just a tennis court
they are playing on. It's a stage as well.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ilie Nastase, ``As the game progressed out of the
wooden-racket era, the power game ruined the entertainment. And the
game was a lot more human when I was playing. These guys today put
no passion into it. For me it is the difference between the cinema
and the theater. Give me the drama of the theater any time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody's not a character,'' said McEnroe, ``you can't
expect him to become one. But the game certainly could use a few
more characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Say one thing for Sampras: He's been so good in his pursuit of
history-making tennis, he has worn down the opposition. He's amused
by the journalists who once called him boring, and now praise him
to the skies, because ``I pretty much haven't changed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In subtle but significant ways, Sampras has helped improve his
image. Fans have seen him clowning around on the practice court,
doing impressions of other players. He has jumped into ESPN's
clever series of star-athlete advertisements. As opposed to truly
boring guys like Lendl and Michael Chang, he'll joke around and
crack wry smiles during interviews.
</P>
<P>
   His classy, no-nonsense style also happens to work in some
quarters. ``My idols growing up were Rod Laver, Arthur Ashe and Roy
Emerson,'' says the top-flight broadcaster Mary Carillo. ``I don't
remember them being laugh riots. It didn't hurt the game. Bjorn
Borg wasn't exactly ready for the Copacabana. But everyone seems to
think that Borg leaving the game was one of the great tragedies of
our sport.''
</P>
<P>
   For American tennis fans, it really comes down to this: Tennis
isn't that cool any more _ not to the point where kids can't wait
to find a racket _ and the world-class power has shifted to other
countries. There are no up-and-coming American prodigies in the
men's game, either. So we take the game as we find it. As it stands
this morning, the Wimbledon field has a dashing Brit (Tim Henman),
a leaping Czech (Petr Korda), two unknowns (Sanguinetti, Siemerink)
and three can't-spell-it guys with really big serves (Krajicek,
Mark Philippoussis, Goran Ivanisevic).
</P>
<P>
   To put it another way, Wimbledon needs Pete Sampras. And so does
the sport of tennis. He and Rodman just might make a nutty doubles
team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
