<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK EXTENSION TALKS STALL  
 GAP BETWEEN COYOTES, STAR REMAINS VERY WIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes efforts to reach a contract extension with
captain Keith Tkachuk have apparently hit a stone wall as talks
halted on Tuesday, according to Tkachuk's Boston-based agent, Bob
Murray.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments, the team obtained veteran center Mike
Sullivan from the expansion Nashville Predators for a seventh-round
draft pick in next year's NHL Entry Draft and also informed veteran
defenseman Michel Petit that it won't pick up the option year of
his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith said Tuesday that he met
with Murray two or three times during last weekend's Entry Draft in
Buffalo, and the parties aren't close to an agreement on a
five-year contract extension. Tkachuk has two years left on his
5-year, $17.2 million contract, which calls for him to earn $2.8
million and $3 million in the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk is seeking $8 million per season, a salary on a par with
the new contracts signed by Paul Kariya, Joe Sakic and Eric
Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   A source said the Coyotes' offer was between $5 million and $6
million per season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met in Buffalo several times and we have a significant
gap,'' said Smith, refusing to discuss financial terms. ``We've
talked a number of times and have been unable to come close to an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say negotiations have ended. We made a good offer,
and Keith and his agent rejected it. So we've taken it off the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has said several times that the team has three options
with Tkachuk: make him honor the final two years of his contract;
reach a contract extension; or trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the team now is intensifying up efforts to trade
Tkachuk, Smith emphatically answered, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray also refused to discuss numbers, saying only that there
is a substantial gap and that Smith told him Tuesday that talks
have ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've run into a road block,'' Murray said. ``We're very
disappointed in the route the team is taking by calling off
negotiations at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel Bobby is not living up to his word when he promised in
good faith to get the extension done before next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith refuted Murray's contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of our offer was extremely high,'' he said. ``There
was never any understanding that Keith would be treated as a Group
II or Group III free agent. We made an outstanding offer and it was
rejected. Keith expects to be treated like a player who has played
out his contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Tkachuk is not prepared to demand a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith wants to play in Phoenix, he has made that very clear,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk staged a brief holdout before last season, sitting out
the Coyotes' preseason games. He returned when Smith said he would
attempt to work out a contract extension after the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30-year-old Sullivan, the Coyotes gained some depth at
center and left wing, specifically on the team's third or fourth
lines, and insurance against the possibility that free-agent
centers Bob Corkum and Mark Janssens might leave.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum becomes a restricted Group II free agent and Janssens
becomes an unrestricted Group III free agent today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real character player,'' Smith said. ``He's a fast
player who will give us more speed, and he's good on special teams,
like penalty-killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, 6-foot-2, 190 pounds is a native of Marshfield, Mass.
He had five goals and 13 assists in 77 games with the Bruins last
season. He has played in 453 NHL games with Calgary, San Jose and
Boston, collecting 41 goals, 62 assists and 103 points with 137
penalty minutes since entering the NHL in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The well-traveled Petit has played for a record 10 teams during
his 16-year NHL career. He had four goals and two assists in 32
games last year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
