<HEADER>
A5028 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SFCHRON     07-01 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS ROLLS INTO QUARTERFINALS 
BY BRUCE JENKINS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ She's out there winning with about half of
the Wimbledon tools she possesses. Even with that eagle's wingspan
and athletic grace, Venus Williams plays more of a Chris
Evert-Tracy Austin type of tennis. Nobody's going to change her
mind, either. And if she gets to the finals here, nobody will even
bring it up.
</P>
<P>
   Now fully comfortable with the grass, the setting and the
pressure, Williams hammered out a 6-3, 6-1 victory over Virginia
Ruano Pascual Tuesday, avenging the loss (actually a retirement) by
her sister, Serena, to the Spanish woman the day before. Meanwhile,
Jana Novotna was completely outclassing the dangerous Irina Spirlea
6-2, 6-3 in another fourth-round match.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening conversation around the All England Club, there
was little mention of either match. It's all about the
quarterfinals now: Williams, looking so menacing in just her second
Wimbledon, against Novotna, who has been hanging around here
forever.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of that match will probably get Martina Hingis in the
semifinals. Hingis dismissed Thailand's Tamarine Tanasugarn with a
haughty flair 6-3, 6-2 to earn a quarterfinal spot against Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario, a 3-6, 6-3, 6-2 winner over Dominique Van Roost of
Belgium. Hingis is looking and acting the champion, in command of
all she surveys. Sanchez Vicario, never a Wimbledon winner in 11
tries, had the dubious distinction of trailing 0-5 to Van Roost in
the first set.
</P>
<P>
   So if you are looking ahead, you are seeing Hingis, Novotna or
Williams in the final, almost definitely against Monica Seles. The
next obstacle for Seles is Natasha Zvereva, who has had her fun
(shockingly, over a sub-par Steffi Graf) but has never reached the
semifinals of any Grand Slam. The other quarterfinal in Seles' half
of the draw, Lindsay Davenport vs. Nathalie Tauziat, is seen to
have little significance on any front.
</P>
<P>
   When the patrons of Wimbledon last saw Williams, they had to
look quickly. She was gone in a flash _ losing to someone named
Magdalena Grzybowska in last year's first round _ then pretended it
never happened. A year's passing has done wonders for Williams, who
now says, ``I'm at the point where I can do this now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's startling to realize what Williams could be doing out
there. Heady old veterans like Martina Navratilova and Chris Evert
shudder at the prospect of Williams, a catlike 6-foot-2, making her
living at the net. ``She'd just throw a blanket over it,'' said
Evert. ``She would be so difficult to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who remember the '50s and '60s, when individual styles
made such a difference in tennis, there are daydreams of Williams
hitting a one-handed backhand: Slicing a few, then unloading the
topspin, and most importantly, having that one-handed shot as a
volley weapon behind her thundering serve.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Williams plays a one-note game. A scintillating note
of high resonance but solitary all the same. If this were baseball,
Williams would be Bob Gibson throwing nothing but fastballs. In
basketball, Grant Hill with only a 15-foot jumper. But that's
tennis in the '90s. Like most every other players of her
generation, Williams grew up on the baseline, and that is all there
is to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never give up the two-handed backhand,'' she says, to
the dismay of tennis connoisseurs, and it is probably too late for
her to change. The decision must come in the formative years, and
as Pete Sampras could tell you, it requires some courage. Sampras
was 14 when he made the switch, and until he got comfortable, he
was routinely thrashed by his junior opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Williams certainly has no idea what to expect against Novotna.
In a bizarre admission, she said she only looks at one name _ her
sister, Serena _ when a draw is announced. Other than that, she has
no idea who she is going to play until the matchup is set.
``Sometimes even then I don't know,'' she says with a coy smile.
``My mom's like, `Venus, who are you playing tomorrow?' And I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Novotna, who has played Williams just once (a victory in
Moscow last year), there is mostly relief about Wednesday's match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm happier that Venus is not a serve-and-volleyer,
because she really has a huge serve and if she came in all the
time, it would be rather difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
