<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPANIA SHOWS SOLID SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vladimir Stepania talked softly. At times, his mind
strained to understand the language spoken to him.
</P>
<P>
   Stepania, though, knew some English. The Sonics' first-round
draft pick from Slovenia was abreast enough with the United States
and NBA to say ``I'd rather play here.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be very little doubt about Stepania's ability to
compete in the NBA. If his past four days in Seattle proved
anything, he is definitely not an ordinary rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-11{ Slovenian performed drills and a little
half-court action with Jelani McCoy and Rashard Lewis, the Sonics'
second-round picks. It would be safe to say Stepania held his own
and even more accurate to say he dominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play in Europe, 70-75 games. It's not NBA, but it's
professional level. Those guys (McCoy and Lewis) don't have the
same experience,'' Stepania said Tuesday when introduced at the
Sonics' practice facility.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after downplaying his impressive workout, Stepania said
the magic phrase again:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to test myself in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepania, the 27th pick overall, has proven to be one of the
better foreign players not in the NBA. He started playing as a
9-year-old. Stepania says he dreads going back to his Slovenian
team because there are not very many challenges remaining for him
there. A wiry 236 pounds, he only needs to get stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got plenty of confidence after seeing him play,'' team
president Wally Walker said of the 22-year-old. ``He's very skilled
and very competitive. If not for the lockout, there's a great
chance of him playing for the Sonics this season.''
</P>
<P>
   There lies the only major problem with Stepania.
</P>
<P>
   His mobility, athleticism, ballhandling, shooting touch and
knowledge of the game will apparently translate to the NBA rather
well. He helped Union Olimpija Ljublana to another Slovenian
championship last season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stepania must figure out if it is worth helping out the
Sonics next season. He is under contract for the coming Slovenian
season. Training camp there begins July 20, and the season can run
through May.
</P>
<P>
   So, either Stepania negotiates a buyout with his team and signs
a contract with the Sonics, or he finishes his European commitment
so he can become a Sonic for the 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics could help Stepania buy the final year of his
contract, but they can offer no more than $250,000 assistance under
the old collective bargaining agreement. Stepania guessed he would
then owe roughly $400,000. But with the NBA's labor situation
unresolved and no relief in sight, Stepania is torn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I'll be there (at the Slovenian training camp).
I'm tired,'' Stepania said. ``And, they signed three players at my
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepania plays mostly power forward, although he can play
center. He is not big enough to defend a player such as Shaquille
O'Neal. Stepania's game is more like Charlotte's Vlade Divac,
according to Bill McKinney, the Sonics' vice president of
basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, who scouted Stepania the most, cited his overall
skills as a reason to be excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mobility and knowledge of the game are impressive,''
McKinney said. ``He's got very good low-post moves. . . . You know,
players get stronger in time. One of the things he'll weigh is the
(NBA) experience having the facilities to get stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepania said he expected to be among the top 20 players
drafted. When the first round ended, he went to bed despite his
agent's belief Seattle would take him.
</P>
<P>
   Stepania is mostly intrigued by the opportunity to compete
against the best players in the world. He's often played against
Americans on other European teams. However, Stepania understands
the difference in the NBA's style of play. He watched NBA games
once a week when they aired at roughly 5 a.m. back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``European ball is a lot of shooting and passing. There are a
lot of smart players there,'' Stepania said. ``The NBA is a lot of
dunking and running. I like the NBA more because of my athletic
ability. Maybe I don't play my first year, (but) I think I can play
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
