<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5030 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT-SUNS-     07-01 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT-SUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAPMAN SEES LABOR FEARS COME TRUE  
 SAYS MINIMUM-WAGE PLAYERS NEED BETTER DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The last time NBA owners and players went to war over
a collective bargaining agreement, Suns guard Rex Chapman was among
a group of so-called dissident players who attempted to decertify
the National Basketball Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   That's how strongly Chapman and about 130 other players believed
that the NBA's middle class would be hurt and that only superstars
would benefit under the proposed labor agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of 10 NBA seasons, Chapman turned out to be among
those hurt the most. He wound up playing the past two seasons for
the Suns while receiving only the league minimum for veteran
players _ an average of about $310,000 over the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   While superstars raked in tens of millions and rookies, despite
a new scale, continued to get big contracts, players such as
Chapman were squeezed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'd say that's true,'' Chapman said Tuesday as the
league prepared for the lockout that began at 9 p.m. Phoenix time.
``But I'll play for a few more years, and I'll be done. Whatever
deal we're under, I'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the more important thing is that a deal gets done so
the league survives for the guys coming in now who will play the
next 10 or 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough for everybody, so both sides just can't be
greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time, with the union split, the league and players
agreed to a ``no strike, no lockout'' policy that got them through
the 1994-95 season. A year later, there was a short lockout before
an agreement was reached. But it included a clause allowing owners
to reopen the agreement this summer if players received more than
51.8 percent of ``basketball-related revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid us,'' Chapman said. ``We gave them an opt-out. This is
the deal the owners wanted. They got almost everything they asked
for in the last agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (dissident players) wanted to decertify the union because
we could see it would be bad for the middle class, guys who weren't
superstars. We ended up giving them everything they wanted, and now
here we are and they want a different system.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to happen in two years? Are they going to want
another new deal?''
</P>
<P>
   The league has conceded that mistakes were made when the last
deal was negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik said Monday that at least 14
teams lost money last season. Commissioner David Stern said the
league as a whole was not profitable for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The players association, meanwhile, has questioned the league's
numbers. Players are willing to compromise on some issues, such as
a new rookie scale, but the players aren't willing to give the
owners a hard salary cap that would eliminate all exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The union has told the players to be prepared to miss paychecks
in November when the season is supposed to start _ something that
Chapman probably feels he has been doing for two years anyway.
Stern said Monday that the owners are prepared to take the lockout
into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a chance that will happen,'' Chapman said of
the possibility of losing games. ``I don't think there's a real
good chance, but in reality, it might. I don't think there's a real
sense of urgency in July. It's like the trading deadline. You hear
the rumors from November through January, but none of the deals are
made until the last two hours before the deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   But the owners may not feel any more urgency in November. They
have the luxury of a new television deal with NBC and Turner
Sports, which will pay teams even if games aren't played. Granik
said Monday, however, that the money would have to be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said he hopes NBA fans don't get the wrong idea about
the players' motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the deal the owners wanted,'' he said. ``I just hope
everything is well-thought-out this time. And I hope the fans
realize that we're not striking, we're being locked out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5031 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON &LR;      07-01 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES ARE PICKED OFF IN HUMBLING LOSS TO A'S 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ About all you could say after the A's got their first
look of the year at the Padres was: (begin ital) This (end ital) is
the team that's giving the Giants such a run for their money in the
National League West? You've got to be kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres did not compile a snappy 53-29 record going into
Tuesday's 12-10 A's win playing like this. They were part of a game
so all over the place that A's general manager Billy Beane resorted
to hiding in the shower until it was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed in the shower during the whole ninth inning,'' Beane
said. ``I didn't want to come out. I was peeking out at the TV. I'm
the cleanest guy in the world now.''
</P>
<P>
   _Five San Diego pitchers were pounded for 14 hits; they also
combined for 10 walks, tying a season high and leading to five A's
runs.
</P>
<P>
   _San Diego closer Trevor Hoffman walked three straight in the
eighth to force in two runs and give the A's a 10-8 lead, soon
augmented by Mike Blowers' two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   _The topsy-turvy game ended when the Padres had a runner picked
off on the cheesiest play in baseball. That's right, the game ended
when A's manager Art Howe called for the old
fake-to-third-throw-to-first play and Mike Fetters executed it well
enough to get pinch-runner Ruben Rivera, who was stuck between
first and second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't work very often,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy.
``They always say `It never works.' But Fetters has a good one. He
sold it.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the game was going, each team scoring at least two runs
per half-inning from the seventh onward, it had that sickening feel
of a game that would never end. Everyone figured, or feared, the
runs would keep coming across and keep coming across, stretching so
long the new Bay Bridge extension would be completed before it was
all over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like anyone was going to quit hitting,'' Howe
said. ``I guess that was the way it had to end. It didn't seem like
anybody wanted to make an out any more.''
</P>
<P>
   That was why Howe called for third-and-first play, with runners
at the corners and the Padres down by two runs. He guessed that
Bochy would have Rivera trying to take second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could smell it,'' Howe said, sniffing a couple of times for
emphasis. ``Boch is aggressive. The tying run was at first. I knew
he wanted to get him in scoring position. I played with Boch. Me
and Boch are close. I know he's always up to something.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe made the right move, but it almost didn't matter. Catcher
Mike Macfarlane relayed the sign to Fetters, who peered in and
thought ``What the heck?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of a little mess-up, too,'' Fetters said. ``I
didn't recognize the sign. Macfarlane put down the sign and I
stepped off. Then he had to gesture, so I knew what he wanted. It
was pretty funny that he had to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of bizarre. Guys are scoring and swinging the bat
and getting walked like that, and it ends on a pickoff. That's
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   That play was all that mattered in the end, even though just
about every A's player offered an important contribution. Ryan
Christenson raced into the right-center gap to snare Greg Vaughn's
drive in the sixth, and Rickey Henderson made his best throw of the
year to nail Ken Caminiti trying to score that inning on Wally
Joyner's fly ball in foul territory.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Voigt, the guy with the .129 average, picked up an RBI by
being one of the three straight Hoffman walked. Jason Giambi and
Matt Stairs both had multi-hit games. Billy Taylor (3-5) had his
first blown save since April 14 (he gave up four runs in 12/3
innings) but picked up the win anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
