<HEADER>
A5032 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI     07-01 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTGOMERY NEVER GAVE UP IN NFL OR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He wasn't a martyr and he wasn't an angel. Glenn
Montgomery was an athlete. He was a fighter, which was more than
enough.
</P>
<P>
   So when the accelerated atrophy of his muscles shut down his
body, when the disease named after Lou Gehrig started to claim its
insidious and fatal victory with such lightning-quick alarm,
Montgomery went down fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, 31, died Sunday with all of the pride, anger, honor
and dignity a fighter can muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a most courageous guy,'' said Dr. Stanley Appel,
director of neurology at Baylor University Hospital, where the
one-time Houston Oiler-turned-Seahawk was treated for amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about ALS is that the mind is perfectly intact as
the body melts away. The reason I feel so strongly about Glenn is
that he had such dignity and was such an inspiration, the way he
helped his teammates and friends to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   You would have expected nothing less from a 6-foot, 280-pound
battler, whose Oiler nickname ``Too Short'' spoke nothing of his
heart. He was a fifth-round draft pick, a guy who was never
supposed to play a lick in the NFL, but who wound up a starting
defensive lineman who could smash-mouth with the NFL's biggest,
meanest, most decorated offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other guys talked about being tough. Other guys acted tough.
But Glenn was just rock-hard,'' said Floyd Reese, the Oiler general
manager who was the team's defensive coach in 1989 when Montgomery
was drafted out of the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public looks at the sports world and sees athletes
who are so wealthy, and they think these guys never quite achieve,
that they could play better or harder or longer. But Glenn was an
over-achiever. He was the kind of player that a blue-collar guy
could appreciate for his total effort. He had such tremendous
intensity,'' Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   After seven seasons with Houston, Montgomery was traded to the
Seahawks in 1996. And during his first season in Seattle,
Montgomery was sidelined with a shoulder injury. But when the
shoulder did not heal, Seahawk trainers suspected it wasn't just
arthritis but the sign of something much worse. An MRI at the
University of Washington led to the diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery never bargained for something like ALS, a disease
where your body fails to clear an amino acid out of your muscles
and the result is atrophy and paralysis and, within 2-5 years,
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it took him awhile to accept that he had the
disease,'' said Seahawk quarterback Warren Moon, who grew close to
Montgomery as Oiler teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a lot of pride. He was in denial for a long time. It
took him quite awhile to believe his career was over and that this
thing was going to take over his body.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon said Montgomery met with several other doctors, hoping for
a different, better diagnosis. At the same time, Montgomery's
initial reaction to the disease caused tremendous strife between he
and his wife. Moon said Montgomery's failure to start making
adequate plans for what lay ahead led to tension and anger, and
finally, Montgomery moved out of his home, living instead with a
former college teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a proud guy. He didn't want his wife babying him
and crying, and that created problems,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you saw him, he would be very upbeat, just the way he was
before, always in a great mood, putting on the impression that
everything was OK. But you just knew it couldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Within months, signs of Montgomery's deterioration were obvious.
Last November, when the Seahawks played in New Orleans, Montgomery
visited the Superdome, bringing food for his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe how fast it happened,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a guy strong as an ox, quick as a cat, and six months
later, if he was standing on uneven ground, he was likely to fall
over. He couldn't use his hands, and when he spoke you could
understand maybe 50 percent of what he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Moon saw Montgomery again, this time at a
fund-raiser for the G. Montgomery Foundation. The lineman was in a
wheelchair, unable to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem to affect his mind, from what I saw. He was so
alert, so on top of things. He wanted to visit NFL training camps
this summer and make people aware of ALS. He had this whole plan
and now ...
</P>
<P>
   Of all the so-called news in sports this week, none of it means
a damn thing next to one particular item: Glenn Montgomery, a
31-year-old defensive lineman, husband and father of two, died
after an 18-month battle with Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we didn't even have a chance to offer him a drug
(Miotrophin) because the federal Food and Drug Administration is
dragging its heels, even though the drug was shown to slow the
progress of the disease 26 percent,'' Dr. Appel said.
</P>
<P>
   After learning something like this, who cares if the NBA
millionaires have started a labor war or if the U.S. soccer coach
ruined a World Cup or if the Mariners' season is all but lost?
</P>
<P>
   The news of sports is the news of nothing compared to this _ one
tough lineman's fight worthy of recognition from all of us left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
