<HEADER>
A5033 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RICKEYHENDERSON-S     07-01 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RICKEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKEY STILL STEALS THE SHOW 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
 HENDERSON-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Rickey Henderson was always a blur. All that
speed and talent and exuberance swept him along in an insane blur
that seemed to defy nature or clear understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson at 39, leather-faced and giddy, still has the amazing
body, and he defies nature more than ever. But he has slowed down
enough for those of us with mere mortal perception to get a sense
of what he is all about and to fill in some of the blanks looking
back at a career that guarantees Henderson first-ballot induction
into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The running-back legs have him leading baseball in stolen bases,
and the trained eye has him leading the league in walks. Throw that
together with his infectious enthusiasm and his unflagging advice
and support for the A's young players, and you start to get a sense
of what those close to him have always understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to be playing still, that tells you how much he loves
the game,'' says Dave Stewart, a boyhood friend of Henderson's in
Oakland and a teammate on the last great A's teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you something about all the years before. Some of the
talent goes out of you, and you find other ways to show your love
for the game, talking to guys in the clubhouse, teaching them about
the game. But watching him play all these years, you always saw his
spirit for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's habit of moving a little too fast to follow is never
more apparent than when he's speaking. Even now, he sometimes
throws it into overdrive and unleashes a torrent of words so fast
and so syncopated, even veteran Henderson-watchers only catch bits
and pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes me laugh every time I see him, but sometimes you
can't understand what he's saying,'' teammate Kevin Mitchell says,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Mom always tells me, `You need to slow down,' '' Henderson
says. ``But sometimes there's so much in my mind, it all comes out
all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   This might be the least-understood side of Henderson, the
restless intelligence behind the mastery of the basepaths. It all
starts with the legs, toned and strong ever since he was a kid
chasing the family chickens, but to watch Henderson work a pitcher
and make his way around the basepaths is to watch a man bursting
with ideas and creative impulses.
</P>
<P>
   The shimmying and strutting off the bag. The feint toward
second. The all-out burst of speed, followed by a few quick steps
before he puts the brakes on, showing it was all just a fake. The
constantly varying leads. The mocking stares.
</P>
<P>
   One trip around the bases can be as entertaining as a Mark
McGwire moon shot. Over the weekend in Denver, Henderson ended up
at third base and did a number on Rockies pitcher Jamey Wright. It
was like watching a Little Leaguer being outclassed by a
big-leaguer, so thoroughly did Henderson demonstrate his edge in
concentration and feel for the game. He faked a steal, and Wright
balked him home, just as Henderson had predicted to third-base
coach Ron Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's thinking,'' Henderson says. ``You're taught the
fundamental parts of stealing a base, but as far as knowing how to
make sure the pitcher knows you're there, that's thinking.
Sometimes they're more aware of you than the hitter. Sunday in
Denver, I was telling Wash, `I can make him balk if I keep it up,'
because I had yelled at him and saw him flinch. So I faked a steal
and he freaked out.''
</P>
<P>
   To fully appreciate moments like that, you have to think about
Henderson's audience. He's playing for history, and he's playing
for himself, and he's playing to do right by the game. But he's
also playing to pass something on to rookies like Miguel Tejada,
A.J. Hinch and Ben Grieve. Grieve could end up following Henderson
into the Hall if his rookie-of-the-year season paints an accurate
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never big-leagues anyone,'' Grieve says. ``He's probably
the most exciting player on our team, he and Tejada, guys who can
run and make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Henderson's place in the game as the all-time leader in
steals, and also among the all-time leaders in runs and walks,
there is no danger of any rookies failing to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I collected his card when I was in first grade,'' Hinch says.
``I had a Rickey Henderson rookie card and I got sent home from
school because I got in a fight over it. He has as much energy and
spark for the game as anyone in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at something like the all-time leaders in runs. He's
in sixth place and the names ahead of him are guys like Ty Cobb and
Hank Aaron and Babe Ruth. That shows you the mark the man has made.
And for all that, he really cares about his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the man. When we were in Seattle, he stood behind
the cage all during batting practice watching every pitch and told
me what I was doing. I heard the stories about Rickey, how he
didn't even know the names of his teammates, and now I'm a friend
of his.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinch, 24, was in diapers around the time Henderson started
wowing people. Born in Chicago, Henderson played baseball,
basketball and football at Oakland Tech before graduating in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Football was his love, and it showed. He was an explosive
running back and ended up with at least a dozen scholarship offers.
Stewart still goes a little glassy-eyed talking about Henderson as
a football talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played Babe Ruth baseball against Rickey, but to me the
first time I really noticed Rickey Henderson was when I went to see
Rickey play football for Oakland Tech, and that really impressed
me,'' Stewart says. ``He ran a kickoff back 101 yards. He made one
juke about the 5-yard line, made a couple of cuts and he was
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   An Oakland police officer named Jim Guinn scouted Henderson for
the A's, and director of player personnel Syd Thrift will never
forget the first time he saw Henderson at a predraft workout his
senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran him in a 60-yard dash and he ran it in about 6.4,
6.5,'' Thrift recalls. ``That's explosive speed. He had good power.
He was a center fielder with good range. He was the most exciting
player I've seen at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one problem: Owner Charlie Finley didn't want to shell out
the money to sign Henderson as a first-round draft pick. So Thrift
had to sweat out the draft, hoping no one else grabbed the unknown
Henderson before the A's could pick him in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The night before the draft, I didn't sleep at all,'' Thrift
says. ``I was trying to figure out how to best place Rickey
Henderson so we could sign him. It was a huge gamble. Immediately
after the draft, I talked to Charlie. I told him I wasn't concerned
about No. 1 and No. 2 and No. 3, but I want to sign No. 4. He said,
`I want you to spend $10,000.' I had to sweat the whole night out
before we drafted him, and now I had to sweat out this, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrift and a lot of other people did not expect Henderson to
choose baseball over football. ``When Jim Guinn came back a few
days later with a signed contract, I almost fainted,'' Thrift says.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson put the decision in the hands of his mother, Bobbie.
``My Mom chose baseball for me,'' he says. ``I was mainly a diehard
football player. She said I was too small for football. When she
chose baseball, I cried. But she chose right.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has put to rest the talk of him as a disruptive
influence in the clubhouse, but he may never satisfy those who
questioned his willingness to play hurt. But even if Henderson made
errors of judgment as a younger man, it is hard to ignore the
message he is sending late in his career. He will be back again
next year, at 40, and he will still be dancing and dashing and
leaving everyone he crosses paths with smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm done playing, I want them to say `He played hard,' ''
Henderson says. ``People got into the habit of saying, `You're
joking it. You're not hurt.' But I don't think any player who knows
what's involved, the pounding you take playing the way I do, would
say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has played in 78 of the A's 81 games this season,
second only to Grieve. Once baseball's highest-paid player, this
year he is playing for $1.1 million in salary, plus incentives, and
he is not wasting much time wondering what the A's will offer him
for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I'm having fun,'' he says. ``I've been
through all that contract stuff. That's been a burn and a drag. Now
I'm like a kid out there. It feels like the beginning of my career,
just going out there every day and having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
