u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TRANSIT-KICKBACKS-     07-01 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-KICKBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSIT POLICE UNION EX-PRESIDENT IS SENTENCED IN SCHEME TO PAY
KICKBACKS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By BENAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ronald Reale, the former president of the city's
transit police union, and Richard Hartman, a leading labor
negotiator, were among five people sentenced to prison on Tuesday
by a federal judge in Manhattan for their roles in a
multimillion-dollar racketeering scheme. A sixth man was sentenced
in a related scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Reale, 45, who was sentenced to seven years, and Hartman, 57,
who received five, had been convicted in January with two other men
in a racketeering conspiracy that involved the payment of more than
$400,000 in bribes to transit union officers in return for more
than $2 million in union money paid to the law firm of Lysaght,
Lysaght &AMP; Kramer, which represented the transit union and other
local police unions.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Deborah Batts of Federal District Court in Manhattan said
that Reale had ``shamelessly abused'' a ``position of authority and
trust for his own corrupt gains and those of others.'' And she
called Hartman ``an architect of several of the kickback schemes,''
which increased his business as well as ``contributed to the
corruption of the labor negotiation process.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those also sentenced on Tuesday were James Lysaght, 51,
and Peter Kramer, 44, the former sole partners in the law firm and
labor consultants for the transit union, who received terms of 27
months each. Lysaght and Kramer _ and, earlier, Hartman _ did legal
work for the transit police union and also represented the union
that now represents all New York City police officers, the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
   Reale and Hartman had also been convicted of trying to defraud
the city's Campaign Finance Board of matching funds during Reale's
1993 campaign for public advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of
New York, said that the convictions and sentences ``are a warning
to those individuals who corrupt the election system or steal from
union members that they will be prosecuted and, if convicted,
sentenced to lengthy prison terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White said that her office's investigation was continuing.
Although she did not elaborate, a federal grand jury subpoaened 10
years of financial records last year from the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association, as part of a widening investigation into
allegations of corruption. After the transit police and the city's
Police Department were combined in 1995, the PBA absorbed the
members of the transit police union.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman's defense lawyer, Gerald Shargel, criticized the
government on Tuesday, saying: ``I don't think it had anything more
than big eyes for a larger investigation. I don't think there's
ever been any evidence to substantiate what they've hinted at for
years _ the notion of widespread corruption in the PBA or
wrongdoing by the law firm.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shargel, as did the other defense lawyers, sought leniency for
his client. He told Judge Batts that Hartman ``has had a brilliant
career'' and was regarded as the pre-eminent representative of
police officers throughout this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Reale's lawyer, J. Bruce Maffeo, wrote to the judge that his
client's humiliation as a result of the conviction ``has eclipsed
his many accomplishments'' as a reformer and decorated police
officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Batts ordered Reale, Hartman, Lysaght and Kramer to
forfeit a total of $200,000 as part of their sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that money may be returned to the city's Campaign
Finance Board, said Nicole Gordon, the board's executive director.
Ms. Gordon said in a telephone interview that her agency, which
first uncovered the allegations of campaign fraud and took them to
Ms. White's office in 1994, would seek to recoup the $163,000 in
taxpayer money that Reale and Hartman were convicted of obtaining
fraudulently.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Batts also sentenced two other former transit union
officials on Tuesday who had earlier pleaded guilty. Thomas
Zichettello, 38, the former first vice president of the transit
police union, who had cooperated with the government's
investigation, received a six-month sentence for his role in the
racketeering conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Richardone, 37, the former treasurer of the transit union,
was sentenced to 33 months for his plea to one count of mail fraud
in connection with what prosecutors said was a scheme to use union
funds to buy luxury cars for himself, his friends and family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
