<SLUG> BC-CAR-BOAT-RECOVERY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOAT HOPES TO RETURN BY AUG. 16 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Believe it or not, Billy Boat received good news
Tuesday after surgery at Indianapolis Methodist Hospital to repair
an upper femur fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who also suffered a fractured pelvis in Sunday's Indy
Racing League New England 200 at New Hampshire International
Speedway, may miss only two races and may return to the circuit in
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   It was feared that Boat, who lives in Glendale, would miss the
remainder of the season, which resumes July 19 at Dover Downs
(Del.) International Speedway. Another race is scheduled July 25 at
Charlotte (N.C.) Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Although the recovery period for such injuries is about eight
weeks, Dr. Kevin Scheid, who performed the surgery, said Boat could
drive sooner.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Boat's likely return to the driver's seat would be Aug.
16 at Pikes Peak (Colo.) International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Boat was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Bill, said he was told the recovery period could be
shorter because the swelling wasn't as bad as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, 32, spent Sunday night in a Concord, N.H., hospital, then
was transported Monday to Indianapolis, where he underwent three
hours of surgery to insert an L-shaped plate and screws.
</P>
<P>
   The four-car collision occurred on Lap 96, when rookie J.J.
Yeley of Phoenix spun and collided with Boat, regarded as one of
the circuit's rising stars. Boat spun into the infield grass and
was struck broadside by Raul Boesel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nose (from Boesel's car) went through the sidepod and
through the tub and hit Billy's leg,'' said Heather Handley, a
spokeswoman for A.J. Foyt Enterprises. ``They (IRL officials)
couldn't get the nose out of the car for at least an hour after
Billy was put on a stretcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Boat hasn't talked to his son since Monday, when he
still was in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was full of morphine and couldn't hardly talk because his
mouth was so dry,'' the elder Boat said. ``But he sounded good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he'll have any problem getting back in the car.
He's been through this kind of stuff before and knows it's part of
the game. If a guy lets something like that (injuries) bother him,
he's not going to be a good racer. You just might as well hang it
up because those things happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worse part is drivers get mad because they can't get back
in the seat the next day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
