<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS SUCCEED IN ANNOYING DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Some of us were raised to believe the San Francisco
Giants exist for only one reason: to annoy the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're adults and we know better. The Giants exist not merely
to annoy the Dodgers but to mock them as well.
</P>
<P>
   The men in black are ahead of the boys in blue softball jerseys
for the second straight season, leading them by seven games in the
National League wild-card race, shameful enough considering the
spread between their bankrolls.
</P>
<P>
   What is more insulting is the way the Giants are doing it.
</P>
<P>
   With only left fielder Barry Bonds placing in the top eight in
All-Star voting at an every-day position, and Dodgers outpolling
Giants in five of the six races.
</P>
<P>
   With three starting pitchers at least 36 years of age, all so
healthy that they haven't missed a start, while Dodgers ace Ramon
Martinez is out for the year.
</P>
<P>
   With the spoils of two once-unpopular trades by general manager
Brian Sabean, including the one in 1996 that dispatched the beloved
Matt Williams, Mike Piazza-style, to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   With a clubhouse that has seen 80-percent turnover in the past
two years yet epitomizes !ital!esprit de corps!off!, the quality
that always eluded the home-grown Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   With a well-deserved sneer toward the wealthier rivals to the
south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Dodgers,'' said catcher Brian Johnson, drawing the
contrast between the Dodgers, perennial division favorites, and the
Giants, consensus long shots the season after their '97 division
title. ``They were born with silver spoons in their mouths, if you
will. They were given the division every year, but they haven't won
a division title lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the Dodgers are now, the Giants were supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   They won 90 games last year in the strangest way possible, while
getting outscored over the course of the season. Logically, their
success had to be the result of good luck, good timing or good
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us guessed it was good luck and based our '98
predictions on the what-goes-up-must-come-down theory of pennant
races. The Giants had to tumble back to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Even those of us who gave the Giants and manager Dusty Baker
credit for their extraordinary unity got it a little wrong. The
Giants took all that ``chemistry'' stuff as a backhanded
compliment. As if they didn't have the talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that Billy Joel song _ `Everybody wears their
emotions on their sleeve, but some people roll up their sleeves,'''
said pitcher Orel Hershiser, caught up in the Giants spirit in his
first season with the club. ``We roll down our sleeves. You can see
our emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   For Los Angeles, the most searing memory of the '97 race might
be Johnson's 12th-inning home run Sept. 18 to beat the Dodgers. The
Giants jumped into a tie for first place and never trailed again.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants celebrated wildly on the field, emotion dripping from
their sleeves. The image stuck, a plucky Little League team riding
a wave of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it was a lot of guys that weren't household names
doing well,'' said Johnson, one of 20 Giants who joined the team in
'97 or '98. ``This year it's a bunch of guys that still aren't
getting a lot of respect who are still doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't convinced anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   At their current pace, equal to last year at 48-36, the Giants
will have back-to-back 90-win seasons for the first time since Dick
Dietz. So give us time to adjust to the thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have the time.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Cleveland Indians a few years back, they're a
small-market team that, through a series of smart moves, has
developed a strong core.
</P>
<P>
   By signing first baseman J.T. Snow through 1999; third baseman
Bill Mueller, closer Robb Nenn and left-handers Shawn Estes and
Kirk Rueter through 2000, second baseman Jeff Kent through 2001 and
Bonds through 2002, they've promised something good to watch when
Pacific Bell Park opens in two years.
</P>
<P>
   By trading prospects for pitchers Wilson Alvarez, Roberto
Hernandez and Danny Darwin as '97 division insurance, then letting
Alvarez, Hernandez and and closer Rod Beck go to free agency, they
stockpiled draft picks and precious money.
</P>
<P>
   By using five of the top 42 picks in last month's amateur draft,
they restocked their farm system. By spending the money, they got
Hershiser and shortstop Rey Sanchez as free agents and the
high-priced Nen in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Of the core, only leadoff hitter Darryl Hamilton can leave after
this season.
</P>
<P>
   With the lowest payroll in the NL West, lower even than the
expansion Arizona Diamondbacks, the Giants aren't a complete team.
The age of their rotation is worrisome. So is their lack of power
below Bonds, demonstrated when they lost 11 of 16 following Kent's
knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Either of those weaknesses could cost them the three-game lead
over the New York Mets in the wild-card race with which they
started Tuesday night's game against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   But if they win, it will be because of shrewd management, an
almost infallible bullpen and spectacular intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers fans, how annoying is that? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
