<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CUBS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE COMES THROUGH FOR BLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ They turned back the clock to the 1970s on Tuesday
night at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, among them Chicago Cubs broadcasters Chip Caray and
Steve Stone, wore clothing from the decade, including Afro wigs. A
glittering disco ball hung from the ceiling of the broadcast booth.
A red lava lamp glowed. The group Sister Sledge sang.
</P>
<P>
   And oh, yes, there was a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Diamondbacks starting pitcher Willie Blair won was
so long, it seemed like it was the 1970s. But it was only a little
more than month ago, on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, Blair's frustration came to a merciful end, like
platform shoes and leisure suits.
</P>
<P>
   By defeating the Cubs, 5-4, the Diamondbacks gave the
right-hander his third victory in 14 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up a solo home run to Sammy Sosa, his 20th of the month
and 32nd overall, and a solo shot to Mark Grace. Henry Rodriguez
hit a solo homer off reliever Alan Embree. But the Diamondbacks
countered with a three-run shot by Matt Williams and a solo homer
by Andy Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the second in a row for Arizona (29-54). The
Cubs (43-39) lost for the eighth time in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Blair lasted 6 innings, giving up three runs on six hits,
walking two and striking out four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think Willie was as sharp as he has been in other
games. But we gave him some runs to work with (Williams' homer came
in the first inning),'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   So Blair finally got a little justice, after he lost previous
games while pitching better?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Did Blair concur?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when you go out and you don't have your best
stuff,'' he said. ``But you get a feel for what is working. I felt
I made the necessary pitches when I needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams ended a 14-game homer drought, his longest of the
season, with the shot off right-handed starter Mark Clark. His last
homer was on June 13 off St. Louis' Jeff Brantley at home.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' homer Tuesday night also increased his hitting streak
to 12 games. He also had a sacrifice fly in the third inning and a
double in the sixth. He has 14 homers, 41 RBIs and a .272 average.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this was a signal that he might begin a home-run binge,
Williams said it was a strong possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, they have come in bunches for me,'' he said.
``I've been hitting the ball a lot harder lately, even the outs. I
just want to continue to make good contact and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   After Williams' sacrifice fly scored Devon White in the fourth,
the Cubs snapped Blair's shutout in their half of the fourth on
Rodriguez's 18th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's eighth homer of the season with two outs in the sixth
cut the Arizona lead to 4-2, but Fox gave the Diamondbacks more
breathing room in the top of the seventh with a homer to right with
one out. His homer total matches his uniform number _ 6.
</P>
<P>
   Blair retired the first two batters of the seventh, but gave up
a single to center by Manny Alexander. Showalter called on the
left-handed Embree, who surrendered an RBI double to pinch-hitter
Matt Mieske. The run was charged to Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa connected on a 3-2 pitch from Embree for his homer with one
out in the eighth to make it 5-4. Rodriguez doubled with two outs,
and Showalter brought in right-handed closer Gregg Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Olson retired Kevin Orie on a fly ball to left to end the eighth
and retired the side in order in the ninth for his 11th save.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive play of the game, and perhaps for the Diamondbacks
to date, came in the ninth on a foul popup by Alexander. Rookie
first baseman Travis Lee turned his back and sprinted through foul
territory toward the Arizona bullpen, then reached out at the last
second to snare the ball near the brick wall along the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my eye off it, then I found it again. I reached out and
it just fell in the glove,'' Lee said. ``The thing I was worried
about was David (Dellucci, right fielder) coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes after everything full-bore. I think he might have
tripped a little on the bullpen mound. Otherwise, there would have
been a pretty good collision.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
