<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY SHARES FALL 8 1/2 POINTS ON GLOOMY FORECASTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares of Walt Disney Co. took their biggest loss
in more than eight years Tuesday, losing 7.2 percent of their value
on worries about movies, home videos and consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   Disney shares plunged 8 1/8 to $105 1/16, marking the largest
decline since a 9.2 percent fall on Dec. 20, 1989. The
entertainment giant's loss accounted for 32.4 points of the
45.34-point decline in the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the declines are nowhere near the terrifying 29 percent
drop that hit Disney on Oct. 19, 1987, also known as Black Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Seven analysts cut profit forecasts or lowered ratings Tuesday.
Long-time bull Stewart Halpern of Furman Selz lowered his rating to
``buy'' from ``strong buy,'' citing worse-than-expected performance
in video and overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the stock is likely to be weighted down in the
near-term by investors taking more a `show-me' attitude,'' he said,
adding it would take another quarter or two for Disney to hit his
1998 target of $122.
</P>
<P>
   Shares have now dropped 17 percent since May 4, when the stock
hit an all-time high of 127 1/8. But they remain 42 percent ahead
of the 52-week low last July.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern cited soft sales of ``Flubber'' in U.S. home video and
foreign theatrical markets; competition from the World Cup soccer
tournament at foreign theaters; poor overseas performance by
``Starship Troopers''; soft consumer product sales overseas;
continued weakness at ABC Television; and no ``runaway'' hits
expected among its upcoming movies.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern cut 6 cents from his estimate for the third quarter
ended June 30 to 62 cents a share, 9 cents from his 1998 estimate
to $2.91 a share and 7 cents from the 1999 estimate to $3.48.
</P>
<P>
   Also cutting forecasts were Melissa Cook of Prudential
Securities, David Londoner of Schroder &AMP; Co., Richard Bilotti of
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Jill Krutick of Salomon Smith Barney,
Larry Petrella at Lehman Bros. and Richard Simon of Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
