<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN APPROVES $18.1 BILLION STATE BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman signed a new $18.1 billion
state budget into law on Tuesday night, using her line-item veto
power to eliminate $42.8 million in legislative spending, as well
as language prohibiting her from turning public employee jobs over
to private contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The state budget, approved by lawmakers on Monday, raises
spending by almost $1 billion for public schools, state colleges
and universities, preservation of open spaces, and various other
programs. It also puts $700 million aside in a ``rainy day fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Whitman and lawmakers had reached agreement on the
broad outlines of the new spending plan for the fiscal year, which
begins on July 1, she used her line-item veto power to strike some
spending increases that were included by lawmakers and some budget
language that her aides said would have reduced her authority.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman eliminated the biggest item that legislators had
included for property tax relief: a $10 million increase in state
aid for municipalities. Whitman aides said that before allocating
more municipal aid, the governor wanted to see what recommendations
her commission on property tax reform would make at its meeting
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman cut other spending increases, including a $6.5 million
addition for park maintenance and $6 million that had been added
for capital projects at state colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing concern about the rise in the number of ``special
appropriations'' that lawmakers added to the budget this year for
various projects in their districts, she warned that groups and
organizations receiving the extra aid should not rely on it in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   She also eliminated state spending for about a dozen legislative
projects, including $300,000 for a proposed Yogi Berra museum on
the campus at Montclair State University and $1.5 million for a new
Morris County Fire and Police Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Spending for various legislative projects totaled about $60
million in the new state budget, about $20 million more than this
year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in special appropriations reflects the
availability of revenues generated by our robust economy,'' the
governor said. ``During such times, it is appropriate to support
worthy causes and to meet unaddressed needs. The recipients of such
special appropriations should not, however, become reliant on state
support since such support is, by its nature, temporary.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cuts that Whitman made in the new budget were not
popular with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Robert Littell, a Republican and chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Committee, said he was disappointed by many
of the changes the governor made. He had recommended the spending
increase in park maintenance and he called Whitman's decision to
reduce the allocation ``very shortsighted,'' particularly since she
was pushing to purchase a million acres of undeveloped land over
the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask people to buy more land when you don't take care
of what you have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also struck out language that would have prevented the
administration from withholding funds to municipalities for
development projects, like sewers and roads, that are inconsistent
with the state's growth-management plan.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of privatization of state jobs, she eliminated
language that would have prevented the administration from turning
any state jobs over to private contractors.
</P>
<P>
   But in a move suggesting that Whitman may not use privatization
this year, she left $7 million untouched that lawmakers had put
back into the budget, the amount her aides estimate privatization
would save. The Whitman administration is considering privatizing
an estimated 500 jobs in the Department of Transportation's
engineering department and the Corrections Department's food
service division.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard Bagger, a Republican and chairman of the
Assembly Appropriations Committee, said the language had been
inserted because lawmakers did not think it was appropriate for
state employees to lose their jobs when the economy was pouring so
much extra tax revenue into the state's coffers.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer James A. DiEleuterio Jr. said that the question
of eliminating some state jobs and turning them over to private
contractors was still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the urging of some lawmakers and Mayor Milton Milan of
Camden, Whitman did not change language that authorizes a
state-appointed review board to oversee Camden's finances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
