<HEADLINE>
MEEK RANGERS NO HELP TO HELLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers right-hander Rick Helling took the
mound with one final opportunity to forge an All-Star-deserving
impression upon Cleveland Indians manager Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, though, found no support among the Rangers last night
at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Helling's attempt to become the major leagues' first 12-game
winner and perhaps secure Hargrove's selection to the 1998 American
League All-Star team went awry during a 4-1 defeat to the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who went meekly in Sunday's 7-0 loss to the San
Francisco Giants, managed only three hits for the second
consecutive game. Only a one-out, sixth-inning home run from third
baseman Fernando Tatis prevented the Rangers from their second
consecutive shutout and third during their past eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers right-hander Darren Dreifort (5-6) dominated with a
fastball/slider combination and mixed in an occasional changeup
that gave the Rangers fits for eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff tonight was good stuff,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said of Dreifort's seven-strikeout, no-walk performance.
``That was Class-A, No. 1 stuff. I would put it up there in the top
three we've seen all year. I put it right up there with the game
\RCleveland's Bartolo\S Colon threw against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had three pitches: a fastball that didn't go straight at 94
or 95 miles per hour, a nasty slider and _ once in a while _ a good
changeup. We just didn't get too many good swings at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling (11-4) pitched well himself, but the right-hander would
not be a match for Dreifort without command of his curveball. The
Dodgers' three run-scoring hits _ a second-inning single by left
fielder Matt Luke, a fifth-inning single by right fielder Gary
Sheffield and a two-run, sixth-inning home run by third baseman
Adrian Beltre _ came on fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I'm most disappointed with is the home run,''
Helling said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between a two-run deficit and that of four runs
would be overwhelming with Dreifort pitching as he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping I could keep up with him,'' Helling said.
``I knew it was going to be tough to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, right-hander Aaron Sele (11-5, 4.26) and closer John
Wetteland (22 saves) will be among those Rangers who merit
Hargrove's consideration for the All-Star Game. The manager's
selections for pitchers and reserves will be announced at 5 p.m.
today. Ivan Rodriguez and Juan Gonzalez were voted to the team as
starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't even thought that much about it,'' Helling,
whose earned-run average rose slightly to 4.25, said about being an
All-Star. ``I have no control over it. I'm happy with the way I've
pitched the first half of the season, but the last thing I want to
do is start thinking about individual stuff. You get into trouble
when you start doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates predicted last night that at least six AL pitchers
deserving of an All-Star berth will be slighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's deserving, certainly, with 11 wins,'' Oates said
of Helling. ``It'll be up to Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove said last week that he would be ``very hesitant'' to
choose a pitcher scheduled to start Sunday, since the All-Star Game
is Tuesday. Helling remains the Rangers' scheduled starter for
Sunday's game against the Seattle Mariners at The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Helling does not expect a berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have no idea,'' Helling said. ``With what Hargrove
said, I don't even know if it matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, a potential All-Star berth will not consume Helling's
thoughts between now and today's 5 p.m. announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be thinking,'' he said, ``about that home run I gave
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
