<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT, BELTRE LEAD DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Tex. _ They might be the Fox-run Dodgers, but once in
a while they play it like the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   The team that must decide if they want to play for today or live
for tomorrow, saw the future Tuesday night in Darren Dreifort and
Adrian Beltre, who led the Dodgers to a 4-1 interleague victory
over the Texas Rangers in front of 37,873 at the Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort could have been a Seattle Mariner and Beltre could have
been with the Cincinnati Reds. The Dodgers are confident those are
good moves for more than one night.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Ramon Martinez underwent surgery that will put him
out for a year, Dreifort limited the Rangers to three hits and one
run in eight innings. Beltre, the replacement for injured Bobby
Bonilla at third base, hit his first career home run.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the Dodgers won't look into Randy Johnson
during the offseason or Reds closer Jeff Shaw during the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
   But in this wildly uncertain season, the Dodgers for once looked
like they had options.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all that's happened we're not ruling anything out, but
we don't feel the need to panic,'' new manager Glenn Hoffman said.
``You have to look at everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Including a replacement for Eric Young, who is headed to the
disabled list after injuring his right thigh muscle for the third
time. Young, injured running out a ground ball in the first inning,
thinks he can still come back.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Tom Lasorda said he expects to use Wilton
Guerrero at second and the leadoff spot and recall Alex Cora from
Triple-A. Both played most of the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which opened a six-game road trip, didn't really do
much for the Dodgers' place in the standings. Even a loss by the
division-leading San Diego Padres trimmed the Dodgers' deficit only
slightly to 12{ games.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre took 11-game winner Rick Helling deep in the sixth
inning, not the Double-A pitchers he beat up for the first three
months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about where I'm headed after Bonilla comes
back,'' Beltre said. ``To me every game is a confidence boost.
Whether I do well or do bad, I'm here. That is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre had a throwing error in the ninth inning of Sunday's 6-4
loss to Pittsburgh. It led to a run and led many to believe that he
was a talented player, but not ready for the big leagues. After
getting an RBI single in his first big league at-bat, Beltre went 2
for 18.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest proof of Beltre's ability was the Reds'
insistence that he be included in any trade for Shaw. The Reds have
hinted the Dodgers offered Paul Konerko, despite Lasorda's denials.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (5-6) made only 87 pitches on a 96-degree night and
thought he could pitch the ninth. But Hoffman said he wanted
Antonio Osuna to pitch instead. While they debate offers for Shaw,
the Dodgers are giving Osuna a final chance to see if he is the
closer. After earning the save against the Rangers, he is five for
five in save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's only mistake was a sixth-inning home run by Fernando
Tatis that was the first run in 21 innings for the Rangers, who
have dropped three straight and 12 of 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff was good stuff, probably in the top three we've seen
this year,'' said Rangers manager Johnny Oates of Dreifort. ``We
didn't get too many good swings off him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
