<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CHANGES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TRADE AWAY STABILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Alston managed the Brooklyn and Los Angeles Dodgers for
23 years. Tommy Lasorda followed him for 20 more.
</P>
<P>
   Two managers in 43 years, not to mention three general managers
and one family of owners, is almost unprecedented in any sport. It
gave the Dodgers an unusual air of stability in a sport known for
high casualty rates in front office and managerial positions.
</P>
<P>
   During those 43 years, the New York Yankees changed managers 24
times, yet won three more pennants than the Dodgers. The Rangers
have been around for just 27 years, and Johnny Oates is their 14th
full-time manager.
</P>
<P>
   But, with one hefty check worth more than $300 million, the
Dodgers' famed stability has almost disappeared. New owner Rupert
Murdoch and the Fox Group, after buying the team from Peter
O'Malley, seemed to have turned the franchise into the West Coast
version of George Steinbrenner's Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' said Lasorda, who has found himself in the
middle of the maelstrom. ``Stability was always a strength when
Peter O'Malley owned the team. But \RFox\S figured they had to do
something. We weren't playing well. We were slipping.''
</P>
<P>
   The O'Malley family owned the Dodgers for almost a half-century.
But in the three months since Fox took over ...
</P>
<P>
   All-Star catcher Mike Piazza, after turning down an $84 million
contract offer, was sent to the Florida Marlins along with third
baseman Todd Zeile in a whopping seven-player deal that brought
Gary Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles Johnson, Jim Eisenreich and
Manuel Barrios over from the world champions.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star pitcher Hideo Nomo was designated for assignment and
traded to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Fred Claire and manager Bill Russell were fired.
Lasorda has taken over as interim general manager, and Glenn
Hoffman, 27-41 as manager at Triple-A Albuquerque, was hired as
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Reggie Smith, pitching coach Glenn Gregson and
bullpen coach Mark Cressi were fired. Charlie Hough became pitching
coach, Mickey Hatcher took over as hitting coach and John Shelby
was named bench coach to replace Cressi.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were big changes,'' Hough said. ``There was probably no
better owner in baseball than the O'Malley family. The thing was,
people who worked for the Dodgers a long time knew they had a job
forever. It has been great. That's why this shake-up has caught
everybody by surprise. Things have changed but hopefully for the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Said first base coach Mike Scioscia, another longtime member of
the Dodgers organization, ``I think the face of the Dodgers will
change the club slightly with a new manager and with Fox Group
taking over, but the core of what the Dodgers are all about will
still be there. There are a lot of people in player development,
scouting and on the minor-league and major-league staffs who have
been around a long time and know how to do it. That will be there
for a long time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the changes, the Dodgers remain a major
disappointment. They entered last night's game with a 39-42 record
and in third place in the National League West. They have a $57
million payroll and a growing reputation as the biggest
underachievers in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating,'' Lasorda said. ``Very frustrating. If
somebody had told me in spring training that we would be 13 1/2
games out by the first of July, I would have told them they were
crazy. But that's what has happened, and we're trying to right it
if it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   But some problems are even greater than even the mighty Fox
Group can control. Pitcher Ramon Martinez underwent shoulder
surgery yesterday and is through for the season. First baseman Eric
Karros, third baseman Bonilla, outfielder Todd Hollandsworth and
shortstop Jose Vizcaino have all spent time on the disabled list.
Second baseman Eric Young left last night's game with a strained
right quadriceps muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things that have happened that have really
kept this team from being a very good club instead of the club we
have now,'' Hatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   That still doesn't help Hoffman, a former major-league shortstop
who was a surprise choice to replace Russell. Scioscia was
considered the leading candidate within the organization, while
such heavyweights as Sparky Anderson, Whitey Herzog and Lasorda
himself were also being mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Even now there is a strong feeling that Hoffman, unless he can
pull off a miracle, won't last beyond this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here taking it one day at a time,'' Hoffman said. ``This
is a game of adjustments, and I've made the adjustment to
major-league manager. Hopefully, these guys will see what I can do.
All you can do is ask for the opportunity, and I have that
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clubhouse, the players adjust on the fly and cling to the
hope they can make a run in the second half. A division title may
be a fading possibility, but the Dodgers, going into last night's
game, were eight games behind the San Francisco Giants in the
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``As players we have no say in what's going on with the
management of the team,'' said Johnson, the catcher acquired from
the Marlins. ``We just need to go out there every day and win
ballgames. It would be nice to have the same group together for a
long time, but it always doesn't happen that way. We still feel we
have a chance. The teams in front of us may not play as well in the
second half and we could play outstanding. We just have to play
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
