A5103 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     07-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DEFEAT GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels have been here before. The trick is staying
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels finished the month of June with a 4-3 victory over
the San Francisco Giants on Tuesday night before 25,629 at Edison
Field and maintained their firm grasp on first place in the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Angels know all too well, pennants aren't awarded on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson's three-run homer, a gritty performance by
starter Chuck Finley and clutch pitching by the bullpen (including
Troy Percival's league-leading 25th save) helped the Angels win for
the 10th time in 14 interleague games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels enjoyed their best month ever, finishing 22-6 and
going from 5{ games behind Texas to first place, 3{ games up on the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Angels sorry to see the month end?
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to end sooner of later,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``I'm just glad the month of June got here. We needed to do
what we did in June. I was glad to get May (12-15 record) over
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, though, stressed the Angels don't have to put pressure
on themselves to repeat their success of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to win 22 games each month,'' he said. ``If
we're playing six games at home, we should win four or five. If we
do that, we'll look up in three months and like where we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to go out and win series, keep building on what
we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the best Angels hitters of the month was Anderson, the
smooth-swinging outfielder from Kennedy High School. And it's no
coincidence that he keyed the team's offensive hot streak. Anderson
entered June hitting .264 with five homers and 21 RBI. In the
month, he hit .343 with five homers and 18 RBI, raising his average
to .290.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson traditionally is a slow starter, so he didn't press
when he struggled in April and May this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just go up there and get my at-bats every day,'' he said.
``If I start out fast, I start out fast, but I know I'll be there
at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Collins: ``When you put the lineup together, you've got the
(Cecil) Fielders and those guys in there, they need to be protected
so they see better pitches. If you want to pitch around Cecil,
we've got Garret there. He's just not missing pitches right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley (8-4), who was 0-2 with one no-decision in his previous
three starts, gave up three runs and seven hits in 61/3 innings.
But he was far from sharp, tying a season high with six walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tall guys get out of whack mechanically so easily,'' Collins
said. ``He's working at it. He'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got off to a slow start against Giants starter Shawn
Estes (6-7). They had just four hits _ all singles _ through five
innings, and only one baserunner got as far as third base.
</P>
<P>
   But they broke through in the sixth with four runs on four hits.
Dave Hollins led off with his second single of the night and went
to second on Jim Edmonds' infield single.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon followed, and after being refused a timeout by plate
umpire Mark Johnson, hit a line drive off the scoreboard in right
field, scoring Hollins to tie the game at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson followed with his home run, smacking a hanging
curveball into the right-field seats for a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tremendous comeback for us, especially with the way
Estes was throwing,'' Collins said. ``He had good stuff, I'll tell
you that. We had guys coming back to the dugout talking to
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   With 10 home runs, Anderson has already surpassed his total of
eight in 1997. But he says it's just a matter of making adjustments
based on situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been up in situations to drive the ball more this year,''
he said. ``Last year, I was in situations to get base hits to win
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Freak accident: Eligible to come off the disabled list Tuesday,
pitcher Allen Watson instead will stay there for about another 10
days. But it has nothing to do with the strained flexor muscle in
his elbow that put him on the DL in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he cut his wrist opening a beer bottle Monday
afternoon. The wound required six stitches, which will be removed
in 10 to 12 days. He won't begin throwing again for a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a friend's house at the beach,'' said Watson. ``I had
a Corona bottle and was just opening it up. The top of the bottle
broke off and the momentum carried the jagged end into my wrist. I
wasn't drunk or nothing, I was just having a beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little scary. Blood was shooting out. I guess I'm
lucky... but not lucky baseball-wise.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 0242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
