<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5106 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-01 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON FANS 12 ROCKIES IN LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To point out what went wrong at the Kingdome Tuesday
night would only be repeating the message scribbled on the
Mariners' locker room chalkboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is the first day of the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   That can only mean that the sinking Mariners are not about to
come up for air anytime soon. They indicated that with a 6-4 loss
to the Colorado Rockies in front of 28,221 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners endured yet another in a series of sloppily-played
defeats that have bolted them to the bottom of the American League
West. There were pitching lulls and mental mistakes aplenty.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner miscues erased a 12-strikeout effort by starter Randy
Johnson and dropped the Mariners 15 games under .500 at 34-49.
Manager Lou Piniella is about ready to throw his arms above his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Why does this keep happening?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me anymore about it,'' Piniella said after the game.
``Write what you see. It's certainly not up to my standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (7-7) wasn't a consistently strong force on the mound as
he had been in his two previous starts. He yielded four earned runs
after giving up just one in his last 17 innings.
</P>
<P>
   But for as much as Colorado got to Johnson, he was untouchable
at times. Johnson recorded at least 10 strikeouts in a game for the
91st time in his career during the on-again-off-again performance.
</P>
<P>
   However, even Johnson could not overcome two late-inning
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   With the scored tied 4-4 in the seventh inning, M's third
baseman Russ Davis bobbled a ground ball, allowing Neifi Perez to
reach base. Perez later scored the go-ahead run on Dante Bichette's
single.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies added a cushion in the eighth. Johnson gave that run
away. Greg Colbrunn hit a one-out double and stole third. He
eventually scored when a Johnson fastball sailed over catcher John
Marzano's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy threw the ball well. He battled,'' Marzano said. ``He
didn't have the greatest stuff but he threw well when he needed to.
We've just got to start playing better basic baseball. It seems
like every time we make a mistake, it kills us. I've never seen
anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado parlayed three Mariner errors into two runs _ the
difference in the game. Second baseman Joey Cora committed his 14th
error of the season. Davis ran his total to 20.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems the situation is getting increasingly worse for the
M's, that's because they finished their worst June ever. After
going 21-7 last year, the Mariners hobble into July after going
8-20.
</P>
<P>
   They are even worse in comeback situations _ 1-39 when trailing
after eight innings and 4-28 in games decided by three runs or
fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, yeah. Piniella knows all of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get the runs in,'' Piniella said. ``We had some
chances and they wiggled out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners mounted a threat in the bottom of the ninth. Dan
Wilson pinch-hit for Marzano and poked a single to left. Joey Cora
followed with a walk. But Alex Rodriguez hit into a double play,
and Ken Griffey Jr. ended the game with a line drive out to right
field.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado did not chase Johnson until the ninth inning, so it was
not another case of the bullpen throwing the game away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get his strikeouts but what you try to do with
him is stay close,'' said Colorado manager Don Baylor. ``When they
went up 3-1 (in the second), it's not late enough in the ballgame
where Randy just smells it and it's lights out. We just kind of
kept battling back and battling back. You can't let him get too far
out (in front).''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies pierced Johnson in the first inning when Perez led
off with a single and stole second base. Two outs later, Perez
scored on Vinny Castilla's double off the right-center field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson then yielded a single to Ellis Burks before retiring the
side.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners answered in the bottom of the first. Griffey
launched his 33rd home run of the season in the bottom of the
first. Griffey turned on Pedro Astacio's first pitch and sent the
ball down the right-field line into the foul-pole screen.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey homered in his 12th consecutive series. He trails St.
Louis' Mark McGwire by four for the major league home run lead.
McGwire hit his 37th Tuesday night in a loss to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The M's seized control and went ahead 4-2 in the third. Johnson
retired nine of the Rockies' last 11 batters in the middle innings.
But the Rockies began to apparently see his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's catcher Kirt Manwaring led off the fifth with a
double. The very next batter, Perez, belted his fifth homer over
the left field wall. The two-run blast tied the score at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Only three runners got into scoring position for the M's after
the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team starts losing guys start to press,' Marzano said.
``Once we relax, hopefully we'll play better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
