 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 392 - JULY 1, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 392 -- July 1, 1998 We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. LIV TYLER INTERVIEW Once a precocious teenager, Liv Tyler has
grown into a precocious adult. She will be onscreen soon in the
Bruce Willis blockbuster ``Armageddon.'' It's hard to believe Tyler
is only 20. Tall and voluptuous, she is also incredibly poised.
Virtually everyone who meets her is struck by her remarkable
openness and innocence - surprising traits, considering everything
she has lived through so far. The daughter of
groupie-model-musician Bebe Buell, Tyler learned at the age of 10
that her real dad was Steven Tyler of Aerosmith, who didn't even
know he had a daughter. By James Fallon. From W magazine. 1,500
words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
``ARMAGEDDON'' LOOKING TO MAKE DEEP IMPACT AT BOX OFFICE A
Texas-sized rock hurtles towards earth at 22,000 miles per hour. If
it hits, kiss the planet goodbye ... It's time for the summer's
second asteroid-threatens-to-destroy-the-earth 'popcorn' movie:
``Armageddon.'' So what makes it worth seeing, even if you've
already seen ``Deep Impact?'' Several of the movies' heroes - Bruce
Willis, Liv Tyler, Ben Affleck and the king of action-producers,
Jerry Bruckheimer, explain. (For the actors, it was something of a
life-changing experience to work with NASA experts and observe at
close range the space shuttle and other high-tech marvels.) By
Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
BOCELLI'S BLITZ Within the five years since the release of his
first CD in Italy in 1993, Andrea Bocelli has become one of the
hottest stars in the record business. Last year he sold 14 million
CDs worldwide, second only to the Spice Girls. At 39, Bocelli is a
late bloomer for a pop star, even for an aspiring opera singer. As
Richard Dyer explains in this profile, the singer became a pop star
almost by accident. The Boston Globe. 2,100 words. 4. NATIVE
AMERICAN WRITER SENDS 'SIGNALS' OF CHANGE ``Smoke Signals'' is the
first full-length feature film written, directed and co-produced by
Native Americans. Award-winning poet Sherman Alexie is the film's
guiding light. He wrote the script, based on his short fiction,
chose the director and was involved in every aspect of the
production. The results, says the talented and confident Alexie,
``prove that Indians can make good movies.'' The film mixes comedy
and drama, fantasy and reality as two young men travel from their
Idaho reservation to Arizona to pick up the ashes of one
character's recently departed father. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000
words. 5. THE OPPOSITE OF INNOCENCE There is nothing cute or
childlike about Christina Ricci's latest character in ``The
Opposite of Sex.'' Ricci plays Dedee Truitt, a nasty bit of
Southern discomfort who wreaks havoc in the lives of just about
everyone she encounters. Within the movie's first half hour, she
trashes her stepfather's funeral, steals her half-brother's hunky
boyfriend, and names him as the father of her unborn child. Ricci
received the script from her mother, and was immediately interested
in playing Dedee. By Renee Graham. BPI. 1,200 words. 6. FRASER'S
EDGE Actor Brendan Fraser's furrowed brow always manages to give
him a rather sweet air of faint bewilderment, which he used to
comic advantage in ``George of the Jungle,'' and which made him
touchingly vulnerable in the film ``School Ties.'' But at 6 feet 3
inches, the 29-year-old Fraser's price tag these days matches his
size: His salary jumped from $1 million for ``George'' to several
million for his latest film, ``The Blast from the Past,'' which
will co-star Alicia Silverstone. Find out in this interview why it
took a loincloth to propel Fraser to the brink of Hollywood stardom
. By Louise Farr. Fairchild. 1,600 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
IN THE MURKY WORLD OF KENJI MIZOGUCHI The films of Kenji Mizoguchi,
the Japanese director who is being given a comprehensive
retrospective at the Paris Cinimathhque until July 20, take one
into a strangely compelling world that does not easily yield up its
secrets. Although lionised abroad, Mizoguchi was less appreciated
in his own country. He was able to get audiences to accept the
violence of his films, their virulence and their moral
intransigence. Prostitution, whether literal or metaphorical, is
the mainspring of almost all his movies. By Bernard Eisenschitz. Le
Monde. (English translation available.) 1,800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
SNO-KOAN Enigmatic Icelandic singer Bjork talks about the love of
information, fear of technology, the sound of schizophrenia, and
how today's young musicians use new technology. 1,000 words.
