<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HONG-KONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPES STOPOVER IN HONG KONG WILL BOLSTER CONFIDENCE THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ When he visits Hong Kong Thursday, President
Clinton will convey what his aides hope will be a calming message
about Asia's economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive caps his nine-day tour of China late
Thursday with a 29-hour visit to Hong Kong, the enclave of Chinese
capitalism where leaders, investors and citizens are badly shaken
by the economic turmoil that has driven Asia to the brink of an
economic depression.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Clinton hopes his visit will buck up
investors' confidence and celebrate democratic practices that
survived Hong Kong's smooth transition from British colonial status
to Chinese sovereignty one year ago Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   During his summit in Hong Kong with Tung Chee-hwa, the
territory's Beijing-appointed chief executive, Clinton will discuss
additional steps that the United States can take to bolster Asia's
economic recovery. a White House national security official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's meeting with Tung follows two days of consultations
with Chinese President Jiang Zemin in Beijing and precedes a summit
in Washington in late July with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has ``an enormous stake in helping Asia out of
this situation because it will have a direct bearing on Main Street
in America,'' the U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Asian nations accounted for 29 percent of U.S. world-wide trade
in 1997 of almost $2 trillion. Ten of America's top 23 trading
partners are in Asia. Hong Kong, China and Japan accounted for 51
percent of the $568.3 billion in U.S. trade across Asia in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Clinton's visit to Hong Kong also will highlight
the seamless transition that Hong Kong made from 156 years as a
British colony to Chinese control last year. The ease of the
transition had reassured worldwide investors over the future of
Hong Kong, before the Asian financial crisis began exacting its
toll.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is urging Hong Kong's leaders to accelerate the 10-year
phase-in of full elections to allow Hong Kong voters to directly
elect all representatives. Two-thirds of the representatives in the
legislature are now appointed by Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit comes amid White House concern that Jiang could
suffer a political backlash at home if his overtures to the United
States go awry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked in an interview on state-run Chinese
television on Wednesday whether he or Jiang had the tougher job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that he faces enormous challenges here at home of a
scope that Americans have a hard time imagining,'' Clinton said of
Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry said in an interview
that Chinese political hard-liners could challenge Jiang ``based on
any outcome that was less than positive,'' adding: ``We're trying
to be sensitive to how much load we put on the leadership structure
right now because we don't want to push it so hard that we push
them over the side of the cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials ruled out photographs or news coverage of
Clinton's private meeting Friday with Martin Lee, the head of Hong
Kong's Democratic Party and an opponent of the Beijing
administration. The move appeared designed to ease heartburn for
Jiang
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the worried economic environment is the fact that
Tung froze property sales in Hong Kong until next March in a bid to
stem tumbling prices in the worst economic downturn since World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong property prices have plummeted 40 percent this year;
the stock market has dropped 20 percent; unemployment has climbed
to a 15-year high; economic output in the hard-charging economic
tiger has fallen by 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Hong Kong is his latest effort to use the
symbolic clout of the United States to persuade frightened
international investors to ride out a fast-moving economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Roger C. Altman, Clinton's former deputy treasury secretary and
now an investment banker, issued a bleak warning in an opinion
piece that appeared in Asian editions of the International Herald
Tribune as Clinton arrived in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dangerous moment,'' warned Altman. ``In economic and
financial terms, much of the East Hemisphere is in flames and the
fire is spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has steadily deepened his personal involvement in
finding a solution. In recent weeks, he has ordered $2 billion in
U.S. reserves to be spent to bolster the value of the Japanese yen
_ the first time that the United States has sold dollars to buy a
foreign currency since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He is pressing the Japanese government to overhaul insolvent
Japanese banks and stimulate its faltering $4 trillion economy _
the second largest in the world and the engine of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has encouraged Chinese authorities not to devalue
China's currency that would make Chinese exports more competitive
with the depleted prices of Japanese exports due to the fall of the
yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say that I appreciate the very constructive role China
has played in promoting financial stability in the region,''
Clinton told U.S. business leaders. Clinton praised Beijing for
doing ``its part in avoiding another round of competitive
devaluations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
