<HEADLINE>
U.S. JET FIRES MISSILE AT IRAQI MILITARY SITE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a reminder that tensions have not disappeared in
the Persian Gulf region, a U.S. attack jet Tuesday hurled a missile
at an Iraqi military site, which had trained its radar on British
patrol planes flying over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials confirmed the missile launch by
an F-16 jet, the first against Iraq since November 1996, saying it
was standard procedure in response to what is perceived to be a
hostile action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They turned their radar on, and that's a first step toward
launching a missile, or it can be, and is considered threatening,''
said Vice President Al Gore, who fielded questions about the
incident at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that it was not clear whether the action was an
isolated one or part of a deliberate military escalation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know for certain. But we do know from the history of
patrolling the no-fly zones that there are a lot of incidents like
this from time to time and there are other possible explanations,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen suggested that the action might
be an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not seen any evidence on the part of the Iraqis
altering their air defense system. We have not seen examples of
higher alert,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Cohen said that if U.S. aircraft or forces are
threatened, ``it will be met with a very vigorous response.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has about 20,000 military personnel in the
region, down from earlier in the year when the U.S. presence was
fortified in response to Iraq's refusal to allow United Nations
officials to inspect possible weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he did not expect to boost military manpower in the
region because of the latest incident.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, an Iraqi official called the incident ``proof of the
aggressiveness of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unjustified, aggressive act. No radar was opened,''
said an official at the Ministry of Culture and Information,
according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi news agency said the missile struck a drinking water
reservoir, according to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Persian Gulf War in 1991, the United States and its
allies have used warplanes to patrol the southern part of Iraq. The
daytime incident occurred near Basra in southern Iraq, around 1:30
am., EDT.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. jet was part of a 10-plane patrol that included four
British Tornadoes who were enforcing the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi radar had ``locked on'' or ``painted'' the British
planes, which is viewed as a sign that that surface-to-air missiles
would soon be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the U.S. jet, rather than the British, fired the
missile because it was equipped with HARM missiles, which he said
was best equipped to target the radar site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a split-second type of operation,'' he said. ``We have
a lock-on of the radar only seconds at a time. And so this decision
was made on that kind of a split-second decision-making status.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Secretary said it was not clear whether the Iraqi
military site had been hit. The Associated Press reported that
British officials said they believed it had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 planes in the allied contingent returned to the base
safely.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Central Command in Tampa, Fla., plans to order
resumption of the patrols.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who is in China, was notified of the incident
by his National Security Advisor Sandy Berger while he was in route
to his hotel in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   While the White House found out about the missile firing soon
after it occurred, President Clinton was not informed until eight
hours later, about the same time the media found out about the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official traveling with Clinton said that
officials delayed telling him about the missile firing because of
the apparent routine nature of the incident and the desire to get
more details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
