<SLUG> BC-OYSTERS-RECALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF PEOPLE SICK FROM TAINTED TEXAS OYSTERS UP TO 128 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Fla., La., Calif., Colo. and N.M.) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
and CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ The number of people reported to have been
sickened by raw Galveston Bay oysters jumped again, going from 107
Monday to 128 Tuesday, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas Department of Health telephone hotline still was ringing
Tuesday with calls from people who have had intestinal problems
they think were caused by eating raw oysters and from health
officials who treated possible victims of the recent outbreak of
Vibrio parahaemolyticus, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the outbreak, which has shut down harvesting of
oysters by fishermen who lease state-controlled beds in the bay,
remains unknown, said David Estlack, of the Texas Department of
Health's Seafood Safety Division. This outbreak is the first of its
kind in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Results of tests on oysters and water from the bay beds are due
in about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers have been working since Friday to keep suspect
oysters from being served in restaurants across Texas, California,
Colorado, Florida, Louisiana and New Mexico. At least 18 of the
people who reported falling ill after eating oysters since early
June were customers.
</P>
<P>
   Estlack said state health officials believe oyster wholesalers
and restaurateurs have taken all the suspect oyster shipments off
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Although some have suggested that high heat and low salinity in
bay waters because of drought contributed to development of the
Vibrio parahaemolyticus in oysters to levels high enough to cause
illness, Estlack said state officials aren't convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a commonly occurring organism in sea water,'' Estlack
said. ``It has nothing to do with pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms from eating tainted oysters include diarrhea, abdominal
cramps, nausea, fever vomiting and headache, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   People who have suffered such symptoms within a day or two of
eating raw oysters have been asked to report the illness to state
officials by calling 1-888-883-9997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
