A5303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-robertsoncolumn-HNS &LR;      07-01 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-robertson </SLUG>
 column -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Innumerable aces &QL; 
don't serve public
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ The rains stopped Tuesday, and, suddenly, so
did the wild torrent of aces. If there is an obvious correlation,
it escapes me. But no matter. Good news is good news _ on both
counts.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis is supposed to be about strategy, about plotting one's
way through the minefield of a match, about probing and prodding
until a seam is found in the opponent's defense. It is not supposed
to be about beating him unconscious with a Kevlar-graphite stick,
which for all practical purposes is what grass-court tennis has
come to among the, ahem, gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   A holdover habit from the last century at Wimbledon is to refer
to the ``gentlemen's singles.'' It would be more appropriate today
to call the competition ``Neanderthal men's singles.'' Fittingly,
both Goran Ivanisevic and Richard Krajicek are sporting new
tattoos, and Ivanisevic has also grown a beard. He looks like a
Barbary pirate without the eye patch.
</P>
<P>
   Crash. Fifteen, love. Boom. Thirty, love. Bam. Forty, love. Oh,
yes, smashing. Watching the Centre Court grass die is more
exciting. If you've seen one ace, you've seen most of them.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the fourth round, Ivanisevic, Krajicek, Pete Sampras
and Mark Philippoussis _ a k a ``Scud'' _ were each averaging 22 or
more aces per match and winning 90-plus percent of their
first-serve points. Thomas Enqvist, an extreme case, was down 0-2,
0-30 before he actually touched his racket (barely) to a Sampras
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Women more watchable
</P>
<P>
   If clay is the great equalizer, routinely reducing the big
hitters to also-rans at Roland Garros, grass is the great
terminator. In effect, it shrinks the size of a skidding tennis
ball traveling 130 mph to that of a BB.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. These days, with rackets having been engineered
into becoming quasi-lethal weapons, devices only the NRA could
embrace, the women play the more interesting lawn tennis. They
actually have rallies and stuff.
</P>
<P>
   You'll note there is no relationship whatsoever between the
ace-count standings and the very predictable look of the distaff
draw in Wimbledon's quarterfinals. None of the last eight still
standing is ranked among the top four in said category.
</P>
<P>
   Although Venus Williams blows away her peers in service velocity
_ with a top speed of 125 mph, she has been surpassed by only 10 of
the men _ she rarely smacks an ace past anyone. Virginia
Ruano-Pascual whiffed but once against Williams on Tuesday, yet
Venus won easily in barely an hour's worth of effort.
</P>
<P>
   By coming to the net and volleying, Williams succeeded in
short-circuiting the Spaniard's intended impersonation of a human
backboard. As Venus noted later: ``I saw that she wanted to hit the
ball at least 50 times on one point, and I figured that on grass
that really shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not. But the men go too far in the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   No Borgs here
</P>
<P>
   The four blokes with the best chance of winning the Cup are also
the same Four Aces I've already mentioned. Despite tapering off
drastically in the fourth round, averaging a paltry 13 each per
victory, Ivanisevic, Philippoussis, Krajicek and Sampras are still
the runaway leaders. Goran's norm of 26, down from 30, is more than
any of the eight remaining women have total.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he calls Wimbledon ``the most important tournament for
me.'' It's the only tournament for him. He had dropped nine
first-round matches in the 14 events he had played this year before
coming here. If somebody returns Goran's serve, a dastardly chore
because he's 6-4 and lefthanded, half the time he doesn't know what
to do next other than cuss up a storm in Croatian.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever accused Ivanisevic of having fellow lefty Rod
Laver's tactical acumen. Of course, the Rocket probably never fired
104 rockets in four matches as Gorin' Goran has, either.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sweet, baby-faced Tim Henman, England's honey, turns
into a hun when he swaggers onto Centre Court. Nobody left in the
tournament has served harder than Henman's 133 mph, and he has
himself whacked 49 aces in reaching the quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Wimbledon today makes the memory of Bjorn Borg's
patiently hacking away for hours on end from the baseline seem a
fantasy. Borg was the ultimate right-place, right-time guy,
reaching the apex of his brilliant career when there was a dearth
of serve-and-volleyers and right before technology made his winning
form obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   The Borg style was tedious in its own way, but it at least
resembled tennis as it was intended to be played. At Wimbledon,
circa the cold, wet summer of '98, we would be better off, I think,
with a little less bang for our bucks. Uh, pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
