<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP TESTIFIES BEFORE GRAND JURY IN CLINTON INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Linda Tripp, whose tape recordings triggered a
criminal investigation of President Clinton, went before a federal
grand jury Tuesday to tell what she knows about the alleged
presidential affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Except for short breaks and lunch in a vacant room at the
federal courthouse, Tripp spent six hours with the panel examining
Clinton's relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. Tripp secretly taped a number of her phone conversations
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old Pentagon worker was expected to return for more
testimony Thursday and in coming weeks, as prosecutors try to
determine whether Clinton and Lewinsky had sex, lied about it in
sworn statements and obstructed justice by trying to conceal the
alleged affair.
</P>
<P>
   Looking weary as she left the U.S. District Courthouse, Tripp
answered ``yes'' when asked if her session with the grand jury had
been easy. Otherwise, she declined comments as she made her way
past dozens of reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Her two grown children _ Allison and Ryan _ stood alongside her
attorney, Anthony Zaccagnini, outside the courthouse as he quoted
Tripp saying it had been ``easy to truthfully answer the questions
posed ... by the prosecutor and the grand jury.'' The lawyer
declined to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   After six months of virtual silence and seclusion, Tripp _ who
is viewed unfavorably by a vast majority of Americans in public
opinion polls _ said she was looking forward to her session with
grand jurors. Among her goals, she said in a Washington Post
interview, was convincing  &UR; them  &LR; she had not manipulated Lewinsky
as part of a book deal or an effort to embarrass the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not cultivate Monica _ she cultivated me,'' said Tripp,
who is twice the age of Lewinsky. ``Monica is a very worldly
person. She educated me.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials dismissed questions about the timing of
Tripp's appearance, which coincided with the president's trip to
China. ``It hasn't had any impact on our work here,'' White House
spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House
counsel's office, said, ``We'll let the American people draw their
own conclusions about Linda Tripp.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is being used by independent counsel Kenneth
Starr to examine whether Clinton or his associates tried to cover
up his alleged sexual misbehavior with Lewinsky or Kathleen Willey,
who has testified that the president fondled her during an
encounter outside the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Lewinsky have denied under oath engaging in
sex. Clinton has said publicly that he did not have a sexual
relationship with the former White House intern and did not
encourage anyone to lie. He also denied any improper behavior
during his November 1993 meeting with Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, an 18-year civil servant, was on the fringes of both the
alleged Lewinsky affair and the Willey encounter. A holdover from
the administration of President Bush, Tripp worked as a secretary
at the White House. She was among the last people who saw deputy
White House counsel Vincent Foster alive, and testified before a
Senate committee investigating his death, which was ruled a
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, Tripp _ who by then had begrudgingly accepted a
transfer to an $88,200-a-year job at the Pentagon _ was quoted by
Newsweek magazine saying that in November 1993 she had seen Willey
emerge from the Oval Office with her lipstick smeared and her
clothing askew. Tripp recalled Willey smiling and saying she would
``never believe'' what had just happened in her meeting with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Before the article appeared, Tripp discussed the Willey episode
with Clinton's long-time friend and confidant, deputy White House
counsel Bruce Lindsey, who was involved in efforts to minimize
potential political damage Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   It was about this time that Tripp, who was working on a book
deal with New York publicist Lucianne Goldberg, began taping her
telephone conversations with Lewinsky. The two women had become
friends after Lewinsky had been shipped from the White House to a
job at the Pentagon. The working title of Tripp's book was Behind
Closed Doors: What I Saw at the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Tripp turned over about 20 hours of taped
conversations to Starr's investigators. She also gave them the
so-called ``talking points,'' two typewritten pages she said
Lewinsky provided as a guide to help throw Jones' lawyers off the
scent when they asked about the Willey encounter.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Starr's deputies, Tripp later wore an
electronic eavesdropping device and led Lewinsky through another
lengthy discussion of her alleged White House trysts with Clinton
and his effort to keep the relationship secret. Shortly after that
session, Tripp rushed off to meet with Jones' attorneys as they
prepared to question Clinton under oath about alleged extramarital
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Starr used the most recent tape to help secure
authority from Attorney General Janet Reno and a three-judge
federal panel to expand his investigation of Whitewater to include
possible White House involvement in obstruction of justice in the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   In the tapes, according to published reports, Lewinsky discusses
a sexual relationship with the president and attempts by Clinton
and his friend Vernon Jordan to keep her from talking about it.
Some accounts indicate that Tripp appears leading Lewinsky into
making what could be incriminating statements.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a frequent golfing partner of the president, denied any
knowledge of a sexual relationship between Clinton and Lewinsky. He
has acknowledged trying to help Lewinsky get a job in New York at
the behest of Clinton's personal secretary, Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Since turning over the tapes, Tripp has continued her Pentagon
job but has worked from her suburban Maryland home and, at times,
from a government safehouse under the protection of FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
