<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-CONTROL-HNS &LR;      07-01 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS TOUT POSSIBILITY OF CONTROLLING, NOT ELIMINATING, AIDS
VIRUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Eradication of the AIDS virus from the body may never
be possible, but that does not mean the disease cannot be
controlled, experts said Tuesday at the 12th World AIDS Conference.
</P>
<P>
   While not optimistic about eliminating every cell infected with
the human immunodeficiency virus, Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of
the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Disease in
Bethesda, Md., said he is hopeful the immune system can be
strengthened to control remaining cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us carry a herpes virus,'' he said. ``But we have
immune systems that keep it under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the ability of the immune system to recognize and
fight HIV would be the second step in treatment, after most of the
virus has been eliminated by potent drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A cure seemed right around the corner two years ago with reports
at the Vancouver AIDS conference in Canada that triple-drug
combinations, including the new protease inhibitors, were reducing
HIV levels in patients to undetectable levels and prolonging lives.
</P>
<P>
   But Fauci and others discovered a pool of inactive immune system
cells silently harboring HIV, making the task of a cure much
harder.
</P>
<P>
   This pool, spread throughout the body, appears to keep the
infection alive, even when treatment has reduced the virus in the
blood to undetectable levels for years, Fauci said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Dr. David Ho, head of the Aaron Diamond AIDS
Research Center in New York City, had planned to discontinue
treatment in some patients where new drugs had reduced the virus to
undetectable levels for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But discovery of this pool of infected cells caused Ho to change
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to plan strategies to deal with this late reservoir,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fauci said that when he evaluated people treated within days of
their infection with HIV, he found evidence that the pool of
resting infected cells already existed, indicating it is
established early in the infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this tells us is that even with the earliest possible
therapy, a pool of latently (or quiet) infected cells is
established very early,`` he said. ``The obvious question is 'Can
we do something to purge those latently infected cells?'''
</P>
<P>
   Fauci said it is not likely to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roberto Silicano of Johns Hopkins University Medical School
was more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now able to think in a rational way about HIV
eradication. My conclusion is that cure of HIV infection is not a
myth. In my opinion, this is a problem that we can tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Silicano said the newly discovered reservoir may be a major
barrier, but one that can be surmounted.
</P>
<P>
   The number of cells is low, no more than 1 million in some
cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took all of these cells, put them together and spun
them down to the bottom of a test tube, you would have a little
pellet that is barely visible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If patients are treated early, the size of the pool might be
reduced and the gradual death of cells in the pool accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been on the triple-drug combinations long enough to
determine how long it would take for the cells in the pool to die,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, Silicano said it has not been proven that
the reservoir can rekindle infection in a patient who stops
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, it is possible that in some situations, the
immune system may be able to control the small amount of virus that
is released when cells in this compartment are activated,''
Silicano said.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened in at least one case in Germany, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fauci warned that recent reports of serious side effects from
protease inhibitors and virus strains that are resistant to the
drug may make it impossible to continue treating patients lifelong.
</P>
<P>
   Some patients have developed high cholesterol and other high
blood fat levels, abnormal deposits of fat in the abdomen and upper
shoulders, and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not feasible to treat people indefinitely with toxic
anti-viral drugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, he said, doctors have to develop a one-two
punch _ hitting the virus hard with potent anti-viral drugs and
then boosting immunity so that it can contain any deposits of
virally infected cells that remain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
