<HEADER>
A5325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-THREAT-NYT &LR;      07-01 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA, OTHER NATIONS PONDER THREAT OF U.S. CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA, June 30 _ Nineteen nations, including America's closest
friends, joined forces at a conference here Tuesday to protect
themselves from what they see as the gravest threats to their
collective cultures _ free trade and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the 19 countries, including Mexico, Britain and
Brazil, came to Ottawa to discuss ways to distinguish culture from
ordinary commerce, with the goal of denying the American
entertainment industry easy access to their markets.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, which organized the meeting, set the tone of the event
by not inviting representatives of the United States to
participate, though invitations had been extended to about 40
countries in all and half accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials said the United States was not included
because it did not have a Cabinet-level culture minister as do the
other countries. But the representative from Mexico, Rafael Tovar y
de Teresa, is president of the National Council for Culture and
Arts, which is roughly the equivalent of the National Endowment for
the Arts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the intent behind the snub seems to have been to
prevent the United States from imposing its view that Canada and
many other countries hide behind culture to erect commercial trade
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said they closed the meeting to the public and to
news organizations to encourage frankness. But after some
embarrassment to the Canadians, the United States was allowed to
send observers from its embassy in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Observers and participants said the morning sessions went by
without any open hostility to American policies. Still, American
officials tried their best to keep the obvious slight from turning
into yet another skirmish over cultural policies. Gordon D. Giffin,
the U.S. ambassador to Canada, said he had recently met with
Canada's culture minister, Sheila Copps, and discussed at length
the blurry line between culture and the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that we'll be able to try to work things out,''
said Giffin, who attended a dinner for the culture ministers on
Monday night at the Canadian Museum of Civilization in Hull,
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything that happened here was as low key as Giffin's
statement suggests. Canada and Mexico share little with countries
like Iceland, Croatia and others that attended the meeting except
for the fear that Hollywood and the rest of the American
entertainment industry threaten their cultures.
</P>
<P>
   The countries that took part want to form a special partnership
with enough influence to insure that culture is treated as an
important characteristic of a nation's identity, and not just
another category of merchandise governed by new international
treaties that seek unrestrained trade _ including films, television
programs, books and magazines _ between nations. ``Culture should
not be locked up in agreements on investment,'' said Marita Ulvsko,
Sweden's minister of culture.
</P>
<P>
   At a similar meeting on culture sponsored by the United Nations
in Stockholm in March, delegates recognized the need for closer
cooperation to protect their cultures. They agreed to press for
special exemptions for cultural needs in the continuing
negotiations for the latest global trade pact, the Multilateral
Agreement on Investment.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Ottawa, concrete actions seemed to be few, beyond
establishing a World Wide Web site linking culture ministries. But
there was an outpouring of concern over the loss of a nation's
culture to the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Because most of its population shares both the English language,
as well as a continent-wide border with the United States, Canada
is in a unique position. Sixty percent of all the books sold in
Canada come from other countries, primarily the United States.
Three-quarters of the music played on Canadian radio is not
Canadian. Four of five magazines sold on newsstands in Canada are
foreign, primarily American. And when it comes to films, 96 percent
of what is shown on Canadian screens is foreign, the overwhelmingly
majority of it from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the best that Hollywood has to offer,'' said
Mrs. Copps, an outspoken critic of American policies on cultural
exports. ``In Canada, we also know, however, that culture is more
than Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, though it also shares a long border with the United
States, feels protected from overexposure to American culture by
the Spanish language. Although American films and television
programs are popular, the need for translations limits their broad
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to recognize that there are international cultural
forces that promote the idea of common cultural standards,'' said
Tovar y de Teresa, who added that there was no need to panic. ``We
should be less fearful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he did not agree with the decision to exclude the
United States and that he hoped the next meeting of culture
ministers, which will be held in Mexico in 1999, would be more
inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's attempts to protect its culture have often infuriated
the United States. In the past, Canada has removed an American
country music cable station because a Canadian version became
available, and the government requires television and radio
stations to broadcast a minimum amount of Canadian material.
</P>
<P>
   But the most bruising battle with the United States has been
over Canada's attempts to protect its domestic magazines, which it
considers an essential aspect of Canadian culture. Canada has
desperately tried to keep out cheaply produced Canadian editions of
big American magazines, like Sports Illustrated, that carry few
Canadian articles but offer bargain advertising rates that the
Canadians can't match.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a stiff 80 percent excise tax on Canadian advertising
profits in local editions of American magazines was rejected by the
World Trade Organization, an international body that oversees trade
among most nations of the world, after the United States filed a
complaint. A proposal floated on Monday morning to impose a heavy
tax on Canadian companies that take out ads in the local editions
was abandoned later in the day. Now Canada is reported to be
considering an outright ban to prevent Canadian companies from
placing ads in those editions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 0944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ON-DEMAND02-COX     07-01 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ON-DEMAND02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOKS ON DEMAND: A PUBLISHING BREAKTHROUGH?
 &HT;    580&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The book business is turning to a new page:
on-demand printing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it could work in the not-very-distant future. Looking
for a volume of retro rhymes, some bell-bottomed bibliophile will
bop into a local shop and browse menus on the computer screen of an
automatic book machine. Passing a credit card through an electronic
reader, the customer will transmit an order to a digital library,
which will then bounce a signal off a satellite to the book
machine's built-in printer.
</P>
<P>
   Within five minutes or so, the book lover will be holding a
fresh paperbound copy of Rod McKuen's ``Listen to the Warm'' _
groovy, but sometimes hard to find, poetry from the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   This emerging technology could resurrect thousands of titles
that have gone out of print and exponentially expand the choices
for book buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have a big impact in terms of customer service,''
said Joyce Meskis, manager of the Tattered Covers Bookstore in
Denver, where the first BookMachine(cq) is to be installed by the
end of this year. ``There are so many titles in print that no
bookstore, now matter how large, could stock them all.''
</P>
<P>
   The in-store BookMachine is still being developed by the On
Demand Machine Corp. of St. Louis, but publishers and printers are
already using similar technology to take orders by phone or
Internet to provide next-day service on custom-made books.
</P>
<P>
   Through its Lightning Print Division, for instance, the nation's
largest book wholesaler, Ingram Books, prints books on demand _ as
few as one per order _ in its high-tech facility in LaVergne,
Tenn., and then ships the book or books to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real significance is that a book never has to go out of
print,'' said Larry Brewster, an Ingram vice president and general
manager of Lightning Print. ``In the long run, more books are going
to be available in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   The same on-demand principles are being applied to other
elements of the popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, CDnow, a cyberspace record shop, lets customers
create customized CDs by selecting the artists and hits they want
from a Web site catalog of digitalized music. When the order and
credit card authorization are received via the Internet, the
company produces a personalized compact disc and mails it to the
customer. CDnow has licensed 60,000 songs from artists ranging from
Louis Armstrong to Patsy Cline to Bob Marley.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the book business _ burdened by the high costs of
keeping inventory on store shelves and returning unsold volumes _
that foresees quick economic relief from on-demand service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers no longer have to worry about unprofitable print
runs and warehousing costs,'' said Brewster. ``With on-demand
technology, you print to meet your demand _ whether the demand is
one copy or 1,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The system reduces publishers' reprint risks for books that sell
slowly or sporadically over a long period. With on-demand printing,
the publisher no longer has to print a minimum run of 1,000 or so
copies and keep the books on shelves until orders hopefully arrive,
or allow books with some, albeit slight, demand to go out of print.
</P>
<P>
   ``We face this issue every month when we have our reprint
meetings,'' said Steven Schragis, publisher of Carol Publishing
Group in New Jersey. ``There are a lot of hard decisions when we're
out of stock on a particular title and fewer than 100 re-orders
come in. This program provides the answer for those books.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Ross, president of On Demand Machine Corp., said the
BookMachine will pay for itself in savings for bookstores. Ross
said $1.64 of the price of every book sold now goes to cover the
costs of shipping, inventory and return of unsold books to the
publisher. The BookMachine will eliminate these expenses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the BookMachine will be leased, rather than sold, to
bookstores in order to ensure quality control. Many authors have
guarantees of print quality written into contracts with publishers,
Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Another major publisher involved in on-demand printing is Simon
&AMP; Shuster, which already has a digital library of 12,000 titles and
is adding 4,000 to 6,000 per year, said Don Seise, assistant vice
president of the company's Demand Production Center in Ramsey, N.J.
Most current on-demand printing is for paperbacks, he said, but
customers will be able to get hardcover books ``very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   While it might cost about $4.32 to print a book in the on-demand
system _ versus $1.85 each using the traditional offset printing
method in a 5,000-book run _ the advantage is obvious if only 200
books sell, Seise pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   The system is especially suited for academic books, where a
college professor might require a class of 50 students to buy a
certain book every semester or where textbooks are frequently
updated, rendering earlier editions obsolete, said Brewster of
Ingram's Lightning Press.
</P>
<P>
   However, on-demand printing will probably not be used for
best-sellers, at least until the technology makes another leap
forward, since traditional printing is cheaper if the books sell
fast and returns are minimal.
</P>
<P>
   So bookstores won't be bookless for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 0950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
