</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-MEGAN-SHOOTING-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBOR HELD IN `MEGAN'S LAW' SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH, N.J. _ A 23-year-old neighbor of a paroled rapist who
authorities say was the target of vigilante gunfire two weeks ago
was arrested Tuesday and accused of firing five bullets into the
house where the parolee lived.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting at the home of the parolee, Frank Penna, 55,
occurred two weeks after the police circulated fliers notifying
neighbors and officials, under New Jersey's ``Megan's Law,'' that a
convicted rapist lived in their town.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect arrested Tuesday was identified as Jimmy Johnson,
23, of Linden, N.J. Johnson lives with his mother, Jean, and two
sisters, 9 and 17, in a two-family house around the corner from
Penna's home.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday at her home, the suspect's mother said
he was upset after reading the flier in early June about Penna.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Johnson said she did not think that her son had fired the
five bullets into Penna's house. But after reading the flier, Mrs.
Johnson said, her son said: ```Oh, my God, my baby sister lives
next door to a rapist.' His mind just snapped that something might
happen to his baby sister. Me, my daughter and his baby sister are
Jimmy's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was charged with aggravated assault, illegal possession
of a handgun and illegal use of a handgun and ordered held in
$150,000 bail by Judge John Triarsi of New Jersey Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the importance New Jersey officials attached to
the case, the state attorney general, Peter G. Verniero,
interrupted his schedule to travel here from Trenton to announce
the arrest and denounce vigilantism against paroled sex offenders,
whose names and addresses are distributed to neighbors in police
fliers as a result of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law enforcement community is united in our intolerance of
any act of vigilantism against a known sex offender,'' Verniero
said in a news conference at the Union County Prosecutor's office.
``Megan's Law is not about violence or retribution. Unlawful
conduct will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The law recently survived one protracted legal challenge in the
federal court system and is now facing another by the office of New
Jersey's Public Defender. Both before and after the June 16
shooting, Verniero has voiced concerns that the law could be
legally jeopardized by any outbreak of violent acts against paroled
sex offenders who are publicly identified.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Defender's lawsuit, now before a federal appeals
court in Philadelphia, contends that the law is an unconstitutional
invasion of the privacy rights of the parolees.
</P>
<P>
   Until the shooting, the authorities say, Penna had lived without
incident at his home since his parole from prison in 1992, after
serving 16 years for raping two teen-age girls in Linden in 1976.
State parole officials say he is self-employed. They say he has not
violated terms of parole in the six years since his release.
</P>
<P>
   He has made no public statements about the shooting. Neighbors
say they have not seen him since.
</P>
<P>
   None of the bullets struck his basement apartment. All five
pierced the windows and walls of the first-floor apartment of Joan
Bazydlo, 66, as she watched television. She was not hurt.
Immediately after the shooting, she left the apartment and lived
with friends until she returned last Thursday. Ms. Bazydlo said
today she was thrilled that an arrest had been made.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Verniero and the Union County prosecutor, Thomas V. Manahan,
said they were confident of the evidence detectives had assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have evidence that leads us to the inescapable conclusion
this was a case of vigilantism,'' Manahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation has led to no other path,'' Verniero said.
</P>
<P>
   They said Johnson went to Linden police headquarters voluntarily
this afternoon after they distributed word in his neighborhood that
they wanted to question him about tips that he had a .45-caliber
handgun. Tests on shell casings found at Penna's house determined
that the five shots came from a .45, the authorities have said.
</P>
<P>
   During questioning Tuesday, Johnson told detectives that his .45
was at his father's home, Manahan said. Detectives found the
handgun there, the prosecutor said. Tests on Tuesday afternoon
confirmed that the recovered handgun was the one used to shoot at
Penna's house, Manahan said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Verniero declined to say if the suspect had made a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Manahan and Verniero said they were led to Johnson by a series
of tips. One resident, they said, saw two men running from the
vicinity of Penna's home after the shooting. Others residents of
Penna's neighborhood then directed detectives to a particular
neighborhood where rumors circulated about the shooting. There,
Manahan said, detectives picked up information about Johnson's
owning a .45. Eventually, they began looking for him for
questioning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 0953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MAFIA-PLEA-NYT &LR;      07-01 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAFIA-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RESCINDS PLEA DEAL, INFORMER MAY FACE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four years ago, Anthony S. Casso, who was depicted by
the authorities as one of the Mafia's most notorious leaders,
struck a deal with federal prosecutors. For disclosing mob secrets
and testifying against other high-ranking gangsters, he would
probably avoid a lifetime prison sentence even though he had
participated in 15 murder plots and other violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal judge in Brooklyn has authorized the government to
rescind that plea agreement on the ground that Casso, known by the
nickname Gaspipe, bribed prison guards to smuggle food and liquor
for him while in custody and that he lied about other prominent
mobsters who become government witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   He could now face life in prison. In a ruling released
yesterday, Judge Frederic Block of Federal District Court in
Brooklyn found that Casso, 58, had breached his signed cooperation
deal with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also denied his request that he be returned to the
federal witness protection program. Casso had said that he was
being treated harshly by prison authorities and that his safety was
endangered in a normal prison environment.
</P>
<P>
   Block's ruling clears the way for Casso to be sentenced next
Wednesday in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early '90s, federal law enforcement
officials identified Casso as the underboss and consigliere in the
Lucchese crime family, one of the five Mafia gangs in the New York
City region. In 1994, after becoming an informer, he pleaded guilty
to 70 crimes, including murder, attempted murder, extortion and
racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plea agreement, prosecutors said they would
recommend leniency as a reward for his assistance in solving Mafia
crimes. He was placed in the witness protection program, which
provides inmates with more comforts than other prisoners get and
with new identities to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, George A. Stamboulidis, an assistant U.S. attorney,
told Casso's lawyers that he had violated the cooperation agreement
and that the government would not recommend leniency. Stamboulidis
said that Casso, while in two unidentified prisons, had assaulted
another inmate and bribed prison guards with cash, auto tires and
tickets to Broadway shows to supply him with vodka, wine and
steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that Casso had made false statements that would
have wrongly discredited the testimony of two other top mobsters
who had defected: Salvatore Gravano, the former underboss of the
Gambino crime family, and Alphonso D'Arco, the former acting boss
of the Lucchese family.
</P>
<P>
   Casso, in a motion asking that the government honor the plea
agreement, said that prosecutors had acted in bad faith by not
pursuing his leads and not permitting him to testify at federal and
state trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put,'' Block said in his ruling, ``criminal behavior by
cooperators should be condemned, not condoned, and repudiation of
the government's obligations under a cooperation agreement is an
effective means of delivering such an important message.''
</P>
<P>
   Casso's lawyer, Matthew J. Brief, declined to be interviewed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
