<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX     07-01 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Submit to government graciously
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c: 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When Southern Baptists recently voted to amend
their essential statement of beliefs to declare that a wife should
``submit herself graciously'' to her husband's leadership, I
wondered if they could get away with that.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, it would seem to be illegal under some
federal law _ or at least unconstitutional _ for any
state-sanctioned institution to call for unequal treatment between
the sexes .
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Southern Baptists may not believe that wives
submitting to their husband's leadership is unequal as long as
husbands live up to their end of the bargain, which says a husband
must ``provide for, protect and lead his family.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if Southern Baptists, or some other denomination,
didn't believe that the marriage partnership was equal and said so
right up front? Could the government step in at that point?
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment says, ``Congress shall make no law
respecting an establishment of religion.'' That separation between
church and state appears to mean that the government cannot meddle
with the faith-based practices of religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, logic tells us that our society would never allow a
religion to practice human sacrifices, as many religions have done
throughout human history. Courts have allowed at least one religion
to practice animal sacrifices but that was highly controversial and
may have been overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the government got away with telling the Mormons that
they couldn't practice polygamy even though that was a faith-based
practice among consenting adults that harmed no one and was not
considered unusual in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The government felt that a man with multiple wives somehow hurt
society. In the case of the Mormons, the government sided with
established American religions and its own government-approved view
of traditional marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to interfere with the Mormons' belief in polygamy
appears to be in violation of the First Amendment's establishment
clause. But the government got away with it because that's what
most people wanted, an exercise that might be described as the
tyranny of the majority.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, when David Koresh, the Branch Davidians'
self-proclaimed messiah, declared that only he could have sex with
all Branch Davidian women, the government had a clear duty to step
in and stop him from committing statutory rape on the children,
despite claims that sex with children was a faith-based practice.
</P>
<P>
   A Libertarian-type argument might be made that the government
shouldn't be in the business of sanctioning marriages in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   This argument would hold that it's none of the government's
business whether its citizens enter into the institution of holy
matrimony. Marriages should be left to the preachers, priests,
rabbis. Magistrates, bureaucrats, politicians and tax collectors
should butt out.
</P>
<P>
   Why does the government go to all the trouble to pass laws and
procedures to perform civil marriage ceremonies? Is it a courtesy
to atheists?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. More likely, however, the government has gotten
involved in marriages for the same reason the government gets
involved in everything _ it thinks it knows what's best, there are
votes in it and anything the government controls, it also can tax.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians know there are votes in being pro-family, at least
the popular view of America's traditional family structure.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Congress sees votes in taking up the Christian
Coalition's war on the so-called ``marriage tax.'' Despite the
flaws and the rush to judgment, legislation to repeal the marriage
tax will pass because the politicians, like the Southern Baptists,
are in the marriage business to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
