</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKFILMS02-COX     07-01 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKFILMS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cable TV festival brings back early black films
 &HT;    (With BLACKFILMS-LINEUP)
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A lot of independent films are made to satisfy
the creative desires of the filmmaker. But pioneering black
independent filmmakers of the 1920s and '30s had a more profound
goal: to counter the demeaning, racist depictions of their people
seen in mainstream films at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Few Americans, black or white, know anything about these films,
called ``race films'' because they were made especially for black
audiences. Distribution was limited when they were made, and, in
the decades since, many have been forever lost.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Classic Movies has located 29 of these historic classics
and will air them on five consecutive Wednesdays, beginning July 1,
under the umbrella title ``A Separate Cinema.'' The films start at
7 p.m. and sometimes run all night, so serious film buffs should
prepare to do some serious taping.
</P>
<P>
   Husband-and-wife actors Ossie Davis and Ruby Dee serve as hosts
of the festival from the historic Douglass Theater in Macon, Ga.,
one of the first all-black theaters in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Modern audiences may be surprised by some of these movies. In
prolific filmmaker Oscar Micheaux's 1920 film ``Within Our Gates,''
for example, there are graphic scenes of lynchings and scenes of a
white man attempting to rape a black woman. In a later Micheaux
film, ``Scar of Shame,'' the focus is on class issues within the
black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these films first came out, there was a whole spectrum of
response among blacks,'' said Thomas Cripps, author and retired
history professor from Morgan State University in Baltimore. ``Some
people thought it was great because everybody was black. Others
said, 'Oh, you shouldn't see those Oscar Micheaux movies. They're
full of crime and sin and corruption.' There were others who
thought they were primitive compared to Hollywood films. That whole
spectrum surely will repeat itself. Some will marvel, and others
will say this is a past we should forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Cripps, who is white, became interested in black cinema when he
was studying Southern history and working on his dissertation on
black Republican politics in the South. A pioneer in the study of
black film, he wrote a paper in 1962, ``The Negro Reaction to the
Motion Picture `The Birth of a Nation,''' that attracted attention
in academic circles.
</P>
<P>
   White viewers, who probably have never heard of filmmakers such
as Micheaux, likely will have the same varied responses. Indeed,
the production values are often crude and the acting less than
impressive. But the stories, especially in the context of the
post-Civil War times, are fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of this early work has been dismissed because it was
thought of as perpetuating stereotypes,'' said Pearl Bowser, film
archivist and producer of ``Midnight Ramble,'' the '94 PBS
documentary about race films that introduces the TCM festival.
``Even Micheaux was criticized for that. ... We need to look at
these movies today not from the viewpoint of Hollywood stereotypes
but in relation to what the filmmaker is trying to tell us about
how he uses those stereotypes in the context of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn-of-the-century films and literature, black people were
portrayed as ape-like, oversexed and simple-minded. Such insulting
portrayals inspired the first independent black filmmakers, who
formed their own companies and produced their films on shoestring
budgets. They were driven by the lack of opportunity in mainstream
movies and by the deep desire to respond to negative images. The
biggest inspiration in the black film movement came from D.W.
Griffith's 1915 epic, ``The Birth of a Nation,'' which glorified
the Ku Klux Klan and vilified blacks. President Wilson praised the
film as an ``artistic triumph,'' and crowds flocked to see it.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, ``race movies'' arrived. Brothers George and
Noble Johnson of Omaha, Neb., formed the Lincoln Motion Picture
Company and began producing films. Their 1916 movie ``Birth of a
Race'' was a pointed response to Griffith's movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interoffice memos from Lincoln Films referred to the need to
get something on screen that repudiates what Griffith put on the
screen,'' said Cripps, a consultant on the series. ``In essence,
they said, `We must make these because they make those.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, Micheaux, an author and rancher in South Dakota, wrote
and directed his first film, ``The Homesteader.'' Sadly, that film
has been lost, but ``Within Our Gates'' was recovered in 1979 by
Cripps. The American Film Institute had found several films in a
vault in Spain, and one was missing its opening title. Cripps was
called in to investigate, and he recognized the film as ``Within
Our Gates,'' a controversial work that was banned in the South
because theaters were afraid it would lead to rioting. Festival of
little-known talents
</P>
<P>
   ``A Separate Cinema'' is organized into theme nights, starting
Wednesday with an evening devoted to Micheaux films, including the
newly restored version of ``The Symbol of the Unconquered,'' a
romantic drama about racial pride that criticizes blacks who pass
for whites. It also includes a stinging attack on the KKK. The
restored version has a new score composed by jazz legend Max Roach.
</P>
<P>
   July 8th's presentations feature the films of the multi talented
Paul Robeson, one of the few early black stars with whom white
viewers may be familiar, and Herbert Jeffrey, who starred in a
series of Westerns and soon became known as ``the black Gene
Autry'' because of his singing cowboy roles.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, the spotlight shines on the films of the glamorous
and exotic Josephine Baker and the crusading director-writer-actor
Spencer Williams (best-known today as Andy from ``Amos 'n' Andy''),
who spent most of the early '40s working in Texas (based in Dallas
but filming all over the state) making religious allegories such as
``The Blood of Jesus'' and ``Go Down, Death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those movies were very sentimentally religious,'' Cripps said.
``They were marvelously touching for being unashamedly
fundamentalist.''
</P>
<P>
   The films showcased on July 22 are crime stories, mirroring the
popular Warner Bros. gangster and mystery movies of the time. Ralph
Cooper, the top black mystery star, is featured.
</P>
<P>
   The festival winds up July 29 with sports and musical films of
the '30s and '40s. First up on the final night is ``The Jackie
Robinson Story,'' which starred the famous baseball player as
himself but was produced by a white company. This 1950 film marked
the end of the all-black race movies. Included in the musicals that
night is the film debut of Lena Horne in ``Duke Is Tops.'' Making
black films accessible
</P>
<P>
   So, why has it taken so long for these films to come to light?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just too many problems to mess with,'' Cripps said.
``They're a risk in terms of content because they're not like
Hollywood movies. They wear their low budgets on their sleeves. And
they've been inaccessible to the point that people say they're
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that fewer than 100 of an estimated 500 films produced
by black independents still exist is shocking, but Cripps said
there was no conscious attempt to get rid of them. Economics played
a big part in the loss. Because black film companies had so little
capital, they made fewer prints and had fewer vaults in which to
store them. Shot on nitrate film stock, they deteriorated quickly
and sometimes even exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood movies have disappeared, too,'' Cripps said. ``About
50 percent of all films ever made before 1950 were lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The early black films will have their largest audience ever
during the airing of ``A Separate Cinema.'' Even in their heyday,
race movies had limited exposure. They often were screened after
midnight (hence, the term ``midnight ramble'') in segregated
all-white theaters or in the relatively small number of all-black
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But they managed to have a profound impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were seen as a resource that could transform what people
thought of themselves,'' Cripps said.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway is TV critic for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
