<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: It's time for all to realize: Feminism is not dead
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend and I groaned in chorus over the Time magazine cover:
``Is Feminism Dead?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wishful thinking,'' harrumphed Lynda. ``How many times have
you seen that cover?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we shouldn't take it so personally. This was, after all,
the magazine that once asked the same question about God.
</P>
<P>
   The cover art got us hopping mad, all over again. The lineup of
photos was intended to represent the state of feminism throughout
the ages: Susan B. Anthony. Betty Friedan. Gloria Steinem. Ally
McBeal.
</P>
<P>
   Ally McBeal? What is she doing there? Is she the Anti-Feminist _
proof positive feminism today is a waif, next to nonexistent?
</P>
<P>
   Those of us still brazen enough to call ourselves feminists
aren't surprised by the Time article. Ally's part of a historic
lineup, all right _ media attempts to define, and diminish,
feminism. To explain who we are, what we think and how marginal we
are.
</P>
<P>
   Time trumpets: ``Feminism: It's All About Me! Want to know what
today's chic young feminist thinkers care about? Their bodies!
Themselves!''
</P>
<P>
   What evidence do they use to support their
``decline-of-feminism''? Where are they looking for the ``face of
feminism''?
</P>
<P>
   Surprise! They're looking at other magazines (Exhibit A is the
celebrity-studded 25th anniversary party for Ms. magazine). They're
looking at Hollywood and pop culture. They're looking everywhere
except the places where real women live.
</P>
<P>
   The story goes on to compare ``then and now,'' in quick
snippets, comparing feminism past to whatever is most frivolous in
today's society: protests against male violence and Vietnam vs.
Glenn Close and Whoopi Goldberg performing The Vagina Monologues (a
performance piece about female private parts). Mary Richards vs.
Ally McBeal. Helen Reddy vs. the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   What a clever sleight-of-hand, taking the most insulting images
of women and linking them with feminism. Since when are feminists
responsible for the Spice Girls? If the '60s were the high water
mark for feminism, how do you explain I Dream of Jeannie?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to pull examples from popular culture to prove
whatever point you want to make. It's a lot harder to visit the
places where feminism is at work in the lives of women.
</P>
<P>
   I wish Time had visited Imogen Trolander's park in Yellow
Springs. Correction: It's not Trolander's park, it's the Women's
Park, and she's busily preparing for its dedication July 19, in
honor of the 150th anniversary of the first Woman's Rights
Convention in Seneca Falls, N.Y. ``It's a real turnoff that the
popular national media is so insulting to women and so disregarding
of their strength, their work, their wisdom,'' Trolander said.
</P>
<P>
   Trolander, married for 50 years, has seen too much progress to
feel downhearted about a vapid magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course feminism is alive and well,'' she said. It's alive
and well in the home, in the workplace, and, she hopes, in the
Women's Park: ``It's not a park for a big achievers. It's a bed of
tiles with the name of a woman _ any woman that somebody wants to
honor _ and some few words that describe her.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be the kind of place where you could find the name of
your mother, your aunt, your kindergarten teacher. But you won't
find Ally McBeal.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
