<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE     07-01 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonnette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: ... So the risk of transmission with swimming pool
water, or even wastewater, is virtually nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where has the E. coli bacteria been all my life? As a kid, I
played in many swimming pools throughout the summers, but I don't
ever recall hearing about E. coli until recently. Is it a new
strain?
</P>
<P>
   A: It isn't new. The E. coli implicated in the current outbreak,
0157:H7, was identified in 1982 as a source of illness in people,
said the CDC's Katy Hopkins. That was the outbreak related to
contaminated hamburgers in the Northwest. There are literally
hundreds of strains of E. coli, most of which are harmless, Hopkins
added. They live within the intestines and don't cause any
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many times has Larry King of CNN been married?
</P>
<P>
   A: He took the vows for the seventh time last November.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain what ``derivatives'' are? I've read that many
banks and insurance companies are heavily invested in them.
</P>
<P>
   A: Derivatives are financial contracts whose gains and losses
are tied to the performance of underlying financial instruments,
such as stocks and bonds. An option to buy or sell a stock is one
example of a derivative. Many companies use derivatives to hedge,
or reduce risk, from changes in interest rates, currency values and
commodity prices. But they also are used for speculation, and some
derivatives are considered more risky than others.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the case of Jeff Smith, ``The Frugal Gourmet'' on PBS,
ever resolved? Several months ago I heard some accusations were
made about him, but I never saw a followup.
</P>
<P>
   A: Smith has been accused of molestation by several men who
allege that he used his power as their employer to force them to
perform sex acts with him years ago. Edward Winskill, Smith's
attorney, has denied all accusations in the lawsuits and in public
statements by the plaintiffs. No criminal charges have ever been
filed against Smith and the statute of limitations has expired on
the alleged incidents. A civil case is set for trial July 9. One
sexual abuse lawsuit against Smith has been dismissed in Pierce
County, Wash., Superior Court. It involved Clinton Smith (no
relation to Jeff Smith), who was sentenced to four years in prison
in 1981, partly for stealing money from the Chaplain's Pantry, a
business Jeff Smith owned in Tacoma, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in a story I heard about the Greenbrier Hotel
in West Virginia. It supposedly had an underground area where U.S.
government officials would go in case of a nuclear attack.
Apparently its existence was made public only when information was
declassified in recent years. Can you tell me about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The former government relocation facility under the hotel was
a top secret of the Cold War. ``Project Greek Island,'' as it was
code-named, was designed to house members of Congress in the event
of a nuclear strike on Washington. The Greenbrier is in White
Sulphur Springs, W.Va., a four- or five-hour drive from Capitol
Hill. The secret 112,000-square-foot bunker was built into a
mountain when the hotel's West Virginia Wing was added in 1960. Its
existence was revealed in 1992, and in 1995 the bunker was opened
for public tours _ but with its furnishings and equipment removed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A wonderful montage of the NBA playoffs was shown recently on
ESPN ``SportsCenter.'' It was done to the music of ``He Got Game.''
Is it being sold to the public?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, ESPN says it's not available for purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did CNBC cancel the Charles Grodin TV program?
</P>
<P>
   A: When ``Charles Grodin'' was canceled abruptly earlier this
month, midway through its fourth season, the official reason cited
was that the talk show and the network were going in different
directions. NBC News President Andrew Lack, who is responsible for
CNBC's prime-time and weekend programmimg, said the network's
increasing focus on news-oriented programming didn't mesh well with
Grodin's increasing focus on social issues, ``and that warranted a
change.'' USA Today reported this comment from Grodin after he was
zapped: ``It's remarkable that they let me do it for three years. I
go against the grain and the grain is bottom line and business.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports keep recommending that we wash our vegetables
and fruits as a safeguard against bacteria. Does that mean just
rinsing them with water, or should we use some kind of soap? If
soap is needed, can it be dishwashing soap, or should it be
antibacterial?
</P>
<P>
   A: You don't need to use any kind of detergent, bleach or
special rinse. In fact, that would do more harm than good, says
Judy Harrison, food scientist with the University of Georgia
Extension Service. Her advice: Remove and discard the outer leaves
from green, leafy vegetables and wash one or two leaves at a time
thoroughly in clean water. You can peel other fruits and vegetables
to eliminate possible surface bacterial contamination, but some of
the fiber will be lost. So you're better off just washing them
thoroughly, using running water.
</P>
<P>
   One other recommendation is to choose fruits and vegetables from
a ``name-brand, reputable company,'' Harrison added. ``They tend to
have more strict control measures in place to ensure sanitation and
safety of their foods.'' She also pointed out that the United
States has the safest food supply in the world, so the problem here
isn't as acute as in some other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A committee is being formed to investigate the transfer of
technological information to China under the administration of
President Clinton. I thought this sort of thing was started in the
Ronald Reagan administration, and continued in that of George Bush.
Don't I also remember that either China or Japan gave Reagan $2
million after he left office? Which country was it, and why was it
given?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're likely thinking of the case of Reagan's visit to Japan
in October 1989. Reagan, who had left office the previous January,
and his wife, Nancy, were guests of the Fujisankei Communications
Group, a leading Japanese media conglomerate. Some eyebrows were
raised, particularly in the United States, when it was reported
that Fujisankei paid Reagan a $2 million fee to give two 20-minute
speeches during his stay. While Reagan foes questioned the taste
and seemliness of a former U.S. president accepting such an
enormous sum for so little work, his staffers rebuffed the
criticism by saying large honoraria were the norm in Japan at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand Bill Gates' net worth is an estimated $40
billion. When Cornelius Vanderbilt died, his fortune was estimated
at more than $105 million. What would that amount be today, if it
had been invested since 1877?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gates would look like a pauper in comparison, said Lawrence
D. Brown of Georgia Georgia State University. Brown based his
assessment on the assumption that Vanderbilt's $105 million would
have earned a return of 10 percent a year, compounded annually.
That's essentially what the stock market has done on an annual
basis over the past 121 years, he said. By that reckoning, at the
end of 1997 Vanderbilt's $105 million would have ballooned to $10.7
trillion. ``Vanderbilt would have been worth more than 267 times
what Gates is worth today,'' Brown said. ``Or, to put it another
way, for every dollar that Gates has, assuming it's 40 billion,
Vanderbilt would have almost 268.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
