<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-COX     07-01 1885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonnette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Greg Louganis, the Olympic diver, who has
HIV? How is he doing now? He hasn't been in the news lately.
</P>
<P>
   A: The four-time Olympic gold medalist, who found out in 1988
that he had tested positive for HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, is
making the rounds to promote ``Looking to the Light,'' a video
diary of his life over the past two years. The video shows his
tedious daily routine of taking several medications that help him
battle HIV and a wide range of side effects. He participated in the
video project in lieu of another book. His autobiography,
``Breaking the Surface,'' was a best seller and was made into a USA
Network movie.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., where he was
appearing at a bookstore, he said he has ``some great doctors'' who
look after him physically and mentally. ``For some people, HIV has
become their first occupation,'' Louganis said. ``I just have other
things to do. ... I am reminded every time I take my medication,
but there are other things going on that's taking my focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Louganis also makes speeches, to student groups among others,
about health issues. ``With all my stumbles and falls, I've picked
myself up and I'm still going,'' he told an audience recently at
Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The League of Conservation Voters grades members of Congress
annually on their voting record on environmental issues. How can I
contact that group to get its scorecard?
</P>
<P>
   A: The scorecard is produced for each session of Congress. The
organization welcomes inquiries from everyone interested in knowing
how members of Congress have voted on issues related to the
environment, said spokeswoman Lisa Wade.
</P>
<P>
   The scorecards are free and can be obtained by writing: League
of Conservation Voters, 1707 L St. NW, 750, Washington, DC 20036;
or by calling toll-free 1-888-744-8683 or 202-785-8683. You also
can request the information by e-mail (lcv(at)lcv.org). And for
those with Internet access, the League has posted its scorecards on
its home page: www.lcv.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is Margaret Thatcher doing these days? She seems to have
dropped out of the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   A: Baroness Thatcher of Kesteven _ her title since 1992 _ still
pops up on the lecture circuit from time to time. But other than
that, the former British prime minister appears to prefer a low
profile at her base in London. In April, she met with Zhu Rongji,
China's newly selected premier, during his visit to London. And she
traveled recently to the United States to address a group at St.
Louis University on the topic ``Reflections on Freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't think Thatcher has been forgotten, however. She was one of
only thee women selected by Time in April for its list of 20 people
designated ``the most influential leaders and revolutionaries of
the past century'' (the other two: Eleanor Roosevelt and Margaret
Sanger).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the atomic-powered merchant ship
Savannah?
</P>
<P>
   A: The N.S. (nuclear ship) Savannah is moored in the James River
at Norfolk, Va., along with about 100 other vessels in the James
River Reserve Fleet. It's under the jurisdiction of the U.S.
Maritime Administration. The Savannah, the world's first
atomic-powered merchant vessel, was launched in 1959. In 1979 it
was retired from active service, and in 1981 was moved to
Charleston's Patriots Point Naval &AMP; Maritime Museum, home of the
USS Yorktown (CV-10) and other vessels. The Savannah was designated
a National Historic Landmark in 1991 and was turned over to the
Maritime Administration and moved to Norfolk in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 595 1/2-foot Savannah will be in the James River
Reserve Fleet for quite some time _ because of radiation concerns
it will be at least 30 years before it can be safely scrapped,
according to the maritime agency's Robert Rohr _ it won't be
reopened to the public. It is constantly monitored with remote
alarm systems to ensure its ``integrity,'' Rohr said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Garth Brooks is the No. 3 best-selling recording
artist of all time. Is that correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: He appears to be No. 2. International statistics are hard to
come by, so this information applies to the United States. Brooks,
with total album sales of about 68 million, is second only to the
Beatles, whose total U.S. album sales are about 105 million (1
billion discs and tapes worldwide). But there's an asterisk
involved: As Brooks himself has noted, the keeping of statistics
didn't begin seriously until well after Elvis Presley was
established.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the current wages and benefits of the striking
General Motors workers?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to The Wall Street Journal, GM pays $44 an hour, on
average, in wages and benefits to its workers who are members of
the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent editorial said tobacco kills 400,000 Americans a
year. How does that compare to alcohol-related deaths?
</P>
<P>
   A: More than 100,000 deaths annually in the United States can be
attributed to excessive alcohol consumption, according to the
National Clearinghouse on Alcohol and Drug Information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you print ``13 Things Graduates Need to Know But Are
Never Taught,'' as read by Paul Harvey recently?
</P>
<P>
   A: Harvey read ``Rules Not Learned'' by Charles Sykes, author of
``Dumbing Down Our Kids,'' and is reprinted with permission of Paul
Harvey News:
</P>
<P>
   (1) Life is not fair. Get used to it. (2) The world won't care
about your self-esteem as much as your school does. The world will
expect you to accomplish something before you feel good about
yourself. (3) You will NOT make $40,000 a year right out of high
school. You won't be a vice president with a car phone until you
earn both. (4) If you think your teacher is rough, wait till you
get a boss. He doesn't have tenure. (5) Flipping burgers is not
beneath your dignity. Your grandparents had a different word for
burger-flipping. They called it ``opportunity.'' (6) If you screw
up, it's not your parents' fault. So don't whine about your
mistakes; learn from them. (7) Before you were born, your parents
weren't as boring as they are now. They got that way paying your
bills, cleaning your room and listening to you tell how idealistic
you are. So before you save the rain forest from the blood-sucking
parasites of your parents' generation, try de-lousing the closet in
your own room. (8) Your school may have done away with winners and
losers, but life hasn't. In some schools, they've abolished failing
grades. They'll give you as many times as you want for the right
answer. This, of course, bears not the slightest resemblance to
anything in real life. (9) Life is not divided into semesters. You
don't get summers off. And very few employers are interested in
helping you ``find yourself''; do that on your own time. (10)
Television is not real life. In real life, people actually have to
leave the coffee shop and go to jobs. (11) Be nice to nerds;
chances are you'll end up working for nerds. (12) Smoking does not
make you look ``cool;'' it makes you look moronic. Ditto for purple
hair and pierced body parts. (13) Living fast and dying young is
romantic _ only until you see one of your peers at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   And this, June graduates, is a footnote of my (Harvey's) own:
Get up when you fall down. Get up when you fall down. Michael
Jordan has missed the basket 9,000 times. He has lost almost 300
games. Twenty-six times, Michael Jordan has been trusted to take
the game-winning shot _ and missed. Jordan says, ``Over and over
and over again, I have failed. And that is why I succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The book ``The Fourth Estate'' by Jeffrey Archer has a story
about a media mogul who takes his yacht out and jumps overboard to
commit suicide. Isn't this something that actually happened a few
years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're thinking about the case of Robert Maxwell, flamboyant
British billionaire press baron who was called ``the Citizen Kane
of his time.'' His unclothed body was found floating in the
Atlantic near the Canary Islands Nov. 5, 1991, several hours after
he was reported missing from his yacht. An official pathologists'
report from the Spanish National Institute of Toxicology concluded
that Maxwell, 68, had suffered a heart attack before he fell off
his yacht. The pathologists ruled out the possibility that his
death had been caused by poison, drugs, alcohol or foul play,
noting that there were no signs of violence on the body other than
marks on the head, apparently caused when the body was lifted out
of the water by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the report, some people speculated that Maxwell's death
may not have been from a heart attack. Not long before he died,
Maxwell had been accused in a book by U.S. investigative reporter
Seymour Hersh of having close ties to the Israeli secret service.
Maxwell was buried Nov. 10, 1991, at the Mount of Olives in
Jerusalem. He received what was close to a state funeral, with
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and President Chaim Herzog in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article mentioned that Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.)
receives $37,500 in veterans' benefits. What is that all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cleland receives annual disability benefits from the Veterans
Administration in the amount of $37,506, said his spokeswoman,
Julie Robinson. Cleland was left a triple amputee by wounds
suffered in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was Will Smith paid for his role in the original ``Men
in Black''? I heard he would make $20 million for the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hollywood sources say Smith was paid $5 million for ``MiB.''
Although his base salary for the sequel is said to be $20 million,
it could be more. Like other heavyweights involved in the film _
Tommy Lee Jones and Barry Sonnenfeld _ he is said to be seeking
whatever amount is higher, the $20 million or 10 percent of the
film's gross income. Steven Spielberg, by the way, is seeking 20
percent of the sequel's gross.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article said that cholorine, when used in swimming pools,
wipes out virtually all bacteria and most viruses, including all
coliform, polio virus, hepatitis A and common cold germs.
Conspicuously omitted was any reference to the AIDS virus. Does
chlorine kill that, too?
</P>
<P>
   A: The risk of transmission in swimming pools or whirlpools of
HIV (the AIDS virus), or other viruses such as hepatitis B or
herpes simplex type II, is so low that it's unmeasurable, according
to medical experts at the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. While the usual amount of halogen used to disinfect
swimming pools and whirlpools is considered more than sufficient to
kill these viruses, ``chemical germicide,'' such as chlorination,
isn't a factor. The simple dilution of the water wouldn't allow the
pathogenic agent to invade a susceptible individual, the CDC adds.
So the risk of transmission with swimming pool water, or even
wastewater, is virtually nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
