<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN02-COX     07-01 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Open winner often overlooked
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Her name is Alison Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   She's the one who actually won the U.S. Women's Open last year.
</P>
<P>
   You may have missed her. Not because she's only 60 inches tall _
well, maybe because of that, too _ but mostly because the giant she
beat by one shot on the Witch Hollow Course at Pumpkin Ridge in
North Plains, Ore., was the legendary Nancy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have thought Nicholas was the Witch Hollow witch for
having turned Lopez's Open coach into a pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get a lot of sleep (Saturday night before 1997's
final round),'' said Nicholas, who was born in Gibraltar and lives
in England. ``I just wanted to enjoy (Sunday) and soak it all in. I
knew the crowd was going to be with Nancy all the way. I was
prepared for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the longest day of my life, I can tell you that. The
last day was magnificent. It was a fairy-tale scenario playing
Nancy Lopez head-to-head. It's something you dream about, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas, in fact, had done exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   She was a 17-year-old European with a handicap befitting a bogey
golfer when someone gave her a book. The subject was Lopez, who at
the time was crashing onto the LPGA Tour and winning almost every
tournament she played.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of decades later, about the only thing missing from the
Lopez resume' is a U.S. Open title. She has been runner-up four
times, and it was Nicholas, of course, who seated her in that
position most recently. She did it with a record 10-under par score
that was just enough to hold off Lopez, who lost despite becoming
the first woman to shoot four rounds in the 60s in the event.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas grabbed sole possession of the lead with a second-round
66, never let it go and held up against one of the great heroines
not only of women's professional golf but of women's professional
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Open time again.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects Nicholas to use Blackwolf Run Golf Course as a
venue to pull an Annika Sorenstam, who won back-to-back Open titles
in 1995 and 1996. Sorenstam missed the cut last year, but stayed in
Oregon through the weekend to motivate and eventually congratulate
Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says what kind of person Annika is,'' said Nicholas, who
has played on the past two Solheim Cup teams for Europe with
Sorenstam and is one of six players on her side who has competed in
all four Solheim competitions.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Sorenstam, who has won the last two tournaments she has
entered, who is again the Open favorite. Nicholas, on the other
hand, has endured a mediocre LPGA season with three missed cuts and
a withdrawal in nine tournament. Her best finish this year is a tie
for seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe a year has passed,'' Nicholas said. ``It's
exciting and a lot of attention will be on me, I suppose. A lot of
top players have never won the U.S. Open (Lopez, obviously, will be
a sentimenal favorite in her 22nd attempt). My family is coming
out. We're just going to have a fun week.''
</P>
<P>
   About that attention ...
</P>
<P>
   ... Nicholas sat, unbothered, in the media center Tuesday
afternoon watching England vs. Argentina in the World Cup while
Lopez _ who else? _ ran past her scheduled time for a group
interview session.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas didn't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can watch a little longer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And when England scored to take a 2-1 lead, it was Nicholas who
jumped up and yelled, 'Take that, you Argies!!!' That's the
reigning U.S. Women's Open champion. Not bad for a 36-year-old who
got involved with golf only when she decided tennis wasn't going to
take her very far.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't see your opponent across the net, it's a bit
tricky,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, look for Nicholas amid all the hoopla when the Open
begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She's the one about the size of the trophy with her name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
