<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-REACTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPELLATE RULING WON'T DETER MICROSOFT FOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WARREN WILSON   
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Antitrust regulators say they are proceeding at full
steam in their litigation against Microsoft Corp., despite an
appeals court ruling Tuesday that some believe delivered a torpedo
below the waterline.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate decision came in a narrow case filed last fall,
the regulators pointed out, not the broader one they filed last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The newer case, which invokes the Sherman Antitrust Act and is
scheduled for trial in September, raises issues such as Microsoft's
allegedly anticompetitive dealings with computer makers and online
content providers that are separate from those discussed in
Tuesday's ruling, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein Wednesday reiterated his
confidence in the strength of the Sherman Act case and stressed
that it was distinct from the narrower dispute that prompted
Tuesday's ruling, spokeswoman Gina Talamona said.
</P>
<P>
   New York Attorney General Dennis Vacco, among the leaders of a
parallel effort by 20 states and the District of Columbia, took a
similar view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this is a substantial development,'' Vacco spokeswoman
Mollie Conkey said. ``But we really believe it will not have a
significant impact on our case ... it isn't affecting anything
we're doing, as far as forging ahead toward the Sept. 8 trial
date.''
</P>
<P>
   Key competitors of Microsoft tried to hammer home those points.
One, Oracle Corp. chairman Larry Ellison, dismissed the ruling as
``a little tactical decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision came in a dispute that began last fall when
the Justice Department accused Microsoft of violating a 1995
consent decree by ``tying'' its Internet browser software to its
Windows operating system. Computer makers had no real alternative
to Windows, the government said, so tying the products together
amounted to an abuse of monopoly power. Microsoft said it had
``integrated'' the two products to better serve consumers, as the
consent decree specifically allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruled on Tuesday that U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson had made both procedural and substantive
errors in December when he referred the case to a special master
and ordered Microsoft to offer computer makers a browserless
version of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The panel looked closely at the integration issue and said that
what Microsoft had done appeared not to violate the consent decree.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, it also examined the integration issue in light
of antitrust law and made numerous points that many observers read
as undermining the broader case as well.
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently agreed. Buoyed both by the ruling and
today's retail release of Windows 98, the latest upgrade to
Microsoft's pervasive operating system for desktop computers, they
bid the company's shares to a record high for the second straight
day.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed Wednesday at 104 15/16, up more than 9 percent
from Monday's closing price of 95 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newer lawsuit's allegations are claims that Microsoft
abuses its Windows monopoly by denying computer makers
opportunities to customize their products and by driving bargains
with online content providers and Internet service providers that
squeeze out competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insists it has done nothing wrong, but has nonetheless
granted some business partners more leeway in the last few months
in the face of mounting legal and political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling prompted speculation that Microsoft could
reassert its hard-nosed attitude.
</P>
<P>
   But Dataquest analyst Chris LeTocq considers that unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Microsoft realizes those issues are still on the
table,'' LeTocq said.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts suggested it would risk squandering the strategic
and public relations gains made with Tuesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco, asked why the company's business practices should still
be litigated if Microsoft has already eased its stance, said the
lawsuit could both clarify what the company had actually done and
impose enforceable restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we believe that Microsoft has eased contractual
restrictions on Internet Service Providers and online providers as
a result of the states' and Department of Justice's investigations,
it is not clear how far Microsoft's changes actually go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additionally, absent an injunction, it is possible for
Microsoft to revert to its former practices if the investigation or
litigation is terminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many observers agreed with Giga Information Group analyst
Rob Enderle that the appellate ruling undercuts one of the pillars
of the government's case, an argument without which ``it's hard to
justify a federal case of this magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors haven't yet found a ``smoking gun'' in the case
_ such as evidence of harm to consumers, Enderle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had a lot of allegations, some hearsay and some
documentation,'' he said, ``but almost a complete lack of credible,
independent witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-24-98 2140EDT &QL;
</P>
