<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-SUIT-NY     07-01 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT DECISION REFLECTS DEBATE OVER HOW TO APPLY ANTITRUST LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Microsoft Corp., a federal appeals court ruling in the
company's favor on Tuesday was a gratifying triumph of sweeping
import for its long-running antitrust battle with the government.
</P>
<P>
   To the Justice Department and 20 states pitted against
Microsoft, it was merely a bump in the road as they head to court
again in September with a broader antitrust case against the
leading computer software company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet antitrust experts said Wednesday that the split decision by
the three-judge panel _ a majority opinion written by a
conservative and partial dissent from a liberal _ was both a big
victory for Microsoft and a reflection of the wider debate over how
antitrust doctrine should apply to high-technology industries.
</P>
<P>
   The majority ruling, they say, echoes the hands-off approach
championed by Microsoft, while the dissent mirrors the Justice
Department's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a landmark antitrust opinion,'' said Stephen Axinn, a
leading antitrust litigator. ``It deals with a classic fault-line
in antitrust _ when a court can second-guess a company's product
decisions. The majority opinion, at least for the moment, moves the
law further toward a non-interventionist stance, especially in
high-tech cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors viewed the opinion as a critical victory for Microsoft
and a green light to buy Microsoft stock, which rose 5.15 percent
Tuesday and a further 4.16 percent Wednesday to $104.9375, a
record.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials and state attorneys general
Wednesday pointed to reasons why the impact of the ruling may be
limited. The appeals court struck down a ruling last year by a
federal judge who had ordered Microsoft to offer its Windows 95
operating system and Internet Explorer browser program separately.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
was intended to preserve competition in the market for browsers,
software used to navigate the Internet's World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   In the case, the Justice Department had alleged that by bundling
its browser with its industry-standard Windows operating system,
Microsoft was violating its 1995 consent decree with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's majority opinion, Justice Department officials noted,
applied to the consent-decree case and not necessarily to the
government's broader antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The broader monopoly case, based on a far more extensive federal
investigation, contains several additional charges against
Microsoft. But a pivotal argument in the case _ and one sharply
criticized by the appeals court majority opinion _ is that by tying
new software programs to its Windows operating system, Microsoft is
unfairly squelching competition in new markets, like Internet
software and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insists that it, and it alone, should be the arbiter
of what new software is bundled into its Windows operating system,
the equivalent of the central nervous system on some 90 percent of
personal computers. Besides, Microsoft contends, its Internet
browser is not a separate product, as the government asserts, but
an ``integrated feature'' of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court majority sided with Microsoft, saying ``the
limited competence of courts to evaluate high-tech product designs
and the high cost of error should make them wary of second-guessing
the claimed benefits of a particular design decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court, legal experts say, could have merely struck
down Jackson's injunction with a brief ruling. Instead, it
presented detailed views on antitrust law and high-technology
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion, legal analysts say, is clearly intended as
a warning signal to the government, the states and Jackson, who
will hear the broader antitrust case starting Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion is very applicable to the broader case,'' said Joe
Sims, a partner at Jones Day Reavis &AMP; Pogue, who is a former senior
official in the Justice Department's antitrust division. ``It's a
first indication that this court believes that the conceptual
approach of the Justice Department is a stretch legally.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court majority ruling must figure into the
preparations for the broader case, acknowledged Justice Department
officials and state attorneys general, by suggesting where more
facts must be marshaled to strengthen its arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very definitely a bump in the road,'' said Richard
Blumenthal, the attorney general of Connecticut, ``but it doesn't
knock the wheels off our wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Miller, Iowa's attorney general, emphasized that the
appeals court setback will not prompt the states to reconsider
proceeding with the broader case. ``It's full-speed ahead _ no
thought of the opposite,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Several states filed a friend-of-the-court brief in the Justice
Department's consent-decree case. Though Justice Department
officials said no tactical decision has yet been made on appealing
the appeals court ruling, it is unlikely to try to appeal to the
Supreme Court _ saving that option, if necessary, for the broader
case.
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion reflects the more conservative approach
termed ``judicial restraint'' by its advocates. Its author was
Judge Stephen Williams, a Reagan appointee and self-described
adherent of the doctrine of judicial restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative approach leans hard on the notion that if a
company, like Microsoft, can show a discernible consumer benefit to
its tying together of products or features, such bundling should be
permitted under antitrust law. The government contends that other
factors, especially the potential harm to competition and
innovation, should also weigh in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives tend to shun judicial ``balancing'' in antitrust
cases. Williams wrote, ``Courts are ill-equipped to evaluate the
benefits of high-tech product design, and even if they could place
an evaluation on one side of the balance, the strength of the
`evidence of distinct markets,' proposed for the other side of the
scale, seems quite incommensurable.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Patricia Wald, a Carter administration appointee, took
issue with the majority opinion in some key respects. The majority
view, she wrote in her dissenting opinion, seemed to mean Microsoft
could bundle anything into its Windows operating system merely by
``identifying some minimal synergy associated with such
`integration.'''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wald suggested that some sort of balancing of consumer
benefit vs. economic harm in product decisions was, at times,
something courts should do.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means do I endorse routine judicial intervention in the
details of product design,'' she wrote. ``But I also do not endorse
(as the majority comes close to doing) judicial abdication in the
face of complexity. The courts are certainly capable of determining
whether a particular integration offers any synergistic benefits at
all or whether these benefits are minimal, significant or great.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Fox, a professor at the New York University Law School,
observed, ``The majority opinion is one possible interpretation of
antitrust law, but it's a very laissez faire interpretation. Judge
Wald's interpretation is much closer to the Justice Department's
argument.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-24-98 2035EDT &QL;
</P>
