<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BACKING FOR BILL TO SHIELD CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma congressman won preliminary support last week for
legislation that would require public schools and libraries to use
filters on their computers as a way to keep children from seeing
sexually explicit material on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by Rep. Ernest Istook Jr., a Republican, was added
to an $81.9 billion budget bill pending in the House Appropriations
Committee to cover education, labor and health and human services.
The bill is expected to be sent to the full House after lawmakers
return from the July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Communications Decency Act was overturned by the
Supreme Court last year, lawmakers have sought more narrowly
tailored legislation to shield children without violating the First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appropriations bill is a must-pass bill, so it is very
dangerous that the provision has been added to that bill,'' said
Ron Weich, a legislative consultant to the American Civil Liberties
Union, which successfully challenged the Communications Decency
Act.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Istook said the amendment stirred no controversy
among members of the subcommittee that approved it. ``There was no
opposition,'' the aide said. ``It was a 14-0 vote.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill, sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has
passed the Senate Commerce Committee. But it is narrower, applying
only to schools and libraries that receive federal financial
assistance in obtaining Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   THE FINE ART OF LURING READERS
</P>
<P>
   Want to learn how to put an end to junk e-mail forever? Don't
ask Avatar Publishing _ even though a piece of widely circulated
promotional electronic mail from Avatar has been luring readers
with the subject line: ``Never Receive Junk E-Mail Again!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be great to never get junk e-mail again?'' the
message begins. ``Well, no one can make you that promise,
unfortunately. But you can profit from junk e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Avatar, which has an unlisted phone number and has hidden its
return e-mail address, then invites the reader to mail $29 to a Los
Angeles address for more information and a junk e-mail starter kit
that includes a primer on what is legal and what is not.
</P>
<P>
   The message explains that Avatar is in a ``fun little war'' with
the producers of Internet filter software, to see just who can
outsmart whom. ``We know all the secrets,'' the message says.
``Obviously, or you wouldn't be reading this, would you?'' Probably
not.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO WEAR WHEN THE FUTURE COMES
</P>
<P>
   With all the dire predictions that airlines, banks, power grids
and even the federal government will be felled by ill-programmed
computers when the calendar turns over to Jan. 1, 2000, there is
now one less thing to worry about: what to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Two entrepreneurs in Birmingham, Mich., have come up with what
they have trademarked as the ``Official Logo of the New
Millennium.'' And they have the Web site _ and the T-shirts _ to
prove it.
</P>
<P>
   The idea grew from a brainstorming session a year ago, said
Larry Smith, a managing partner of the venture, called Millennium
321. (The 3 denotes the third millennium; the 21 refers to the 21st
century.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just read that M &AMP; M's had just applied to be the
official candy of the new millennium,'' he said. ``We thought,
`What could we do that could have a global impact?'''
</P>
<P>
   He and his partner, James Iacobucci, came up with a logo with
three columns that Smith said ``looks as though you're unzipping
the future.'' Shirts, sweatshirts and caps with the logo are for
sale on the company's Web site, which opened last week
(www.m321.com).
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   IRS REDESIGNS FORM ON TAX-EXEMPT STATUS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's tax collectors are planning a surfing safari on the
Web to hunt for nonprofit groups that are really commercial
enterprises in charitable camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service is redesigning the application form
for organizations that seek tax-exempt status. The existing
application form asks for examples of brochures and other printed
materials, which IRS officials use to evaluate applications. More
than 1.5 million organizations have won tax exemption from the
service. The new form, expected to be released by fall, will add a
box for a would-be nonprofit to list its Web address.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing ourselves up to 21st-century technology,'' said
Don Roberts, an IRS spokesman, ``and realizing that a lot of these
organizations have Web sites, as well as printed materials, will
help us evaluate applications.''
</P>
<P>
   KPMG Peat Marwick, the accounting firm, tells clients in its
June newsletter that having a list of nonprofit Web sites will also
help agents quickly check whether a tax-exempt organization is
straying too far into commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofits are allowed to engage in business activities like
operating museum gift shops if the activities are related to the
organization's core purpose. But if the venture is unrelated to
that mission, the group must pay taxes on any profits.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet on the IRS agenda for the 21st century: online
application for tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-28-98 1852EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
