<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY A RUCKUS AT THE FRONT DOOR OF THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When America Online rebuffed AT&AMP;T's merger flirtations last
month, it could hardly have known that the long-distance giant
would soon marry what may be the online service's most potent
long-term enemy: the At Home Corp.
</P>
<P>
   At Home, in which AT&AMP;T will get a 42 percent interest as part of
its $31.8 billion acquisition bid for Tele-Communications Inc. last
week, markets a high-speed Internet service over cable television
wires. It is hardly a force today, with only about 100,000
subscribers. America Online says it has 12 million customers, more
than half of the homes in the United States that have online
access.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a new front is opening in the Internet wars with the
development of so-called broadband services like At Home that offer
transmission speeds 20 to 100 times as fast as traditional modems.
That is fast enough to offer rich graphics, live video feeds and an
end to the finger-tapping waiting that most online users endure
today.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the most visible battles in the broadband world are
among various technology providers _ for example, between
cable-modem systems and a new standard of high-speed Internet
access over telephone wires called digital subscriber lines. And
the cable industry itself is divided: One group backs At Home, and
another supports Time Warner's cable-modem service, Road Runner.
</P>
<P>
   But a much more intense clash is brewing over whether access to
broadband lines will be open to America Online or any other online
service or will be closed to all content except that chosen by the
system operator, just as cable systems now choose which channels to
carry. Not surprisingly, both At Home and Road Runner want to use
their wires to promote their own online news, information and
entertainment services.
</P>
<P>
   Why does this matter? For the same reason that media giants like
the Walt Disney Co. and General Electric's NBC have been buying
Internet directory services: It is clear that whoever controls the
front door that people use to start their Internet surfing _ a
``portal'' in industry jargon _ will control the biggest share of
advertising and shopping revenues. And whoever sells the connection
to the Internet, as America Online and At Home both do, controls
the portal.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the AT&AMP;T-TCI deal was announced, America
Online's chairman, Steve Case, issued a statement challenging At
Home's exclusive deal to provide high-speed programming over TCI's
cables and challenging AT&AMP;T to let his service offer high-speed
cable-modem access under its own brand.
</P>
<P>
   This did not sit well with At Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought that AT&AMP;T or TCI will become a dumb pipe and turn
over the portal service to AOL is just ridiculous,'' Thomas
Jermoluk, At Home's chairman, said in an interview last week. ``AOL
is paranoid about keeping exclusive control of the portal. But in
the new broadband world, the facilities provider wants to
participate in the revenue stream when users see ads and buy
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are compounded for At Home, which has a minority of
its shares trading publicly. The company has shot up to a value of
$4.2 billion despite huge losses because of the perceived potential
of its exclusive contracts with TCI and other cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, even if At Home controls the first screen its users
see, any At Home user with only a modest technical ability could
use the cable modem to gain access to America Online or any other
Internet service at high speeds. That is no different than the
ability of a current America Online user to jump right to Yahoo or
any other Internet site. But experience shows that that most people
do not tinker with default settings; they use whatever pops up on
the first screen they see.
</P>
<P>
   At Home, however, does not want simply to depend on inertia. It
has been developing attractive content that takes advantage of its
service's speed. Its news and information screens, for example,
have much bigger, brighter color graphics than other Web-based
services. And it offers a wide range of short video clips from
sources like CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Jermoluk says that one measure of the drawing power of these
flashy offerings is that half of At Home's first customers were
America Online members and that most of them dropped the online
service once they got used to the cable offering. His conclusion:
America Online will have to give up its dream of being the
exclusive portal in a broadband world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the access to the home,'' he said. ``If AOL wants to
get there with broadband, they will have to work with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pittman, America Online's president, insists that despite
the protests over the current cable lockout, he is not worried. To
start with, it is very early in the game, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadband is just not ready for prime time,'' Pittman said. As
much as consumers may want faster access, broadband will not take
off, he said, until its price comes down from the current $40 a
month and customers can hook themselves up easily without
technicians visiting their homes, as the current technology
requires.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Pittman argues that for the foreseeable future,
the most likely prospect for broadband services is someone who is
already on line at slower speeds. Thus, America Online offers the
biggest pool of broadband prospects in the world. So the cable
companies and the phone companies will all eventually trip over
themselves to cut deals with the online service.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, economics always win,'' he said.
``Since we have so many subscribers, we have big buying power
already.'' Moreover, Pittman argues that AT&AMP;T's strategy of selling
telephone, cable and Internet services in one package will
ultimately prove ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about bundling, but what's missing is someone to
sell the bundle,'' he said. ``The only thing TCI can sell is cable
TV. AT&AMP;T has 80 million customers, but it was only able to get 1
million customers for Worldnet,'' the Internet service AT&AMP;T
introduced two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an interactive relationship with our consumers,'' he
added, ``so when we started offering long distance we converted 1
million lines in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-28-98 1649EDT &QL;
</P>
