<HEADER>
A5504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMP-USA-COMPUTER     07-01 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMP-USA-COMPUTER-CITY-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUSA: REVISING COMPUTER RETAILING
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By ALLEN R. MYERSON  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDISON, Texas _ By a few minutes before midnight, a line
outside CompUSA's flagship store in this Dallas suburb stretched
past the training center entrance next door, the GNC nutrition
store, the Subway sandwich shop, the Packaging Store, the Elegant
Salon, the Converse Shoe Factory and Pam's Hallmark store.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had muted its mighty hype machine for the release of
Windows 98. But CompUSA, having just agreed to pay $275 million to
buy its chief rival, Computer City, from Tandy, was out to prove
that the computer retail store was not about to go the way of the
ice house.
</P>
<P>
   Its radio and newspaper advertisements offered the first 10
people in line a 266 megahertz computer for $98, and there were
special deals on modems, hard drives and so forth for those farther
back in a queue that began forming at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   But how many in that line would buy a computer from CompUSA at
regular prices?
</P>
<P>
   Among the first 10 in line were Frank Callahan, a retired
regional sales manager for Raleigh Bicycles, and his wife, Janet.
Two years ago, when they bought their last computer, they came to
CompUSA to comparison shop. But they ordered their machine from IMS
Computers, a local assembler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get what we wanted built by IMS much cheaper,'' Janet
Callahan said.
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA's Packard Bell, Compaq and Acer models offered less
value and flexibility. ``Here, we had to take what was in the
package,'' Callahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Against competition from no-name direct marketers and shops like
IMS and big-name direct marketers like Dell Computer, CompUSA's
challenge is to keep the computer store alive even as it
diversifies into corporate sales and services.
</P>
<P>
   To attract customers like the Callahans, CompUSA again began
offering built-to-order computers last September under its own
brand name. Because the chain's previous effort to build its own
computers flopped a few years ago, this time it tried to avoid
accumulating a parts inventory _ whose value drops, on average, 2
percent a week _ by having contractors build the machines. But
since the contractors have not been able to keep up with demand,
the company says it will again start building computers.
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA's chief executive, James F. Halpin, a blunt, brusque
400-megahertz type of guy in an industry where last year's business
model is usually as outdated as last year's computer, came in and
saved the company in 1994 when it was on the brink of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry has become even more competitive in the last
four years. Falling computer prices, strong competition and
diversification costs caused CompUSA's first-quarter profits to
fall 22 percent compared with the corresponding period a year
earlier, to $25.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Company-wide, sales rose 14 percent, to $1.45 billion, but for
the 122 stores that have been open a year or more, they rose just
1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As computer buyers become more informed and confident, direct
marketers like Dell and Gateway 2000 are growing faster than
computer superstores like CompUSA.
</P>
<P>
   Halpin concedes that Dell and other companies that take orders
on line or over the phone offer more megahertz for the money. ``Our
major vendors haven't been able to give us machines that compete,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   While superstores as a category sold 3.1 million computers last
year _ an increase of almost a million in two years _ direct sales
rose by than 2 million, to 5.5 million units.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Direct markets are gaining a further advantage as more customers
shop on the Internet. Dell, which had sales of just $1 million a
day on its World Wide Web site in March 1997, was up to $3 million
a day by Christmas and is now billing $5 million a day on line _
more than 13 percent of its total sales.
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA also recently began selling over the Internet, but the
popularity of computers selling for less than $1,000, at slim
profit margins, is squeezing revenues. Dataquest, a market research
company in San Jose, Calif., expects computer sales to rise 16
percent, to 35.2 million units, this year, but revenues to rise
only 3 percent, to $69.5 billion. The average price will fall to
$1,974 this year from $2,223 last year, Dataquest predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Halpin portrays lower prices as an advantage because they expand
the market. Over the last two years, he said, the average family
income of computer buyers has fallen from $75,000 to less than
$50,000. ``Computers have become affordable to the middle class,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts called the Computer City acquisition a bargain,
pointing out that it eliminated a chief rival and afforded CompUSA
inexpensive expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Harrington, editor of Computer Retail Week, sees the
Computer City acquisition raising CompUSA's profit margins, but
wonders if the company is trying to do too many things at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't fully integrated all the businesses they've
started,'' Harrington said. ``A bleeding Computer City on its back
is really going to test the company to the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Though CompUSA announced that it would close some Computer City
stores, keeping the remainder staffed with qualified salespeople
could be a challenge. At one nearby Computer City store,
salespeople said that under Tandy, commissions had often doubled or
tripled their daily earnings. If CompUSA pays them like it pays its
own salespeople, who work without commissions, ``We're going to
leave,'' said one Computer City salesperson as others nodded.
</P>
<P>
   But in a field littered with wounded rivals _ Computer City has
been a steady money loser _ CompUSA and Halpin still appear to have
the best shot at revising the formula.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight last Thursday, Halpin was seen surveying the
600 or so customers storming through the doors of his San Francisco
store. ``I'm pumped!'' he was heard bellowing. ``It's like election
night. The votes are coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has positioned Windows 98 as minor upgrade, but Halpin
describes it as a spark for the whole computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I installed it on my daughter's computer at home,'' he
recounted. ``I asked her how she liked it. `Awesome,' she said.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case shoppers are less impressed, CompUSA is moving
beyond brick-and-mortar stores. ``We sell computers any way a
customer wants to buy them,'' Halpin said. ``We can deliver and
install from one PC up to 2,000. We want to train you. We want to
service you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Addison store's back offices include a sales operation where
each workday 28 salespeople ring up businesses and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, challenges grow in the consumer end of the business.
Despite a towering kiosk trumpeting CompUSA's built-to-order
computers, few of the customers who showed up at the Addison store
on Thursday seemed aware of this option. With its own label, the
company says it can beat even Dell's prices on such systems _ a
contention Dell disputes _ but it will have to convince the many
current CompUSA customers who say they visit the stores mostly to
see what's new, maybe buy some cables or software before heading
elsewhere to buy a computer.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, many shoppers are increasingly able to outsmart
the best marketing schemes.
</P>
<P>
   As Lisa Adams and Howard J. Huang, Dallas medical students,
stood in a checkout line, they described what seemed like an offer
of free _ or better than free _ computer memory modules: 16
megabytes of memory for $38 with a $40 mail-in rebate, but with
only one rebate per customer. They explained, however, that the
memory could only be installed in pairs. One rebate on two memory
chips made the price higher than that charged by other marketers on
the Internet, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're counting on you to buy the other one,'' Huang said.
``Smart marketing trick.''
</P>
<P>
   But not smart enough. Huang and Ms. Adams were each buying one
16-megabyte module and pooling their rebates. They got 32 megabits
of free memory for Adams' computer _ truly for free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-28-98 1623EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
