u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTEL-SUIT-REACT-     07-01 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-SUIT-REACT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL'S ANTITRUST ALTERNATIVE: AVOID PUBLIC CONFRONTATION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By JOEL BRINKLEY  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Justice Department was readying its
antitrust suit against Microsoft this spring, the company hired a
dozen powerful lobbyists, choreographed rallies and news
conferences and issued sharp denunciations of the government. In
short, it waged the technology industry's equivalent of a holy war.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when the Federal Trade Commission was preparing its
antitrust suit against Intel this month, the company offered a
simple, polite statement: ``We are cooperating with the government
and will continue to cooperate. They are just doing their job, and
we respect their right to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since the federal government filed its suit against
Intel, the world's largest manufacturer of microprocessor chips,
the company has remained largely silent, unwilling to offer
anything more than the most rudimentary public defense. And while
Microsoft representatives have been aggressively lobbying Congress
and the administration, Intel's are nowhere to be seen _ except at
the trade commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard from them at all,'' said a senior
Congressional aide, who would normally be a target of lobbying on
antitrust issues. ``I just cleaned out my in-basket, and there's
nothing from them there at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Mulloy, the company spokesman who management decided would
be Intel's sole voice on the subject, explains the silence this
way: ``We don't think it benefits either side in this case to
conduct a debate in the public forum.''
</P>
<P>
   But background discussions with other Intel executives and
interviews with analysts who track the company closely suggest a
more complex set of motives. For one, they say, Intel's leaders
believe that Microsoft's aggressive public-relations blitz
backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe Microsoft hurt themselves as much as they
helped,'' said Michael Slater, editor of The Microprocessor Report,
an industry newsletter. ``Microsoft came across as basically
arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Peck, a technology analyst with Cowan &AMP; Company, said,
``They took their cue from Microsoft and realized that the more
exposure they get, the less good it is for them.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Intel executive agreed. Just after Microsoft staged a
rally of sorts in New York in early May, at which the company's
chairman, William H. Gates, and other industry executives exhorted
the government to stay out of the software business, this executive
asked with a dismissive chuckle, ``Can you imagine Andy doing
that?'' Andy Grove, Intel's chief executive at the time, is widely
admired in the computer industry for being a fierce but gracious
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   No one contends that Intel's leaders are humble, self-effacing
sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The egos at the top of Intel are every bit as large as the
egos at the top of Microsoft; they feel just as self-righteous,''
said Richard Shaffer, a principal of Technologic Partners, an
industry research company.
</P>
<P>
   But the company shows little of that to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel's not a company that likes to talk about anything but
product,'' Slater said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Intel's lawyers say they view the outcome of the trade
commission's suit as crucial to the company's future. The
government accuses Intel of threatening and injuring three computer
manufacturers as a means of coercing them to turn over patented
technologies by withholding technical information about Intel's
latest chips.
</P>
<P>
   The company insists that it must maintain full control over its
patented technologies and therefore will take the case all the way
to the Supreme Court if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts and Intel executives noted that the company
faces even greater threats beyond the scope of the antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to deal with a real upheaval that has never
been seen before in the PC business _ pricing challenges'' in the
sub-$1,000 personal computer market, Peck said. There, Intel's
competitors are making real inroads, and the company's stock has
been in a prolonged slump. It closed Friday at $76.1875 a share,
down more than 25 percent from its 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the other challenges they face now,'' Peck said, ``this
doesn't have the highest priority. Besides, I don't think Intel
wants to be the test case, the litmus test for intellectual
property cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy says only, ``We have made a decision to litigate this in
the courts.'' And 10 days ago, the company did file a motion with
the court, arguing that the companies named in the suit _ Compaq,
Digital Equipment and Intergraph _ were customers, not competitors,
and therefore not subject to harm under federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy does take issue with the notion that Intel's strategy is
a direct reaction to Microsoft's approach.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that Intel issued a press release on Sept. 24,
announcing that the FTC had notified the company that it had opened
an investigation _ several weeks before the Justice Department
filed its suit against Microsoft. And that early release was just
as low key as the more recent statements and remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company said it will cooperate fully with the FTC in its
investigation,'' the release said, and then concluded with a bit of
what turned out to be undue optimism: ``In 1993, after a similar
investigation, the F.T.C. concluded that no further action was
warranted, and the investigation was closed. Intel expects that the
current investigation will come to a similar conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-28-98 1610EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
