<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHREPORT30-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Tech Report: Listen up _ minidisc or CD-RW? 
By Michael E. Kanell  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dueling formats _ you know the story.
</P>
<P>
   It could be VHS against Betamax. Or compact discs against vinyl.
Fax vs. e-mail, vs. the Postal Service. Among wireless phones, it
could be traditional cellular against personal communications
services, or analog against digital.
</P>
<P>
   In connecting to the Internet, there is a coming battle between
phone lines called Asymmetric Digital Subscriber Lines, known as
ADSL, and cable modems running over cable lines. And for them to
succeed, they must both overcome the slower but more entrenched
modems.
</P>
<P>
   The formats clash. Sometimes one dies, and sometimes they
coexist. Television did not kill radio _ although both were changed
by the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Music in the past few decades has provided some high-stakes
confrontations _ and plenty of reasons for consumers to place bets
on a winner by spending billions of dollar on a format. And if they
bet on a loser, well, they get to bet all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Before there were CDs, cassettes had to stomp eight-track
players and reel-to-reel. Quadraphonic sound arrived roaring and
expired quietly. Before that, long-playing vinyl records learned to
live with the 45 rpm single. That was, after the LP dealt a
post-World War II death blow to the old 78 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Now the industry is at it again.
</P>
<P>
   The minidisc is a format that offers users a chance to pick
their own selections. It lets people customize their workout or
driving music. There is a recording deck at home, but the medium
you carry is nice and light, affordable and portable.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds kinda like the cassette, doesn't it? And that is just
what the minidisc makers want to replace. After all, the minidisc
is a digital format, a far superior recording to cassette.
</P>
<P>
   Minidisc, while big in Japan, has never been a smash here. Sony
years ago introduced it to thundering apathy. Not one to be easily
beaten, Sony came back into the market about 18 months ago with a
new version and a marketing blitz. Prices for some minidisc
recorders have fallen since then from $600 to under $500 _ with
some still-cheaper machines to be released this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the minidisc has a new foe: the rewriteable compact disc.
The CD-RW has some potential advantages _ most obviously, that it
comes in the CD format. But the folks at Sony want you to know that
minidisc is easier to record, smaller and more portable than the
CD-RW. Sony also notes that current CD players cannot play CD-RW,
although any machine that can play CD-RW can play all your other
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle is still evolving. Both CD-RW and minidisc have
yet to amass the kind of market size that can make all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highest-profile makers of the technology are Philips
(http://www.philips
</P>
<P>
   .com/home.html) and Ricoh (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .ricohdms.com/welcome.html). Another good place to start for
more information about CD-RW and other similar technologies is a
Web site run by Worldspan Communications
(http://www.span.com/shoptext
</P>
<P>
   /c.htm).
</P>
<P>
   For more information about dealers selling the minidisc, call
Sony (1-800-222-SONY). For information about Sony's products, visit
the company Web site (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .sony.com).
</P>
<P>
   High-tech ethics
</P>
<P>
   Computer error? Yeah, sure.
</P>
<P>
   Technology offers choices, and apparently an awful lot of
Americans are choosing to do things with it that are somewhat ....
questionable, including the use of technology as an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   A study shows nearly half of America's workers have ``engaged in
unethical actions'' related to new technologies, according to the
report commissioned by Guardian Life Insurance Co. of America and
State Farm Insurance Cos.
</P>
<P>
   The study was released by the American Society of Chartered Life
Underwriters, the Chartered Financial Consultants and the Ethics
Officer Association.
</P>
<P>
   The second-most-common behavior listed in the study was
``wrongly blaming an error you made on a technological glitch,''
which 14 percent of those surveyed admitted to. Nearly the same
number acknowledged using office equipment to shop on the Internet
and copying company software for home use.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more ominously, nearly 50 percent reported that
technology was causing them increased on-the-job pressure. But
perhaps a lot of answers depend on your definition: More than half
of those responding said playing computer games during work hours
and using e-mail for personal messages was not unethical. By
contrast, 70 percent said using technology to intrude unnecessarily
on privacy was unethical _ for example, paging an employee during
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But the most common confession was one familiar to any Atlanta
commuter: 19 percent of those surveyed said they have created ``a
potentially dangerous situation by using new technologies while
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Is your computer watching you?
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission has released a report on privacy to
Congress that seems to show the long arm of the Internet reaching
into your home and office.
</P>
<P>
   The report, based on an online survey of 1,400 commercial Web
sites, concluded that upward of 85 percent of Web sites collect
personal information, while only 14 percent provide any notice
about that practice, according to the Electronic Privacy and
Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   The center called the findings proof ``that self-regulation has
been so far unsuccessful.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report is available online
(http://www.ftc.gov/privacy/reports.htm). A previous report by the
center, called ``Surfer Beware,'' is also online
(http://www.epic.org
</P>
<P>
   /reports/surfer-beware.html).
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 1048EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
