<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHTOOLS30-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Tech Tools: Many frustrations of computing call for the touch of a
poet 
By Jack Warner  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I occasionally meet people who, upon finding that I'm
the guy who fills this space, tell me that they often read it but
rarely understand it, because it's too technical for them.
</P>
<P>
   I seldom know how to reply. I would like to take it as a great
compliment that my prose is presumably so intrinsically riveting
that people habitually read it even though they know they cannot
understand it. However, this smacks of fetishism, of some bizarre
kind of literary masochism. I am reluctant to assist in such
pursuits. Who knows where they might lead?
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, this column is dedicated to the literati among you
who run computers despite an innate loathing of them; consider it
your reward for reading this column even when it bewilders you.
</P>
<P>
   For those more involved in computers than poetry, I should
probably make clear that these are haiku, a form of Japanese verse
made with only three lines, the first usually consisting of five
syllables, the second of seven and the third of five.
</P>
<P>
   I am indebted to Dr. Frank Miller of Greenville, S.C., who sent
them to me, and to a gentleman named Robert Shiarella, who sent
them to Dr. Miller, and to whomever wrote them, wherever he/she may
be. She/he is a true artist.
</P>
<P>
   Three things are certain:
</P>
<P>
   Death, taxes, and lost data.
</P>
<P>
   Guess which has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95 has crashed.
</P>
<P>
   I am the Blue Screen of Death.
</P>
<P>
   No one hears your screams.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing my great fault
</P>
<P>
   Through darkening windows,
</P>
<P>
   I begin again.
</P>
<P>
   Chaos reigns within.
</P>
<P>
   Reflect, repent, and reboot.
</P>
<P>
   Order shall return.
</P>
<P>
   First snow, then silence.
</P>
<P>
   This thousand dollar screen dies
</P>
<P>
   So beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   The code was willing.
</P>
<P>
   It considered your request,
</P>
<P>
   But the chips were weak
</P>
<P>
   ABORTED effort:
</P>
<P>
   Close all that you have.
</P>
<P>
   You ask way too much.
</P>
<P>
   You step in the stream,
</P>
<P>
   But the water has moved on.
</P>
<P>
   This page is not here.
</P>
<P>
   The Tao that is seen
</P>
<P>
   Is not the true Tao, until
</P>
<P>
   You bring fresh toner.
</P>
<P>
   Server's poor response
</P>
<P>
   Not quick enough for browser.
</P>
<P>
   Timed out, plum blossom
</P>
<P>
   This site has been moved.
</P>
<P>
   We'd tell you where, but then we'd
</P>
<P>
   Have to delete you
</P>
<P>
   You step in the stream,
</P>
<P>
   But the water has moved on.
</P>
<P>
   This page is not here.
</P>
<P>
   With searching comes loss
</P>
<P>
   And the presence of absence:
</P>
<P>
   ``My Novel'' not found.
</P>
<P>
   A crash reduces
</P>
<P>
   Your expensive computer
</P>
<P>
   To a simple stone.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing my great fault
</P>
<P>
   Through darkening windows,
</P>
<P>
   I begin again.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 1048EDT &QL;
</P>
