</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Norton Tops Win 98's Wizard  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; Does the Maintenance Wizard in Windows 98 do essentially
the same thing as Norton Utilities, which finds and fixes problems,
improves performance and troubleshoots?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Ah, our first question about Windows 98! Maintenance
Wizard, which is new to Win 98, does in fact offer many of the
features that you get with a program such as Norton Utilities. It
lets you fix common hard disk problems, defragment the disk (also
called optimizing) and remove unnecessary files. You can even
schedule those operations to run on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   However, the $70 Norton Utilities offers some powerful features
beyond what Maintenance Wizard can conjure up. It can rescue
information from damaged disks, and recover files that may have
accidentally been erased.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; Last month, my area code changed. That means the area code
also changed for the number I use to connect to the Internet. How
can I replace the old number with the new one?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Go to Windows Explorer, which you'll find under the
Programs menu after clicking the Windows Start button. In the
directory tree on the left side of the screen, click the entry
titled Dial-up Networking. This will display a list of connections.
Find the one for your Internet service provider and click using the
right mouse button. In the menu that appears choose Properties. Go
the tab labeled General and change the number, then click OK.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I'm searching for a handheld personal computer that I can
take outside the United States and use for Word, e-mail and faxes.
I've heard that phone lines in Europe are not compatible with ours.
Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; All the phone lines I've used in Europe have worked fine
with my laptop, and that includes Germany, Switzerland, France,
Italy and England. The problem is not the phone lines, but the
phone jacks, which are different for each country. You can buy a
set of international jacks at Radio Shack or at most big drug
stores.
</P>
<P>
   As for the computer, you'll need a handheld model that runs on
Windows CE (a smaller palm-sized PC doesn't let you do word
processing). You'll also need a modem. Some handhelds, like the
Philips Velo or Hewlett-Packard 660LX, come with modems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I am looking for software packages that I can use to create
a living trust. Hope you can help.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Living trusts, for those who don't know, are like wills,
only they let your heirs avoid having to go through lengthy probate
proceedings. When you transfer property to a living trust, it's
owned by the trust, not by you as an individual. But as trustee,
you can keep full control of it. After you die, the successor
trustee is in charge of transferring the property to family,
friends and charities you named as beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Software packages for creating living trusts include Living
Trust Maker, from Nolo ($48) and Living Trust Builder, from Jian
($33). Since I haven't used them, I don't know how good they are.
But I believe they are valid in most states, just like
computer-generated wills.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; Please help me solve a problem that has been nagging me.
Does it do any harm to turn off the computer without proper
shut-down? I often do that because it gets stuck in the ``please
wait'' part of the shut- down process, and the advice on the
Microsoft Web site for troubleshooting this problem is too
complicated to begin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; It shouldn't inflict any permanent damage if you fail to
complete the shut-down procedure. However, the next time you start
the computer (as you've probably already learned), it may check the
system for errors before Windows boots up. And that can take a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, why is your system hanging during shut-down?
Unfortunately, the problem could be half a dozen things, including
startup files, memory conflicts or system settings. If you can't
live with the situation, you might consider just reinstalling
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Tip of the Week &QC; Give your right hand, wrist and elbow a break by
switching your mouse to the left hand for a while. You can easily
reverse the left-right button functions by going to the Mouse icon
in the Windows Control Panel (click Start, point to settings and
choose Control Panel).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a computing question? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 2155EDT &QL;
</P>
