<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: 
 CITYPASSES -- SIGHTSEEING AT A LOW PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    We were in Copenhagen without a car and wanted to go to Roskilde
to visit the Viking Museum, where five formerly sunken ships have
been restored. While searching for a mode of transportation, we
discovered the Copenhagen Card _ a way of paying a single price for
admission to a variety of museums and attractions and
transportation.
 &HT;    We used the card to take the train for a 30-minute ride to
Roskilde. Then we continued to use it during our stay for admission
to the city's museums, castles and other sites.
 &HT;    It's a great value _ about $20 for one day, $46 for three days _
and is available at train stations, tourist offices and hotels.
 &HT;    For additional information about the Copenhagen Card or similar
cards for other Danish cities, call the Danish Tourist Board at
(212) 885-9700, or visit www.woco.dk on the Web.
 &HT;    Now some U.S. cities are following Europe's lead by instating
their own passes and enhancing the idea with additional discounts
for mature travelers.
 &HT;    For example, CityPass cards are now available in Boston, New
York, San Francisco and Seattle, and they include special senior
prices.
 &HT;    CityPass features tickets to six popular attractions in each
city. And what a bargain! CityPass users save about 50 percent on
the combined total cost of regular admissions.
 &HT;    For example, in New York, the CityPass can be used at the
American Museum of Natural History, the Empire State Building, the
Intrepid Sea Air Space Museum, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the
Museum of Modern Art and the Top of the World Trade Center.
CityPass costs seniors $18 compared to the regular adult price of
$26.75.
 &HT;    CityPass attractions in San Francisco include the Blue &AMP; Gold
Bay Cruise, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, the M.H. de
Young Museum, the California Academy of Sciences and Steinhard
Aquarium, the Exploratorium, the California Palace of the Legion of
Honor and zoo. Here, the CityPass price for seniors is $19.85.
 &HT;    In Boston, the John F. Kennedy Library/Museum, the New England
Aquarium, the John Hancock Observatory, the Isabella Stewart
Gardner Museum, the Museum of Fine Arts and the Museum of Science
are included. The price for seniors: $20.50.
 &HT;    CityPasses can be bought at any participating attraction,
visitor center and many hotels.
 &HT;    Other city cards with discounts for mature travelers include:
 &HT;     _ CITY CONNECTION-DENVER.  This pass, which costs $7 for
seniors ages 65 and older ($10 for other adults), opens the doors
at the Colorado State Capitol, the Denver Art Museum, the Museum of
Western Art, the U.S. Mint, the Butterfly Pavilion and the Botanic
Gardens. It can be purchased at Denver Visitors Centers and RTD
stations.
 &HT;     _ SWISS MUSEUM PASSPORT.  This passport costs seniors about $25
and is good for admission to more than 180 museums for a month.
They're available at participating museums or by contacting the
Swiss Tourist Office at (212) 757-5944, or visit
www.switzerlandtourism.com on the Web.
 &HT;     _ MATURE TRAVELERS PHILADELPHIA DISCOUNTS.  This is not a card,
but rather a free, 50-page booklet filled with discounts of up to
30 percent off on public transit, attractions and restaurants for
travelers ages 50 and older.
 &HT;    For your free Mature Travelers Discounts brochure, call the
Philadelphia Visitors Center at (800) 537-7676, or write the center
at 16th St. and JFK Blvd., Philadelphia, Pa. 19102. The Web site is
www.libertynet.org/phila-visitor.
 &HT;     _ ORLANDO MAGICARD.  The Magicard, which is free from the
Orlando/Orange County Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau by calling (800)
551-0181, offers discounts of up to 50 percent off at attractions,
restaurants and shopping malls.
 &HT;    When you get your Magicard, be sure to ask for Orlando's
brochure listing discounts of 10 percent or more _ especially for
mature travelers. Call (800) 643-9492 or write the Orlando/Orange
County Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, 6700 Forum Drive, 100,
Orlando, Fla. 32821-8087.
 &HT;    On the international front ...
 &HT;     _ GREAT BRITISH HERITAGE PASS  offers free admission to more
than 500 estate homes and museums and costs $45 for seven days.
Available from BritRail, (800) 677-8585.
 &HT;     _ LONDON FOR LESS  offers discounted admissions at many tourist
attractions for a price of $19.95 for eight days. A city guidebook
and map are included.
 &HT;    By calling (800) 677-8585, you can get information about passes
for other locales such as Edinburgh, Wales and Ireland.
 &HT;     _ PARIS VISITE,  at about $30 for three days or $62 for Visite
Plus, includes regional rail, bus and Metro transportation.
 &HT;    Another card, The Carte Musees, which costs about $8, provides
admission to some 70 museums such as the Louvre and Notre Dame and
let's you bypass the queue to get in. They range in price from $11
for one day to $23 for five days.
 &HT;    If you wait until you're in Paris, buy the cards at any
participating museum, tourist office or Metro station. You can also
get information from the French Government Tourist Office's Hotline
at (202) 659-7779 or visit their Web site at www.Francetourism.com.
 &HT;     _ STOCKHOLM, GOTHENBURG AND MALMO CARDS,  for travel in Sweden,
are priced on the basis of time: For example, a one-day, Stockholm
card costs about $28 for one adult and two children under 18 and
allows admission to about 70 museums and attractions along with bus
and boat tours. These cards are available at the Sweden House
Information Center or other city visitor offices. For more
information, call (212) 885-9700.
 &HT;     _ BUDAPEST CARD,  for travel in Hungary, now comes in either
two- or three-day versions and covers public transit, admission to
the zoo and amusement park, as well as restaurants and shops. A
two-day adult card costs $10 and admits a child under 14. For more
information, call (212) 355-0240.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
 &HT;     (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 The Mature Traveler Newsletter  
