<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Love Him Or Hate Him _ King of the Business Press Release  
 By Tom Abate   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If business news gushes out of corporate America with fire-hose
intensity, then Lorry Lokey is the guy directing the nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   Lokey, 71, is founder and president of Business Wire, the San
Francisco firm that disseminates about half of all the business
press releases in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, 15,000 pieces of corporate propaganda on everything
from products to mergers pour into Business Wire's offices. The
firm's 335-person staff pumps these releases into thousands of
national and international media outlets such as newspapers,
magazines and wire services.
</P>
<P>
   Companiespay Business Wire anywhere from $65 to $1,350 to send
out a release, depending on whether the distribution is local or
global.
</P>
<P>
   Media outlets pay nothing for the information and can choose to
use it or _ more often than not _ trash it.
</P>
<P>
   Lokey said his privately held firm will gross $70 million this
year and now is neck and neck in market share with its only
national rival, New York-based PRNewswire.
</P>
<P>
   Lokey said his firm has a 63 percent share of the Northern
California market, which includes most high-tech news releases.
</P>
<P>
   Since founding Business Wire in 1961, Lokey has seen enormous
changes in the way business news is disseminated and received. Back
when he started, releases traveled on teletype machines, and the
business staffs at most papers were small or nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the releases travel over high-speed private electronic
networks, and the number of business journalists working at
newspapers and specialty magazines has exploded.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest boost to his business has come from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Lokey said that when Business Wire was founded, there was no
established procedure for issuing business press releases. The
Texas Gulf Sulphur case changed that. In the mid-1960s, the
Securities and Exchange Commission prosecuted officers of the Texas
firm for buying shares in their own company before publicly
distributing news of a major ore discovery.
</P>
<P>
   That case established the precedent that important business news
must be widely circulated, to level the investment playing field
between insiders and the general public.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Telling all? &LR;  Authors Jennifer Edstrom and Marlin Eller blew
through San Francisco yesterday to tout their insider's book on
Microsoft, ``Barbarians Led by Bill Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   Edstrom is a freelance writer and the daughter of Pam Edstrom, a
partner in Microsoft's long-standing PR firm.
</P>
<P>
   Eller is a former lieutenant of Gates who became a millionaire
on Microsoft stock.
</P>
<P>
   Although they wrote it together, the duo disagreed on several
scores, including the conclusions one could draw from the book.
</P>
<P>
   To Edstrom, Microsoft emerged as a ``predatory'' firm that
should be reigned in by antitrust regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eller left the company in 1995 (he now runs
Seattle-based Sunhawk Corp., which publishes sheet music on the
Internet), he defended Microsoft, which he joined in 1982 as
employee 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we're going out to eat the grass and, yes, we want to
eat all the grass, and if some of the other grass-eaters die, that
doesn't make us a predator,'' Eller said.
</P>
<P>
   The authors even disagree on Edstrom's motivation for writing
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Edstrom, 29, said the book was not an act of rebellion against
her super-successful mom, but a chance that any journalist would
have seized.
</P>
<P>
   Beside her, 45-year-old Eller sat shaking his head. ``Total
rebellion,'' he said, pointing at his younger collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Ramblin' man: &LR;  The digerati rocked the Fillmore last Friday
night at the Electronic Frontier Foundation's second annual
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   As tech events go, EFF's gig was magnitudes more fun than the
norm, with people actually dancing instead of milling around
reading name tags.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment was provided by four amateur bands _ Where's
Julio, The Raving Daves, The Flying Other Brothers, and David Gans
and the Broken Angels _ whose members hail from local tech firms
like Excite and PeopleSoft.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the night was a success. EFF board member John
Gilmore said the group raised about $170,000, up from $130,000 last
year. EFF will use the money to lobby in favor of First Amendment
issues that relate to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   And though my wife and I danced until the baby sitter demanded
that we return home, it did seem odd to see the light show project
the names of corporate sponsors like Merrill Lynch and Pacific Bell
on the brick walls where Jimi Hendrix and Janis Joplin rebelled
their way to fame.
</P>
<P>
   I guess the times, they are a changin'.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 2152EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
