<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTEL-CHIP-SFCHRO     07-01 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-CHIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL BETTING ON `WARRIOR PRINCESS' CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAN FOST   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel Corp. thinks it has found a savior to help carry the
company out of its slow-growth doldrums: Xeon, or as one analyst
calls it, ``the warrior princess chip.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the Pentium II Xeon, which Intel officially starts
shipping to customers today, could add $1.5 billion to $3 billion
to Intel's revenues this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the growth Intel has going forward will be from these
chips,'' said Nathan Brookwood, a microprocessor analyst with
Dataquest in San Jose. ``This is really central to the company's
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   With Xeon (pronounced zee-on), the world's largest chipmaker
moves firmly into the high-end market. The new chip will run
servers and workstations, powerful computers used to manage
Internet traffic, large databases and fancy graphics applications.
</P>
<P>
   The chip should spur new competition between Intel customers and
IBM, Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and other makers of big
corporate computers who use a different kind of chip.
</P>
<P>
   Although Intel already supplies chips for some servers and
workstations, Xeon gives it a new capability. Instead of selling
chips for computers that cost $2,000 to $10,000 _ a market Intel
now dominates, according to Peter Kastner, an analyst with the
Boston-based Aberdeen Group _ Intel will now move into servers that
start at $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of money can chase the chip blues away. And Intel's
had plenty of blues lately _ a year of flat growth, slow sales in
Asia and an antitrust prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Even Intel's vaunted technology came into some question, as the
Santa Clara giant announced a delay in its next generation of
high-end chips, Merced.
</P>
<P>
   For a fleeting moment last week, Xeon looked like it might have
caught the same bug. Word leaked out that when ultra-powerful
computers tried to run four Pentium II Xeons at once, a flaw was
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel says such ``errata'' are routine, and while this one
will delay certain high-end computers several weeks, it won't stop
today's official launch of Xeon. Intel is working on a set of
software instructions to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the most complex devices on the planet,'' said Intel
spokesman Bill Calder. ``There are 7.5 million transistors now on a
single piece of silicon smaller than the size of your thumbnail.
... We test, we check, we validate all the time. You can't possibly
have a perfect chip. All processors have errata.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger challenge for the Pentium II Xeon will be beating
some established competition in the high-end market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xeon is just a Pentium chip,'' said Jeff O'Neal of Sun
Microsystems, group marketing manager for products made with Sun's
Sparc chips _ one of Xeon's chief competitors. ``It's desktop
technology trying to play in the enterprise market. It looks from
this perspective like Pentium's last gasp. How far can they push a
20-year-old architecture?''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's customers don't see it that way. Kevin Joyce, director
of product marketing for Sequent, an Oregon company that makes
servers that cost from $50,000 to more than $1 million, said the
400 megahertz speed of the Pentium II Xeon beats Sun's speeds.
Sun's chips are based on RISC architecture, or reduced instruction
set computing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel, which has been lagging RISC performance, makes it clear
they are capable of delivering processors that out-perform RISC,''
Joyce said.
</P>
<P>
   Dataquest's Brookwood said the companies buying high-end servers
and workstations want the best performance available, and they're
willing to spend what it takes to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Intel notes that for its customers, the price-for-performance
equation improves with Xeon. Since 1996, Intel has sold the Pentium
Pro for big corporate computers. But last fall, Intel announced
that it was coming up with new names for its chips. It released the
Celeron for the sub-$1,000 PC market, and now it launches Xeon for
the high end.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium II Xeon will sell for $1,124 to $2,800 _ a much
higher price than the desktop Celerons but comparably priced to the
Pentium Pro. Jonathan Joseph, analyst with NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities in San Francisco, said he expects Intel to sell 1
million Xeon chips this year and 6 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   While PC sales have slowed, server and workstation sales are
soaring. Big servers are needed to keep up with the soaring growth
of the Internet. Big software programs require more-powerful
processors to run them.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's market clout, and its ability to run the increasingly
popular Windows NT operating system, give it a huge edge as it
moves into the high-priced arena, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Will Xeon push Intel out of the chip industry slump? Not by
itself. ``Intel's problems have largely been a result of a slowdown
in the PC market,'' analyst Joseph said. ``Intel now represents the
PC market. It's got 90 percent of that market. If prices are under
pressure, Intel will feel that pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Xeon, Joseph said, will only account for 5 to 10 percent of
Intel's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   While Intel won't say how much it expects to make from the chip,
it concedes that Xeon alone won't restore the phenomenal growth it
enjoyed until recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``There never is a silver bullet,'' said John Miner, Intel vice
president and general manager of the enterprise services group. ``A
nice portfolio of products allows us to ride the ups and downs of
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Xeon was two years in the works, Miner noted.
</P>
<P>
   The name Xeon, like Pentium and Celeron before it, is the
concoction of Sausalito-based Lexicon Branding. Lexicon coined the
word after much effort, looking for something that adhered to
Pentium's Greek roots but also would give it a forward look.
</P>
<P>
   With the ``x'' at the front, Lexicon President and founder David
Placek said, the name evokes ``the next generation.'' With ``eon''
meaning a period of time, ``It all came together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, a coined name can be the most effective route for
you,'' Placek said. ``We have found, when you have a new product
and you put a newly created word like `Xeon' on it, that says,
`Hey, this is new.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 1307EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
