A5561 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-LSI-SFCHRON &LR;      07-01 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-LSI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 LSI Logic To Acquire Hyundai's Symbios  
 By Amy Doan   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chipmaker LSI Logic Corp. said yesterday it will acquire Symbios
Inc., a Hyundai Electronics America unit that makes high-end data
storage and adapter cards, for $760 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us an `instant on' in the storage market that we
couldn't get through licensing,'' said Bruce Entin, vice president
of Milpitas-based LSI.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst said the acquisition is a natural evolution for LSI.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little overlap in the product lines of the two
companies,'' said Nimal Vallipuram, managing director of Bear
Stearns &AMP; Co. Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives LSI a broader base of intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   LSI is known for its chips for networking equipment and for
``system-on-a-chip'' technology, which combines multiple computing
functions onto a single chip.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Symbios will help LSI penetrate higher-end
computing markets by integrating Symbios' storage features with its
existing line of chips, analysts and LSI said.
</P>
<P>
   Although most analysts viewed the purchase as a shrewd way for
LSI to tap into the fast-growing storage market, one said that LSI
was ``paying too much'' for Symbios.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term, it's an expensive move,'' said Robert
Chaplinsky of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco. ``They're paying
greater than 1.2 times Symbios' 1997 sales.''
</P>
<P>
   But LSI's Entin called the $760 million purchase price ``quite a
bargain in today's market.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes just days after Adaptec Inc. of Milpitas, which
also develops storage technology, halted its planned acquisition of
Symbios over concerns that the U.S. Federal Trade Commission would
block the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Adaptec on Friday said it believed the FTC would object to
perceived monopolies in certain markets. Together, Adaptec and
Symbios control 80 percent of the market for high-end data storage
products, according to Hambrecht &AMP; Quist LLC.
</P>
<P>
   Both Adaptec and Symbios offer technology that lets computer
servers communicate with other systems on the network like scanners
and printers.
</P>
<P>
   LSI had been talking with Symbios during the same six-month
period Adaptec was courting it, according to LSI's Entin.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from LSI and Symbios met Saturday afternoon after the
Adaptec deal was scuttled and agreed to the acquisition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   LSI will take an undisclosed charge in 1998 for the purchase,
and will assume Symbios' liabilities. LSI had revenues of $1.29
billion in 1997 and Symbios had sales of $620 million.
</P>
<P>
   LSI has 4,400 employees, 2,100 of whom are in the Bay Area.
Symbios, based in Fort Collins, Colo., has 2,400 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition should be complete, pending regulatory approval,
by September 30, the end of LSI's third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at LSI said they do not expect any layoffs at either
company. Symbios will be operated as a wholly owned subsidiary of
LSI.
</P>
<P>
   LSI closed up 19 cents at $23.31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 2149EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
