A5565 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPAQ-LAYOFFS-HN     07-01 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPAQ-LAYOFFS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ TO LAY OFF 1,000 WORKERS IN HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN and KAREN SANTOS  
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The 1,000 Houston layoffs announced Monday by Compaq
Computer Corp. were planned before the company's purchase of
Digital Equipment Corp. and were inevitable even if Digital hadn't
been acquired.
</P>
<P>
   The local cuts come with the elimination of factory lines that
make desktop system boards _ also known as motherboards _ and some
consumer PC operations, said Greg Petsch, Compaq's senior vice
president for manufacturing and quality.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs, in manufacturing and warehousing, are part of 5,000
worldwide, most of which are directly related to Compaq's $9
billion acquisition of Digital.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs will take place over a 6-12 month period, with most
of them happening sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Compaq still expects about 17,000 layoffs worldwide,
which a Compaq spokesman called ``the big-picture number.'' About
15,000 of those will involve Digital employees.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,000 Houston cuts represent about 7 percent of the
14,000-person work force at the company's headquarters. The
combined Compaq/Digital workforce is about 84,000.
</P>
<P>
   More job cuts are coming here, but they'll be few and will be
offset by new jobs resulting from the acquisition, Petsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, this represents the majority of the (layoffs) that
will take place in Houston,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They are the largest number of job reductions since the company
cut about 2,000 positions through layoffs and attrition in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The local cuts are the result of ongoing changes in the way
Compaq is building and distributing its personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   From its beginning, Compaq designed and built its own
motherboards for its desktop computers. But what started as a way
to engineer technological advances into Compaq's systems, soon
became a drag on its ability to bring large numbers of PCs to
market quickly.
</P>
<P>
   With its new line of both business and consumer desktops, Compaq
has started using motherboards designed as commodities by other
manufacturers, Petsch said. As older machines that use Compaq-built
motherboards are phased out, those workers will be laid off, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Workers who assemble Compaq's lower-priced consumer PCs are
being laid off because those machines will be built in the Far East
where labor costs are cheaper. Petsch said Houston workers will
still work on Compaq's higher-priced Presario systems. That
includes PCs configured and purchased via in-store kiosks through
Compaq's new ``Built for You'' scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the consumer business, it's my sense that the
Houston factory is no longer a low-cost production plant,'' said
William Conroy, an analyst in Houston with Sanders Morris Mundy.
``Labor is just a small cost of the PC, but in an industry this
hypercompetitive, to say that every dollar counts is an
understatement. It's quarters, dimes and nickels that count.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's stock closed Monday at 29 5/16, up 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the workers streaming into a McDonald's across the street
from Compaq's northwest Harris County headquarters seemed concerned
about the layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected it, with this big merger,'' said one employee.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was as fatalistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned. I've put in a lot of years (at Compaq). I don't
want to let it go,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq is usually helpful to the employees it lays off, said
another worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help people get another job better than any other company
in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Sockwell, director of human resources for manufacturing at
Compaq, said the laid-off workers will receive a cash severance,
continuation of benefits and may be offered a chance to apply for
other jobs within the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also in discussion with some other firms regarding the
outplacement of these employees,'' Sockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not say how many weeks of severance pay workers would
receive.
</P>
<P>
   Petsch said that even though the local layoffs were planned
before the Digital acquisition, their announcement was delayed
until Monday ``to keep all this together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used the Digital acquisition to help validate our decision
points,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Conroy said Compaq held back word of the layoffs
because, ``It's probably more salable to do it today than three
months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also will close its warehouse and logistics facilities in
Houston, the result of the company moving to a build-to-order
system, Petsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Compaq built its computers based on sales
forecasts and used its warehouses to hold inventories waiting to be
sold. But to better compete with companies such as Dell Computer,
which sells its PCs direct to buyers, Compaq now assembles
computers only after orders are received.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's goal is to have 95 percent of its products deliverable
to the customer within five days.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also has transferred much of its storage needs to its
resellers and a network of satellite warehouses around the country,
Petsch said.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston warehouse space, as well as the assembly lines freed
up by the motherboard and consumer PC layoffs, will be used for
expansion of the built-to-order system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq is the top PC manufacturer in the world and, with its
acquisition of Digital, is the second largest maker of all kinds of
computers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the market for personal computers is in flux. Compaq is
trying to recover from a glut of commercial PCs that flattened its
profits in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Also, recent reports show that the consumer PC market, which had
been healthy earlier in the year, slowed over the past couple of
months as buyers awaited the release of Microsoft Corp.'s new
Windows 98 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The other 4,000 manufacturing layoffs will come as Compaq closes
and consolidates plants as far away as Australia, China, Brazil and
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   It affects plants operated by Compaq, Digital and Tandem
Computer, the Cupertino, Calif.-based maker of large systems that
Compaq bought last year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, plants that builds Tandem computers in Stirling,
Scotland, and Digital machines in Irvine, Scotland, will be closed.
Their operations will be moved to Compaq's own factory in Erskine,
Scotland. The former Digital factory in Irvine will become home to
Compaq's services operation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 1934EDT &QL;
</P>
