</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DELL-IRELAND-QNA-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Dell to exec sees Ireland as doorway to Europe 
By Jerry Mahoney  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Thefollowing is an interview with Michael
Dell conducted by Austin American-Statesman business writer Jerry
Mahoney on June 8.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much time do you spend in Europe?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it's a little harder because they're further away. I'd
say, certainly when I'm there, it's a big portion of the time. I'll
probably go over about four times this year to Europe. We tend to
rotate different countries, different operations, reviews.
</P>
<P>
   I was over in April, and I was there in January-February time
... and I went back in October. But it's important to get over and
understand the differences in the markets and what customers are
doing and understanding their requirements better. The other great
thing is the market, Europe is just booming.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening is that a lot of these companies are waking up
to the old idea of productivity and that they have to be
competitive in a world market. For example, I went to Italy and you
talk to the Italians, and what just about every Italian
businessperson will tell you is 'Well, the Euro is coming, and
because of the Euro we have to catch up with the Germans.'
</P>
<P>
   And if you're a banker or a construction company or any kind of
business you pretty much realize that you're going to have
competition from European competitors and you're no longer in this
island market that's protected and sold under one country. You talk
to the Germans and they think about the Americans and the Japanese,
they think about their competition on a global scale. Real Audio
Listen to this portion of Michael Dell's interview in Real Audio.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have Real Audio, you can download it here.
</P>
<P>
   More Real Audio excerpts from Michael Dell's interview.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a lot of the Germans see this as a real kind of
pinnacle time for their economy and their all excited about the
Daimler-Chrysler merger.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are either of those companies customers of Dell?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're both customers, both very good customers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do they buy from other vendors too?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh yeah, it's pretty rare that you can get all the business.
It's kind of like the Chicago Bulls, they don't win every game, but
they win a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is Dell in Ireland with manufacturing and later with the
call center?
</P>
<P>
   A: This goes back to 1990 when the business was growing quite a
bit across Europe, and it came time to have a manufacturing center
for all of Europe. The things we considered included the work force
availability, infrastructure, education level, the political
environment, the receptivity toward new businesses, the incentive
structure, labor availability.
</P>
<P>
   You consider all these things and Ireland came out number one in
all categories. The only category they didn't come out number one
in was, which was a question at the time and now I think it's not
an issue, is the question of if you put you're plant in France or
Germany or the UK, you probably have some enhanced business in
those countries, which is true, but all the other things
dramatically offset that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think there's a stronger, bigger corporate structure
that would maybe spinoff from that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the idea that you would be able to get more business. If
you look in Malaysia where we have a plant, we're the number one PC
supplier. It's kind of like in the Austin area, who do people buy
their PCs from? You kind of have the home town advantage.
</P>
<P>
   So you could make the argument, if you're going to have the home
team advantage, you should put it in a big city or a big town or a
big country. Ireland has just exceeded all of our expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the business in Europe grow very quickly, but the
operations there have kept pace, we've expanded it and we've
continued to make commitment after commitment and investment after
investment because the operation and the people there keep
delivering. The results are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of the employees I met over there said Michael has been
unequivocal about Ireland's role in Dell's plans. What is that
role?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it's really the backbone of our European
infrastructure. If you look at Europe, we have more employees in
Ireland than we do anywhere in Europe. In fact, outside of Austin,
there's no place in the world where we have more people than
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   There are some real good reasons for this. In our business, if
you think back to the computer companies of the past, they had this
idea that you stuck plants everywhere around the world, kind of one
in every town. The problem with that is you don't get any critical
mass and the key part of Dell's business models is inventory
velocity.
</P>
<P>
   If you took our plant on Metric Lane and you said OK here's this
plant that's producing a couple million computers a year, and we're
going to divide this plant into 10 plants and spread them all out
over the United States. Would you get higher inventory velocity or
lower velocity? Much lower, no question. Real Audio Listen to this
portion of Michael Dell's interview in Real Audio.
</P>
<P>
   You have more places to have stuff and more forecast inaccuracy
so the same applies: Austin is to United States as Ireland is to
Europe for Dell. It pays for us to concentrate our resources in a
particular geographic area. I'll put a little disclaimer on the end
here.
</P>
<P>
   At some point it gets to be too much in one place. And that's
true of anywhere in the world whether it's Austin or Ireland or
Malaysia because you could run into other kinds of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Workers, for example?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, the availability of work force, the availability of
infrastructure. I think we're a ways away from that but we keep
making commitments to the same places so I think we're away from
that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you look at the European market two years, five years,
10 years down the road, and it's importance to Dell?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dell's business in Europe this year will be approximately the
same size as all of Dell was three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Wow. What is that $3 billion?
</P>
<P>
   A: Last year it was $3 billion, this year according to the
analysts' estimates, close to $5 billion. I mean this is really
neat stuff. I think a lot of people look at Dell and they go, 'Gee
this is an incredible story.' But actually it's a lot of incredible
stories.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Europe in itself is an incredible story. If you just had
Dell Europe as a company, it'd be an amazing company. The thing's
11 years old, it's growing like wild. It's a very profitable,
successful business for us.
</P>
<P>
   The economy in Europe is about the same size as the economy in
the U.S., but there's half the number of PCs in Europe as there are
in the U.S. And what I think is going to happen is over time, that
gap will be narrowed considerably. Think about it this way.
</P>
<P>
   If the average employee in the average company in Western Europe
costs the company about $140 a day. I'm including salary, benefits,
labor, overhead, everything, which, by the way, is not that
different than the rate in the U.S. A PC costs $2 a day. What
people figure out is instead of giving people slates and chisels,
you give them PCs.
</P>
<P>
   These are the weapons of capitalism, the tools of modern
productivity. The growth rates in Europe are tremendous. The growth
in the U.S. for Dell continues to be very strong, and even Asia is
growing pretty nicely for us.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have the Europeans been just a little slower to realize that
efficiency?
</P>
<P>
   A: They've been slower to adopt in an aggregate market, but you
would see companies in Europe ... into computing as any company in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   You see companies in the Nordic region doing the same thing, but
then you see other companies that were more regional competitors
and didn't feel compelled to engage in computing as much.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the use of PCs in the home has not been as popular,
although that's one of the fastest growing areas of our business,
not only in Europe, but in the U.S. as well.
</P>
<P>
   Our consumer growth right now in Europe is about 100 percent.
So, as income levels increase, as the cost of telecom comes down in
Europe, you'll see more and more PCs in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you project that the European market at some point is
going to become more important to Dell's overall revenues than the
U.S. as this market matures?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think so. I think, like the movie Godzilla, size
matters. I mean, the U.S. market is still the biggest market in the
world. The way you ought to think about is, think about the top
markets in the world. It's U.S., Japan, Germany, UK, France.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those markets are in Europe, but even those three
together and the rest of Europe aren't as big as the U.S. So the
U.S. is still a huge, huge market, and I believe a market that will
continue to grow. If you look at the education market, the home
market, small business, medium-size businesses, and even large
businesses who are on a replacement calysts continue to speculate
that this enterprise market is going to be a problem for Dell. Do
you get tired of hearing that?
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I'm used to hearing analysts repeat themselves. There
is another thing that goes on here. And that is that the analysts
will quickly recoil and come up with a different approach when they
see Dell delivering results.
</P>
<P>
   We've had now seven quarters in a row of server growth in excess
of 150 percent. That keeps happening, and people say, 'Well, gee,
maybe we did miss something here.'
</P>
<P>
   Q: It seems to me that's a Compaq and Pfieffer's strategy of
punishing Dell.
</P>
<P>
   A: Doesn't seem to be working very well.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at the facts, OK. Two and half years ago, if you
said, let's look at the server market, you know, You needed a
microscope to find our server business. Now in the U.S. market,
we've got 14 percent share, Compaq has 30.
</P>
<P>
   HP has 12 and IBM has 10. So we're 40 percent larger than IBM in
the server business in the U.S. And we're almost half the size of
Compaq. And by the way, all this has occurred, this unprecedented
growth and share gain, with what I would consider to be our first
round of server products, which were pretty good but not awesome.
</P>
<P>
   And now, enter the new generation of products, which comes out
starting with the PowerEdge 2300, which has already come out. And
then the end of this month with Intel's Xeon introduction, we have
a whole new range of server and storage products.
</P>
<P>
   I think the game gets really interesting here because Dell goes
from fast-follower in the server market to product leadership.
</P>
<P>
   And if these guys think they're going to maintain 40 percent
gross margins as we're zooming ahead of them in technology, and the
customer everyday realizes that there's no reason to pay these
proprietary margins ... I hope they believe that. Because they're
going to be in for a very unpleasant surprise and it's called Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the delay of new Intel chip going to affect your plans?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not measurably. This is Heywoods. No '70s collection would be
complete without them.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Bertha Butt Boogie''? ``The Morning After''? Gimme a
break. Why would anyone consider singing about a woman's ample
backside or a romance aboard a doomed luxury ocean liner? How
utterly '70s. That would never happen today.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Wait. I forgot about ``Baby Got Back'' and ``My Heart Will
Go On.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Were there songs that Rhino missed? Sure. The roadkill called
``Muskrat Love'' by The Captain and Tenille. ``Margaritaville'' is
missing in action. There's nothing to hint that rap music broke out
of its crib with Sugarhill Gang's huge hit, ``Rapper's Delight.''
There's neither a Bee nor a Gee in sight, and there's nary a whiff
of Manilow.
</P>
<P>
   But the general mix is great. One minute you're enduring the
``Godspell'' reject, ``One Tin Soldier.'' The next moment you're
ready to skip class after hearing ``School's Out'' by Alice Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   So here now is a condensed, disc-by-disc review of the box's
outta sight highlights _ and lowlights. Right on!
</P>
<P>
   DISC ONE
</P>
<P>
   The first of the disc's 24 songs to smack you in the face is
``American Woman,'' by The Guess Who. Sure, it's got great
screaming vocals and chugging drums and guitar. But the lyrics?
Let's just say it's odd for a man to scream ``American woman, get
away from me,'' during the height of the sexual revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vehicle'' by the Ides of March quickly redeems this disc. When
Jim Peterik belts out ``I'm your vehicle baby/I'll take you
anywhere you want to go/Great God in heaven/You know I love you,''
you feel like you're listening to the commencement address at the
Tom Jones School of Macho Vocals.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end, ``Band Of Gold'' is covertly snide. Freda
Payne tells the tale of an unfulfilled bride who hopes her man will
``walk back through that door and love me like you tried before.''
Nothing like an impotent wedding night to send a song rocketing
Viagra-like up the charts, eh?
</P>
<P>
   DISC TWO
</P>
<P>
   Now we're cooking. It's the ``Theme From Shmetimes When We
Touch'' _ Dan Hill
</P>
<P>
   ``The Streak'' _ Ray Stevens
</P>
<P>
   ``Disco Duck'' _ Rick Dees &AMP; His Cast Of Idiots
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bertha Butt Boogie'' - Part 1 _ Jimmy Castor Bunch
</P>
<P>
   ``The Entertainer'' _ Marvin Hamlisch
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WAS THAT?
</P>
<P>
   What you heard might not have been what they meant to say . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Not In Love,'' 10cc
</P>
