 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Dell helps wire Irish city 
By Jerry Mahoney  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS, Ireland _ Ireland, in a furious pace to transform its
agrarian economy to a technological marvel in just over one
generation, hopes to have the world's first fully wired city.
</P>
<P>
   The project is called the Information Age Town. It's a joint
effort between Ireland's national telecommunications company, Dell
Computer Corp. and Ennis, a prosperous city of 20,000 whose origins
date to the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, each of Ennis' 12 schools was wired with a powerful
Dell server and Dell Optiplex personal computers for every
classroom _ 750 computers in all.
</P>
<P>
   Next, every school will be connected to the Internet by Telecom
Eireann, and the city's 7,500 students and teachers will get
personal e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   But the most ambitious part of the project is just getting under
way.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Internet access, each of Ennis' 5,800 households
will get a computer from Dell, which manufactures them 20 miles
south in Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   Dell will discount the price of the computers and Telecom
Eireann will provide a subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the computers, each household will be asked to
contribute the equivalent of $360, which will be used for future
community projects, said Kyran Kennedy, director of the Clare
(County) Education Centre in Ennis.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, already the No. 1 personal computer company in Ireland,
outbid Gateway and other PC makers to supply the computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to understand that market, which is on
our doorstep,'' said Tim McCarthy, sales director for Dell in
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The close tie-in with Ennis schools _ including specific uses
for special-education classes _ may have swayed Telecom Eireann's
judges, said Kennedy, who oversees the project for Ennis schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're trying to do is make everybody Internet-wise,
e-mail-wise and computer literate,'' he said. ``I would be happy if
the initial response was that all teachers saw the computer as a
friendly teaching aid.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that many of Ennis' 400 teachers are leagues
behind their pupils in their computer abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greater challenge is, what are we going to do in six
months' time when the novelty wears off?'' Kennedy said. ``And the
only solution is to get the curriculum totally integrated on the
PCs.''
</P>
<P>
   State-owned Telecom Eireann is a former monopoly now facing
competition for international business because of the opening of
markets associated with Ireland's membership in the European Union.
Competition for local business will begin in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The company also worries about customers who may bypass any
local call provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're heavily dependent on local call revenue,'' said Colm
O'Toole, who is managing the Ennis project for Dublin-based Telecom
Eireann.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see voice telephony over the Internet as a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Irish government recently began IT2000.
</P>
<P>
   Over three years, the $70 million project will put 60,000
computers in schools throughout the country, train 20,000 teachers
in the uses of information technology and wire every school to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for every teacher and student in Ireland to have
an e-mail address, according to the national Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-30-98 1058EDT &QL;
</P>
