<HEADLINE>
IN FIRST FEW DAYS, WINDOWS 98 SELLING AS WELL AS WINDOWS 95 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Windows 98 went on sale last week with little fanfare and a puny
marketing budget compared with its relentlessly promoted
predecessor, Windows 95. And Windows 98 also came to market under a
legal cloud, as Exhibit A in the Justice Department's antitrust
suit against the Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, it seems, at least not in the first few days. Windows
98 flew off store shelves just as quickly as did Windows 95 when it
went on sale, even slightly faster, according to PC Data, a market
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four days of sales, from last Thursday through
Sunday, retailers sold 530,000 copies of Windows 98, PC Data
reported Tuesday, based on daily sales reports from 20 chains with
6,000 stores. In its first four days on the market three years ago,
Windows 95 sold 510,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had sought to deflate expectations for Windows 98,
positioning the new operating system as a ``tune-up'' to its
predecessor instead of a ground-breaking new product. With the
low-key introduction, most analysts had expected Windows 98 sales
to build more gradually than was the case with Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was wrong in saying there was no pent-up demand for
Windows 98,'' said Ann Stephens, president of PC Data in Reston,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the early results, analysts say, do not necessarily indicate
how well Windows 98 will do in the long run. The first few days of
retail sales tend to be to computer enthusiasts, who are but one
slice of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the guys who regard putting a new operating system
on their personal computer as a form of entertainment,'' said Chris
LeTocq, an analyst at Dataquest, a research firm in San Jose,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the number of these computer enthusiasts has increased
sharply in the last few years as more and more people use
computers. By the end of this year, the number of personal
computers in use running some version of Microsoft's Windows
operating systems will be 376 million, Dataquest estimates. At the
end of 1995, the number of machines using Windows was 153 million,
according to Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   With more people using Windows machines, the potential market of
those who might spend $89 to upgrade to Windows 98 is far greater
than when Windows 95 was introduced _ making the initial sales of
Windows 98 somewhat less impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, about 90 percent of all shipments of PC operating
systems come already installed in new machines instead of as
retail, shrink-wrap programs for upgrading an existing operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   David Readerman, an analyst at Nationsbanc Montgomery
Securities, estimates that Windows 98 will generate revenues for
Microsoft of $3.2 billion in its first 12 months from sales to both
computer makers and retail customers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-30-98 2027EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
