<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT RULING SHOWS A FAULT LINE OF ANTITRUST THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ State and federal prosecutors insist that while
last week's federal Appeals Court ruling favoring Microsoft Corp.
might force them to alter their legal tactics, it also offers a
road map to help sharpen their new antitrust case against the
software giant.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of intense discussion, Justice Department
prosecutors and state attorneys general are even more determined to
press their case, several of them said in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has yet to decide whether to appeal last
week's ruling in an earlier federal suit against Microsoft. But
because the new case brought by the federal government and 20
states earlier this month deals with some of the same issues, state
prosecutors say they have decided that the Appeals Court opinion
has to be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of discussion, and the consensus is this
was the dicta of just two judges,'' Wisconsin Attorney General
James Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new case, Michigan Attorney General Frank Kelly
declared, ``We would be remiss if we stopped short of taking this
case up to the highest decision-making body we can get to'' _ in
this case the full Appeals Court or, if necessary, the Supreme
Court. Federal officials say they share that view.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, a three-judge panel of the Appeals Court
overturned a District Court injunction that had prohibited
Microsoft from requiring computer manufacturers to install
Microsoft's browser software for navigating the World Wide Web as a
condition of installing Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95 and its successor, Windows 98, which went on sale
last Thursday, are the operating system used on more than 90
percent of all computers sold today.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 opinion, the panel said Microsoft had the right to add
whatever new features it wanted to its operating system, even if
that included ``bundling'' other products, as long as the result
benefited customers. The opinion contained the clear message that
this standard could also be applied to at least some of the issues
in the new case. Acknowledging that, a senior prosecutor directly
involved with the case said that last week's decision ``gave us a
framework to follow _ and a framework to attack'' in the new case.
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal antitrust suits have been consolidated,
and Steven Houck, chief of the Antitrust Bureau in the New York
attorney general's office _ and the lead litigator for the states
in the new suit _ agreed that the Appeals Court ruling would help
prosecutors define their new case.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he said that the ruling would ``change the
emphasis of how we present our evidence'' in at least two ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, Houck said: ``We think the most important part of our
case is now the exclusionary contracts Microsoft has with Internet
service providers that require them to refuse to promote competing
browsers. What the Court of Appeals said had no impact on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Under arrangements with several companies that serve as Internet
gateways _ including AT&AMP;T Worldnet and America Online _ Microsoft
places links to these companies' Web sites on the first screen
users see on their new computers. As part of those arrangements,
Microsoft has required the companies to promote only Microsoft's
browser, Internet Explorer, to the exclusion of competing products,
most notably Netscape Communications Corp.'s Navigator browser.
</P>
<P>
   In March, just before Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates, was
scheduled to testify before a Senate committee about this and other
practices, the company announced that it was dropping these
restrictive contract provisions. But Houck remains skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft says they have eased those restrictions,'' he said.
``But I haven't seen the contracts. I've asked for them and haven't
gotten them. In any case, there is a body of case law that says if
you alter your behavior in the face of a lawsuit, it does not moot
the suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle agreed, saying, ``We are particularly concerned with these
restrictive contracts with online services.''
</P>
<P>
   Houck and other attorneys general also said that they would
alter their method of litigating another part of the case that most
resembles the ``bundling'' charge in the earlier federal suit. In
the first suit, the Justice Department accused Microsoft of
violating a provision of antitrust law that regulates ``tying'' _
the bundling of one product with another as a condition of
licensing the more popular product _ in this case tying Internet
Explorer to Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   The Appeals Court ruling was framed around the tying provision.
But Houck said the plaintiffs would press the new case using a part
of the law that regulates monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the law, monopolists are less free to engage in certain
behaviors, including this sort of behavior,'' Houck said. ``If the
Appeals Court decision holds, then the courts have abdicated any
responsibility for regulating the software industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said the
attorneys general and federal lawyers had accumulated far more
evidence against Microsoft for their new case than the Justice
Department had gathered in its earlier case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-29-98 2041EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
