<SLUG> BC-EXTRA-MARITAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FRENCH ARE PASSING UP LONG EXTRA-MARITAL AFFAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ French husbands are abandoning the once-accepted
institution known here as the ``five-to-seven,'' referring to the
early evening hours they spent with their mistresses before
returning home for dinner with their families.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of time and money has gradually obliterated the practice,
says sociologist Michel Piatte of Paris University. In fact, he
adds, while the French may still engage in the occasional
extra-marital fling, men have been forced by changing times to give
up what Piatte calls ``institutionalized infidelity'' engaged in as
a matter of course by their fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``French men take lovers but no longer keep mistresses,'' he
explained. ``There is an important distinction between the two.''
Lovers are temporary; mistresses are long-term.
</P>
<P>
   None of this may rate headlines, but it probably should.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing less than a social revolution, marking a
transformation in the relationship between the sexes here that was
centuries old.
</P>
<P>
   The five-to-seven was so commonplace even in the recent past
that it was employed as a plot device in countless novels, plays
and films. But writers don't evoke it any more, Piatte observed,
because ``it doesn't reflect French life now. It's something from
another era.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern economic conditions and heavy traffic have proved fatal
to the five-to-seven,'' Piatte noted. ``At five o'clock, people are
still at their desks. When they finally leave their offices, they
are likely to face an hour in traffic jams. There is simply not
enough time for a few relaxing hours'' of hanky-panky.
</P>
<P>
   The five-to-seven, which started declining about a decade ago,
assumed that there was a long-lasting liaison, something
increasingly rare these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mistress was usually supported in a material sense,'' Piatte
said. ``Her apartment was paid for by the man in her life as were
her clothes. She was what used to be referred to as a kept woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Most French women now refuse to be put in such a humiliating and
dependent position, according to political analyst Anne Kreibel.
What's more, she added, the acquiescent wife no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wives are no longer content to keep dinner warm wondering when
their spouses will turn up,'' Kreibel said.
</P>
<P>
   But Raoul Chautemps, an author of several books on French social
history, argues that the transformation has really been the work of
the tax system. It costs a lot to maintain a second household, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is that tax officials will discover that someone is
keeping a mistress and will start looking for hidden income,''
Chautemps said. ``In the old days, nobody in France worried about
that because tax evasion was easy. Now it is anything but. As with
so many other matters, it is the tax collector who has changed the
way people live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-01 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIZARRE MURDER SHOWS DIRE SHORTCOMINGS IN NEW YORK LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Yakov Gluzman wanted his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   He was a world-class cancer researcher _ a brilliant,
$170,000-a-year scientist who'd emigrated to America from the
Soviet Union, by way of Israel. For 25 years, he'd been married to
Rita Gluzman, a chemist, and he wanted out of that marriage.
</P>
<P>
   So Yakov moved out. He left Rita in their fancy house in Saddle
River, N.J., and moved into an apartment near his laboratory in
Rockland County, N.Y. For the next year and a half, Rita would
visit him.
</P>
<P>
   They continued a physical relationship, but Yakov held firm. He
still wanted a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Furious, Rita enlisted the aid of her cousin, Vladimir Zelinin.
He was in this country illegally, a refugee from Kyrgyzstan in
south-central Asia. Help me kill Yakov, Rita told him, or back to
Kyrgyzstan you go. OK, said Vladimir.
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday night about two years ago, Rita and Vladimir
sneaked into Yakov's apartment in Rockland County. When Yakov came
in, they killed him with an ax. They then moved his corpse to the
bathtub and cut it into 68 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Yakov's remains went into plastic garbage bags, which went into
the trunk of Vladimir's car. He was to dump what used to be Yakov
into the Raritan River behind a little industrial park in East
Rutherford, N.J. Rita Gluzman knew the neighborhood. She operated a
computer components business in that industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   Only, as Vladimir was feeding Yakov to the fishes, an East
Rutherford cop came cruising by and asked him what he was doing.
Growing up in Kyrgyzstan, Vladimir had developed a healthy terror
of uniformed men with guns. He spilled his guts to the cops,
implicating Rita.
</P>
<P>
   Since the murder had taken place in Rockland County, the case
ended up in the hands of the district attorney there, a guy named
Michael Bongiorno. But Bongiorno realized that he had a problem.
</P>
<P>
   He had Vladimir cold. Vladimir had, after all, been caught with
all those pieces of Yakov, and he'd confessed. But prosecuting Rita
was another proposition entirely.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the murder, Rita and Vladimir had cleaned
Yakov's apartment pretty thoroughly. There was physical evidence
that Rita had been in the place, but none that she'd been there on
the night of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   All Bongiorno had going for him in prosecuting Rita was
Vladimir's confession. And, in the wonderful, compassionate state
of New York, you can't convict somebody on the uncorroborated word
of an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   Bongiorno had no case against Rita _ not under the laws of the
Empire State.
</P>
<P>
   But Rita had made one big mistake. She'd sent Vladimir across a
state line to dispose of the body. That meant that the U.S.
attorney could act. And federal courts do permit conviction on the
uncorroborated testimony of an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   So, the feds moved in and prosecuted Rita under a federal
statute called the Violence Against Women Act. The law was designed
to nail wife-beaters who cross state line to batter their spouses.
Both Rita and Vladimir were convicted and sent to federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   This bizarre and macabre story is detailed in a fascinating new
book, ``Severed Relations,'' by New York author Tim Hays. It's a
chilling, captivating true crime story, but it's something else as
well. It's a story that points out that, in its treatment of
criminals, New York offers a level of protection well beyond what
the U.S. Constitution and common sense requires.
</P>
<P>
   Yakov Gluzman was murdered in a particularly vicious way. And if
Rita Gluzman had ordered her cousin to dump those 68 body parts in
the Hudson rather than in a river across a state line, New York
prosecutors couldn't have touched her.
</P>
<P>
   Am I the only guy who sees something seriously screwed up here?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SAFETY-HNS &LR;      07-01 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAX FOOD SAFETY COULD SPOIL THE HOLIDAY WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Kathy Felt learned an unexpected lesson in
graduate school four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Money was tight, food was scarce and a knish on the kitchen
counter wasn't going to last long with her roommates. So she ate
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was way before I knew anything about food safety and when
I was a hungry graduate student,'' Felt said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the knish, a baked dumpling, had been left
unrefrigerated several hours. Long enough to cultivate the kind of
bacteria that sickens thousands of people every year.
</P>
<P>
   Felt, now 27, remembers the nausea. Then the diarrhea. The next
several hours blurred in the bathroom. ``I was just violently,
violently ill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Felt is a program assistant at Cooperative Extension of
Albany County, where she tries to keep others from making the same
mistake by passing along tips on food safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only the bacteria were visible so people could see it, that
would be interesting,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This July 4th weekend, food-borne illnesses will be waiting for
a chance to spoil picnics and parties.
</P>
<P>
   Not to ruin your appetite, but consider deviled eggs, chicken
salad and hamburgers. That's a menu of potential problems like
salmonella, staph and E. coli contamination.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta
estimates that E. coli, found in some hamburger meat, is
responsible for 20,000 illnesses and 400 deaths a year.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Tom Gallagher, a former meat inspector, will
stand guard at the picnic he's helping to host this weekend in
Albany County.
</P>
<P>
   If people put out the salads too early for lunch, he'll stick
them back in the cooler. As a general rule, two hours
unrefrigerated is the limit for picnic foods. If the sun is shining
on your table, an hour tops.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher, a Cooperative Extension agent, is especially careful
about meats. Before he slaps the hot dogs and hamburgers on the
grill, he'll use a wire brush to remove any leftovers from the
picnic a week ago. To keep meat from sticking, he sprays on Pam.
</P>
<P>
   The key to a healthy burger is making sure it's well-cooked,
brown in the middle with no pink juices. Gallagher's pet peeve is
the platter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think nothing of bringing out a platter of meat,
cooking it up and putting it back on the same platter with the raw
juices on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though tempted, he keeps his mouth shut. Nothing ruins a party
faster than talk about bacteria. ``Generally, I don't say anything.
I'll go and rinse it off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5728 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-REUNITE-     07-01 1789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-REUNITE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 PREVENTING WAR in the TAIWAN STRAIT  
 &HT;     (For purchase information _ the rates are not prohibitive --
contact one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By CHAS. W. FREEMAN JR.  
 c.1998 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Two and a half years ago China and the United States stumbled
into a military confrontation that neither had sought or
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in retrospect, the March 1996 face-off between U.S.
aircraft carriers and Chinese warships and land-based missiles may
have had a salutary effect. The crisis reminded both countries of
the stake each has in positive relations with the other.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the two governments have worked hard to establish a
respectful dialogue about a range of bilateral and international
issues. Summits and other high-level meetings are once again a
regular feature of Sino-American diplomacy, and there have been no
further military confrontations in the Taiwan area.
</P>
<P>
   Until President Lee Teng-hui's visit to the United States in
June 1995, Taiwan and the Chinese mainland had been moving toward
mutual accommodation through informal economic and cultural
exchanges and dialogue. On both sides of the strait there was a
consensus on the ideal of ``one China'' and the imperative of
realizing it through some form of reunification.
</P>
<P>
   This consensus, endorsed by the United States, kept the peace
and fostered an atmosphere conducive to negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   But again the consensus has collapsed. Taiwan seems convinced it
can campaign for independence with the military backing of the
United States. If war is to be prevented, Washington must convince
Taipei as well as Beijing that it is time for them to work out a
mutually acceptable relationship.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has underscored the U.S. interest in resolving
the Taiwan question by peaceful rather than violent means. Yet most
American observers, including most members of Congress, have drawn
a lesson that the prospect of U.S. military intervention can deter
a Chinese attack on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   China's leaders have always said they would go to war to prevent
the permanent division of China. They now believe that they are
likely to have to do so. China's armed forces have begun a
decade-long effort to acquire the capabilities to overwhelm
Taiwan's formidable defenses.
</P>
<P>
   If a demonstrated ability to do this proves insufficient to
dissuade Taiwan from separation, China's armed forces expect to
receive an order to invade the island, notwithstanding the risk of
conflict with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Taiwan, the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) displays
of force that followed Lee's visit to the United States stimulated
fear and dislike of the mainland and accelerated the demise of
popular support for reunification. The sudden arrival of U.S.
aircraft carriers halted any conciliatory moves toward Beijing. It
convinced the leaders of Taiwan's ruling and opposition parties
that they could count on U.S. intervention to shield them.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has attempted to shake this
conviction through quiet dialogue with Taiwan. But its leaders put
much more credence in the unqualified public statements of support
they hear from majorities in both houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's leaders make no secret of their belief that, whatever
the cause of a crisis in the Taiwan Strait, U.S. congressional
pressure would quickly overwhelm a reluctant Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   And so Taiwanese politicians have concluded that they have wide
latitude to reject reunification and to maneuver the island toward
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's Kuomintang (KMT) still pays lip service to reunification,
saying that it might be considered when and if the Chinese mainland
democratizes. Hsu Hsin-liang's opposition Democratic Progressive
Party flatly opposes reunification under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, governments on both sides of the Taiwan Strait
embraced the concept of ``one China'' _ although they disagreed, of
course, on which was the legitimate regime.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, cross-strait trade was worth about $26.5 billion a
year. About 35,000 Taiwanese companies had invested $30 billion in
the PRC. Nearly 1.5 million visits _ the vast majority of them from
Taiwan to the Chinese mainland _ were being made each year. The
steady relaxation of tensions included minor steps to facilitate
the exchange of mail and trade across the strait.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing and Taipei also established a regular channel of
communication between citizens' groups, or ``nongovernmental''
organizations, to handle discussions with the other.
</P>
<P>
   Lee now asserts that the Republic of China, first established in
1912 by Sun Yat-sen, is still a sovereign independent nation whose
territory is limited to Taiwan and its offshore islands, and
entitled to international recognition as such.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's efforts to redefine itself as a sovereign nation-state
distinct from the PRC have been backed by well-financed ``pragmatic
diplomacy'' aimed at changing the global context of the Taiwan
question and raising the island's profile. Taipei has used economic
grants to persuade developing countries to recognize it as a state
separate from the PRC and to support its campaign to gain a seat at
the United Nations and other world groups.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, Taipei cannot join international
organizations unless Beijing agrees. Beijing was willing to
compromise on this issue when Taipei's membership was consistent
with the principle of ``one China.'' Taipei's new insistence on
independence has made additional compromises unacceptable to
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a flag and other symbols of nationhood, it is difficult
to see what Taiwan would gain from formal separation from China.
Nor, truth be told, would Beijing gain much from reunification.
Mainland China is already benefiting from Taiwan's economic
know-how and financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Taiwan accept Lee's redefinition of the status quo and
see no reason to return to a view of the status quo as ``one China,
even if not now.'' In short, Taiwan's domestic politics now makes
it difficult for its leaders to address Beijing's reunification
agenda, even if they wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's political establishment does not want to appear to be
against talks across the strait because that would not sit well
with the United States or Japan. The problem is that Taiwanese
public opinion will only permit talks with Beijing about how to
preserve and enhance Taiwan's separation from China. Taiwan's
leaders know that Beijing cannot accept such a premise for talks.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the 1950s, there is a real danger that
decisions in Taipei, not just Beijing, could ignite a conflict in
the Taiwan Strait. The United States, as well as both Chinese
parties, would be a loser in any such conflict, whether American
forces joined it or not.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policy can no longer hope to deter war exclusively by
keeping Beijing at bay. The United States must also discourage
decisions and actions by Taipei that could leave Beijing with
little choice but to react militarily.
</P>
<P>
   But such a policy cannot be implemented if Congress and the
administration remain at odds. A serious effort to forge a national
consensus on policy toward China, including Taiwan, is overdue. The
United States should state unequivocally that it will not support
or endorse any unilateral change in Taiwan's status by either
Beijing or Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   The rising military tensions in the Taiwan Strait also call for
a reevaluation of arms sales to Taiwan. In the 1982 Sino-American
communique, China pledged ``to strive for a peaceful solution to
the Taiwan question.'' In return the United States promised to cap
the quantity and sophistication of its arms sales to Taiwan,
``leading to a final resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States cannot hold Beijing to its word if Americans
do not keep theirs. The sale of 150 F-16 fighters to Taiwan in 1992
and some subsequent deals do not square with the 1982 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing is now wavering in its determination to stick with a
policy of peaceful resolution of its differences with Taipei. How
much of this wavering is due to U.S. noncompliance with the 1982
communique and how much to Taipei's new opposition to reunification
is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that U.S. arms sales to Taiwan no longer work
to boost Taipei's confidence that it can work out its differences
with Beijing. Instead, they bolster the view that Taiwan can go its
own way, regardless of history, geography and the views of Chinese
across the strait. This is not the message the United States should
be sending Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   That is why at a minimum the United States should return to
strict compliance with Ronald Reagan's 1982 understanding with Deng
Xiaoping and insist that Beijing do likewise. And as the United
States considers further arms sales to Taiwan, it should weigh
their impact on Taipei's intentions and behavior as well as
Beijing's.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest strengths of Taiwan's 22 million people are their
superior political and economic systems, not their capacity to
outspend, outarm or outfight the nearly 1.3 billion Chinese across
the strait _ with or without backing from U.S. forces. Taiwan's
security depends, in the end, on its ability to work out a mutually
satisfactory relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is no longer the central actor in cross-strait
relations, but its words and actions continue to shape their
context.
</P>
<P>
   Washington should return to a focus on the most important
interest of the Taiwan question _ ensuring that it is resolved
peacefully, by mutual accommodation, rather than in war.
</P>
<P>
   The regular summit meetings on which China and the United States
have now embarked offers ample opportunity to do so.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Chas. W. Freeman, Jr., is co-chair of the United States-China
Policy Foundation. A former diplomat, he served as deputy chief of
mission at Beijing from 1981 to 1984 and assistant secretary of
defense for international security affairs from 1993 to 1994. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is adapted from a longer version in Foreign
Affairs Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
