<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5747 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONG-KONG-REFORM-HNS &LR;      07-01 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-REFORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY ADVOCATES VOW CHANGE IN HONG KONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ A year after Britain turned its longtime colony over
to Chinese control, two outspoken democracy activists vow to push
the tempo of reform in Hong Kong's legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lee, Hong Kong's best-known democracy advocate, said in
his law office that he would introduce a motion calling for debate
on making the chief executive and entire Legislative Council
elected by popular vote. The newest council was sworn in Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's chief executive is picked by an 800-member election
committee; 20 of the legislature's 60 seats were popularly elected
in the May 24 election. Most of the other 40 seats are allocated to
conservative, pro-business members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We desire to increase the pace of democratization and the
changing of the Basic Law,'' said Lee, leader of the popular
Democratic Party. Of Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee-Hwa, Lee
added, ``They are very consistent in making sure our numbers are
reduced everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Basic Law has been Hong Kong's constitution since the island
and the adjoining New Territories became part of China on July 1,
1997, after more than 150 years of British rule. It specifies that
24 seats will be popularly elected in 2000, increasing to 30 seats
in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist government in Beijing would need to approve any
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he believed democracy could be advanced more quickly,
even in the face of determined opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Taiwan,'' Lee said. ``Ten years ago, the people of
Taiwan were oppressed by the Kuomintang (nationalist party).
Indonesia more recently _ Suharto was given another five-year term,
or so he believed. Now, he is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Lau, the American-educated founder of The Frontier, a
2-year-old reform group, went further, saying she will call for a
constitutional convention to revise the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very well to go back to the Legislative Council and
debate,'' she said in her office located in a public housing
project. ``At the end of the day, we will be outvoted. That's not
enough. We need a mass meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to demonstrate to Beijing that we have the support of
the people,'' said Lau, who also favors a directly elected
legislature and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's secretary for constitutional affairs, Michael Suen,
said that Tung's administration believes democratization will
happen in due time. Holding a copy of the Basic Law, Suen said,
``It's all here. You need time to do this _ cautiously, gradually,
one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in the final years of British colonial rule did Hong Kong
residents gain a semblance of democracy, including a directly
elected Legislative Council. That was replaced by the new council
and the colonial governor was replaced by the chief executive, a
position that must ultimately answer to rulers in Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
