<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5751 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREEK-ORTHODOX-BOS &LR;      07-01 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEK-ORTHODOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERSHIP TURMOIL STIRS GREEK ORTHODOX CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago the nation's 2 million Greek Orthodox cheered the
news that Metropolitan Spyridon had been chosen to be their new
archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, there is revolution within the Greek church,
with people who once supported Spyridon now formally demanding his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   What started last year as criticism by some church activists of
what they considered Spyridon's autocratic style, has ballooned
into a full-fledged attempt by many deep-pocketed Greek Orthodox,
including several in Boston, to force the archbishop to step down.
</P>
<P>
   It's an extraordinary display of public dissent that has
dismayed many Orthodox and non-Orthodox Christians. Some Orthodox
say the seriousness of the controversy is underscored by the makeup
of the dissident group, Greek Orthodox American Leaders, or GOAL.
The group's leaders are some of the most powerful church members;
at least 20 of GOAL's 54 leaders have each contributed $100,000 or
more to the Greek church over recent years, according to church
records and GOAL leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The archbishop fails to have an understanding of fundamental
American values _ freedom of expression, the dignity of the
individual and participatory decision-making,'' said Dr. Thomas
Lelon, executive director of GOAL and vice president and dean of
academic affairs at Nichols College in Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon, through a spokesman at the archbishop's headquarters
in New York, declined requests to be interviewed for this story.
But in an interview published in June in the official newspaper of
the Greek Archdiocese of America, he chastized his critics for
failing to put the good of the church ahead of their own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate that individuals have concerns and issues, and
even band together, but the church is not composed of parties and
lobbies,'' Spyridon told the Orthodox Observer. ``We are all
members of the Body of Christ. I hope we never forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   GOAL leaders have taken their campaign against Spyridon across
the country, trying to convince the rank and file that financial
mismanagement and a leadership style that devalues the laity should
cost the archbishop his job. So far, they have held meetings in 17
different cities, including Boston, where typically the meetings
are held by teleconference or in private homes. Their first meeting
was last November in Southborough, Mass. at a Nichols College
conference center.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A showdown between Spyridon and his detractors could occur
early next month when the church's clergy and laity gather for
their biennial convention.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has tainted the Greek Orthodox Church, caused church
donations to drop, and left many to wonder whether Ecumencial
Patriarch Bartholomew, who appointed Spyridon and is the spiritual
leader of the world's 300 million Orthodox, will intervene.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Orthodox church sources say, Bartholomew is
standing behind his embattled archbishop but is becoming
increasingly alarmed by the turmoil engulfing the church. Some GOAL
members and other church activists have personally appealed to
Bartholomew to oust Spyridon.
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon's defenders say the archbishop is being victimized by
malcontents, unhappy with Spyridon's efforts to safeguard the
church's Orthodox integrity from changes to suit American tastes.
For instance, Spyridon has chafed at the decreasing use of Greek in
the liturgy, and the abandonment of Byzantine chanting in favor of
Christian hymns. His critics believe he is trying to impose Old
World customs on a modern American Greek church that has moved
beyond its Greek origins.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Spyridon supporters acknowledge he faces a series of
problems he must deal with if they are not to undermine his ability
to lead the church:
</P>
<P>
   _The church's flagship educational institution, Hellenic College
and Holy Cross School of Theology in Brookline, Mass., is under
investigation by two independent academic accrediting agencies
investigating whether academic standards were violated last year
when the president and three professors were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Some professors have told the Globe that the four priests were
fired for their refusal to cover up sexual misconduct by another
Greek Orthodox priest. Archdiocesan officials say the firings were
based on personality conflicts and had nothing to do with the
sexual misconduct, which occurred at a campus party.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at least two professors have left the school in
recent weeks, according to two priests who work at the college. A
spokesman for the school could not be reached. The number of new
students entering Holy Cross for the September term is 25.
</P>
<P>
   _The Archdiocesan Council, the panel that helps Spyridon run the
church, has raised concerns in a report prepared by a special
committee about what they described as ``serious cash flow
problems'' in the church's finances, including the archbishop's
attempt to purchase a $1.4 million home without the council's
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Dimitriou resigned as the archdiocese's financial director
earlier this year. Church sources said it was because of
disagreements over the way church funds were being handled.
Attempts to reach Dimitriou last week were unsuccessful. Spyridon
abandoned his attempts to purchase a house, and aides say church
finances are being audited by an outside accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   _Priests in parishes in Massachusetts, Ohio, and California say
that Sunday collection box donations have dropped significantly in
the past few months. ``People who are disgusted by the direction of
the church's leaders are voting with their pocketbooks,'' said one
priest in a parish in Boston's western suburbs, who like seven
other priests interviewed for this story asked not to be identified
because they did not want to be linked publicly with the
controversy. Some supported Spyridon, others did not.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond issues of leadership style and financial management,
observers say the conflict between Spyridon and dissidents is also
a cultural clash.
</P>
<P>
   Though Spyridon was born in Ohio, he has spent most of his
adulthood in Greece and in Istanbul, where he has been shaped by a
strongly hierarchical and cleric-run church structure. Before his
appointment two years ago, he had lived many years in Italy,
serving as a priest and then as metropolitan.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the United States in 1996 and found a church that had
fully embraced American democratic values, where a premium had been
placed on giving laity a strong voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been puzzled that this commitment to Greek Orthodox
tradition has been misintepreted by some people as a negative
change, a `roll-back' or backward turning for our church,''
Spyridon told the Orthodox Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon's supporters recall that when he was appointed, it was
hoped he could help unite the 5 million Orthodox Christians in
America into a major religious force.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Methodios, bishop of the Greek Diocese of Boston,
said that Spyridon has endured a steep ``learning curve,'' and is
now trying to be more conciliatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's becoming more tolerant of situations he can't
change as quickly as he wishes he could,'' Methodios said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
