<HEADER>
A5755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-IWENT-BOS &LR;      07-01 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-IWENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFORMANCES PROPEL WILD IRISH CRIME YARN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
I WENT DOWN 
Directed by: Paddy Breathnach 
Screenplay by: Conor McPherson 
Starring: Peter McDonald, Brendan Gleeson, Peter Caffrey, Tony
Doyle 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: R (pervasive strong language, some sexuality and violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I Went Down'' is an offbeat Irish gangster movie that
overcomes its meandering nature with engaging performances, an
avoidance of formula and, above all, its characters' way of making
us take everything personally _ as they certainly do. Protagonist
Peter McDonald, as a Dubliner named Git who isn't even a criminal
but did time for an inept petty crime committed by his foolish old
father, is able to convince us that most of what he does is
improvised as the mission he's pressured into undertaking never
goes as planned, insofar as there even is a plan.
</P>
<P>
   The most convincing thing Git does is simply stand there and not
say too much as, barely out of prison, he learns that his dumb
buddy has run afoul of their unfriendly neighborhood gang boss,
played with surly panache by Tony Doyle. The only way Git can
prevent his pal's fingers from bring broken, he's told, is to
hightail it into the country and bring back one of the boss's
associates, Frank, with 25,000 pounds that's also missing. To
insure Git's focus on the task at hand, the boss sends along one of
his thugs, a hapless oaf named Bunny (Brendan Gleeson), as driver
and backup.
</P>
<P>
   Once into enemy territory, with Bunny playing Hardy to Git's
Laurel, they run into the usual traps, betrayals and
double-crosses. Convincing us he's making it up as he goes along,
and is able to stay ahead of the local goons because they're even
slower-thinking than he is, Git finds their quarry imprisoned in a
houseful of armed men. Breaking in with Bunny, they remove the
sought-after Frank at gunpoint. Then things really start getting
complicated as Frank turns out to be the Sheherezade of Irish
crime, a glib con man who won't stop talking until he finds
something that'll get to Git and Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   He knows nothing about the missing money, Frank swears, adding
that their boss only wants to get back at him for having bedded the
boss's wife. What's clear is that there's something rancorous in
the shared past of both older criminals, and that Git and Bunny are
unlikely to learn the full truth of it. What's also clear that
Frank is about to wear them down, or at least numb them into
lowering their guard at precisely the point where they want it up.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the comic bumbling starts to wear thin, and it begins to
occur to the chocolate-munching Bunny that he's not destined to
become the next John Wayne, the film convulses on cue, leading us
back to the feuding older men. If the climax seems anticlimactic
and ordinary after what had been its zigzag wildness and mournfully
funny larkiness, it at least throws into relief the inventiveness
of most of what has gone before, including an endearing belief in
the saving grace of blarney as the lowlifes realize with more than
a twinge of regret that they're really not inhabiting an American
tough guy movie after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
