<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5759 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIONEER-COGAN-BOS &LR;      07-01 1764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIONEER-COGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEER GROUP: OLD LINE, NEW FRONTIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when many executives of retirement age are selling
their firms and repairing to the fairways, John F. Cogan Jr., 71,
is jogging through Siberian timber farms, inspecting African gold
mines in a dead-faint heat, and conversing with Kremlin chiefs
about foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   And that is when he is not eyeing new ways to get citizens in
former communist countries to buy mutual funds, or tending a stable
of US funds, one founded during the Roaring Twenties.
</P>
<P>
   Cogan, the irrepressible president of the Pioneer Group Inc., is
the Energizer bunny of the asset management world.
</P>
<P>
   Bowtied and spunky, he presides over a paradox. Pioneer, one of
the nation's oldest mutual fund companies, epitomizes the rarefied
Boston Brahmin culture that considers the art of managing money a
gentleman's endeavor. Yet it also boasts &UR;  &LR; a passel of assets in
some of the world's wildest emerging markets, boldly going where
traditional investors fear to tread. The company, whose $23 billion
in total assets make it a relatively small player in the mutual
fund world, began aggressively investing in emerging markets long
before they became fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, Pioneer's eclectic collection of assets has led some
shareholders of the publicly traded Boston company to wonder if
Cogan has stretched his dealings too thin.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, investors are salivating at the prospect that
Cogan &UR;  &LR; _ who has run Pioneer for 35 years _ may sell off all or
part of the company &UR;  &LR; to cash in on the record prices that asset
management firms now command.
</P>
<P>
   More than seven decades after legendary investor Philip L. Caret
founded Pioneer with the then-novel idea of investing in
undervalued companies, what is perhaps the asset management world's
most idiosyncratic company is at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   With operations ranging from a core US fund business to timber
farms in the Russian Far East, a gold mine in Ghana, and funds and
ventures in the former Soviet bloc and Asia, Pioneer is literally
all over the map. So is the company's share price, which, after
quadrupling earlier this decade, has slumped. And so, too, is
Cogan, a Harvard-trained lawyer who mixes a rigorous globe-trotting
schedule for Pioneer with a practice at Hale and Dorr, a prominent
Boston law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for any reason I lost my energy level, I would want to
retire,'' says Cogan, blue eyes flashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see us remaining independent,'' he adds. But he notes that
is ``always a challenge'' given the temptingly high values of asset
management companies in a buoyant stock market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pioneer's main business is domestic mutual funds, &UR;  &LR; with
retirement money accounting for 40 percent of fund sales. But it is
the company's capital-intensive overseas doings that garner the
most attention _ and, sometimes, the greatest criticism from
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic fund business comprised 50 percent of the company's
1997 revenues of $343 million. While Russian financial services
contributed the next greatest chunk, 16 percent, other operations
abroad, including mutual funds, real estate and gold mining,
provided much slimmer revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Only three years ago, Pioneer's Teberebie Goldfields gold mine
in Ghana, &UR;  &LR; one of Africa's largest, generated most of the company's
profits. Since then, the operation has been tarnished by the lowest
bullion prices in 20 years and by power supply glitches, and the
mine has slipped into the red.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, where Pioneer runs a securities brokerage, a bank,
and some of the former Communist giant's first mutual funds,
turmoil stemming from Moscow's transition to a market economy has
depressed stock and debt markets and raised questions about
Russia's prospects for growth. Pioneer's Forest-Starma timber
operations in Siberia have been temporarily felled by collapsed
demand from Asia and moribund log prices. The troubles will hand
Pioneer a $10 million loss for the second quarter and have
depressed the company's already limp share price.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It is not unusual for mutual fund companies to have subsidiary
assets _ Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest fund firm, has
telecommunications, real &UR;  &LR; estate, newspaper, and limousine
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   And plenty of fund companies are now going overseas to tap into
the next investment frontier _ although few own and operate
physical assets abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But some wonder if Pioneer should become less diversified to
compete in the burgeoning mutual fund business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cogan is brilliant, and he sees a lot of different
opportunities that others don't see,'' says &UR;  &LR; Michael S. Beall,
executive vice president of Davenport &AMP; Co., a financial services
firm in Richmond, that holds a 1.5 percent stake in Pioneer. ``I
think he sees too many for a company of his size. I just question
the efficiency of trying to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer faces more than volatility in commodities and emerging
markets. The value-style investing that made some of the company's
15 stock funds good performers in the last decade has been less
fruitful in today's market, which favors well-known, large-company
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Over 12 months through June 18, Pioneer funds have been erratic.
Returns at the company's Capital Growth fund, which invests in
lesser-known, underpriced companies, are less than half the 20.1
percent average of other such funds, according to fund tracking
firm &UR;  &LR; Lipper Analytical Services Inc. Returns at most other Pioneer
funds that buy ``value'' stocks are squarely in the middle or at
the bottom of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pioneer's Growth Shares fund, which buys large
company stocks, has soared over the same period, gaining 35.6
percent, compared with the average 20.1 percent. And the flagship
Pioneer fund, a growth and income fund started in 1928, rose 26.7
percent, nearly 8 percentage points above its peers.
</P>
<P>
   Not all is gloomy for the company. Last year Pioneer's revenue
rose 43 percent, to $343 million, mainly on record sales of its US
funds. Earnings rose 55 percent to $29.2 million. And the strong
stock market has more than doubled Pioneer's total assets in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   But redemptions of shares in Pioneer funds last year rose
sharply from &UR;  &LR; the previous year. The company was the first to set
foot in many foreign markets but now has a pack of competitors
nipping at its heels in the global race for investors' money. &UR;  &LR; As
the mutual fund and retirement assets businesses soar, Pioneer is
having to compete with larger fund houses with broader offerings
and more marketing muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Among analysts and shareholders, ``there is discussion now that
maybe they should try to sell off the mutual fund business,'' says
R. Bentley Offut, an analyst at Offut Securities in Hunt Valley,
Md.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, Pioneer as a whole could fetch as much as $1
billion, with Cogan, who owns 14 percent of the common stock and
even greater voting rights, pocketing at least $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, investors bought Pioneer stock on the strength of the
company's gold mine. Now, with production setbacks, analysts
speculate that Cogan may seek to &UR;  &LR; sell the gold interest. The
company tried but failed to spin off its gold-mining subsidiary in
1995. The plan was intended to raise cash to prospect new veins in
Africa and Russia, but it faltered because of &UR;  &LR; a drop in bullion
markets and pricing issues for the gold unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hate to take this world-class operation and give it
up in a fire sale,'' says Pioneer chief financial officer William
H. Keogh. But he acknowledges that shareholders have been concerned
about the mine's profitability.
</P>
<P>
   But to Cogan, whose company has been through everything from the
Great Depression to the 1980's Wall Street boom, &UR;  &LR; the mine is a
hedge against inflation designed to produce revenues when stocks
falter.
</P>
<P>
   While he still considers natural resources ``a natural fit'' for
the mutual fund company, he adds &UR;  &LR; that the mine's fate is ``an open
question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a fine line between patience and
stubbornness,'' Cogan says,``and I've always got to watch that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogan, who runs three to four miles daily, and who describes
himself as ``adventurous with a sense of protocol'', shows no
desire to retire soon from the company he has molded in his image.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, in training that foreshadowed &UR;  &LR;  his predilection for
the unconventional, Cogan was already looking eastward. In a
Harvard undergraduate thesis on the role of astrology in European
medieval medicine, he examined the influence of Byzantium.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing law school, he considered a practice in
California before joining Hale and Dorr, which counts Pioneer as a
client. In 1963, he bought Caret's interest in Pioneer, then an
old-line, blue-blood mutual fund house.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, at a time when no asset managers were looking
at foreign markets, Cogan registered Pioneer to sell US mutual
funds in Germany. After the Soviet bloc's collapse, he raced into
Russia and Eastern Europe to set up the region's first funds. None
of them produce big revenues yet. But many of them, especially in
Poland, have been quite successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cogan's probably the most complete one-man band I've ever
met,'' says David Silver, a former chairman of the Investment
Company Institute, a mutual fund industry trade group. (Cogan is an
ICI chairman and does much philanthropic work in Boston).
</P>
<P>
   Still, some shareholders carp that Cogan's capital-intensive,
long-term strategy inhibits short-term profits and that Pioneer
needs to ramp up its stock price, which has been more or less flat
since mid-1995. Now at 27 3/4 on the New York Stock Exchange, it
is &UR;  &LR; down 1 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of love them and hate them,'' Beall says. ``I like a
lot of the things they have, but they can just wear me down. Jack
is a little too long term in his vision for some of us.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cogan, long term is precisely the point. Describing
Pioneer's future as increasingly overseas, he speaks of
a &UR;  &LR; potpourri of assets _ mutual funds for the Chinese, pension
schemes for Russians, and gold as a hedge against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many times along the way, people would say,
`Jack, don't spend your money on this _ why don't you just drop
it?'' he says, describing Pioneer's first forays oversees.
</P>
<P>
   But Cogan makes clear that much of Pioneer's future lies far
from his perch in downtown Boston. ``A lot of the play,'' he says,
``is going to be abroad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
