<HEADER>
A5763 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-TESTING-BOS &LR;      07-01 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-TESTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMERS SAY THERE'S MUCH TO LEARN FROM JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To make teaching a more attractive profession to the smartest
college graduates, the model reformers cite most often is Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In a comprehensive comparison of 26 countries that prompted much
hand-wringing in this country last fall, Japan, like most of the
nations surveyed, outranked the United States in math and science
at three grade levels from elementary to high school.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the difference is cultural, but questions on the test
suggested some of the differences may be in the way the United
States trains and treats teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese teachers have larger classes than their US
counterparts, their students watch as much television, and spend
less time in school. Yet teachers there get more intensive
training, including a year residency in a school much like medical
residencies in the United States. They then take a highly
competitive exam, after which those who pass are placed in school
under the direction of a master teacher, who is assigned to counsel
young teachers for the year. In that year, teachers also spend 60
hours in special, school-based training sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries are higher for beginning teachers, although they don't
rise as dramatically as salaries do here. And the profession is
much more competitive. Only one out of six teachers in training are
certified to become teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very selective,'' said Richard Murnane, professor of
education at Harvard and author of ``Who Will Teach?'' ``That means
you've got a profession people want to go into. Just raising
salaries is not a very effective way of getting better teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   And teachers have better working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   They get 25 hours of preparation time for every 20 hours they
teach. US teachers, by comparison, get 8.3 minutes per hour of
teaching, according to the National Commission on Teaching and
America's Future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our general view of teaching is that if the teacher is not in
front of the classroom, she is not teaching,'' says Paul Reville,
the head of the Massachusetts Education Reform Review Commission,
set up to study the success of the 1993 school reform law. ``In
Japan, they spend a fair amount of their day with one another,
talking about student performance and talking about ways to improve
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, says Richard Elmore, an education professor at
Harvard, is that we get what we demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers have higher status in every other industrialized
nation,'' Elmore says. ``Americans don't take the profession
seriously, they don't think it takes much skill to teach. So we
tend to get that level of skill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5766 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-PRISONER-BRACELET-     07-01 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PRISONER-BRACELET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC PRISONER BRACELETS HAVEN'T CAUGHT ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY R. DOWDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six months ago, Stephen C. would end his nights by
lifting himself off a barstool at closing time. Now, he rushes home
to beat his 6:30 p.m. curfew.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30 on most nights, he is fast asleep, curled up with a
book. &UR;  &LR; Any thoughts of slipping out are arrested by the black band
hugging his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even chance it,'' he said, bluntly. ``If I screw up I
go back to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen, a convicted drunk driver, is among a handful of
offenders in Massachusetts who serve time outside of prison,
strapped to an electronic bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic monitoring, widely viewed as tougher than probation
but less stringent than prison, has become known through such
celebrated cases as those of Raymond and Shirley Souza, the elderly
Lowell couple convicted in 1993 of raping their grandchildren, and
of Adalberto Bonilla, the Boston police officer who was arrested
last month on home-invasion charges.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being a significantly cheaper and potentially
more-productive alternative to incarceration, they barely are being
used in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the lack of appeal range from a penchant among
prosecutors, attorneys, and judges to shun a newfangled device to
the weekly fees offenders must pay to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Poor public relations also may play a role. Criminal justice
experts have not yet extolled the virtues of home detention, and
state authorities seldom have chosen to use it on offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 46,000 adults on probation in Massachusetts, about 125
are beholden to the gadget. That contrasts with Michigan, which
uses electronic monitoring on 3,000 of its 52,222 probationers and
parolees, and North Carolina, which has bracelets on 750 of 92,456
such offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 24-hour-a-day sanction,'' said John F. Cremens Jr.,
Massachusetts' &UR;  &LR; first deputy commissioner of probation. ``We'd like
to see it used more.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic monitoring is available for people convicted of
nearly all offenses, but county-run programs tend to disqualify
violent offenders, sex offenders, and people serving mandatory
minimum drug sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Bracelet wearers can live at home, hold a job, and keep family
ties but venture away from home only at specific times agreed to
with probation officers. The bracelet emits radio waves 24 hours a
day that alert officers when an offender is AWOL.
</P>
<P>
   Bracelet wearers also must take a Breathalyzer-type test every
time they enter their homes. They speak and breathe into a gun that
is hooked up to sensitive equipment through phone lines, and the
gun reads their blood-alcohol level. A positive alcohol reading
could land an offender back in a cell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; An offender who is released with a bracelet must pay 25
percent of his or her job earnings to the Department of Correction
or to local law enforcement agencies. &UR;  &LR; Stephen C., a construction
worker, pays $125 a week to the Norfolk County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have left me in prison to rot,'' he said, asking
that his last name not be used to avoid embarassment. ``It's the
price of freedom, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 study by the Massachusetts Institute for a New
Commonwealth found that using the bracelet could help cut down on
recidivism. It found probationers and parolees to be behind 60
percent of the heroin and cocaine transactions in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vastly underutilized,'' said Michael Gritton, policy
director of the institute, which conducted the 1996 study. ``The
biggest opportunity to lower crime in this state is in the area of
community corrections, and electronic monitoring is one of the two
or three most effective tools we have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritton recalled cases in which violent offenders struck again
while on probation, including Brian J. Nagle, a convicted child
molester and probationer who was charged last month with sexually
assaulting a 6-year old boy in Amesbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wasn't he on a bracelet?'' Gritton asked, adding that
Nagle lived around the corner from a Boys and Girls Club. ``In most
cases like this one if we don't use electronic monitoring, then
we're using nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   US District Court Judge Nancy Gertner relies on the bracelet
often, particularly for nonviolent offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly prison and not exactly home,'' she said.
``It's appropriate for people for whom prison makes no sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Gregory Phillips of Roxbury District Court said the
bracelet is best applied to teenagers. ``I like the concept of
having tighter, more secure positions with respect to juveniles as
opposed to adults,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bracelet is easy on state coffers _ it costs about $10,000
per year &UR;  &LR; _ while a cell bed costs more than $30,000. Many criminal
justice experts say society benefits when offenders keep up family
relations and maintain job skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strong case to be made for using it more,'' said
Francis J. Carney, executive director of the state Sentencing
Commission. ``They're almost as restrictive as if the offender's
behind bars, but in a more constructive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Community Corrections, created last year and
funded at $17 million, hopes to use more electronic monitoring in
Barnstable, Worcester, Hampden, Bristol, Suffolk, and Norfolk
counties, said Jonathan Randall, deputy director of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk County, which was ordered by the federal courts to ease
jail overcrowding in 1988, was one of the first places in the
nation to use electronic monitoring. During the past decade, it has
used bracelets on nearly 2,000 offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no joke,'' said John H. Flood, the Norfolk sheriff.``A
lot of guys don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flood recalled an offender who was under strict house arrest but
who went a few feet out into his backyard to soak up some sun. The
bracelet alerted authorities that he left the house. The offender
was given a second chance. He tried again to leave his house to do
some gardening. He was caught again. This time, he was thrown in
jail for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go on a bracelet, you understand that this is a
privilege,'' Flood said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
