<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-SQUEEZE-2TAK     07-01 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-SQUEEZE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED FOR TEACHERS ACROSS US SQUEEZES STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the news that half the teacher candidates could not pass a
test of basic skills has shocked Massachusetts over the past two
weeks, it is merely a hint of what is to come nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   As a baby boomlet pushes enrollment to its highest level ever,
and teachers hired for the baby boom prepare to retire, the United
States will find itself replacing 2 million of its 2.7 million
teachers over the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as schools demand more of students, their teachers are
still held to remarkably low, if any, standards. With between 30
and 60 percent of new teachers across the country already failing
in basic skills, schools will have no choice but to staff the
nation's classrooms with undereducated and unqualified candidates
when the demand for new recruits rises.
</P>
<P>
   It is this tension between quantity and quality that has
historically frustrated efforts to improve a profession long
plagued by low salaries, low test scores, and the old jibe, ``Those
who can't, teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider California, where a 1996 initiative to shrink class
sizes put so much pressure on schools that they hired 11,000
teachers without credentials. In Los Angeles, 59 percent of new
hires _ 2,100 teachers _ had never been in a classroom. Hundreds
more were let in without passing basic skills tests.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, after so many prospective teachers failed the
test last month, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci called for testing
all teachers and firing those who fail. But before that, he, like
President Clinton, California Governor Pete Wilson, and dozens of
others, had talked only of hiring more teachers _ 4,000 of them in
Cellucci's case _ and not at all of how to get better teachers. Yet
if the teachers who fail skills tests are fired, who will replace
them?
</P>
<P>
   States have talked tough in recent years about teacher tests,
but faced with so few qualified applicants they set a passing
standard even lower than the one Massachusetts set last week _ an F
nationwide compared to a D here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we've tended to solve the problem is the way
California is: put warm bodies in front of kids,'' says Richard
Elmore, professor of education at Harvard and a member of a
nationwide commission on teacher education in the mid-1980s. ``You
don't open school without having teachers in the classroom, so any
determination we have to crack down on the quality of the teaching
force goes out the window when we need teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   And now more than ever, the nation needs teachers. Whether
states fire bad teachers, hire more teachers to shrink class sizes,
or just replace the ones who will retire, the challenge will be not
only to find more candidates, but more qualified candidates.
Solutions come from all directions, and faster than you can add 2
plus 2. But fixing what's wrong with the nation's teaching force is
a more complex equation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
An urban issue
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To some, calling America's teaching problem a shortage is a
misnomer. Over and over, suburbs find hundreds of applicants queued
up for a dozen or so jobs. Education schools report that enrollment
is up.
</P>
<P>
   But urban districts and bulging border states like Texas,
California, and Florida are having a harder time finding enough
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the teachers who do apply want to teach elementary
school, or subjects like English or history. Sixty percent of
Massachusetts superintendents surveyed by the business-backed
research group Mass Insight last year reported problems finding
qualified teachers for foreign languages, science, or math. Other
states face similar shortages.
</P>
<P>
   So if not everyone agrees on whether there is a shortage of
numbers, they agree almost unanimously about the shortage of
qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure are initiatives like Clinton's plan to
hire 100,000 more teachers to shrink class sizes, and similar plans
by several other governors. In California, the class-size
initiative created a demand for 21,000 teachers, more than half of
them hired without completing basic training like student teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did bring in a lot of people off the street,'' says Emily
Feistritzer, head of the National Center for Education Information
in Washington, which publishes an annual survey of who enters
teaching. ``When you get that kind of demand, there's no other
way.''
</P>
<P>
   So when so many teaching candidates in Massachusetts failed the
state's new literacy test, the obvious question became: how would
existing teachers do if forced to take the same test?
</P>
<P>
   The indications suggest a similarly dismal answer.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 11,000 students in 10th grade, Harvard Professor
Richard Murnane found that those with the strongest academic skills
were least likely to become teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Entering college, those who declare an interest in teaching have
historically had lower SAT scores than those who do not. And while
the scores required to enter teacher colleges have risen
nationwide, they still lag behind the average scores of
college-bound freshmen. A study by the Massachusetts Board of
Education in 1996 found teacher education programs accepting
students with as low a combined SAT score as 642, out of a possible
1600. Public colleges like Salem State, which turn out the most
teacher candidates, required scores only in the 800s, still far
below the average state combined SAT score of 996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically open admissions,'' says Massachusetts Board of
Education Chairman John R. Silber, the former Boston University
president who argues for shutting down teacher education programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, 44 states have imposed teacher tests,
trying to demand more of those who come out of teacher colleges.
But the tests have proven no guarantee of high standards. The most
commonly used Praxis test grades between 150 and 190; in most
states, passing is between 168 and 172, barely the halfway mark.
Virginia, with a passing grade of 178 is considered the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Knowing the score
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In response to public demands for tests, teachers unions often
argue that a score can't measure a gift for teaching.
</P>
<P>
   But if common sense doesn't support the notion that teachers
with high scores might produce students with high scores, repeated
studies have. In a report last November, the National Commission on
Teaching and America's Future found that states that had made the
most investments in teaching had produced the most gains in student
tests.
</P>
<P>
   But what appears most important is teachers' grounding in the
subjects they teach.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report quoted a Texas study which found that
teachers with expertise in the subject they teach accounted for 40
percent of the difference in students' reading and math scores. A
New York study found it even more significant, accounting for 90
percent of the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in this area, too, American teachers lag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
