<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5772 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WENTWORTH-WOODHOUSE-A     07-01 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENTWORTH-WOODHOUSE-ANTIQUES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AUCTION TO MAKE MERCHANT IVORY PROUD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Mitchell Owens is the design editor of Traditional Home magazine.  
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is a country-house auction without the house? The answer: A
mirage of marketing. That is the case with the sale on Wednesday at
Christie's in London dedicated to Wentworth Woodhouse in Yorkshire,
the biggest house in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on reflected glory and occasional provenance by
association, the auction house has spun a slender cache of books,
art and furniture into a Merchant Ivory-like production.
</P>
<P>
   But given the riches of the Earls Fitzwilliam, who inherited
Wentworth in 1782, the splendors, though few, are nonetheless
extraordinary. Among them is the Rockingham Chaucer, printed in
1473-74 and acquired by a Fitzwilliam ancestor in 1776. Valued at
$1.1 million, it is the last privately owned first edition of ``The
Canterbury Tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Paintings by Stubbs and Reynolds are represented, but the star
is a 7-foot-by-4-foot portrait of the Countess of Carlisle, painted
in 1637 by Sir Anthony van Dyck, which is expected to bring $5
million. It is, however, merely the largest of a half-dozen
portraits by the artist owned by the family, so it seems fair to
presume that the really good stuff is still at home.
</P>
<P>
   Home, however, is not Wentworth. Though the catalogue limns its
glory _ the cavernous interiors are depicted in 1920s photographs _
its demise is ignored. Leased to a teachers' training college from
1946 to 1986, it was sold in 1989, a decade after the death of the
10th and last earl.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Bode of Christie's confirmed that most of the items in
the sale come from a collection in the south of England. Yorkshire
residents identified the primary beneficiary as the eighth earl's
only child, Lady Juliet de Chair, 64, who lives in Essex.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is expected to bring between $13 million and $16
million, money that Lord Hindlip, chairman of Christie's
International, said would ``protect the future of the family and
the remainder of the collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyperbole aside, there are, after all, no Fitzwilliams left, and
much of what is being sold is either redundant or of little
historical importance. At least 16 of the 106 lots have no apparent
Wentworth connection. The catalogue reports, for example, that lot
47, a George III mahogany pedestal desk ($17,000-$24,000), was
purchased at Christie's in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Juliet and her family have been a steady source of
Wentworthiana since 1948, when Christie's handled a sale of
furnishings after the death of her father. The earl _ called ``King
dandy and scum'' by Evelyn Waugh _ was 37 and estranged from his
wife, a Guinness beer heiress, when he was killed in a plane crash
with his 28-year-old mistress, Kathleen, Marchioness of Hartington,
the favorite sister of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   A recent castoff was the heroic 1762 George Stubbs portrait of
the champion stallion Whistlejacket, which had a state room created
for its display. Depicting the Arabian steed as a mass of
mane-tossing, barebacked muscle, the painting was acquired last
December by the National Gallery for a reported $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Built around 1630 by the first Earl of Strafford, and
extensively Palladianized by his heirs in the 1700s, Wentworth is a
freak of domestic architecture, a tribute to statistics over style.
As one visitor laconically wrote of the swaggering 606-foot-long,
365-room structure, ``The house has always rather overwhelmed the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Its fabulous contents were assembled in the 18th century by the
Marquess of Rockingham and his son, Charles, a British prime
minister whose cheering for the American Revolution cost him his
job.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the son's best additions to Wentworth are the sale's
least well documented: 19 pieces of furniture attributed to an
obscure pair of 18th-century Yorkshire cabinetmakers, Richard
Wright and Edward Elwick. Executed in toothsome exotic woods like
amaranth, padauk, sabicu and fustic, the works shed light on a
design team about whom much remains to be written.
</P>
<P>
   Barely known outside a small circle of connoisseurs and
scholars, Wright and Elwick were followers of Chippendale and, as
Christie's experts discovered to their surprise, helped furnish
Wentworth in the 1750s and 1760s. Though relying on their idol's
popular portfolio of designs, the pair often interpreted
Chippendale's fashionable sketches into sinewy, slightly menacing
furniture that seem perfectly suited to Wentworth's hypermasculine
majesty.
</P>
<P>
   The pagoda-swoop shoulders of nine dashing yew-wood dining
chairs recall the epaulets of the evil flying monkeys in ``The
Wizard of Oz'' ($65,000-$97,000).
</P>
<P>
   Their Wentworth masterpiece, however, is a secretary-on-cabinet
made for Lady Rockingham, the prime minister's wife
($330,000-$490,000). A circa-1765 chinoiserie sensation crowned by
a spiky pagoda hung and faced with five different patterns of
fretwork, it is success, power and fashion in one trendy
multicultural package: rococo drawer pulls, neo-classical urns and
Gothic arches framing the letter slots.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of Wright and Elwick's creations, the nine-foot-tall
secretary is the real thing: a provincial masterpiece whose honesty
of construction is a gentle rebuke to the occasionally obfuscating
sale it graces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-SQUEEZE-2ND &LR;      07-01 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-SQUEEZE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... teachers lag.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its original 1996 report, the teaching commission _ a group
of education professors, teachers, business people and politicians
formed by the Rockefeller Foundation and Columbia University _found
that one-quarter of all high school teachers have not taken a
course in the subjects they teach since they were in high school
themselves. For math teachers, the figure rises to 30 percent. Half
the nation's high school students are taught science by someone
other than a science teacher or scientist, with the proportions
highest in poorer urban schools.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1987 and 1991, the percentage of teachers entering the
classroom with either a college minor or major in the subject they
teach, dropped from 74 to 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, not all teachers are bad. Even Frank Haydu III, who
Monday said he will resign as the state's interim commissioner of
education amid fallout from his decision to demand that teachers
pass the state test, warned against ``teacher bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the number of truly incompetent teachers is only
five percent _ the figure given by Stanford University professor
Edwin Bridges in his book ``The Incompetant Teacher'' _ multiply
that by at least 20 students in a classroom, and it's nearly three
million students across the country learning from unqualified
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   For the students, the effects may outlast the incompetent
teacher. According to an ongoing University of Tennessee study that
has tracked students in two large school districts over 15 years,
the results of both good and bad teaching can be seen in student
test scores as long as four years later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Causes for concern
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as the quality of teachers has gotten worse, it has become a
self-fulfilling prophecy: the profession is held in such low esteem
that no one wants to enter it.
</P>
<P>
   The number of college students going into teaching dropped
steadily from the 1960s, when thirty percent were likely to teach,
to the 1980s, when 10 percent were. The biggest change came in the
opening of more opportunities for women, who still make up 73
percent of the teaching force. The higher achieving women went into
more lucrative professsions, so teacher colleges, and hence schools
themselves, had no choice but to drop the standards for people they
hired as teachers.
</P>
<P>
   And who would go into teaching, then or now? Almost any
profession was more lucrative, and still is. Teaching offers none
of the comforts and amenities other professionals take for granted
_ such as telephones, voice mail, fax machines, computers, even air
conditioning. It offers high personal rewards, but can also mean
high stress. And the faddishness of education strategies and the
demands of parents who think they know best creates a push-me,
pull-you effect that any teacher, talented or otherwise, would find
wearying. Add to that the social pressures of schools in poorer
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a good teacher in an urban school, you have to give
12-13 hours a day, and those are intense hours,'' says Jesse
Solomon, a 30-year-old MIT graduate who taught in the Boston Public
Schools before moving to City on a Hill Charter School in the
city's Fenway section. ``I don't know anyone who isn't exhausted by
Friday. If schools were places people felt they could carve out
long-term, fulfilling careers, I think you'd attract better
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But even for those who seek the rewards of working with young
people, teacher education remains an obstacle to better teaching.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide survey of teacher education schools last year might
have presaged the dismal results on the recent Massachusetts tests.
In it, professors by overwhelming margins said the most essential
thing teachers needed to impart to students was to be ``active
learners.'' But few thought it essential to teach the skills most
people would consider essential for the well-educated mind. Only 19
percent felt correct spelling and punctuation was important. Only
33 percent said students should know the names and locations of the
50 states. And just 55 percent said they would require proficiency
in spelling, grammar, and punctuation before receiving a high
school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The survey captured the key problem: teacher education programs
have too often shortchanged content for pedagogy, stressing the how
over the what. In fact, only 500 of the nation's 1200 teacher
education programs are accredited.
</P>
<P>
   The commission on teaching found that teacher education is too
disconnected from actual classroom practice. Yet in most states,
teacher colleges have remained the only game in town for people who
want to teach. Some states, including Massachusetts, have changed
their requirements to demand a liberal arts degree instead of a
teaching degree. Yet superintendents say teacher candidates are
still being hired if they earned education degrees in other states.
And every teacher has to earn a masters within five years of
beginning to teach. In most cases, they take a masters of
education, emphasizing what tends to be worst about teacher
training.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grab bag of solutions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With education now emerging as the hottest political issue
across the country, it seems everyone has a strategy for improving
teachers _ the most basic element of any reform.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposes forgiving student loans for talented
students who agree to teach in urban or rural districts, and
shrinking class sizes. Cellucci proposes shrinking class sizes and
testing teachers. Massachusetts Senator John Kerry, perhaps testing
the waters for his own presidential campaign, suggests luring
people from other fields into teaching, without putting them
through the onerous hurdles of teacher education.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is probably D: all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Those who've studied the problems of the nation's teaching force
say alternative programs can be one successful strategy: witness
the popularity of Teach for America, a kind of Peace Corps for
teachers that attracts college graduates into schools in some of
the country's most dangerous neighborhoods. But they fault these
kinds of programs _ now offered in some form in 41 states _ for
providing too little mentoring for teachers, resulting in high
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   And, specialists say, salaries must be raised. Salaries tend to
rise dramatically over a long teaching career. Now, with older
teachers retiring, policy makers say the time is ripe to raise the
salaries at the lower levels as incentive to get in, even if it
means a less dramatic rise in pay over the course of a career.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing alone will work without also raising the esteem of
the profession _ an elusive goal, but one would-be reformers say
ultimately comes from elevating the demands of teacher education.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers call for raising standards at teacher colleges.
States, they say, need to hone alternative programs to tap the
energy of outside candidates, while making sure they get the
mentoring they need. And states need to create other ways for
teachers to become certified. One option is the National Board for
Professional Teaching Standards, a Detroit-based group that puts
teachers through an elaborate year-long series of tests of
everything from their knowledge of the areas they teach to how they
plan lessons and interact with students.
</P>
<P>
   All this, specialists say, will force traditional teacher
education schools to prove they are the most effective method of
training. And it will make the profession something to strive for,
rather than fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this is easy,'' Murnane cautions. ``But given how high
the stakes are, it seems a wise investment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUTCH-ART-2TAKES-$ADV     07-01 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTCH-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC ACCUMULATIONS IN MINIATURE SPACES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 16th- and 17th-century Dutch were probably not
the first Westerners to be more interested in this world than the
next, but they pursued that interest with unusual energy, openness
and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Their assured, enterprising curiosity is reflected in their
advances in cartography, navigation, exploration, lens-cutting,
medicine and science, and a bustling sea trade that sustained
Amsterdam as a center of international commerce as well as
learning.
</P>
<P>
   It is also evident in their art, which built upon the
observation and accuracy first formulated by Van Eyck and then
Durer. With an alacrity suggesting that love of the world engenders
love of self, Dutch artists pursued subjects among their immediate
surroundings, painting Dutch men and women, their everyday lives
and the Dutch landscape.
</P>
<P>
   They gave genre painting its first definition and painted so
many depictions of objects that the term ``stilleven'' _ still life
_ was coined.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most vivid reflection of this worldliness _ this
inclusive embrace of knowledge, experience and beauty _ was the
kunstkamer, or art cabinet, the often encyclopedic arrays of art,
artifacts and natural specimens assembled by prosperous Dutch or
Flemish burghers.
</P>
<P>
   So argues ``A Collector's Cabinet,'' a pocket-size show at the
National Gallery of Art. A summer hit now extended to Nov. 1, it
qualifies as a blockbuster in a teapot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Collector's Cabinet,'' organized by Arthur K. Wheelock Jr.,
the museum's curator of northern Baroque painting, loosely
re-creates an eclectic, 17th-century kunstkamer. In all, 180
artworks have been shoehorned into three galleries with a combined
area of less than 800 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The show features walls double- and triple-hung with smallish to
tiny oil paintings, mostly Dutch, Flemish and Italian. Handsome
built-in vitrines brim with table-top sculptures, decorative
objects, Roman coins, jewelry, Chinese lacquers, prints,
illustrated books, exotic shells, botanical and zoological
drawings, musical instruments, the occasional map, an elephant's
tooth and scientific instruments like microscopes, telescopes,
globes and a protractor. The kunstkamer was multicultural and
multimedia before the fact.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The installation gives claustrophobia a good name, or at least
distracts effectively from its anxieties. The slightest shift of
the eyes causes images and objects to group and regroup according
to subject, style, form or material and creates a shifting flow of
thoughts and perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The fascination with nature's exotica takes different forms. In
one vitrine, sea coral, highly prized, appears in its natural
state, as an impressive bright-red trident. A nearly identical
sprig commands the center of a beautiful, kunstkamer-like still
life (by Jacques Linard, a French artist) of shells. A third bit of
coral serves as the stem of a finely wrought silver spoon.
</P>
<P>
   In other instances, rare natural forms inspired ostentatious
artifice. With the addition of a gilded silver head, wings and
feet, an ostrich egg becomes a sculpture of the bird itself (also
an ewer). Similarly, a large nautilus becomes a snail when
supplemented with a graceful head, rippling foot and tiny fairy
astride its back. Above these hang images of unaugmented natural
wonders: prints of a rhinoceros and a pig with six legs, both by
Durer.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the juxtapositions of paintings make the most
interesting points, dramatizing the range of realist styles and
subjects. After regarding the quiet precision of Pieter Jansz
Saenredam's pale interior of a vaulting church nave, from around
1632, the eye is drawn across the way to the serenity and radiance
of Jan Olis's ``Interior With Young Men Playing Tric-Trac,'' a
tavern scene in whites and creams from around 1632.
</P>
<P>
   On the intervening wall, Adriaen Brouwer's ``Youth Making a
Face'' (1632-35) gives a grittier picture of tavern life, as does a
tiny gray scene (around 1635) that includes a man relieving
himself, this one by David Teniers the Younger, who was influenced
by Brouwer.
</P>
<P>
   Amid these different realist styles, and flanked in one instance
by two small turbulent Rembrandts, Johannes Vermeer's ``Woman
Holding a Balance'' and ``Girl With a Red Hat'' communicate a
startling modernity _ an economy of form, purity of color and odd
flatness that border on the abstract.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeer seems almost as removed from the painting of his time as
that painting was from the art of the Italian Renaissance, with its
idealized treatments of biblical and classical subjects. When
Roelandt Savery paints his 1624 image of the Holy Family resting on
the Flight Into Egypt, they appear deep in the background of a
scene filled with farmers and cattle.
</P>
<P>
   It seems appropriate that the galleries holding this show aren't
much bigger than a small one-bedroom apartment. For despite its
vivid glimpse of a distant time, place and mind-set, it is not
alien.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch or Flemish kunstkamer may be ground zero for a number
of familiar phenomena: the private art collection, for one. Neither
members of royalty nor the clergy, the Dutch in particular were the
first bourgeois art collectors in the West, habitually displaying
art in less than palatial homes and thereby encouraging the
production of small objects and paintings.
</P>
<P>
   In their ostentation, some of these objects contain hints of
bric-a-brac to come and might even qualify as pre-industrial
kitsch, despite the uniqueness, consummate craft and high
production values.
</P>
<P>
   But the kunstkamer's density also resonates with the
chock-a-block displays found throughout the art world these days.
In a time as modest as ours can sometimes be, young artists often
sneak up on large scale by massing together lots of little things _
small paintings, drawings, photographs, found objects.
</P>
<P>
   Other echoes can be found in some recent high-density museum
exhibitions organized by noncurators looking to take liberties with
the whole exhibition concept. One thinks of the cheek-by-jowl
display of portraits that the painter Chuck Close organized, with
Kirk Varnedoe, in a small gallery at the Museum of Modern Art in
1991; of the sculptor Arman's dense installation of works from his
collection of African art at the Museum of African Art in SoHo last
fall, and of ``A/Drift,'' a wild mix of contemporary art and
artifacts (record albums, rock posters, T-shirts and music videos)
organized in 1996 by the critic Joshua Decter at the Center for
Curatorial Studies at Bard College in Annandale-on-Hudson, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   And at the moment, there's ``Bathroom'' at the Thomas Healy
Gallery in Chelsea, one of many thematic compendiums presented by
New York art galleries every season.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery's exhibition returns to the moment when the
experience of art was, in effect, privatized by successful
commoners with uncommon amounts of disposable income. Their
nonhierarchical collections _ the kunstkamer theory of relativity?
_ made these ensembles machines for seeing, like the lenses and
microscopes they sometimes included, and exemplars of a
multicultural connoisseurship whose relevance endures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
