<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-01 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIETY'S WORST CAN STILL HIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a trailer beside an auto body shop, a father raped his own
children and the little girl next door for years. He went to prison
for forcing those boys and girls to have intercourse with each
other and to watch while he raped each of them in turn. He did his
time and is no longer on parole or probation.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Sex Offender Registry Board classified him
among the most dangerous of sexual predators, but because he
appealed, the board is barred by law from notifying the North Shore
community where he is living.
</P>
<P>
   On a roadway at dusk on a June night nine years ago, a large man
in his mid-30s with a long criminal record for rape picked up a
hitchhiker. He drove her to a deserted parking lot where he raped
her and beat her with a tire iron. He did his time and is no longer
on parole or probation.
</P>
<P>
   The Sex Offender Registry Board classified him among the most
dangerous of sexual predators, but because the rapist moved when he
received his classification notice and the law prohibits the
dissemination of his name statewide, the board cannot locate, let
alone notify, the community where he is living.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoons after swimming lessons, an 8-year-old boy
and his sister would go to their father's house to spend the
weekend. Their father raped them both on the dining room floor
weekend after weekend until the boy finally told his mother. The
father did his time and is no longer on probation or parole.
</P>
<P>
   The Sex Offender Registry Board has not yet classified this
rapist. He is one of an estimated 15,000 individuals with one or
more criminal convictions in Massachusetts that would require
registration as a sex offender. To date, the five-member,
part-time, volunteer board has classified only about 1,300 of them.
</P>
<P>
   These cases are only a small sample of the unanticipated
consequences of the legal challenges and legislative inertia
plaguing this state's much-touted sex offender registry law, a
statute designed to alert a crime-weary public to a rapist or child
molester in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court declaring
sections of the law dealing with low-risk offenders
unconstitutional has allowed the most high-risk offenders to live
undetected, even by the police, in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   A failure of the Massachusetts Legislature to allocate the
necessary resources to the Sex Offender Registry Board has meant
that the evidentiary hearings are not being held that would satisfy
the high court that the due process rights of sex offenders were
being protected.
</P>
<P>
   Cited by Acting Governor Paul Cellucci as a major achievement of
his administration, the registry law is all but unenforceable.
Those legislators most eager to take credit for its passage are
reluctant to correct its flaws.
</P>
<P>
   The law mandates that anyone convicted of one of 11 sex crimes
since 1981 register with their local police department. The state
is required to categorize each offender according to his likelihood
to commit a similar crime again.
</P>
<P>
   That job falls to the unpaid Sex Offender Registry Board, a
panel that consists of two psychologists, a victims' advocate, a
probation officer, and a lawyer designated by the state's public
safety secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The board meets for a few hours once a week, poring over the
case files of some of the most despicable crimes committed in
Massachusetts. Their Friday morning reviews move at a snail's pace
because the stakes are so high and their resources so low.
Classification as a high-risk offender means that an individual's
photograph will be distributed to his local police department and
his name made available to neighbors who inquire. It is not a task
to be taken lightly.
</P>
<P>
   A little boy is molested in the bathroom of a fast food
restaurant; a little girl is assaulted in the bedroom of her own
home; and this state's politicians bemoan the system's inability to
protect the public from the worst among us.
</P>
<P>
   But while they posture, corrective legislation languishes on
Beacon Hill that would make the Sex Offender Registry Board a
full-time, paid panel with the staff and funds to tackle the
backlog of cases and conduct the necessary hearings.
</P>
<P>
   If that measure, now stuck in the House Ways and Means
Committee, does not move to the floor for a vote before the end of
the session this month, it will be January before lawmakers can
address the problems with the sex offender registry. That's six
more months of the public not knowing the whereabouts of the man
who raped his children in the trailer or the man who raped and beat
the hitchhiker in the parking lot or the man who raped his son and
daughter on the dining room floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
