<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5780 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     07-01 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING ALL THE RIGHT MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theater often has less to do with passion, art or even
accomplishment than it does with real estate commitments that, in
turn, help to decide which plays and shows we see and which are
allowed to drift into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the good fortune of Michael Mayer's production of
``Side Man,'' Warren Leight's alternately flip and melancholy,
sometimes brutal memoir about the last years of the Big Band era.
</P>
<P>
   Having received favorable notices and enthusiastic audiences
earlier this year at the Classic Stage Company's Off Broadway
theater, ``Side Man'' has now transferred to the Roundabout
Theater's Stage Right on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the move isn't just another example of how quality
inevitably rises to the top. Chance and the availablity of real
estate have also had a lot to do with it. They're as much a part of
the culture of our theater, non-profit as well as commercial, as
the artists who commit their lives to the theater on spec, that is,
with blind faith and no guarantee of rewards. These are neither
Good Things nor Bad Things, but the way theater is.
</P>
<P>
   At Stage Right, ``Side Man'' is in the larger of the
Roundabout's two spaces, the one most recently occupied by a turgid
revival of Terence Rattigan's 1952 romantic drama, ``The Deep Blue
Sea.'' The long-scheduled opening of the Rattigan play in late
March prompted the transfer of the Roundabout's hit revival of
Arthur Miller's ``View From the Bridge'' to the Neil Simon Theater.
</P>
<P>
   It was only when ``The Deep Blue Sea'' closed that the space
became available for ``Side Man.'' You see how chance operates.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a happy one. It brings a new American play to the
Roundabout, which has built up its large, loyal subscription
audience by concentrating on revivals. Some of these have been
stunning achievements like ``A View From the Bridge'' (also
directed by Michael Mayer) and the Sam Mendes production of
``Cabaret,'' which is at the Gilbert Miller Theater, temporarily
renamed the Kit Kat Klub. Many of their revivals, however, have
been very mixed bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man'' is not only a new play but also something of an
original. It's a recollection of a time now recalled chiefly
through the names of Benny Goodman, Artie Shaw and the other
leaders of the big swing bands, which, before the coming of Elvis
Presley, the Beatles and rock-and-roll, embraced great jazz
musicians and set the musical tastes for the country from the
mid-1930s into the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Leight is not a name-dropper, nor does he deal in the kind of
nostalgia that depends on the easy sentiment evoked by the music
itself. He's not interested in the stars of that era. He's
concerned with the side men, those crazily obsessed, sometimes
gifted musicians who floated from one band to the next earning
peanuts, heedless of their haphazard, messy existences, aware only
of the music by which they connected to one another and to life.
</P>
<P>
   Such a man is Gene (Frank Wood), the quietly remarkable trumpet
player, terrible husband and thoughtless father remembered by his
son Clifford (Robert Sella), the narrator of ``Side Man.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing much wrong with Gene except that he should never
have married and become a father. Certainly he should never have
married a woman as ill-equipped as the emotionally unstable Terry
(Wendy Makkena) to deal with a man who lives only through his
music.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that she probably would never have married him
except that the first time she sat in on one of his gigs, she heard
the genius of Dizzy Gillespie in his horn. She becomes his most
dangerous fan. He probably never would have married her except that
it seemed the the thing to do and, once done, he never gave it
another thought.
</P>
<P>
   Gene drinks and smokes dope but, unlike so many of his pals, he
never becomes a junkie and he doesn't play around. He's simply
remote, disconnected from life as the rest of us know it.
</P>
<P>
   As the years go by, Gene scarcely ages a day. Terry, working as
a waitress, slips into alcoholism and teeters on madness. When she
screams, throws food and threatens suicide, he goes out to move the
car and stays away, sometimes for days or maybe just until he's
sure she's drunk herself to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford is less their child than their keeper, furious with and
saddened by his mother, mesmerized by his glimpses of his father's
secret life.
</P>
<P>
   He beautifully catches the private spirit of his father in a
monologue:
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's up there, blowing, he's totally in touch with
everything that's going on around him. Ziggy bends a note, he
echoes it instantly. A car horn sounds outside, he puts it in his
solo, or harmonizes under it, a second later. I used to wonder how
he could sense everything while he was blowing, and almost nothing
when he wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   At another, earlier point in the play, Clifford remembers when
he permanently evicted his father from their Upper West Side
apartment. After an especially brutal fight between his parents,
Clifford announces that his father has to move out. Gene is
bewildered but he accepts the ruling. Later Clifford reports: ``hat
night, at midnight, I drove him over to Ziggy's. It was like moving
a cat. I don't think he had any idea of what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man'' is an engrossing play without being entirely
satisfatory. One character is missing from this family: Terry as
wife and mother. I'm not sure whether this is a reflection of the
role as written or as played by Ms. Makkena.
</P>
<P>
   When first met, she's a flutist from South Boston, though
nothing more is made of her own interest in music. As the play
progresses, she seems to become increasingly simple-minded in a way
that has nothing to do with alcohol or abandonment. Much of the
time her tirades are just gibberish. She should break your heart.
Instead you wish she would vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Leight has created a fascinating character in Gene, who's
revealed as much by how other people react to him as by what he
does or says. There's something benignly ghostlike about him. Wood
plays him with just the right proportion of dimness to
recognizable, maddening eccentricity.
</P>
<P>
   Sella is good in the schizoid role of narrator-son, meaning that
he must stand outside the events, often jokily commenting on them,
even as he's participating in them as one of the victims. Not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Gene's musician colleagues are sharply, comically defined in the
performances of Joseph Lyle Taylor, Michael Mastro and Kevin Greer.
Anjelica Torn, as a good-hearted club waitress, effectively stands
in for all the women the men meet away from home as the palmy days
of the big bands dwindle down to isolated club dates, private
parties and the occasional job with Lester Lanin.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of ``Side Man,'' that's a fate worse than death,
but it's also a living. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playing next door to ``Side Man,'' at the Roundabout's smaller
Laura Pels Theater, is Nicholas Martin's revival of George Bernard
Shaw's ``You Never Can Tell.'' The good news: a performance by
Robert Sean Leonard so disciplined, technically assured and
commandingly funny that the impulse is to say that a star is _ if
not exactly born _ then at long last recognized.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, without fuss or hype, Leonard has been learning
his craft in films (``Dead Poet's Society,'' ``Much Ado About
Nothing'') and on the stage (``Philadelphia, Here I Come,''
``Arcadia'').
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears to be pay-off time. As Valentine, whose Shavian
mind amd dashingly romantic soul inhabit the body of a failed
dentist, he has a role that he can run with, which he does with an
almost Olivier-like pleasure, transforming a rather perfuntory Shaw
revival into a farcical delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Never Can Tell'' is not in a league with such great,
characteristically Shavian comedies as ``Pygmalion'' and ``Major
Barbara.'' Its conventions are of the 19th century. Shaw began
writing it in December, 1895, the year of Oscar Wilde's triumph
(the production of ``The Importance of Being Earnest'') and
humiliation (his trials and imprisonment).
</P>
<P>
   Shaw finished it in 1896 and, though he might not have admitted
it, ``You Never Can Tell'' has a lot of Wildean wit in it. Note the
apology of a mannerly waiter to his betters for having raised his
son to become a Queen's Counsel: ``Never mind my being the
gentleman's father, ma'am: it is only the accident of birth after
all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You Never Can Tell'' has a marvelously absurd plot involving
one impossibly enlightened New Woman, whose treatises on
20th-century cooking, creeds, clothing, conduct, children and
parents are the rage in Madeira; her three children, the rich old
husband she abandoned 18 years earlier, and Valentine, the dentist.
The place and time: a Devon seaside resort on a blissful summer's
day.
</P>
<P>
   As often happens at the Roundabout, the casting is uneven,
though Leonard brings the ensemble together. He doesn't stand apart
from the others; instead his energy and enthusiasm have a way of
carrying everyone along with hin.
</P>
<P>
   Two other very good performances to note: Charles Keating, who
plays the august waiter whose only indiscretion is his successful
son, and Jere Shea as that son, who freely acknowledges his father,
without ever forgetting that the man is, after all, a waiter. Alan
Moyer's sets are charming.
</P>
<P>
   Imperfect, perhaps, but still potentially revivifying on a
blistering summer's day or night. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Fire,'' the Acting Company production housed in the
Newman Theater at the Joseph Papp Public Theater, is an engaging
stunt: a program of one-act plays by seven of our major
playwrights, each commissioned to take as inspiration one of
Shakespeare's sonnets or, in the case of John Guare, two sonnets.
</P>
<P>
   The other contributors: Eric Bogosian, Ntozake Shange, Marsha
Norman, Tony Kushner, William Finn and Wendy Wasserstein. The
director is Mark Lamos.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most successful of the lot is Mr. Kushner's
contribution, titled ``Terminating, or Lass Meine Schmerzen Nicht
Verloren Sein, or Ambivalance,'' inspired by Sonnet No. 75. That
title is part of the joke, which is about Esther, an analyst, and
Hendrik, her patient, both gay and both besieged during their
session by the demands of their respective lovers, who won't stop
playing mind games during this crucial 50-minute hour.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Hendrik, hilariously played by Stephen De-Rosa, is so
desperate at being terminated by Esther that he becomes convinced
he wants to sleep with her. Sleep? says Esther. Is that what he
means? It isn't, of course, but words have always been coming
between Hendrik and the rest of the world. They're how he protects
himself from the terror of life and love.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wasserstein's ``Waiting for Philip Glass,'' inspired by No.
94, plays like the first super-bitchy scene in a full-length comedy
about the East Hampton summer colony (which, reportedly, is what it
may turn out to be). Sample line, spoken by an especially chic mom:
``Kids are great. Kip's in Maine and Taylor's at this terrific
summer camp in Cambodia ...'' Ms. Shange's ``Hydraulics Phat Like
Mean'' (No. 128) is an erotic dance piece with dialogue, scored by
Chico Freeman, choreographed by Dyane Harvey and played by Lisa
Tharps and Jason Alan Carvel.
</P>
<P>
   The most elaborate piece is Guare's ``General of Hot Desire''
(Nos. 153 and 154), about the problems of pinning down
Shakespeare's meanings to concoct the play we're seeing.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright apparently worked with the actors in putting the
piece together, and though it goes on too long, as improvisations
sometimes do, it's a beautifully boisterous, unruly way to end a
program that celebrates one of the most severely disciplined of all
literary forms.
</P>
<P>
   A note of reassurance: each of the sonnets is spoken twice in
the course of each play and, if you're brain tires and you lose the
thread before arriving at the final couplet, they're also published
in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Fire'' is a serious fun festival all by itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
