<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO VOTES CLEAN AND GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE -- The election was special, but in today's
mechanized politics, the battle plan is routine. Consultants exhume
a peccadillo about a rival candidate, which they then convert into
a televised, 30-second scare story that out-Herods Herod. They
collect their fees and move on.
</P>
<P>
   This plan, pursued by both Democrats and Republicans, backfired
in the June 23 election to replace Steve Schiff, a much-admired
Republican who died in March. Voters in New Mexico's 1st
Congressional District were appalled, and a hefty number of them _
15 percent _ voted for the Green Party candidate, Bob Anderson, who
spent $3,000 on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Democrats in California rejected a wealthy self-financed
candidate, voters here cast aside Democrat Phil Maloof, who spent
$1.5 million of his family fortune. He lost, with 39 percent, to
Republican Heather Wilson, who won 45 percent, but the buzz
afterward was about the third-party total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have guessed before the election that the Green would
have got about 3 percent,'' says Fred McCaffrey of Santa Fe, whose
decades-deep knowledge of state politics leads him to conclude that
the Green candidate drew from both parties: ``It was a backlash
against negative campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   A duel of dirt engulfed Maloof's mother and Wilson's husband in
charges that were as bizarrely irrelevant as they were nasty.
Before the 1970s, when ``reformers'' changed campaign laws, a major
party might shun or discipline rogue candidates whose excesses
could damage the party's reputation. Today, party leaders embrace
and bankroll them.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader,
stumped for Wilson. On the Sunday before the voting, an all-star
Democratic rally boosted Maloof, led by Hillary Clinton, House
minority leader Dick Gephardt, and Representatives Patrick Kennedy
of Rhode Island and Loretta Sanchez of California.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats need 11 more seats to regain control of the House, but
the party's record in special elections is dismal; the last time a
Democrat took over a Republican seat was in 1991, when John Olver
succeeded Silvio Conte in Massachusetts. Since Albuquerque is the
most Democratic of Sun Belt cities and Bill Clinton twice won the
district easily, big bucks and a Beltway attitude dominated the air
waves of a city accustomed to a gentler political pace.
</P>
<P>
   Maloof, the 31-year-old scion of one of the state's wealthiest
families, had ducked earlier debates, and the first televised
encounter explained why. Voters found Wilson's demeanor and resume
more impressive. A native of New Hampshire and a mother of three,
Wilson, 37, was a state official and is a graduate of the Air Force
Academy. She is now the first female veteran ever to serve in
Congress and the first woman to represent New Mexico in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Television and print media covered the race closely, resulting
in a respectable special-election turnout _ 40 percent of
registered voters. The Albuquerque Tribune said that Maloof's
Seattle-based consultant, Tom Hujar, declined to comment
afterwards. The Democratic county chairman said the consultant
``was calling all the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the third loss for a Hujar candidate in the state.
Fewer than 1 percent of the state's voters belong to the Green
Party, but Green Party candidates helped defeat his candidate for
governor in 1994 and a special-election congressional candidate in
the Santa Fe district in 1997. Is there a trend here?
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune, which had endorsed Maloof, editorialized: ``The
bloodiest, most appalling election campaign in recent New Mexico
history is over. Hallelujah.'' Imported, one-size-fits-all cynicism
harangued the Land of Enchantment into a Land of Disgust until
voters rebelled.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's no national trend and maybe other jurisdictions still
have a Pavlovian appetite for mud pies, but Democrats and
Republicans discovered that the only mud that sells in New Mexico
is adobe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
