<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BUFFALO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUFFALO 66' SHOWS GALLO'S HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BUFFALO 66 
Directed by: Vincent Gallo 
Screenplay by: Alison Bagnall, Gallo 
Starring: Gallo, Christina Ricci, Anjelica Huston, Ben Gazzara,
Kevin Corrigan, Mickey Rourke, Rosanna Arquette, Jan-Michael
Vincent 
Running time: 112 minutes 
Rated: Unrated 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although its limitations are inescapably apparent, ``Buffalo
66'' is nevertheless an impressive showcase for Vincent Gallo, who
evidently was concerned that his flavorful lowlife roles in
``Palookaville'' and ``The Funeral'' didn't give him the chance to
show enough sensitivity and soul. Here he plays a grungy little
nonentity named Billy Brown, who slides back into his native
Buffalo after being released from prison. Looking like an
ambulatory hangnail, filled with rage, and possessed of the social
skills of a fungus, he takes a bus into town, kidnaps a ballet
student and proceeds to peel away layer after layer of curdled
exterior to reveal hitherto unrevealed depths of sweetness and
insecurity.
</P>
<P>
   The story hinges on the character of the kidnap victim
convincing us she's not against the chance to break out of her
usual routine. Christina Ricci, looking appropriately bored and
ready for a change, steals the film with her inscrutability while
Gallo digs in and chews on the overwritten and oversentimentalized
role he gave himself, seeming insufficiently aware that he and the
film would have looked better if he had made his victim do more
talking while saying a lot less himself. This might have drawn us
into the mysteries of his character. But Billy, no grabber to begin
with, turns pretty banal pretty fast.
</P>
<P>
   He takes the dancer home with him at gunpoint, although it's
quite plain she's curious enough to go willingly. Gallo reveals a
flair for black humor in his depiction of Billy's parents, whose
response to him runs a narrow gamut from anger to virtual denial of
his existence. As the reasons for his insecurities and troubles
become over-apparent, it's wryly amusing to watch him turn
invisible in the eyes of his fanatical Buffalo Bills football fan
mother (played by a virtually unrecognizable Anjelica Huston), who
still resents the fact that she was pulled away from a playoff game
to give birth to him. Meanwhile, his gruff father, played by Ben
Gazzara, ignores Billy to grope the young woman he's told is his
daughter in law.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo chews on Billy's pain in his airless childhood home, in a
bowling alley where he takes Ricci to revisit his past, and in a
diner where he runs into a slatternly girl (played by Rosanna
Arquette) who was the unrequited love of his life and who barely
remembers him. The question is what, if anything, Billy is going to
do once he threatens to shoot the retired Bills kicker whose missed
field goal led to the lost bet that sent Billy to jail. The trouble
is that our interest in Billy has long since been exhausted and our
interest in Ricci's improbably pliant and complaisant character is
left unsupplied.
</P>
<P>
   He should have allowed Ricci's Layla to talk more. She's a
cipher, who exists solely as a projection of Billy's longing for
uncritical adoration and the infinite patience and attention he
never got as a child. But even though she seems little more than a
male fantasy, with no back story, nobody in her life to wonder what
happened to her, Ricci makes Layla compelling, a tough, overripe
kewpie doll with a complex play of feelings in her eyes that the
screenplay never gets near. Gallo is a talented and energetic new
face, with an ability to estheticize bleakness. But, succumbing to
overindulgence, he shortchanges his film of the most interesting
thing in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
