r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PESTICIDE-CONTAMINATI     07-01 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PESTICIDE-CONTAMINATION-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PESTICIDE COMPANY TO REMOVE ARSENIC AT THREE SITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pesticide company accused of contaminating four northeast
Texas sites with massive amounts of arsenic has settled with the
state, ending a series of disputes that spanned almost four
decades, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Bonham, Texas-based Voluntary Purchasing Groups
are not acknowledging responsibility for the contamination, but
they have agreed to pay $2.5 million to the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission, agency spokesman Patrick Shaughnessy said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, VPG has agreed to spend up to $800,000 to develop
11.2 acres of freshwater wetlands and another 4.5 acres of
shoreline habitat, Shaughnessy said.
</P>
<P>
   VPG officials also agreed to enter the commission's Voluntary
Cleanup Program, in which the company will be required to remove
arsenic at two Bonham sites and one in nearby Ridgeway, Shaughnessy
said. Cleanup in neighboring Commerce, the fourth site, was
completed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   VPG, which blends and distributes pesticides and fertilizers
under the product brand names Hi-Yield and Ferti-Lome, has been
accused of arsenic contamination virtually since it began
operations in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Large doses of arsenic are fatal, and repeated exposure to low
levels of the heavy metal can cause lung, skin, liver, bladder and
kidney cancers, the state Health Department has reported.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of cleaning up the Bonham and Ridgeway sites has not
been determined, Shaughnessy said, but state officials at one time
estimated that it would be about $23 million.
</P>
<P>
   Once commission officials have approved VPG's cleanup of the
sites, documents will be filed with the company's property deeds
stating that future owners will not be held liable by the state for
any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will settle all claims we have against the company,''
Shaughnessy said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which a judge approved Monday after bankruptcy
court negotiations between the company and the Texas attorney
general's office, ``is significant and unusual,'' Shaughnessy said.
The large financial settlement is not a record, but it is uncommon,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   VPG President Bill Turnage was out of town Wednesday and could
not be reached to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bonham Mayor Bryan Peeler said he was unaware of the settlement,
and never really knew much about the contamination. He said he did
not follow the litigation closely, in part because the company's
current facility is outside Bonham's city limits.
</P>
<P>
   The other Bonham site to be cleaned is near downtown, within the
city limits. Before moving to its current facility outside town,
VPG operated a small plant there. State officials found arsenic
contamination at the site and filed a complaint, which was later
withdrawn because the state was unable to link the contamination to
VPG, which no longer owned the property. However, the company has
agreed to clean up the site.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler said he is pleased that the downtown site will be cleaned
up because it will make the property more marketable.
</P>
<P>
   The town's mayor since last year, Peeler said most Bonham
residents don't know that sites on the company's properties are
contaminated. ``Most folks, if you took a general poll, would be
totally unaware of the lawsuit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   VPG, based in Commerce until 1971, was one of several companies
named by state officials as potentially responsible for arsenic
contamination in the Commerce neighborhood that surrounds the
now-abandoned plant site.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Protection Agency officials finished the cleanup
in Commerce in 1995, including removing contaminated soil from
residents' yards and replacing it with untainted soil. VPG
allocated millions of dollars for the cleanup. Large portions of
the neighborhood around the site were fenced off, with warning
signs posted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, officials with the Texas Agriculture Department and the
conservation commission began investigating allegations that the
company improperly dumped chemical waste on the Bonham site, which
they opened shortly after closing the Commerce plant.
</P>
<P>
   Bonham resident Mary Lankford, whose property adjoined the
plant, had complained that cattle were dropping dead on land
between her house and the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lord, they were lying in the waterways, down the fence
line,'' Lankford said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The investigation came to a halt in 1993 when VPG officials
declined to allow state officials onto the plant site.
</P>
<P>
   The case lingered until 1995, when company officials settled a
portion of the case, paying $30,000. The rest of the case was
transferred back to the conservation commission.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, VPG filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in
U.S. District Court in Plano.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy proceedings delayed lawsuits filed by about 1,500
residents who claimed that contamination in Commerce and Bonham
caused deaths, created emotional distress and lowered property
values.
</P>
<P>
   VPG attorneys have said they filed for bankruptcy protection to
end the barrage of lawsuits being filed against them in Tarrant,
Hunt and Dallas counties.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the company's reorganization plan, VPG officials set
aside about $10 million to settle lawsuits filed against them,
primarily by Bonham and Commerce residents, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A committee that includes several attorneys has been formed to
help decide who gets money and how much they will receive.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
