<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5793 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-ARMAGEDDON-BOS &LR;      07-01 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ARMAGEDDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF THE WORLD, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
ARMAGEDDON 
Directed by: Michael Bay 
Screenplay by: Jonathan Hensleigh 
Starring: Bruce Willis, Billy Bob Thornton, Liv Tyler, Ben Affleck,
Will Patton, Peter Stormare, Keith David, Steve Buscemi 
Running time: 150 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sci-fi disaster action, sensuality and brief
language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' is big and noisy and stupid and shameless and
it's going to be huge at the box office. Never mind what you hear
about the movie's low-tech oil riggers sent into space to blow up a
Texas-sized asteroid before it creams our planet. ``Armageddon''
isn't really about an asteroid attack. It's about a testosterone
attack. Guys whose idea of a good movie consists of watching things
get blown up to an amped-up soundtrack are going to be happy with
this one, even if it seems no more than an attitude-heavy recycling
of ``Deep Impact.'' Just to make sure the frenzy concept stays
upfront, director Michael Bay shakes the camera a lot as the heroes
blast off and favors a rapid-fire cutting style that raises the
question of whether the world is going to be saved by America or by
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Blast is the operative word here, as it usually is in films
produced by Jerry Bruckheimer, the high-energy advocate behind this
one. ``Armageddon'' is a manufactured object that parodies itself
in the image of a big heavy thing about to be dropped on us from a
great height. You probably won't be furrowing your brow wondering
if the heroes do the job. We're still here, right? Still, one sign
of a truly advanced civilization is that in a given summer you can
have a choice of killer comet movies. We now have two, and compared
with ``Armageddon,'' ``Deep Impact'' is the one that seems as
multilayered as ``Ulysses.'' Lest your week be ruined by the idea
of the planet getting off clean, enough pieces of the asteroid make
their way to Earth to let the film have it both ways and dish out
some spectacular destruction, especially to major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, you're tempted to cheer for the asteroid, the only
counterinfluence being Bruckheimer's shrewdness in casting a
screenful of fresh faces and independent-movie mainstays. They take
the sting out of the blatant manipulation and utter predictability
of this film that has to be called escapist, if only because of the
frequency with which you find yourself wanting to escape it. Since
Hollywood is hooked on thinking ever bigger, it won't come as a
surprise that ``Armageddon'' throws a bigger space menace at us
than ``Deep Impact'' does, although in cruder fashion. Think of it
as ``The Dirty Fourteen'' in space suits.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, when you want to save the world, who ya gonna
call? Bruce Willis, of course. As the roughneck oil driller, he
almost charms his way past the trashy material by his ability to
convey the idea that there's always a part of him hanging back, not
taking too seriously anything we see him do. The film also shrewdly
makes him the father of the love interest, not the male end of it.
The boy-girl stuff is left to Liv Tyler and Ben Affleck, whose
youth and intensity make it seem almost alive.
</P>
<P>
   Casting Affleck and Tyler was a smart way to ensure that this
hard-hitting crunchorama will also become a date movie. The urgency
and emotions on the faces of both proclaim that while this may be
each one's first big mass-market broad-brush studio project, it
won't be their last. In fact, if you can ignore the basic dumbness
of the story line and superficiality of the characters, there's a
lot to enjoy, thanks almost entirely to the venturesome casting.
Billy Bob Thornton, for instance, arrives at more than a few
resourceful colorations of the role of the guy fretting back at
mission control, and Steve Buscemi's loose-cannon nervousness
enables him to exchange cliche for entertainment value, too, as a
bosom-fixated genius.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Stormare, the brutal silent killer alongside Buscemi in
``Fargo,'' energizes his role as a Mir-based cosmonaut who's part
of the planet-saving team, finding ways to put fresh spin on the
mad Russian caricature he's been handed. Owen Wilson, of ``Bottle
Rocket'' fame, is another source of freshness, and Will Patton
shades his astronaut's role with rueful facial expressions. Give
them credit; when this umpteenth visit to the planet of the big
bangs is watchable, they're almost always the reason. The
fabricated brand of can-do spirit battling the asteroid is dwarfed
by the can-do spirit the actors muster to get through the movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
