<SLUG> BC-BACKGROUND-MUSIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOUND INVESTMENT IN ID TAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time a song from one of his music production company's
compact discs is played, Andrew P. Mark hears the sound of money
clinking.
</P>
<P>
   Mark is president of BRG Music Works, a division of Jacor
Communications Inc., which produces background music for 2,000
radio stations nationwide. He has digitally watermarked his songs
with MusiCode, indelibly imprinting a unique identification number
into the soundwaves. When picked up by a decoder, the ID number can
document that Mark's song was played on the radio, entitling his
company to a royalty payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a great payday for us,'' says Mark about MusiCode,
which was created by Aris Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Aris is betting on Mark and other music-industry executives to
turn MusiCode into the worldwide watermarking standard. One of a
dozen or so companies that constitute the infant digital
watermarking industry, Aris depends on MusiCode's market
penetration for success.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the start-up firm, founded in 1995 and privately owned
and financed, has not turned a profit. President and cofounder
Gregory L. Wertheimer esti-mates Aris might pass the break-even
point in about a year. But company officials are already signing up
customers and planning spinoff products modeled on MusiCode.
</P>
<P>
   Digital watermarking is an attempt to solve one of the
fundamental problems of intellectual property: Who owns what?
Unlike books or other printed materials, audio recordings do not
ordinarily include the name of the composer, performer, or
recording company. The music industry needed a way to stamp the
owner's name directly onto the music.
</P>
<P>
   To solve this problem, watermarks like MusiCode imprint a
digital signal within audio recordings, including songs,
advertising jingles, and background music for such features as
radio traffic reports. Once the code is embedded, a decoder can
pick up the signal.
</P>
<P>
   Because the watermark enters the music during the recording
process, it can appear only on new recordings, including rereleases
of old songs. But David E. Leibowitz, vice chairman at Aris,
estimates the majority of songs played on the radio turn over about
once every three years. ``It's a forward-looking technology,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Aris envisions several applications for MusiCode, a patented
technology for which the company recently received a Discover Award
1998, in the sound category, from Discover magazine. &UR;  &LR; The original
idea was to encode music so that drivers could see a song's title
and artist on a display screen in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what got me intrigued,'' remembers Wertheimer, who
heard about the idea at a dinner party at his house. ``Then we went
to the (recording) industry, and they said, `That's nice, and we
like that feature, but there are other applications.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most eagerly awaited uses of MusiCode involves
fighting electronic music piracy. The process could embed a
transaction code within the watermark that identifies not only the
artist and record company, but also the name of the person who
purchased the song and the company that sold it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this use becomes widespread, when people know that music
has this information on it, they're going to think twice about
putting it on (computer) bulletin boards or making unauthorized
copies, because it's traced back to them,'' says Leibowitz.
</P>
<P>
   But chief among the uses for watermarking is royalty-payment
enforcement. Every time a song is played publicly, whether on a
jukebox, in a nightclub, or on radio or TV, the copyright owner is
entitled to a royalty payment. Currently, three federally licensed
royalty-collection societies operate in the United States, tracking
the number of times music is played and making sure performers,
composers, and recording companies get their payments.
</P>
<P>
   Without an electronic solution, the royalty societies employ
workers to write down the names of songs broadcast over the radio
and on TV. In the future, a more efficient method, says Aris chief
technology officer Joseph Winograd, would be MusiCode-watermarked
music and a decoder ``in a closet someplace'' within broadcast
reach of every radio station in the country. Aris recently signed a
joint marketing agreement with Lucent Technologies Inc. to market a
watermarking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a continuous 24-hour basis, it monitors the broadcast
audio,'' Winograd says. ``When it sees or hears the watermark, it
records it and sends it to us over a telephone or Internet
connection, and we send (the customer) a log either daily or
weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for MusiCode came from Jack Wolosewicz, Aris's
cofounder and an engineer who sits on the board of directors but no
longer works for the company. He pitched the idea to Wertheimer, an
entrepreneur and financier, who brought together a number of
private investors. Winograd, 30, joined Aris from Boston
University's electrical engineering department, where he had been
researching digital signals.
</P>
<P>
   Aris is building a customer base slowly; BRG Music Works is the
only music production company to have signed on thus far. But
Nashville-based SESAC, the smallest of the royalty agencies, has
signed an agreement and will launch its MusiCode decoders Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   SESAC chose Aris not only because it thought MusiCode was the
best watermarking technology, but also because Aris has connections
to the Recording Industry Association of America, which will play
an important role in deciding which of the competing watermark
firms becomes the de facto standard. The company making the chosen
watermark stands to gain by supplying encoding software and
decoding machines to record companies, consumer electronics
manufacturers, and royalty societies.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Leibowitz comes in. When Aris hired him as vice
chairman, they selected a lawyer whose last job, as executive vice
president and general counsel to Washington-based RIAA, put him at
the heart of the watermark-standard debate.
</P>
<P>
   Leibowitz's contacts impressed SESAC president and chief
operating officer Bill Velez. The RIAA is ``going to be an
important body in terms of which company wins and becomes the
standard,'' Velez says.
</P>
<P>
   The task of defining the new watermarking standard rests with
the Muse Project, a committee of the International Federation of
Phonographic Industries, a European trade group. This October, the
Muse judges are expected to release their report, which,
watermarking companies hope, will name one watermark as technically
superior to its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But with the choice of standards still undecided, few watermark
companies in this highly contentious industry have licensed their
technology or lined up customers for their decoders. And the size
of the market itself is undefined.
</P>
<P>
   Because digital watermarking technology is so new, Aris
officials don't know how large the market for MusiCode might be.
``You really can't define it,'' says Wertheimer. ``We're developing
the market.''
</P>
<P>
   He notes that 4.2 billion CDs are sold annually worldwide but
declines to say how much Aris could make if every new song were
watermarked with MusiCode. Competitors similarly say they can't put
an exact figure on the market for watermarks, especially since each
firm has different plans for its technology.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall L. Snyder, executive vice president of Arbitron New
Media, a division of Ceridian Corp. (a Minneapolis company that
makes the competing watermark CBET), says his firm's business model
anticipates a market of $30 million to $50 million per year. But
unlike Aris, Arbitron, an audience-information services company,
plans to use its watermarks to provide music companies with
information on where and how often their songs are being played for
market research purposes. Additional applications could also
increase CBET's potential market beyond what MusiCode could expect.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainty over the future of watermarking, Aris
and its competitors are optimistic about the industry's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``In five years, hopefully we'll have computers and consumer
electronics and everything in place'' for fully-integrated digital
watermarking, says David W. Stebbings, senior vice president for
technology at the RIAA. ``Hopefully the marketplace will provide
consumer enjoyment and information of this type.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  And supporters of Aris say they're confident MusiCode will
prevail in the watermark-standard contest. Doug A. Wood, president
of Port Washington, N.Y.-based Franklin Douglas Inc., a music
production company, has evaluated Musi-Code and is considering
adopting the watermark for his background-music CDs. When he tested
MusiCode by broadcasting music and then reading the watermark off
the airwaves, the identifying code came through clearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like shooting fish in a barrel,'' he says. ``There's a
very good chance we might be using it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
