<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO UPS MONEY OFFER FOR GOP CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANITA McDIVITT  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ San Antonio community leaders have quietly
increased their bid for the 2000 Republican National Convention to
$21.5 million after comparing their original proposal to those of
other cities and finding it lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The $3 million increase in proposed private funding was
confirmed Tuesday at a news conference to promote the convention as
a means of helping the GOP attract Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Rep. Tom Loeffler, co-chairman of the San Antonio
Convention 2000 Host Committee, said the decision to increase San
Antonio's bid came Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have upped the bid from the private sector to $15.235
million to cover all the forseeable costs,'' Loeffler said. By
comparison, New York bid $40 million for the event and Chicago's
package is estimated at $25.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new figure was discussed during a private two-hour
presentation by San Antonio city and business leaders to the site
selection committee, Loeffler said.
</P>
<P>
   GOP officials and members of the site selection committee have
stressed during their three-day visit to the Alamo City that a city
can't buy the convention. Nonetheless, funding is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't the money per se,'' said Jim Nicholson, chairman of
the Republican National Committee. ``The money is relevant only to
the degree that it's (enough) to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler said San Antonio's bid was not increased ``in a sense
of scrambling to outbid someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As we reflected upon our bid here in San Antonio, quite
frankly, there was a question of the cost of the stage, which is a
huge cost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman with The Freeman Cos., which contracted with the RNC
to build the stages for the past four conventions, said the total
cost for the San Diego convention in 1996 was $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler said, in comparison with the bids put up by competing
cities for the 2000 convention, ``we felt we had probably
underbid'' the stage construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Eight cities _ San Antonio, Philadelphia, Charlotte, N.C., New
York, New Orleans, Chicago, Indianapolis and Minneapolis _ are
fiercely competing for the Republican mega-event.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is an incalculable amount of national media coverage
for the host city, and an estimated $100 million to $200 million
economic impact from spending by 35,000 conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Loeffler said the extra money for the bid will come from private
donations, not from taxpayer dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the City Council passed a ``not-to-exceed''
ordinance that limited the city's contribution to $6.3 million,
most of which will come in the form of city services such as
transportation and security for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the GOP site selection committee wrapped up their
visit to San Antonio Tuesday after two days of wining and dining
and a pep rally in the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic officials at Tuesday's news conference said having
the convention in San Antonio would allow the party to showcase a
``different face of America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The party's message of less government, fewer regulations,
educational opportunity and entrepreneurial values makes us a
natural ally to the Hispanic community,'' said Tony Garza of
Brownsville, Texas, a former Texas secretary of state who is
running for state railroad commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, local Republicans believe San Antonio is making a good
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very good about our prospects,'' said U.S. Rep. Henry
Bonilla, R-San Antonio. ``It's still early in the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
