<HEADLINE>
CALLING INTO QUESTION AT&AMP;T'S ACQUISITION OF TCI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, chairman of AT&AMP;T Corp., says his company's
acquisition of cable giant Tele-Communications Inc. will give
consumers a single source for a panoply of services _ from long
distance to ``broadband services'' like video and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will combine the best name in the (long-distance)
industry with the best broadband company in the industry,'' he said
last week in announcing the $32 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   The logic seems compelling: With TCI and affiliated cable
systems, the New York-based telecommunications company would have a
direct link into about one-third of the nation's homes. Those
customers could generate billions in new revenue from local phone
service, Internet access, and movies-on-demand. Moreover, AT&AMP;T
could avoid some of the billions in fees it pays local carriers for
using their networks to start and finish long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics see it differently.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, they note, AT&AMP;T spent heavily to break
into the $110 billion local phone market, which it was forced to
abandon in 1984 with the court-ordered dismantling of the Bell
System. Four billion dollars later, its effort to bridge the ``last
mile'' _ the gap between AT&AMP;T's long-distance network and homes and
small businesses _ has failed to pay off. The TCI takeover, critics
say, is a pricey and risky ``Plan B.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the obstacles:
</P>
<P>
   TCI's network is not ready for the digital age. Although half of
its cable systems use modern fiber-optic technology, only 30
percent of the lines can handle two-way transmission _ vital to
telephone and Internet access. Upgrading the rest will be
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T will still lack ``last-mile'' coverage to two-thirds of US
households.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how strong demand will be for broadband services
or how much consumers will be willing to pay. For starters, TCI
cable subscribers will need set-top boxes costing $400 to $500 to
get phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Melding the two companies will be difficult, and AT&AMP;T's track
record with big acquisitions is mixed. Its buyout of McCaw Cellular
has been a success, but it stumbled badly _ and lost billions _
when it bought computer maker NCR Corp. (NCR was later spun off to
shareholders.) Meanwhile, AT&AMP;T must digest Teleport Communications
Group Inc., a provider of local and long-distance services to big
businesses that AT&AMP;T agreed to acquire in January for $11.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Early reaction to the TCI deal among investors has been
negative. AT&AMP;T's stock has fallen 12.7 percent since it was
announced, closing Friday at 56 3/4. To be sure, the decline partly
reflects short-term fears about the hit AT&AMP;T will take on its
earnings. But analysts say it also demonstrates skepticism about
whether AT&AMP;T can win its bet on cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T has three things to do, starting with spending about $9
billion to upgrade TCI's cable facilities to be able to deliver the
new services,'' said Howard Anderson, managing director of the
Yankee Group, a Boston market research firm. ``Second, it has to
build a single network for local and long distance, voice and data,
consumer and businesses. ... And finally, protect its base of big
corporate customers through Teleport.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a tall order _ especially at a time when AT&AMP;T must
defend its long-distance turf from rivals like MCI Communications
Corp., Sprint Corp., and the Baby Bells, if, as expected, they get
permission from regulators to enter the business.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has another challenge: improving the image of the
fragmented cable TV industry, which annually comes under state and
federal scrutiny for escalating rates. It also has a reputation for
sloppy service and support.
</P>
<P>
   TCI, for example, does not have the stellar customer
satisfaction ratings that other regional cable companies enjoy,
according to a recent Yankee Group study. Thus, if customers are
unhappy with the quality of their cable TV service, they are less
likely to add AT&AMP;T for telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask any customer of cable and telephone service which is more
reliable and the perception is always that the phone is far better
both in quality and reliability _ issues AT&AMP;T will have to deal
with now,'' said Jeffrey Kagan, a telecommunications analyst based
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   To reach a broader national audience, AT&AMP;T, with 90 million
long-distance customers, must expand geographically and persuade
other cable operators to join it in pursuit of providing customers
with end-to-end communications.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong acknowledges AT&AMP;T cannot buy the other major cable
carriers, some of which have longstanding alliances that could
prevent a takeover frenzy. Time Warner Inc., one of the largest
cable operators, has a partnership with U S West Inc., the
Denver-based regional Bell company.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and others maintain that AT&AMP;T's strategy to provide a
basket of communications services via cable is simply one approach
and that long-distance carriers such as Sprint and the regional
Bell companies will also provide similar services using different
technologies, including fiber optics or wireless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a Sony Betamax vs. VHS battle, where one will
prevail over the other,'' said Kagan. ``Everyone wants to get to
the same finish line and there are many paths that will take you
there.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if AT&AMP;T is successful, it could gain a higher portion
of spending by packaging, for example, cable television, local
telephone, and Internet access service for one set monthly price,
with cellular service thrown in for free. Such combinations on a
single bill could give AT&AMP;T a major boost over its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will connect personal computers, television sets, phones,
and a whole new generation of interactive devices,'' said John
Malone, chairman of TCI, which is based in Englewood, Colo. ``Would
you like to order Viagra while watching your favorite entertainment
show? Just point and click.''
</P>
<P>
   Importantly, the promise of AT&AMP;T competing aggressively for
local phone service has encouraged regulators frustrated by the
lack of competition since the passage of the Telecommunications Act
of 1996. The bill removed the regulatory barriers separating the
local, long-distance, and cable industries, with the aim of luring
players in each of those markets to expand into the others. In the
last two years, however, most of the action has involved
consolidation within those sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see if AT&AMP;T is committed to investing in advanced
facilities and competing head to head with local phone companies to
provide high-speed voice and data to the home,'' William Kennard,
chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, said last week.
``That's what makes this deal thinkable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
