<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      07-01 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING WITHOUT A RETAINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here today, gone tomorrow. It's happened so many times in Felipe
Alou's tenure as manager of the Expos, he barely feels the pain.
Alou still enjoys his trips to the ballpark. The yearly shuffle of
players and front office people out of town is simply the way of
life in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   You need to know this because the Montreal club that arrived at
Fenway Park last night was replete with names that you'll soon
forget but, a year or two later, will emerge as stars _ on another
team. That is the Expos' history.
</P>
<P>
   Where do you think Tim Raines, Andres Gal-arraga, Marquis
Grissom, Moises Alou, Tim Wallach, Delino DeShields, Wilfredo
Cordero, and Larry Walker came from? They were all Expos, and proud
of it, until they were traded or left as free agents because the
Expos weren't willing to pay out big contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Montreal had an outstanding farm system,
built by Dave Dombrowski, Dan Duquette, Kevin Malone, and Kevin
Kennedy. It supplied the big-league club with enough outstanding
talent to finish second in the National League East in 1992 and
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1994, the Expos astounded the baseball world with a
74-40 record and seemed on their way to the postseason. It never
happened, as a strike cut the season short.
</P>
<P>
   Now Montreal may never see the postseason, at least until the
team owners make the Expos something other than a farm club for the
rest of the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' says Alou, whose own son, Moises, in 1996
became another Montreal star-in-the-making to disappear. ``You
don't like to lose players, but we do all the time. I know this is
not the most glamorous condition for anybody. But I accepted this
job two years ago, when I signed a longterm contract. So why
complain? I love this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou has been in professional baseball for 24 years, the first
17 as a player. ``I belong to a family of baseball players,'' he
said. ``I played with my brothers, Jesus and Matty. I had Moises
for a few years. I've just had a 19-year-old son (Felipe Jr.)
drafted by the Royals. This team is like my family. We are old; we
are young. I see myself as somebody who is responsible for
something. I just don't know what the hell it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou understands that his job as manager is in the dugout and on
the field _ front office politics are beyond his control. The Expos
have the look of an expansion club _ after 30 years in the majors.
No one will ever confuse Montreal with this year's real expansion
clubs, Tampa Bay and Phoenix, whose owners have fat pocketbooks,
made that way by new stadiums with luxury boxes and seat licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos, on the other hand, keep seeing attendance shrink _
it's at just over 10,000 fans a game this season. Talk of a new
stadium and a new beginning fills the newspapers and the TV and
radio airwaves. But most Canadians are not reading or listening.
Alou is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got used to it in the minor leagues,'' said Alou, repeating
one of his favorite statements. ``You're given a new team every
year. Like a new class. In the big leagues, you hope you keep the
same team, but it doesn't happen that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my son left, it was something for which I was prepared.
Other people had left before him. I knew he was vulnerable. But I
knew he would go, too. Especially after Larry Walker was let go. It
was a big thing, a Canadian and being the quality player that he
was. Look at the money he's making. Remember, we're still a small
market.''
</P>
<P>
   With less money to spend on talent, the Expos must rely on other
resources. ``We have to do a lot of things here,'' said Alou. ``And
if we succeed, it's not because we're smart. It's because of hard
work.''
</P>
<P>
   And Alou doesn't miss only his star players. How good could the
Expos be if they had retained the coaches who also went on to
greener pastures?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see,'' he said. ``Joe Kerrigan is with the Red Sox, and
we know about him. Tim Johnson is managing Toronto and Jerry Manuel
the White Sox. Kevin Kennedy left here to manage Texas and then
Boston. We've had some fine people go through here. Sometimes I
think I'm the only one who's sticking with this thing. Of course,
Tommy Harper was here when I arrived. He's a very loyal person and
a hell of a baseball man. I'm glad he stayed with us, teaching the
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou expresses his loyalty by, season after season, getting the
most out of the playing talent he is given by the front office and
farm system. This season he has had to rebuild from a 78-84 club
that lost not only Cy Young Award winner Pedro Martinez but also
Joe Orsulak, David Segui, Henry Rodriguez, Darrin Fletcher, and
Mike Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's team is a very young team,'' said Alou. Evidence
of that: In last night's 7-4 loss to the Red Sox, the young Expos
made four errors. ``This is the most different team I've managed
since I took over. A lot of people still don't understand that we
lost five position players who were regulars on Opening Day. We
also lost Pedro Martinez, and you know how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Help may be on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a farm system,'' said Jim Beattie, the Expos'
general manager. ``We didn't make trades just to cut payrolls. We
got some good young talent in return, like a Carl Pavano. You'll
hear from him, as well as several other young players coming
along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
