<HEADLINE>
HER GOAL: REACH NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER AND SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The future looks bright for Melissa Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Feinstein, a Weston (Mass.) High graduate who will be
a sophomore at Stanford University, became the US Junior National
champion at the pole vault when she cleared 12 feet, 1 1/2 inches
at the national meet in Edwardsville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was unable to defend her title when she returned
last weekend, she actually vaulted 8 inches higher than last year
for a personal best of 12-9 1/2, good enough for second place and a
trip to France for the World Junior Nationals July 28-Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all. ``I was really close at 13-1 1/2,'' she said
in a telephone interview Monday night. ``I was over, but I didn't
lift my elbows enough to clear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boding well for the future, Feinstein cleared that personal-best
vault using a 14-foot pole instead of her usual 13-footer. ``The
bigger the pole, the more risk there is but also the higher you can
jump,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a great year for the 19-year-old, who won the
Pacific-10 title in only her freshman year even as women's pole
vaulting, a relatively new event, is becoming more competitive.
``When I was still jumping at 12-1 1/2, there were 12 girls still
attempting that height, which is amazing,'' said Feinstein of the
junior national field. Last year, only four vaulters were left in a
field of 14, less than half the size of this year's. Samantha
Shepard, a 14-year-old competing for Air Time Athletics of Natick,
Mass., finished fourth at Edwardsville with a jump of that height.
</P>
<P>
   Given the progress Feinstein has made in the past year, she will
likely be in the mix for a spot on the US national team next year
when women's pole vaulting makes its debut at the 1999 World Track
and Field Championships in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot to work on,'' said Feinstein, noting she also
has a lot to look forward to.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Triathlon update
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Gerri Shea listened attentively at the seminar
held by Sally Edwards, as the triathlon guru outlined a six-week
training schedule that she said would guarantee anyone success in
completing a race. Shea will find out Sunday at the Danskin
Triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited, but definitely a little nervous,'' said Shea, who
drove out to Wrentham last week to scout out the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been going well, and I've done back-to-back biking and
running, and swimming and biking, but I haven't put all three
together yet,'' Shea said, who convinced her roommate and a
co-worker to do the race with her.
</P>
<P>
   The plans haven't gone as well for Sue Stockard, who also was at
the seminar and had hopes of doing the race with her daughter from
Seattle. Unfortunately, Stockard's training has been disrupted due
to her ill father, and she has had to commute from Cambridge to
Maryland to be with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have continued to work out _ running, swimming, and
biking, but following a schedule that fit in with our immediate
circumstances rather than with Sally Edwards's training schedule,''
she said. ``It has been as good for my mental health as my physical
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Massachusetts woman on US team
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tennis player Elizabeth Freeman-Young, of Newton, Mass.,
recently got word that she'll join three other women in September
to represent the United States in the Young Cup in England in the
Women's 40 division ... The ABL plans to start its third season in
early November, several weeks later than its usual mid-October
kickoff, so its championships won't get lost in the shuffle during
the NCAA Women's Final Four. Meanwhile, the New England Blizzard
has signed its top draft choice, Barbara Farris, to a three-year
contract. Farris is a 6-foot-3-inch center/forward out of Tulane
... Ireland's Sonia O'Sullivan shattered Lynn Jennings' 13-year-old
world record for two miles when she ran it in 9 minutes, 19.56
seconds Sunday at a meet in Cork. Amy Rudolph, a Providence College
graduate and 1996 Olympic teammate of Jennings at 5,000 meters,
also broke the old mark in finishing second in 9:21:35, which now
stands as the new American record in the rarely-run distance.
Rudolph also holds the US record in the 5,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
