<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      07-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULDER'S POETRY FILES; AVENGING THURMAN; PRINCELY PASSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is blockbuster season, but still a couple of
entertainment magazines are checking in with the movies'
smarty-pants set. The July  &UR; Movieline &LR;  gets real with David
Duchovny, letting the ``X-Files'' actor exercise his dry wit, spout
some of his Princeton-then-Yale theories, admit to a few personal
failings, and print one of his own poems for all the world to see.
The quips include a wonderful comparison between fame and
Catholicism, ``because you can't do anything without getting
caught,'' and the confessions include his desire to be Mick Jagger
and the obvious fact that David Duchovny thinks an awful lot _
``which is not necessarily an advantage for an actor. Intelligence
and thinking are not what we want from our actors.'' (Maybe that's
why he's turned to his dog for acting tips: ``Just total focus.
Total concentration. Maybe one ear goes back to figure something
out.'')
</P>
<P>
   The poem, however, is surprisingly sophomoric, and not as
inventive as you might expect based on his brainy chitchat. Called
``Cliche Juice,'' it's a pulpy blend of Hallmark sentiments: ``Up
into the wild blue yonder,/ wingless, prayerful that this miracle
of flight/ will not end, just yet. ... Wherever our home may be/
will be/ wherever we happen/ to be.'' Ten minutes with Duchovny is
worlds better than listening to more of Mel Gibson's timeless
wisdom about ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' but, alas, the great Fox Mulder
is no William Shakespeare. &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The July  &UR; GQ &LR;  brings us Ralph Fiennes, another coolly
intelligent actor who once earned a Vanity Fair cover story damning
him for his arrogance. The gentle Brit is not smug anymore, if he
ever was, but he seems to inspire plenty of literary referencing.
Before the piece is over, we've discussed Pushkin's ``Eugene
Onegin,'' Lord Byron, Emily Bronte's Heathcliff, Cormac McCarthy,
Martin Amis, William Faulkner, T.S. Eliot, Ted Hughes, and, of
course, Shakespeare. Fiennes, who ``looks like the kind of man who
might often hear the line `Did anybody ever tell you you look like
Ralph Fiennes?','' is most passionate when talking about ``King
Lear,'' and during his photo shoot, he becomes overwhelmed with
inspiration and recites a bit of Blake for the photographer.
Fiennes, by the way, has bucked the young-actress-older-actor
relationship trend by having a love affair with a woman 17 years
his elder who played Gertrude to his Hamlet, Francesca Annis. &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The July  &UR; Premiere &LR;  takes on Fiennes' costar in ``The
Avengers,'' a forthcoming movie that like ``The X-Files'' thrives
by keeping its main characters in a state of low-key sexual
tension. Uma Thurman, pregnant and married to Ethan Hawke,
apparently expends a lot of energy hiding her fierce intelligence
and her inability to suffer fools. Just don't call her ``The Albert
Einstein of actresses'': ``That's totally insulting!'' she says.
``It's a put-down of all women, certainly all actresses. They say
that about everyone: `And she's smart.' It means underneath it all,
she's not really.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Duchovny shares his forgettable poetry in Movieline, Ethan
Coen gives us a fine short story in  &UR; The New Yorker &LR; . Coen is the
younger half of the Coen Brothers, the filmmaking team that has
given us ``Fargo,'' ``The Big Lebowski,'' and ``Raising Arizona.''
But there is no black humor in ``The Boys,'' which is from Coen's
first collection of stories, ``Gates of Eden,'' due this fall. It's
a fairly depressing snippet of family life, as a father hardly
tolerates a camping trip with his two young sons, who might as well
be aliens. It features a variation of Jack Nicholson's famous diner
scene in ``Five Easy Pieces,'' as the father tries to order an
omelette for his son from a difficult waitress _ but the scene is
tinged with oppression and disappointment, and not rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last September, after Princess Diana was hunted down by a pack
of wild photographers, the world was stricken with remorse and the
paparazzi appeared to realize the dangers of its bloodthirst. But
10 months is forever among the flashbulb set, and already there is
a growing hunger for details regarding the young man who may be
more of a teen fantasy than Leonardo DiCaprio. Prince William is on
the cover of this week's  &UR; People &LR; , a 16-year-old boy who shares his
mother's fair-haired grace and her uneasiness regarding the press.
The story delivers just about every detail you might want to know
about the prince, including small passions like computer games,
fast food, techno music, and water polo, largely thanks to that
wonderful army of knowledgable royals experts. ``William's shoes
are always so shiny, his trousers well-pressed,'' notes one Eton
bookshop owner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
