 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-SQUEEZE (Undated) -- With the baby boomlet bulging
enrollments and teachers hired for the baby boom poised to retire,
the nation will find itself replacing 2 million of its 2.7 million
teachers over the next eight years. By Kate Zernike. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-TESTING (Undated) -- How Japan and some other countries
are dealing with the teaching question more effectively than the
United States. By Kate Zernike. 450 words.
</P>
<P>
   GREEK-ORTHODOX (Undated) -- What started as criticism by some
American Greek Orthodox members of their archbishop's autocratic
leadership style has become a full-fledged attempt to get him to
resign. By Diego Ribadeneira. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-PRISONER-BRACELET (Boston) -- Electronic monitoring of
offenders via radio ankle bracelets is well known but is little
used in Massachusetts, where it is supported by law enforcement
officials and prisoner advocates. By Zachary Dowdy. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (Albuquerque)-- New Mexico votes clean and Green.
By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- More and more parents are under
increasing pressure to try and raise ``perfect'' children, giving
them every advantage, so that they can grow into sucessful, happy
adults. By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   MCNAMARA-COLUMN (Undated) -- The Massachusetts Sex Offender
Registry Board is limited by lack of staff and funds and the
Legislature isn't helping the matter. By Eileen McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Globe columnist David Nyhan is on vacation.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) --) If Supreme Court Justice David Souter
defends Karen Finley and Robert Mapplethorpe, that's a small price
to pay for real freedom. By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-ARMAGEDDON (Undated) -- ``Armageddon'' is just another
cataclysm flick, although the cosmic cast is a bright spot. By Jay
Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BUFFALO (Undated) -- Although its limitations are
inescapably apparent, ``Buffalo 66'' is nevertheless an impressive
showcase for Vincent Gallo. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-IWENT (Undated) -- ``I Went Down'' is an offbeat Irish
gangster movie with engaging performances, an avoidance of formula
and, above all, its characters' way of making us take everything
personally. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Mulder's poetry files; avenging
Thurman; princely passions. By Matthew Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PIONEER-COGAN (Boston) -- John F. Cogan Jr., 71, chairman of The
Pioneer Group, started his company investing in emerging markets
long before they became fashionable. By Lynnley Browning. 1700
words.
</P>
<P>
   ATT-TELCOM (Undated) -- AT&AMP;T's expenditure of $32 billion for
Tele-Comminications Inc. is an expensive consolation prize in its
quest to offer local telephone, Internet and other enhanced
services. By Ronald Rosenberg. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   BACKGROUND-MUSIC (Undated) -- Every time Andrew P. Mark plays
one of his CDs, he hears money clinking. His company, BRG Music
Works, produces background music for 2,000 radio stations. By Chana
Schoenberger, 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBN-COMMENT (Undated) _ Here today, gone tomorrow. It's happened
so many times in Felipe Alou's tenure as manager of the Expos, he
barely feels the pain. By Larry Whiteside.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN (Undated) _ The All Star Game will be
played at Fenway Park next summer, on Tuesday, July 13. It will be
the toughest ticket in the history of Fenway. By Dan Shaughnessy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOMEN'S SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WOM-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ The future looks bright for Melissa
Feinstein, who became the US Junior National champion at the pole
vault when she cleared 12 feet, 1 1/2 inches. By Susan Bickelhaupt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
