</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, July 2,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, July
2, 1998. This budget will be updated at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON _ SHANGHAI _ As President Clinton nears the end of
his historic nine-day China trip, he continues to stress the need
for environmental awareness and reform in the giant nation.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To be filed by 1 p.m. EDT Wednesday. Will likely be updated
around 11 p.m. EDT Wednesday with quotes from latest Clinton
appearances and dateline will shift to Guilin.)
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-HISTBOX _ China's tortured history of environment vs
development. (Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ON-DEMAND _ WASHINGTON _ The book business is turning to a
new page: on-demand printing. This emerging technology could
resurrect thousands of titles that have gone out of print and
exponentially expand the choices for book buyers. (Dart, Cox News
Service 600&AMP;add).
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ DALLAS _ Coverage of Newt Gingrich's appearance with
Gov. George W. Bush at Dallas LULAC convention, a kickoff for the
GOP's effort to recruit more minorities. (Sherman, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-MAIN _ The latest developments in the outbreak of E-coli
at the White Water park in metro Atlanta and the spread of the
ailment to other states: number of cases, lab tests on other
avenues of the investigation. It's possible the health department
will announce a new cluster of cases in the Athens, Ga., area.
(McKenna/Anderson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-WATER _ Checking other White Water or public health
records to see if there were other days of low-chlorine levels at
the park that might suggest a pattern. Also asking officials what
levels of violation must register to trigger harsher action and
whether state, county or other agencies have jurisdiction to take
action if a pattern of mismanagement emerges and what would cause
the state to declare a public emergency. (Schneider/Payne/Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   KIDMAIN _ The news on the investigation of the heat-related
death in metro Atlanta of a child who was left in a day care van:
Have the cops interviewed the driver? Do they have a better idea
what happened? Is the DA filing charges? Is the day care center
still closed? What do parents say? What is the church doing to help
the family? (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
