<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, July 1, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed or will file these
stories for Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;  (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HONG-KONG (Shanghai, China) _ already filed _ When he
visits Hong Kong Thursday, President Clinton will convey what his
aides hope will be a calming message about Asia's economic turmoil.
The chief executive caps his nine-day tour of China with a 29-hour
visit to the former British colony that reverted to Chinese control
a year ago. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA-MARITAL (Paris) _ already filed _ French husbands are
abandoning the once-accepted institution known here as the
``five-to-seven,'' referring to the early evening hours they spent
with their mistresses before returning home for dinner with their
families. A lack of time and money has gradually obliterated the
practice, and women no longer accept it. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FIREWORKS-SAFETY (Washington) _ The father of a 12-year-old
Chicago boy blinded in one eye by a faulty Roman candle last year
warns about the dangers of fireworks in a news conference held by
the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ In some ways, the Supreme Court,
whose process of reaching monumental decisions is secret and
mysterious, is the most intriguing wing of government. It is a
constant example of the influence a single individual can have in a
democracy since many of its rulings are decided by votes of 5 to 4.
By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
