<SLUG> BC-WHOOPING-COUGH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS SAY WHOOPING COUGH RESURGENT IN SAN FRANCISCO
AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It starts with a nagging cough and progresses to
hacking fits that seem endless and can be so severe that it's
impossible to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   In infants it can cause the characteristic ``whoop,'' a labored
gasp of breath after a coughing spasm. Whooping cough, a disease
that many people thought went the way of polio, smallpox and
measles, is hitting the San Francisco Bay area particularly hard
this season.
</P>
<P>
   This year it has killed two infants and prompted health
officials to alert schools and health workers to the higher than
normal number of cases. Groups of schoolchildren in Alameda and
Santa Clara counties were advised to take preventive antibiotics
after classmates came down with the illness before the end of the
school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an outbreak in the Bay area and it's going pretty
strong,'' said Cynthia O'Malley, an epidemiologist with the state
Department of Health. ``We always have (whooping cough) but now
we're getting cases and cases and cases. It's really spreading a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County has had about 25 cases of whooping cough, up from
10 cases last year. In Santa Clara County, there have been 80
cases, compared with 23 all last year. San Francisco has had eight
cases, double the number reported in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers probably represent the tip of the iceberg,'' said
Laura Levin, an epidemiologist with Santa Clara County's health
department. ``A lot of health care providers don't realize it's
around. Some of them don't realize that adults are susceptible to
it or that the vaccine wears off and kids who are vaccinated can
still get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whooping cough _ or pertussis _ can range from an annoyance
that's never diagnosed to weeks of painful coughing in adults and
older children. But it can be deadly to infants. Coughing spasms
may leave babies gasping for air. In some cases, lack of oxygen has
caused brain damage or death.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is endemic in the United States, with cyclical
upsurges, O'Malley said. It has not been eradicated because the
vaccine, given in four doses starting at about 2 months of age, is
not completely effective. It also wears off, leaving teen-agers and
adults vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The bacterium that causes whooping cough, Bordetella pertussis,
secretes a toxin that damages airway cells involved in the cough
reflex. Rejuvenating those cells can take weeks or months.
Antibiotics given early in the illness will kill the germ, but may
not stop the coughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to diagnose,'' said Mel Lippmann, disease control
investigator for San Francisco's Health Department. ``Most people
who go to a doctor won't find out it's pertussis. ... So it's
difficult to get the disease out of the community. You can't get
rid of it like you do with polio or smallpox.''
</P>
<P>
   School-age children are required to have pertussis vaccinations
_ usually given with diphtheria and tetanus inoculations _ before
they enroll. But many children get the disease before they're old
enough to be vaccinated, or before they're forced to be by school
regulations. And some parents fear the pertussis vaccination
because of the side effects of a vaccine widely used up to two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That form _ a ``cellular'' vaccine made from the whole cell of
the germ _ caused fever, swelling and other symptoms in many
infants. Some parents were so reluctant to have their babies
vaccinated that the United States experienced its first outbreak of
whooping cough in 40 years in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But two years ago, the Food and Drug Administration approved an
``acellular'' vaccine made from part of the bacterium's cell, which
causes 90 percent fewer side effects.
</P>
</TEXT>
