<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHRODER-TV-LADN     07-01 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHRODER-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHRODER'S ROOKIE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; You'd think after 20 years you'd know a guy.
</P>
<P>
   But just when images of an 8-year-old Ricky Schroder crying in
``The Champ'' and a trust-fund teen-ager in ``Silver Spoons'' are
burned deeply into your subconscious, he is ready to make a
comeback into series television all grown up.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any grown-up, mind you. Schroder will not play some
middle-of-the-road guy in a romantic comedy. He will play a
homicide detective.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any homicide detective, mind you. Schroder beat out
about 40 actors to land the role of Andy Sipowicz's (Dennis Franz)
third partner on ``NYPD Blue,'' the grittiest show the networks
have to offer; a show for which he will have to sign a nudity
clause, making his rear end public property.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, looking to prove himself as a dramatic
actor, Schroder sent his manager and agent out looking for a role
as a police officer, and they hooked him a whopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in shock,'' said Schroder by cellular phone on the
way back from a fishing exposition that netted eight brook and
rainbow trout ready for the barbecue. ``I feel so lucky. I know I'm
going to be under the microscope, but in every profession, it
doesn't matter what the career is _ banking, acting or whatever _
there are moments in life when your destiny is largely in your
control, and I feel like this is one of those moments for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroder, 28, is no stranger to life's big moments. He purchased
a giant ranch on the Colorado-Utah border eight years ago, got
married six years ago and has seen the birth of his three children
(Holden, 6, Luke, 4, and Cambrie, 1{).
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time over the past decade, Schroder has compiled an
impressive resume of movies of the week, miniseries and an
occasional feature film. He says that during the last 20 years, the
longest he went without an acting gig was 14 months. But he still
made sure to leave himself plenty of time to work the land and the
livestock on his 15,500-acre ranch in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his days building fences, riding horses, raising cattle
and putting culverts in streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to get my hands dirty,'' Schroder said. ``When I'm away
from the ranch for two months, I get soft. I lose all of my
callouses and forget what it's like to dig a hole with a shovel.''
</P>
<P>
   Until, as he said, quality material became harder to find,
television movies were the best compromise between life on the farm
and a career as an actor. The audition process was not too
rigorous, the paychecks kept him and his family in chaps, and he
only had to work in short, concentrated intervals of a couple of
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be in the feature-film game, you have to go out and hustle.
To be in a series, you have to go out and hustle,'' he said. ``TV
movies are like driving up to McDonald's and ordering a Quarter
Pounder with cheese. They just come.''
</P>
<P>
   But, then, a role worth hustling for fell on his plate.
</P>
<P>
   To win the ``NYPD Blue'' part, which was more like getting a
table at Cafe Bizou on a Saturday night, Schroder had to audition
three times, reading lines opposite the Emmy Award-winning Franz.
Each time, he changed the perception that executive producer Steven
Bochco had of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not really kept up with Rick's most recent work, so I
suppose to some degree I carried the image of a much younger guy in
a half-hour sitcom,'' Bochco said. ``In my mind now, he's a man _
and he's a man of some substance and some complexity. He offers a
wonderful combination of youth and optimism with a certain degree
of experience and savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochco would not divulge much about Schroder's new character
other than to say that he will join the show in the sixth or
seventh episode of the season after Jimmy Smits' Bobby Simone exits
_ conveniently coinciding with November sweeps. Schroder will play
a 28-year-old detective. Terms of his contract were not made
available.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Bochco unpacked Schroder's professional baggage to see
what was inside, this is the actor's chance to silence the people
who are amazed that Schroder is replacing television's No. 1 hunk _
a cool, confident customer capable of exploding at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people tune in with a legitimate interest and curiosity
about what kind of character he will play and if he is up to the
task,'' Bochco said. ``And David (Milch, executive producer) and I
are absolutely convinced that he will dispel any doubts about his
ability in about five minutes, because we have a character for him
that is very interesting. You cannot replace Jimmy, and you
shouldn't try to.''
</P>
<P>
   Franz, whose first ``NYPD'' partner was David Caruso, is eager
to begin work with his new co-star.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rick will) be bringing a new character with qualities unlike
any others on the show,'' Franz said. ``I'm looking forward to the
many possible story-line opportunities this character will provide
for the show and existing characters' relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   And Schroder is eager to test his chops with Franz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could fit very well in a show like this,'' he said.
``I had very little doubt that I could handle it _ I just needed
somebody else to believe in me like I believe in myself so I can
start my new adult career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read with Dennis during my audition. What a powerful actor
and what a powerful human being he is. If you don't stand up to
him, you will get crushed. I am very ready to do good work.''
</P>
<P>
   If all three men are right, Schroder will have completed the
transition from child star to actor of substance that has eluded so
many others, from Danny Bonaduce to Erin Moran.
</P>
<P>
   Many kids in the spotlight succumb to pressure and are not able
to shift to life after their big break. But Schroder has kept
control of his career _ and his life.
</P>
<P>
   This steady role on one of television's top dramas will require
some time off from the ranch; Schroder plans on living in Los
Angeles during the week and returning home to Grand Junction on
weekends to keep up those callouses.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of appreciation for the sanctity of the outdoors,
his commitment to a strong family and his tenacious focus on what
he wants to achieve that Schroder credits for his longevity in the
fickle entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Like most others, he also made sacrifices. Schooled by a private
tutor on the set from third to 11th grades, Schroder missed out on
a lot of peer interaction. He eventually transferred to Calabasas
High School for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was uncomfortable,'' he said. ``It wasn't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   To fit in, Schroder joined the wrestling team. As the only
person to try out in the 143-pound weight class, he was handed a
spot on the varsity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' he said. ``I got in good shape and got to roll
around on a mat with big ... guys from Chatsworth. I won a couple
of matches, but mostly I got twisted like a pretzel. We'd go to a
wrestling tournament someplace like Reseda, and there would be
these inner-city kids going for scholarships that lived, ate and
breathed wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   He vividly remembers one tournament in which he was the lowest
seed and was pinned by the No. 1 seed within 28 seconds of the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom, dad and sister were there and everyone was cheering me
on,'' Schroder said. ``It was embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Win-loss record notwithstanding, Schroder will have to remember
some wrestling takedowns and holds to help him subdue the perps
corralled in New York's fictional 15th Precinct, 10 p.m. Tuesdays
on KABC (Channel 7). In this arena, it seems he's made all the
right moves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
