<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-01 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRODUCING THE NEW, SELF-DEPRECATING AL GORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a tireless believer in the value of America's two-party
political system, I must say it was encouraging to watch Texas
Democrats whoop it up at their convention in San Antonio the last
weekend of June.
</P>
<P>
   With no regard at all for polls that show Democratic candidates
in big trouble, party loyalists staged a terrific pep rally in the
Alamodome. They lit up the Alamo City as if they had something to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   It is not entirely clear what previously untapped source of
unbridled optimism might have fueled the delegates' enthusiasm. But
here's a guess: Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I'm talking about THAT Al Gore. The vice president of the
United States. The guy whose wooden demeanor has provided six
years' worth of punch lines for Jay Leno, David Letterman and just
about every other comedian who might be prone to taking an
occasional shot at an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   The jokes about what a stiff he is are so commonplace, by now,
that even Gore is telling them. In his speech to Texas Democrats on
the convention's opening day, Gore reprised a joke that Billy
Crystal used when he hosted the Academy Awards in 1997:
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows who's gonna go home with the Oscars. The only one
guaranteed of waking up with a statue is Tipper Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Tipper. She wakes up with a statue every day.
</P>
<P>
   But if Al has reinvented himself at home the way he has in
public, Tipper must feel like she's living with Robin Williams.
This new Al is a barrel of laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing as how he was addressing a dome full of Democrats, most
of Gore's jokes in San Antonio were aimed at Republicans. The best
ones, though, were those he aimed at himself.
</P>
<P>
   Which suggests that Gore's game plan for the 2000 presidential
campaign is to make fun of his own image, even as he tries to
redefine it. It's a good idea, because the American people have
always displayed a fondness for politicians and/or entertainers who
are willing to laugh at themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Self-deprecation is a tried-and-true vote-getter in this
country, probably because it suggests a level of humility that is
sadly lacking in too many candidates for public office. Most
politicians are inclined toward self-defeating defensiveness when
they become the target of ridicule or criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Are you listening, Dan Quayle?
</P>
<P>
   Gore's new approach unquestionably serves him well in the
partisan environment of high-energy political functions such as the
Texas convention. But it remains to be seen whether Gore can adapt
his new image to the mass audiences he will encounter in a
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate for vice president and second banana to Bill
Clinton in the 1992 and '96 elections, Gore didn't have to do much
except trumpet the party line and outshine the likes of Republican
counterparts Quayle and Jack Kemp. His personal appeal was barely
tested.
</P>
<P>
   Gore clearly understands that, which is why he has set out to
establish a new image that makes him seem more human, more dynamic
_ more the sort of person that voters can visualize as commander in
chief.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the new and improved Gore, however, is that
some of his attempts to project charisma seem forced and contrived.
The stiff jokes are funny, but they get old in a hurry. At times,
he seems to be trying so hard to make light of his image that he
ends up reinforcing the image rather than eradicating it.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the vice president's exuberant new speaking style _
has he been taking lessons from Jesse Jackson? _ and the whole deal
can start wearing a little thin.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is absolutely correct in assuming that the American people
prefer presidential candidates who bring enthusiasm and vitality to
the task of campaigning _ and, if they win, to the task of
governing.
</P>
<P>
   But voters also insist that would-be presidents be themselves.
We don't mind electing an actor, but we don't want him to be acting
when he's asking for our votes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore might want to give that some thought before totally
transforming himself into a character who may not ring true to the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
