<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-HN     07-01 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP NEW YORK OFFICIALS RETAIN LAWYERS AT TAXPAYER EXPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's top three elected officials _ the
governor, the attorney general and the comptroller _ have hired
defense lawyers in a series of employment-related cases, billing
taxpayers at least $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that despite having about 450 state lawyers at
their disposal:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, hired three Manhattan law
firms to represent him and top aides in two cases alleging wrongful
termination, at a total cost of $550,719.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attorney General Dennis Vacco, also a Republican, hired a
Manhattan firm to represent him in several employment matters,
costing taxpayers at least $507,985.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a Democrat, is using a Manhattan
law firm to represent him in two pending employment cases, which
have cost taxpayers $260,284.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 13 lawsuits are pending, meaning that the legal
bills to taxpayers are mounting. In addition, there are dozens of
cases for which outside attorneys have not yet submitted bills.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to all three officials said the use of outside counsel is
justified because of various conflicts, legal and political, that
disqualify the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   New York employs hundreds of lawyers, most of them in Vacco's
office, whose job, in part, is to represent the state and its
officials against lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   However, under Section 17 of the state's Public Officers Law,
officials can hire any lawyer they want in matters where
representation by the attorney general would be ``inappropriate,''
so long as the attorney general signs off on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco has signed off on scores of such cases, state records
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a disgrace,'' said former Attorney General G. Oliver
Koppell, a Democrat seeking his party's nomination to challenge
Vacco in November. ``Vacco doesn't have the confidence in his own
office. In essence, he is testifying to his own ineptitude in
appointing counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacco spokesman Chris McKenna accused Koppell of political
grandstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really sad that ... his campaign is so foundering and
desperate at this point that he will say just about anything to
draw attention to himself,'' McKenna said. ``It is a basic legal
principle that you have to avoid conflicts. Retention of outside
counsel by this office is no different than it was when Oliver
Koppell was attorney general for 11 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Koppell claims he used outside counsel far less frequently than
Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the comptroller's office has paid legal
bills in 13 employment cases, nine of them involving Vacco. In
addition, there are another 19 Vacco cases for which the state
apparently has not yet been billed by the lawyers representing the
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general, who ousted about one-third of his legal
staff after taking office in 1995, hired the politically connected
law firm of Snitow &AMP; Pauley to represent him in cases stemming from
those ousters. Approximately one-third of the bills for those
matters, totaling $507,985, have been submitted to the
comptroller's office.
</P>
<P>
   A single case accounts for more than half the total, $265,363,
records show.
</P>
<P>
   Snitow &AMP; Pauley also was involved in a recently concluded case
involving Pataki, billing at least $22,891 for that matter. Another
law firm, Hoguet Newman &AMP; Regal, the lead counsel in the case,
charged at least $159,838 for that case.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's attorneys for a pending whistle-blower suit _ the firm
of Hoguet Newman &AMP; Regal, an expert in employment litigation, and
Wilson Elser Moskowitz Edelman &AMP; Dicker, a law firm that is also
one of the major lobbyists at the state capital _ have billed at
least $367,990.
</P>
<P>
   McCall hired the law firm of Paul Weiss Rifkind Wharton &AMP;
Garrison to represent him in two pending wrongful termination
cases. The firm has billed at least $256,652 for one of the matters
and $3,631 for the other, at the rate of $260 per hour for lawyers
and $60 per hour for paralegals, according to McCall spokesman
Dennis Tompkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The claim is the comptroller acted politically (in firing
employees),'' Tompkins said. ``Inasmuch as the attorney general and
comptroller are of opposite parties, the attorney general, the
comptroller and the courts felt it was in the best interests of
everyone to allow outside counsel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
