<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCEPTIONAL WILL TO WIN DOMINATES GERMAN SOCCER PERSONALITY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Perhaps the classic image of Germany's extraordinary
soccer team comes from the 1982 World Cup semifinal against France.
With his team trailing 3-1 to France and minutes left to play, the
great striker Karl-Heinz Rummenigge came on as substitute and
immediately removed his shin guards.
</P>
<P>
   By disdainfully hurling away his protection, Rummenigge was
declaring that the real battle, unsoftened and unfettered, had
begun. France, with perhaps its greatest team ever, and one clearly
more skilled than the German, shuddered. Germany surged back to 3-3
and won the game on a penalty shootout.
</P>
<P>
   So it has been countless times in soccer's supreme competition.
When, as now, the final rounds loom, the game moves beyond the
control and distribution of a ball to the realm of psychological
confrontation. Nations unwittingly bear their souls in what amount
to life-and-death struggles for victory.
</P>
<P>
   This is an area in which the German team has excelled, coming
from behind, often in the last minutes, to reach a remarkable six
finals and nine semifinals in thirteen World Cup appearances. It
has won the trophy three times, a record surpassed only by Brazil,
and is once again in the quarterfinals here.
</P>
<P>
   One of those victories came in the 1954 World Cup in
Switzerland. Germany was thrashed 8-3 in an opening game against
Hungary but nonetheless qualified for the knockout rounds. It
reached the final to find itself facing Hungary again. Within
minutes the Hungarians took a 2-0 lead; the match seemed over. But
the Germans, true to form, came back to win 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has his own conception of tactics,'' Jurgen
Klinsmann, the German captain, said here this week. ``For
ourselves, we try to concentrate on our power. That is to say, we
try to build the pressure, increase the pressure, until the
adversary finally cracks and is overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ability counts, but so, too, does the sheer
strength of character and self-belief that alone can keep tide
after tide of attacks coming and turn near-certain defeat into
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsmann, who has played more than 100 times for Germany, was
speaking after Germany had reached the quarterfinals here by
beating Mexico 2-1. It was a textbook German victory against a team
that often seemed more skilled. Two goals in the last 15 minutes,
by Klinsmann and fellow striker Oliver Bierhoff, literally
shattered the Mexicans, who had seemed headed for victory.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the tournament, Germany trailed Yugoslavia 2-0 with
20 minutes left and came back to tie, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans are in the final eight yet again, playing Croatia
Saturday, and it seems, more than ever, that sheer force of
character has brought them this far. For this, by any estimate, is
not a great squad. Indeed its midfield has often resembled nothing
so much as a great and gloomy void.
</P>
<P>
   This team has been compared in Germany to the Russian space
station MIR, staggering from mishap to mishap but somehow staying
aloft. Manager Berti Vogts has tried so many players in midfield _
even dropping what looked like the best of them, the 25-year-old
Jens Jeremies _ that attempts to discern his strategy have appeared
a fruitless exercise.
</P>
<P>
   What then keeps the ``Mannschaft'' _ simply, The Team _ as they
are known at home _ going here, urged onward by the 34-year-old
Klinsmann and the 37-year-old sweeper Lothar Matthaus? Where does
this exceptional will to win _ recognized by all of Germany's
opponents _ find its roots?
</P>
<P>
   The expression of national pride has, of course, been a
difficult issue for Germans ever since World War 11. In the soccer
team the nation clearly finds a uniquely powerful symbol for values
of strength, determination and cohesion that cannot readily be
displayed elsewhere. While every country takes pride in its soccer
team, not every country takes pride in the team's moral fiber and
will power above all else.
</P>
<P>
   But with so many players over 30, and so many evident problems
in the team, a fourth World Cup still looks like a long shot,
despite the fine performances of striker Oliver Bierhoff, the best
header of the ball in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the team's repeated last-minute comebacks here,
left-back Christian Ziege said this week, ``It is time we won a
game safely, otherwise our fans will die of heart attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, however, the heart attacks have generally been
suffered by Germany's opponents. France, which will meet Germany in
the semifinal if the teams win against Italy and Croatia
respectively, still bears the scars of that 1982 game which seemed
to many French commentators to reflect an old French inferiority
complex beside its powerful neighbor. France has never won the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   As the French sports columnist Roland Gransart commented
laconically this week of the German side, ``Defeat? Never heard of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
