<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ESPN-GAMES-NYT &LR;      07-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ESPN-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A VIDEO GAME, IT'S TV, AND YOU'RE THE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On television, a montage of hockey footage unfurls against the
ESPN National Hockey Night musical theme, leading into Dan Patrick
and Kenny Mayne making fun of themselves in one of those
self-mocking Sports Center commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Then you see a screenful of ESPN graphics about the matchup, an
exhibition game between the Detroit Red Wings and the Colorado
Avalanche. Cut to Joe Louis Arena, with all the ambient hoopla of a
sold-out crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The camera pans over the rink from high above as the National
Hockey Night anchors, Gary Thorne and Steve Levy, recall a vicious
brawl between the teams in the 1996 playoffs. This is a bad-blood
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Detroit Red Wings and the Colorado Avalanche do not like
each other,'' Thorne says. ``Tonight, that battle continues.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting lineups flash onto the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're ready to drop the puck to start the first period.''
</P>
<P>
   Minor jostling ensues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, what a hit!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Painkillers, please!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have gotten away with one there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary, if the referee doesn't start calling some of this stuff,
things are going to get out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a television broadcast. It's a video game, one of
three developed by Radical Entertainment under the aegis of ESPN
Digital Games. Scheduled for release this fall, National Hockey
Night, NBA Tonight and X-Games Pro Boarder are the first
installments in a series of what ESPN is calling ``playable
broadcasts.''
</P>
<P>
   National Hockey Night, for instance, plays like any hockey game
for the personal computer or Playstation, except you see everything
from signature ESPN camera angles like the fisheye goalie cam with
an overlay of ESPN broadcast graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Everything you do is accompanied by color commentary by Thorne
and Levy. When you score a big goal or slam dunk, there are ESPN
instant replays from multiple points of view to cap the moment. On
the PC version, you can see those replays on the Jumbotron, a video
screen framed by a television broadcast and viewed on a computer
monitor (paging Marshall McLuhan...).
</P>
<P>
   The visual elements, the pacing, the commentary, the graphic
design, the crowd response _ all of it conveys the look and feel of
a live television event. Except in this case, you can do more than
sit there and yell at Shaquille O'Neal for missing a shot because
you're the one who's playing.
</P>
<P>
   It's your team. You're the star. You shoot. You score. The crowd
goes wild, and ESPN has something to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   The object here is to blur the line between television and
interactive media. And it works. Because unlike other sorts of
television (sitcoms, movies, music videos), a sports event does not
have to be translated into a game.
</P>
<P>
   It is already a game. It has players. It has rules. It has
winners and losers. It's already interactive. All you have to do is
reassign the players. Extract the kernel, intact, from one medium
and wrap it in another, preferably with a bright, prominently
displayed brand logo.
</P>
<P>
   It's a packaging job. And television is great packaging for
sports. The commentary, the on-screen scorecards and statistics,
and the camera angles provide a context for the action. That's the
value added by a network. It's not just a window. It's a frame. It
makes everything inside seem more significant and dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   In the newspaper or on the radio or in a fully equipped home
theater, hockey is hockey is hockey. Context defines the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is a context for understanding sports. By the same token,
ESPN Digital Games is a context for understanding simulated sports.
After you have played for a week in season mode, the computer will
create a 30-second Plays of the Week segment, a cross-section of
highlights from the league, including a few of your most
spectacular plays and memorable flubs (the thrill of victory, the
agony of defeat).
</P>
<P>
   So it really seems as though your games are part of a pro
season. It puts your wins and losses in context.
</P>
<P>
   At 28 minutes and 58 minutes after the hour, the ESPN sports
ticker unfurls across the screen with updates about games in
progress. If you're playing on a Playstation, those updates are
hypothetical. But if you're playing on a PC hooked up to the
Internet, that sports ticker can stream information directly from
ESPN's Web site, customized according to your preferences.
</P>
<P>
   So while your favorite overpaid athletes face off on a simulated
ball court, the sports feed from the real world is updated on a
continual basis _ the off-line world is delivered intravenously,
courtesy of your cable sports network.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of next year, ESPN Digital Games tickers will also
download statistical data on players and teams _ wins, losses,
injuries, suspensions, arrests for drug possession _ throughout the
season, so the game world will accurately reflect its televised
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   All of this creates a strange sort of parallel universe for
sports fans, a replica of the sports world that lets you branch off
at any point. Can you do a better job managing the New York Yankees
than Joe Torre? Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of an ESPN baseball game, you'll be able to
stream Yankee stats down the ticker and synchronize the real league
with the simulation _ or not.
</P>
<P>
   And just to venture into the realm of paranoia for a moment, if
that ticker can download team rosters, scores and statistics, it
can probably download other sorts of information as well.
</P>
<P>
   Say you're a registered member of ESPN Sports Zone. You're a
26-year-old man in Phoenix who likes basketball and snowboarding.
Who says the sponsor banners in your virtual stadium have to be the
same as everyone else's? How long will it be until ESPN Digital
Games is selling demographically tuned advertisements on the
virtual Jumbotron?
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned, sports fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
