<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6090 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ASTRO-SOFTWARE-3T     07-01 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ASTRO-SOFTWARE-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING THE STARS WITHIN REACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Marshall L. McCall is a professor of astronomy at York University
in Toronto.  
 By MARSHALL L. McCALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is 3:24 a.m. in New York City on Saturday, Sept. 12, 1998.
You are returning home after a long night of partying. Looking high
in the east, you see a half-moon.
</P>
<P>
   You notice what appears to be a reddish star right next to the
moon, near the imaginary line that divides the light and dark
parts. Suddenly, the star disappears. Yet there are no clouds in
the sky, and the moon remains crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the beginning of the end? Have you caught an
invading alien vessel in the act of cloaking? Have you had too many
drinks? Or is there an astronomical explanation for this alarming
phenomenon?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so long ago that the only way of answering the last
question was to consult your neighborhood astronomer. But where do
you find one at 3:30 in the morning, even in New York?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you have just installed a desktop planetarium on
your home computer. Firing it up, you tell it your location and the
time. Suddenly, a myriad of stars appears on your screen. The
computer displays a view toward the north, so you scroll around to
the east.
</P>
<P>
   There you see the moon among the stars. You click on the moon,
and it becomes centered on the screen. No bright star is
immediately obvious. Investigating further, you turn your
planetarium into a time machine, telling it to step back two
minutes in time every second.
</P>
<P>
   Now you see the moon move with respect to the stars. Suddenly, a
bright star emerges. Clicking on it, you are told that it is
Aldebaran, a true star that is one of the brightest in the sky.
Mystery solved!
</P>
<P>
   Now you reverse time to move into the future. The moon passes in
front of Aldebaran as it moves on its orbital journey around Earth.
At 3:47 a.m. by your planetarium's clock, the star emerges from the
dark half of the moon's disk. Running outside, you indeed see that
the subject of your concern is back in the sky, but on the other
side of the moon. You can sleep soundly knowing that the world is
safe.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, many software tools have become available
to bring astronomy down to earth. One of them, Astronomy Village,
is an interactive disk that makes it possible to act out the life
of a professional astronomer. Another one, Real Sky CD, brings to
the masses the actual survey images of the sky used by professional
astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular programs are desktop planetariums, five of
which are reviewed here. Unlike Real Sky CD, desktop planetariums,
for the most part, simulate the view of the sky seen from any
location on Earth at any time, day or night, in the past or the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Although they may allow you access to real images of the
heavens, scenes are normally constructed by plotting the locations
of celestial bodies, using information recorded in vast catalogs.
In this way, they are very much like traditional atlases of Earth.
</P>
<P>
   What makes them special is that they allow you to see how things
change over time at a pace you choose. And many can let you look at
the heavens from the perspective of another world.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, most do not require you to be an expert. If you
simply want to learn about astronomy, a good desktop planetarium is
the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you have a fast computer, though; a lot of number
crunching is done with every tick of the clock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASTRONOMY VILLAGE: INVESTIGATING THE UNIVERSE, VERSION 1.0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NASA Central Operation of Resources for Educators; $5;
Macintosh. Requires Apple Hypercard 2.2 or later.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a grant from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, educators at Wheeling Jesuit University in
Wheeling, W.Va., have developed role-playing multimedia software
that acquaints students with the practice of modern professional
astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is designed for the ninth grade, it can be used by
anyone with at least that level of education to learn about the
universe and feel like a professional while doing it. Best of all,
it costs next to nothing, although you have to buy Apple's
Hypercard to run it.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomy Village opens with the sky darkening over a
mountaintop village, with a large telescope dome in the center.
Besides the observatory, there is an orientation center, a
conference center, a library, a computer laboratory, a hands-on
laboratory, an auditorium and a cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on any of the buildings takes you inside. To learn the
skills needed to navigate through the village, it is first
necessary to visit the orientation center. Research is begun at the
conference center, where a topic of interest is selected.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
