<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWRUSALEM-LANDGRAB-E     07-01 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWRUSALEM-LANDGRAB-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSATIABLE ISRAEL: STRETCHING JERUSALEM _ AND PATIENCE _ TOO FAR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 675-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 27 June 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the Middle East's impossible issues, Jerusalem, it has
long been argued, is best left to the last: once everything else is
sorted out, the irreconcilable may perhaps be reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   True or not, there is no questioning the rider to the
proposition: that high-handed unilateral action to determine the
future of a city that both Israel and the Palestinians claim as
their capital could well destroy any hope of a peace agreement.
Yet, Israel, seemingly deaf to this logic, is once again embarked
on such action.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides promised, when they signed the Oslo peace
agreement in 1993, that the status of Jerusalem would stay
unchanged until they negotiated its future as part of a final
settlement. Strictly speaking, its political status has not
altered.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Israel has used demography. The peace talks were frozen
16 months ago when Israel began building a large Jewish settlement,
Har Homa, in an Arab area.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, as the Americans struggled to unfreeze the talks,
the Israeli cabinet gave initial approval to a plan that expands
Jerusalem's municipal borders, partly by including (though not
annexing) two Jewish settlements east and north of the city and the
West Bank land between them and the city.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any ``peace process'' still left to save? Making that
question yet more vexed, the Israeli government is considering a
non-binding referendum on America's proposal for a small, staged
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The charitable view of this poll is that Benjamin Netanyahu,
Israel's prime minister, is seeking popular support to squeeze
acceptance out of his hard-line cabinet. But the American plan,
crucial as it is to getting talks restarted, deals only with one of
the three interim ``redeployments'' that were supposed, under Oslo,
to precede the final-settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   If a slow-motion referendum has to hold matters up at this
stage, the hopes of pushing on to a realistic, worthwhile
settlement are dim indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on the principle that possession is nine-tenths of the
law, Netanyahu appears to bank on the Palestinians, unequal
partners in the peace process, having no option but to wait quietly
for whatever crumbs the squabbling Israeli government may be
prepared to drop. And they will not get even the crumbs unless they
ensure that no dissident or desperate Palestinian attacks an
Israeli citizen.
</P>
<P>
   This security pledge is intrinsic to the original land-for-peace
bargain. But with limited power over small enclaves of land that
are often cut off from one another, let alone from the outside
world, by Israel's summary border controls, the Palestinians are
growing ever more dissident and desperate.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the IMF's Middle Eastern Department reveals
how cruelly economic conditions in the West Bank and Gaza have
deteriorated since peace broke out: by the beginning of last year,
the unemployment rate was 15 percent higher than in 1993, and
income per head 20 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   These are sour rewards for peace. Yet they would be endurable if
there were genuine hope of better, more independent and more
honorable, times to come. Unfortunately, nothing that the Netanyahu
government has yet offered justifies such hope.
</P>
<P>
   So where will the Palestinians turn? Weaklings compared with the
Israelis, they have two possible forms of pressure. One is force,
albeit suicidal _ in all senses of the word.
</P>
<P>
   They ponder a reprise of the intifada, the uprising in the late
1980s that eventually helped to bring the Israelis to the
negotiating table. A new intifada, it is acknowledged, would be a
grimmer affair: men with arms, not boys with stones.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could turn to world opinion, nearly all of it critical
of Israel, which buttresses, or should buttress, their weakness as
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Without America's influence, the Palestinians might already have
been repulsed from the table. But this influence does not extend to
pressing the Israeli government to break a pattern that is steadily
pushing a Middle East peace out of sight. Until it does, the
descent to violence seems ineluctable. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 675-word article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6094 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ASTRO-SOFTWARE-2N     07-01 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ASTRO-SOFTWARE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: is selected.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An astronomer acts as your mentor and leads you through your
investigation. A separate research path diagram guides you through
the various stages of background research and data collection,
analysis and interpretation, and the presentation of findings.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, you are interested in learning about the
structure of galaxies. Your mentor first directs you to the library
to do some background work. Once that is completed, you go up to
the observatory to use an electronic camera to get images of
galaxies in a cluster.
</P>
<P>
   A quick nighttime trip to the cafeteria allows you to satisfy
your appetite and talk to other astronomers on the mountain about
their experiences. When you have finished observing, you go to the
computer room to make some measurements, then to the hands-on
laboratory to study how a galaxy's environment might affect how it
evolves.
</P>
<P>
   Another trip to the computer room allows you to simulate galaxy
interactions. Finally, your moment of glory comes: you present your
results at a press conference. Of course, you have to be prepared
to cope with questions from the news media throng.
</P>
<P>
   At each step of the way, the mentor appears to explain where you
should go next and what you should do. Some instructions come by
e-mail (of course, you have to go to the computer laboratory to
read those messages).
</P>
<P>
   Although additional teaching materials are available, the
Astronomy Village CD-ROM is easy enough for anyone to master. It is
worth getting to learn about astronomy while learning how
astronomers learn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REAL SKY CD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Astronomical Society of the Pacific; $250 for each of Northern
or Southern sky, $450 for both; Windows 3.1, 95 and NT, and
Macintosh.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1950s, professional astronomers have been poring over
photographic atlases of the sky constructed painstakingly by
special telescopes in California, Australia and Chile. The pictures
reveal stars a million times as faint as the eye can see. The
dimmest extremities of nebulae and galaxies can be seen with
exquisite detail.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the materials have been confined to back rooms of
observatories and universities, essentially inaccessible to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Hubble Space Telescope came along. To point the
telescope accurately, it was necessary to create a database of
stellar positions that included even very faint stars. That was
accomplished by scanning and digitizing the entire collection of
photographic images.
</P>
<P>
   One outcome was the Hubble Guide Star Catalog, a massive index
of stars that has been added to many desktop planetariums,
including three reviewed here (The Sky, Voyager and Starry Night).
</P>
<P>
   Another was Real Sky CD, in which the actual digitized images
have been compressed by a factor of 100 to fit on 18 CD-ROMs. It is
a marvel of modern technology that allows anyone to see the sky as
the professionals do, much as the Landsat project has allowed us to
view Earth in all its splendor. To view the images, a program
called Real Sky View is included.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there are some significant hitches. Unless you
want to look at one of a predefined set of obscurely named objects,
Real Sky View requires you to identify the astronomical coordinates
of a field of interest to be able to look at it. That requires
advance knowledge, perhaps gained through a book or desktop
planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   The program allows you to zoom in on specific locations, but
zooming in too much reveals imperfections in the images caused by
their compression. A smoothing tool is provided to make things look
nicer.
</P>
<P>
   In a practical sense, the main strength of Real Sky CD is that
it allows you to measure a precise position for anything you see.
The software can also be used to create ``finding charts'' to help
locate faint objects with a telescope, but you have to take the
trouble to determine the scale yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy Real Sky CD to learn about astronomy. It should be
regarded as a resource that augments the capabilities of the
serious amateur. Those with occasional needs can probably get by
with the link to the online version of the Digitized Sky Survey at
the Space Telescope Science Institute. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REDSHIFT 3, VERSION 3.0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Piranha Interactive Publishing; $49.95; Windows 95 and 98,
Macintosh will be available in July.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some people want to observe the heavens, and others want to go
there. Redshift is the Desktop Planetarium that comes closest to
satisfying both camps. For the would-be astronaut, it beautifully
integrates detailed planetary landscapes into its regular functions
by employing sophisticated 3-D rendering software: features of a
planet change as you move around it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you can simulate a trip around Saturn by placing
yourself on one of its natural satellites or on a satellite of your
own creation. Or you can beam up to an imaginary platform high
above the surface and command Redshift to take you on a journey
around the planet. The changing view of the rings and their shadows
is breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Standing back on Earth, it is possible to magnify the moon to
make it appear up to 10,000 times as large without loss of
resolution, in steps small enough and at a rate fast enough that
you feel as though you are traveling there.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
