<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ASTRO-SOFTWARE-3R     07-01 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ASTRO-SOFTWARE-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: traveling there.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Redshift is an outstanding instrument for learning. It is the
only desktop planetarium with a full-featured astronomical
dictionary on line (The Penguin Dictionary of Astronomy). And
multimedia is used to introduce many fundamental astronomical
concepts, like the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   Redshift is a masterpiece of multimedia engineering. If you need
to fly, Redshift will get you there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARRY NIGHT DELUXE VERSION 2.1.3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sienna Software; $89.95; Windows 95 and NT, and Macintosh.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are few experiences as invigorating as being out in the
countryside standing under a canopy of stars on a still night.
Starry Night conveys that feeling better than any other desktop
planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   As the Sun sets, shadows of trees both move and lengthen.
Through twilight, the blue of the sky deepens and stars begin to
appear. Finally, night arrives, and the glory of the heavens is
revealed. The brightness and colors of the stars are rendered so
well that it is hard to believe that you are indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Starry Night also does a very good job of integrating planetary
landscapes. When you visit a planet, you can see your feet: a pair
of sneakers on Earth or a spacesuit if you are in a more
inhospitable environment.
</P>
<P>
   Starry Night is a beautifully constructed desktop planetarium
that is easy to learn. If you cannot get out of the city, this is
the next best thing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SKY, LEVEL IV &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Software Bisque; $249; Windows 3.1, 95 and NT. A version for
Macintosh and Windows 95 and 98 will be available in August.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amateur astronomers around the world examine the sky regularly,
usually with binoculars or telescopes. In the past, they had to
wrestle with flashlights and charts. An unfiltered flashlight would
blind night vision for minutes. Charts would flap in the breeze.
Now a PC with the right desktop planetarium can make observations a
lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   The Sky excels as a field companion. It is unique in providing a
Night Vision Option that converts the display to red on black. It
is also able to show how the heavens should look through your
telescope. It is the only desktop planetarium that can link
directly to Real Sky CD.
</P>
<P>
   More serious amateurs can use The Sky to control many
commercially available computer-driven telescopes. The Sky falls
short in not allowing the user to view the heavens from other
virtual vantage points in the solar system. But it is hard to find
a better friend in the field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VOYAGER II &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Carina Software; $159.50; Macintosh.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When using a desktop planetarium, it is easy to lose sight of
the forest while examining the trees. Voyager excels at revealing
order on grand scales.
</P>
<P>
   Although Voyager lacks the gloss of Redshift or Starry Night, it
excels at displaying celestial systems. Suppose, for example, a new
asteroid is discovered. As with other desktop planetariums, it is a
simple matter to enter its orbital parameters (readily accessible
on the Web).
</P>
<P>
   With Voyager, it is easy to go to a convenient vantage point in
space and track the rock's motion relative to the other planets. An
impending catastrophe can become painfully obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Voyager can show the entire sky at once. Particular objects can
be turned on or off to reveal their locations with respect to the
Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   One deficiency of Voyager is that there is no online help, but
the manual is excellent. An add-on called Sky Pilot can be
purchased to enable you to use Voyager to control a telescope. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE OF THE PLANETS, STANDARD EDITION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ARC Science Simulations; $95; DOS 5.0 or later.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desktop planetariums rely upon mathematical descriptions of the
locations and motions of planets, satellites, asteroids and comets
to track their positions through space and time. That works well as
long as the bodies do not come too close to a strong source of
gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The only desktop planetarium that automatically accommodates
perturbations to all orbits caused by the gravitational influence
of bodies other than the Sun is Dance of the Planets. The only
other one capable of dealing with gravitational perturbations is
Redshift, but it can do so for only one body at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Dance of the Planets excels at tracking objects in the solar
system. It is dated and hard to use, but if you really need to know
how hazardous those pesky PHAs (potentially hazardous asteroids)
might be, Dance of the Planets is for you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
