<HEADER>
A6115 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBECUEBIBLE-2ndTake     07-01 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBECUEBIBLE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: for 4-6 hours.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remove drained yogurt from refrigerator (it will be quite thick)
and discard the liquid. Transfer yogurt to large nonreactive bowl.
Add garlic, ginger, onion, lemon juice, cayenne, salt, black pepper
and cumin seeds and whisk to blend. Set aside while you prepare the
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Remove and discard skin from chicken pieces, then rinse pieces
under cold running water. Drain and blot dry with paper towels.
Make 2 or 3 deep slashes, to the bone, in each piece. Add chicken
to marinade in bowl and turn pieces to coat. Cover and let
marinate, in refrigerator, for 4-6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high. (Charcoal is preferable for this recipe.)
</P>
<P>
   When ready to grill, oil grill grate. Remove chicken from
marinade and arrange on hot grate. Grill, turning with tongs, until
chicken is nicely browned on outside and the juices run clear when
tip of skewer or sharp knife is inserted in thickest part of a
drumstick or thigh, 8-10 minutes per side (16-20 minutes in all).
</P>
<P>
   Transfer chicken to serving plates or platter and serve
immediately, garnished with onion, tomato, cucumber, radish slices
and lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 264 calories, 15 grams fat, 6
grams carbohydrates, 24 grams protein, 79 milligrams cholesterol,
905 milligrams sodium, 52 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN STEAK IN GARLIC-LIME MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   Adobo:
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Steaks:
</P>
<P>
   4 bottom round steaks (about 6 to 8 ounces each) cut 1/2-inch
thick (no thicker, or the steaks will be tough)
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, cut crosswise into 1/2-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the adobo. Combine first 4 ingredients in mortar and
grind to a paste with the pestle. Work in lime juice and oil to
form a smooth paste. Alternatively, place all ingredients in a
blender and process to a smooth puree. Correct seasoning, adding
salt and pepper as necessary; the mixture should be highly
seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, oil the grill grate. Brush onion slices with
the oil and arrange on hot grate. Brush the steaks with the adobo
mixture and place on hot grate with the onion. Grill steaks to
taste, 2 to 3 minutes per side for medium-rare, basting with adobo
and rotating 90 degrees after 1 minute to create an attractive
crosshatch of grill marks. Always use tongs when moving or turning
the steak. Grill onions until nicely charred, 3 to 4 minutes per
side, seasoning with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer steak to plates or a platter and brush one final time
with the adobo. Let stand for 3 minutes, then serve with the
grilled onion on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To give the steaks a richer garlic, cumin and lime flavor,
marinate them in the adobo in a nonreactive baking dish for 10
minutes before grilling.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 360 calories, 19 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 37 grams protein, 106 milligrams cholesterol,
558 milligrams sodium, 52 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SALT AND PEPPER GRILLED SHRIMP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds jumbo shrimp (2 pounds if using shrimp with the
heads on), shells left on but deveined (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons coarse salt, preferably sea salt
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 large, juicy lime
</P>
<P>
   Note: To devein an unpeeled shrimp by hand, make a lengthwise
cut along back of shell, using kitchen scissors. Scrape out exposed
vein with tine of a fork or tip of a paring knife.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse shrimp under cold running water, then drain and blot dry
with paper towels. Place shrimp in nonreactive baking dish and
sprinkle with the lime juice and 1 teaspoon each salt and pepper.
Toss to coat, then let marinate, at room temperature, 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cut the lime into 4 lengthwise wedges. Place 1 wedge
in each of 4 tiny shallow bowls or dishes. Place a small mound of
salt (1/2 teaspoon) on one side of lime wedge and a mound of pepper
(1/2 teaspoon) on the other. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, oil the grill grate. Arrange shrimp, in
their shells, on the hot grate and grill, turning with tongs, until
meat is firm and pink, about 2 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer shrimp to serving plates. To eat, squeeze lime wedge
over the salt and pepper and stir 2 or 3 times with chopsticks;
peel shrimp and dip in the lime mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 191 calories, 3 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 35 grams protein, 258 milligrams cholesterol,
1,555 milligrams sodium, 14 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
