<HEADER>
A6116 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DOMAIN-NAMES-NYT &LR;      07-01 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DOMAIN-NAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSST, OVER HERE ... WANT YOUR GOOD NAME BACK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is Michael J. Fox worth $10,000, while Tommy Lee Jones is
worth only $3,500? Kathie Lee Gifford goes for $7,500, three times
the rate for Zsa Zsa Gabor. Meanwhile, Bill Gates is available for
$1 million, which is pocket change if one happens to have access to
Gates' pockets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By those standards, Peter Lewis, measured in the amount of money
it would cost to own peterlewis.com, is a bargain at $850. Still,
that puts me in the same price range as Janet Reno, Barbara Bush,
Billy Graham, Chelsea Clinton, George Brett and Marlon Brando. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, nearly every conceivable celebrity name has
been registered in the commercial (.com) top-level Internet domain,
including those of business leaders, sports stars, politicians and
other luminaries. But the people and companies registering these
names are not the stars or politicians themselves, but others
hoping to turn a quick dollar by selling the names back to their
rightful owners _ or the highest bidders. It's called domain name
poaching, and it's a thriving business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices are negotiable. ``I would give up VannaWhite.com for a
shot on `Wheel of Fortune,''' said Vern Barke, owner of many
celebrity names. ``I would give up WoodyAllen.com for a cameo
appearance in Woody's next movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Barke, in an e-mail message, said that as of July 1 all of his
celebrity names are redirected to sex-related sites on the Web.
``Sex sells,'' he noted. Now these celebrities know how Bill
Clinton feels; his name was until recently used to sell sex toys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Friend to Friend Foundation, a Christian ministries service
in Kansas that registered peterlewis.com, is outraged that this is
happening. It just sent me a 15-page letter decrying the horrible
situation, noting four major causes for concern.
</P>
<P>
   First, unscrupulous entrepreneurs are using the names of
well-known people as access points to pornography. Second, these
poachers are seeking to sell celebrity names to the highest bidder.
Third, some of the names are being offered to the public for use as
e-mail addresses or access points for astrology or dating services.
And fourth, the letter said, some names, like Brad Pitt's, are
being sold to Arabs, who, for some reason, the foundation sees fit
to group with pornographers and astrologers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, the foundation has been holding my name and several hundred
others including Steve Wozniak, Ray Bradbury, Peter Drucker, Anita
Bryant, Arthur Treacher and even Manhattannewyorkcity _ and by
doing so has kept them from falling into the hands of dating
services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Friend to Friend Foundation wrote that I can show my
gratitude and claim peterlewis.com for a minimum donation of $850,
as long as I promise not to display pornography on my Web site. The
foundation will keep $350, and $500 will go to one of 11 charities
it supports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alas, I had already found a domain of my own, lewis.cx, on
remote Christmas Island in the Indian Ocean. A peek into the zone
file of the London-based computer that serves as host for the
Christmas Island domain revealed that I had only 18 virtual
neighbors. Two companies _ the Intel Corp. and Federal Express _
together owned at least half of the virtual real estate on the
island's domain roster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Intel had already staked out Christmas Island addresses for
celeron.cx, intel.cx, intel-inside.cx, intercast.cx, mmx.cx,
pentium.cx and proshare.cx, basically carpet-bombing the tiny
island with subdomains. Federal Express had already registered
fdxcorp.cx, federalexpress.cx, fedex.cx and _ could it be? _
ups.cx. Perhaps they made a typo and meant to type ``oops.cx.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   None of this answers why michaeljfox.com is worth $10,000, of
course, or why ladydiana.com is reportedly being offered for
$250,000. Except, perhaps, that michaeljfox.net and michaeljfox.org
are both still available, whereas princessdiana.com is owned by
someone in Oregon, princessdiana.net by someone in California, and
princessdiana.org by someone in Haifa, Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Princessdi.net and princessdi.org reside in Pennsylvania.
Someone in Jerusalem owns dianaprincessofwales.com, a New Yorker
has dianaprincessofwales.org, and dianaprincessofwales.net belongs
to someone with the e-mail address MakeOffer(AT)DomainClub.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
