r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAT-FREEFRIES-TEX     07-01 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAT-FREEFRIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A TCU COED INVENTED A FAT-FREE FRENCH FRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's a 26-year-old with a mathematics degree supposed to do?
Cook, of course.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what you do if you're Candace Vanice.
</P>
<P>
   The petite Gen Xer may still look the part of the Texas
Christian University coed that she once was (she later graduated
from the University of Kansas), but she drops words like
``co-pack'' and ``patents.''
</P>
<P>
   She began experimenting with food while she was still in
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was when everyone was becoming aware of low-fat food,''
Vanice said. ``I love french fries, so I tried to make some myself
that would be healthful. First I just sliced potatoes and baked
them on cookie sheets. Then I tried coating them in mayonnaise and
vinegar to get some flavor and some crunch. Then I remembered that
when I'd bake bread with my grandmother, she'd brush the top with
egg whites to make it brown and crusty.''
</P>
<P>
   So with some experimenting, Vanice came up with a method of
coating crinkle-cut fries with diluted egg whites and spices,
resulting in a fat-free fry (that is actually baked). But how to
take a great idea to the masses wanting a fat-free fry?
</P>
<P>
   With a patent pending on her process, Vanice approached the big
boys, Ore-Ida and Inland Valley, about her idea of mass marketing
frozen fat-free fries. The big boys weren't interested.
</P>
<P>
   By now a college graduate with a day job as a consultant with an
actuarial firm in Kansas City, Mo., Vanice was not to be deterred.
</P>
<P>
   She found little Mr. Dell Foods of Kearney, Mo., a manufacturer
of hash browns. That company agreed to produce her fries, now named
8th Wonder Fat Free Fries. And an advertising company came up with
packaging. (''I wanted something that looked new and light, not the
orange and brown that was on the packages out there,'' she said.)
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City and Des Moines, Iowa, markets for a year, 8th
Wonder Fries are now moving into five Texas markets, including Fort
Worth. Look for the fries in the frozen-potato sections of
Albertson's and Tom Thumb stores.
</P>
<P>
   And like every hip, happenin' firm today, 8th Wonder Fat Free
Fries offers information on the Web, at www.fatfreefries.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
