<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HONG-KONG (Shanghai, China) _ already filed _ When he
visits Hong Kong Thursday, President Clinton will convey what his
aides hope will be a calming message about Asia's economic turmoil.
The chief executive caps his nine-day tour of China with a 29-hour
visit to the former British colony that reverted to Chinese control
a year ago. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Guilin, China) _ President Clinton plays
enviro-tourist after lecturing Chinese business executives about
the toll that economic development can take on natural wonders. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CHINA (Shanghai, China) _ In a country where sons are
prized and daughters neglected, Hillary Rodham Clinton makes her
case on the need to value women, to educate them, to provide legal
rights, to stop violence and abuse in their homes, and to allow
them the freedom to plan their own families, a quiet reference to
forced abortions. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ENTOURAGE (Shanghai, China) _ We take a look at the
1,000 or so people traveling with President Clinton on his trip to
China. About two-thirds of them are government workers and family
members. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-REALITY (Geneva) _ Reality is sobering the 2-year-old AIDS
drug treatment revolution that has saved thousands of lives in
Europe and the United States. According to health experts, no more
than 50 percent of AIDS patients can reduce the human
immunodeficiency virus in their blood to undetectable levels. By
RUTH SoRELLE.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA-MARITAL (Paris) _ already filed _ French husbands are
abandoning the once-accepted institution known here as the
``five-to-seven,'' referring to the early evening hours they spent
with their mistresses before returning home for dinner with their
families. A lack of time and money has gradually obliterated the
practice, and women no longer accept it. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FIRES (Mexico City) _ Mexican officials say the rainy
season has arrived and that the major fires that plagued the
country for more than a month are all but extinguished. By PHILIP
TRUE.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FIREWORKS-SAFETY (Washington) _ With tourists mulling around the
Washington Monument, the Consumer Product Safety Commission
demonstrates the hazards fireworks pose for children and other
Fourth of July merrymakers. ``Sparklers which burn at 2000 degrees
Fahrenheit are especially dangerous for unsuspecting children,''
one official of the safety agency says. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BURNED-BOY (Splendora, Texas) _ Investigators say they are all
but convinced that the teen-ager who was named by an 8-year-old
burn victim was with friends and could not have been involved in
the attack. The boy, who was doused with gasoline and burned over
99 percent of his body on his birthday, is in critical condition.
By PAUL McKAY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLD-CUP (Paris) _ A look ahead to the final eight in the
World Cup of Soccer. By JOHN P. LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Astros, fresh off a 17-2 win night,
host the Chicago White Sox again in Game 2 of their series. By
JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-RESERVES (Undated) _ The reserves are named for the National
League and Americal League All-Star teams. The 69th All-Star Game
is scheduled for Tuesday night at Coors Field in Denver. By ALAN
TRUEX.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ In some ways, the Supreme Court,
whose process of reaching monumental decisions is secret and
mysterious, is the most intriguing wing of government. It is a
constant example of the influence a single individual can have in a
democracy since many of its rulings are decided by votes of 5 to 4.
By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
