<HEADLINE>
REQUESTS FOR JUNETEENTH TEA CAKES FULFILLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several readers wrote and phoned last week after reading
reporter Janette Rodrigues' story about the African-American
heritage of tea cakes as a part of Juneteenth celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   We have several tea cake recipes in our files; here are two
variations on the theme. Mary Bass of Fort Worth originally sent in
the first recipe. The second recipe was sent by Alice Leslie of
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-FASHIONED TEA CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 1/2 dozen
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon milk
</P>
<P>
   Beat butter at medium speed with electric mixer; gradually add
sugar, beating well. Add eggs, beat well. Combine dry ingredients,
add to creamed mixture alternately with milk, mix well. Cover and
chill 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Work with half of the dough at a time, storing remainder in
refrigerator. Place stockinette cover on rolling pin and flour
well. Roll dough to 1/4-inch thickness on lightly floured pastry
cloth. Cut with a 2 1/2-inch round cutter and place on a greased
cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for 8 minutes (cookies will be pale). Cool
on wire racks.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cookie: 67 calories, 3 grams fat, 11
grams carbohydrates, 16 milligrams cholesterol, 26 milligrams
sodium, 34 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TEA CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 9 dozen
</P>
<P>
   4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter-flavor solid shortening
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla OR lemon extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sift first 3 ingredients together. Cream shortening and sugar.
Beat eggs just enough to break yolks.
</P>
<P>
   Add eggs to shortening mixture. Mix well. Add flour and milk
alternately. Then add extract.
</P>
<P>
   Knead lightly on floured board. Roll out and cut with cookie
cutter. (If the dough is rolled thick, cakes will be soft. If dough
in rolled very thin, cakes will be crisp.) Place on greased cookie
sheets. Place sheets in oven and immediately reduce heat to 350
degrees. Bake for about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tea cake: 50 calories, 2 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 4 milligrams cholesterol, 29 milligrams
sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Always a favorite: A reader called looking for the squash
casserole recipe from the Black-eyed Pea chain. This is one of the
few recipes from that restaurant that we have on file. When owned
by Gene Street, the chain shared its recipes. Unfortunately, that's
no longer the case. Clip and enjoy this local favorite.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-EYED PEA'S BAKED SQUASH
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds medium-size yellow squash
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bread crumbs plus additional bread crumbs for topping
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   Dash of pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cut tips off squash and cut each squash into 3 or 4 pieces. Drop
squash into a large saucepan with enough boiling water to cover.
Return to boil, reduce heat and cook until tender. Drain in
colander and mash.
</P>
<P>
   Combine with beaten eggs, 1 cup bread crumbs, butter, sugar,
salt, onion and pepper. Turn into 3-quart casserole that has been
lightly greased or sprayed with nonstick spray. Cover with light
layer of bread crumbs. Bake at 350 degrees for 20 to 25 minutes or
until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 174 calories, 11 grams fat, 17
grams carbohydrates, 43 milligrams cholesterol, 161 milligrams
sodium, 56 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Bruhin of Irving, Texas, would like a recipe for a
chocolate Italian cream cake. She has one for the white version of
the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one that is a little more obscure. John B. Hughes, from
somewhere in Cyberland, is trying to track down a recipe for the
Original Dallas County Jail Chili. He writes that one of the Dallas
papers had a columnist named Weldon Owens who was in possession of
said recipe.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
