<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOCOOK-PASTASAUCES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO COOK' PASTA SAUCES ARE STIRRING NEWS FOR SAPPED SUMMER CHEFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A book that includes ``No Cook'' in the title is guaranteed to
catch my eye during a Texas July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joie Warner's No-Cook Pasta Sauce'' (Chronicle, $17.95) is one
sure-fire attention getter. The book's 75 recipes combine room
temperature sauces with a pot of cooked pasta to create delicious
meals for cooks wrung out from a simple trip to the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes range from a simple butter and Parmesan sauce to a
budget-busting lobster tarragon sauce. But in between are recipes
using the season's lush tomatoes, herbs such as rosemary and basil,
and pantry items such as canned black beans and canned clams.
</P>
<P>
   Get off the sofa. Go into the kitchen. You can do this.
</P>
<P>
   HOT-HOT TOMATO SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2-4
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh, ripe tomatoes, seeded and coarsely diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup well-drained, oil-packed sun-dried tomatoes, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fruity olive oil (See Note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1-2 teaspoons crushed red pepper, or to taste (See Note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese, plus extra for serving
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh flat-leaf parsley, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Note: Two teaspoons of crushed red pepper is hot-hot, 1 teaspoon
is medium-hot and 1/2 teaspoon is mildly hot. And make sure your
crushed red pepper is still red; if it's brown, it's old and musty.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended olive oil is extra-virgin; it should be a
greenish-gold color and should cost about $8 or $9 dollars for a
17-ounce bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Combine garlic, fresh tomatoes, sun-dried tomatoes, olive oil,
butter, crushed red pepper, salt and Parmesan cheese in pasta
serving bowl. Set aside to warm to room temperature, or just until
flavors mingle.
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta in large pot of boiling salted water until al dente.
Drain pasta well and immediately add to sauce in bowl. Sprinkle
with parsley and toss. Serve at once with Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Recommended pasta: 8 ounces rigatoni or penne rigate
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 175 calories, 15 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 19 milligrams cholesterol,
420 milligrams sodium, 79 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GREEN OLIVE PESTO SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2-4
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup drained sliced pimento-stuffed green olives (5-ounce jar),
coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fruity olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 1 large lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   Combine garlic, olives, olive oil, lemon zest and lemon juice in
pasta serving bowl. Set aside to warm to room temperature, or just
until flavors mingle.
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta in large pot of boiling salted water until al dente.
Drain pasta well and immediately add to sauce in bowl. Sprinkle
with basil, parsley and thyme, and toss.
</P>
<P>
   Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Recommended pasta: 8 ounces medium shells (conchiglie rigate).
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 171 calories, 18 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 854
milligrams sodium, 96 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ALFREDO SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese, plus extra for serving
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cracked (very coarsely ground) black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh basil leaves, cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   Place butter, cream, Parmesan, salt, pepper and nutmeg in pasta
serving bowl. Set aside to warm to room temperature or, preferably,
place bowl (be sure it's heatproof) over the pasta pot to warm the
ingredients and melt butter while heating the water. Once water
comes a boil, remove bowl and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta in large pot of boiling salted water until al dente.
Drain pasta well and immediately add to sauce in bowl. Sprinkle
with basil and toss. Serve at once with extra Parmesan cheese. Pass
pepper mill.
</P>
<P>
   Recommended pasta: 1 pound fresh or dried fettuccine
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 252 calories, 26 grams fat, 1
gram carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 76 milligrams cholesterol, 590
milligrams sodium, 92 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
