<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-CILANTRO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CILANTRO: DON'T GO ETHNIC WITHOUT IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Cilantro is an annual, a native of the eastern
Mediterranean and southern Europe but widely cultivated elsewhere.
It reaches 24 inches in height. Leaves have a distinctive, pungent
flavor. ``Cilantro'' is the term for the leaves; ``coriander''
refers to the seeds of the same plant.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Plant in full sun from seed, or transplant
after last frost or in fall. Cilantro can't take heat. Apply a
little fish emulsion when the plant is small; occasionally apply
compost.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Tomatoes, squash, eggplant, meats, cheeses _
especially in Mexican, Chinese, Southeast Asian and Indian
cuisines.
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Avoid planting near fennel and other members of the
Apiaceae family.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN WITH SPINACH AND YOGURT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups finely chopped spinach
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken (3 1/2 to 4 pounds), cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, grated
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 green chiles, such as jalapenos, seeds and stems removed,
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed fresh garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Combine yogurt, spinach, cilantro and mint. Coat chicken well
with mixture and marinate for 1 hour in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil and brown onion in oil. Add tomatoes, chiles, garlic,
ginger, all spices and salt. Then add chicken, along with its green
marinade. Simmer, stirring frequently, until chicken is tender.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 489 calories, 35 grams fat, 9
grams carbohydrates, 34 grams protein, 105 milligrams cholesterol,
530 milligrams sodium, 65 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Flavors of Africa Cookbook'' by Dave DeWitt, Mary Jane Wilan
and Melissa T. Stock (Prima Publishing, $16)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NUTTY BROCCOLI AND CHILI OMELET
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2 as main course, 4 as appetizer
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces broccoli, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons light soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 medium-size red chiles, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup (about 1 ounce) finely chopped roasted cashews or
peanuts
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   6 green onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Cook broccoli in boiling water until just tender; drain very
well. Combine eggs, soy sauce, chiles, cashews and cilantro in a
bowl. Add broccoli and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in 8-inch omelet pan. Add garlic and green onion and
cook gently until onion is soft. Pour in egg mixture and stir well.
Cover and cook over low heat until bottom of omelet is set and
browned. Finish cooking omelet under hot broiler until set in
center. Cut into wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving for four: 167 calories, 11
grams fat, 10 grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 159 milligrams
cholesterol, 170 milligrams sodium, 62 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Taste of Indochina'' by Jan Castorina and Dimitra Stais
(Barron's, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHAYOTE SLAW
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup low-fat mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1 whole chayote, grated (2 cups), see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 jicama, peeled and grated (1 cup), see Note
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium red onion, grated or cut into julienne slices (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, grated or cut into julienne slices (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Whisk mayonnaise, vinegar, mustard and honey together in a small
salad bowl. Add vegetables and salt and pepper to taste. Toss well.
Top with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Chayote is a squash that tastes like a cross between
cucumber and zucchini. Jicama is a root vegetable with a white,
crunchy flesh resembling a water chestnut. Look for both in the
produce section of the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 67 calories, 2 grams fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 5 milligrams cholesterol, 91
milligrams sodium, 26 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Vegetarian Dinner in Minutes'' by Linda Gassenheimer
(Chronicle, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
