<HEADER>
A6180 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-KORFBALL-NYT &LR;      07-01 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KORFBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB OFFERS WIDE MENU FOR SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (af)  
 By VICTOR MATHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the days before the Web, few fans of baseball or football
felt as if they were missing anything. After all, newspapers,
magazines and television provided ample coverage of their favorite
sports.
</P>
<P>
   But fans of rowing, swimming, cycling and other less popular
sports had to make do with the occasional paragraph, if they were
lucky, or maybe just a monthly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the biggest American sports have certainly benefited
from the explosion of information provided by the Web. But it has
probably made the greatest difference to enthusiasts of
lesser-known sports. Now even devotees of billiards, rounders and
korfball can find something for themselves on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Korfball? More on that later.
</P>
<P>
   Surely one of the less extensively covered sporting events is
the World's Strongest Man competition. An event seen on ESPN and
ESPN2 late at night, it features burly Icelanders and others
lifting barrels and dragging anchors in races against the clock.
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Henderson, 18, a college student in Ewing, N.J.,
posted some information about the competition on his personal Web
site, he had no idea what was in store. Soon he was deluged with
mail from other enthusiasts and, later on, from some of the
entrants themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually ESPN and Transworld International, which televises
the competition in Europe, recognized the page as the event's
official site.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said his Web site (www.strongestman.com/magnus. html)
filled a void. The site includes results dating from the first
competition in 1977, profiles of the competitors and photographs.
One highlight is the extensive collection of sound files, enabling
the curious browser to hear the American strongman O.D. Wilson
boast: ``There is nobody stronger than me, nobody. I'm the
strongest man on this planet,'' or John Pall Sigmarsson of Iceland
declare, ``I am a Viking.''
</P>
<P>
   The site gets about 1,300 hits a week, and Henderson, who
answers questions about the competition on a site bulletin board,
gets 50 to 70 e-mails a week from fellow fans.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, bicycle racing, especially each summer's Tour
de France, has attracted more press attention. Die-hard fans
subscribe to Velonews, a 50,000-circulation magazine, for more
complete results year-round. Now Velonews has a Web site with daily
reports from races around the world
(www.greatoutdoors.com/velonews/index.htm).
</P>
<P>
   Most people think of tug-of-war as a friendly pastime at a
picnic or fair. But there is also international competition in the
sport, which used to be an Olympic event. In addition to world
championship results, www.tugofwar.org devotes much of its space to
the rules: the eight pullers on each team are allowed to apply
resin on their hands only, and spikes and nails in the shoes are
not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Once every four years, Olympic viewers watch men and women slide
down a refrigerated chute on their backs. The rest of the time,
luge fans can turn to www.luge.com for results of non-Olympic
competitions, world rankings and tips on technique.
</P>
<P>
   Bandy is a winter sport with a profile even lower than luge's.
Essentially it is hockey played on ice the size of a soccer field
with a ball rather than a puck. Although most popular in Europe, it
has a North American following, as well.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian site, www.escape.ca/gbgre, is realistic about the
sport's popularity. The page begins, helpfully, by answering the
question ``What is bandy?'' It offers links to other bandy sites,
including the results of the 1997 world championships (won by
Sweden) and a history of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   For a good all-in-one site, there is www.sportcal.co.uk, with
schedules of events and links for 180 sports like dragon boat
racing, Canadian five-pin bowling, underwater rugby (there was a
competition June 20 in Slovakia) and, yes, korfball.
</P>
<P>
   Korfball, a nearly 100-year-old sport, is a form of basketball
with teams of four men and four women. ``Korf'' is Dutch for
basket, and the Netherlands won the European championship in April.
The Dutch also win the prize for best korfball Web site:
www.knkv.nl/english/index.html. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
