<SLUG> BC-BAT-ATTACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGER SENTENCED FOR BEATING YOUNGER BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EVE MITCHELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MATEO, Calif. _ Calling it the most difficult case in her
two-decade judicial career, a judge has sentenced a teen-age boy to
detention for hitting another youth in the head with a baseball
bat.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum sentence of up to seven years in a California Youth
Authority facility was handed down by San Mateo County Juvenile
Court Judge Margaret Kemp. The boy, 15, has been in custody since
his arrest May 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as difficult a case as has been presented to me in
those 20 years,'' said Kemp, who called it an ``enormous tragedy''
for both the victim and his attacker.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager sentenced Tuesday and a second boy, also 15, were
arrested just hours after the May 24 attack in the parking lot of a
Foster City shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has alleged the two teen-agers went out looking
for someone to attack after viewing ``Menace II Society.'' The boys
watched the 1993 movie, which tells the story of a teen-age gang
member trying to turn his life around, the night before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the entertainment media is poisoning our
children,'' Kemp said. The boys ``armed themselves, and they went
out to hurt somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim, a 14-year-old from Foster City who is undergoing
therapy for a severe head injury, said outside court, ``I think
it's good he got the maximum punishment. I also think it was unfair
for me to go through this and for him to go through it himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy sentenced Tuesday, whose name is not being disclosed
because he is a juvenile, will be eligible for parole in 2 1/2
years.
</P>
<P>
   His mother gasped, then cried out, when the judge announced the
sentence after a two-hour hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the boy admitted to an assault charge in exchange
for dismissal of an attempted murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   At his sentencing hearing, the boy said he and the other youth
had only meant to use the bat to scare somebody but that he had
ended up hitting the victim instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll ever be able to forgive myself for what I
did,'' he said. ``There's no excuse for what I've done. It hurts a
lot to see my sister and my mom to have to go through this pain I
bring to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
