<HEADER>
A6208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLAR-TECH-ART-NYT &LR;      07-01 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLAR-TECH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL REACHING FOR THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Solar-powered fiber optics? Photovoltaic
cell-laminated tensile hyperbolic paraboloids? Today's visionary
gibberish is tomorrow's plain English. The nifty thing about
emerging technologies is the way they sneak up on you, then
transform your life overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Sun: An Outdoor Exhibition of Light,'' a garden
installation inside the wrought-iron fence of the Cooper-Hewitt
National Design Museum in Manhattan until Oct. 25, explains how
solar technology has been sneaking up on civilization in the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   As for the transformation of daily life _ the one foretold in
the 1970s, when solar-energy zealots worshiped clunky black panels
and declared independence from fossil fuels _ it is once again in
sight. This time around, the show declares, the design
possibilities are endless. So are the global perks (cleaner air,
fewer oil wars). No, really.
</P>
<P>
   Solar power as a source of electricity was discovered in 1839,
refined for satellites in the 1950s and lately has been engineered
into glass panels for the rising office tower at Four Times Square
designed by Fox &AMP; Fowle Architects with Kiss &AMP; Cathcart Architects.
</P>
<P>
   But only over the last few years have scientists figured out how
to make photovoltaic material _ now a thin black film that can be
attached to other materials _ turn sunlight into electricity
affordably. The Energy Department and BP Solar (a subsidiary of
British Petroleum, and a manufacturer of photovoltaics) helped
sponsor this traveling exhibition to spread the news: This is not
your father's solar energy.
</P>
<P>
   It is not your father's old museum fare either. Lucy Fellowes,
who shaped the exhibition over four years, did more than the
standard curatorial sweep. Yes, Ms. Fellowes, the museum's curator
for special projects, created a time line of solar history, and
collected solar-powered products and prototypes (lawn mower,
lantern, call box, computer, lights and so on). But there is plenty
of innovation, too.
</P>
<P>
   She commissioned two forward-looking New York architects to
design the exhibition and to create two original structures using
photovoltaics in new ways. Early on, the exhibition and its message
became a collaborative mission.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Goldsmith, of FTL Happold Architects and Engineers,
designed the garden's most imposing structure: a 30-foot-high solar
tensile pavilion, a fabric tent laminated with photovoltaic film
five-thousandths of an inch thick. At night the film electrifies a
display of red lights.
</P>
<P>
   The show's timing is fortuitous. At the apex of a stock market
that has financed a cavalcade of giant gas guzzlers and small
electronic consumables, ``Under the Sun'' offers a change of
perspective. Refreshingly, it involves no recycled garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Its wonders may be arriving just in time. After a decade of
techno-ennui _ the fatigue of being startled by an onslaught of
PCs, laptops, cell phones, satellites, lasers _ users are jaded.
Cash-machine cards in hand, they stand ready to be wowed, then
bored, then wowed again by the next barrage of personal gadgets in
black or taupe. Is that all there is?
</P>
<P>
   What is missing is awe. It takes something like this exhibition
to show off the poetry of solar energy. When designers express the
link between earth and sky, between the sun and our insatiable need
for power, the trick can be downright thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the Himawari, an intricate silver pod with a transparent
dome tucked under one of the Cooper-Hewitt's windows. It is a solar
lighting system making its first American appearance. Invented and
produced in Japan, the Himawari (sunflower) tracks the sun with 36
moving lenses that gather energy into light-conducting
(fiber-optic) glass strands. The light is transported indoors to
six lamps that illuminate, poetically enough, some solar souvenirs,
like a German pocket sundial of 1748. The room reflects the mood of
the sky outside; clouds change the intensity of the lighting.
</P>
<P>
   In midgarden is a self-powered solar glass pavilion invented by
Gregory Kiss and Goldsmith. The pavilion is made of
photovoltaic-laminated glass panels that do triple work: structure,
enclosure and electrical generator. Inside, visitors are cooled by
a fan and lighted by fluorescent lights in the glowing glass floor.
``We want to make energy production palpable,'' Kiss said. ``We're
trying to do sensual design.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology that warms the soul as it cools the body? Maybe there
is such a thing as progress after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MATCHUPS     07-01 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANIZATION OF SOCCER APPARENT AT 1998 WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, this story subsumes material originally skedded at
SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE)  
 (JT)  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The world's finest teams have played 56 soccer matches
over three weeks. Their players have scored with feet, knees,
heads, chests, shoulders, and, in the unfortunate case of
goalkeeper Andoni Zubizarreta of Spain, with a hand.
</P>
<P>
   The gaffes and heroics have kept fans up late in Asia and gotten
them up early in South America. But when one examines the list of
World Cup quarterfinalists, what is striking is that this
quadrennial flurry of very well-documented activity has done very
little to change the balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   The teams that have had the most success in this competition
since it was launched in 1930 _ Brazil, Germany, Italy and
Argentina _ are all among the final eight. So is the host nation,
France, and three other representatives from Europe _ the
Netherlands, Croatia and Denmark _ which simply reaffirms that,
despite globalization, the old world remains firmly at the center
of the soccer universe.
</P>
<P>
   There were six European quarterfinalists in 1990, seven in 1994
and six this year. Even if a South American team does manage to win
a World Cup on European soil for the first time since Brazil in
1958, it bears remembering that the contemporary South American
stars spend more time in this climate and this time zone than they
do in their own. All 11 of the Argentinians who started against
England on Tuesday play for European clubs, and of the 11
Brazilians who started against Chile, seven are under contract with
European employers. Ronaldo has seen a lot more of Eindhoven,
Barcelona and Milan in the last four years than he has of sunny Rio
de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is hardly new. Argentine coach Daniel Passarella,
to cite just one example, spent many seasons playing on this
continent, but the Europeanization of soccer has continued to
gather speed and Europe's influence arguably has never been so
complete since the English began exporting the game via their
colonies in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The best Africans play in Europe, and increasingly they are also
educated and trained in Europe, which was why many were expecting
what the French term ``mountains and marvels'' from Nigeria, but
the World Cup is not just an athletic exercise. It is also an
administrative exercise, and multiple coaching changes, financial
squabbles, intramural bickering and political pressure ultimately
could not have helped the Nigerian cause _ a fact striker Victor
Ikpeba readily admitted after his team's convincing loss to Denmark
in the second round. It is telling that of the African teams,
Morocco, which had both coaching continuity and means at its
disposal, came closest to fulfilling its potential in France.
</P>
<P>
   But that is last month's news. This month, it is time to see
which of the perennials will fulfill its potential, and if there
have been disappointingly few surprises until now, that only makes
these predictable quarterfinal matchups more enticing. A look at
Friday's and Saturday's games:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; France vs. Italy, Friday &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Italian coach Cesare Maldini jokingly called this a match
between two Italian teams with a few foreigners thrown in for good
measure. That is because 11 of the 22 French have played or are
still playing in the Italian first division. The most prominent is
Zinedine Zidane, the playmaker for Juventus of Turin who missed
France's last two games because of a red card. He is back in the
lineup, which means that Youri Djorkaeff can stop frenetically
attempting to make something out of nothing and concentrate on
scoring. The French surprisingly have as many goals (10) as the
Brazilians, but they have yet to prove they can score consistently
against the world's finest teams and the probable absence of speedy
and injured striker Thierry Henry won't make a tricky task easier.
</P>
<P>
   On paper and on grass, Italy has a more formidable attack with
the relentlessly opportunistic Christian Vieri and either
Alessandro Del Piero, who has yet to show his full panoply of
tricks in France, or Roberto Baggio. They are backed up by a fine
defense that after a shaky start against Chile has begun to look
very Italian despite losing top goalkeeper Angelo Peruzzi to an
injury before the World Cup and losing defender Alessandro Nesta to
an injury last week. The French defense, led by Lilian Thuram and
Marcel Desailly, is arguably even better, which means that anybody
expecting the first half of Italy-France to resemble the first half
of Argentina-England is a hopeless romantic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Brazil vs. Denmark, Friday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians temporarily silenced their nation's chattering
classes with their 4-1 trouncing of Chile. Since then, there has
been considerable hand- wringing over the state of Ronaldo's left
knee and waistline. The fact that he missed practice on Tuesday
launched a thousand headlines at home, but Ronaldo, who suffers
from recurring tendinitis in the knee, said it would have no effect
on him Friday and that he weighed just as much _ 83.4 kilograms _
as he did at the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Though Brazil-Nigeria would unquestionably have been more fun to
watch in the quarterfinals, the Danes have gotten this far for the
first time for a reason. They were able to capitalize on defensive
errors from Nigeria and put their experience to good use _ the
Danish team's average age of 29 is second only to the Germans.
Veteran goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel should get ample opportunity to
display his talents against Brazil. But it is much less certain
that the Laudrup brothers and Peter Moller will give Brazilian
goalkeeper Taffarel the same chance to shine: even with Brazil's
uneven central defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Netherlands vs. Argentina, Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Potentially the most spectacular of the quarterfinals, and the
second straight match for Argentina in which they have history on
their side. The Argentines already had beaten the English in the
1986 World Cup, and they defeated the Dutch in the 1978 final in
Buenos Aires. They have not played each other again in a World Cup
until now. Both teams have multiple strengths and world-class
strikers: Gabriel Batistuta for Argentina and Dennis Bergkamp for
the Netherlands. Bergkamp is more versatile: a player capable of
creating his own chances while Batistuta is more adept at seizing
those presented to him. While the Argentinians rely on a playmaker,
Ariel Ortega, the Dutch have a less predictable attacking flow.
Unfortunately for them, they also have been less predictable on
defense, surrendering a very late goal to Mexico. The Argentine
defense _ Michael Owen's unforgettable run excepted _ have been
exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Germany vs. Croatia, Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These are the first World Cup finals for Croatia, but this is
already a rivalry because the Germans defeated the Croatians 2-1 in
the quarterfinals of the 1996 European Championships. The Germans
went on to win that title, but they have yet to play like World Cup
favorites in France. What they have done is play like Germans late
in the second half: rallying to draw with Yugoslavia in group play
and to defeat Mexico in the second round. Oliver Bierhoff has used
his head superbly, but the problem has been the transition from
defense to offense: a role Andreas Moller plays quite well for his
club Borussia Dortmund but not nearly as well for his nation.
Goalkeeper Andreas Kopke also has looked shaky, but the oldest man
on the oldest team, 37-year-old Lothar Mathaus, has been a rock. If
Germany is to improve on its disappointing 1994 World Cup, when it
lost in the quarterfinals, it will need to be more precise against
an emotional team with an in-form striker: Davor Suker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
