<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY MEAT IN HOT DOGS? MYSTERY SOLVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With July Fourth, fireworks, watermelon and overeating on the
calendar, the National Hot Dog and Sausage Council has mounted a
campaign to clean up the image of its food.
</P>
<P>
   July is National Hot Dog Month.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the council believes there really isn't anything to
clean up, other than a few misconceptions. It would like, for
instance, for people to stop saying that hot dogs are made of beef,
pork, chicken, turkey and mysterious miscellaneous body parts.
</P>
<P>
   It's just not so, the council says. ``In fact, hot dogs are made
from the same fresh meat and poultry in the grocer's case,'' it
says. ``When variety meats like hearts are used to make hot dogs,
the package clearly states `with variety meats.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That should make us feel better. Apparently, the labeling would
also cover tongues, livers, gizzards, combs and feathers.
</P>
<P>
   To make wieners, the council explains, the meats are chopped in
a gigantic chopping bowl and blended with ice chips, spices, salt
and curing ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the glop is forced through a funnel into a casing of some
sort, smoked, then packaged in neat little rows. Those rows should
never equal the number of buns in a package.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, I never doubted the purity of hot dogs. I never cared.
I've heard all those stories about missing gangsters and lost pets,
but I figured that was covered under ``spices.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times when you just want a hot dog. Some people have
to have their tripe, some long for their menudo, some crave their
headcheese.
</P>
<P>
   I once heard a Cajun friend denounce his own father because the
man stopped putting liver in his boudin.
</P>
<P>
   I don't worry much about what's in my hot dog, as long there's
mustard and onions to go on top.
</P>
<P>
   Which, by the way, brings on another revelation.
</P>
<P>
   What you put on your hot dog appears to be regional. The council
says Chicago dogs are served with yellow mustard, dark green
relish, chopped raw onion and tomato slices and topped with a dash
of celery salt on a poppy seed bun.
</P>
<P>
   New York City dogs are served with steamed onions and a pale
yellow mustard sauce; Southerners eat ``Slaw dogs'' topped with
coleslaw.
</P>
<P>
   The council claims Kansas City dogs are served with sauerkraut
and melted Swiss cheese on a sesame seed bun. I grew up in Kansas
City, and I don't remember Swiss cheese on anything. I never saw a
sesame seed hot dog bun.
</P>
<P>
   Easterners, by the way, eat more all-beef hot dogs than people
in any other region; Westerners eat more poultry dogs. Or so says
the council.
</P>
<P>
   The hot dog probably started out as a frankfurter back in
Frankfurt, Germany. Some say it was created as a sausage there in
1652. They were advanced in the United States around 1904, the
council says, when a concessionaire at the Louisiana Purchase
Exposition sold them as plain sausages.
</P>
<P>
   To help his customers eat them, he supplied white gloves, but at
the end of the day, he was out of gloves. He then quickly consulted
a baker, who came up with buns to protect the fingers of the
eaters.
</P>
<P>
   Another story claims that wieners got their name back in 1901,
when concessionaires sold their ``dachshund sausages'' from hot
water tanks on the New York Polo Ground, shouting: ``They're red
hot! Get your dachshund sausages while they are red hot!''
</P>
<P>
   And they wonder how rumors get started?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, a cartoonist sketched the vendors selling their sausages
and since he didn't know how to spell dachshund, he simply wrote
beneath his sketch, ``Hot Dog!''
</P>
<P>
   There is an etiquette to eating hot dogs, the council explains.
You should never put toppings between the hot dog and the bun.
Always ``dress the dog,'' not the bun.
</P>
<P>
   Never, never use cloth napkins; always paper. Paper plates are
best as well. Don't take more than five bites to finish a hot dog.
For a foot-long wiener, seven is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been invited to a hot dog cookout, never bring wine,
don't put ketchup on your dog if you're older than 18, and for
crying out loud, don't send a thank you note.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a food column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Write him at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
