 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Xxxxday, Xxx. xx. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Shanghai) _ President Clinton, in his last
address to a mass audience in China, said Wednesday that he would
continue to speak out on behalf of democracy and individual
liberty, but that the United States did not seek to dictate to
China the path of its development. In an interview with China's
main government-run television network, Clinton said that China's
current course of economic liberalization and greater personal
freedom is ``morally right,'' and that the status of the United
States as the world's lone superpower did not give it the right to
use its economic and military right to impose its values on China
or any other nation. The interview with China Central Television is
to be broadcast on Thursday. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-KHATAMI (Tehran, Iran) _ President Mohammed Khatami of Iran
Wednesday lauded the Clinton administration for softening its
rhetoric toward his country, but added that a concrete change in
American policy toward Iran was necessary. Until now, Khatami had
made no public comment either on a speech by Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright last month in which she called on Iran to
help create a ``road map'' to normal relations between the two
countries or on the conciliatory words by President Clinton that
followed. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   STARR-HUBBELL (Washington) _ In a blow to Whitewater
prosecutors, a federal judge today dismissed the tax evasion case
against former Justice Department official and presidential friend
Webster Hubbell. U.S. District Judge James Robertson said a Hubbell
motion seeking dismissal ``will be granted.'' By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-ELDERLY (Cedar Rapids, Iowa) For Milford Hartz, the
adrenaline started to flow right about the time that the
teal-colored deluxe motor coach bus pulled into the parking lot in
front of the Wal-Mart store, located right behind the Royal Fork
Buffet restaurant. It was 8:30 a.m. and the bus was soon loaded
with over 30 elderly adults, most of whom had spent a lifetime of
early morning hours toiling on the surrounding farms and in nearby
factories. With hundreds of casinos scattered throughout 26 states,
and a growing population of seniors looking for places where they
can socialize, find companionship and be a part of something that
is lively and new, casino gambling has become a favorite pastime
for older Americans. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-ELECT-ASSESS (Montgomery, Ala.) _ As a battle for the soul
of Southern Republicanism, the Alabama primary that Gov. Fob James
Jr. won so convincingly on Tuesday reinforced a number of political
truths about the party and the region. Religious conservatives
still wield immense influence. Strong stands against taxes still
sell. Race still matters. And even as Southerners take a leading
role in national politics, they still resent federal intrusion.
Each of those factors played a role in James's surprisingly
conclusive victory over Winton Blount 3d, a Montgomery businessman,
in their hard-fought primary runoff. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CT-TOBACCO (Hartford, Conn.) _ The state of Connecticut asked a
state judge to freeze more than $10 billion in tobacco company
assets and to hold an immediate trial on the state's claim the
companies violated antitrust laws. By Jonathan Rabinovitz.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The nation's manufacturers are slowing
production, the clearest impact so far of the Asian crisis on the
American economy. Exporters in particular are hurt. The Jefferson
Smurfit Corp., which makes the ingredients of corrugated shipping
boxes, shut a big mill in Jacksonville, Fla., for 40 days because
of slumping exports to Asia. The production slowdown may help
explain why the Federal Reserve chose yesterday at its latest
policy meeting to leave interest unchanged, although labor
shortages and robust economic growth in recent months have
suggested in some quarters that the Fed should raise rates to slow
the economy and prevent a higher inflation rate. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
</TEXT>
