<HEADER>
A6235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROOKLYN-ROWHOUSE-ART     07-01 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-ROWHOUSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LONG ROAD HOME TO A HOUSE FULL OF MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Laurie Miller said goodbye to the narrow house
on Quincy Street, there was still a pull chain attached to the
wooden toilet tank up near the ceiling. There was still a claw foot
bathtub. The boiler didn't always work.
</P>
<P>
   It was home, though, and had been since she was 10 years old,
when she often ran the five blocks to the previous owner's house
with the mortgage payments, grabbing a hastily drawn receipt for
the cash her mother had handed her.
</P>
<P>
   But her mother, a nurse, had died of cervical cancer at 51, and
the house, in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, was
foreclosed upon. Laurie Miller and her siblings, all in their early
20s, had to move out. That was in 1981. ``We just kind of went our
separate ways,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, that would have been the end of it. The old row
house would have been bought, sold and maybe bought again, its
fortunes dependent on the whims of strangers. But Ms. Miller is no
ordinary woman. And for close to two decades, in her travels around
the city, she kept her eye on Quincy Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mom died, I had had my own daughter, and she was,
like, 2 years old,'' said Ms. Miller, who is now 37. ``I went on
public assistance, and I found a cheap apartment out in East
Flatbush near my cousin. Then I was just apartment hunting every
year to find a new place.
</P>
<P>
   ``On May 13, 1985 _ they called and told me on Mother's Day _ I
was laid off my job as a veterinary assistant,'' she said.
``There's been a lot of ups and downs,'' she concluded, her voice
trailing off.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, while visiting childhood friends, Ms. Miller
learned that there were vacant apartments in a city-owned building
on the same block of Quincy Street where her mother's old house
was, between Nostrand and Marcy Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I squatted in a back apartment in that building,'' she said.
When the housing department found out, they ordered her out. But
Ms. Miller visited the city officials and wound up renting the
apartment for $227 a month. She ended up staying there 12 years,
giving birth to a son, Anderson, who is now 7. Her daughter, Adina,
is about to turn 19.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Miller's fortunes improved, she watched her mother's
little beige and chocolate-brown house, hoping she could someday
get it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the changes it was going through,'' she recalled. ``When
the original owner passed away, the house was taken by the city. A
lot of drugs were brought to the block and then sold out of the
house. There were fires, negative stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the building was stoppered with cinder blocks. Three
years later, Ms. Miller got up the courage to start asking
questions. Eventually, she tracked down an office of the New York
City Department of Housing Preservation and Development; workers
there told her to call the Enterprise Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Enterprise is a nonprofit group that buys derelict houses from
the city, then selects architects and contractors to fix them up
and, eventually, sells them. The money for construction comes from
a consortium of banks that lends in distressed areas. The
difference between the development costs and the market value of
the house is picked up by the city. The new owner moves into a
totally rehabilitated home, with unglamorous but workable kitchens
and tiled baths. The program is called City Homes.
</P>
<P>
   The group told Ms. Miller that, yes, the Quincy Street house was
scheduled for reconstruction but that the project wouldn't get off
the ground until the next year. To her dismay, they merely took her
name and told her they'd be in touch. She didn't expect much.
</P>
<P>
   A year later almost to the day, they sent her an application.
``I sent them a $50 money order, the application fee, and I
waited,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, City Homes houses _ because they include a
Sheetrock-to-the-rafters renovation _ are in great demand. In a
lottery to choose buyers for 21 houses, Ms. Miller drew No. 22.
Others opted out, though, or were disqualified after credit checks.
When her own credit was checked, there were student-loan payments
outstanding, and an old gas bill. She paid them off.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1996, she signed a contract to buy the house. That was
when her long-lost father showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad called and wanted to move in with me in the place down
the block,'' she said. ``He was elderly. He'd retired from the
Transit Authority and had moved to Florida. I made the living room
into a bedroom, and he moved in with us.''
</P>
<P>
   He was doing all right, Ms. Miller said, ``but then he died, and
he didn't have any money.'' Mr. Miller, it turned out, was a
frequent patron of the Offtrack Betting office. ``I mean, I knew,''
Ms. Miller said, noting that he bet only his own money.
</P>
<P>
   But the funeral cost $5,000, and there went her down payment for
the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had followed that house,'' she said, rocking side to side,
remembering how tough things looked back then. ``I saw it when it
was gutted, the roof to the basement. I saw when they brought the
new beams in. I saw when they put in the staircase and the room
dividers. I saw it come together.''
</P>
<P>
   She was desolate. She called the City Homes directors to
persuade them to give her time to save the money she needed. After
all, she pointed out, she had a good job now: a branch manager for
New York City Partnership, another nonprofit housing program. She
was also working toward her college degree.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the City Homes directors agreed to stop work on the
Quincy Street house and turn their efforts to the 20 other houses
they were rehabilitating. This March, she bought the house _ and
brought her pastor over to bless it.
</P>
<P>
   On an early summer's day, the block is full of friends, old and
new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Will,'' she called, as she ran out of the house to move
her big red '78 Chevrolet sedan. ``Taking the day off?'' She
chuckled and jumped into the car. (``It's sturdy and it runs,'' she
said.)
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the house, Ms. Miller conducted a tour of the six
rooms she and her family live in: the first-floor living room and
kitchen; the second-floor front bedroom for her daughter and a
family room with a sports-bar-size television, and the top floor
for her and her son.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The City Homes program allows low- and moderate-income men and
women to buy row houses in neighborhoods all over the city. It
starts with an abandoned house that has been taken over by the
city, usually for nonpayment of taxes. The house is bought for $1
by a local subsidiary of the Enterprise Foundation, a national
nonprofit housing group. Enterprise, with backing from banks and
the city, renovates the house, then oversees the choice of a new
owner. The owner pays the market value of the house; the city picks
up any extra renovation costs.
</P>
<P>
   LOCATIONS : Hundreds of houses are scheduled for renovation in
East Harlem and Washington Heights in Manhattan; in Morrisania and
Crotona Park in the South Bronx, and in Bedford-Stuyvesant,
Saratoga Square, East New York, Oceanhill-Brownsville and Bushwick
in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   INCOME LIMITS : An applicant's combined household income cannot
be more than $70,900 a year, before taxes.
</P>
<P>
   MORTGAGES : Participating banks offer below-market interest
rates. For more information: (212) 262-9575, ext. 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
