<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-RENTAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMERING AGAIN AT HOTEL MOM AND DAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SOLOMON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm thinking of renting a summer house. Actually, I've been
thinking of renting a summer house for about 20 years now, and I
can't say that I have made enormous progress. The problem is that
every time I say to myself, ``You must rent a summer house this
year,'' my palms grow sweaty and I am overcome with a desire to lie
down.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains why I happen to spend my summer weekends
at Hotel Mom and Dad. Here's a place that is so exclusive it's not
listed in any guidebook and only I can get in. On weekends I ride
from Manhattan's Grand Central Terminal up to the suburbs, to
Scarsdale, N.Y., where my parents live in a white-shingled house
that I've come to think of as my country place _ my home not far
enough away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the joys of summer! Swimming, sunning, barbecues . . .
regression.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is the season when I rediscover my vanished adolescence,
a delicate and complicated process requiring me to lie on a lounge
chair on my parents' patio and feign deafness as they recount the
times I used their Jeep and forgot to pull down the garage door. My
parents harbor a morbid fear of strangers seeing into their garage.
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, who could blame them for feeling overextended?
I arrive accompanied by my own brood: my husband and two young
sons, whose idea of a summer sport consists of consuming
frozen-yogurt pops at 30-minute intervals and dripping them on the
kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   My mother is a stylish, dark-haired woman _ in my youth I
secretly believed she was Jackie Kennedy, slipping off to the White
House after dropping me at school _ but these days she seems a
little frazzled. On weekends, she mops until she drops, while my
father takes refuge in the den, sitting with the lights off and
watching the original, 1933 version of ``King Kong,'' a movie shown
on television in the area with a mysterious round-the-clock
frequency.
</P>
<P>
   How old am I? And what am I doing here? Maybe it's just a matter
of economics. It's nice to escape the city on weekends, and staying
at my parents' house is relatively cost efficient (namely, free).
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the laziness factor. It takes effort to set up
a home, and why should I bother when my parents' manse comes
equipped with a staff of two to run the household according to my
own impeccable standards? There's mom to do the laundry and lug
oversize jugs of Diet Coke home from the supermarket. There's dad
to take the Jeep to the car wash and fill up the tank.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, the social life at my parents' house is not
exactly glittering. Truth be told, the opportunities for celebrity
sightings are slim. Henry Kissinger or Donna Karan have yet to drop
by for a backyard barbecue, though I wonder if they realize how
much fun they are missing. I can't begin to count the times my
father has held us spellbound over dinner with his musings _ on
``King Kong,'' for instance.
</P>
<P>
   My mother is full of fascinating stories, all of them concerning
new strains of food-borne bacteria. First it was hamburgers. Now
it's lettuce. ``You can't wash the lettuce too carefully,'' she
likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I myself can claim to have contributed a wealth of mots
to mealtime conversations. One advantage of summering with your
parents is that you need not be on good-guest behavior. This
includes not having to prove one's skill at conversation. Astute
observations? Witty repartee? Not at our house!
</P>
<P>
   Am I proud of this situation? Hardly. On the other hand, it
gives me great comfort to know that I am by no means the only
Manhattanite over the age of 22 to summer chez mom and dad. Many of
my friends and acquaintances happen to do the same thing. This
means either that a) it's a trend or b) I deliberately form
friendships with people who summer at their parents' house because
it lessens my feelings of deviancy.
</P>
<P>
   Take my friend Daphne Merkin, an author and movie critic. She
leads a sophisticated, big-city sort of life _ film screenings,
parties and all that, not to mention those excitement-packed
weekends at her parents' place in Atlantic Beach, N.Y. As she says,
``On weekends I lie in the sun and think, `Ugh, I'm back where I
started.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the novelist Cathleen Schine, who has few rivals as
a daughter-cum-guest. The shocking truth is that she and her
children descend on her mother's house in Westport, Conn., not just
for weekends, but for the entire summer. ``It's sort of my last
stand as a child,'' she explains. ``My mother tells me to make my
bed, and when I go out she asks where I'm going. And I'm almost
50!''
</P>
<P>
   In hope of gaining some professional insight into this
situation, I contacted Carolyn Douglas, a 44-year-old psychiatrist
and associate professor at Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she's a model of autonomy; she, her husband and their
children spend their weekends at her mother's place in
Bridgehampton.
</P>
<P>
   Why do people do it? ``The motivations range from strictly
practical considerations,'' she said, ``to more complex issues of
separation anxiety on the child's part _ children may have guilt
about leaving behind their parents _ or dependency issues on the
part of the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. That's pretty Freudian. Can't one just say that summering
at one's parents' house represents a celebration of family
togetherness?
</P>
<P>
   It certainly does at our place. Thanks to my visits, my parents
have the chance to slip back to a time when they were slimmer and
brisker and their children's less attractive behavior _ tying up
the phone, smoking pot, blasting Carole King records _ led them to
wonder how they raised such Neanderthals. My weekend visits allow
my parents to relive those precious moments. It keeps them young.
</P>
<P>
   It also enables them to pretend that their eldest daughter is in
need of their guidance. Recently, for instance, I was in the
kitchen snacking on salt-free potato chips when my mother
interrupted her mopping and joined me at the table. I prepared
myself for a poignant heart-to-heart, but my mother just stared at
my nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are those new glasses?'' she wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' I said, ``I really like them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' she replied, looking pained. ``I think I like your old
glasses better.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what you get for going home: constructive or
not-so-constructive maternal criticism. But am I complaining? Not
at all.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, I suspect that somewhere deep in my freeloading
soul floats a hidden, sentimental truth, one having to do with a
desire to linger with my parents, to keep our lives forever
entwined. Who's to say where mooching leaves off and love begins?
</P>
<P>
   Or so I wondered on a recent Sunday, sitting at the patio table
as my parents busily got dinner ready. It was one of those rare,
golden, picture-perfect moments. Dad was tending to the barbecue,
his shirt drenched in a Niagara of sweat, as Mom ferried a 10-ton
tray laden with plates, wineglasses and silverware to the table.
Watching them, I was overcome with a sense of good fortune. I
decided that for once I would do the adult thing: I would thank my
parents _ my hosts par excellence _ for their years of unstinting
hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   When they sat down at the table, I gazed at them tenderly and
prepared to deliver my toast. But before I got the chance, my
mother turned to me and said, ``Your hair could use a trim.''
</P>
<P>
   My father piped in, ``Maybe she just needs to comb it.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, I swear, I'm renting a summer house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
