<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6249 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      07-01 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TEST SHOWS CALIFORNIA STUDENTS BELOW NATIONAL AVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE and ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California public school children scored below
the national average in reading, math and science and lagged far
behind in spelling, according to results of a new statewide exam.
</P>
<P>
   Students in all grades managed to exceed national averages in
only 12 of 43 grade-and-subject combinations, according to results
released Tuesday by the state Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   In writing, students scored above the national average in grades
2 and 4 through 9.
</P>
<P>
   The scores, of nearly 3 million English-fluent students in
grades 2 through 11, offer the first look at student performance
since 1994 and compare most of California's students to their peers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a judge's order last week, the state was prohibited
from releasing the Statewide Testing and Reporting Program scores
of 1 million students classified as having limited English skills.
</P>
<P>
   The scores, neither utterly grim nor uplifting, confirm a
nagging perception that California _ one of the wealthiest and most
innovative states in the country _ is doing a mediocre job of
teaching its children.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pete Wilson said the ``disappointing but not surprising''
scores were the byproduct of years of failed attempts at reforms,
coupled with weak policies on promoting failing students and
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 43 (grade and subject levels) reporting and only 12
reporting scores at or above the national average, that means that
more than two-thirds of California's grade-level performance is
below the national average, and that is clearly not acceptable,''
the Republican governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Delaine Eastin, the superintendent of public instruction, put a
more positive spin on the results, saying they were better than
``the doomsayers predicted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For those crepe hangers who thought today would be a day of
sackcloth and ashes, I would just say today is the day when we
began to move ahead in California,'' Eastin said. ``Yes, we can do
a lot better, but please give us the resources to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastin said the scores showed California schools were doing a
better job of educating children than in 1994 and 1996, when the
state's students ranked among the lowest of the low on the National
Assessment of Educational Progress, given every two years to a
sampling of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're within striking distance'' of the national average,
Eastin said. ``Given the fact that we were dead last in NAEP when I
came to office ... that we were at the bottom in so many of the
indicators of student achievement, these results are much better
than anyone would have a right to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest areas by grade were 11th-grade social studies,
where students ranked in the 61st percentile, and in writing, where
seventh-graders ranked in the 57th percentile. In writing, students
exceeded national averages in seven of 10 grades tested.
</P>
<P>
   California students did the worst in 10th-grade reading, where
California ranked in the 36th percentile, and eighth-grade
spelling, where students were in the 38th percentile.
</P>
<P>
   On that scale, 99 is best, 1 is worst and 50 is the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   Eastin said poor showing in spelling stemmed from an era in
which the state was experimenting with educational fads. The state
has adopted a more back-to-basics approach, with an emphasis on
phonics.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson signed the testing mandate into law in October 1997,
requiring that all students _ regardless of language ability _ take
the English-only exam. Students in grades 2 through 8 are tested in
reading, writing, spelling and math. Students in grades 9 through
11 are tested in reading, math, writing, science and social
sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and the state Board of Education believe the test is
useful as a benchmark for future comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson assailed legal challenges against the test brought by
school districts in Berkeley, Oakland and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This test is providing us with a baseline from which we can in
the future measure progress or lack of progress and make necessary
changes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
