<HEADER>
A6272 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HEART-MONITORS-AR     07-01 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HEART-MONITORS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING THE HEART TO TRAIN THE BODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By ALEX FRANKEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask fitness buffs how they know just how hard to push it, and
you're likely to hear about the doneburn in the muscles or the
feeling of being spent. Rebecca Ray will furnish you a flow chart
full of numbers and optimal training zones.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Ms. Ray, 31, was 30 pounds overweight and at a
crossroads. In an effort to lose weight, she started working out at
the San Francisco YMCA's Embarcadero health club up to five times a
week, but she found little success and thought she was wasting her
time.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Ms. Ray says, she started working with a wireless heart
monitor, and earlier this month she competed in Northern
California's Vineman Triathlon, her fifth such event.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ray, a graduate student in research psychology at San
Francisco State University, has also dropped 20 pounds. She learned
how to use a heart-rate monitor from Mischa Kubancik, a trainer at
the YMCA, and she subsequently joined a triathlon training squad
coached by Ms. Kubancik.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ray says one of her greatest problems in getting fit was her
inability to regulate herself. ``Some people might know their
bodies well, but I don't,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Heart-rate monitors are an increasingly popular tool and a part
of a nationwide boom in fitness-equipment sales, which reached $3
billion last year. In 1998 heart-rate monitor sales in the United
States will top $40 million, up 15 percent from 1997, says Corey
Cornacchio, director of marketing at Polar Electro, a company that
claims 80 percent of the worldwide market.
</P>
<P>
   These monitors are a step up from simple wrist or finger pulse
meters. They use a transmitter equipped with electrodes strapped to
the chest to record the heart's electrical impulses and radio
precise measurements of the heart rate to a receiver worn on the
wrist. Using this basic information _ how many times a heart beats
each minute _ trainers or exercisers themselves can structure
productive routines and workouts.
</P>
<P>
   For someone like Ms. Ray, this means that she can train in
various heart-rate zones to achieve various results, like improving
cardiovascular fitness, strengthening, increasing endurance or
losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing to regulate, and the most powerful way to
improve fitness, is intensity,'' says Dr. Carl Foster, director of
clinical physiology at the Milwaukee Heart Institute and director
of sport science for United States Speedskating, the national
governing body for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Heart-rate monitors provide feedback about what is really
happening to an exercise participant; consequently there is less
chance that a workout will be too easy or too hard _ what some call
junk workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Heart-rate monitors are the best means to proper exercise,
according to a growing number of exercise physiologists, coaches
and personal trainers. Perhaps the most ardent supporter is Sally
Edwards, a 15-time Ironman triathlon competitor who first began
using the device in 1984 during Olympic running trials.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards calls the monitors ``windows to the heart'' that can
unite mind and body. She says they are being used in stress
management, psychotherapy and cardiac rehabilitation, as well as
sports.
</P>
<P>
   But most people who use the monitors are recreational athletes,
people who might be training for a first marathon. This is a group
that Foster calls ``aging yuppies who have resources, are
technologically literate and like to do things that they can do
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   The monitors range from basic models that simply provide a
continuous readout to more complex mechanisms that store times
spent in various zones and can download data to a PC.
</P>
<P>
   To use the monitor effectively you have to spend some time
understanding the features and commands and then learning how to
interpret data and alter behavior. But with a little work and some
patience you can use a monitor to remake yourself into a living
science experiment.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to the American College of Sports Medicine, the heart
rate training zone is calculated by subtracting your age from 220
to find a maximum heart rate. Moderate-intensity training is done
at 60 percent to 80 percent of this maximum figure. For example, if
you are healthy and 35 years old, your training zone is between 111
and 148 beats per minute.
</P>
<P>
   But this way of calculating maximum heart rate is seen by many
in the field as imperfect. Foster says these rates are rough
estimates, not exact for all people or all sports. Many experts
recommend consulting a doctor before undertaking any new exercise
regimen. Also, determining which zones to train in depends on your
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless heart-rate monitor was developed in 1983 by Seppo
Saynajakangas, a Finnish researcher who recognized the importance
of measuring heart rate during exercise. He had started Polar
Electro in Finland in 1977, in an effort to improve the standard
pulse measurement done with the fingertips and to create an
ambulatory device. In 1986 Polar introduced its first consumer
device.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a heart-rate monitor has dropped from a high of
$500 to $59 for basic models, and the user base has swelled as a
result. According to Polar, there are over three million of the
monitors in use in the United States. Health clubs and gyms are
increasingly using them to train members.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kevin Steele, the vice president of health services
and education at the 180-club, 1.5-million-member 24 Hour Fitness
clubs, about 40 percent of the clubs' members use heart-rate
monitoring, both transmitters and devices that are built into
exercise equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Jackson, a head trainer at a San Francisco Bay area Club
One gym, designated last May as healthy heart month. During the
month more than 100 members began to use heart-rate monitors and
recorded the time they spent in their target training zones.
Jackson says a monitor helps him assess how hard a member is
working. ``It is much clearer than perceived exertion,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And many people who use heart-rate monitors gain a new level of
self understanding. ``Some people need to feel totally spent at the
end of the workout, as if they were hit by a bus,'' says Ms.
Kubancik, the YMCA trainer. ``That is not the best way to use
fitness.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a Heart Rate Monitor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are four levels of heart-rate monitors, according to Sally
Edwards, an author and 15-time Ironman triathlon competitor. The
simplest models, which cost less than $100, are the easiest to
operate. They display only the heart rate in beats per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Devices at the next level, which cost up to $120, include time
functions and can also be programmed to note specific target zones
and beep when a user falls out of the zone. At the third level, as
much as $200, monitors include a memory function and can provide
extensive feedback, like average heart rate and time spent in,
above and below a target zone.
</P>
<P>
   Some models can calculate calories burned. The fourth-level
models, above $200, allow data to be transferred to a PC, where the
information can be analyzed and stored. Software and interfaces are
sold separately.
</P>
<P>
   The following mid-range heart-rate monitors have basic watch
functions and include a chest transmitter and a wrist receiver.
</P>
<P>
   FREESTYLE CIRCUIT 5 By Sports Instruments, $149. This has a
light and memory, and can register upper and lower ranges. The
display is easy to read and the buttons are large. Information:
(800) 949-1563.
</P>
<P>
   POLAR SMART EDGE Polar Electro, $199. This model includes a
calorie-counting function in addition to upper- and lower-limit
alarms and extensive memory functions. (800) 227-1314.
</P>
<P>
   SENSOR DYNAMICS PRO SPORT 2 $119. Has target zone settings with
audio and visual alarms and dual display. (800) 764-4327.
</P>
<P>
   PRECISE ACUMEN 330 Precise International, $159. Includes target
heart rate memory functions. (800) 431-2996.
</P>
<P>
   CARDIO SPORT ZONEROBIC $129. Several preset target zones can be
selected. (888) 760-3059.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
