<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-SEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL BREAD CRUMBS THROUGH THE FOREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a long time, I thought that it was my fault that I could
never find the information I wanted on the Web. My search method _
typing one or two words hastily into a query box _ rarely yielded
worthwhile results.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine my relief to learn that my approach is typical. A
recently published study of 1 million queries conducted in a single
day in 1997 on the Excite search site found that only one in nine
users embrace the nuances of Boolean logic to concoct sophisticated
queries. The rest of us ``are basically entering one or two search
terms in the query box,'' said Amanda Spink, one of the study's
authors and an assistant professor in the School of Library and
Information Sciences at the University of North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no evidence that users can be persuaded to
change, search sites have begun to mold their tools to fit our
habits. The challenge is to improve the search results even if
users do not improve their search techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The Excite search site has been the most innovative so far,
taking the first steps toward what Chris Charron, an analyst at
Forrester Research, describes as ``adding real intelligence to the
search function.''
</P>
<P>
   What Excite (www.excite.com) has done is try to guess what a
user is seeking _ the specific bit of information the user wants to
know even when typing a general query _ and then to use that
assumption as a starting point for search results.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how it works: If you type a single keyword in the query
box on the Excite home page _ try ``orioles,'' for example _ you
will see that Excite's staff has made the assumption (based on
users' past patterns) that you want information about the Baltimore
Orioles baseball team. The search results will be about the team
but will not be limited to relevant Web pages from Excite's index.
You will also get information culled from other databases _
including those of current publications, for example _ giving you
game scores, the team's schedule and recent news articles. All that
information will appear on the first screen of the search results.
</P>
<P>
   Excite's co-founder Joe Kraus describes this approach as
creating ``channels'' of information. It also takes into
consideration the fact that some users who type ``orioles'' will
not be looking for information about the sports team. For them, the
search results page displays a prominent link to sites relevant to
other meanings of the word.
</P>
<P>
   Excite has organized information about public companies into
channels, as well. So if you type ``Microsoft'' in the query box,
the search results will display the information that past users
have sought most frequently: the company's phone number and
address, as well as recent news articles, culled from 350
publications, and the stock price (updated every 20 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   When I tried out Excite's system, searching suddenly seemed fun.
Not since the long-ago day when I finally mastered the intricacies
of the Dewey Decimal System had I felt so empowered by the giddy
knowledge that vast troves of valuable facts were mine for the
asking. I felt, for a moment, as if the Web could live up to the
so-far-mythical promise of organizing the world's information in a
coherent and accessible fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Here was proof of the value of such a dynamic medium, where
facts are in flux _ things like sports scores and stock prices
change from minute to minute _ and the latest bits of data are just
a click away.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to get spoiled, but reality brought me up short. It
turns out that Excite has so far organized only a fraction of its
available information into channels. So if you are searching for
something other than information about a sports team or a public
company, no channels for you. Back to the old search results, lists
of Web sites that might or might not be relevant to the query.
</P>
<P>
   That frustrated me at first. Why was Excite discriminating
against users who wanted to search for ``applesauce recipes'' or
``Chesapeake Bay retrievers''? Were we not entitled to, say, the
most recent articles published on those topics?
</P>
<P>
   But Kraus calmed me with the news that Excite will expand the
scope of its intelligent search function, with plans in the next
few months to create a number of other channels on topics like
health, cities and celebrities. These channels are likely to appeal
to a broad cross-section of users; Ms. Spink's analysis found that
users often searched for information about a specific person or
place.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it is impossible to organize all information into
channels, Kraus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to know something very specific _ say, the effects
of sleep deprivation on heart disease in men on the East Coast _ we
won't ever be able to program a channel to answer that query,'' he
said. ``That's what we call a needle-in-a-haystack query.''
</P>
<P>
   To increase the success rate for those kinds of searches, some
sites have borrowed a technique that off-line information retrieval
systems have been using for decades: improving the relevance of
search results.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek (www.infoseek.com), for instance, determined from
search patterns that when most users searched for ``airlines,''
they wanted search results that included the home pages of major
airlines. So search results now include those pages.
</P>
<P>
   Another search site, Cnet's Snap (www.snap.com), uses a recipe
for finding relevant results to make searches more successful. When
a user types a keyword query, the site's software automatically
assesses the potential relevance of all the sites in its index,
assigning a weight to each site's Web address, description and
content, then using those weights to rank sites.
</P>
<P>
   To supplement its method, Snap has human editors assign keywords
to specific documents to give them added weight. ``We can quickly
improve relevancy by responding to seasonal trends, news and
current events,'' said Katharine English, the site's executive
producer.
</P>
<P>
   How relevant are the results? In my own unscientific
experiments, I conducted searches on both sites to try to answer my
7-year-old daughter's question about the average life span of a
house cat, and the results indicated that the technology still has
a long way to go. It took me about 10 minutes of clicking on
unlikely search results to learn that the answer is probably 15
years (according to a source who identified herself only as Cat
Lady in a message she posted on the cat health bulletin board of
Acme Pet).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the search results suggested that I might also find
the answer at a link called ``Stupid (threatened) Snakes Don't
Deserve to Live.'' But at least I no longer think that's my fault.
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address: Slatalla(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
