<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A MONOPOLIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday July 3)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer vacation has begun, which means it's time for the
traditional Grimes family Monopoly tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Call me a sentimentalist, but to me nothing says ``family
values'' like slowly bankrupting a spouse or conning a small child
into a one-sided real estate deal that costs him the game.
</P>
<P>
   The way their little shoulders slump ... the way their lower lip
quivers and their eyes well up with tears ... I don't know, you
just can't put a price on that kind of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for some strange reason, I detected something less than
unbridled joy on the faces of my wife and son when I dragged out
the Monopoly game and began herding them toward the dining room
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing,'' said my wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about it, Dad,'' said the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it had something to do with last year's tournament,
which I won thanks to a cagey investment strategy and a shrewd real
estate deal where I promised the boy he could go without brushing
his teeth for a week if he would trade me Park Place for Oriental
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   That lost him the game, of course, plus I made him brush his
teeth twice as often for making such a dumb trade. Boy, I'll tell
you, parenting doesn't get any better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game chatter'' is a big part of Monopoly's appeal and is
certainly what brings us closest together as a family. When, for
example, an opponent lands on a property you own, such as Illinois
Avenue, the correct way to call for the rent is to shout, ``THAT'S
MINE!! That'll be $20, lady, and I want it NOW!!''
</P>
<P>
   This tells everyone that you are a real ``player'' and not
someone to be trifled with or, for that matter, entrusted with
sharp objects.
</P>
<P>
   It is also important to publicize, in as loud a voice as
possible, any financial difficulties your opponents may be having,
such as: ``Whatsamatter, kid? A little light on cash? Tell you
what, I'll give you 30 bucks for Pennsylvania Avenue and I'll even
throw in this Get Out of Jail Free card 'cause I like your face.
Whaddya say? Deal? Huh? Deal? Huh? Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   This is called ``keeping the pressure on'' and it always
succeeds in rattling an opponent, sometimes to the point that he or
she will whip a soft drink bottle at your head, so you've got to
stay alert.
</P>
<P>
   Since the object of Monopoly is to reduce your opponent to a
whimpering, quaking, bankrupt blob of goo, it is important that you
don't get ``soft'' with an opponent just because he or she is a
spouse or a small child who has not yet mastered addition and
subtraction, let alone the finer points of mortgaging.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I know some people who think Monopoly is more
``fun'' if everyone owns a block because then everyone is ``in the
game'' and has a chance to win and yadda yadda ya. This, of course,
is sheer nonsense and the kind of behavior that should draw the
attention of the House Un-American Activities Committee, assuming
such a committee still exists.
</P>
<P>
   To me, the perfect Monopoly game would be me and three
opponents. One opponent would own Mediterranean Avenue, another
would own Vermont Avenue and the third would own St. Charles Place.
I'd own everything else. The reds, the yellows, the greens,
everything. Plus all the railroads and both utilities.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a beautiful thing, the kind of moment you'd like to
share with your family, if they'd only give you a chance.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
