<HEADLINE>
KANSAS WHEAT IS RIPENING AT QUICK PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The wheat harvest is racing across Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Department of Agriculture reported 68 percent of the
harvest complete as of Sunday. A year earlier, the harvest was only
5 percent complete on the same date.
</P>
<P>
   This year's pace is the quickest since 1994, when the harvest
was 86 percent complete by the end of June. An average year would
see the harvest about 28 percent complete by now.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is the leading producer of hard red winter wheat, which
is used for making bread and similar products such as hamburger
buns. Hard red winter wheat is planted in the fall and harvested in
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Hand, an agricultural statistician with the Kansas
Department of Agriculture, said the rapid pace of this year's
harvest was due to hot, dry weather about a month ago that allowed
wheat in many areas to ripen faster than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a cool, wet spring helped wheat plants recover from an
early spring freeze but slowed ripening and delayed the start of
harvest, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent heavy rains in many Kansas wheat areas did not slow down
the harvest as much as had been expected, state officials said.
Much of the land was so dry the ground soaked up the rain and
remained firm for field work.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department has rated 21 percent of the season's
wheat crop as excellent, 53 percent as good and 20 percent fair.
Five percent of the crop was rated poor and 2 percent very poor.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas farmers are expected to harvest 393.9 million bushels of
wheat this year, based on June 1 conditions. The estimate is up
from the 377.4 million estimated as of May 1. The next official
estimate will be July 10 and will be based on conditions as of
today.
</P>
<P>
   This year's projected hard red winter wheat output is down from
last year's record 506 million bushels. Farmers seeded fewer acres
this year to hard red winter wheat compared with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expected lower output, this year's crop still is a
decent one. But with exports down and prices low, many farmers will
be putting their crops into storage.
</P>
<P>
   Many will opt to put their crops under government loan programs,
predicted Kansas farmer Ray Crumbaker, who is president of the
Kansas Association of Wheat Growers.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat can be placed under loan for nine months, during which the
farmer can watch for higher prices, sell the wheat and repay the
loan. If prices do not rise to acceptable levels, the farmer can
choose to forfeit the wheat pledged for the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign demand has slowed in the wake of the Asian economic
crisis. Asia is the second-largest buyer of hard red winter wheat,
after the Middle East, said Doug Ohlemeier, marketing specialist
for the Kansas Wheat Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Because Kansas farmers produce more wheat than can be used
domestically, the export market is vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to help,'' Ohlemeier said of the Asian economic
crisis. ``Asia is an important market.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture recently said U.S. wheat
farmers might forfeit as much as 10 million bushels of wheat to the
government this summer under government price support loans.
</P>
<P>
   Low wheat prices are prompting producers to forfeit stocks for
the first time in several years. Farmers already have forfeited
about 2.5 million bushels of wheat in recent weeks rather than
repay their 1997 loans.
</P>
<P>
   Prices that farmers receive for wheat under loan vary from
county to county and depend on storage rates, among other things.
Currently Kansas farmers are getting between $2.46 and $2.97 a
bushel for wheat under loan, very near current cash prices, said
John Drach, program specialist in Manhattan with the Farm Service
Agency, which helps with government loans. The national average
loan price is $2.58 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   For Kansas farmers, the decision to put wheat under government
loan usually is made in July or August after the harvest is
complete, Crumbaker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By March or April of 1999, there should be some rise in prices
where farmers will be better off selling wheat and paying off the
loan,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
