<HEADLINE>
A WHOLE SUMMER TO SHOW THE COLORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeing red, white and blue this weekend? Take off the
color blinders for the rest of the summer. After the parades pass,
refresh the table with garden settings: new green majolica plates,
silk poppy napkin rings and bright orange and pink napkins. Or with
new reproductions of American classics like a glass hobnail
pitcher. They're perfectly patriotic.
</P>
<P>
   A white Parian ware pitcher called Jonquil is a reproduction of
a mid-19th-century example from Bennington, Vt. The original is in
the American Wing of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Unglazed
Parian ware, highly fired porcelain that looks like marble, has a
matte finish that is nonporous and will not stain or leak. The
pitcher, which is 8{ inches high and holds two quarts, is $38 at
the museum, (800) 662-3397.
</P>
