<HEADLINE>
SUMMER HEAT WAVES DISPLAY NEED FOR MORE POWER GENERATION CAPACITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The story hasn't attracted much mainstream
media attention yet, but if the already hot summer gets hotter, a
prolonged heat wave could underscore a largely unnoticed need for
more power-generation capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas of the Midwest already have been hit with power
interruptions and if shortages spread, an electricity squeeze has
the potential to put a serious damper on economic growth during the
third quarter. The industry's shrinking reserve capacity has been
mostly ignored because it hasn't threatened to hamper normal
activity yet.
</P>
<P>
   One of the constants of economic growth, however, is an
accompanying rise in demand for electric power. The economic
expansion that began in the early '90s entered its eighth year this
spring, and demand for electricity has been rising steadily during
a period when the industry hasn't added appreciably to its
generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as fate would have it, the early signs are pointing to
a hotter-than-usual summer in many parts of the country even as an
unusually large number of nuclear plants have been shut down for
repairs throughout North America.
</P>
<P>
   The good news hereabouts is Kansas City appears to be in
reasonably good shape, for now at least. After Mother Nature turned
up the heat last week, a Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co.
representative said the company currently saw no need to request
usage reductions but would continue to monitor the situation
closely.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of America, though, it's a different story, as
some Midwest factories have been forced to shut down temporarily. A
Ford assembly plant energy manager in Chicago told The Wall Street
Journal after three shutdowns that the utility industry ``seemed
very ill-prepared'' for the recent heat waves.
</P>
<P>
   The story also said New England companies were alerting
customers to the possibility of power shortages and were expecting
possible service interruptions for large industrial customers in
July and August.
</P>
<P>
   If a crisis develops, it will further prove how the blessings of
electrical power are too much taken for granted. Utilities
regularly advise that more capacity will be needed, but consumers
and their regulatory watchdogs usually pooh-pooh such warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuffs are effective because the cost of new generating
capacity must be factored into the rate base to finance the
investment. Neither residential nor corporate customers are eager
to pay for something not immediately needed, so construction is put
off until the crunch comes.
</P>
<P>
   This time, The Wall Street Journal reported, any significant
shortfall is likely to be exacerbated by inadequate investment in
transmission lines in recent years. This is hindering the
industry's ability to transmit power from surplus areas to
power-short areas.
</P>
<P>
   Those with surpluses, however, are reaping big rewards.
Companies with power to spare reportedly have received as much as
$7,000 per megawatt hour, compared to the usual $50 to $100 cost
during normal summer conditions.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, of course, that Americans will luck out. The
early hot spell may moderate and life may go on without much
hot-weather hassle for individuals and corporations alike.
</P>
<P>
   If Americans do dodge a bullet, however, it still won't
eliminate the need to be mindful of how prosperity fuels demand for
electricity and that prosperity isn't sustainable without adequate
supplies of power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
