<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT DEMONSTRATES THAT IT IS A DYNAMIC FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 4)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once again, the Supreme Court has spoken with
authority on matters reaching directly into the American home and
workplace as well as into congressional chambers and the Oval
Office. In doing so, it has demonstrated that it remains a dynamic
Force in the splendid government triad created by the founding
fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Washington often gives the impression that almost all government
activity is the province of Congress and the executive branch, the
noisy and most publicized two thirds of the triad.
</P>
<P>
   But in some ways, the Supreme Court, whose process of reaching
monumental decisions is secret and mysterious, is the most
intriguing wing of government. It provides a constant example of
the influence a single individual can have in a democracy since
many of its rulings that transform America's social and political
behavior are decided by votes of five to four.
</P>
<P>
   We may disagree vehemently with some actions taken by the
justices, but we should understand that each, in his or her way, is
engaged in the vital task of upholding the Constitution and
defining its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the court's sacred mission since 1801 when the
great John Marshall became chief justice and, according to court
historian Henry J. Abraham, ``raised the court from its lowly if
not discredited position to a level of equality with the
legislative and executive branches _ perhaps even one of dominance
during the heyday of his chief justiceship.''
</P>
<P>
   During its 12 years of existence before Marshall's appointment,
the court, according the first chief justice, John Jay, lacked
``energy, weight and dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   That began to change when Marshall in 1803 decreed in the
landmark Marbury v. Madison case that the Constitution is supreme
and that the high court has the authority to declare laws passed by
Congress and signed by the president unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the high court found the line-item veto, which
permitted the president to kill individual appropriations,
unconstitutional and ruled that individuals suffering from HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS, are protected by the federal law that bars
discrimination against the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   It also established procedures under which individuals can sue
businesses in cases of sexual harassment. The court likewise ruled
that the National Endowment for the Arts may consider general
standards of decency in deciding what projects should receive
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   The same court that a few months ago refused to delay Paula
Jones`s suit against President Clinton until he has left the White
House, decided that the attorney-client privilege protects
communications between the late White House Deputy Counsel Vincent
Foster, a close friend of the Clintons, and his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   When people oppose the actions of Congress and the president,
they have highly visible targets for their protest. That is less
true with the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   The seven men and two women who currently make up the Supreme
Court work, as did their predecessors, in isolated splendor behind
marble walls and great columns. Few Americans, even those who damn
the justices, can recite their names.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court decisions may not be molded in concrete, but they
are difficult to repeal or circumvent.
</P>
<P>
   For years, people who claim to be advocates of ``strict
constructionism'' have sought to reverse Supreme Court rulings on
such controversial issues as school prayer, abortion and flag
burning. But they have not succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The genius and the frustration of our Constitution is that its
meaning can be interpreted in different ways by different people.
The shift of a single seat on the current court from a bona fide
conservative such as Chief Justice William Rehnquist or Justices
Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas to a more moderate jurist could
change the philosophical coloration of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Such a justice _ by joining John Paul Stevens, David Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer _ could point the court in a
less conservative direction.
</P>
<P>
   Were John Marshall alive today, he might take issue with
activist justices because he believed that ``courts are the mere
instruments of the law and can will nothing.'' But he would
recognize that the court must keep pace with the times. The
Constitution, he said, was ``intended to endure for ages to come
...''
</P>
<P>
   With their lifetime appointments, justices are supposed to the
immune to political pressure. But they know what is happening in
our society, and many of them view the Constitution as a living
document that must be, as Marshall also said, ``adapted to the
various crises of human affairs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
