<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-ART </SLUG>
 EXHIBIT-TEX 
Oil sketches at the DMA shimmer with artists' compressed vision 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Several North Texas art museums are pitching
exhibitions as vicarious getaways this typically sizzling summer.
But none as explicitly as the Dallas Museum of Art, where curator
Eleanor Jones Harvey has placed a big picture of a snowy mountain
at the entrance to ``The Painted Sketch: Impressions From Nature,
1830-1880.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harvey's witty pandering to our desperate need for a respite
is only one _ and not the primary _ reason for viewing ``The
Painted Sketch.'' For starters, it is historic: This DMA
presentation is the first survey of 19th-century painting devoted
exclusively to the oil sketch. Then there is the scholarly
incentive: ``The Painted Sketch'' adds an engaging chapter to our
knowledge of American painting.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the exhibition sheds light on the well-known work
of Frederic Edwin Church, whose views of exotic places were
rendered on a scale that, in the mid-19th century, was the
painterly equivalent of CinemaScope. At the same time, it
introduces viewers to the relatively unknown Sanford Robinson
Gifford, whose work will probably be looked at more closely as a
result of this show.
</P>
<P>
   But best of all is the pleasure of viewing dozens of luscious
little paintings, composed and executed with irresistible bravura.
Many of them inspire covetousness, which is the most selfish and
truest compliment we can pay any exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Other artists represented include Worthington Whittredge, Albert
Bierstadt, John F. Kensett and Jasper Cropsey. Artists whom many of
us would expect to be included are not because they didn't fit
Harvey's criteria. Thomas Moran, for example, worked in watercolor
instead of oil and would have diluted the exhibition effect.
</P>
<P>
   A bonus: The book for ``The Painted Sketch'' features crisply
written essays and a logically organized, fully illustrated color
catalog of all works on view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Painted Sketch: American Impressions From Nature,
1830-1880''
</P>
<P>
   Through Sept. 20: 11 a.m.-4 p.m. Tuesday-Friday, 11 a.m.-5 p.m.
Saturday and Sunday, also 4-9 p.m. Thursday at the Dallas Museum of
Art, 1717 N. Harwood St., Dallas. Tickets: $1-$5. Information:
(214) 922-1200
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
