<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL SAFETY OFFICIALS WARN OF DANGERS OF FIREWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With help from mannequins and exploding
watermelons, the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission on
Wednesday issued its annual July 4th warning about the dangers of
playing with fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Brown, CPSC chairman, warned that even legal fireworks are
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``No firework is 100 percent safe. Sparklers which burn at 2000
degrees Fahrenheit are especially dangerous for unsuspecting
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her warning came as CPSC staffers demonstrated how a sparkler _
a firework often viewed as harmless _ quickly burned through a
doll's dress.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying explosives in your pocket can also be dangerous. Safety
officials showed how a bottle rocket _ a firework allowed by the
CPSC and by some state laws _ burned a hole through a pair of
trousers when it was placed in a mannequin's pants.
</P>
<P>
   The safety exhibition included such hazardous fireworks as the
M-80 and the M-1000 explosives, both banned by the CFSC.
</P>
<P>
   According to Brown, children and adults have lost fingers and
hands in M-80 explosions. At the CPSC demonstration, a mannequin
holding an M-80 lost a hand when the device exploded.
</P>
<P>
   CPSC staffers also blew up watermelons with M-1000s.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a sampling of injuries in hospital emergency rooms
across the nation in 1997, the CPSC estimated that 8,723 people
were hurt by fireworks last year, with approximately half of the
injuries sustained by children under the age of 14.
</P>
<P>
   Burns accounted for over half of the injuries, but there also
were more serious injuries such as amputations, fractures and
lacerations, the CPSC reported.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Burns, 12, of Chicago was blinded in one eye by a faulty
firework, lit in celebration of the Chicago Bulls' basketball
championship in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to his father, Joe Burns, his son was watching an
adult set off a rocket in his friend's backyard, but the firework
exploded without warning. Pieces of shrapnel shattered the boy's
cheekbones, and he lost his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adult thought he knew how to handle these fireworks ...
but the danger zone for fireworks is not a mere 10 feet,'' Burns
said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said his son will never have more than 20/50 vision with
corrective lenses in his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   Burns urged parents to watch professional fireworks instead of
allowing their children to use fireworks in the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not become a July 4th statistic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) warned
holiday travelers that federal law prohibits carrying fireworks on
airplanes, either in carry-on luggage or in checked bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fireworks of all shapes and sizes _ from roman candles to the
smallest poppers and sparklers _ are strictly prohibited from
passengers' bags,'' Cathal Flynn, associate FAA administrator,
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only would you be risking fines, or even criminal
prosecution by carrying fireworks on board a passenger plane, but
you would endanger yourself and everyone else on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil penalties of up to $27,500 per violation are in effect for
both domestic and international flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
