<HEADLINE>
CIRCUITS Q&AMP;A: SURGE SUPPRESSORS FOR PHONE LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is it true that your telephone line should be plugged into a
surge suppressor before being attached to the computer? I have been
told that a power surge could go through the phone and hurt the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   A. Using a high-quality surge suppressor that includes a jack
for your modem line is definitely a good idea, as Mother Nature
does not stand in awe of technology. Sudden, enormous power surges
from lightning strikes can travel through your telephone line and
power cords. External modems are often at risk for a double whammy,
as they generally plug into both the telephone jack and an
electrical outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Some types of internal modems are equipped with relay switches
that will trip if the power surges and prevent further damage to
your computer's components. That is not a certainty, of course, as
anything can happen when it comes to nature.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in an area that with frequent storms, unplug the
power and telephone cords from your computer when you are not using
it, or invest in a surge suppressor that protects both kinds of
cables. Don't trust your expensive equipment to a cheap suppressor
that is little more than an extension cord.
</P>
<P>
   A computer-grade surge suppressor should have an on-off switch
to control all devices, a telephone-line jack and a status light to
indicate that the suppressor is working. It should carry a label
from Underwriters Laboratories, which tests products for electrical
safety.
</P>
<P>
   A good surge suppressor, which will clamp down on excess voltage
before it can fry your components, can be found at electronics and
computer stores. It may cost you $50 or more, but it is still far
cheaper than replacing all your sensitive hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   QandA(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   or by postal mail to:
</P>
<P>
   Questions
</P>
<P>
   Circuits
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd Street
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
</P>
<P>
   This column will answer questions of general interest, but
letters cannot be answered individually.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
