<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR AND LOVING IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You simply cannot comprehend the expression, ``fear gripped
me,'' until you have been truly terrified for minutes that seem
like hours.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than that haunted house, fake blood kind of scared,
or the cheap shower curtain rod falling down in the bathroom
because someone hung a towel on it. I'm referring to that
heart-pounding, fist-clenching, teeth-grinding, pressure-rising
terror that only bullets and babies can bring.
</P>
<P>
   No, I have not been to war and crouched in a foxhole as bullets
whizzed overhead. I did drive through a rough neighborhood in
Amarillo late one night some years ago, but no one was out except
an old gray cat with no tail and just three legs.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I know fear.
</P>
<P>
   While in school, I worked at a fast-food joint as a cashier.
Late one night, three coked-out masked men robbed us at gunpoint.
Miraculously, my pants did not get wet. However, as frightening as
it was, that incident ranks No. 2 on my list of most terrifying
experiences. My No. 1 happened just a few weeks ago at the mall.
No, no one refused my credit card. That was the day I lost my son.
</P>
<P>
   I had bribed Junior into shopping with me by promising him a
toy. The toy store was right across from my favorite place in the
world, a bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son,'' I said, ``let's just stop in B. Dalton's a minute, and
then we'll get your toy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, he followed me into the store. I headed for the New
Fiction section, and when I glanced back to tell him something, he
was gone, suddenly vanished into thin air.
</P>
<P>
   I searched all over the bookstore and then the toy store. He
wasn't in either place.
</P>
<P>
   I checked the plaza, then the food court and the arcade. There
was no sign of him anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Fear gripped me.
</P>
<P>
   In a panic, I found a security guard and begged him to help me
find my boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was he wearing?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea. My mind was like a river of white water; things
were going by so fast that I couldn't hang onto a single thought.
</P>
<P>
   I kept babbling until the guard finally asked for a picture of
my son, and that set the search in motion. A million horrifying
thoughts and images filled my head as I tried to ``stay put'' as
I'd been instructed. But I couldn't just sit there as precious
minutes passed by.
</P>
<P>
   I started running through the mall, calling my son's name.
Miraculously, I soon spotted him standing near the escalators with
a mask of bravado disguising his fright. When he saw me, he said:
``Mom, where have you been? I've been looking everywhere for you!''
</P>
<P>
   With relief, I chose a smile and a bear hug over the screaming
lecture that I'd planned. For once, he let me hug him in public
without protesting.
</P>
<P>
   I lifted him up, and love lifted me. Only then did fear let me
go.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
