u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CHINA-HNS &LR;      07-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY PUSHES ISSUE OF WOMEN'S RIGHTS DURING SHANGHAI SPEECH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Standing prim in pink before an auditorium
filled with the Shanghai Women's Federation, Hillary Rodham Clinton
echoed a Chinese maxim: Women hold up half the sky.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where sons are prized and daughters neglected, she
made her case on the need to value women, to educate them, to
provide legal rights, to stop violence and abuse in their homes,
and to allow them the freedom to plan their own families _ a quiet
reference to forced abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women can only hold up half the sky when their feet are
planted firmly on the soil of freedom and equal justice,'' she told
the 450 Chinese women gathered at the Shanghai Library auditorium.
Her daughter, Chelsea, and her mother, Dorothy, also were in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Here and on her travels through the world, Hillary Clinton has
used symbols and substance to carve a new role in foreign policy
for a first lady, pushing the issue of women's rights onto the
administration's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great privileges of my position is to travel on
behalf of my country. Wherever I go, I speak with women and
girls,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said that no matter what nation we live in, we face the
same challenges, and dream the same dreams. We all hope for the day
when no woman is a victim of domestic abuse and other forms of
violence. When no woman is the victim of economic discrimination.
When no woman is denied the basic rights of health care and
education.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a message the first lady has taken to Argentina, where she
spoke in favor of reproductive rights to the loud cheers of women
opposed to that nation's restrictive abortion laws. In Africa, she
voiced support for women's efforts to stop the custom of female
genital mutilation. And she has urged families to stop selling
their daughters into prostitution in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are issues that are included in our foreign policy.
These are not marginal issues. These are very central issues. What
she does is validate the good that is going on,'' said Melanne
Verveer, the first lady's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   A White House aide said the best example of the first lady's
influence on foreign policy was the president's 11-day journey to
Africa, in which he retraced many of her stops from the previous
year. It was at the first lady's behest that the president visited
small villages where women operate microcredit programs that
provide small loans to women to set up their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   And Hillary Clinton's remarks occasionally have a stronger
reverberation in a country than the president's.
</P>
<P>
   Last October in Buenos Aires, she told several hundred
applauding women that ``access to quality health care _ especially
family planning and reproductive health services _ is crucial to
advancing the progress of women.'' The comment was considered
especially daring in Argentina, which is 90 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of that speech, Hillary, who was not well known,
became very popular,'' said Ana Baron, a journalist with the
Argentina newspaper Clarin.
</P>
<P>
   In Shanghai, there also was a demand from women who wanted to
see the first lady. ``Everybody wanted to see her. They all
recognize her talents,'' said Julie Prado, a Chinese-born U.S.
citizen helping with the event.
</P>
<P>
   The Shanghai Women's Federation is an association of about 1,000
professional women who sat quietly throughout Hillary Clinton's
address. The first lady also has visited a girls school, a
children's medical center and a women's retraining facility for
those needing new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In China, the first lady also has been paired with Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in meeting with women lawyers and
professors at Peking University in Beijing and touring a restored
synagogue in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House spokesman, called the pairing a
``happy coincidence.'' But the joint appearances also present a
powerful symbol for women in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   But even overseas, where she draws huge crowds, her bitterness
at scandal and criticism in Washington, D.C., comes through. When
she and the president had a discussion session with Shanghai
community leaders she was asked about the restrictions on her
personal life because of her public role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often refer to my life before the White House when I was a
`real person' because then we are in a position like this, people,
particularly all these people with their pencils and their cameras,
try to record everything you do and then they try to put meaning
into it _ whether you intend the meaning or not,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That jab at the U.S. media struck some as inappropriate
considering the Chinese Communist government refuses to allow
freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many women it is a constant challenge to claim your own
identity and your own position and to make clear who you are, as
opposed to society's expectations as to who you should be because
you hold a position of woman novelist, woman law professor, first
lady, or any of the other positions that women hold in any
society,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
