<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6447 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEACH-BOOKS-TEX     07-01 0257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF SUMMER READING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lucifer's Hammer''
</P>
<P>
   By Larry Niven and Jerry Pournelle
</P>
<P>
   Del Ray, 629 pages, $14
</P>
<P>
   THE AUTHORS: Niven and Pournelle are part of sci-fi's old guard,
with an obsession for scientific detail and a loooooong cast of
characters.
</P>
<P>
   THE RELEVANCE: Lucifer's Hammer is about what happens when a
comet hits the Earth. Pretty prescient stuff, considering two of
summer's biggest movies (Deep Impact and Armageddon) are on the
same theme _ and this book was written in 1977. An updated version
published last year notes that, in 20 years, your chances of being
killed by a meteor have risen from 1 in 20,000 to 1 in 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so what happens when a comet hits the Earth? Tidal waves,
earthquakes, volcanic explosions, floods, another ice age.
California finally falls off; Florida becomes an island. (This
being the '70s, the Russians also launch some nukes in the middle
of all this, just to keep things interesting.)
</P>
<P>
   THE PLOT: Trashy fun in the tradition of other '70s disaster
epics like The Towering Inferno. The surviving scientists, led by
an iron-willed senator, set about rebuilding a sliver of society.
Not always easy: They wind up defending a nuclear power plant
against an army of cannibals.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOVIE PITCH: Imagine if Tom Clancy wrote sci-fi _ and sex
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/_ Reviewed by Lisa Davis
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
