(Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   STODA-COLUMN _ KOHLER, Wis. _ Her name is Alison Nicholas. She's
the one who actually won the U.S. Women's Open last year. You may
have missed her. Not because she's only 60 inches tall _ well,
maybe because of that, too _ but mostly because the giant she beat
by one shot on the Witch Hollow Course at Pumpkin Ridge in North
Plains, Ore., was the legendary Nancy Lopez. (Stoda, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCGANN _ Michelle McGann tries to find her game in what, to this
point, has been a disappointing year (Stoda, West Palm Beach) ETA:
9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR-FIRE _ NASCAR maintains everything is go for Saturday's
race at Daytona. We paint the scene. (McCollister, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FENCING-NATIONALS _ Austin has long had The Drag. But for the
next nine days it will also have The Strip. That's where the action
will be for the more than 1,000 fencers invading the city for the
USA Fencing Summer Nationals. The Strip is what fencers call the
thin, 44-foot long area where they play their ancient craft. There
will be 40 of those laid out in an 80,000-square foot area at the
Convention Center to accommodate all the fencers coming to town for
the national championship. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman). ETA:
10 p.m.
</P>
