<HEADER>
A6485 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     07-01 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Kingdom of the Cults''
</P>
<P>
   By Walter Martin
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Hank Hanegraaff
</P>
<P>
   Bethany House, $29.99
</P>
<P>
   Even the sturdiest structures need occasional repair and
renovation, and major books on controversial topics are no
different _ thus, the updated and expanded edition of Walter
Martin's classic ``The Kingdom of the Cults.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who died in 1989, sees a ``cult'' as a religious group
that differs significantly from those regarded as normative in a
culture and, more important, as one gathered around a particular
misinterpretation of the Bible. About one-third of this massive
volume criticizes the theology of Jehovah's Witnesses, Mormons and
Christian Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism and Islam are discussed as world religions rather than
cults per se. Other topics are ``mind control,'' apocalyptic groups
such as the Branch Davidians, and the Word Faith movement
(represented in Tarrant County by Kenneth Copeland, who is quoted
as saying that God is about 6 feet tall and weighs about 200
pounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kingdom of the Cults'' is a frequently blunt but heavily
researched examination of out-of-the-mainstream theology. The
revised edition (complete with a CD-ROM) brings new and worthwhile
material to light.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Is an Action Word''
</P>
<P>
   Witness
</P>
<P>
   CGI Records
</P>
<P>
   Witness is Laeh Page, Lisa Brooks, Ayana Thomas and Candice
Smith, a well-regarded Detroit group that for the past 12 years has
fused light urban pop, a hint of mellow jazz and direct gospel
messages into something strong and subtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Is an Action Word'' is the group's first CD in two years,
and it is a worthy follow-up. The overall sound _ frothy, easygoing
pop/gospel _ always goes down easy, but this is one of the
quartet's best selections of songs. Working again with
producer/writer Michael Brooks (a former member of Commissioned),
the four have fashioned a CD chock-full of cool harmonies, a few
nods to the gentler side of '70s funk (check the drifting guitar on
``I'll Reign),'' and bright, full harmonies. And saxophonist David
McMurray adds some breezy touches, most notably on the easygoing
``Justified by Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the group does a laudable job of balancing pop and
forthright messages of devotion to God. ``Never Let Go, Faith'' and
``Resting in Him,'' among others, have a light touch but a firm
grasp on conveying messages of persistence and trust in God. Mellow
but never sappy or slight, ``Love Is an Action Word'' is a solid,
consistently pleasant effort.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
