<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKING-BLUES-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVAL OF THE FITTEST
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE, with GREG BROWN in Santiago, BRENDAN M. CASE in
Mexico City, MERY GALANTERNICK in Rio de Janeiro and ANDREA
MANDELL-CAMPBELL in Buenos Aires 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    For evidence that Latin America's banking industry is less than
exuberant, consider the case of Chilean Gonzalo Marin. A
26-year-old computer executive, Marin recently decided to buy a
US$60,000 apartment in Santiago. In the past, he had little trouble
getting credit to buy two new cars, so he thought getting a
mortgage would be a snap.
 &HT;    Not exactly. His lender, Citibank, told him it would take a
month to get a mortgage. The process ended up taking three months.
While he was waiting, interest rates went up. By the time the
mortgage went through, Marin's initial payment had quintupled from
$660 to almost $3,300. ``Part of it's bad luck _ the market went
down. But part of the problem was in their delay,'' Marin says.
``It left a bad taste in my mouth.''
 &HT;    Compared with some of his neighbors in other countries, Marin
was lucky to get a mortgage at all. While the availability of
credit has improved a little since the 1994 Mexico peso devaluation
sent interest rates sky high and sapped consumer spending across
the region, Latin America's banks are still keeping a tight hold on
their purse strings. That's actually a good thing in this
topsy-turvy region, which seems to go from boom to bust every
couple of years. But if these countries have learned anything, it's
that the weaker the banking system, the harder a country will fall
when an economic crisis strikes. ``If the banking system is strong,
the crisis is very, very mild,'' says Jose Garcia-Cantera, a
respected Latin America bank analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in New
York. ``It only becomes a crisis if the banking system becomes the
weakest link in the chain.'' Most of the region's banking systems
are trying to reinforce their links. They're tightening their
belts, strengthening their balance sheets and adopting new
technologies. They're also beginning to diversify into
higher-margin financial services, such as insurance and asset
management.
 &HT;    Some of the impetus has come from competition _ namely, from
foreign banks that continue to invade Latin America's banking
systems. Spanish banks like Banco Santander, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya
(BBV) and Banco Central Hispano (BCH) have been the most
aggressive. But U.K.-based Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corp.
(HSBC) has also moved in, as has Holland's ABN-Amro Bank and
Canada's Bank of Montreal. Only a few U.S. banks have tested the
waters, primarily Citibank, BankBoston and Chase Manhattan.
 &HT;    Conservative Chile. In the early 1980s, a financial collapse
similar to Mexico's 1994 currency crisis drove control of Chile's
banks into the hands of its central bank.
 &HT;    A few issues remain, but most of Chile's banks have recovered _
or were swallowed up in mergers. They are now aggressively delving
into consumer credit markets to regain public trust and dependable
bottom lines.
 &HT;    Today there are 31 banking-sector entities, 17 of which are
foreign-owned commercial banks, among them Banco Santander and
Citibank. Chilean banks are well-disciplined compared with most in
Latin America and are comparable to U.S. institutions in terms of
safeguards for investors and depositors. In part, the discipline
springs from strict regulations imposed during the military
government after the 1982-1983 collapse. This makes Chile's banks
safe but extremely conservative in an otherwise freewheeling
economy. Despite recent passage of a new law that allows commercial
banks to diversify into insurance, factoring and foreign lending,
most banks have taken a wait-and-see attitude.
 &HT;    Conservatism, however, has its virtues. Bad loans totaled only
about 1 percent of all loans, while loan growth has registered 11.6
percent per year over the 1990s, according to a study by Chilean
think tank Sociedad de Fomento Fabril (Sofofa). Return on equity
rose by 18.3 percent per year between 1990 and 1995.
 &HT;    Chile's bank regulator, the Association of Banks and Financial
Institutions, reports total bank loans rose almost 60 percent
between 1994 and 1997 to $45 billion. Earnings, meanwhile, have
been less stellar, but steady, increasing nearly 37 percent to $3
billion over the same period. Initially, Chile's banks were hit
hard by the Asian crisis. But they recovered quickly, leading to
first-quarter 1998 results that surpassed analysts' expectations.
 &HT;    Underbanked Argentina: Conditions are a little more tense in
Argentina's banking sector. Scenes of irate customers and
out-of-work employees protesting before the closed doors of the
defunct Banco Patricios are all too familiar to Argentines, who
have experienced first hand the turbulent past of the country's
banking sector. It's one of the main reasons Argentina remains the
most ``underbanked'' countries in Latin America, with a
deposits-to-gross-domestic-product ratio of a meager 22 percent.
 &HT;    Since August, Argentina's central bank has suspended three banks
over insolvency and fraud issues. Financial problems within the
Spanish-Swiss investment group, Socimer, led to the closure of its
two banks: Medefin-UNB in February and Banco Patricios in March.
Added to the scandal-ridden closure of the Banco de Credito
Provincial de la Plata, some $791 million in deposits and an
estimated 300,000 accounts have been affected.
 &HT;    Yet, despite the bad apples, the sector remains one of the most
dynamic and open in the Argentine economy, according to a recent
report by brokerage firm Santander Investment. ``This is not an
indication of the health of the system,'' says Carlos Gomez Lopez,
an analyst for CS First Boston in New York. ``The central bank is
keeping a watchful eye and the big banks are very, very solid.''
The sector has become increasingly sound under the tutelage of
foreign investors, whose deep pockets have managed to scoop up most
of the country's major banks in the last year and a half. The
Spanish have led the way, with BBV acquiring and merging Banco
Frances with Bnco de Credito Argentino, while arch rival Banco
Santander picked up Banco Rio de la Plata.
 &HT;    As a result, the number of Argentine banks has dropped from 205
in December 1994 to 139 currently. The foreign invasion _ and the
flight to quality after the 1994 Mexican peso devaluation _ has
resulted in 20 of the top banks controlling 75 percent of the
market. The consolidation is expected to continue. According to the
central bank, 15 banks merged or were liquidated in the last two
years. More are expected to come by 2000. Analysts predict the
sector will be pared down to about 50 banks. As for the rest, ``I'd
be surprised if they survive the next five years,'' says Malcolm
Gibson, an analyst at HSBC Roberts Capital Markets in Buenos Aires.
Investors are encouraged by promising growth prospects in
Argentina's retail banking sector. Since 1990, deposits have jumped
from $11 billion to $71.4 billion, or an accumulated annual rate of
25.6 percent, while loans have increased by 17.5 percent a year.
Since last November, an estimated 1.9 million new accounts have
been created due to a new government regulation making it mandatory
for companies with 100 or more employees to issue paychecks through
ATMs. In a bid to capture this dynamic growth, banks have embarked
on an aggressive expansion plan. Over the next two to four years,
the number of bank branches in Argentina is expected to nearly
double from 4,000 _ one of the lowest in the world _ to almost
8,000. Last year alone, the central bank received a record 600
applications to open new branches, while between 250 and 300 ATMs
are opening every month. Among the most ambitious are the
Spaniards, with BBV planning to double its branches from 200 to
400. Banco Rio has signed a deal with the country's leading oil
company, YPF, to open 100 branches in gas stations.
 &HT;    The focus on the retail sector and the growing competition have
made banks increasingly accessible to the population, according to
CS First Boston's Gomez Lopez. Interest rates on loans, for
example, which reached 85.8 percent in 1990, now average around 8.6
percent. In fact, private-sector loans now amount to $61.5 billion,
representing 20 percent of GDP. Mortgage rates have come down, too,
from 17 percent before the Mexican economic crisis to below 11
percent. ``The central bank is particularly keen on increasing
bancarization [expansion of the retail banking sector],'' he says.
While banks boosted the peso prime lending rate by as much as 60
percent during the Asian crisis, those rates have rapidly returned
to normal, Gomez Lopez says. ``It's almost as if the crisis didn't
happen. The sector is healthy, it's growing, it's liquid, it has an
enormous potential for expansion and it's very interesting.'' The
industry is now waiting for the proposed privatization of
Argentina's biggest bank, Banco de la Nacion, which is expected to
bring in anywhere between $3 billion and $4 billion when it's sold
off next year or the year after. While the banking sector welcomes
the move, many point out that the institution provides
government-subsidized loans to agricultural producers and small
companies that would not otherwise qualify for financial
assistance. Those would probably stop under private ownership.
 &HT;    Brazil bounces back. Brazil's banking sector has also had a
rough ride. In 1994, Brazilian banks had it made. With inflation
running around 2,000 percent in 1994, earning money on what came in
and what went out was a piece of cake.
 &HT;    But after President Fernando Henrique Cardoso tightened Brazil's
monetary policy through the Real Plan, banks lost their ability to
make money on inflation spreads. So many had to relearn basic
banking skills, such as how to squeeze profits out of lending and
deposit-taking. It soon became survival of the fittest. Between
1995 and 1997, nearly 100 financial institutions, including 50
banks, disappeared, either because of bad management, corruption or
fraud. The cost of private bank failures to the government amounted
to $21 billion. State banks were also affected. Due to years of
losses, Brazil's central bank took over two of the biggest
state-owned banks. Rio de Janeiro-based Banerj was eventually
restructured and sold to Itau Bank in 1997 for $300 million. In
1994, Sao Paulo-based Banespa was transferred to federal control as
part of an agreement to restructure the Sao Paulo state debt. It is
now being readied for privatization, which is scheduled to take
place later this year. Last year, foreign banks began to invade.
HSBC bought the banking assets of Banco Bamerindus do Brasil S.A.,
Brazil's fifth-largest private bank, for $1 billion. The
announcement marked a turning point in the consolidation of
Brazil's banking industry. It also showed the government's new
willingness to allow foreign investors to take a prominent role in
the country's banking sector. After that, a series of acquisitions
were announced in 1997, including a 50 percent acquisition of
investment bank Multiplic by Lloyd's TSB for $600 million and 51
percent of Banco Geral do Comercio by Banco Santander for $100
million.
 &HT;    And in late April this year, BBV announced the $450 million
acquisition of 55 percent of Banco Excel Economico. The number of
foreign bank branches authorized by the central bank jumped from
200 in 1995 to 2000 in 1998 and the volume of foreign groups'
assets increased from 10 percent to 16 percent of the country's
banking assets.
 &HT;    After four years of dramatic restructuring, Brazil's banking
industry is about to gain momentum. But the strength of foreign
banks is posing a sticky problem to local banks. How to face this
fierce competition?
 &HT;    The biggest private-sector banks have already adjusted by
adopting conservative lending policies, investing in technology,
reducing costs through layoffs and charging for previously free
services. Service fees, freed from central bank control in 1996,
are an increasingly important part of their income. Despite the
discomfort, Brazil's banking sector is now better off.
 &HT;    ``Competition is very healthy because it will force banks to
offer better services at lower costs,'' says Mario Coelho, director
of Austin Asis, a Sao Paulo-based consulting firm that specializes
in risk analysis.
 &HT;    Watch for more banks to disappear, be acquired or merge.
According to three different banking analysts, there are still too
many banks in Brazil _ more than 200 at last count. Smaller banks
are expected to be swallowed up by bigger banks. These new
alliances will offer a wider range of financial products, from cash
management to securities trading to underwriting.
 &HT;    The Asian crisis last October forced the government to take
harsh measures to protect its currency. Among those measures,
interest rates were doubled to nearly 40 percent. As a result,
neither low-paid workers nor small businessmen dared to borrow from
banks. The worry was needless. The government gradually reduced
rates again, from 34 percent to 28 percent and to 23.25 percent at
press time. But Brazilians' memories run deep. ``[In 1997] I
borrowed $250 to buy a vacuum cleaner. After 12 installments, I
realized I had paid back $490,'' says Ana Maria de Andrade, a
29-year-old Rio de Janeiro housekeeper. ``Never more in my life
[do] I want to go through such an experience.''
 &HT;    Mexico moving again. Mexico's banks have also been to hell and
back. But they've still got a long way to go. Mexican Finance
Minister Jose Angel Gurria is known for his suave, smooth-talking
style. But when it comes to banks, he does not mince words. The
banking system, he said in recent testimony to Congress, is the
``weakest link in the economic development of Mexico.'' Actually,
compared with any time since the economic crisis of 1995, Mexico's
battered commercial banks are in relatively good shape. Thanks to a
massive government bailout program and huge capital injections by
foreign banks, which have taken stakes in some Mexican banks and
bought others outright, capitalization levels are up and
non-performing loan rates are down.
 &HT;    Credit is still scarce and expensive, with consumer credit
carrying interest rates of about 35 percent _ compared with
expected 1998 inflation ofabout 13 percent _ and commercial loans
carrying interest rates of around 20 percent. But lending to the
non-financial sector is widely expected to grow in real terms this
year for the first time since the crisis. Carlos Gomez y Gomez,
director general of Santander Mexicano and new president of the
Mexican Bankers Association, says real lending could grow by 4
percent or 5 percent this year. Some private-sector analysts are
even more optimistic. Rafael Bello, at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
in New York, reckons lending could grow as much as 10 percent this
year. But such lending is only a small improvement from a very
small base, and banks have become a marginal force in promoting
economic growth.
 &HT;    Nearly all GDP growth since 1994 has come from exports and
investment, with recent improvements in consumption. But large
Mexican exporters and foreign multinationals, which have accounted
for the lion's share of exportsand investment, have access to
cheaper financing abroad. The nascent consumer recovery is based
almost entirely on pent-up demand and savings, not consumer credit,
according to consumer goods analysts.
 &HT;    The lack of competitive domestic financing is already
threatening to upset Mexico's balance of payments, as large
companies have realized they can get better financing terms from
foreign banks or debt markets. Of the $34 billion in Mexican
foreign debt that matures this year, about $18 billion is thought
to be held by the private sector. U.S. rating firm Standard &AMP;
Poor's estimates that the private sector's foreign debt reached
about 40 percent of exports last year, roughly similar to what it
was before the crisis.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, taxpayers will be paying for banks' mistakes for
years. The cost of the bailout was recently raised to about $65
billion. Of the $60 billion in bad loans held by government agency
Fobaproa, Finance Ministry officials think about 30 percent might
be recoverable. Private-sector analysts are less sanguine. No
short-term banking fix seems to be available. But the government is
in the midst of implementing several policies that will promote a
far-reaching restructuring in the banking sector. In a recent
package of reform proposals sent to Congress, the government
proposed lifting the restrictions on foreign ownership of banks.
Foreign banks were allowed to own most Mexican banks before, but
not the three biggest, because each accounts for more than 6
percent of the total capitalization of Mexico's banking system. If
the legislation is passed (which is expected by September 1),
foreigners will legally be able to own the three biggest banks and
will no longer need special permission to own smaller banks.
 &HT;    ``Without a doubt, these are measures that have to do with the
globalization of the Mexican financial system,'' says Gomez y
Gomez. ``They will give more flexibility to Mexican and foreign
investors in the search for solid, profitable financial
institutions.'' Foreign institutions have already picked up stakes
in smaller banks, led by the Spanish. BBV acquired Cremi, Oriente,
Credito and Probursa, Santander bought 51 percent of Banco Mexicano
and BCH owns 20 percent of Bital. Last August, Citibank jumped on
the bandwagon, announcing it would buy Confia for $45 million. Bank
of Nova Scotia owns 10 percent of Inverlat with an option to
acquire 55 percent more. In the meantime, Mexican banks have been
consolidating like crazy. After President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
reprivatized Mexico's banking industry in the early 1990s, bankers
blanketed the country with branches. But after the economic crisis
hit in late 1994, pushing up interest rates and pushing down
purchasing power, demand for financial services fell dramatically.
As a result, Mexico became one of the most ``overbanked'' countries
in the region.
 &HT;    So Mexican banks have been pairing off to achieve economies of
scale. Late last year, GBM Atlantico announced it was being
acquired by Grupo Financiero Bital, creating the fourth-largest
financial institution in Mexico with nearly $14 billion in total
assets. More mergers and acquisitions are expected later this year,
possibly involving a foreign purchase of BanCrecer. Andean
countries. Banking conditions are improving in other parts of Latin
America.
 &HT;    In Peru, loan growth and profitability declined slightly last
year. But past-due loans decreased from 6.7 percent at the end of
1996 to 5.3 percent at the end of 1997. Coverage of past-due loans
has also increased, reaching 88.4 percent, versus 84.9 percent a
year ago. Despite its political problems, Colombia has one of the
strongest banking sectors in Latin America. Last year, the industry
showed loan growth of 33.2 percent, 11.8 percent of which came in
the fourth quarter. However, liquidity declined slightly from 8.8
percent to 9.2 percent and net interest margins narrowed from 7.7
percent to 6.1 percent.
 &HT;    Venezuela is the hot new banking market. [Latin Trade, May
1998]. While the recent decline in oil prices may affect asset
quality, the Venezuelan banking industry is much stronger and
healthier than it was in 1994. For instance, its coverage of
nonperforming loans as of the end of 1997 was 124 percent.
 &HT;    While foreign banks throughout Latin America have brought in
fresh capital, they've also kept Latin American bankers on their
toes, all the better for these countries' fragile economies _ and
their consumers. ``The entrance of foreign institutions is really
going to make a difference,'' Salomon's Garcia-Cantera says. ``At
the end of the day, the whole system is going to be much more
efficient.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
