<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-MAIN02-COX     07-01 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MAIN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIDS is hard to treat if patients stop taking their medication
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geneva _ The failure of HIV patients to correctly and
consistently take their medication is the greatest obstacle in
curing AIDS with drugs, leading AIDS researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies presented at the 12th World AIDS Conference show
that people with HIV who don't adhere to their prescribed drug
regimens often become resistant to the drugs, creating tough new
strains of the virus that then become very difficult to treat.
</P>
<P>
   And once patients become resistant to a particular drug, other
drugs in the same class also tend to be ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite clear that incomplete adherence represents the
single most important challenge to long-term effectiveness of
currently available regimens,'' Dr. Julio Montaner of Vancouver
said Wednesday. Montaner heads AIDS research at St. Paul's
Hospital/University of British Columbia.''Overwhelmingly, the
patient's ability to take the drugs dictates the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The reports emerged as the first known case of a patient being
infected with a strain of HIV resistant to the most powerful new
anti-viral drugs was reported by San Francisco AIDS specialists.
Scientists at the conference in Geneva said the case could mark an
ominous new turn in the global epidemic that has already claimed
more than 10 million lives.
</P>
<P>
   The mutated strain of the AIDS virus, seemingly impervious to
protease inhibitors and older anti-virals now in use, was found in
a newly infected patient at San Francisco General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be seeing an emerging and dangerous edge to the
epidemic,'' said Dr. Frederick Hecht of the University of
California at San Francisco, who delivered the report on the
disheartening case.
</P>
<P>
   A study conducted by researchers at the University of Geneva
found similar drug-resistant strains of HIV in six of 57 male
patients, who, like the San Francisco patient, contracted the virus
through unprotected sex. A report on those cases was presented by
Dr. Sabine Yerly of the university's virology laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Montaner said treatment regimens and schedules must be made
easier and more tolerable for patients to protect the potency of
existing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Those taking three-drug combinations with protease inhibitors,
the most powerful class of anti-HIV drugs, must take pills up to
five times a day and must schedule their meals so they can take
some pills with food and some without. Skipping a dose or taking it
incorrectly could decrease the level of drug in the patients blood,
and in turn would give HIV an opportunity to develop resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The protease inhibitor saquinavir, for instance, must be taken
three times a day, six pills per dose, soon after a full meal, or
the body won't absorb as much as it should. Another protease
inhibitor, indinavir, must also be taken three times daily but two
pills at a time, and at least one hour before or two hours after a
meal.
</P>
<P>
   A patient survey presented at the conference showed that a
majority of patients taking such drugs missed a dose at some point
during the three days prior to answering the survey. Many people
with HIV, while thankful for the drugs, say their jobs and
lifestyles make it difficult to keep a rigid dosing schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Side effects share the blame for poor adherence. Nausea and
diarrhea are common. Protease inhibitors can also cause
lipodystrophy, in which fat wastes away from the face, limbs and
upper trunk; cholesterol levels as astonishgly high as 1,000; a
condition called ``buffalo hump,'' in which fat accumulates on the
spine; and type II diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Already drugs are being created or reformulated for less
frequent doses and fewer pills. Efavirenz (Sustiva), a once-a-day
drug manufactured by DuPont, is now pending approval by the U. S.
Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb has reformulated a existing drug,
didanosine, or ddI, into a once-daily pill. This form, called
Videx, is still in testing.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs are being combined into single pills, such as Glaxo
Wellcome's Combivir, which contains two common anti-HIV drugs, AZT
and 3TC. Combivir is designed to be taken one pill at a time, two
times per day, with or without food.
</P>
<P>
   A new experimental drug that has impressed researchers at the
conference is abacavir, which belongs to the same class of drugs as
AZT and 3TC. Abacavir also is a one-tablet, twice-daily formulation
by Glaxo, and has the additional advantage of being relatively slow
to cause resistance. Last week Glaxo asked the FDA for accelerated
approval of abacavir.
</P>
<P>
   Another experimental Glaxo drug, amprenavir, is a new protease
inhibitor that also shows promise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
