<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6510 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-TANKS-COX     07-01 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-TANKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TANKS A LOT!
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It recently occurred to us that _ to keep spotlighting trends
that appeal to our readers _ we should get out of the office more
to see what people are really wearing. The results of our first
foray, on a jungle-hot day, are as follows. We found a range of
women wearing tank tops. Atlantan Nicole Warren, 21, expressed the
consensus with: ``Tank tops and little skirts or shorts and sandals
... that's all I'm wearing this summer. They make getting dressed
easy. And there's plenty (of tank tops) to choose from.'' Who knows
what we'll discover on our next style safari. But look sharp. The
next subject we turn our camera on could be you.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE POINTS: Tank tops invite the question of what _ if
anything _ to wear under them. Some tanks may be of the right
texture and fabrication to allow less endowed women to go braless.
Wearing two tanks of contrasting colors is another stylish and
modest option. But when wearing a bra under a tank is a must, heed
the advice of Awa Woodf, manager of Bisou-Bisou in Atlanta: ``You
should wear a strapless bra. It looks too tacky if the straps are
showing.'' Unless that's the look you like.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
