</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BERRIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take your pick: The berries of summer vs. the perils of the
brier patch
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orchard Hill, Ga.--One of the surest ways of telling a city kid
from a country kid in the South is to ask whether he's been
blackberrying. City kids may not have heard the berry used as a
verb. Country kids have; they know it means long pants and long
sleeves, stickers and chiggers, inky fingertips and pails of
precious berries that catch the sunlight like cut glass.
</P>
<P>
   I am a city kid, and, frankly, blackberries have always
frightened me a little. Not the berries but the bushes, with their
canes and thorns reaching out like long arms and claws. And the
chiggers, legions of red larvae itching to bite your flesh. And
worst of all, the snakes that we were always warned could be a
hiding in the brush, because they like the critters that like the
blackberries.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I love cobbler and preserves as much as the next person,
but the prospect of wading into blackberry thickets seemed kind of
risky to a suburban boy raised on the soft lawns of DeKalb County.
</P>
<P>
   So I was relieved when I phoned Buck Creek Farm, a pick-your-own
place 50 miles south of Atlanta, and heard the man make berry
picking sound almost as easy as grocery shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on down. Our blackberries don't even have thorns. We've
got restrooms, water, picnic tables. Wear shorts if you want to.''
Chuck Aly didn't guarantee that his berries were serpentless, but I
got the picture: This was no Little Shop of Briers.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of picking thornless blackberries in a parklike
setting would have amused generations of Southerners. They took it
as an article of faith that the best-tasting blackberries were wild
and that you had to dress like a beekeeper to extract them from the
inconvenient places where they grew. In ``Sook's Cookbook''
(Longstreet, 1989), Marie Rudisill tells about an old woman in
Monroeville, Ala., who always took a fierce razorback named Red Rip
along when she went into the woods blackberrying. Her reason? ``His
squealing scared the snakes away.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people still think wild blackberries taste better than
domesticated ones. The agricultural experts don't necessarily
agree. They say the two taste about the same, as long as there's
been enough rain. If the weather has been dry, wild berries will be
seedier and less juicy than the irrigated ones on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think wild berries taste better because they have to
sweat and fight those chiggers and rattlesnakes to get them,''
jokes Gerard Krewer, a small-fruit specialist with the University
of Georgia Extension Service in Tifton.
</P>
<P>
   Although blackberries go way back in Southern cooking, they've
never developed into a sizable industry here, perhaps because the
berries are readily available in the wild. By contrast, blueberries
_ more associated with New England cooking _ have become an
industry with its own trade association. Georgia has more than 250
commercial blueberry growers, many of them around the southeast
Georgia town of Alma, where the 24th annual blueberry festival was
held last weekend. The blueberry farmers were sassy enough four
years ago to try to win a statewide property tax exemption from
voters. ``Blackberries, of course, have no lobbyist,'' wrote The
Atlanta Journal's Jim Wooten, who opposed the tax break, having
been a blackberry-eating country boy in McRae before he became an
editor in the big city.
</P>
<P>
   They grow both berries _ black and blue _ at Buck Creek, a
30-acre fruit and Christmas tree farm off Interstate 75 in the
community of Orchard Hill, near Griffin. When my wife and Iarrived
on an overcast Saturday in June, the first day of berry season,
people were already picking at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Aly, a slender 47-year-old in jeans spotted with dark berry
juice, was sitting under a tarpaulin shelter next to a scale and a
stack of white buckets. Farming isn't his regular job; he pays the
bills selling insurance. But he grew up on farms in Florida and
North Carolina, and when he heard Buck Creek was for sale a couple
of years ago, he bought it rather than see it subdivided for home
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to come down here from Atlanta and see things
growing,'' he said. ``We've got a generation of kids who don't know
where their food comes from. We had a woman in here _ she must have
been 32 _ and when I took her to the vegetable garden, she said,
'Wow, I didn't know that's how potatoes grew.'''
</P>
<P>
   I chuckled knowingly, then stopped as it dawned on me that I,
who had never been blackberrying, could be the subject of his next
anecdote.
</P>
<P>
   We grabbed a couple of buckets and headed into the field, where
there were long ranks of blueberry bushes, looking like azaleas
with nandina berries, and half as many blackberries, their leggy
canes trained on stakes and wires to grow in hedgerows. Picking
blueberries is simple, Aly showed us; they're ready when they've
turned from pink to blue-gray. Blackberries are trickier; they go
from plum-red to deep indigo but aren't really ripe until they fall
into the palm at the slightest tug.
</P>
<P>
   I noticed that Luce, his pet hound dog, had followed us and had
her nose stuck in a blueberry bush. ``She eats the blueberries, but
she won't touch the blackberries,'' Aly said. Maybe if dogs could
make cobbler...
</P>
<P>
   Aly left us and we got to work. An hour or so later, we returned
to the weigh stand with two buckets full of berries and fingers the
color of new bluejeans. We had seen Japanese beetles, but no snakes
or chiggers. Aly weighed the produce _ 10 1/2 pounds _ and charged
us $9.70, maybe a fourth what you'd pay at the store. He doesn't
weigh pickers, or we'd have paid twice as much for all the berries
we ate in the field.
</P>
<P>
   While we were settling up, we struck up a conversation with a
couple of regular customers who had clearly never suffered from
brier patch phobia. William and Barbara Yeoman grew up down the
road in Barnesville and have been picking berries all their lives.
``We've been married 13 years, and I don't guess she's bought five
jars of store-bought jelly all that time,'' William said in an
accent as tangy as an unripe blackberry. Barbara smiled bashfully.
``I just like putting things up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   William has a great job for a berry lover; he operates heavy
machinery for the county road department. As he grades dirt roads
way back in the woods, he notes the location of blackberry patches
and muscadine and scuppernong vines. When the time is ripe, he
turns off the machinery, harvests the fruit in his tractor cap and
takes a snack break.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded nice. But the city boy in me wanted to know whether
he'd ever had a close brush with a snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, snakes love to curl up in the old brier patch. I've
run into them plenty of times. Might near stepped on them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this calmly, as if he were talking about stepping over
the family cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what really got me,'' he continued, ``was the day I ate
too many. Some of them had fermented. I got kind of woozy and had
to sit down in the shade.''
</P>
<P>
   PUI _ picking under the influence. That's one blackberrying
danger I hadn't counted on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
