<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sugary to cerebral: Angelique, La Bouche rule dance floor
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   La Bouche _ the creation of disco Frankenstein Frank Farian, the
same man who brought you Boney M and Milli Vanilli _ became dance
music darlings in 1996 with the high-energy hits ``Be My Lover''
and ``Sweet Dreams.'' The duo's perfectly credible sophomore
effort, ``SOS,'' offers more proudly synthetic dance grooves, again
lathered with Melanie Thornton's creamy vocals and Lane McCray's
terse raps.
</P>
<P>
   The first single, ``You Won't Forget Me,'' lives up to its name
_ it's a sassy bit of sexual bravado set to a percolating beat.
Alas, the title track isn't a cover of the Abba classic, but,
incredibly, it's almost as catchy. (Dig McCray's sly chant
``dit-dit-dit, dash-dash-dash, dit-dit-dit.'')
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Indians vocalist Angelique wants you to dance as well, but
she has something more ambitious in mind than La Bouche's sugary
melodies. On her solo debut, the exotic-looking Los Angeleno
fashions herself a hip-hop/techno Fiona Apple. The leadoff track,
``Number,'' pulsates with quasi-industrial intensity, while the
slow groove ``Ruby'' employs baroque-sounding strings to tell the
tale of a jilted girl.
</P>
<P>
   For all their differences, though, the two acts occasionally
touch on similar themes. ``I don't want to be just a number,''
Angelique intones on ``Number,'' while on ``You Won't Forget Me,''
Thornton insists, ``I'm better than the rest.'' In the often
faceless world of dance music, La Bouche and Angelique stand out by
celebrating the individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``SOS''
</P>
<P>
   La Bouche. RCA.
</P>
<P>
   14 tracks
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Cheerfully disposable dance-pop candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Present''
</P>
<P>
   Angelique. Red Ant. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Earnest, techno-tinged tunes for the mind as well
as the hips.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
