<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talented pair still mired in the '70s
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1980, no one would have lumped Lionel Richie and Linda
Ronstadt into the same category. She was the loopy-earring queen of
country rock, he the Afro-and-platform-shoe-wearing lead singer of
the Commodores (and, later, a suave solo act). But here we are,
nearly 20 years later, and these two are stuck on the same page of
the baby-boomer musical yearbook like a time-warped ``cutest
couple.'' On their new albums, neither of these onetime superstars
has changed the formula from the days when they ruled pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   Richie tries to upgrade his smooth '70s vibe on ``Zoomin','' the
opening track, which kicks off with the plucky guitar intro from
TLC's ``Don't Go Chasing Waterfalls.'' And there's an ambitious rap
number, ``To the Rhythm,'' that sounds like Mase on Xanex,
delivering over-the-top, fight-the-power lyrics straight out of the
Temps' ``Ball of Confusion.'' But most of these tunes sound like an
echo of Richie's syrupy 1983 love ballad ``Hello.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronstadt sticks equally close to comfort. Her soprano is still
as hauntingly beautiful as in her ``Love Is a Rose'' days, but most
of these tunes are about as fresh as an owl-shaped macrame wall
hanging.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Raitt and Elton John have both proved there can be life
beyond the '70s. Ronstadt and Richie need to clue in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Ran''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ronstadt. Elektra.11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Still talented, but stuck in a time warp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time''
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Richie.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: See above.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
