<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EINSTEIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spinning bare facts into magical `Einstein'
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The facts are bare. In 1986, love letters between Albert
Einstein and physicist Mileva Maric revealed that in 1902 they had
a child out of wedlock. Mileva went home to Serbia to give birth to
Liserl but left the baby behind when she returned to Einstein in
Switzerland, where they eventually married. A 1903 letter mentioned
that Liserl was ill with scarlet fever. Then she was lost to
history, perhaps adopted, perhaps dead. Einstein probably never saw
her.
</P>
<P>
   Anna McGrail transforms fact into magical realism and brings
Liserl's voice to life in this intelligent, engaging novel that
opens in 1910. Adopted by a Hungarian woman, Liserl is 8 when she
meets Mileva for the only time. The child has inherited her
parents' brilliance in mathematics, and Mileva pays for her
education. Liserl craves her biological mother's unavailable love,
then replaces that hunger with a desire for revenge on the father
who rejected her. When she learns that he is Albert Einstein, she
vows to use her mathematical genius to bring him down.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually World War I forces Liserl to leave Hungary with her
teacher, a curious fraulein named Maja, who metamorphoses into many
guises and becomes younger over time, a word never to be used
loosely in a novel about an Einstein. Liserl, unmindful of history,
prefers to formulate a theory of relativity, to muse over the
nature of light. In Berlin, she marries Josef and has two children,
slow-witted Albertina and precocious Paul. In a challenge to
Einstein's pacifism, she works with the Nazis on creating the
atomic bomb. But hers is a Jewish family, and she learns too late
that ``we are condemned to a world that is more and more chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Maja, adopting new identities, leads Liserl safely through time
and space: from London to Los Alamos. There, disguised as a
secretary in 1945, Liserl corrects the physicists' equations as she
types and gives birth to the bomb. History's invisible daughter
finally confronts her famous father on his deathbed and learns that
``we only ever go backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Science, it seems, wrought the Theory of Relativity, but the
Theory of Everything, which Einstein seeks at the end, lies in the
realm of art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Einstein''
</P>
<P>
   By Anna McGrail. Norton. $24.95. 333 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   A magical exploration of time and space in science and art.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
