<HEADER>
A6518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MEMOIRS-COX     07-01 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MEMOIRS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memoirs show life for blacks in the South
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carrie Allen McCray, daughter of African-American activist Mary
Rice Hayes Allen, remembers a photo of a white man on her mother's
bedroom mantel. Only much later did McCray learn that John Robert
Jones, a Confederate general, was her mother's father. It was part
of a ``monstrous history'' about which Mary Allen never spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Working with a researcher interested in the officer, McCray, now
in her mid-80s, has pieced together the family's past. When she was
16, Malinda Rice, a freed slave, went to work in Harrisonburg, Va.,
for Jones' sickly wife. Malinda had two children by the general,
including the light-skinned Mary. Jones went against custom by
acknowledging paternity and supporting his black children, even
after Malinda died at age 29. For this, and for standing by a later
black mistress and their children, he was essentially written out
of Confederate history. But McCray concludes that her mother was
``a child of two (nurturing) worlds'' who learned self-worth from
the general, who was an integral part of her life, and from her
Uncle John, the ex-slave who raised her.
</P>
<P>
   At age 12, Mary began her fight for ``full freedom'' when she
tried unsuccessfully to integrate an ice cream parlor. The general
sent her to Hartshorn Memorial College and she married black
educator Gregory Hayes, who gave her ``the courage to stand up to
governors, mayors, superintendents of schools, managers of stores,
or whoever she felt she had to confront about injustice.'' They had
seven children, and when he died, she took his place as president
of Virginia Seminary for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Mary's second husband, lawyer William P. Allen, with whom she
had three children, including Carrie, took the family north. In New
Jersey, Mary taught her children to fight racism everywhere. She
made a daughter return again and again to a beauty shop that
refused her service until the owner relented.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Rice Hayes Allen emerges as a courageous worker who
believed that education was the road to freedom and that good, if
insistent, would overcome evil. Her life proved that credo true.
McCray's story about her mother is a welcome, important
reconstruction of the shards of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom's Child: The Life of a Confederate General's Black
Daughter''
</P>
<P>
   By Carrie Allen McCray. Algonquin. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   269 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Southern readers are divided into two types: those whose
families were so changed by the Civil War that it remains of vital
concern to descendants today, and those for whom the conflict is as
distant as the American Revolution. Clay Lewis' memoir will
enthrall the former group, as he shows how the war stamped one
generation after another, so that even 20th-century relationships
are built on residual battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' mother had North Carolina roots, while his father's
family hailed from Mississippi and Oklahoma. After the family
settled in the Washington area, Lewis and his sister grew up in a
dysfunctional home. Lewis' father drank, leading to family
violence, while his mother seemed too aware of their
lower-middle-class status. Over the next few decades, Lewis jumped
in and out of marriages and jobs and struggled with anger and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   He seeks answers to the puzzle of himself in the past, delving
into family history all the way back before the Civil War, even
visiting an old abandoned homestead. What he finds, through partial
reconstruction, explains how he became who he is. He discovers that
his inheritance is the giant absence that the war left _ of lives
lost and a kind of life lost, of fathers who didn't return home. He
finds in himself a historical trace of ``a vast inner night that I
possess more truly than I possess anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the book is sometimes overwritten and overwrought,
there is poetry and a touch of Proust in this fine memoir in which
absence is at the heart of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Battlegrounds of Memory: A Memoir of Southern Family''
</P>
<P>
   By Clay Lewis. University of Georgia Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
