<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evanovich goes from housewife to romance to mysteries
 &HT;    By Don O'Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little more than a decade ago, Janet Evanovich was a housewife
and mother of two who was looking for a way to make some extra
income.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no writing skills,'' Evanovich says. ``I tried (writing)
children's books and was no good at that.'' She proposed a mystery
series about a female private eye, but publishers weren't
interested. Finally, a friend suggested she try writing romance
novels.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, after churning out bodice-rippers such as
``Back to the Bedroom'' and ``Naughty Neighbor,'' Evanovich decided
it was time to try something different. ``I wanted more action,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired while watching ``Midnight Run'' on television one
night, Evanovich created Stephanie Plum, a New Jersey department
store lingerie buyer turned bounty hunter. Her first novel, ``One
for the Money,'' sold to the movies for nearly $1 million, and
Evanovich was on her way to becoming a best-selling author.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta this week to promote her fourth book, ``Four to
Score'' (St. Martin's, $23.95), Evanovich says she tries to lace
her mysteries with lots of humor.
</P>
<P>
   In the new novel, Stephanie's assignment is to track down Maxine
Nowicki, who stole her boyfriend's car and then jumped bail. After
Stephanie's car is blown up, her apartment firebombed and Maxine's
mother scalped, she is so desperate to solve the case that she
hires 83-year-old Grandma Maxur, along with 7-foot transvestite
rock musician Sally Sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made Stephanie in some of my own image, except she's slimmer
and braver,'' says Evanovich.
</P>
<P>
   -- KID STUFF: Encouraged by the success of Rosie O'Donnell's
book ``Kids Are Punny'' (625,000 copies so far), publishers are
scrambling to get similar books onto their fall lists. ``Punny 2''
is coming in October from Warner Books, and ``Kids Say the
Darnedest Things,'' comments gleaned from Bill Cosby's CBS series,
is scheduled for September from Bantam. Also in the works, from
Simon &AMP; Schuster, is ``Dear Socks, Dear Buddy,'' children's letters
to the nation's first pets. Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   -- GRAND OPRAH: The Oprah Winfrey magic continues. When Soho
Press published Edwidge Danticat's debut novel, ``Breath, Eyes,
Memory,'' in 1994, the critically acclaimed book sold 9,000 copies
in hardback and 43,000 copies in a Vintage Contemporaries paperback
edition. After Winfrey picked the novel for her May Book Club
selection, Soho rushed back to press with 20,000 additional copies,
and Vintage printed 600,000. Danticat's next novel, ``The Farming
of Bones'' (Soho, $23), will be published in September with a
50,000 first printing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
