<HEADER>
A6520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIVIEWS02-COX     07-01 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIVIEWS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINI VIEWS: Reviews of movies now on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Amistad'' (R) _ Steven Spielberg's earnest but unbalanced
film is at its best in its wordless moments, including a horrific
glimpse into the sweaty belly of a slave ship and in its opening
minutes, when captured Africans viciously slaughter the ship's crew
and try to retrace their way homeward by following the sun.
Unfortunately, the movie has a lot of talk in it. Based on a
historic 1839 incident, ``Amistad'' grows thick at the middle with
the intricacies of the Africans' court case, argued by Matthew
McConaughey, Morgan Freeman and Anthony Hopkins (as a crotchety
John Quincy Adams).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Long Way Home'' (unrated) _ This powerful,
Oscar-winning 1997 documentary focuses on the overlooked time
between the 1945 liberation of German concentration camps and the
founding of the state of Israel three years later. Freedom from the
horror of genocide was not the end of the war for the Jews. Bereft
of family, property, homes and every trapping of their prewar
lives, the Jews found themselves unwelcome in their former
hometowns and were lumped together for months in U.S.-operated
camps for displaced persons. The film shows their determination to
find a new homeland, often suffering the same sort of hardships
they thought they had left behind during the war. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ma Vie en Rose'' (R) _ In a sunny French suburb, 7-year-old
Ludovic (Georges De Fresne) can't understand all the fuss when he
dons his sister's dresses and announces that he plans to marry the
son of his dad's boss. Director Alain Berliner's candy-colored
comedy interweaves Ludo's fantasy world, involving a Barbie-like
doll named Pam, with the accelerating anger of both neighbors and
his own family as he insists that God made a mistake, that he was
meant to be a girl. The movie is emotionally uneven, but it
elegantly scores its points about intolerance for anything that's
perceived as not ``normal.'' In French with subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``No Looking Back'' (R) _ Wildly overrated
writer-director-star Edward Burns (``The Brothers McMullen'') tries
to get serious in this drama about a waitress (Lauren Holly) torn
between her loyal boyfriend (Jon Bon Jovi) and the handsome heel
who walked out on her three years ago (that would be Burns). It
wants to be a sensitive, if dull, character study of a young woman
learning to make choices. But the problem is that the character is
underwritten and Holly is too pretty and too limited an actress to
make us care. Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Replacement Killers'' (R) _ Hong Kong action star Chow
Yun-Fat aims for a Hollywood crossover in a flick that plays like a
light version of ``The Killer'' and other, better titles. Teaming
with Mira Sorvino as a passport forger, he plays a hit man who
wants out. But the Los Angeles mob would rather kill him first.
Directed by Antoine Fuqua, it's briskly paced, with some
interesting chases. But it lacks the delirious, ante-upping payoffs
of the real-deal flicks directed by John Woo and his colleagues.
Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
