<HEADER>
A6523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKEETERS-BOX-COX     07-01 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKEETERS-BOX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Things that work well: Winning the war against mosquitos
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Removing stagnant water: Mosquitos need water to breed. Dump
or get rid of all containers that collect rain water. Dump plant
dishes and squirt birdbaths with a hose every three days.
</P>
<P>
   -- DEET: DEET _ the active ingredient in many repellents, such
as Off! _ has been used for more than 50 years and is considered
generally safe. However, a few cases of illness and even death have
been reported, so don't use a dose that's too concentrated.
Products containing up to 35 percent DEET are sufficient for
adults; 10 percent is the maximum for children. With these and
other repellents (except permethrin) the user must coat every bit
of exposed skin for effective protection.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bite Blocker: This all-natural repellent formula has been
available in Europe for several years but is a recent arrival in
the United States. Bite Blocker is made of soy, coconut and
geranium oils and has tested as effective as DEET. Some people
dislike its sweet smell and oily texture. Manufacturer: Consep,
Bend, Ore. 1-800-367-8727
</P>
<P>
   -- Citronella-based lotions and sprays: Most repellents
described as ``natural'' contain citronella, which generally
provides shorter protection time than most DEET-based products.
Buzz Away, a spray containing citronella and other natural oils,
provided an average of 88 percent repellency during a two-hour
exposure. Buzz Away manufacturer: Quantum, Eugene, Ore.
1-800-448-1448.
</P>
<P>
   -- Permethrin: An artificial insecticide, permethrin keeps
clothes mosquito-free. It's not for use on the body, so it's
generally used along with a lotion or skin spray. Two brands are
Sawyer Permethrin and Coulston's Duranon, which can be used on
tents and other camping gear as well as clothing. Both are sold in
camping stores.
</P>
<P>
   Things that work less well: Winning a battle against mosquitos
</P>
<P>
   -- Smoke: Studies show citronella candles can reduce the number
of bites, but only for a person who's very close to the candle.
Ingredients in other smoke-producing repellents vary. One, an
incense coil called Eaton's, relies on a chemical called
``allethrin.'' Says Ray Noblet of the University of Georgia, ``It's
fun to use, and it may have some effect, but it's negligible.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Avon Skin-So-Soft: This bath oil received a lot of publicity
several years ago when NASA trainees used it when parachuting into
Florida swamps. In the lab, Skin-So-Soft provided about a half-hour
of protection, a duration 10 times less than DEET. Avon now offers
Skin-So-Soft with citronella, which may be more effective. Avon:
1-800-367-2866
</P>
<P>
   Things that don't work: Surrendering to mosquitos
</P>
<P>
   -- Electric bug zappers: These kill a lot of bugs, but not many
mosquitos. Tests show yards with zappers have about the same number
of mosquitos as those without.
</P>
<P>
   -- The citrosa plant: A genetically engineered geranium hybrid,
these are supposed to emit a citronella aroma that repels
mosquitos. However, in tests in Florida, mosquitos actually landed
on the plant's leaves.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ultrasonic repellent devices: Supposed to mimic other insects
and thus repel biting mosquitos, research shows they don't work.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bat houses: Locked in a room with mosquitos, bats do feed on
the bugs. Outdoors, they seem to prefer other insects.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bug-repellent bracelets: John Gormley of the Fulton
County(Ga.) Health Department is not impressed. ``Bug-repellent
bracelets don't protect anything but the wearer's wrist,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   -- Eating garlic or vitamin B: Says UGA's Noblet, ``I have never
seen any conclusive evidence that what you eat repels mosquitos.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Mosquitos and Mosquito Repellents: A Clinician's
Guide'' by the Annals of Internal Medicine.
(www.acponline.org/journals/annals/01jun98/mosquito.htm);
</P>
<P>
   Wayne J. Crans, Rutgers University
(http://www-rci.rutgers.edu/(tilde)insects/proprom.htm); Cox News
Service staff interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
