</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Declaring war against mosquitos
 &HT;    By Holly Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is it that we can send a man to the moon, but we can't
manage to make our back yards liveable in the summer? Despite years
of spraying, zapping and slapping, mosquitos still seem an
unstoppable menace.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that people haven't tried to get rid of mosquitos. They
have, for centuries. They've drained swamps, covered ponds with
oil, sprayed whole counties with insecticide. More recently,
they've stocked waters with fish that eat mosquito larvae.
</P>
<P>
   But mosquitos are tough customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insect populations evolve and adapt very quickly, rather like
a virus,'' says Ray Noblet, who heads University of Georgia's
Department of Entomology. Their systems can adjust to insecticides
and other manmade changes in their environment.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, mosquitos can travel for miles, so eradicating them
in one area has limited effect.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, mosquitos are a nuisance, but for people who are
allergic to substances in the bugs' mouths, too many bites can
bring on a fever.
</P>
<P>
   And some people just seem to get bitten than others.
``Blood-feeding insects find some individuals more attractive than
others. We don't know why, but this is true whether you're talking
about people or cattle,'' says Noblet.
</P>
<P>
   One such person is Clare Sahling, an Atlanta interior designer
who is turning a grassy embankment by her house into a garden. The
cost in mosquito bites is high.
</P>
<P>
   Sahling says her ``mosquito-magnetism'' forces her to wear an
elaborate costume _ bandanna, blue jeans, high socks and
long-sleeve shirts, all sprayed or soaked in repellent _ to tend
her garden on hot days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out the door and every mosquito in both counties screams
`LUNCH!''' she says. ``Off! is my summer perfume.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bolen, a Northlake accountant, says he's known to
neighborhood mosquitos as ``a good blood meal.'' When he goes
outside, he douses himself with repellent lotion, and resigns
himself to ``let whatever gets through the repellent chew on me.''
</P>
<P>
   As troubling as mosquitos can be, some anti-bug meaures really
do work. With a little information, it's possible to choose a
weapon that succeeds _ and to avoid those that don't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
