<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Ample sunshine, comfortable humidity and seasonable temperatures
will prevail over a large area from the northern Mississippi Valley
to the Northeast coast. High pressure moving east from the Ohio
Valley will promote gentle breezes across most of the region. Some
puffy cumulus clouds will develop near the Appalachians. A few
brief showers or thundershowers will blossom over the mountains of
the central and southern Appalachians later Thursday afternoon as a
jet stream disturbance approaches from the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will persist over the southern Plains and much of
the Southeast. A front separating the hot air mass from the cooler
air over the northern states will be the focus for clusters of
clouds and thundershowers. Local flooding is possible over portions
of the southern Mississippi Valley where thunderstorms pass
repetitively over the same area. Clouds from a tropical disturbance
over the southern Gulf of Mexico will approach the coast of Texas,
but heavy showers are expected to remain offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Some sunshine will yield to scattered strong thunder near the
Canadian border from Montana to Minnesota as a cold front slips
south. Clouds and showers will linger into the night over the
Dakotas and southern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually hot conditions will linger over most of the interior
West. Thunderstorms will form over many mountain peaks during the
afternoon. Most of the West Coast States will be dry and
seasonable. A few strong thunderstorms will form over the mountains
of northern California and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Downburst
</P>
<P>
   A fist of powerful winds called a downburst punched parts of
Pittsburgh Tuesday afternoon, causing widespread damage. As a
series of severe thunderstorms marched across western Pennsylvania,
momentum from fast, high-altitude winds was transferred to the
ground by downdrafts in the thunderstorms. In Pittsburgh, downburst
winds gusted as high as 85 mph in the North Hills section, creating
a swath of damage five miles long and one to two miles wide. Trees
were blown down on homes and power lines. A preliminary report
indicated that 10 people were injured by the downburst.
</P>
</TEXT>
