<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZVEREVA'S ROLL CONTINUES AS SHE OUSTS SELES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Natasha Zvereva had never beaten Steffi Graf before
ousting her from Wimbledon in straight sets last week.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently something about this year's tournament has put a
charge into Zvereva's game, because she ended another winless
streak Wednesday by dumping Monica Seles, 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, to move
into the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on Center Court, Venus Williams was losing to
third-seeded Jana Novotna, 7-5, 7-6 (7-2), and screaming at the
umpire over line calls.
</P>
<P>
   Two calls in particular upset the 18-year-old, who at one point
yelled: ``I know it's out, she knows it's out, everyone knows it's
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the crowd probably enjoyed my emotional
outbursts,'' said Williams, the seventh seed. ``I guess someone
would turn the channel and suddenly see some girl screaming and
keep it there, because I know I would. It probably brightened up
someone's day.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no such histrionics in the Zvereva-Seles match, as
the unseeded native of Belarus eliminated the sixth-seeded former
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played pretty steady from the baseline and I didn't go for
many shots,'' said Zvereva, who was only hoping to make it past the
first round before Wimbledon started. ``I just tried to put the
shots deep and I hit them flat. Usually I intend to put more spin
on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised big time. I'm absolutely thrilled. It's
completely unexpected. It makes it a double pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva held a 4-1 lead at one point in the first set, but she
held her own in the tiebreaker. In the second set, Zvereva broke in
the fourth and sixth games to seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed my backhand all over the place; you just can't do
that,'' said Seles. ``I definitely had quite a few chances, but she
definitely played some really smart tennis. I just didn't feel
anything was going well. Once you miss a few key shots, I got more
uptight with myself and she made some good shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when you walk out there, you can lose every
match,'' added Seles, who had difficulty with her serve as well as
service return. ``It was just my performance that really bugs me,
it's very tough. Today, the standard I was playing was not good.
She's definitely playing better than she used to, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles did advance the farthest at Wimbledon since 1992; she
bowed out in the third round last year.
</P>
<P>
   But this day belonged to the 27-year-old who wears sunglasses
even on shady days and who wants to become the finest farmer ever
in Minsk when her playing days have concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, France's Nathalie Tauziat pulled off another upset by
whipping Lindsay Davenport, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the second seed, hurt herself with an inaccuarte
forehand, while Tauziat changed her strategy and stayed at the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you always go to the net she starts to return well, to
pass well,'' said Tauziat, ``so I mixed it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, the 16th-seeded Tauziat overpowered Davenport, a
surprise since Davenport is 6 feet 2 inches, 175 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now my game is powerful and I worked hard for that
because the tennis game today is very powerful,'' stated Tauziat,
2-0 on grass against Davenport (0-7 on other surfaces). ``I showed
I can play faster and faster and better than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really hitting the ball very hard and I knew this was
her favorite surface coming in,'' said Davenport. ``And once I
started losing a bit of confidence in my forehand, I started
backing up on it. She was putting so much pressure on me, returning
my serve very hard and very deep.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last quarterfinal match, top seed Martina Hingis broke
through to oust fourth-seeded Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, 6-3, 3-6,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to be like playing on clay or hard court and not on
grass,'' Hingis said. ``There was lots of running, long rallies. I
played a very good match, with not too many mistakes. I kept having
40-0 each service game and I kept losing it, so I didn't feel quite
happy about that. I was like, `Come on, not again.' But finally, I
made it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
