<HEADLINE>
THE $600 PC IS HERE _ ANYBODY FOR $500?  
 FLAW IN WORD 98 CAN SPREAD PERSONAL INFORMATION  
 NEW INTERNET LOAN SERVICES NOT FOR FAINT OF HEART  
 THIS ELEPHANT CAN REMEMBER THOSE LOST WEB PAGES  
 NEW LAPTOP BUS PUTS `PORT' BACK IN `PORTABLE'  
 NEW MEXICO INTERNET LAW RULED UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was considered a breakthrough last year when new
Windows-based personal computers were offered for less than $1,000.
But now it looks as if the $500 barrier will be next to crack, at
least if an Internet-based PC company called iDOT continues on its
current pace.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, iDOT (www.idot.com) broke the $600 level with
an entry-level Windows 98-based system that includes a
200-megahertz AMD K6 (Pentium class) processor with MMX technology,
32 megabytes of high-speed SDRAM, a 2.1-gigabyte hard drive, 2MB of
video memory, a 32X CD-ROM drive, and a pair of Universal Serial
Bus ports.
</P>
<P>
   The $599 iDOT system is about as far back in the technology pack
as one can get these days without looking for a hand crank _ the
front edge today is a 400-MHz Pentium II system _ but it is a
workable computer for those who have modest computing needs and
whose primary interest is low price.
</P>
<P>
   For an extra $79, users can add an upgraded sound card, speakers
and a 56K modem, and for another $99, a 15-inch monitor. (A 17-inch
monitor is $199 extra.) With a $199 Canon BJC 4300 color printer,
the total system price is $976, which is a few bucks cheaper than
any other comparable new system found on www.pricescan.com, a
comparative shopping service on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   A Gateway salesman named Leo snorted derisively when a caller
asked what Gateway had in the sub-$600 price range. ``I can tell
you where your $599, 200-megahertz K6 system will be one year from
now _ an expensive doorstop,'' Leo said. He advised spending $1,200
for a faster Pentium-based system.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Advanced Micro Devices said he was not sure
whether AMD still made the 200-MHz K6 chip _ it does not _ and
suggested that the faster 266-MHz chip was ``the sweet spot'' for
entry-level PCs these days.
</P>
<P>
   While competitors carped about iDOT's 200-megahertz system, the
Austin, Texas-based company shut them up by cutting the price of
its leading-edge 400-MHz Pentium II computer to $1,699.
</P>
<P>
   When will we see new Windows 98-compatible computers slip below
the $500 mark? Mark Marlow, iDOT's vice president for marketing,
said it could happen before the end of the year. _ PETER H. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Flaw in Word 98 Can Spread Your Personal Information
</P>
<P>
   It's a paranoid computer user's worst nightmare: private
information from your hard disk made accessible for the reading
enjoyment of strangers. And it could happen if you use Microsoft
Word 98 for Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   As reported last week on the MacInTouch Web page
(www.macintouch.com), hidden chunks of old e-mail, disk-directory
paths, Web addresses and other confidential information from the
user's hard drive or RAM can be embedded in Microsoft Word 98
documents. The unintended information can be made visible when the
documents are opened with a text-editing program like BBEdit, thus
making e-mailed or networked files a potential security risk.
</P>
<P>
   Users have blamed the glitch on Word 98 failing to overwrite
previously stored data in the hard drive when it saves a file to
the same part of the disk. In MacWeek magazine, a Microsoft
spokesperson acknowledged the problem and stated that the bug rises
from the file-deletion methods used by Macintosh operating system.
</P>
<P>
   According to MacInTouch, however, similar problems have also
been reported in Microsoft Office 97 for Windows and Adobe
PageMaker files. The site notes that Microsoft posted an
appropriate patch for Windows 95 on its Web site, but that the
company was still investigating the Macintosh problem. _ J.D.
BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   New Internet Loan Services Not for the Faint of Heart
</P>
<P>
   Applying for a loan is an eerie process. You disclose
information about yourself that you'd be loath to share with your
shrink, and then wait while numbers get vetted and crunched by
anonymous clerks at the lender's offices.
</P>
<P>
   Online mortgages make the process eerier still _ yet more
satisfying for those who prefer instant gratification. Spend
fifteen minutes tapping your personal finance information into a
database out in cyberspace and within a few hours you've
prequalified. No unnecessary interaction with humans need take
place.
</P>
<P>
   Several e-loan services are already well established. They
include E-loan, Quicken and Home Shark. The types of loans they
offer include mortgages, home equity, personal, auto, credit cards
and debt consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1997, $482 million in loans had originated on the
Internet, according to a report from Forrester Research. The same
report predicts that this number will reach $40.5 billion by 2001.
The latest entrant is Lending Tree (www.lendingtree.com), an online
loan center that distinguishes itself from the others by sending
applicants to multiple lenders simultaneously, and having those
lenders bid against each other for the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Like its competitors, Lending Tree has a privacy statement in
which it assures customers that it will not sell or share any
personal information with any organization, other than the lenders
to whom they send the applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take great precautions in handling personal information,''
said Douglas Lebda, president of Lending Tree. Such disclosures are
an improvement over the physical loan applications, where no such
overt assurances are made. Still, it might take some time before
people feel comfortable tossing their social security numbers and
salary information out into cyberspace. _ KATIE HAFNER
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This Elephant Can Remember Those Lost Web Pages
</P>
<P>
   Want to recall that fabulous Web page you found yesterday? You
know, the one you forgot to bookmark?
</P>
<P>
   If that happens to you often, you might be suffering from
internesia (the inability to remember important Internet
information.) For people who do suffer from internesia or whose Web
bookmarks can fill a disk drive, help may be on the way. Elephant
Tracks, a new downloadable program, watches where a Web browser
goes and allows users to retrace their footprints.
</P>
<P>
   The program was written by Ed Staub, a 44-year-old programmer
who said he found himself suffering from internesia around New
Year's. ''I had this problem and looked for a solution,'' Staub
said. ``I couldn't find it, so I wrote this.''
</P>
<P>
   Elephant Tracks indexes the words on Web pages that are viewed.
When people need to look up an earlier page, they can search the
index for that page. Staub said it is much easier then looking
through a history folder or hitting the back button, and certainly
handier than a bookmarks list that goes on and on. ''It is an
infallible extension to a fallible memory,'' Staub said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to find a lot of users for the product, saying that
the average age of the Internet user has gone from 32 to 38 in the
past two years. Elephant Tracks for Internet Explorer costs $24.95
and may be downloaded from www.elephantsoftware.com. A version for
Netscape Navigator should be ready in September. _ STEVEN E. BRIER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Laptop Bus Puts the ``Port'' Back in Portable
</P>
<P>
   Laptops are more mobile than desktop models, but they have their
own problems, including smaller screens, smaller keyboards and less
useful pointing devices. You can buy full-size peripherals for your
desk but as subnotebook manufacturers downsize their machines, they
often leave off ports. A port replicator is one solution, but they
are not available for many machines.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona company wants laptop users to hop on the Bus, a
universal port replicator that plugs into the PC Card slot on
almost any notebook. Connect all the peripherals into the Bus, they
say, plug the Bus into an available Type II PC card slot and you
are rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Made by CNF, Inc. (www.cnfinc.com), the device supports
industry-standard serial, parallel and video ports, as well
keyboard and mouse peripherals. The current model works with
Windows/Intel machines. _ STEVEN E. BRIER
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico Internet Law Ruled Unconstitutional
</P>
<P>
   Laws that seek to protect minors from Internet pornography may
be palatable to politicians and voters. But thus far, they haven't
passed muster with the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a law was to take effect in New Mexico that would
have made it a misdemeanor to ``knowingly or intentionally''
transmit sexual content, including ``actual or simulated nudity,
sexual intercourse or any other sexual conduct'' to a minor. Late
Tuesday, however, a federal judge issued an opinion enjoining the
legislation and declaring that it violates the First, Fifth and
Fourteenth amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Judge LeRoy Hansen, a U.S. District Court judge for the District
of New Mexico, ruled that the proposed law threatens the ability of
adults to post and share such content among themselves, and the
capacity of minors to receive constitutionally protected speech,
such as art.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the judge ruled that the law would have given New Mexico
the right to regulate trade in other states, which is a not allowed
under the Fourteenth Amendment's Commerce Clause.
</P>
<P>
   The decision should come as no surprise given the fate of two
similar laws. In June 1997 the U.S. Supreme Court threw out the
Communications Decency Act, which would have made it a felony to
send ``indecent'' material to minors. _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
</TEXT>
