<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COMPANY BUYS ANOTHER NEW ENGLAND DAIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another sign of rapid consolidation in the dairy industry,
West Lynn Creamery Inc. said Wednesday it has been acquired by the
same Texas company that acquired Garelick Farms a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies will now be owned by Suiza Foods Corp., a $1.8
billion-a-year Dallas &UR;  &LR; distribution firm and holding company.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its home base, Suiza runs dairy operations up and
down the East Coast and in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the all-cash transaction were not disclosed. Layoffs
and plant closings are not expected at closely held West Lynn, of
Lynn, Mass., said Suiza chairman and chief executive Gregg L.
Engles.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, West Lynn chief executive Arthur Pappathanasi
said he and his management team will continue to run the dairy,
which has estimated annual sales of $215 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partnership with Suiza...offers us access to capital
necessary to continue our expansion in both our dairy and ice cream
operations,'' Pappathanasi said.
</P>
<P>
   Engles pointed out that West Lynn primarily serves food service
customers while Garelick Farms, of Franklin, Mass., is more focused
on supplying dairy products to grocery chains.
</P>
<P>
   Savings can be realized by ``rationalizing'' the distribution
systems of Garelick Farms and West Lynn, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, opportunities could arise where one truck could
deliver milk to a grocery store and a nearby food-service customer
rather than dispatching different trucks to each location as
Garelick Farms and West Creamery do now.
</P>
<P>
   There may also be ways for the two companies to save money on
advertising and marketing costs, Engles said.
</P>
<P>
   Dairies have been traditionally a regional business.
</P>
<P>
   There were once about ``15 players'' in the Northeast market,
many of them family owned, and that number has fallen to about 10,
according to Engles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire dairy industry is consolidating,'' said CJS
Securities analyst Arnold Ursaner, who follows Suiza.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming a public company in 1996, Suiza has ridden
the &UR;  &LR; surging stock market to make nearly 40 acquisitions; in the
last year or so, its stock has risen from $14 a share to about $60.
</P>
<P>
   Under Engles, who has a background as an investment banker and
merger-and-acquisitions expert, Suiza seems to be in a race with
Illinois-based Dean Foods Co., as both look to piece together a
national distribution network of dairy operations.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent fiscal year, Dean made nine acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   With all this consolidation going on, a few big operations now
tend to dominate a region, and some smaller players are feeling the
squeeze, Ursaner said.
</P>
<P>
   What Suiza does is to ``offer independent dairy entrepreneurs a
reasonable exit strategy'' with an acquisition offer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With estimated annual revenues of more than $500 million,
Chelsea-based H.P. Hood Inc. said it has succesfully competed for
years with Garelick Farms in supermarkets and with West Lynn in the
food-service segment of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't change a lot for us because we compete with them in
different channels,'' said chief operating officer Jeffrey Stephen
of Hood, which is now owned by the Kaneb family.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, having Garelick and West Lynn owned by the same
Texas conglomerate is more likely to hurt smaller players than
someone as big as Hood, Ursaner said.
</P>
<P>
   For fiscal 1997, Suiza reported a profit of $28.8 million on
sales of $1.79 billion. On the New York Stock Exchange, shares of
Suiza closed at 59 7/8, up 3/16 Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
