<P>
   STARR-HUBBELL (Washington) _ In a blow to Whitewater
prosecutors, a federal judge dismisses the tax evasion case against
former Justice Department official and presidential friend Webster
Hubbell. U.S. District Judge James Robertson says a Hubbell motion
seeking dismissal ``will be granted.'' By Stephen Labaton. With
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The nation's manufacturers are slowing
production. In the latest evidence of a slowdown, the National
Association of Purchasing Managers reports that manufacturing
activity turned in its weakest performance in nearly two years
during June. By Louis Uchitelle. With FED.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-ELDERLY (Cedar Rapids, Iowa) For Milford Hartz, the
adrenaline started to flow right about the time that the
teal-colored deluxe motor coach bus pulled into the parking lot in
front of the Wal-Mart store, located right behind the Royal Fork
Buffet restaurant. It was 8:30 a.m. and the bus was soon loaded
with over 30 elderly adults, most of whom had spent a lifetime of
early morning hours toiling on the surrounding farms and in nearby
factories. With hundreds of casinos scattered throughout 26 states,
and a growing population of seniors looking for places where they
can socialize, find companionship and be a part of something that
is lively and new, casino gambling has become a favorite pastime
for older Americans. By Brett Pulley. With photo. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Shanghai, China) _ President Clinton, in his last
address to a mass audience in China, says Wednesday that he will
continue to speak out on behalf of democracy and individual
liberty, but that the United States does not seek to dictate to
China the path of its development. In an interview with China's
main government-run television network, Clinton said that China's
current course of economic liberalization and greater personal
freedom is ``morally right,'' and that the status of the United
States as the world's lone superpower did not give it the right to
use its economic and military right to impose its values on China
or any other nation. The interview with China Central Television is
to be broadcast on Thursday. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-ELECT-ASSESS (Montgomery, Ala.) _ As a battle for the soul
of Southern Republicanism, the Alabama primary that Gov. Fob James
Jr. won so convincingly on Tuesday reinforced a number of political
truths about the party and the region. Religious conservatives
still wield immense influence. Strong stands against taxes still
sell. Race still matters. And even as Southerners take a leading
role in national politics, they still resent federal intrusion.
Each of those factors played a role in James's surprisingly
conclusive victory over Winton Blount 3d, a Montgomery businessman,
in their hard-fought primary runoff. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
