<SLUG> BC-BALLET-AFTER-MEJIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE FORT WORTH DALLAS BALLET, BALANCHINE IS OUT, ECLECTIC IS
IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new coach, a new conductor, a new director _ sometimes it
means a continuation of the old style under a new person. Sometimes
it means a whole new epoch.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet, the departure of Paul Mejia,
50, as artistic director and the arrival of Benjamin Houk, 36,
definitely means a new era.
</P>
<P>
   It is the end of Fort Worth Dallas Ballet's years as the most
strongly Balanchine-devoted company in America, and the beginning
of a post-Balanchine era.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographer George Balanchine (1904-83) arrived in the United
States in 1922, in the post-Revolutionary wave of refugees from the
old Russian empire. From his base in New York, he created a style
of ballet rooted in the Russian tradition but capturing the energy
and breadth of America. It focused on the beauty of the female body
and was accompanied by musical masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine lived in a manner that was materially modest _ he
ironed his own shirts _ and sexually extravagant _ including a
string of affairs and ballerina wives _ while creating the greatest
body of choreographic masterpieces in history for his company, the
New York City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   His influence in ballet is comparable to that of Beethoven in
music or Shakespeare in drama: From now to eternity, not a step
will be taken on any ballet stage anywhere that will not contain a
bit of Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   His numerous pupils spread the Balanchine gospel around the
world. Paul Mejia, who earned Balanchine's ire in 1969 when he
married Balanchine's favorite ballerina, Suzanne Farrell, is one of
dozens of still-active apostles who knew Balanchine in person, who
worked with him in the studio and who learned his style and
philosophy from direct contact.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's professional adoration of Balanchine, unencumbered by
their personal feud, was reflected in the way the dancers in the
Fort Worth Dallas Ballet looked and moved _ and in the repertory
they danced for over a decade, devoted entirely to works of
Balanchine and works by Mejia in a style that was an unmistakable
extension of Balanchine's.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 years, under Mejia's guidance, Fort Worth audiences came
to know and love Balanchine's creations, from ``Serenade'' to
``Apollo'' to ``Western Symphony'' to ``Jewels'' _ a varied
universe of dance, all from one source.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the pupils of Balanchine's pupils are filling the ranks.
Benjamin Houk never knew Balanchine. But he danced for 13 years,
eight as a principal, in another Balanchine-focused company, the
Pacific Northwest Ballet, which was directed by two Balanchine
dancers, Kent Stowell and Francia Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole dance world is built on Balanchine's genius,'' Houk
says. ``As in music, one era builds on another. Baroque goes to
classical, classical goes to romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in dance, Balanchine leads to post-Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean we stop dancing Balanchine ballets,'' Houk
says. But it does mean that the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet will dance
fewer works by Balanchine and more works by other choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's season in Fort Worth, arranged by consultant Bruce
Marks after Mejia's resignation in January and before Houk's
appointment in June, includes only two relatively short works by
Balanchine, and a whole range of works by major choreographers
previously unknown on the live stage in Fort Worth: Antony Tudor
and Agnes de Mille from earlier in the 20th century, for instance;
Marius Petipa from the 19th; and, from our own time, Lila York and
Kent Stowell.
</P>
<P>
   Houk, who will arrive in Fort Worth this month, says that future
seasons will probably have a little more Balanchine _ three or four
works _ but that the general pattern has been set for a mix of
established choreographers, historical pieces and contemporary
choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   And Houk has promised a more eclectic company. In the
traditional pieces, audiences will see more of ballet the way it
looked before Balanchine. (Although Balanchine worshipped the
female form, he also helped liberate the male dancer from the
stand-up role.) We'll see a calmer, more picturesque image of
ballet than Balanchine envisioned in some of the 20th-century
works, with more overt development of character and plot _ as in
Tudor's ``Lilac Garden'' and De Mille's ``Rodeo.''
</P>
<P>
   And we'll occasionally move into the anything-goes realm, where
the lines between modern dance and ballet blur. Physically, it
won't be harder for the dancers, but it will stretch them
emotionally and philosophically. Instead of working with just the
half-century of dance marked by Balanchine's career, they will be
asked to go back to the 19th century and forward to the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Houk expects to present a few of his own works through the
years, but he certainly won't be present as a choreographer to the
extent that Mejia was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're combining elements of contemporary dance and strong
classical technique,'' Houk says.
</P>
<P>
   That's all right with Barbara Horgan, general director of the
Balanchine Trust, the New York City Ballet-based organization that
controls the performance rights to Balanchine ballets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think an artistic director should have the freedom to
present whatever ballets he feels are right for his company and
audience,'' she says. ``Even Mr. Balanchine would have criticized
an all-Balanchine company.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Fort Worth Dallas Ballet still a ``Balanchine'' company?
</P>
<P>
   ``That label becomes less important and significant as
repertoire becomes more eclectic, as the lines are blurred,'' Houk
says. ``We're an `American' company.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
