<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GUIDE-COVERS-NYT &LR;      07-01 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUIDE-COVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM COFFEE-TABLE CLUTTER TO COVETED COLLECTIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Batscha was wary. ``I really don't think you
should say,'' the president of the Museum of Television and Radio
cautioned a second time as Steven Reddicliffe's finger came close
to pointing out TV Guide's most valuable cover.
</P>
<P>
   Reddicliffe, the magazine's editor in chief, eyed Batscha
quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you just say which covers are most collectible,
rather than mentioning what they're worth,'' Batscha advised.
</P>
<P>
   Surely there aren't fanatics out there who would try to rip a
plexiglass-encased TV Guide cover off the wall of the museum's
galleries, at 25 W. 52nd St. in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have security,'' Batscha replied, a bit indignantly.
Then he sighed. ``I guess this is what Philippe de Montebello has
to deal with all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of ``A Television Diary: 45 Years of TV Guide
Covers,'' which runs through Aug. 31 at the Museum of Television
and Radio, fail to see any irony in linking their show to those
overseen by the director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on April 3, 1953, when a newborn Desi Arnaz Jr. gazed
winsomely from the first cover of Walter Annenberg's new creation,
the ``bible of television'' has aspired to greater heights than
mere coffee-table clutter.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,350 covers later, and well into Desi Jr.'s middle age,
the magazine has racked up enough commissions by prominent artists
_ 37 Hirschfelds, two Charles Addams, a Rockwell, a Peter Max, a
Warhol and (could it be?) a Dali _ to invade The New Yorker's turf
and to catapult its status at least as high as a television tower.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors can discuss their newest acquisitions on some 15
sites on the Internet. So big, in fact, is cover collecting that it
warranted its own ``Seinfeld'' episode. (TV Guide returned the
favor by issuing a special collectible four-cover farewell to the
sitcom.)
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, according to a press release, strives to show
``how far television (and society) has come in its depiction of the
American family,'' and 400 covers are categorized to do just that:
``The Viewer on Television,'' ``History: Fact and Fiction,''
``Spies and Private Eyes,'' ``Friends and Neighbors'' and, yes,
``The Changing Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Even animals get their own category. (What else to do with
Lassie and her _ uh, his _ 11 covers?) But after hundreds of
covers, most of them unflinchingly upbeat and energetic, a viewer
may wonder just whose society is on view.
</P>
<P>
   Consider ``The Changing Family.'' If the '50s were idyllic _ and
they were if you believe the scenes of domestic tranquillity on
``Ozzie and Harriet'' and ``Father Knows Best'' _ then the '60s and
the '70s were blissful. Fred MacMurray and two of his three
television sons frolic aboard a Schwinn; Bonnie Franklin, Mackenzie
Phillips and Valerie Bertinelli keep a lid on their ``One Day at a
Time'' hysterics; even Archie Bunker smiles winningly from his
La-Z-Boy. Only the women of ``Good Times'' manage to conjure a
prickly distance deemed appropriate to the show's theme of racial
struggles. By the '90s, ``Roseanne'' comes out smelling like the
Avon lady.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the news category. ``Since the early days of
television, we have trusted journalists to tell us what's going on
in the world around us'' reads the accompanying release.
</P>
<P>
   Trust an avuncular Walter Cronkite, dressed in gray wool and
thoughtfully caressing his pipe? Most definitely. Trust the ``60
Minutes'' correspondents as they surround a paper-strewn conference
table, serious expressions all? Yes, probably. Trust Barbara
Walters wearing a mad polka-dot print, giant hoop earrings and her
hair in a major flip? Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: TV Guide did go with the flow, mirroring
its vast readership. It began with a circulation of 1.5 million and
has grown to a readership of 13 million, making it the
largest-selling weekly magazine in the country. The cover
photographs from the '60s recreate the era's psychedelic energy as
the Hullabaloo Dancers do the monkey in Douglas Kirkland's
strobe-effect sequence, as a groovy Tom Jones throws out a
succession of hipster gestures in Prigent's collage, or as Mike
Connors takes cool aim on Gene Trindl's quadruple-exposure
``Mannix'' cover. Richard Amsel's pale pastel drawings capture the
'70s hair infatuation in the feathered fantasy dos of ``Charlie's
Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   The '90s fixation on body, if not soul, is evident in cheesecake
shots of Teri Hatcher, Jenna Elfman and the ``Baywatch'' babes,
even if their bodies were covered, peculiarly, by bold type. ``The
type was a dynamic feature of the cover and there was lots of it,''
said Reddicliffe. OK, but only from the neck down?
</P>
<P>
   And what about those Hirschfelds of subjects including Lawrence
Welk, Bob Hope and Lassie, her ears woven with Nina's? Or Warhol's
multiple of Barbara Feldon from ``Get Smart''? Or Dali's Surrealist
view of television, amputated thumbs implanted with television
screens?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were special commissions,'' Reddicliffe said. ``We try
to come up with something unique when the situation warrants it.''
</P>
<P>
   (For the record, covers by famous artists aren't necessarily the
most valuable. That honor goes to a mint-condition first cover of
baby Desi Arnaz Jr., valued at $3,000, although the ``Superman''
cover, with George Reeves in the Sept. 25, 1953, edition, runs a
close second. Both are in the exhibition, which moves to the
museum's Los Angeles galleries from Sept. 10 through December.)
</P>
<P>
   Other unusual situations have required a two-part ``X-Files''
cover where opposing halves of David Duchovny's face, bought
separately in the same week, could be matched to make a whole; a
four-part ``Simpsons'' cover that joined end-to-end to become the
family's couch, and a four-part ``Star Trek'' cover, each part
featuring a different crew member, that when joined form the
fleet's insignia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to have fun,'' said Reddicliffe, pointing to the
magazine's ubiquitous red logo. ``It's not always red. Sometimes
we'll change the color of the logo to match the uniform of a sports
team. Other times we'll have an animator deal with it creatively,
bitten off by the Cookie Monster or chiseled away at by Fred
Flintstone.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains the jumping. Lucille Ball in black leotard, above
a hothouse flower. (The most popular subject of all, Ball had 31 of
her own covers.) Sonny and Cher, captured midflight with their hair
_ lots of it _ swaying to the beat. The cast of ``Third Rock From
the Sun'' decked out in '60s paraphernalia with legs akimbo.
Regardless of the decade or even the topic, TV Guide liked to shoot
its subjects with their feet off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word is always energy,'' said Reddicliffe. ``It's high
energy that really captures your eye and conveys your authority.
Jumping is good.'' Reddicliffe pointed to Lucy Lawless' ``Xena: The
Warrior Princess'' cover as an example of ``spontaneous energy.''
But for all that energy, the superhero Xena isn't jumping. ``Oh,
well,'' shrugged Reddicliffe. ``Maybe it's the armor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
