<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-PLANS-ART-3RDTA     07-01 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-PLANS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 WICKFORD, R.I.: love it.''   &HT;    HOW DO THE STARS (AND NEAR-STARS) MEASURE UP?
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Ireton, the editor of Fine Homebuilding magazine, spends
his days scrutinizing blueprints and renderings, anxiously
delivered by architects hoping for a display in his pages.
</P>
<P>
   A former builder, Ireton can spot an ineffective layout, an
unbuildable roof, an indecipherable plumbing diagram. He agreed to
review the mail-order plans of five architects _ Robert A.M. Stern,
Michael Graves, Dennis Wedlick, Sarah Susanka and Duo Dickinson _
including Stern's Life magazine house, one of the most popular of
the ``dream houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Praising the ``strong detailing'' in the plans _ a hallmark of
an architect-designed house _ Ireton noted that those details make
a house trickier to build. ``There isn't a house here I would build
without a really competent builder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of his observations.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A.M. Stern
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL APPRAISAL _ It's rare that a builder gets to deal with
such extensive, well-detailed plans as his 1994 Life dream house
($505). Stern even specifies the pattern of the bathroom tile and
offers a dozen different cutouts for the shutters.
</P>
<P>
   CONSTRUCTION _ Designed for a flat site.
</P>
<P>
   PROS AND CONS _ The foundation is complicated, with many jogs
and bays. The octagonal first-floor bedroom might be done more
cheaply by cantilevering it over a rectangular foundation. For a
gutsier look, Stern uses heavier _ and more expensive _
two-by-sixes for interior walls rather than the normal
two-by-fours. Custom windows and a roof that is very tricky to
frame are all part of the charm, but cost more money.
</P>
<P>
   COST _ The most expensive: I wouldn't be surprised to hear it
cost $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Graves
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL APPRAISAL _ His 1996 Life dream house ($505) is an
amalgam of traditional and industrial shapes.
</P>
<P>
   CONSTRUCTION _ Designed for a flat site.
</P>
<P>
   PROS AND CONS _ This is a fairly easy house to build. Graves
literally threw a curve into the design by adding one of his
trademarks _ a rotunda, complicating what had been an easy roof to
frame. But don't let the builder talk you into a square gallery:
the rotunda is the thing you fell in love with. The exterior
detailing is the cleanest of all five houses. Builders may see
dollar signs when they catch the copper-clad chimney, but it may
not be more expensive than masonry. Graves puts glazing to good
effect by keeping the number of windows low, then splurging on the
wall of windows over the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   COST _ In the $250,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Wedlick
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL APPRAISAL _ His 1995 Life dream house ($505) has the
simplest footprint _ a rectangle with a striking roof. While Stern
uses traditional details, Wedlick plays with textures and shapes.
</P>
<P>
   CONSTRUCTION _ Designed for a flat site, but like the Stern and
Graves plans, it can be rotated to capture views and light.
</P>
<P>
   PROS AND CONS _ A contractor must be very good to build the
steep roof and work out the way it meets the eaves. The roof will
cost more, but if anybody tried to build this house with a
shallower roof, I think I'd shoot him. One advantage: The plans
list the stock molding numbers and make use of manufactured
windows, which saves time and money.
</P>
<P>
   COST _ One of the least expensive houses _ but to be done right,
at least $250,000 in the Northeast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Susanka
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL APPRAISAL _ Her 1998 Better Homes and Gardens Home Plan
Ideas plan ($430) is deceptively complex; it looks simple but is
carefully thought out.
</P>
<P>
   CONSTRUCTION _ Of the four houses, this is the most
site-specific _ designed for a steep south-facing slope. It could
be built on a flat site but would not be nearly as charming. If you
built on a north-facing slope, you'd want to add more
energy-efficient, possibly smaller, windows.
</P>
<P>
   PROS AND CONS _ The plans are smaller and more difficult to read
than the others; the house is harder to visualize. To work,
everything must line up perfectly. But the roof is framed by
manufactured trusses, so you can get the house ``out of the
weather'' quickly, a plus in cold climates.
</P>
<P>
   COST _ It would probably cost between $300,000 and $325,000 in
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Duo Dickinson
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL APPRAISAL _ His 1997 Better Homes and Gardens plan
($300) is the most unusual and contemporary house. The structure
and many details are built with cement. (It was commissioned by the
Portland Cement Association.)
</P>
<P>
   CONSTRUCTION _ Designed for a flat lot and difficult to rotate
because of the elaborate front entrance. Because of the material,
the design is full of zoomy details like sweeping arched ceilings
and columns.
</P>
<P>
   PROS AND CONS _ Many builders will be scared off by the
unconventional concrete wall system. If they aren't, they may come
to love the system _ which is designed to be put together quickly _
and want a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   COST _ Ireton declined to give an estimate, but Dickinson said
the house was built for $340,000 in Indianapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
