<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-AGENT-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITCH TO NEW AGENT IS WOODY ALLEN'S LATEST
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Woody Allen, who has overhauled most of his longtime
production staff, has abruptly left his New York-based agent as he
vigorously pursues an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 years with Sam Cohn, the vice chairman of International
Creative Management in New York, Allen has decided to move to the
William Morris Agency, where he will be represented by John
Burnham, executive vice president of the agency and a head of its
motion picture department in Los Angeles. Diane Keaton, a longtime
friend of Allen's, has been Burnham's client for 15 years. She
introduced the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's move caught Hollywood agents, executives and producers
by surprise. Although directors and stars periodically leave their
agents, especially if they endure a flop or two, Allen's long-term
bond with Cohn was considered unbreakable.
</P>
<P>
   Allen declined to comment on the change, except to issue a
statement through Leslee Dart, his spokeswoman, saying, ``Sam and I
had a long and productive professional relationship and remain
close friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But two of Allen's associates said that he had decided to leave
Cohn, a venerable agent in New York's theatrical and literary
community, partly because, he felt, the Los Angeles-based Burnham
was better suited to find him acting roles periodically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's keen on acting; he wants more choices and
opportunities,'' said one of Allen's associates, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has acted in only a handful of movies made by other
filmmakers, but he is now interested in finding more roles,
associates said. Allen starred with Bette Midler in the 1991 comedy
``Scenes from a Mall,'' directed by Paul Mazursky. The movie was a
box-office disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn's clients include actors such as Paul Newman, Susan
Sarandon and Sigourney Weaver, as well as writers E.L. Doctorow,
Arthur Miller and Nora Ephron.
</P>
<P>
   Why Allen is seeking more acting roles is unclear, but film
parts are often lucrative and, as one of his associates said, ``can
be a lot of fun.'' But Allen is not expected to limit his
remarkable output of films; he releases about a movie a year. His
next film, ``Celebrity,'' set to be released in the fall, stars,
among others, Leonardo DiCaprio, Winona Ryder, Kenneth Branagh and
Judy Davis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Associates of Allen said that Ms. Keaton had introduced Allen to
Burnham several years ago, and that the two men had established a
friendly relationship. Burnham has visited Allen in New York
several times. When Allen visited Los Angeles late last year for
the first time in about 20 years, Burnham had a party at his home
for him. Allen was in Los Angeles to promote his film
``Deconstructing Harry.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen's decision to leave Cohn comes after the filmmaker's moves
over the last year to substantially overhaul the tightly knit
production staff that has been with him for decades and helped
fashion classics like ``Annie Hall,'' ``Manhattan'' and ``Hannah
and Her Sisters.'' The departures included Allen's longtime
producer, Robert Greenhut, as well as his associate producer, film
editor, cinematographer, set photographer and costume designer.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup of the Allen team was sought and made by Jean
Doumanian, Allen's current producer and his best friend for 30
years, who wanted to cut costs. In recent years, Allen's films,
most of them highly praised, have not earned money in the United
States but remain popular abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Doumanian's company, Jean Doumanian Productions, is financed
by Sweetland Films, an independent company of mostly European
investors, who took over the financing of Allen's films.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn and Burnham declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   One top talent agent, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said that the Allen move, while unexpected, did not come as a
shock. ``He's changed everything else in his life,'' he said, ``so
why not change agents too?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
