<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-DIVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON SELLING WESTERN MASSACHUSETTS BRANCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BankBoston Corp. said Wednesday that it had agreed to sell its
Berkshire County operations to Banknorth Group, Inc. of Burlington,
Vt., for $52 million, shedding for the second time in a decade its
presence in the western Massachusetts region.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is a sign that mid-sized and superregional banks are
keen to pare operations in markets deemed more suitable for
community banks. In an era of mergers and consolidations, larger
banks cannot achieve big earnings growth serving smaller areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our geographic separation and less urban market lends itself
more to a community banking approach, where we can be agile and
focused in meeting the specific needs of the region,'' said Steven
H. Massicotte, who oversees BankBoston's Berkshire County
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Under Wednesday's deal, Banknorth, which owns seven community
banks throughout Vermont, New Hampshire and Massachusetts, will
gain 10 BankBoston branches with retail, consumer, small business,
and commercial lending operations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to close in the third quarter, will not
result in management changes or layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, New England's second-largest bank, had four branches
in Berkshire County in the 1980s. Known then as Bank of Boston, it
sold them in 1989 but re-entered the area four years later when it
bought Multibank Financial Corp. of Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Banknorth will gain approximately $285 million in deposits and
$120 million in loans from BankBoston's Berkshire operations.
BankBoston's private banking, trust and investment management units
in the area will become part of a Banknorth subsidiary, The
Stratevest Group
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston is the nation's 16th-largest bank holding company,
with $71.4 billion in assets, operations in Latin America, and a
national corporate lending unit. The company nudged up 1 3/4 to
close at 57 3/8 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
