<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: HOLLYWOOD IN BOHEMIA; EXCHANGING `ART'; JAPANESE
VOCALIST HONORED; MIDLER PLAYS SUSANN; FREE CONCERTS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Great Britain, Canada)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Honors await Michael Douglas, Lauren Bacall and Rod Steiger at
the 33rd Karlovy Vary International Film Festival, beginning Friday
in the Bohemian spa town once known as Carlsbad, west of Prague in
the Czech Republic. Douglas will receive the Special Prize for
Outstanding Contribution to World Cinema; Ms. Bacall and Steiger
will receive Life Achievement Prizes. The festival runs until July
11 with feature films and documentaries in competition. The
festival's Special Prize will go to Saul Zaentz, the producer of
``Amadeus,'' ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' and ``The English
Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Frame of Reference
</P>
<P>
   In a display of ``Art'' for art's sake, London audiences will
get a chance to see the Tony Award-winning American version of
Yasmina Reza's play ``Art,'' while Broadway theatergoers will see
Britain's Olivier Award-winning version.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an agreement between British and American Equity, the
exchange will begin on July 28, when Stacy Keach, George Wendt and
David Dukes will step, respectively, into the roles of Marc, Serge
and Yvan in the comedy at Wyndham's Theater in London. In
September, a British cast will take over in ``Art'' at the Royale
Theater on Broadway, where Alan Alda, Victor Garber and Alfred
Molina are currently Marc, Serge and Yvan.
</P>
<P>
   Both productions were directed by Matthew Warchus, and most of
the differences consist of colloquialisms and turns of phrase
appropriate for the audiences of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Throats
</P>
<P>
   Mieko Sato of Japan has won the gold medal in the women's vocal
division at the Tchaikovsky international music competition in
Moscow. Among the men, the winner was Besik Gabitashvili of
Georgia. Besides the medal, each receives $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chapter
</P>
<P>
   Is it a match made in casting heaven? The results won't be in
until the film is released next spring, but Bette Midler is
starring as Jacqueline Susann, the flamboyant author of ``Valley of
the Dolls,'' in ``Isn't She Great,'' a film biography now in
production in Montreal. Nathan Lane plays Susann's husband and
manager, Irving Mansfield. Andrew Bergman (``The Freshman'') is
directing from a script by Paul Rudnick (``In and Out''). The
production moves to Manhattan next month.
</P>
<P>
   Local Heroes
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With ``New York Composers: A Century of New Music''
as its theme, the Summergarden series of free concerts in the Abby
Aldrich Rockefeller Sculpture Garden of the Museum of Modern Art
opens Friday. When the music begins at 8:30 p.m., Joel Sachs,
Summergarden's artistic director, will lead works by Charles Ives,
Stefan Wolpe, Samuel Barber, Edgard Varese, Chou Wen-chung and
Kenji Bunch. The series, on Fridays and Saturdays, continues
through Aug. 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
