<HEADER>
A6584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH02-COX     07-01 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WELCOME WARMER FOR BUSH THAN GINGRICH AT HISPANIC MEETING
 &HT;    440&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Two potential competitors for the 2000 Republican
presidential nomination came together Wednesday to make a pitch for
the votes of Hispanics, who have objected to GOP-led immigration,
welfare and education initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
delivered essentially the same message to the annual meeting of the
League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC), a civil rights
group for the fastest-growing minority in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came today to say my door is open. We want to work with
you,'' Gingrich said at a luncheon for nearly 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But while Gingrich was politely received, Bush heard cries of
``We love you'' from the audience and responded in kind. ``Te
amo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their back-to-back speeches showed, in Bush's case, the
potential for Republican success among Hispanics and, in
Gingrich's, how far the party still has to go after the 1996
election, in which President Clinton received nearly three-fourths
of the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-speaking governor, who got only a quarter of
Hispanic votes in 1994, has worked hard to cultivate Hispanic
support in his first term. He opposed the Gingrich-led House vote
in 1996 to make English the nation's official language and has
called for maintaining bilingual education programs that work. In
his bid for re-election this year, Bush leads Democrat Gary Mauro
among Hispanics in the latest Texas Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is, to many Hispanics, the embodiment of the
Republicans' harsh treatment of Latinos. LULAC's Texas delegation
officially boycotted his speech, vice president Margaret Mata said,
``because he has never supported the Hispanic community.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich himself acknowledged his surprise at being invited to
speak. ``This is not the first of five things I thought I'd get
invited to today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker mainly avoided areas of controversy Wednesday,
instead promoting his proposal to use budget surpluses to create
retirement accounts for working Americans and speaking in vague
terms about supporting legal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   LULAC President Belen Robles praised Gingrich for pressing one
bill that would allow Puerto Ricans to vote on statehood and
another to study land claims in New Mexico relating to the
Mexican-American War.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was silent on several issues important to Hispanic
groups, including his fierce opposition to the use of statistical
sampling to improve the accuracy of the 2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau contends that sampling will give a truer
picture of the size of racial and ethnic minorities, who are most
likely to be missed in the traditional head count.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Gingrich has expressed opposition to
``English-only'' legislation that would bar governments from
printing official documents in other languages.
</P>
<P>
   But campaign spokesman Mike Shields said Wednesday that the
speaker continues to support making English the nation's official
language, a proposal Hispanic groups vociferously oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican-sponsored legislation pending in the House
would make it harder for legal immigrants to become citizens and
would let voting registrars use government naturalization data to
verify voter eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of critical policy issues on the table
where the leadership in Congress can send a signal that they will
continue to offend the community or send a signal of support for
the community,'' said Cecilia Munoz, vice president of the National
Council of La Raza, another leading Hispanic organization.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz was one of a dozen Hispanic leaders who met Gingrich in
his Capitol office last week, the first such meeting since he
became speaker three and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Vargas, director of the National Association of Latino
Elected and Appointed Officials, said Gingrich used the right words
in the meeting. ``Actions, we're still waiting for,'' Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's speech Wednesday drew a similar reaction. ``We want
to hear more commitments, but it was still the beginning of
dialogue,'' said Peggy Anastos, LULAC's New Jersey director.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
