<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PRIMAKOV IN CYPRUS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov of Russia _ long
the KGB's top operative in the Middle East and still Saddam
Hussein's closest ally _ sees himself as a new Andrei Gromyko.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike that Soviet stoneface, Primakov represents no superpower.
But because he now runs Boris Yeltsin's foreign policy, and because
he has the latest Russian missiles to sell, this Gromyko with a
smiling face has found a way to split the NATO alliance by
inflaming Greeks and Turks over the island of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Cypriots on that independent Mediterranean island near Turkey
number 650,000 ethnic Greeks and 200,000 ethnic Turks. When Greek
nationalists got pushy in 1974, Ankara sent in troops to protect
its Turkish minority in the north, cruelly driving out Greek
residents, setting up a republic that the world does not recognize,
and establishing air control over the whole island. Cypriots have
been glaring at each other ever since. (You have to be Irish to
understand.)
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Cypriot government is irritated at Turkey's air
control. It is feeling feisty at the European Union's signs that it
could gain membership in the coveted economic club, especially
since the EU has snubbed Muslim Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   To assert its nationhood, Greek Cypriots went shopping for
surface-to-air missiles that could knock down Turkey's planes if
war came. First stop was the United States. Then Europe; none of
its nations would join in an obvious military provocation of
Turkey, a NATO member.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes Primakov, lighting a match in the gas-filled room.
How much do you Cypriots have to spend? $200 million. At $5 million
a missile, that'll buy you 40 of our best new S-300s, not only
threatening Turkish air domination, but capable with some
modifications of hitting Turkish soil. When can you take delivery?
September. A deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Turks are reacting to this deal today the way the Kennedy
Administration did when Khrushchev put the Soviet missiles on ships
to Cuba: You put those missiles in and we'll take them out. The
nuclear missiles Gromyko lied about were 90 miles from the United
States; these offensively defensive SAM's are 50 miles from Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has a fistful of interests in Cyprus. His commercial
interest is in getting hard currency for Russian arms and keeping
missile factories humming.
</P>
<P>
   Especially delicious to the ex-spymaster is the espionage
interest: Cyprus has long been the intelligence crossroads of the
Eastern Mediterranean, of benefit to Syria, Iraq and Libya. Turks
charge that along with the missiles would come Russian
``technicians'' to bolster Russia's intelligence network.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, international spooks know that corporations in Cyprus'
capital, Nicosia _ a city split by a ``green line'' like a Berlin
wall separating Greeks and Turks _ have for years made it the
money-laundering capital of the Middle East. Our State Department
says the Greek south is now cleaner than the Turkish north, but the
whole island launders. Primakov will be able to monitor the flight
of Russian rubles to foreign banks, and gain added leverage over
Serbia, which gets clandestine foreign money support through
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the strategic interest. Cyprus is the flashpoint of a
Greek-Turkish tension that extends into the Balkans. Here was
Primakov's way to retaliate at NATO expansion by breaking apart the
southern flank of the Western alliance _ not only at no cost to
Russia, but at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Madeleine Albright, in a meeting with Primakov in Luxembourg in
May, tried to talk him out of shipping the missiles; she failed.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, unable to negotiate the Cypriot factions into
a sensible ``bizonal, bicommunal'' federation, creatively tried to
use the impending Cyprus crisis as a shoehorn to ease Turkey into
being fairly considered for EU membership. But the Germans and
Greeks would have none of that.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Primakov's maneuvering and European anti-Turk
bias, we now have (1) Ankara more adamant than ever about a
separate Turkish Cypriot republic; (2) the United Nations, which
patrols the green line, passing resolutions blaming Turks for
everything, and (3) Greeks lurching into a foolish missile
provocation.
</P>
<P>
   This thing could get out of hand. President Clinton should get
on the horn to Yeltsin and say, ``Tell Primakov to cancel that
missile order.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
