<SLUG> BC-GAS-BLAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN BURNED AS BLAST DESTROYS HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL LANGNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 33-year-old Springfield, Mass. man was reported to be in
critical condition at Brigham and Women's Hospital Wednesday being
treated for third-degree burns he suffered in a botched attempt to
kill himself by blowing up his house with gas, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Swiderski had removed a half-inch drip plug from the gas
service line coming into his Hood Street house and let the
pressurized gas stream in while he remained in the house, said Sgt.
Kenneth Gustafson of the Springfield arson squad.
</P>
<P>
   The blast at about 2:30 a.m. destroyed Swiderski's house, but it
did little damage to neighboring ones and injured only him. It blew
the roof off the house and blew out all the walls, leaving only
some of the structural timber standing.
</P>
<P>
   The force blew Swiderski, who was alone in the house, onto the
front lawn, a fire department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A woman living next door told investigators that the blast was
so loud she thought lightning had struck Swiderski's house.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary investigations found that Swiderski, who is
separated from his wife, had composed a five-page letter and posted
it as E-mail to 207 people in the hours before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; His wife and two children had been living elsewhere, Gustafson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a long, rambling letter and we consider it tantamount to
a suicide note,'' Gustafson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said investigators are not sure what ignited the gas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
