<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-PRESCOTT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN H. PRESCOTT, 63; DIRECTED THE N.E. AQUARIUM FOR 22 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John H. Prescott, who developed New England Aquarium in Boston
into ``the preeminent aquarium in the world,'' died Tuesday at his
home in Weston, Mass. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Prescott was executive director of the aquarium from 1972 to
1994. During his tenure he oversaw the design and construction of
the aquarium's $2 million floating Discovery exhibit of sea lions
and dolphins and expanded the institution's educational and
research programs.
</P>
<P>
   His work in establishing a marine mammals rescue and
rehabilitation program at the facility helped pave the way for
similar rescue programs at other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   As Mr. Prescott said in a story published in a the Globe on
Sept. 23, 1990, ``It's not fish in a box any more. The old kind of
aquarium was like a postage-stamp collection. One fish after
another, each with its label. We want to show fish as they live in
their actual habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Jerry R. Schubel, current president of the aquarium,
said, ``John Prescott provided remarkable leadership for the
aquarium for more than two decades. He established standards of
excellence across the institution which persist today.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Prescott was also an accomplished marine biologist who, with
colleague Ken Norris, is credited with being the first to document
the existence of dolphin sonar and echolocation.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from the University of California, earned a
master's degree in ethology at the University of Southern
California, and completed the advanced management program at
Harvard Graduate Business School.
</P>
<P>
   He was affiliated with Marineland of the Pacific from 1957 to
1972 and rose from assistant curator to general manager of the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Prescott consulted on the development of aquariums
throughout the world, most recently in the Biosphere in Arizona. He
was chairman of the committee of scientific advisers to the US
Marine Mammal Commission and was an adviser to the International
Whaling Commission.
</P>
<P>
   He was the recipient of many awards, including the Marlin
Perkins Award, the American Zoo and Aquarium Association's highest
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Rudolph Pierce, chairman of the board of trustees of
the aquarium, said, ``John Prescott developed the New England
Aquarium into the preeminent aquarium in the world. Our success is
his legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Sandra (Baker); two sons, Blane and Craig;
and two stepsons, William Marsh and John Marsh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
