<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-775&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-01 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: NERVOUS TWITCH IN THE WALLET 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To think that Wednesday's consummation of the merger
of Random House and Bantam Doubleday Dell doesn't mean important
changes in book publishing is to believe that it is the swaying
grass that causes the wind. But mostly the changes will be gradual,
played out over time, since the conglomerate that put it together
actually considers the publication of books a primary business.
</P>
<P>
   The merger molded by Bertelsmann AG, the German media company,
creates the world's largest English-language trade-book publisher,
with a seemingly endless number of divisions and imprints. For
anxious authors and their agents, the fear is that this
consolidation will mean that the various members of this giant
family will not be allowed to bid against each other for books. And
the bidding game is the spine of agenting and the stem of authors'
income.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in this atmosphere of slashed competition, not only will
there be fewer places for an agent to sell a writer's work, but the
author's advance is likely to be considerably lower than before.
Another fear is that there will be a large number of book contract
cancellations when the new management gazes upon the inventory of
books in the pipeline and finds duplications. Cancellations, one
may forget, would mean fewer choices for readers. Management was
emphatic that these feared cancellations would not happen.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding question is more complicated, largely because Bantam
Doubleday Dell, which was owned by Bertelsmann before the merger,
has one set of rules about intrapublishing-house bidding among its
divisions and Random House has another set, which is far more
popular with agents and their authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it the Random House rules or the Bantam rules? No one
knows,'' one agent said, making the point that this was the single
most important question for authors.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that some form of the more writer-friendly
Random House rules will be used by the merged company, which will
be called Random House Inc. But there will have to be a definitive
answer quickly, since agents are not going to take much of a
vacation from deal making, and there are many other publishing
houses waiting to bid and buy.
</P>
<P>
   Every agent can recall an exception to the policy, but the
Random House rules allowed an agent to submit a manuscript secretly
to an imprint in any or all of its four adult trade-book divisions
(and, of course, to other publishing houses as well) and set them
bidding against one another, up to a point. Good money-letting
competition, enjoyed by agent and client. If in the end, however,
there were only two Random House imprints left in the auction, then
the agent had to disclose that fact, so the publishing house did
not have two of its own imprints skyrocketing the advance by
last-minute bidding.
</P>
<P>
   At Bantam Doubleday Dell, multiple submissions to its imprints
had to be made known by the agent from the start. If more than one
of its four adult trade divisions were interested in bidding, they
decided among themselves which imprint would take part in the
auction. Surprisingly, it was usually the imprint offering the most
money, since it was believed that that imprint had the most
commitment to the project and therefore would have more fire in
nurturing the book through publication and sales.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Priest, an agent, said the merger was not necessarily bad,
``if multiple companies within the big one are allowed to make
their own editorial decisions'' and not have such determinations
forced upon them from the top. ``Sometimes there's a problem when
the auction gets up to very high money,'' he said. ``They don't
then want to bid against themselves, but it's all right if they
allow lots of their people to compete up to a certain level of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is that the new Random House will allow its
divisions to bid against one another until the auction reaches
hundreds of thousands of dollars, and then the company, after
conversations among its intramural competitors, will decide which
one of its imprints stays in the auction.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kay Murray, assistant director of the 7,400-member
Authors Guild, said: ``We've maintained all along that the merger
isn't good for writers. We are afraid of a decrease of diversity in
the books published, with one publisher having a third of the
market share.'' Actually, the new publishing company will have 10
percent of the total book market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She said that every time there has ``been a big merger, imprints
are closed and contracts are canceled and editors leave.'' Still,
she will be happy, she said, if the Random House rules apply to
bidding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Author Nick Lemann said that it certainly ``is not nuts to be
against the merger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they will let the divisions bid freely against
each other,'' he said, ``and this is particularly sensitive in book
publishing because it involves the public discourse. If you are the
guild, you have to be aware of both economic self-interest and the
public's interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is not to have a million small publishers or one big
publisher. Everybody agrees that the ideal is somewhere in the
middle, and the merger reduces the number of major players by
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the new company drop some of its imprints? Its management
says no, certainly not any time soon. But experience suggests that
trimming some is a real business possibility. Will it consolidate
some of the noneditorial departments? The history of such mergers
says yes. And will that be any time soon?
</P>
<P>
   The merger comes just as book publishing is shivering from flat
sales, large returns from booksellers and the rocketing advances,
among other perceived horrors. But even the American dream of 40
acres and a mule eventually became 140 acres, and so on, and so on.
And apparently Peter Olson, the chairman and chief executive
officer of the new Random House Inc., hasn't heard that books as
such have been terminated to be replaced by computer reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
