<SLUG> BC-MA-WEAPONS-CHIEFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CHIEFS DECRY LOSS OF POWER IN WEAPONS BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts Chiefs of Police Association lined up
on the State House steps Wednesday to denounce the latest version
of an assault weapons ban, saying it takes away their power to
regulate who should have a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The group originally supported the overall measure. But a
late-filed amendment forming an appeals board to overrule police
chiefs' gun-licensing decisions has made them sour on the final
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Although the House approved the legislation last week, the bill
still needs to be rectified with the Senate version, a process that
creates an opportunity for the amendment to be deleted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amendment, if passed, would put firearms in the hands of
individuals previously rejected for such purposes by the local
chief of police,'' said Dennis Teehan, president of the MCPA. ``The
local police chief is in the best position to make decisions
regarding the issuance of firearms permits. The chief knows his
local citizens better than any politically appointed board. An
appropriate review process is already in place for a district court
judge to appeal a chief's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   While Acting Governor Paul Cellucci issued a statement
supporting the group's outcry, he has refused to ask gun lobbyist
Michael Yacino to step down as the head of the Massachusetts
Neighborhood Crime Watch. Under the amendment, Yacino, who also
serves as executive director of the Gun Owners Action League, would
have the right to nominate a member to the seven-member board that
could overrule the police chiefs. Yacino's efforts on behalf of gun
enthusiasts to dilute the assault weapons bill has drawn criticism
from Cellucci's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Cellucci urged the Legislature Wednesday to
``reject the amendment and restore muscle to the bill and to our
police.''
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, who joined the group in
denouncing the amendment, said Cellucci ``needs to address it in
action as well as words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Yacino's full-time job is to kill this legislation,''
Harshbarger added. Yacino could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
