<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SAVING THE CITIES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For many years the goal of people concerned
about the nation's cities was, for the most part, simply to stop
the hemorrhaging. Crime seemed out of control, longtime residents
were fleeing, entire neighborhoods were collapsing into rubble and
ash.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core inner-city neighborhoods _ the South Bronx in New
York, the Hough section of Cleveland, the Central Ward in Newark _
were seen by many as incurable concentrations of poverty and
pathology. Much of the rest of the country closed its eyes and
turned its back. Such neighborhoods, according to a particularly
destructive but pervasive view, not only were beyond saving, they
weren't worth saving. In the early 1980s a devastated neighborhood
in Kansas City, Mo., was used as a location site for ``The Day
After,'' a television movie about the aftermath of a nuclear
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Hard at work but hardly noticed during those terrible years were
the many men and women who, in small, often ragtag groups, rolled
up their sleeves and did what they could to counter one of the
biggest problems _ the desperate need for housing. Sometimes, in
the midst of chaos and misery, their goal was to build just one
house. Their attitude, invariably, was, ``You have to start
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago the Clinton administration released a
report declaring that, finally, after decades of struggling, the
nation's cities were rebounding. It's too early to reach for the
champagne. The inner cities, especially, are still intensely
isolated communities in which joblessness is high, poverty is
rampant, drug addiction is flourishing and genuine opportunities
are hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   But some very good things are happening. Crime is down,
municipal budgets are in much better shape, and even in hard-core
areas there are unmistakable early signs of renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Go back now to the men and women who rolled up their sleeves and
decided to build some housing. In the really tough neighborhoods,
they are the unheralded heroes. Working with churches and small
community organizations, they pulled off surprising early
successes. New homes would go up on a block, or old buildings would
be renovated, and before long a startling transformation would
occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the miracle of small steps,'' said Paul Grogan,
president of a national support group _ the Local Initiatives
Support Corporation (LISC) _ that recognized the potential of these
local groups, which came to be known, accurately but not very
excitingly, as community development corporations, or CDC's.
</P>
<P>
   Certain things happen when new homes, even a small number,
appear in a previously blighted neighborhood. The construction
itself creates economic activity. Architects and contractors are
hired. New families are drawn to the neighborhood and a new sense
of pride can be seen. Graffiti and other forms of vandalism tend to
occur with less frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blighted and abandoned housing sends a terrible signal,'' said
Grogan, whose group held its annual meeting here this week. ``It's
a magnet for drugs and other criminal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   What groups like LISC have found is that the new or refurbished
housing in most cases became a stabilizing force, a locally
developed defense against what had appeared to be unstoppable
blight.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, although very slowly, economic activity would pick
up. As a Boston resident described it: ``The neighborhood became a
neighborhood again.''
</P>
<P>
   LISC and some other groups began working with CDC's several
years ago, helping to arrange financing and offering the kind of
expertise that allowed the local groups to operate on a much larger
scale. What began small is now huge, and hugely important. LISC,
the largest of the intermediary groups, has directly raised $3
billion in financing since 1979 and has leveraged $3.5 billion
more. With the help of LISC and others, CDC's have built thousands
upon thousands of units of decent affordable housing all across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   It's still not enough. There is still a critical shortage of
affordable housing in the big cities. And there are many other
problems as well. But the cities are better off than they have been
in many years. And the men and women who built housing during the
worst of times deserve to be applauded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
