<HEADER>
A6611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOPEZ-COX     07-01 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOPEZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez begins yet another quest for elusive Open title
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. -- Ray Knight, otherwise known as Nancy Lopez's
husband, became a statistics freak through baseball. A few years
ago, Knight suddenly awoke in bed at 3 o'clock one morning, rolled
over and asked the greatest player in modern women's golf: ``Do you
know who the best player in the LPGA is?''
</P>
<P>
   Knight had been figuring career driving statistics, scoring
average, average money _the whole package _ but at 3 a.m., Nancy
Lopez was not too fond of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' she said groggily. ``Who is the best player in
the LPGA?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patti Sheehan _ but you're second.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me all the stats,'' Lopez said this week, ``and I
went back to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   As Knight probably could tell you now, his wife also has 42
runnerup finishes to accompany her 48 wins. Unfortunately, four of
them have come in the U.S. Women's Open, which begins today on the
Blackwolf Run Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to sleep after her last near-miss was the toughest. A
year ago at Pumpkin Ridge, Lopez lost her grip on a U.S. Women's
Open trophy on the last stroke of the 72nd hole.
</P>
<P>
   When her final putt, a 10-footer that slid left of the hole,
allowed England's Alison Nicholas to secure her victory, it marked
the beginning of a lengthy mourning period for Lopez. Now 41, the
Albany, Ga. resident had to wonder if she had just blown her last
good opportunity to win the most prestigious title in women's golf.
Each post-tournament interview that day was a fight to hold back
the tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hard not to start crying,'' she said, ``because
I instantly felt the emotions that I felt walking to 18, that whole
day, then missing the putt. They came back like they had just
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 21 years later, a lot of people forget that Lopez tied for
second in the Open as an amateur in 1975. Or that she nearly won
the Open in her first try as a professional. Her undoing? A zipper
on her pants that had broken and opened up every time she bent down
to read a putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through so many different feelings through the years
of playing the U.S. Open,'' Lopez said. ``I went through years of
basically choking myself when I got there because I wanted to win
it so bad. ... Then, I said, 'OK, it doesn't really matter if I win
the U.S. Open. I'm just going to play the best that I can.' I was
trying to take the pressure off myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics insist that Lopez's career will not be complete
without the USGA's highest honor. Some days she agrees; some days
she doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to win the U.S. Open,'' she said Tuesday, when all
the old pressures of the tournament started to form again. ``I just
have to keep trying. Eventually I will get too old, and maybe I
can't do it then after a certain time, but I still feel pretty
young. I feel like I still have a chance to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in April, Lopez suggested, ``I don't think it would bother
me much if I never won the U.S. Open. I never won the U.S. Amateur
and I was the No.1-ranked amateur for years. I don't think it would
take away from what I've done if I don't win a U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, with her missing treasure approaching again, Lopez
offered a more honest appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think deep down inside it probably will matter to me,
but I can't be selfish, really,'' she said. ``I think it would be
selfish saying that I would be unhappy not winning a U.S. Open
because of not completing my career. ... I've had a great life and
a great career on the tour. If I don't win a U.S. Open, I just
believe that God didn't have it in his plan for me to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   It might take a U.S. Women's Open to put Lopez's season into a
higher gear. It's been a struggle, beginning with the missed cut in
Atlanta in April, followed by another the following week at the
Sprint Titleholders. For her career, Lopez has missed just 19 cuts
in 395 events. Lately, though, it's three of her last six and a
mediocre spot on the money list, 35th with $120,585. Not exactly
what Lopez had in mind 20 years after her spectacular nine-win
season.
</P>
<P>
   It continually mystifies Lopez as to how some players can win an
Open but little else. Nicholas, for example, owns only two other
LPGA wins. Slowed by bronchial pneumonia this year, she has missed
three cuts, withdrawn twice and barely gets a mention as a
contender this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't now if it's because all the pressure has gone
somewhere else and they're just playing, or what it is,'' Lopez
said. ``I try and think about that and analyze it. Maybe the
pressure is so much more on players you'd think would win the U.S.
Open and maybe it lets somebody come in there and sneak in and win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Lopez's fans should not wish too hard for her to win an
Open. In Knight's opinion, such a development might push Lopez to
full-time car-pooling with their three kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she would win an Open, I'm sure there would not be a
tremendous amount of motivation left,'' Knight says. ``It's gotten
to where she gears everything for that tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
