<HEADER>
A6612 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGANN-COX     07-01 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGANN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf no longer old hat for McGann
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ There is an expression, used mostly among cowboys
and ranchers yet somehow appropriate during U.S. Women's Open week
in America's heartland/Dairyland, too, about folks who are more
style than substance.
</P>
<P>
   All hat and no cattle.
</P>
<P>
   This is an unflattering reference (if not a downright unkind
one) to somebody who looks good on the job, but doesn't quite
measure up when it comes to doing the real work.
</P>
<P>
   The fancy headwear by which Michelle McGann _ the Glad Hatter of
the LPGA Tour _ is so easily identifiable makes her an easy target
for such an insult as she endures a difficult year.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not reduce McGann to imposter status.
</P>
<P>
   Not again.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   McGann, who for the past three seasons has been one of her
sport's superstars, is struggling. She started well enough with a
couple of high finishes _ including a tie for third in The Office
Depot near her Singer Island home _ in her first two events of the
season. But she has missed seven cuts (amounting to more than half
her schedule since those first two tournaments) and comes into the
Open at Blackwolf Run Golf Course in a slump that matches the venue
in terms of nastiness.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't broken 70 in her past 15 rounds. Her stroke average
of 72.73 is her highest in seven years. And in a world where
fractions mean thousands of dollars, the jump from scoring numbers
posted each of the three most-recent LPGA seasons when McGann was
busy winning seven titles _ 71.56, 71.43 and 71.52 _ is more than a
little disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been beating myself up,'' McGann said Wednesday afternoon
after a practice round. ``I lost my confidence, and that's half the
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help that I'm such a perfectionist. You start
expecting that you'll play well every week, and that's not going to
happen. But little things start bothering you, and then everything
gets out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of golf's maddening appeal is that it does that to
everyone, but McGann seemed to be on a roll after waiting until
1995 _ she joined the LPGA Tour in October 1988 at the age of 18 _
for her first victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but I beat myself up then, too,'' McGann said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a twist of fortune, McGann's celebrity status works
against her. At the end of her practice round, for example, her
father and caddy, Bucky, worked the ropes behind the 18th green as
an advance man passing out pictures of his daughter for her to
sign.
</P>
<P>
   She accomodated all requests, and did the same thing at various
times on the course _ even stopping to pose for pictures between
greens and tees _ and heard all the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When are you going to win?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you feeling OK?''
</P>
<P>
   McGann says it's nothing out of the ordinary. A slump is a slump
is a slump ... she hits it well, and can't putt; or putts well when
she isn't hitting it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you feel like saying is, `Hey, I'm human,''' McGann said.
</P>
<P>
   She says she ``likes the test'' at Blackwolf Run, which is the
second-longest U.S. Women's Open course in history and would
therefore seem to suit McGann's power game. But her previous Open
history suggests it is not the kind of event in which to expect a
dramatic McGann recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The can't-break-70 syndrome McGann is enduring on the LPGA Tour
has covered her Open experiences since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all it takes is one round,'' McGann said. ``That can be
all you need to turn your mind around.''
</P>
<P>
   She figures she has the cattle to go with the hat.
</P>
<P>
   She just happens to have misplaced the livestock.
</P>
<P>
   But the heartland/Dairyland of America may be the place to find
it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
