<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN-COX     07-01 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venus loses cool, match
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Rage overwhelmed Venus Williams in the
Wimbledon quarterfinals Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Third seed Jana Novotna happened to be on the other side of the
net at the time, and by keeping control amid chaos, the 29-year-old
grass-court veteran defeated Williams 7-5, 7-6 (7-2) for a spot in
her fifth Wimbledon semifinal today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I played really good tennis today,'' Novotna said.
``And I made Venus desperate at some times. I think she lost it a
little bit there.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, an 18-year-old who had expected to win her first title
here, yelled at the chair umpire twice, nearly cried and bellowed
at a lineswoman _ all over what she considered incorrect line calls
in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that you're upset about the bad call,'' said
Williams, who rarely, if ever, has had such an emotional match or
outburst. ``I was just upset because I deserved the point because
she hit the ball out.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna _ who now plays top seed Martina Hingis _ showed off her
classic Wimbledon winning style in the first set, serving and
volleying well to win 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 3-all in the second set, Williams argued her first call
after winning a point to reach 15-40 on her serve. Despite winning
the point, she thought the previous shot from Novotna was wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball was so far out,'' she hollered above the crowd noise
at an unresponsive chair umpire while pointing to where Novotna's
ball had landed.
</P>
<P>
   She then stomped toward the lineswoman on the service line and
yelled, ``Ya gotta call'em'' while glaring at her.
</P>
<P>
   Williams lost her service game on the next point, then lost the
next game before winning the next two, earning back the service
break. She looked angry but hit both of her aces of the match in
the service game.
</P>
<P>
   At 3-3, Williams double-faulted, falling behind 15-30. She lost
the next point with an long but was convinced Novotna's shot before
hers had also gone long. She walked toward the umpire, arguing all
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's out,'' she screamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows it's out,'' she yelled louder, pointing at someone
in the crowd. ``Everyone else knows it's out, but you don't know
it's out.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams got a round of applause from the fans, but nothing from
the umpire. She stalked back to serve and double-faulted, giving
Novotna a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still shaking in fury, she returned to her seat for the
changeover and snatched her towel off the chair. She had tears in
her eyes and looked close to breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a firm belief that those balls were out and that those
linespeople should have called them out,'' Williams said. ``But I
think it just helped me play better. I was more willing to try to
get that win.''
</P>
<P>
   She did win the next game, breaking Novotna's serve and holding
her own for a 5-4 lead. During the changeover, a team of
linespeople was rotated, which Williams' mother and sister cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna and Williams each held serve until they reached 6-6.
Williams played poorly in the tiebreaker, or as she put it,
``missed some opportunities,'' losing 2-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the crowd probably enjoyed my emotional
outbursts,'' she said, smiling and laughing. ``I guess someone
would turn the channel and suddenly see some girl screaming and
keep it there. I know I would. It probably brightened up someone's
day.''
</P>
<P>
   After reflection, Williams didn't regret her John McEnroe-like
episode, saying she felt obligated to let everyone know her
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I needed to do that and I needed to do that
probably because I really wanted to win those points, and the ball
was really out,'' Williams said. ``And sometimes you need to make
sure that you can go on to the next point.''
</P>
<P>
   She might have been happy with the result, but Novotna was
happier, pointing out that experience is worth quite a bit at
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that I had the edge because I could see in the second
set Venus started to come in quite a lot,'' Novotna said. ``She's
not even coming in in mixed doubles or in doubles. So you can
imagine how desperate she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams expects to learn a lot when she studies both her play
and her behavior at her second Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year I don't think there's anything that will be stopping
me except for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
