<SLUG> BC-TV-CARDINAL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BERNARDIN': ANCHORED BY CHURCH TEACHINGS, DRIVEN BY VATICAN
CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The television producer who sets out to profile as
deeply admired a religious figure as Cardinal Joseph Bernardin
risks losing the human being in an aura of reverence. So credit is
due to Martin Doblmeier and Frank Frost for putting together a fond
portrait that allows the man to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   This program emphasizes the influence on the young priest of the
Second Vatican Council, which opened up church practices and
directed attention to issues of poverty and peace. By the time he
was named archbishop of Cincinnati in 1972, he had already earned a
reputation as a leader of a changing church. But this program makes
clear that on some crucial matters, notably the Supreme Court's
1973 Roe vs. Wade decision, which he steadfastly opposed, Bernardin
felt himself anchored in traditional Roman Catholic teachings.
</P>
<P>
   More to the liking of liberal observers was his opposition to
the use of nuclear weapons. Even as the Cold War raged, Bernardin
took a prominent role in formulating the mandate of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops ``to draw a strong, clear line _
politically and morally _ against resort to nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as his vision of a moral public policy combined support for
poverty programs with opposition to abortion, so he preached
opposition to nuclear weapons without any hint of softness toward
communism.
</P>
<P>
   As recalled by observers of religion in America, his
soft-spoken, noninflammatory approach achieved marvels of consensus
within the church and admiration outside it. In his television
appearances, he presented a principled, self-effacing figure,
always mild but never weak. So it was a shocker in 1993, when at
the peak of his influence as archbishop of Chicago and a member of
the College of Cardinals, he was charged by a former seminarian
with sexual abuse back in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that time, when reports of pedophiliac priests were
making headlines, Bernardin's unambiguous denials at a news
conference _ ``I just want to say to you that everything that is in
that suit about me, the allegations, are totally untrue, they are
totally false'' _ were persuasive, and a few months later his
accuser dropped all charges.
</P>
<P>
   The program ends with the cardinal's typically plain-spoken
television reports on the course of his cancer, which was diagnosed
in 1995. He treated it with the openness for which he always
strove. His final efforts before his death the next year were given
to advancing what he called common ground on divisive issues both
within his church and with other faiths.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this appreciation, some reverence seems in order.
``Bernardin'' helps us to understand why those who knew him well,
as one eulogist says, felt privileged ``to live in the time when a
holy man was the archbishop of Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BERNARDIN'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Thursday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Martin Doblmeier and Frank Frost, co-producers. ``Bernardin'' is
a co-production of Journey-Frost Productions, LLC and Family
Theater Productions in association with Santa Fe Communications
Inc., and is a presentation of WNET/New York. ``Bernardin'' is
distributed to public television stations by the American Program
Service.
</P>
<P>
   With: Martin E. Marty, Kenneth Woodward, Richard Ostling, Eugene
Kennedy, John H. White and Daniel Lehmann.
</P>
</TEXT>
