<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CONTINUED US INVESTMENT IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China -- In an unusual intersection of capitalism and
communism, President Clinton strode onto the floor of the new
Shanghai Stock Exchange Wednesday to the loud applause of its
red-vested traders, capping a two-day blitz through this financial
capital for more open markets and a more open way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly urged United States businessmen here to
continue their investment in China for the good of both countries.
He highlighted a Chinese home ownership program by telling a
nostalgic tale of buying his first house. And he recounted the
highlights of his trip for the Chinese state television station,
describing his press conference with Chinese President Jiang Zemin
as ``historic for a long time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White House aides quietly monitored the less
diplomatic side of the Clinton presidency. They watched from afar
as Pentagon aide Linda Tripp made her first appearance before the
Whitewater grand jury in Washington to begin answering questions
over her secret taping of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the testimony, White House spokesman Michael McCurry
expressed little interest in the topic. ``The president is
concentrating on one trip, and it's China, not Linda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sun-splashed atrium of the Portman Ritz-Carlton Hotel here,
Clinton told members of the American Chamber of Commerce that China
represented the future of America's economic strength, and that in
many respects, American investment here would help China's future
in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the positive impacts you have on the United
States, your work here has a very positive impact in China,''
Clinton told the group. ``China's 20-year track record of
unprecedented growth has been fueled in part by foreign products,
know-how, investment, trade and energy. These ties also have more
profound, long-lasting effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They strengthen the rule of law, openness and
accountability,'' Clinton added. ``They expose China to fair labor
practices and stronger environmental standards. They spread
powerful agents of change: fax machines and photocopiers, computers
and modems.''
</P>
<P>
   That change, at least in business terms, was never more apparent
than when Clinton circled the catwalk of the Shanghai stock
exchange, descended by elevator and walked onto the floor as young
traders in red vests applauded loudly and presented him with a vest
of his own. Above, a stadium-sized videoscreen captured the moment
for distant onlookers. The market was closed temporarily for the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The stock exchange, which began eight years ago with just 30
issues, now lists more than 500.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then ducked into a conference room for a 20-minute
interview with China's national television network -- a session in
which he said he was surprised that Zemin had permitted their joint
press conference Saturday to be broadcast on live television in
China.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that his first memory of China was reading about it
in an encyclopedia as a child. In this, his first visit there, he
said he was struck by the economic growth sweeping the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also believe there is a genuine increase in people's control
over their own lives,'' he said. ``Incomes are going up, people
have more choices in education, more choice in jobs, the freedom to
travel. I think there's a genuine movement toward openness and
freedom in China, which obviously as an American, and as an
American president, I hope will continue and increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the summit's accomplishments, Clinton said, ``I think that in
the end it may be that the biggest achievement was the increased
understanding and the sense of a shared future. I mean, I think the
press conference that President Jiang and I did will be viewed as
historic for a long time to come. And the fact that he wanted to do
it, he enjoyed it and it was on national television I think was
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton, accompanied by US Rep. Edward
Markey, one of six lawmakers in the White House delegation, stopped
at an Internet cafe and talked to students who paid $2.50 an hour
to link up to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also endorsed a novel housing reform program in which
Chinese residents are allowed to buy their own apartments rather
than rent a state-owned company apartment. He visited the home of
Yu Jinyuan, a resident of Jin Hui Gardens, which includes four and
six-story garden apartments where several families have become
first-time homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 20 years ago, I bought my first home,'' Clinton
said. ``I actually bought it because my girlfriend liked the house.
We were driving by the house one day -- it was a very small house
-- and she said, I like that house very much. So I found out the
house did not cost too much money and I bought it. And then I said
to my girlfriend, `I bought that house you like, now you'll ave to
marry me.' And she did.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Shanghai for Guilin, a breathtaking mountainous
region which for thousands of years has served as the subject of
traditional Chinese ink paintings of winding rivers set against
hilly backdrops. There, he planned to focus attention on the
environment, before flying to Hong Kong for a night and day of
meetings and speeches to conclude his trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
