<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, July 2, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   JUG-ANCIENT (Seattle) An ancient Middle Eastern jug found in
Seattle has been returned to the University of Chicago's Oriental
Institute, more than a half century after it disappeared. A
warehouse worker for Goodwill Industries stumbled across the relic
while sifting through donations last spring. The institute had
loaned out the jug to a patron to raise money in 1943, officials
said. The 4-inch jug made of roughly textured brown clay didn't
look like much when warehouse worker Randy Jones found it in an old
camera box among the clothing, costume jewelry and usual
bric-a-brac donated to the charity.
</P>
<P>
   By Gordy Holt. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-SINKING (Seattle) A Seattle woman is believed to be one
of the survivors of a cruise ship sinking en route to the Galapagos
Islands. Her husband is missing and presumed dead. Tuesday was
their wedding anniversary. Several passengers were thrown overboard
when the boat, ferrying elderly American tourists, tipped; our own
Pat Zeisler is believed to be one of them. Two people died. Eleven
passengers and eight crew members survived.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert L. Jamieson Jr. (story will move in the ``a''
category)
</P>
<P>
   FRUGAL-GOURMET (Seattle) Developments in the case of ``Frugal
Gourmet'' Jeff Smith.
</P>
<P>
   By Jack Hopkins, Ed Penhale and Steve Miletich. (story will move
in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-PRODUCTION (Seattle) Boeing executives said Wednesday
they finally have a handle on the company's commercial jet
production problems and will now focus on building airplanes more
efficiently and improving Boeing's overall financial performance.
(They declined to discuss the employment picture saying new numbers
will be announced during the second quarter conference call July
23.) By Karen West. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-CHINA-TARGET (Undated) When President Clinton and Chinese
President Jiang Zemin last week announced to a world audience the
two nuclear powers have stopped aiming nuclear missiles at one
another, their summit statement carefully omitted a key fact: The
Pentagon had unilaterally ``detargeted'' Chinese sites more than
four years ago. The Beijing announcement essentially affirmed that
China no longer is aiming its 13 DF-5 missiles at American targets
as it continued to do after the U.S. unilateral decision in 1994 to
remove all target coordinates from the U.S. land- and sea-based
missiles, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) Mariners host Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-COLUMN-THIEL (Seattle) On the history of Mariner pitching
woes.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
