<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON RAINS BRING END TO MEXICO'S DISASTROUS FIRE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The most disastrous fire season in memory is near
an end, Mexican officials said Wednesday, with seasonal rains
extinguishing some of the thousands of blazes that have consumed
vast areas of brush and timberland this year.
</P>
<P>
   All but eight of more than 13,500 fires registered throughout
the country since January have been extinguished, a Mexican
environmental official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are late, but the normal rainy-season rains have
arrived,'' said Elizabeth Breton, spokeswoman for the Mexican
environmental agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the eight fires still burning throughout the country, four
are already under control,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a million acres of Mexican brush and timberlands were
burned, with many of the fires set by rural farmers clearing fields
for planting. As many as 250 fires were reported burning at any one
time.
</P>
<P>
   One U.S. relief official who visited the country had called the
fires ``the worst natural disaster ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The fires were so intense in late May that smoke drifted into
the United States, prompting health advisories in Texas and
spreading haze across several southern states.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the fires extinguished or under control, the U.S.
Forest Service and its Texas counterpart have been removing 81
firefighters sent in mid-May to help battle the wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   A firefighting team will remain in Mexico to develop long-range
training plans for Mexican firefighters, the environmental agency
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the fire teams, the U.S. Agency for International
Development sent safety, firefighting and communications equipment
for 3,000 Mexican firefighters, as well as portable water pumps and
tanks, firefighting foam, helicopter tankers and two infrared
equipped spotter airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, human efforts combined with seasonal rains ended
the threat to the Chimalapas jungle preserve in southeastern
Mexico. At one time, up to 30 fires were burning in the trackless
jungle mountains of the preserve, the northernmost tropical rain
forest in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering hot spot is at Cintalapa, outside the Chiapas
capital of Tuxtla Gutierrez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-REALITY-HNS &LR;      07-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-REALITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS FACE HARSH REALITY AT AIDS CONFERENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Reality has caught up with jubilation over the
expectations of a two-year-old AIDS drug treatment plan credited
with saving thousands of lives in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success of the new treatment, no more than 50
percent of patients can reduce the AIDS virus in their blood to
undetectable levels, if using the most sensitive tests, Dr. Julio
S. G. Montaner, professor of medicine at the University of British
Columbia in Vancouver, said in a speech Wednesday at the 12th World
AIDS Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle, Montaner said, is the difficulty patients
have in following complicated schedules that sometimes require five
doses a day and dozens of pills.
</P>
<P>
   Patients failing to take drugs as prescribed run the risk of
developing strains of HIV that cannot be killed by drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Side effects that include a puzzling syndrome of high
cholesterol, high triglycerides and abnormal fat deposits, have
been associated with the most potent of the newer drugs _ protease
inhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Waafa El-Sadr of Harlem Hospital Center in New York City
described the difficulties new treatments pose for her patients.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann, 30, suffers a host of problems: asthma, rheumatoid
arthritis, high blood pressure, diabetes, depression. She's
undergone a mastectomy for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she also has AIDS,'' El-Sadr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never misses a pill, ever . . . She never complains. The
cruel truth is that in spite of her superhuman efforts, her viral
load creeps up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rochelle is a grandmother at age 36, Sadr said. She changed her
life when she acquired HIV. Even though her immune system is
reviving and she feels better, she asks: ``Will I always have to
take this handful of medications? Can anyone take these forever?''
</P>
<P>
   Montaner said that serving the needs of such patients requires
fine-tuning drugs so that patients have to take fewer pills fewer
times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Patients responded well two years ago when the first potent
protease inhibitors came out and were paired with two members of
the older class of AIDS drugs called reverse transcriptase
inhibitors. Often, doctors could not detect any virus in their
blood by the most common tests.
</P>
<P>
   But a person could find himself taking dozens of pills daily:
Some with a quart of water, some on a full stomach, others on an
empty one.
</P>
<P>
   That became the standard care for AIDS patients, but it worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our (hospital) beds are empty,'' Montaner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many true alternatives,'' he said, noting that 11
drugs currently are approved for HIV treatment in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Several drugs have the potential for once-a-day treatment, he
said. Another, called Combavir, is a combination of 3TC and ddI,
two older drugs. It simplifies the dosing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Montaner said he is already simplifying treatment for his
patients, but he warned that eventually, people will become
resistant to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get rid of any of the drugs,'' he said. ``Sooner or
later, you will need them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 percent of patients seen by Dr. David Cooper,
president of the International AIDS Society, have developed bizarre
lipid or fat disorders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who practices at St. Vincent's Hospital in Sydney,
Australia, said only 10-20 percent have experienced seriously high
rates of these problems.
</P>
<P>
   And while the problem is serious, Cooper does not recommend that
people stop taking protease inhibitors. That's what saved their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The patients have developed abnormal levels of cholesterol and
triglycerides, but they have no other symptoms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Montaner said some newer combinations that are being recommended
do not contain a protease inhibitor yet have virtually the same
effect. A new drug called sustiva and another called abacavir have
had good success when combined with two older drugs such as AZT,
3TC and ddI.
</P>
<P>
   An encouraging note was sounded by Dr. Brigitte Autran of the
Hopital Pitie Salpetriere in Paris who has seen immune systems
revive in patients in response to the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immune system is not dead, even when patients are treated
at near the end of the disease'' she said. Not only are new immune
systems cells generated, but they function as expected.
</P>
<P>
   When the virus is removed, she said, the immune system can
restore itself.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Hirschel, a chairman of the conference and a
professor at the University of Geneva, said he has found that when
the virus in the blood is reduced, he also can stop preventive
treatment usually prescribed to prevent diseases that cause
pneumonia and severe infections of the mouth and throat. Such
problems are often associated with AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
