<HEADER>
A6624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VILLA-THEATER-REVIEW-     07-01 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VILLA-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VILLA VILLA': FEEL, DON'T THINK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Argentina)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By VICTORIA YOUNG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Villa Villa,'' a performance art show by an
Argentine group called De la Guarda, is described by its creators
as a celebration of life. Each night, at the Daryl Roth Theater,
they aim to re-create the wild atmosphere of random unity that
occurs at street festivals in South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main idea behind De la Guarda,'' said Pichon Baldinu, one
of the show's two directors, who translates the name of the group
as Guardian Angel, ``is to take care of the spirit of the audience:
To try to make something very positive and to make all of the
audience enjoy that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of ``Villa Villa'' (pronounced VEE-sha VEE-sha) were
planted in 1985. It was the second year of democratic rule in
Argentina, and the country was still reeling from the effects of
the military dictatorship's campaign against leftists and
subversives, known as the dirty war.
</P>
<P>
   Baldinu and another director, Diqui James, were fresh out of
drama school, and the mood they recall was dark. They joined an
underground street-theater group called ``La Organizacion Negra''
(``Dark Organization'') to mirror the terror and chaos that they
felt had enveloped the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of violence around us all of the time,''
Baldinu said. ``A lot of murders, suffering and injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the group was to shock audiences out of complacency,
often by using displays of demolition and destruction. Their fame
grew, and when in 1989 they scaled the pyramidal monument in
central Buenos Aires known as the Obelisco, they drew 25,000
spectators. Shortly afterward, a law was passed banning the use of
the monument for performances, and the group took to the
international festival circuit.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992 the group was divided. The political climate was
changing, anger was dissipating, and some members were turning to
more traditional theater. Anxious to continue the spirit of
experimentation, James and Baldinu left to form what was to become
De la Guarda. They teamed up with rock climbers who taught them how
to use ropes and harnesses to fly above an audience. ``We wanted to
test the limits,'' said Baldinu, ``to have the audience inside the
show, to give them strong emotions without using violence, which
was the tool we used to use.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 they were joined by an experimental dance group called
El Descueve, and took the name of their show from the ``villas''
that are equivalent to shantytowns in Argentina. ``We never had
money in that period, and the expression we used to use was `do it
Villa Villa,' meaning, don't stop your idea, just do it with
something you have, without resources,'' said Baldinu. ``We lived
and created the show with that spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a show that is partly improvisational. Drawing on
their experience from festivals around the world, they allow the
audience's reaction to drive each performance, which in part means
dictate the action. ``We try to use these things,'' said Baldinu,
explaining that if something particularly interesting happened in
one part of the show, the cast allows the moment to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is part of the theater _ to use that time, that moment,
that situation,'' he said. ``It is the opposite of mass
production.''
</P>
<P>
   Having presented the show mainly for short runs, in festivals,
the group hopes this philosophy will sustain the performance
throughout its first commercial run of at least three months.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Rent,'' Jeffrey Seller and Kevin McCollum,
joined with two other producers, Daryl Roth and David Binder, to
bring De la Guarda to New York after watching the ensemble perform
at the London Theater Festival last year.
</P>
<P>
   There are no characters in ``Villa Villa,'' and no script in the
traditional sense. ``We don't want you to understand the
characters,'' said Baldinu. ``We want you instead to feel the
expression, and the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience is bombarded with sensory experience: Aerial
choreography is accompanied by primitive drums, multicolored lights
and ambient music. The goal is interaction between the audience and
the lithe, muscular performers who, dressed in business suits,
descend periodically from their aerial playground to interact with
theatergoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the people of a city,'' Baldinu said, ``people who are
trying to fly, to get into another atmosphere, the same people that
you can see in the street walking to their job.''
</P>
<P>
   James said, ``People walk out and some are saying, `Ahh, that
was the beginning of creation,' and someone else will say, `No, it
was Armageddon.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the directors urge people not to analyze. ``We don't want
the audience to think,'' Baldinu said. ``We want them to feel, all
the time. We want to give them a lot of sensations and situations
to react to, so they can't ask what it all means.''
</P>
</TEXT>
