<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GUN-CONTROL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BARS SAFETY RULES IN NEW-HANDGUN SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Attorney General Scott Harshbarger's plan to use
consumer protection laws to attack gun violence was dealt a serious
setback Wednesday by a Suffolk Superior Court judge who ruled
Harshbarger does not have the legal authority to mandate quality
control standards for new guns sold in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Diane Kottmyer Wednesday issued a
preliminary injunction that bars Harshbarger from enforcing the
quality standards that took effect Tuesday. She also barred rules,
scheduled to take effect Sept. 30, from being enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power granted to the attorney general by (state law) does
not encompass the power to establish design and performance
standards for products sold in Massachusetts,'' Kottmyer wrote in
her 15-page order.
</P>
<P>
   She said lawmakers have never authorized Harshbarger to use the
consumer protection law the way he has against gunmakers. The law
``seeks to prevent economic harm'' while the gun regulations are
aimed at ``the threat to public safety posed by defective and
otherwise unsafe'' handguns, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Kottmyer also noted that she issued the preliminary injunction
because gunmakers who sued Harshbarger have shown they are likely
to win their case and would suffer ``irreparable harm'' if forced
to modify their plants to accommodate the Massachusetts
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Harsbarger said Wednesday he is confident he will ultimately
convince the courts that he was within his authority to issue the
rules, which also required gunmakers to start installing child
safety locks in new guns sold in the state after Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger is the first attorney general in the nation to turn
to local consumer laws as a way to attack ``junk guns'' and
Saturday Night specials that law enforcement blames for a large
percentage of gun-related crimes in the state. His effort is backed
by the Massachusetts Chiefs of Police Association as well as
handgun control groups and emergency room physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe common sense will prevail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank A. Libby Jr., the Boston attorney for the industry's
gunmakers and gunshop owners, said he was ``pleased with the
result, but equally gratified with the thoughtful, detailed
decision recognizing the limits on the attorney general's
rulemaking authority.''
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, Kottmyer did allow Harshbarger to enforce one
rule, which requires gunmakers to disclose the accuracy of new guns
with barrels less than 3 inches long. An industry spokesman said
companies will comply, but questioned the validity of the standard,
which requires new guns to be shot from 7 yards, 14 yards, and 21
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody shoots a handgun at 21 yards in self-defense,'' Richard
Feldman, executive director of the American Shooting Sports Council
Inc., said Wednesday. ``What are you doing shooting at someone 63
feet away?''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman also said the industry would prefer to work with
Harshbarger _ instead of fighing in court _ to achieve what Feldman
said was a common goal of reducing gun-related crimes and violence.
The US Conference of Mayors has recently begun talking with
gunmakers about their financial cost and human cost stemming from
gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Under the regulations that Kottmyer put on hold, new guns must
meet quality standards governing the metal used to make them, and
must past ``drop tests'' that show the gun won't accidentally
discharge.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations also require new guns to have ``load
indicators'' which tell whether a cartridge is in the chamber of
semi-automatic weapons, and ``magazine safety disconnect'' that
would prevent a gun from firing if a magazine had been removed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
