<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STARS' GAME A STRANGER IN NEW YORK  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When baseball's All-Star Game begins Tuesday night at Coors
Field in Colorado, the nation's fans have decreed that no member of
baseball's real all-star team, the Yankees, will be in the American
League starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With a 56-20 record before Wednesday night's game with the
Phillies, not having an All-Star starter is a tribute to what the
Yankees have accomplished as a team this season.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also an indictment of both the Yankees and the Mets in
dimming the dazzle of the All-Star Game by not holding it for more
than two decades at Yankee Stadium or Shea Stadium. Out of sight,
out of mind for many New York fans in the annual balloting for
starting lineups.
</P>
<P>
   If the game were played at Yankee Stadium or at Shea Stadium
more often, New York fans would care more about it.
</P>
<P>
   In the fans' voting sponsored this year by CompUSA and Pepsi,
each of the 30 major league clubs received 1 million ballots to
distribute to fans at its ball park. The larger a club's attendance
during the voting period, the more ballots are likely to be filled
out.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rich Levin, the executive director of public
relations for Major League Baseball, no record is available as to
how many ballots were cast in each of the various franchise areas.
</P>
<P>
   Although no Yankee will be among the eight starting position
players, the AL manager, Mike Hargrove of the Cleveland Indians,
added five Yankees to the squad Wednesday _ center fielder Bernie
Williams, right fielder Paul O'Neill, shortstop Derek Jeter, third
baseman Scott Brosius and the left-handed pitcher David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   The only Mets starter, Mike Piazza, opened on the National
League ballot as the Los Angeles Dodgers' catcher before being
traded to Florida and then to New York. Only one other Met, the
right-hander Rick Reed, was added to the NL squad.
</P>
<P>
   If and when the Yankees and the Mets get new stadiums, maybe
they would be willing to put an All-Star Game on display. Until
then, it is something that happens everywhere but New York. There
has not been one at Yankee Stadium since 1977, the year after the
renovated Bronx ball park reopened. There has only been one at
Shea, in 1964, the year it opened.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder New York fans don't seem to get out the vote for the
All-Star Game. It has been a generation since they have had one.
</P>
<P>
   And the earliest New York could get the game is 2001. Next
year's site is Fenway Park in Boston. In 2000, Florida has it.
</P>
<P>
   In any baseball team's big picture, the season is what's
important. The All-Star Game is just a one-night show. Two days
later, nobody remembers who won. But the score isn't important. For
three hours on a Tuesday night in July, it's a wonderful show _ the
best all-star game in sports.
</P>
<P>
   New York was reminded of the fun of the spectacle last February
when the Knicks and Madison Square Garden were the hosts for the
National Basketball Association's All-Star Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a serious result, the NBA's best players were on
display, especially Michael Jordan in what might have been his
final All-Star Game and his next-to-last Garden appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But in the NBA All-Star Game, nobody plays defense unless it
comes down to the final minute, if then. In pro football's all-star
game, the Pro Bowl, nobody is allowed to blitz the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's All-Star Game is much more valid. By the nature of
baseball, its game is sport's ultimate one-on-one confrontation:
the best hitters against the best pitchers. And there's no rule
that says the pitchers can't throw their best fastball, their best
breaking ball or their best changeup.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the game, the All-Star workout day on Monday,
with its home run derby, skills competitions and team batting
practices, provides fun for fans who don't have tickets to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   When the workout day began about two decades ago, it was free.
The ball park gates were open. But it proved to be so popular, it's
now a hot ticket. They needed a lottery to distribute the
workout-day tickets this year in Denver, where the price ranged
from $25 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, there's no baseball All-Star Game, no All-Star
workout day, no All-Star fun and festivities. And until there is,
the All-Star Game will never create the New York interest it
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
