<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREATBAGEL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX OUTLET SATURATION CLAIMS GREAT BAGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Great Bagel &AMP; Coffee Co. closed its 11 company-owned
locations Wednesday after a two-year struggle for profitabilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last two years it's been very hard. We've been losing
money, and the competition continued to come in,'' said Gary
Sandeen, president of the Phoenix-based company.
</P>
<P>
   The closure has put some 120 workers out of jobs. Great Bagel
will refer them to other restaurants looking for workers, Sandeen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Four franchisee-owned stores in the Phoenix area and two Great
Bagel Expresses located in Phoenix and Tempe (Ariz.) Texaco
Starmarts will remain open.
</P>
<P>
   When Great Bagel opened in 1993 offering big bagels, specialty
cream cheese and gourmet coffee, there were only a handful of bagel
and coffee shops in the Valley, Sandeen said. At the start of this
year, however, he estimated there were 128 shops in the Phoenix
area competing in that segment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oversaturation has hurt sales. Where we used to be the only
place, now there are three and four options for people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bagels' reputation as primarily a breakfast item also hurt the
stores' ability to attract a lunch crowd, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company tried a variety of things to survive, he said,
including slashing overhead and merging locations. It stopped
selling franchises more than a year ago as managers tried to get
their hands around Great Bagel's problems, Sandeen said.
</P>
<P>
   A potential deal to sell Great Bagel &AMP; Coffee Co. fell through,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trends kept getting worse and worse,'' he said. He
estimated the company lost $400,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Great Bagel was owned by Uniquely Casual Restaurants Inc. of
Danvers, Mass., and a partnership of private investors, Sandeen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though consumers' bagel consumption continues to rise, Great
Bagel's demise is not the first sign of distress in the once-hot
business.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan Bagel Co. of Eatonway, N.J., which operates primarily
on the East Coast, filed for Chapter 11 reorganization in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court last November.
</P>
<P>
   Stock in Einstein/Noah Bagel Corp., which does business in the
Phoenix area as Einstein Bros. Bagels, has fallen to the $3-$5
range from $15 a year ago. Boston Chicken Inc., which owns 52
percent of the San Diego-based company, has put its stake up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Other major players have yet to achieve their planned
expansions.
</P>
<P>
   Brueggers Bagel Bakery opened in Phoenix in 1996 with plans for
25 stores within five years. It currently has five stores.
</P>
<P>
   Chesapeake Bagel Bakery of Washington, D.C., entered the local
market in 1994 with plans for 20 franchises over the next five
years. It currently has two stores.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix remains a strong market for Einstein, with double-digit
growth year-to-year in comparable-store sales, marketing manager
Matt Sullivan said Wednesday. The company, which entered Phoenix
nearly three years ago, has 14 company-owned stores in the market
and plans four more this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Larson can be reached at jane.larson(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CZECH-GYPSIES-ART-NYT     07-01 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-GYPSIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYPSIES IN CZECH REPUBLIC FACE GROWING DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   USTI NAD LABEM, Czech Republic _ On the outskirts of this
depressed industrial town, about 50 Gypsy families live in two
dilapidated, graffiti-strewn apartment blocks along Maticni Street
where voices are often loud and celebrations boisterous.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street stand three prim row houses with gray facades
and white lace curtains drawn across the windows. These are the
homes of Czech families who have persuaded the City Council to
build a 15-foot-wall on the Gypsy side of Maticni Street to
separate the Czechs, physically and psychologically, from what they
consider their undesirable neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The Gypsies and several Czech human rights groups have called
the wall an attempt to create a ghetto. They declare that the
project is the latest example of designating the Gypsies, who
number between 200,000 and 300,000, as outsiders in the Czech
Republic, which has a population of about 10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, Ladislav Hruska, makes no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wall is about one group that obeys the laws of the Czech
Republic and behaves according to good morals, and about a group
that breaks these rules _ doesn't pay rent, doesn't use proper
hygiene and doesn't do anything right,'' Hruska said as he sat in
his office below a portrait of President Vaclav Havel, a prominent
spokesman for human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a racial problem. It is a problem of dealing with
decent and indecent people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years the Czech government _ once widely
considered the leader in Central Europe in the transition from
communist rule, which ended in 1989, to a civil society _ has come
under increasing criticism for its failure to address the growing
disparities between Gypsies and non-Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent U.S. State Department report on human rights
around the world gave vivid detail of how Gypsies, also called
Romany or Roma, ``suffer disproportionately from poverty,
unemployment, interethnic violence, discrimination, illiteracy and
disease.'' Unemployment among Gypsies is about 70 percent, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   After Usti nad Labem announced that the wall would be built,
Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., co-chairman of the Commission on
Security and Cooperation in Europe, criticized the Czech cabinet
for remaining silent in the face of continuing attacks and
discrimination against Gypsies and other minorities. The only
criticism of the wall by a Czech government official so far has
come from the minister without portfolio, Vladimir Mlynar, who is
responsible for Gypsy affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Smith attributed the government's silence in part
to politics. Public opinion polls have consistently shown that
Czechs harbor what the State Department report called a ``deeply
ingrained popular prejudice against Gypsies,'' and Czech
politicians, like all others, keep a close eye on opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The prejudice, of course, is felt acutely among the Gypsies of
Maticni Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how three families have more sway than 50
families,'' said Miroslav Demeter, 44, as he looked over at the
austere facades across the narrow street. ``The wall will make
things worse. The Romany are very angry, because all over Europe
they are breaking down walls but here they are building walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Demeter and several other Gypsies acknowledged that all was not
perfect at the apartment houses. It was true, he said, that many
families did not pay rent to the city. It was also true, said Tibor
Badi, 48, that some families used the surrounding gardens as a
refuse heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing on my verandah smoking a cigarette one day and
I was almost hit by a falling chair,'' he said, when one tenant
decided to discard the chair by throwing it out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the issue is that the Gypsy community is quite
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   It includes families like Badi's, who have held jobs for many
years and who lived during the Communist period alongside Czechs in
integrated housing. High school certificates on the living room
wall in Badi's apartment attest to the education that he and his
wife, Marta, received under communism.
</P>
<P>
   But other Gypsy families here have little education, have rarely
held full-time jobs and show contempt for the better educated like
Badi.
</P>
<P>
   At the bar U Pristavu on the corner of Maticni Street, the
owner, Eva Kompertova, says she allows in only certain Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let in three families _ they don't make any trouble _ but I
don't let the others in because they get into fights,'' Ms.
Kompertova said as she sipped a beer with some Czech customers.
``On our side of the street, Romanies are not allowed. They don't
even go over there because it's so clean they feel uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with Gypsies from the apartment houses, Hruska
agreed to postpone construction of the wall to September. In the
meantime, the Gypsies are being asked to keep the area clean and
reduce the noise level. But Hruska said he did not believe the
Gypsies would meet the required standard.
</P>
<P>
   Demeter, who was tending a newly planted garden, was not
optimistic either. ``In three months you can't change things,'' he
said. ``It's the culture; Romany people are different.''
</P>
<P>
   In Prague, a human rights advocate at the Helsinki Committee for
Human Rights, Marta Mikluskova, said it is essential that the City
Council drop the plan. ``If Usti is allowed to build a wall, it
will become a precedent for other towns,'' she said, ``and others
will start planning and do it within a year or two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
