<SLUG> BC-IRISH-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON PEACE GROUP TO MONITOR IRISH MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As thousands of Protestants &UR;  &LR; threaten to defy police
and march through a Catholic ghetto in Northern Ireland's Portadown
neighborhood this Sunday, carrying lambeg drums and singing
anti-Catholic songs, a group of Bostonians will be in their midst,
monitoring the violence that's expected to erupt.
</P>
<P>
   PeaceWatch Ireland, a Boston grass-roots group, is sending a
delegation of four that includes Heeten Kalan, a South African who
lives in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Northern Ireland resonates with me,'' said
Kalan, who has toured the Belfast area five times. ``The heavy
level of security and surveillance just blew me away. It reminded
me of parts of South Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fear that the march could become the first large-scale
confrontation between Irish Catholics and Protestants since a peace
agreement was approved in May.
</P>
<P>
   Kalan will arrive in Ireland this morning, along with Sean
Cahill, an Irish-American activist; Jean Riesman, a Jewish woman;
and Scott Daugherty, an Irish Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   With cameras strapped to their necks and pen and pads in their
hands, the four plan to document any violence at the Orange Order
march.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland Parades Commission ruled last week that the
marchers must use another route, but the Orange Order says it is
within its civil rights to march down Garvaghy Road, a main
thoroughfare of the Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the parades commission forbade the Protestant
Unionists from marching down Garvaghy Road, a standoff lasted five
days. When police finally allowed the marchers to go down Garvaghy
Road, they beat scores of Catholic nationalists who tried to block
their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what the Orange Order stands for ... they are
very similar to the Klu Klux Klan,'' Cahill said. ``They are a
supremacist organization. This march is about dominance over
another group. That's why it's so offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalan said he hopes the presence of PeaceWatch Ireland, along
with hundreds of other witnesses from around the world, will help
keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the world will be watching this particular march,'' he
said. ``Whatever happens is going to have a significant impact on
the peace process in Northern Ireland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
