<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6636 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASAMANANA-OVERHAUL-T     07-01 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACE LIFT WON'T ALTER TRADITION AT CASA MANANA
</HEADLINE>
 MANANA-OVERHAUL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The musicals will still go round and round
at Casa Manana, even after the domed theater undergoes a major
renovation _ the first in its 40-year history _ with money raised
in a $5 million campaign that stands at $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Denton Yockey, in his first season as executive producer,
suggested this year that the theater explore changing Casa from a
theater-in-the-round format to a proscenium, or modified thrust,
stage. In May, the Casa board voted 19-16 to keep Casa Manana in
the round but to improve sight lines and add a revolving stage.
</P>
<P>
   Those enhancements will be part of an estimated $4.6 million
spruce-up that includes all-new seats, more restrooms and
concessions, and more classrooms for Casa Manana Children's
Playhouse and School. Any money left over from the $5 million will
be put into an endowment fund for maintaining the building.
</P>
<P>
   When the changes are completed, Casa will seat 1,500 instead of
the current 1,800. If the modified-thrust plan had been adopted,
the capacity would have been 1,200.
</P>
<P>
   The work won't begin until most of the money is raised. Yockey
and his board would like to begin the renovation at the end of a
summer, stage winter shows in the new Bass performance hall in
downtown Fort Worth, and reopen the domed theater the following
summer. Casa's $5 million capital campaign started in February
1996, but for a time, it took a back seat to the Bass hall's
money-raising effort.
</P>
<P>
   With theater-in-the-round, the audience surrounds the stage.
This heightens intimacy, but it limits the use of scenery and all
but rules out the lavish spectacles that are the current rage. In
proscenium-style theaters, such as the Bass hall, the audience is
seated in front of the stage and never sees what happens on either
side of or in back of the performance space. This enables elaborate
changes of scenery. Proscenium-style theaters typically have
overhead ``fly space'' with which to introduce large set pieces and
concoct special effects, such as the famous crashing chandelier in
``The Phantom of the Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether or not to get rid of theater-in-the-round
at Casa Manana has been the topic of quietly intense speculation
within the Fort Worth theater community for several weeks. There
were no apparent heated confrontations between the factions,
although some longtime theatergoers believed that Yockey, the new
guy in town, was reaching too high too soon.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Yockey is straining mightily to be a cheerleader
for Casa Manana-in-the-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is torn up about this,'' he said. ``It was something we
wanted to explore. The debate, I think, was instructive and
positive for the board. It gave them a real issue. We're not
staying theater-in-the-round because we just happen to. We voted to
do it. We endorsed theater-in-the-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a choice. I'm delighted with the changes we've added,
and I think we'll continue to do great theater here. The seat
reduction is not going to harm us. We're not using most of those
seats now. My efforts were always about improving the quality of
the experience as opposed to trying to maximize seating capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Casa Manana will continue to produce summer musicals on its home
stage at University Drive and West Lancaster in the Fort Worth
Cultural District. But the number of shows per season may vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already muted slightly, in that our winter season is
moving to the Bass hall,'' Yockey said. ``In the summers we may
decide to have more musicals, or fewer. And we'll probably present
more concerts in the home theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Clifton, Casa's vice president of development, is one of
the board members who favored the modified thrust stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the limitations of theater-in-the-round,'' Clifton
said. ``And we felt that as custodians of the institution and as
custodians of the funds being raised, we had an obligation not to
reject change out of hand just because it was a departure from
tradition. There was an interest in knowing we were exploring all
feasible and reasonable possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifton agrees that having to decide between two stage designs
has been a healthy experience for board members, forcing them to
inform themselves about the theater's options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to explore what would deliver the best patron
experience from an artistic standpoint,'' he said. ``Then we
explored how to get the greatest breadth in the number of
productions that can be done. Then there was the financial issue,
the cost of putting on shows under each configuration. Then,
finally, you weigh in for the patrons who look at Casa as a Fort
Worth institution and ask how much of that is tied to it being in
the round.''
</P>
<P>
   The redesign of the seating area will enable Casa to correct
what Yockey calls ``a 40-year-old mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Dacus and James Snowden, the two Fort Worth men who had
the most to do with making Casa Manana happen back in 1958, wanted
a sharp rake, or slant, from the seats to the stage. But the city
of Fort Worth was involved in the project. And for some
incalculable reason, the bureaucrats or inspectors of the day
argued for a gentler slope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage was supposed to be at a lower level,'' Yockey said.
``The audience needed to look down at the stage, and Mel Dacus
fought for that. But the city folks apparently thought they were
the experts, and that Mel and Mr. Snowden didn't really know what
they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The stage was built low, all right. But with the mild rake that
the city insisted on, the stage wasn't fully visible. So it had to
be built up, as was the orchestra pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual pit floor is lower than the one we use. You can
just see it,'' Yockey said, pointing to a small fissure in the
wooden floor of the orchestra area.
</P>
<P>
   Dacus, an honorary board member who argued in favor of keeping
the in-the-round format, said he is pleased with the renovation
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can rebuild the interior with high-rake seats in the
back and put a revolving stage in, that would be interesting,'' he
said. ``That would preserve the round and at the same time give
some innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
