<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-TEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION CHIEF OUT; TEACHER TEST THRESHOLD RAISED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Board of Education's acting commissioner stepped
down unexpectedly Wednesday effective immediately, leaving the
meeting room even before the board reversed itself and raised the
passing standard on Massachusetts' first teacher certification
test.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci filed a bill Wednesday
that would require all current teachers to take the certification
test.
</P>
<P>
   At the board hearing, interim Board of Education chief Frank
Haydu III walked out of the meeting, to gasps from the audience.
His departure was prompted by a discussion with board chairman John
Silber Tuesday night, he and Silber said afterward, in which Silber
made clear Haydu no longer enjoyed the support of the board. Haydu
had earlier said he would stay on until September.
</P>
<P>
   The board immediately appointed David Driscoll, longtime deputy
education commissioner and a former Melrose schools superintendent,
as interim chief. Members then resumed debate over the teacher test
grading.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 6-1, the board reversed its vote of last week and
raised the passing score on the new teacher test to the higher
standard recommended earlier by an education panel.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote affects only candidates who took the April 4
test, or who plan to take the July 11 test. Teacher candidates
taking the test in October and later had always been required to
pass at the higher standard.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the passing standard voted in Wednesday, 59 percent of
the 1,800 candidates who took the two-part, eight-hour test in
April failed, compared to 44 percent who failed under the lower
standard. The change affects 263 candidates who passed under the
lower standard, who now must retake the test.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Candidates can expect to get their scores in the mail within
the next few days, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As testing experts see it, the controversy surrounding the
teacher test and the rush by politicians to impugn the quality of
the candidates, and current teachers, is based more on political
motivation than an understanding of the details of the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Finn, executive director of the Massachusetts Association
of School Superintendents, told the board that the change in the
passing standard voted Wednesday is ``relatively minor.'' Raising
the passing score by one or two points, he said, hardly affects the
caliber of teachers who barely pass.
</P>
<P>
   On the literacy and communications test, the education panel's
higher standard, adopted Wednesday, requires that candidates get 28
out of 36 points to pass the reading section; 17 out of 23 to pass
the grammar portion, and 17 out of 24 to pass the writing
mechanics, summary, and composition section.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these standards is only one point higher than the
standards adopted last week, Finn noted, except for the writing
section, where the passing score was raised by two points.
</P>
<P>
   Educators also said references to teachers getting ``D''s or
``F''s on the exam have been incorrect, because no letter grades
are assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret McKenna, president of Lesley College, who addressed the
board Wednesday, said the test is graded much like the Scholastic
Achievement Test in high school; by point, not grade.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Abigail Thernstrom said after the vote that she
will propose a measure at September's board meeting that randomly
selected Massachusetts teachers be made to take the test
anonymously, with no consequences if they fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would provide data to shape professional development
policies and give further insight into the quality of the test,''
she said. She noted that she did not know whether her proposal
would require legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote came after Cellucci, House Speaker Thomas
Finneran, and others lambasted the board's first vote lowering the
standard, saying it undermined education reform's effort to raise
standards for students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever said improving our public schools would be easy,''
Cellucci told board members before their vote Wednesday. ``We want
to make sure that when a new teacher goes into the classroom, they
are competent and capable.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Cellucci's proposal to test all teachers, Beacon Hill
observers said Wednesday that with the legislative term set to
expire in a few weeks, and the likely focus on election efforts in
the fall, there appears little likelihood the bill would get
serious consideration this year.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Wednesday's vote, Thernstrom said she initially
voted in favor of lowering the passing standard ``in deference to
Frank Haydu. I had felt an obligation to work with him and be a
team player. But he is no longer commissioner and that
consideration is off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Thernstrom said, she ``never thought that the
message we delivered (with the first vote) would be heard as a
reduced commitment to high standards. It is important to deliver
more firmly'' the board's support for high standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
