<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-REACT-BOS &LR;      07-01 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS VOICE DISPLEASURE OVER NEW PAPAL CANONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II's effort to end debate on such controversial
issues as the ordination of women through changes he made this week
in canon law, will not succeed in forcing obedience from the many
Roman Catholics alienated from the church, several theologians and
scholars interviewed said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's warning that those who dissent from church teachings
would face a ``just penalty'' unleashed widespread criticism by
theologians Wednesday, though little comment from the American
church hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretentious attempt by the present pope to stifle
conversation and dialogue,'' said Thomas Groome, professor of
theology and religious education at Boston College. ``I read the
blessed thing and without being too melodramatic, I was on the
verge of tears. It's a very sad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Catholic theologians predicted the harsh tone of the papal
document would harden the views of the many American Catholics who
already consider Vatican pronouncements irrelevant to their
spiritual lives. Others said the Pope was merely making definitive
what has been Vatican teaching for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Matthew Lamb, a professor of theology at Boston College
and a prominent Catholic intellectual, said the papal decree was
necessary because too many American theologians have become
enamored with popular cultural trends, abandoning sound
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in communion with the pope and we have a tradition to
uphold,'' Lamb said. ``There has been an awful lot of dumbing down
of Catholic knowledge and tradition and and as a result we have
these sorts of problems and debates. The Holy Father is calling our
attention to what really is Catholic teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   By explicitly spelling out the penalties for any Catholic who
opposes truths the church holds to be ``definitive,'' the pope
seemed to be taking aim at liberal American Catholic theologians,
who have in recent years challenged the Vatican's authority on
doctrinal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Church observers said the Vatican seems concerned that these
professors are too heavily influencing rank-and-file Catholics, and
need to be forcefully reined in.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul said he was acting to change canon law ``to defend the
faith of the Catholic Church against the errors that arise on the
part of some faithful, especially those dedicated to the discipline
of sacred theology.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's letter discussed the church's ``profession of
faith,'' a list of basic Catholic beliefs John Paul reworked in
1989. All clergy and Catholic teachers are required to abide by
this profession. His letter then detailed the penalties for
dissenting from these articles of faith.
</P>
<P>
   What provoked the dismay of many theologians and Catholic
activists was not just the letter but an accompanying commentary by
the Vatican's chief ideological watchdog detailing examples of
articles of faith ``definitively held'' by the church and therefore
``infallibly taught.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those mentioned by Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, who heads
the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, were the church's
teachings on euthanasia, sexual relations outside marriage and the
exclusion of women from the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   Ratzinger said anyone who rejects a Catholic doctrine would ``no
longer be in full communion with the Catholic Church.'' The
punishment dissenters might face could range from warnings to
excommunication, church officials said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The Vatican would be very happy if all discussion of
anything theologically questionable would cease,'' said Carolyn
Osiek, professor of New Testament at Catholic Theological Union in
Chicago. ``In fact, that won't happen, because the job of
theologians is to keep pursuing issues and raising questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will have a chilling effect on theological
discourse throughout the Catholic world,'' said Scott Appleby,
director of the Cushwa Center for the Study of American Catholicism
at the University of Notre Dame. Particularly vulnerable would be
teachers at schools under direct ecclesiastical control, like
Catholic seminaries, and nuns and priests who are under the
authority of religious superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Even at powerful Roman Catholic institutions, like Notre Dame,
Boston College and Georgetown University, where professors enjoy
broad academic freedom, the papal document could be useful
ammunition to conservatives trying to weed out liberal teachers,
Appleby said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been alumni, people on boards of trustees who have
been saying, `Why are we letting liberal theologians question the
teachings of the church?''' Appleby said. ``This kind of ruling
will allow those people to say, `See, we told you so,' and put
pressure on university administrators not to be supportive of
dissenting theologians.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing chasm between the Vatican and a significant number
of American Catholics undermines the church's ability to speak
effectively about social and economic issues, several theologians
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very deeply-rooted trend in the church to simply
ignore the institutional church and concentrate on one's own
community of faith, and that's unfortunate,'' said David O'Brien,
Loyola professor of Roman Catholic studies at the College of the
Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass. ``The institutional church is
becoming less and less important in the lives of people, and as a
result the church is in a weaker position to carry out its mission
and address vital issues like poverty, immigration, labor rights.
People just turn their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's pronouncements also has caused bitter feelings
among some Protestants. Among the articles of faith Ratzinger cited
as being ``definitively held'' was the 1896 declaration of Pope Leo
XIII on the ``invalidity of Anglican ordinations.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Catholic church does not recognize Anglican
ordinations, Roman Catholic and Anglican leaders have made
significant progress in recent years in improving relations between
the two churches.
</P>
<P>
   R. William Franklin, dean of the divinity school at Yale
University and a key participant in Anglican-Catholic
conversations, said the Vatican decree brings the ecumenical
movement to a ``halt, because if someone else's priestly orders are
declared invalid and it's considered an infallible teaching, why
talk?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
