<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED LOTTERY WINNER'S QUIRKS DESCRIBED AT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Watertown widow who claims she won a $21 million
lottery jackpot often changed her mind and canceled lottery tickets
after purchasing them, another avid lottery player testified
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Donald Philippe, 41, said he saw 72-year-old
Paraskeve Kantges play the lottery hundreds of times at different
Watertown locations.
</P>
<P>
   Often, he said, he purchased lottery tickets she had rejected
and declined to pay for after ordering them.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always changed her mind. I'd tell the guy, `I'll take
it.''' Philippe said, referring to Kantges' rejected tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges claims she telephoned the winning Mass Millions bet to
Coolidge Provisions on Feb. 5, but store owner Nick Havan said she
called back later to cancel the bet, so he kept the winning ticket
for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges denies she canceled the bet. She has records to show she
played the same number every day for years.
</P>
<P>
   Former Massachusetts Lottery executive director Samuel M.
DePhillippo ruled in favor of Kangtes, but Havan appealed. Retired
Superior Court Judge Robert Steadman is hearing the appeal at
lottery headquarters in Brantree and will make a recommendation to
the full lottery commission.
</P>
<P>
   A third person, Sonia Bardakjian of Watertown also claims the
jackpot. Like Kantges, Bardakjian said she phoned in a bet on the
winning number to Coolidge Provisions. The lottery rejected her
claim.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Wednesday, Philippe, an MBTA bus driver who lived
in Watertown for years, described an occasion where he said Kantges
snapped a lottery ticket he had just purchased out of his hand and
claimed it was hers. ``I said, `Hey lady what are you doing with my
ticket?.' I grabbed it back from her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
