<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ARCHAEOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHAEOLOGISTS PROTEST REPORTS ULTRA-ORTHODOX TO HEAD ISRAELI
EXCAVATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Breaking ancient clay pots and carrying protest
signs, dozens of angry archaeologists demonstrated Wednesday over
reports that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has promised an
ultra-Orthodox party effective control over the country's
excavations.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeology has been at the center of debate in Israel for years
with the ultra-Orthodox vehemently _ and sometimes violently _
opposed to excavations in which they believe Jewish graves have
been found.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the demonstrators are employees of the Israel
Antiquities Authority. One protester shouted over a loudspeaker:
``We do this to show how we feel about the agreement between Bibi
and the Haredim,'' using Netanyahu's nickname and the Hebrew term
for the ultra-Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such an agreement is ... anti-democratic,'' said Emanuel
Zissman, a Knesset member from the centrist Third Way party who
opposes any deal that would give Israel's ultra-Orthodox a say in
scientific digs. He was one of several parliament members and
public figures gathered at the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The antiquities authority workers said the march from the
Supreme Court to the Knesset was in response to local press reports
concerning a deal with the United Torah Judaism Party, part of
Netanyahu's coalition. One report said Netanyahuy would replace the
current antiquities authority director general with one more
sympathetic to their sensitivities. A spokesman for the prime
minister's office would not comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists said they feared that the move would likely halt
excavations of graves immediately and could eventually hamper digs
throughout a country in which archaeologists have uncovered
evidence corroborating the Bible and shed light on such esoteric
sects as the Essenes, to which many scholars believe John the
Baptist belonged.
</P>
<P>
   With 18,000 digs, Israel has more excavations than any other
country.
</P>
<P>
   Three millennia of Jewish, Christian and Muslim history are
buried beneath the deserts and valleys here. Findings provide a
greater understanding of the history of the Near East, are often
used in textbooks all over the world, and are the subject of
intense debate within the world of archaeology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Step by step, the ultra-Orthodox will try to stop the
archaeological research in the country,'' said Giora Parnos, an
archaeologist with the antiquities authority who works on general
digs. ``They'll try to stop everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Orthodox rabbis have ruled that excavating graves does not
contravene Jewish law. Ultra-Orthodox rabbis contend that the
excavations do, viewing graves as sacred sites that should remain
untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that just as you wouldn't want me to dig up your
grandfather, we don't want you to dig up our grandfathers,'' said
Aren Maeir, an archaeologist who is also Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   But in a country with 3,000 years of human history, coming
across a grave site during a routine ``salvage dig'' _ required by
Israeli law before construction is permitted _ is common.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, ultra-Orthodox, particularly from an
extremist sect called Atra Kadisha, descend on the site, where they
fling themselves into graves to prevent their excavation, throw
stones, call the archaeologists ``Nazis'' and recite the pulsa
dinura, a curse that supposedly brings death to the person named.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do this all the time, every day,'' said Osnat Goaz, an
archaeologist with the antiquities authority. ``A normal day for us
is like that. If there isn't a demonstration, I say, `Wow, a really
nice day.' It's part of our lives here.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Amir Drori, general director of the
antiquities authority, has been the focus of particular wrath from
ultra-Orthodox groups. Local press reports said members of the UTJ,
an Ashkenazi ultra-Orthodox party with four seats in the 120-member
Knesset, threatened to quit Netanyahu's coalition if he did not
replace Drori with someone more amenable to them.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Radio said Netanyahu likely would appoint Tiberias mayor
Yossi Peretz to the job. Some archaeologists said they feared that
Peretz would bring new members to the Archaeological Council, a
body of the antiquities authority, who would see to it that graves
were not excavated. Peretz withheld comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this will happen, it will stop the excavation of ancient
tombs,'' said Motti Aviam, another archaeologist with the
antiquities authority. ``Later they will stop most of the
archaeology in Israel, and this is what we are afraid of.''
</P>
<P>
   Antiquities authority personnel said that if the deal with the
ultra-Orthodox went through, they would fight it at a Knesset
hearing next week and may take the case to the Supreme Court on
grounds that Netanyahu was infringing on scientific freedom by
granting religious oversight to archaeological excavations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
