<SLUG> BC-MEDRISK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medirisk stock tumbles 69% on earnings report
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Shares of Atlanta-based Medirisk plunged 69 percent
Wednesday after the health-care software company said
second-quarter earnings would fall far short of analyst estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Medirisk made the earnings announcement after the market closed
Tuesday. The stock price then tumbled Wednesday from $20.25 to a
52-week low of $4.87 1/2 before closing at $6.31 1/4, down $13.93
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   It was the leading percentage decliner on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume was 6.9 million shares, vs. a daily average of
about 117,000 shares. Also Wednesday, two analysts sharply
downgraded Medirisk stock.
</P>
<P>
   Medirisk declined to comment on the sell-off, saying, ``It's the
company's policy not to comment on market activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock decline caused Medirisk to lose about $100 million in
market value. ``It's a shock,'' Jim Oberweis, a portfolio manager
at Oberweis Asset Management, which owns Medirisk shares, told
Bloomberg Business News. ``It just adds a whole lot of uncertainty
to the equation.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was expected to earn 12 cents a share in the second
quarter, according to analysts surveyed by I/B/E/S. But Medirisk,
which went public last year, said earnings per share, excluding
one-time charges, are expected to be in the range of break-even to
2 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Medirisk said second-quarter revenues are expected to be from
$5.1 million to $5.3 million. In the year-ago quarter, the company
reported revenues of $3.2 million, and adjusted earnings per share
of 7 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the earnings disappointment Tuesday, Mark Kaiser,
Medirisk chairman and chief executive, cited weak sales in its
financial software. Those products include one that tracks
physician charges and reimbursements for 7,400 medical procedures
across dozens of geographic markets.
</P>
<P>
   Other Medirisk software reports patient satisfaction with
managed-care plans, forecasts medical utilization patterns, and
measures outcomes of procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Among Medirisk's clients are employers, hospitals, doctors, and
managed-care companies, which seek data on the cost and results of
physician procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser also said sales lagged in its software that verifies
physician credentials to hospitals and managed-care companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Medirisk also announced Tuesday it acquired a physician
credentialing company, Sweetwater Health Enterprises, for $6.2
million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking action to change sales management, implement new
product distribution channels and introduce new product
enhancements,'' Kaiser said in a statement. But he added, ``The
softness in these (sales) areas is expected to carry over into the
second half of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Medirisk declined to comment further on the sales shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Seth Frank at SunTrust Equitable Securities changed
Medirisk to ``no opinion'' from a ``strong buy'' rating. Robert
Bolen of J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co., who also rated Medirisk a strong buy,
suspended it from coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Medirisk, which employs about 400, expects to announce the
earnings results during the week of July 13. It also announced its
line of credit with NationsBank has increased to $25 million from
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
