<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRAZIL, IT ALL DEPENDS ON DUNGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Only four Brazilians have captained a World Cup
championship team. And only one has a chance to do it twice.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Caetano Bledhorn Verri _ ``Carlos'' to his teammates,
``Dunga'' to the outside world _ has announced his intentions to
become the first repeat captain through his vociferousness as
Brazil has qualified for a quarterfinal match against Denmark in
Nantes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga has been the most demonstrative of the Brazilians,
reprimanding teammates and even coach Mario Zagallo, in an attempt
to galvanize what Pele described as the best group of players in
the World Cup, but not necessarily the best team.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ronaldinho is more prominent, Leonardo more flashy,
Junior Baiano more powerful, Cafu and Roberto Carlos much faster,
if Brazil becomes ``pentacampeon,'' the symbol of success might
well be Dunga.
</P>
<P>
   Others have stereotypical Brazilian qualities. Dunga adds a
sense of purpose and guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga has changed little since the 1990 World Cup in Italy,
except that his light, flowing hair has been cropped in a
Marine-style crew cut. Then, Brazil played conservatively and was
eliminated by Argentina. Coach Sebastiao Lazaroni and Dunga
received most of the blame for removing the fantasy from the
Selecao.
</P>
<P>
   But perceptions of Dunga have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dunga was like a European player, strong but not very
technical,'' Luis Agosto Veloso, former president of CR Flamengo,
said Wednesday from training camp in Ozoir La Ferriere. ``It took
some time for him to earn the respect of Brazilians. Now in Brazil
they are convinced he is necessary in the team as a leader, a point
of reference.''
</P>
<P>
   So, are the days of jogo bonito (the beautiful game) finished?
Is Brazil sacrificing samba for cynicism?
</P>
<P>
   ``The people always want a spectacle,'' Dunga said at the
beginning of the World Cup finals. ``But soccer is not only
fantasy. If it was so, Brazil would not have gone 24 years without
winning a World Cup. Looking back, the best team always prevails,
and the best team is that which is most complete at every level _
technique, but also the best tactically and organizationally,
because in soccer everyone has to help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Brazilian team to win the World Cup, in 1958, was
known for the creativity and dynamism of Didi, Garrincha, and Pele,
but it also had complementary players such as Zito and the captain,
Bellini.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zito was probably more technical than Dunga, but he was
strong, too,'' Veloso said. ``Dunga is the Brazilian player of the
'90s, the type of player who is very necessary the way soccer is
now played. You need one or two like him in the midfield. He is
like Paul Ince with England. They are especially important for
their mentality and personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunga, 34, has announced he will retire from international
soccer after the World Cup. He was courted last year by the New
England Revolution, but has now signed a contract with Jubilo Iwata
in Japan through 2000. Major League Soccer and the Revolution
likely did not pursue Dunga this year because they consider him too
old, as did most Italian teams when he went to VfB Stuttgart in
Germany in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga was 22 when he arrived at Pisa and soon became a teammate
of Roberto Baggio at Fiorentina. He might have had a more
successful career in Italy had not Count Flavio Pontello, the
Fiorentina president, sold Baggio to Juventus. Then, Juventus also
tried to acquire Dunga, but the fans' revolt over the Baggio affair
made such a proposition not only impossible, but life-endangering.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorentina struggled without Baggio, and the directors proposed
that Dunga become captain, as well as management's representative
in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga refused, saying ``I am a player, not a spy.'' He was soon
gone. But Dunga left a strong impression, especially for his
intensity, illustrated by a confrontation with former teammate
Stefano Carobbi.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Milan sports daily La Gazzetta dello Sport
published a picture of a wild-eyed, long-haired Dunga grabbing
Carobbi's shirt during a 1989 game, the caption noting that Carobbi
appeared on the verge of tears.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga followers were not surprised when he made a similar
reprimand to Bebeto during Brazil's 3-0 first-round victory over
Morocco in Nantes. Then, Dunga had appeared to be overreacting
during an easy win, showing up a respected, even-tempered
34-year-old Bebeto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was exaggerating his actions,'' Veloso said. ``He
was very different when Brazil lost to Norway in the next game, and
his teammates called for him to take charge again. They know his
personality is necessary for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunga has recently been inspired by a comment by former Chicago
Bulls coach Phil Jackson, who noted that among Michael Jordan's
qualities is that he improves the performance of less prominent
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another example is Maradona in the 1986 World Cup,'' Dunga
said, ``when Argentina won without any famous names. Because a
champion must not content himself to receive from God the gift of
class; he must put that together with humility and intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   The multi-lingual Dunga has become a reluctant favorite of
interviewers at Brazil's training camp on the outskirts of Paris.
Though Dunga's tacit nature reflects his origins in the
traditionally industrial Porto Alegre region, he bonded easily with
the outgoing Romario, who was raised in the poverty of Rio de
Janeiro's favelas.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the start of the finals, Romario was dropped by
Zagallo and assistant coach Zico (who hired bodyguards for his
family in Rio after being threatened by Romario supporters),
leaving only Aldair, Bebeto, Dunga, and Taffarel as full-time
starters from the USA '94 championship team.
</P>
<P>
   Dunga disputed the decision, both privately and in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dunga is from the south of Brazil, so he has a European
background,'' Veloso said. ``His personality is not as simpatico as
people from other places in Brazil, but he is a very good person
with a lot of character, and he actually is very simpatico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Romario seem like opposites, but the differences made
them close. They were roommates on the national team and they
understand each other very well. Dunga tried to convince them to
keep Romario because he thought his experience and mentality were
very important to Brazil winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dunga is the leader of this team, the coach on the field.
Everything depends on Dunga. He is very motivated because this is
the last international tournament for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
