<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREY HEADED FOR BRUINS TRAINING CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The deadline came and went without the Bruins taking any action
to buy out the remaining two years of goaltender Jim Carey's
contract. Barring a trade, Carey is expected to be in Boston's
training camp this fall in order to fight for a job with No. 1
Byron Dafoe and backup Rob Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   It would have cost the Bruins $2.33 million to buy out the pact
that is due to expire at the end of the 1999-2000 season, which
would have saved them $2.67 million.
</P>
<P>
   President/general manager Harry Sinden and assistant GM Mike
O'Connell mulled their options as late as Wednesday morning before
deciding to retain Carey's services. Carey, obtained in a trade
from the Washington Capitals on March 1, 1997, along with center
Jason Allison and right wing Anson Carter, came into a tough
situation here during a season when the Bruins were on the way to
finishing dead last in the NHL standings.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, with new coach Pat Burns at the helm, Carey struggled
with illness and ineffectiveness (3-2-1, 2.90 goals &QL; 
against average in 10 appearances) before being placed on waivers.
He played with the AHL's Providence Bruins (2-7-1, 3.91 GAA) before
undergoing season-ending shoulder surgery in January. Carey said
recently that he is feeling very strong, the shoulder is 100
percent, and he is looking forward to getting back to the form that
won him the Vezina Trophy as the league's top goalie in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Bruins were hoping for when they made the
decision to hang on to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to three things really,'' said O'Connell. ``No.
1, we were not ready to give up on him yet. Then there were the
money issues and No. 3, there's an expansion draft again next year.
But if he can come back and regain the form that he had, then we'd
have the luxury (of goaltending depth) that a lot of teams don't
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Adam Oates is the only player in the deal still with
Washington. Rick Tocchet opted not to re-sign with the Capitals in
the summer of 1997, going to Phoenix instead, and goalie Bill
Ranford was traded to Tampa Bay at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' options with regard to Carey were few. He was coming
off a poor season, and this is a remarkable summer for top-flight
goaltenders who are unrestricted free agents. Mike Richter, said to
be seeking $7 million, is likely to leave the Rangers. John
Vanbiesbrouck, reportedly seeking more than $5 million a season,
likely won't be back with Florida, and Curtis Joseph, who is
reportedly asking for $6 million a year, is too pricey for
Edmonton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
