<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCEDES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mercedes plant busy renovating
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The summer shutdown at the Mercedes-Benz plant in
Vance, Ala., is hardly a time of inactivity. The German automaker
is expanding and overhauling the plant to boost capacity and
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler-Benz, parent of Mercedes-Benz, is spending $40 million
to add 100,000 square feet to the plant and to install painting and
welding robots. Although the robots will increase automation in
some jobs, about 100 employees will be hired to the two shifts per
day to produce more vehicles and help reduce overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The company wants to increase production of its popular M-Class
sport-utility vehicles to 80,000 units next year from 65,000 this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes estimates demand for the M-Class next year at more than
100,000 units. Spokesman Trevor C. Hale said buyers in some markets
must wait up to a year for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the most ergonomically unfriendly jobs and giving
them to a machine or an assist device vs. having people perform the
tasks,'' said Andreas Renschler, president and CEO of Mercedes-Benz
U.S. International. ``Our investment in plant expansion, new
equipment and additional jobs will help the line run more
efficiently, and offer some relief to our team members who have
been putting in extra hours to help meet the high demand for the
M-Class.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, construction crews are opening the walls between
previously built areas and the factory, installing robots and
arranging logistics bays. The bays are used to organize incoming
parts to meet the assembly lines' need for subsystems on a
just-in-time and in-sequence basis.
</P>
<P>
   The factory builds the V-6-powered ML320 sport-utility vehicle
for North American and overseas customers and the four-cylinder
ML230 for export to Europe. In July, the plant will begin building
the V-8-powered ML430.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
