<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CORRUPTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-JUDGE'S PLEA PROMPTS CONCERN IN TEXAS COUNTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ With a former state judge admitting that he once
bribed a prosecutor to fix the outcome of several drug cases, the
district attorney here said he advised his staff to consider hiring
lawyers as a sweeping federal investigation into corruption
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Garcia, a former state district judge in this border city,
pleaded guilty Tuesday to bribery as part of a deal that requires
him to tell federal prosecutors all he knows about the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not privy to what the federal government has,'' Webb
County District Attorney Joe Rubio said. ``I did tell everyone
yesterday that if they felt they had exposure (to criminal
charges), they needed to consult with an attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   At the federal courthouse in Victoria, Garcia admitted that
while working as a defense attorney, he paid at least $10,000 to an
unnamed assistant attorney in Rubio's office to fix the outcome of
several cases.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his plea-bargain deal, Garcia agreed to testify in
open court and before grand juries as a government witness.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents in late May raided Rubio's office as well as
several other locations, including the homes and residences of a
bail bondsman and a justice of the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Using a moving truck, agents carted more than 5,000 criminal
case files, checkbooks and calendars from Rubio's office.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the parties who have been questioned or searched in
the investigation questioned the tactics the government used to get
Garcia to accept a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to hear the judge agreed to make a deal with the
government,'' said Fausto Sosa, a former county prosecutor who is
representing one possible defendant in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought these allegations transpired. I don't know how
much pressure they put on him. It seems like a sweetheart deal,''
Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 64, faces up to 20 years in prison, but could get off
with as little as parole depending on how much he cooperates with
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The assistant district attorney with whom Garcia made a deal has
not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   A federal search warrant indicates authorities were especially
interested in the activities of Rubio and eight people who work in
his office, including investigators and assistant prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, no one had resigned, been fired or re-assigned
as a result of the probe, Rubio said. He said Garcia's admission
wasn't evidence of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But federal authorities have said the investigation continues
and court documents indicate the case involves not only informants
and witnesses, but secretly-recorded phone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Castaneda, a Laredo bail bondsman whose office and home
were searched by federal agents, said he believed Garcia was scared
he would die in prison if he didn't accept the plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is like the last of the Mohicans _ retired, in bad
health and feeling distressed,'' Castaneda said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's attorney, James Stafford, could not be reached for
comment Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
