<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GHO-CASEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN TO MAKE PGA DEBUT IN GREATER HARTFORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Casey Martin will make his PGA Tour debut in
Thurday's opening round of the Greater Hartford Open at the TPC at
River Highlands and will play in next week's Quad Cities Open. The
next decision he may have to make is whether to tee it up at the
CVS Charity Classic at Pleasant Valley July 23-26. ``If I don't
make a heap of money the next two weeks,'' said Martin Wednesday,
``chances are I will not.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin earned $34,043 when he finished tied for 23d at the US
Open at The Olympic Club two weeks ago, putting him at 176 on the
Tour money list. If he can earn as much as the 150th player last
year (Brian Claar, $121,273), he will be entitled to unlimited
exemptions the rest of the year. And if he finishes the year in the
Tour's 150 money leaders, he will earn an exemption to play on the
Tour next year.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was born with a circulation problem in his right
leg, went to court in Eugene, Ore., and was granted an injunction
to permit him to ride in a cart on the Nike Tour. He qualified in a
playoff to reach the US Open and he is exercising the first of his
sponsor's exemptions to play this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good finish at the US Open and feel I played
solidly,'' said Martin. ``I'm looking forward to playing this golf
course. I love it. It feel like it suits my game. It's pretty long,
and the fairways aren't really narrow. I'm not really worried about
proving anything, but I do want to do well. I know there are big
crowds and a lot of people will be watching. I'd love to play well
for a lot of reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin spent last week in Disneyland with his his wife,
daughter, and brother. Recognition came in droves. ``When I made
the US Open, they couldn't go,'' said Martin. ``There were a few of
the Disneyland characters who came up to me, and it was kind of an
awkward appearance. I met Tigger and Mary Poppins. Just pointing at
me, swinging a club and my brother said, `You know you're somebody
when the Disneyland characters recognize you.'''
</P>
<P>
   There is no avoiding the recognition, especially when you make
your Tour debut in a cart. ``I'd love to just curtail this and go
play golf,'' said Martin. ``I understand why it's going to happen.
I expect the media attention. Ideally, this will fade, and I'm sure
it will. I knew it would be a topic at some level, but I never
anticipated it would be such a big topic and it still is. It's
surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   There were negative comments from some of the game's biggest
names about his use of a cart. It hasn't carried over to the locker
room. ``Personally, I've had no problem,'' said Martin. ``It's been
great. I've been treated very well.'' Part of the reason Martin
accepted this sponsor's exemption instead of earlier ones is
Hartford Life is involved in the GHO and is one of Martin's
financial backers. ``I've said all along,'' he said, ``I would take
one or two (exemptions). I decided this is the best week for me. I
was just going to take one, but I figured on my way back to
California I might as well stop in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who has Klippel-Trenauney-Weber syndrome, feels like he
has been given a new life in the game because without a cart he
couldn't play competitive golf. ``I'm just grateful I'm riding,''
he said. ``It's always been a problem. I've had it since birth. I
was very close to stop playing because of my leg. It was getting
worse, but since I've been riding it's getting better. It's
uncomfortable in the humidity because of the sock I have to wear on
my leg. But I can't say there's any more pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin can acquire a PGA Tour card by finishing in the top 15 on
the Nike Tour, but he has slipped out of the list. Now it's crunch
time in these two weeks on the PGA Tour. ``I would have to play
extremely well the next two weeks,'' Martin said. ``I feel
confident if I play up to my ability I can play very well. I've
been dealing with this all year, and it's a challenge. If I finish
top 5 or top 10, I might consider (playing at Pleasant Valley).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
