<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OYSTERS-RECALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF SICK FROM TAINTED TEXAS OYSTERS APPROACHES U.S. RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Fla., La., Calif., Colo. and N. M.) 
(See optional trim) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ The number of people sickened by raw
Galveston Bay oysters is fast approaching a national record, with
health officials saying Wednesday that the total had hit 187.
</P>
<P>
   That number was expected to climb Thursday and possibly eclipse
the largest outbreak on record. Last year, 208 people fell ill and
one died in the Pacific Northwest after eating raw oysters tainted
by the bacterium Vibrio parahaemolyticus.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's total reflected an increase of 59 from the number of
cases that had been recorded through Tuesday in Texas and Florida,
said Kirk Wiles of the Texas Department of Health's seafood safety
division. People who eat raw oysters tainted with the bacterium
typically suffer diarrhea, abdominal cramps, nausea, fever,
vomiting and headache, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 151 cases in Texas and 36 in Florida,'' Wiles said.
``We expect the number to go higher. I know they're still following
up on additional (reports of) illnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Galveston Bay oyster wholesalers last week recalled suspect
oysters taken from seven of 43 beds where harvesting goes on this
time of year. On Tuesday, they launched a recall of oysters taken
since May 27 from all 43 beds.
</P>
<P>
   That move came after some of the reported illnesses were linked
to oysters taken from beds other than the first seven that were
known to have produced tainted oysters.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials urged people not to eat oysters from
Galveston Bay unless they are cooked thoroughly. There is little
risk from eating other seafood from the bay, they said, as long as
it is cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 187 cases of illness on record by Wednesday, 21 were
confirmed through examination of stool samples from the victims,
Wiles said.
</P>
<P>
   The other cases were judged to be associated with Galveston Bay
oysters by state health department epidemiologists who interview
those reporting the illnesses, Wiles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an epidemiological checklist of questions so that you
can qualify whose illness is associated with raw oysters and whose
isn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oyster wholesalers have recalled shipments from throughout
Texas, as well as from Florida, Louisiana, Colorado, New Mexico and
California.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oysters from the 43 Galveston Bay beds, and the water around
them, are being tested to try to determine why the outbreak
occurred. Until the test results are back, oystermen have
voluntarily ceased harvesting from Galveston Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Although many believe this year's early spate of hot weather and
long period of drought may have contributed to the outbreak by
increasing baywater temperatures and salinity, health officials are
not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   They note that Vibrio parahaemolyticus bacteria are constantly
present in bay waters and that heat and drought have not combined
in the past to taint oysters with sickening amounts of the germ.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People who have suffered symptoms within a day or two of eating
raw oysters have been asked to report the illness to state
officials by calling 1-888-883-9997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
