<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM BUOYS JAPANESE STOCKS AND CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: This story, eliminated earlier, is now shorted and
restored)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese stock market extended its rally Wednesday
for the sixth consecutive day, logging its third-largest single-day
gain this year, on expectations that the government's plan for
cleaning up the nation's bad loans would spur an economic revival.
</P>
<P>
   The yen also rose. It cost 138.28 yen to buy a dollar in Tokyo,
more expensive than the 139.16 per dollar in New York on Tuesday.
The yen rose further in New York on Wednesday to 138.07 to the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is expected to disclose Thursday a plan to tackle bad bank
loans by creating new banks that will take over the business of
failed institutions so that creditworthy borrowers would not be
left in the lurch if their main bank went under.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the proposal is by no means certain. But
investors have begun to raise their hopes that it might actually
begin to reduce large amounts of the nation's bad debt, which is
estimated to be around $600 billion. The benchmark Nikkei index of
225 issues rose to 16,362.89 Wednesday, up 532.62 points, or 3.36
percent, from Tuesday's close. The index has risen 1,300 points in
the last six days, with overall volumes surging to 850 million
shares, nearly twice the usual levels.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that the government also might cut income taxes by
nearly $30 billion also bolstered investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
