A6677 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHING-BARGE-TEX     07-01 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-BARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHING BARGE IS A PIECE OF THE PAST
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEATHERFORD, Texas _ Several times a week, 58-year-old Mills
Mann of Fort Worth slips away from his home before dawn to travel
30 miles toward Weatherford.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the Parker County town, he disappears off
Interstate 20 and drops down among the huge oaks surrounding Lake
Weatherford. By the time the sun comes up, he is intently watching
a red and white bobber do its dance on the moss-green waters at the
Lake Weatherford Marina.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bite good here,'' Mann said. ``Bass, catfish, sometimes a
few crappie. You can catch a lot of sun perch out here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The fishing barge is something of an anachronism in today's busy
recreational scene. Mann said he doesn't know why, but a fishing
dock, or barge, is a relic to which children and old people with
cane poles are relegated.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bother Mann one bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fish here just because I like to fish,'' he said. ``I've
fished at some of the lakes around Fort Worth, and they don't bite
so good. This is about the best lake around. Everybody is real
friendly; that's why I like to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he said, he brings friends. Often, he brings his
wife, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves it,'' he said, breaking into a laugh. ``She loves to
talk; she don't care who it is. She talks to people like she's
known them for 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that socialization that draws Mann, he conceded. You have
to like people, and enjoy spending time with them. You can't do
that alone in a fancy boat.
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly nothing fancy about Lake Weatherford Marina.
The bait and tackle shop is a single-story blue and white building
that looks as if it was built around the mid-1950s. It was.
</P>
<P>
   Fans circulate the summer heat inside, causing the foam minnow
buckets to do a constant jiggle on wires tied to the ceiling. There
are snacks at the counter, ice cream in the cooler. The shelves are
filled with necessities such as bobbers, packages of hooks and tubs
of Elvis ``D'' Catfish Bait, Liz's Best Catfish Bait, Ole Whiskers
Beef Blood Catfish Bait and Taylor Made Fish Dough for Carp.
</P>
<P>
   There are rope stringers and metal stringers. There are two
stacks of cane poles. And there are minnows. They are $1.25 a dozen
for crappie size, and 20 cents more a dozen if you want bass size.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Reynolds and Roy Walker have owned the marina for the past
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an excellent business,'' Reynolds said, sipping coffee
inside the bait shop. ``On weekends we are completely full; you
couldn't squeeze another person in the swimming area. There's a
zillion boats.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the bait shop, boat slips and ramp, the marina
has a small swimming beach.
</P>
<P>
   There is a small charge, usually $3, but if you get there before
the owners do, you deposit your money in the honor box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a pretty calm little lake compared to some of the other
lakes around Fort Worth,'' Reynolds said. ``We have people drive
all the way from Dallas to swim at our beach. It's a nice clean
beach.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a ``Thursday night workingman's fishing
tournament'' from 6 to 9:30 p.m. ``They pay $25 a team, and if we
have less than 15 boats, it's winner take all,'' Reynolds said.
``If we have more than that, we pay two places.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake Weatherford, by most standards, is a small lake, a place
where you go if you have a couple of hours to fish. If you have all
day, you go somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The boat slips at the marina are filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have a vacancy,'' Reynolds said. ``Even in the winter,
when people take their boats out of the water, we have fishermen
who rent the slips and use them as crappie holes.''
</P>
<P>
   The fishers drop bundles of Christmas trees down into the water
to draw the crappie. Some put tarps over their slips to provide
alluring shade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out one morning, about 6 a.m., and I thought I wasn't
going to find a place to park,'' Reynolds remembered. ``It was 8
degrees. It was so cold you couldn't feel your hands, but the
crappie were biting, and people were all over the docks filling up
their 5-gallon buckets with fish.''
</P>
<P>
   The crappie don't bite as well in the summer, but the sand bass
run and the catfish slink around in the deeper water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of kids out here,'' Mann said, nodding toward
16-year-old Bryan Stevens, who was fishing nearby, ``but there
needs to be a bunch more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said parents ought to bring their kids out and show
them how to fish. Spend time with them. Show them just one time
what it's like, and let them get the feel of it. The kids will love
it, and it will keep them out of a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-520&AMP;A     07-01 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S MANUFACTURERS ARE SLOWING PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Also see FED) 
 (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(ps) 
 &HT;    
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's manufacturers have slowed production to the lowest
rate of growth since 1995, the clearest impact so far of the Asian
crisis on the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown has become increasingly evident with each new
economic statistic in recent weeks. On Wednesday, the National
Association of Purchasing Management reported that manufacturing
activity weakened in June for a majority of the companies it
surveys each month. It was the first time in 22 months that a
majority of companies had reported weakening instead of
strengthening in their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing employment has fallen in recent months. And
industrial production has slowed sharply this year, to an annual
growth rate of less than 2 percent, down from 6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Production is slowing in large part because stockpiles of unsold
goods have surged and in part because companies are growing worried
that the economic boom cannot continue at its fervent pace of the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that make goods for sale abroad have retrenched the
most. Take the Jefferson Smurfit Corp. of St. Louis, which makes
cardboard for shipping boxes. It shut a big mill in Jacksonville,
Fla., Wednesday for 40 days because of slumping exports to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But companies that do business mostly in the United States are
feeling the pressure as well. The Goodman Equipment Corp. near
Chicago says its American customers are reducing orders for the
plastic molding machines and mining equipment it makes. ``They are
more nervous about the future, and more reluctant to expand,'' said
Calvin Campbell, the company's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The production slowdown may help to explain why the Federal
Reserve chose Wednesday, at its latest policy meeting, to leave
interest rates unchanged, even though labor shortages and robust
economic growth suggested that higher rates might be needed to
prevent inflation from taking off. Concern about Asia, on the other
hand, is pushing the Fed to keep rates steady, thus supporting
Asian currencies by making investors less likely to switch into
dollars from Japanese yen or Korean won.
</P>
<P>
   The bright spot in manufacturing, which represents 30 percent of
the nation's economy, comes from consumers. They are still big
buyers, and that is strengthening those manufacturers who serve
them. Rubbermaid Inc., for example, which makes toys and plastic
garbage cans with little competition from abroad, says its output
and sales are rising at the same rate as last year.
</P>
<P>
   The strong demand among American consumers holds out the hope
that the slowdown in manufacturing, which first showed itself early
this year, will be short-lived. If it were to continue, however,
the robust growth of the American economy in the last two years
would undoubtedly disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know which way manufacturing and the economy will
go,'' said William Dudley, director of domestic economic research
at Goldman Sachs. ``The issue is how strong is the shock from Asia
versus how strong is domestic demand. Our view is that domestic
demand will win out, but the contest is under way, and we do not
have a clear winner yet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The numbers of late have not been ambiguous. The manufacturing
index compiled by the National Association of Purchasing Managers
dropped below 50, to 49.6, in June. The index has been steadily
declining since last July, when it peaked at 57.5. The 27-day
strike at General Motors was only partly reflected in the latest
figure and may add to the drag on manufacturing for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Inventories surged 40 percent in the first quarter to more than
$100 billion as companies like Jefferson Smurfit found their
exports suddenly evaporating. Eastman Chemical Co., which makes the
chemical ingredients of plastics products and fibers, responded by
trimming a few percentage points off its production. ``We never
close a plant when demand is not there; what you do is shave back
production,'' said Ernest Deavenport, Eastman's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Nervousness about the future is also a significant constraint,
particularly in recent weeks. New orders have been coming more
slowly since spring, particularly for companies like Goodman, in
Bedford Hills, Ill., that make equipment and machinery for other
manufacturers, and the Hiwasse Co. in Jacksonville, Ark., which
supplies control panels for washing machines and other appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had gone on sales calls in February and customers were
urgent in their demand for quotes from me,'' said J. Richard
Derickson, Hiwasse's chief executive. ``And then in April the
requests for quotes just dramatically fell off and they are just
beginning to pick up now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannay Reels Inc. of Westerlo, N.Y., which makes metal reels for
industrial hoses and fuel trucks, has had a similar experience.
``Our production this year is matching last year, which means it
has slowed; last year production was up 7 percent,'' said Roger
Hannay, the chief executive. ``People are putting expansion on hold
for a while, until they see what happens to the economy and the
stock market, and in the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   The weaker production is hardly uniform. General Electric and
other appliance manufacturers say production is up for them, not
down, thanks to strong consumer demand. The Boeing Co., for all its
concern about a production decline next year because of a cutback
in sales to Asia, is producing flat out this year to meet a backlog
of orders. And the nation's auto companies report that from January
through May, auto and truck production equaled the 5.2 million
vehicles made in the first five months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that its inventories had gotten too large _ given the
potential impact of the Asian crisis, Republic Engineered Steels in
Massillon, Ohio, has been selling them off since early spring,
shaving production in the process. ``We felt we had to convert
those inventories into cash,'' said Harold Kelly, Republic's
executive vice president. ``We want to be more liquid.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcapacity is also hurting select businesses. Having closed 11
factories in January, Levi Strauss says its jeans production is now
in line with sales. ``We were seeing that our market strategy could
not be based on volume,'' said Linda Butler, a Levi Strauss
spokeswoman. ``We had to emphasize innovative products, made in
smaller quantities,''
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Chemical is similarly struggling with overcapacity. The
company had exported from American plants over the last several
years while new facilities were under construction in Malaysia,
Argentina, Spain and Holland. ``Now that they are on line, we are
exporting less,'' Mr. Deavenport said. The cutback has come just as
the demand in Asia collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he said, chemical products going from Europe to Asia
``can't find a home there and they land in the United States,'' Mr.
Deavenport added. ``And an American customer says, `I am going to
buy them at a lower price,' and we lose the sale. That is happening
all the time now.''
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown in manufacturing production is helping to feed some
forecasts that economic growth in the summer and fall will slow to
an annual rate of less than 3 percent, from a very strong 5.4
percent from January through March. Even now, despite the surge in
prosperity over the past two years, annual economic growth has
averaged only 2.3 percent in the 1990's _ the slowest growth rate
of any decade since World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
