<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-STARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves top majors with six All-Star selections
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Atlanta Braves organization won't be feeling any
slights Tuesday during the 1998 All-Star Game at Coors Field in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta learned Wednesday that it will be the best-represented
team at the game with six players. Pitchers Greg Maddux and Tom
Glavine, first baseman Andres Galarraga and catcher Javier Lopez
will join shortstop Walt Weiss and third baseman Chipper Jones, who
were voted in as starters by the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``They can't blame me
now for putting all my own guys on (the team).''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux might start the game for the National League. Weiss will
be making his first All-Star appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real honor to make the team,'' Maddux said. ``It'd be
more of an honor to start it.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, who have the best record in baseball,
don't have any starters, but they will have five players in the
game: pitcher David Wells, shortstop Derek Jeter, third baseman
Scott Brosius and outfielders Bernie Williams and Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres and Cleveland Indians also will send five
players each.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most glaring omission was Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood.
Wood's numbers are solid (7-3, 3.38 ERA), and he has become one of
the best stories in baseball this season and tied a major-league
record for strikeouts in a game with 20. Oakland outfielder Ben
Grieve will be the only rookie in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Managers Jim Leyland of Florida and Mike Hargrove of Cleveland
picked the reserves and pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Edgar Renteria was the only player selected from
Leyland's defending World Series champion Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But Leyland selected four players from the championship team who
now will represent other clubs _ San Diego's Kevin Brown, Houston's
Moises Alou, Robb Nen of the Giants and Gary Sheffield of the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released by the Associated Press, several
of the Braves will reap solid financial contract bonuses for being
named to the team. Galarraga, Jones and Weiss will receive $50,000,
and Lopez will earn $25,000. Glavine and Maddux had no bonus money
in their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves sent an all-time high of seven players in the 1996
game and had six last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
