<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENOPEN-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's Open Notebook
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. -- Her length and strength should make her a prime
contender this week. Surely, Laura Davies is long enough to hit
irons into tight landing areas. Obviously, she's strong enough to
leave the rough at Blackwolf Run if a drive should manages to go
off line.
</P>
<P>
   It's Davies' attitude that needs to be improved entering today's
first round of the U.S. Women's Open. Four missed cuts in her last
five events have brought out the cynic in Davies' personality. On
May 28 at Rochester, she opened with an 82. She's been through more
putters than golf shirts. And when things are going poorly, nobody
is harder on Laura Davies than Laura Davies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the year has gone, I'm expecting two rounds and (to)
be on my way back to London Saturday morning,'' Davies said
Wednesday. ``I've missed six cuts this year. I'm expecting
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-longest course ever used for a U.S. Women's Open
(6,412), with five par 4s over 400 yards and several playing into
the wind, might cause Davies to play anywhere from four to eight
drivers, depending on the wind and her round situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rough is there, don't get me wrong,'' she said. ``If you
miss the fairway badly enough, you're in real trouble _ if you find
your ball. That one I missed on 16 (par, 540 yards), I nearly
stepped on to find it. (Many of) the holes aren't long enough to
warrant hitting the driver and risking it.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem, really. Davis hits her 3-iron 220 to 250 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez gets red-carpet treatment
</P>
<P>
   Albany's Nancy Lopez is not seeing Blackwolf Run for the first
time this week. She and husband Ray Knight were special guests of
owner Herbert Kohler last month, flying up from Albany, Ga., on his
private jet. They played 36 holes on the tournament course.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had sent a message through one of the ladies that if I ever
wanted to come here, he would send a plane to pick us up, so we can
get back home to see our kids,'' Lopez said. ``So, it worked out
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Appreciative of Kohler's generosity, she said, ``I love flushing
toilets this week. I mean, it is great.''
</P>
<P>
   The scouting trip to Blackwolf Run was not a total freebie.
Lopez said she brought only a dozen golf balls and by the first day
Ray had lost six by himself. With only three each for the second
day, Lopez had to make a rare purchase of a dozen balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are expensive,'' she said. ``I hadn't bought golf balls
in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb: Sorenstam should be favored
</P>
<P>
   Australia's Karrie Webb downplays the rivalry she has with
Annika Sorenstam of Sweden, but she admits, ``She is No. 1 in the
world. She deserves to be the favorite.'' . . . Designer Pete Dye
placed water on Blackwolf Run's three finishing holes. The 421-yard
18th has a flooded waste bunker on the left side and the Sheboygan
River as the hazard near the green. Fittingly, it's called the
``Dyehard'' hole. . . . Tammie Green, who is three-months pregnant
and recently married, found out she was having a baby while in
Atlanta in April during the Chick-fil-A Charity Championship that
she would be having a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
