<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-ANDVERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Anchor Man''
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Farrar
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Nelson Publishers, $19.99
</P>
<P>
   When reading ``Anchor Man,'' keep in mind the line from that old
commercial: ``Thanks; I needed that.'' By the end of Steve Farrar's
latest book, you'll probably feel as if you've been slapped _ at
least once.
</P>
<P>
   ``God doesn't expect us just to take care of our families
today,'' the Dallas Theological Seminary graduate tells his fellow
fathers. ``''He wants your leadership to be so noble that it will
carry your family for at least a solid century. Maybe two.'' And
the way to do that, according to this straight-speaking writer, is
to anchor yourself and your family in biblical principles so
thoroughly that your children and grandchildren and the generations
beyond will continue to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The North Texas author's style is blunt, his prescription basic:
Don't betray your spouse; give your children your time; discipline
them when they need it; remember that they will copy you; tell them
about what God has done for you.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar unabashedly argues for male leadership in the family, but
he has no patience with tyranny or several other masculine vices.
Never mind the military; for Farrar, being a godly father is the
toughest job you'll ever love.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion _ Live Worship''
</P>
<P>
   From the 268 Generation
</P>
<P>
   Star Song Records
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best praise and worship music being recorded these
days is aimed at the younger set.
</P>
<P>
   It is present in this recording, which was done live in January
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was Passion '98, the second such conference for
college students in the state capital. The first, in 1997,
attracted 2,000 people. This year, 5,000 made the pilgrimage to
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the conference is to encourage freedom of worship
and intimacy with God. The mission statement comes from Isaiah
26:8: ``Yes, Lord, walking in the way of your truth, we wait
eagerly for you, for your name and your renown are the desire of
our souls.''
</P>
<P>
   The music, performed by the conference music team, reflects the
mission statement nicely. These are powerful, intimate praise songs
set to a contemporary beat. ``Knocking on the Door of Heaven'' and
``Did You Feel the Mountains Tremble'' could become anthems for
this generation of Christians.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps even some older folks. Passion should appeal to the
target audience, but there is also a lot there for those of us who
are several years removed from college.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
