<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 5,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-LAWN (Undated) _ ``The American Lawn: Surface of
Everyday Life,'' a corker of a show at the Canadian Center for
Architecture in Montreal (through Sept. 27), begins with a ride on
a lawn sprinkler. Back and forth the camera swings, scanning the
archetypal patch of grass, oscillating between peripheral glimpses
of equally iconic neighbors on either side: the no-nonsense lady
trimming her hedge to clipped perfection, the cool kids hanging out
by the garage. In the background, water hisses. The video is
projected onto the floor, and you hesitate to step on it. Your
shadow might block the projection. Thus the show stylishly connects
two kinds of transgression: one associated with land, the other
with museums. Keep Off. Don't Touch. By Herbert Muschamp. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GESHER-THEATER (Tel Aviv, Israel) _ Making theater in Israel
would seem a daunting task, what with a history more intense than
any drama, a potpourri of cultures that have resisted melding and a
life forever mired in crisis. Yet these are the very ingredients
that Yevgeny Arye has conjured to propel his Gesher Theater to a
predominant position in Israel in less than seven years, a troupe
that has received raves both inside the country and beyond. By
Serge Schemann. (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Theater Reviews of ``Side Man''; ``You
Never Can Tell'' and ``Love's Fire.'' By Vincent Canby. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Brief reviews of films and their
suitability for children. This week: ``Dr. Dolittle``;
``Armageddon'' and ``Gone With the Wind.'' (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   WILL-PATTON-FILM (Undated) _ For Will Patton, it's the end of
the world. Again. In the course of some 30 films, the actor has
endured post-apocalyptic mail carriers, squishy parasites from
outer space and the wrath of God, so this weekend's scourge _ an
asteroid the size of Texas, headed straight for Earth _ should be
no trouble. Patton is appearing in ``Armageddon,'' which stars
Bruce Willis and is the summer's second doomsday adventure movie.
By Justine Elias. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HILDEGARD-MUSIC (Undated) _ We should all be as lively and
robust in our 900th year as Hildegard of Bingen. Unless you've been
dwelling under a rock, the name of this 12th-century German abbess
should at least ring a bell by now. Though never canonized,
Hildegard has achieved an eccentric sort of sainthood, having been
adopted as an icon by partisans of such renegade causes as Creation
Spirituality and feminism. By Cori Ellison. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONIE-FANTASTIQUE (New York) _ Basil Twist's underwater
puppetry, currently at work in the Here theater complex in
Manhattan. Twist's exercise, called simply ``Symphonie
Fantastique,'' manipulates objects and light within a 500-gallon
tank of water, one side of which, 30 by 40 inches, is visible to an
audience of about 100. ``Symphonie,'' performed to an old
Philadelphia Orchestra recording led by Eugene Ormandy, has its
halting moments and flashes of extraordinary beauty. It plays until
July 26. By Bernard Holland. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-ALBUMS (Undated) _ On too many internationally released
albums by African stars, guest vocalists are enlisted to break the
language barrier; American or European producers tweak the rhythms
to sound more like funk or reggae or whatever else they think will
reach the unconverted. It sounds as if the international labels
that sought out African bands went on to second-guess themselves,
deciding that their African talent may know what plays to the folks
at home but needs help overseas. By Jon Pareles. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DUTCH-ART (Washington) _ Dutch artists pursued subjects among
their immediate surroundings, painting Dutch men and women, their
everyday lives and the Dutch landscape. They gave genre painting
its first definition and painted so many depictions of objects that
the term ``stilleven'' _ still life _ was coined. Perhaps the most
vivid reflection of this worldliness _ this inclusive embrace of
knowledge, experience and beauty _ was the kunstkamer, or art
cabinet, the often encyclopedic arrays of art, artifacts and
natural specimens assembled by prosperous Dutch or Flemish
burghers. So argues ``A Collector's Cabinet,'' a pocket-size show
at the National Gallery of Art. By Roberta Smith. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-FAMILY-TIES (Undated) _ Considering the general flood of
television shows, it's startling to realize that at the height of
its popularity in the 1980s, ``Family Ties'' ranked as one of the
most-watched shows not just of the moment but in the history of
television. Watching four episodes just released on videocassette
by Columbia House, one might wonder why but there is no doubt how
well a top sitcom can serve its era before passing on. By Peter M.
Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WENTWORTH-WOODHOUSE-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ What is a country-house
auction without the house? The answer: a mirage of marketing. That
is the case with the sale on Wednesday at Christie's in London
dedicated to Wentworth Woodhouse in Yorkshire, the biggest house in
Britain. By Mitchell Owens. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ITALY (Undated) _ Seeking out Deruta pottery at its
source, and finding modern twists on a centuries-old tradition. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VIETNAM (Undated) _ Vietname offers hotel bargains as
tourism dwindles. By Philip Shenon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS (Undated) _ Hot travel deals. By Janet Piorko.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Summer travel road warnings. By
Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ European beaches get yearly report
