<P>
   CLINTON-HONG-KONG (Shanghai, China) _ When he visits Hong Kong
Thursday, President Clinton will convey what his aides hope will be
a calming message about Asia's economic turmoil. The chief
executive caps his nine-day tour of China with a 29-hour visit to
the former British colony that reverted to Chinese control a year
ago. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Guilin, China) _ President Clinton plays
enviro-tourist after lecturing Chinese business executives about
the toll that economic development can take on natural wonders. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CHINA (Shanghai, China) _ In a country where sons are
prized and daughters neglected, Hillary Rodham Clinton makes her
case on the need to value women, to educate them, to provide legal
rights, to stop violence and abuse in their homes, and to allow
them the freedom to plan their own families, a quiet reference to
forced abortions. By NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ENTOURAGE (Shanghai, China) _ We take a look at the
1,000 or so people traveling with President Clinton on his trip to
China. About two-thirds of them are government workers and family
members. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-REALITY (Geneva) _ Reality is sobering the 2-year-old AIDS
drug treatment revolution that has saved thousands of lives in
Europe and the United States. According to health experts, no more
than 50 percent of AIDS patients can reduce the human
immunodeficiency virus in their blood to undetectable levels. By
RUTH SoRELLE. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA-MARITAL (Paris) _ French husbands are abandoning the
once-accepted institution known here as the ``five-to-seven,''
referring to the early evening hours they spent with their
mistresses before returning home for dinner with their families. A
lack of time and money has gradually obliterated the practice, and
women no longer accept it. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ARCHAEOLOGY (Jerusalem) _ Dozens of angry archaeologists
demonstrate over reports that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
promised an ultra-Orthodox party effective control over the
country's excavations. Archaeology has been at the center of debate
in Israel for years with the ultra-Orthodox vehemently opposed to
excavations in which they believe Jewish graves have been found. By
DEBORAH HORAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FIRES (Mexico City) _ Mexican officials say the rainy
