<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6705 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-ELDERLY-750(     07-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-ELDERLY-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASINO GAMBLING A FAVORITE PASTIME FOR OLDER AND ELDERLY
AMERICANS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BRETT PULLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ For Milford Hartz, the adrenaline started
to flow right about the time the teal-colored deluxe motor coach
bus pulled into the parking lot in front of the Wal-Mart store. It
was 8:30 a.m. and the bus was soon loaded with more than 30 elderly
adults, most of whom had spent a lifetime of early morning hours
toiling on the nearby farms and in factories.
</P>
<P>
   But on this recent morning here, 90 miles east on the
Mississippi River, the Lady Luck riverboat casino was beckoning
like a fountain of youth. For the retirees, like scores of others
making similar pilgrimages each day around the country, the casino
offered free transportation, free food, free drinks, an exciting
place where older people are welcomed and respected, and the chance
to soothe any pains of old age with the magic elixir of instant
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get as old as I am, all your friends are gone and it
is not easy to make new ones, especially in a small town'' said
Hartz, an 87-year-old retired farmer. He goes to the casinos
``mainly to get out and be with other people, he said. : But Hartz
conceded: ``There is a little excitement to it. There's always the
hope you might win a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambling has always been an attraction for the elderly. But now,
with hundreds of casinos scattered throughout 26 states, and a
growing population of elderly people looking for places to
socialize, find companionship and participate in something lively
and new, casino gambling has become a favorite pastime for older
Americans and the elderly and an important source of income for
casinos. Each day, thousands take day trips to gambling
establishments. Like electrified cocoons, the casinos swaddle them
for five to six hours, stimulating them with bright lights and
bountiful buffet food, then sending them home, usually with a
little less of their savings.
</P>
<P>
   In Las Vegas, for example, more than 3 of every 10 visitors are
over the age of 60, according to the Las Vegas Convention and
Visitors Bureau. In Illinois, a recent survey found that 40 percent
of gamblers who visit that state's 12 riverboat casinos are over
the age of 55; 30 percent are retired.
</P>
<P>
   A survey conducted at centers for the elderly and at retirement
homes in the region around Council Bluffs, Iowa, where there are
three riverboat casinos, asked those surveyed to rank their
favorite activities. Based on a 62 percent response, the survey
found that bingo, which is often offered at local senior centers,
ranked first. Casinos were second, ahead of museums, shopping, the
theater, sporting events and church activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Depression-era cohort,'' said Dennis McNeilly, a
clinical psychologist in Omaha who is also an assistant professor
at Creighton University's medical school. ``They grew up doing
without, self-sacrificing, putting their families needs before
their own, and then suddenly they're given the opportunity of
getting something for nothing.'' At the casino, McNeilly said,
``everyone is treated in a receptive manner.'' Aging Americans, who
live ``in a society that isolates and marginalizes older adults,
become a part of the mainstream'' in a casino, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The casino industry is doing its part to encourage the fervor.
While they might not be high rollers, older gamblers _ who almost
fill the casinos on weekdays _ provide a healthy share of the
industry's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   To help keep them coming, the casinos pay tour companies to
organize trips for the elderly and to deliver busloads of them.
Aging entertainers whose stars have faded still perform inside
casino showrooms. And many of the amenities and promotions are
designed, it seems, with older gamblers in mind.
</P>
<P>
   On the bathroom walls of the Lady Luck, for example, there is a
special container for insulin needles. And at the Bluffs Run Casino
in Council Bluffs, gamblers who use a ``Player's Club'' card _
which like other frequent customer cards offers awards to loyal
cardholders _ receive 50 percent off of their prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   For older people who have lost spouses and friends and are
living off of limited resources, the lure of the casino can be very
strong. Madonna Gilroy, a 75-year-old resident of Lost Nation,
Iowa, whose husband died in January, plans to join her friends soon
on one of the bus trips that depart from her church. ``The boat has
quite an enticement,'' said Ms. Gilroy, who lives 40 miles from the
Mississippi River casinos.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Gilroy's daughter, Kathy Gilroy, thinks it's a terrible
idea. ``Here's my mother getting $66 dollars a month from Social
Security, and $300 from my dad's pension, and she wants to go on a
gambling junket,'' said Kathy Gilroy. Kathy Gilroy said she had
become actively opposed to gambling because people in her small
hometown and across the country had been hurt by the growth of
gambling. Despite her daughter's objections, the elder Mrs. Gilroy
was determined. ``I'm trying to spread my wings a little and take
in some things,'' she insisted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Casino gambling has certainly spread its wings in this state
since it was legalized in 1989. There are nine riverboat casinos,
three land-based slot machine parlors at racetracks, and three
Indian reservation casinos. At one of the state's slot machine
parlors, Prairie Meadows, which is just outside Des Moines, daily
gross slot profits are $330,000, far more than the $126,000 that
was anticipated when the casino opened three years ago. ``We still
can't believe it,'' said Steve Berry, the casino's spokeman. ``The
largest group of folks here,'' he noted, ``are 55 to 65.''
</P>
<P>
   While riding on the bus that was headed for the Lady Luck
casino, Ed Schlotterbeck, a 73-year-old retiree, talked about how
his four sisters, all residents of Iowa, visit the casinos
frequently. ``Hell, they go at least once a week,'' he said.
Schlotterbeck, who retired eight years ago after 40 years of
working for a heavy equipment manufacturer in Cedar Rapids, said he
marveled at all of the money being spent at the state's casinos.
``Where's people getting the money?'' he asked. ``I didn't think
these old farmers had that much money.''
</P>
<P>
   The closer the bus got to the Lady Luck, it seemed, the more
Schlotterbeck's leg nervously shook. He usually brings about $200
for gambling. Sometimes he wins, sometimes he does not. His wife
never comes along because she thinks his trips to the casinos are
``the dumbest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the isle, 74-year-old Dee Porter, a widow three times, is
looking for more than a jackpot at the casino. ``I'm single and I'm
looking for a good man,'' she said. Ms. Porter last visited a
casino four days earlier with her daughter, who hit a slot machine
for $6,000, ``but she kept putting the money back in,'' Ms. Porter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Joann Wadsworth, a casino employee, greeted the bus and reminded
the occupants to use their players' cards. The cards are inserted
into slot machines by gamblers and they track all of their play,
allowing for frequent player rewards, ranging from a deck of cards
to a casino logo jacket. More importantly, the player's cards
provide the casino with valuable marketing information about its
customers and their gambling activity.
</P>
<P>
   As they departed the bus, Ms. Wadsworth handed the passengers a
coupon for a free buffet meal and a complimentary silver dollar to
drop into the slot machines. One couple, Shirley Danford and Bob
Marsden, are reminded by the tour operator that this is their fifth
trip, and therefore on the next trip they will receive two free
silver dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Danford and Marsden met over 50 years ago at a dance. They
both married other people and raised families, but after their
spouses died, they began dating two years ago. They visit casinos
on weekdays and go ballroom dancing on Sundays. ``I keep him
busy,'' Ms. Danford said. ``We have a good time.'' They have smiled
and giggled throughout the entire ride and refused to give their
ages. ``We're somewhere between 69 and 80,'' Marsden said.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them have brought $15 dollars each to play slot
machines. ``They're not going to get rich off us,'' Marsden said.
</P>
<P>
   One hour after boarding the boat, Dorothy Hunter sat on a stool
in front of a ``Double Dollars'' slot machine, with the till loaded
with dozens of silver dollars she had just won. Ms. Hunter, a
76-year-old retired secretary, was at the casino for the first time
since undergoing triple-bypass heart surgery in April. ``I feel 10
to 20 years younger,'' she said, as she clutched a handful of the
silver dollars in her thick, strong hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people come here, spend a few dollars, they get a
nice meal and they have a nice afternoon,'' Ms. Hunter said. ``But
me, I like the machines. It's such a nice high when you win
something. A little excitement in our mundane lives.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After nearly two hours on board, Schlotterbeck was walking
around the boat looking a bit frazzled. ``I can't hit anything,''
he muttered.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly four hours on the boat and a total loss of $10,
Hartz quit playing the slot machines and was standing around
watching blackjack players and waiting to soon board the bus to
head home. ``I don't know how to play these card games,'' he said.
``My folks, when we were growing up, they didn't want us to have
anything to do with cards. Money was hard to come by and those
folks knew how to hold onto it.''
</P>
<P>
   When they climbed back on the bus at 3 p.m., if anyone had won,
they did not mention it.
</P>
<P>
   Schlotterbeck, whose sisters love to gamble and whose wife calls
it dumb, lost $90, he said. ``They say `Hey, it's entertainment,'
'' Schlotterbeck parroted. ``Well it ain't entertainment when you
lose your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Porterfound neither a husband nor a jackpot, but she was as
frisky going back as she was coming. ``I had a good time, but I
didn't win,'' she said. During the ride back to Cedar Rapids, when
one of Ms. Porter's friends blurted out Ms. Porter's age _ which is
74 - she threatened, ``Hey, you want a free for all here?''
</P>
<P>
   Marsden and Ms. Danford, the giddy couple, lost $13 dollars
each. ``I'm busted,'' Marsden said. ``We're the last of the big
spenders,'' Ms. Danford added with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
