<SLUG> BC-IRAN-KHATAMI-210&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S PRESIDENT LIKES U.S. TONE BUT SAYS ACTIONS SPEAK LOUDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ President Mohammad Khatami lauded the Clinton
administration Wednesday for softening its tone toward his country
but added that a concrete change in U.S. policy toward Iran was
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, Khatami had made no public comment on a speech
by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in June in which she
called on Iran to help create a ``road map'' to normal relations or
on the conciliatory words by President Clinton that followed.
</P>
<P>
   But in a brief question-and-answer session with reporters after
a meeting with Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi, Khatami said:
``We believe there is change in their tone, but we're always
looking for action. Honesty lies in action, not words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this change in tone is a gesture of better
understanding by American politicians of the status of the Islamic
Republic, the Iranian nation and the global situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Khatami did not break new ground with his comments calling on
the United States to make a specific policy gesture. Other Iranian
officials, including Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi, have already
articulated that view. But the absence of any direct criticism of
the United States or any concrete demand by Khatami reflects a
softer tone on the Iranian side.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Khatami seemed unaccustomed to the Western practice of a ``press
availability'' after an official meeting, at which officials make a
few comments, photographers shoot pictures and reporters fire off a
few questions. But Prodi, who was traveling with a large press
corps, was on a high-profile mission, and it was not surprising
that the two emerged from their hourlong meeting at the Pink Palace
in the presidential compound to greet the media.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami asked Prodi in English whether he wanted to go first.
Prodi replied in English: ``I don't know. Which is your habit? For
me it's OK''
</P>
<P>
   While reporters politely waited, expecting the officials to make
opening statements, Khatami said in Persian: ``Do they intend to
ask questions or not? Or do they want to postpone this?''
</P>
<P>
   After two questions, Khatami ended the brief encounter.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by Prodi, one of the highest-ranking European
officials to visit Iran since its 1979 revolution, was touted by
both the Italian and the Iranian sides as a major political event.
</P>
<P>
   For the Italians, the visit put Prodi in the vanguard of those
Europeans who want to forge close ties _ particularly economic ties
_ with Iran and are bargaining that Khatami can deliver on his
promise to bring about the rule of law and liberalize the country.
</P>
<P>
   But plummeting oil prices have deeply affected Iran's already
damaged economy, and Tehran is not in a position to sign ambitious
financial and industrial contracts.
</P>
<P>
   For the Iranians, the visit helps rehabilitate their global
image. The European Union countries briefly withdrew their
ambassadors from Iran after the verdict by a German court last year
that implicated the country's leadership in a terrorist bombing in
Berlin six years ago. Recently, the Europeans have agreed
informally to allow their foreign ministers to visit Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But Prodi's visit ups the ante, and officials from a number of
European countries were not at all happy that he had decided to
make the trip without consulting them.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, Prodi called his trip important ``not only for
Italy but also for Europe'' and said it would ``open a new chapter
in relations.''
</P>
<P>
   In line with Khatami's mantra that there must be a ``dialogue
among civilizations,'' Prodi received an honorary doctoral degree
from Tehran University and attended the opening of an exhibition at
Tehran's Museum of Contemporary Art of graphic works on Islam by
Italian artists.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the official Iranian press agency reported that Khatami,
in his meeting with Prodi, said, ``Dialogue between civilizations
requires Iran as the cradle of Islamic civilization and Italy as
the parent of Western civilization to have exemplary and excellent
relations with each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
