<SLUG> BC-BELL-PAYPHONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC PAY-PHONE CALL TO COST 35 CENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The days of the one-coin phone call are over.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. said Wednesday it is hiking the cost of a
local call at its pay telephones in Massachusetts to 35 cents from
25 cents. The increase, which is being phased in starting Thursday,
follows closely on the heels of a hike to 25 cents in April 1997.
Before that, the cost of a pay phone call had been a dime since
1953.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bell Atlantic, which owns and operates more than 45,000 pay
phones in the state, says it needs to charge an additional 10 cents
because it faces more competitive pressure stemming from the
Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic ``must charge competitive prices to the users of
our pay phones,'' said Lorraine Chickering, president-Bell Atlantic
Public Communicatoins. ``The competitive price that has emerged
nationwide is 35 cents for a local call.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bell Atlantic acknowledged that its pay phone business
has been hurt by the growing use of cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates were incensed at the price hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rate hike to 35 cents is really wrong,'' said Robert
Sargent, legislative director for the Massachusetts Public Interest
Research Group. ``This is another example of why the public
distrusts utilities and phone companies when they say all this
competition is a win-win situation. Instead of the promise that
prices would go down, they go up'' under deregulation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others pointed out the impact on poor people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The pay phone is a public necessity for that group and the
price increase is unconscionable,'' said Jerrold Oppenheim, an
attorney at the National Consumer Law Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pay phone rates in Massachusetts have been among the lowest
nationwide for years. Until Wednesday, Massachusetts was among only
seven states where a pay phone call cost 25 cents. The rest of the
nation and the District of Columbia have been at 35 cents.
Massachusetts was among the last states where the cost was boosted
to 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic already had raised its rate to 35 cents in
Washington and the 10 other East Coast states it serves. After the
hike in Massachusetts, New York and Rhode Island will be the only
other states Bell Atlantic serves that are still at 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheim, the consumer advocate, said that Bell Atlantic has
indicated in regulatory filings that it costs the company as much
as 17 cents in transmission and other expenses for a single call.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 telecommunications law, designed to spur competition in
the regional Bells' local telephone markets, also included
requirements that standard service to homes and businesses would
not subsidize the pay phone business. That subsidy had kept pay
phone calls relatively cheap. Now, Bell Atlantic's pay phone
operations must become an independent profit center.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bell Atlantic has had competitors in the pay phone
business for years, the elimination of the subsidy also has put it
in more direct competition with challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Morever, since the law went into effect, Bell Atlantic has faced
more competition from other pay phone operators in securing
locations for pay phones. Paul Francischeti, vice president of
marketing and planning at Bell Atlantic Public Communications, said
the rent, or commissions, the company pays to put its phones in
hotels, airports, shopping arcades and other locations has risen
substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic also has faced growing pressure from cellular
technology. The volume of pay phone calls generally has dropped due
to a boom in cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past 18 months, we have started to see a shift to where
cellular and wireless are now eating into pay phone usage,'' said
Francischeti. But he noted that wireless phones are merely ``
stealing growth from pay phones'' rather than ``taking pay phone
usage away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
