<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM'S JUNE SALES SOARED, BUT STRIKE-PLAGUED JULY LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. said Wednesday that June car and
truck sales were the highest for any month in nine years but that
July sales would plummet because of two strikes that have shut down
most of the automaker's North American assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Zarrella, vice president in charge of GM's North American
Vehicle Sales, Service and Marketing Group, said at a news
conference Wednesday that sales would drop 30 percent to 40 percent
this month compared with sales from the month a year earlier
because of the strikes by the United Automobile Workers.
</P>
<P>
   That would push GM's market share to a record low of 25 percent
and put GM behind Ford Motor Co. as the largest volume vehicle
manufacturer in the United States. Already, analysts say the
strikes at two plants in Flint, Mich., have cost GM $1.18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In June, GM sold 492,937 cars and trucks, including heavy
trucks, a 24 percent increase compared with sales in the month a
year earlier. It was GM's best month since May 1989 and its fourth
consecutive month of year-over-year increase. Though total industry
sales in June will not be available until Ford reports its sales
Monday, Zarrella predicted GM's market share would be between 31.5
percent and 33 percent for June.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler Corp., which also reported June figures Wednesday, said
it had a 10 percent increase in sales compared with those in June
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong June sales report for GM, the strikes, which
have closed 26 of the company's 29 North American assembly plants,
have already diminished GM's sales by preventing shipment of
vehicles to daily rental car fleets, which typically represent
about 20 percent of the automaker's sales.
</P>
<P>
   GM was unable to fill an order for 15,000 fleet cars in June and
will be unable to fill any fleet orders in July, usually the
biggest month of the year for fleet sales, Zarrella said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, GM will be unable to build special-order vehicles
for customers, which typically account for 10 percent of sales, and
sales to employees, which have been running as high as 5 percent of
total sales, will most likely plunge.
</P>
<P>
   If the strike lingers beyond mid-July, the consequences will be
more dire and permanent as customers buy cars and trucks from
rivals instead of waiting for the strike to end, Zarrella
predicted. ``If we can't supply it, we're going to lose customers _
21,000 customers we're likely to lose every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree with Zarrella that those customers could be lost
forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition will take as much advantage of the situation
as it can,'' said Joseph Phillippi, an auto analyst with Lehman
Brothers in New York. ``That's not just Ford and Chrysler but also
imports _ every seller from Hyundai to Mercedes-Benz. And the
damage may be lasting.''
</P>
<P>
   GM's inventory of vehicles is already dwindling. The company
entered June with 1.1 million cars and trucks in dealer inventory;
that number dropped to 850,000 by the end of the month, enough to
last through July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough retail inventory to allow our dealers to keep
the sales momentum going in July,'' Zarrella said. ``Consumers can
still go into GM dealerships, see plenty of variety and still get
great value despite the fact that we have a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Total U.S. car and truck sales in June are coming in nearly as
strong as sales in May. The seasonally adjusted annual selling rate
for light vehicles reached 16.3 million cars and trucks in May, the
best month since September 1986, and was on track to be just as
high in June, auto executives and analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler set a new monthly sales record, selling 252,485 cars
and trucks, a 10 percent increase compared with sales in the month
a year earlier and breaking the record set in May, when Chrysler
surpassed the quarter million mark for the first time in a single
month.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota sales totaled 117,043 cars and trucks, up 17 percent, a
new June record. Likewise, Honda sales set a June record, with
88,928 vehicles sold, an increase of 8 percent from the month a
year earlier. Mercedes-Benz sales were up 82 percent from June
1997, at 15,134 vehicles. Also reporting higher June sales were
Mitsubishi, Subaru, Volvo and Land Rover. Saab and Hyundai sales
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the strikes against GM, analysts predicted the
surge of the last two months would ease somewhat in July. Strong
sales in May and June were buoyed by attractive incentive programs,
some of which will be discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   GM has already announced that it will not renew its Loyalty
First program, which provided owners of GM vehicles with
certificates of $500 to $1,000 to use toward the purchase of
another GM vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Chrysler have not said whether they will continue their
programs, which provide their customers with similar loyalty
coupons and allow their dealers to accept GM coupons as well, when
they expire next week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, automakers and analysts predict an unprecedented fifth
straight year of sales of more than 15 million cars and trucks
because of record consumer confidence, low interest rates and
inflation and a healthy stock market. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
