u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNKNOWN-SOLDIER-ACTIV     07-01 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNKNOWN-SOLDIER-ACTIVIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON TESTS CONFIRM WHAT N.C. ACTIVIST KNEW ALL ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CORY REISS NYT Regional Newspapers c.1998 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Four years ago, Ted Sampley proved that the
unidentified soldier killed in Vietnam and interred in the Tomb of
the Unknowns was Air Force 1st Lt. Michael Blassie.
</P>
<P>
   But he says Pentagon officials turned their backs when he showed
them his analysis.
</P>
<P>
   So he printed his story in the 10,000-circulation U.S. Veteran
Dispatch, a North Carolina veterans' newspaper he publishes, then
republished it two years later and posted it on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Few noticed. One who did was a CBS News correspondent who began
investigating Sampley's claims and reported in January that
military officials may have known the soldier's identity when the
remains were buried in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Vindication finally came Monday, when the Pentagon confirmed
that DNA analysis had matched the remains to samples from Blassie's
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the circumstantial evidence was right on the money,''
Sampley said Tuesday from the small antiques store he owns in
Kinston. ``I had no doubt about that. My doubts were with the
Pentagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampley feared the government would cover up the truth even
after Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered the remains exhumed
in May. Sampley believes government officials who knew the
soldier's identity in 1984 bowed to political pressure to
memorialize an unknown soldier.
</P>
<P>
   CBS reporter Vince Gonzales, who said Sampley's claims were the
catalyst for his own research and reporting, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were political and military officials who knew this set
of remains had a name,'' Gonzales said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has denied that officials knew Blassie's identity
when the remains were buried, saying that the DNA analysis used to
identify his remains simply was unavailable in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Sampley _ himself a Vietnam veteran and a political
activist _ and Blassie's family had sought a laboratory analysis of
the remains but were turned down.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes tenuous links made between bones and lost soldiers
upset Sampley so much that he set out to test whether he could do
what the U.S. government hadn't: use the military's own information
to identify the unknown soldier.
</P>
<P>
   He had the tools at his disposal. Since the early 1980s, he'd
been working on a project to collect every scrap of information
about missing Vietnam vets he could find. Sampley now has several
thousand files, all entered into a database that made finding
Blassie's name possible.
</P>
<P>
   The key, he said, was that the government knew the coordinates
where the soldier's remains had been found in South Vietnam, 60
miles north of Saigon. He ran a search on every soldier listed as
missing in that area and made a list.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the process was simple deduction. Sampley knew some
objects had been found with the bones _ parts of a flight suit,
parts of a parachute and a one-man inflatable raft, for example _
which he used to narrow the list.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopter pilots don't use parachutes, so that eliminated
helicopter pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ruled out everyone but a fighter pilot, and Blassie was the
only one who went down there,'' Sampley said.
</P>
<P>
   His quest for the soldier's identity began with anger that had
lingered for a decade, ever since he became convinced that
prisoners of war had not been accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   His stake is personal. His father-in-law is still listed as
missing in action in Vietnam, and now his 5-year-old son is
starting to ask what happened to his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Sampley can't answer that. But he's made it a mission to help
others find peace.
</P>
<P>
   And now that his research has been upheld, he warns the families
of Vietnam veterans who were identified by bits of bone and teeth
to question the government's claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the families have a right to question them now,''
Sampley said. ``How many more cases have they manipulated in order
to appease the politicians?''
</P>
<P>
   A Defense Department spokesman said there was no reason to
believe such allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``An established, rigorous process is followed to ensure the
accuracy and integrity of the identification attempts,'' said the
spokesman, Lt. Col. Tom Begines.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials haven't decided whether to replace Blassie's
remains with another Vietnam soldier who has not been identified.
Sampley opposes such a move with a simple answer: Let no soldier
rest without a name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a great honor to a government if they were
capable of never having an unknown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Cory Reiss writes for The Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
