<SLUG> BC-HUBBELL-DISMISS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES TAX EVASION CASE AGAINST HUBBELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge, denouncing Independent Counsel
Kenneth W. Starr for orchestrating a ``fishing expedition,'' threw
out tax evasion charges Wednesday against Webster L. Hubbell, a
friend and former top political appointee of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest in a series of setbacks for Starr, US District
Judge James Robertson ruled the Whitewater prosecutor violated
Hubbell's Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination by
building the tax evasion case with documents Hubbell handed over
under a grant of limited immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Starr wrongly turned Hubbell ``into the primary informant
against himself,'' Robertson wrote in a 34-page decision.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said he would appeal the ruling, which provided fresh
ammunition for Clinton allies who have accused the independent
counsel of prosecutorial excesses in his four-year investigation
into the president, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and their associates.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robertson, in a sharp rebuke, ruled that Starr exceeded
his authority in pursuing the tax charges against Hubbell and three
co-defendants, including Hubbell's wife, Suzanna. The ruling also
throws out all charges against Hubbell's co-defendants _ his lawyer
and his accountant _ in the 10-count indictment Starr brought in
April.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the judge, who was appointed to the federal bench
by President Clinton, found that a special judicial panel violated
its legal limits by permitting Starr to pursue the case, which
generated the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's original mandate was to investigate the failed
Whitewater land deal in Arkansas involving the Clintons and the
Madison Guaranty Savings and Loan owned by their business partners.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, Robertson said, could have asked Attorney General Janet
Reno to expand his jurisdiction to cover the Hubbell tax charges,
as Starr did to expand his investigation to cover the Monica
Lewinsky sex-and-perjury allegations involving Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Madison-Whitewater matters that were the subject of the
original grant (of jurisdiction) and the tax matters that are the
subject of this case have nothing in common ... except Webster
Hubbell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just very, very grateful,'' Hubbell said outside his
Washington home. ``We didn't expect anything this quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanna Hubbell, standing beside him, added: ``Hopefully, this
is finally over.''
</P>
<P>
   But Starr, in a prepared statement, said he ``will seek a prompt
review of this ruling'' through federal appeals. He said the
judge's ruling ``expressly sets itself in disagreement'' with case
law developed in other federal courts, although he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials welcomed the ruling but refrained from
cheering publicly. ``We believe the judge's legal opinion speaks
for itself,'' James Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House legal
staff, said in the administration's only immediate public
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's ruling is the latest in a string of recent legal
setbacks for Starr. Last month, the Supreme Court rejected his
request to force a lawyer for Vincent W. Foster Jr., the late White
House deputy counsel, to surrender notes of conversations with
Foster shortly before Foster killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a federal judge also ordered Susan McDougal, one of
the Clintons's Whitewater partners, released from prison after she
was jailed for more than 18 months for refusing to testify in
Starr's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Supreme Court refused to grant Starr an emergency
hearing on his request to force three Secret Service agents to
testify in his grand jury investigation of Clinton's relationship
with a former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a further indication of Kenneth Starr's
prosecutorial excesses,'' said Representative Barney Frank, a
Newton Democrat and Clinton ally, said after Robertson's ruling.
``It's a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson foreshadowed Wednesday's ruling during a hearing last
week on Hubbell's motion to dismiss the tax charges. During the
session, the judge described Starr's office's view of Hubbell's
Fifth Amendment rights as ``really scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, Mrs. Clinton's former partner in the Rose Law Firm in
Little Rock, Ark., was appointed a US associate attorney general,
the third-highest position in the Justice Department, after Clinton
took office in 1993. But Hubbell left office in disgrace in 1994 as
Starr investigated charges that he had bilked former law partners
and clients.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of mail fraud and tax evasion, Hubbell was sentenced
to 21 months in prison, served 18 months, and was released in
February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But while Hubbell was incarcerated, Starr pursued a new set of
charges related to more than $700,000 in income Hubbell received in
the months after he left the Justice Department. Starr suspected
the payments may have been ``hush money'' to persuade Hubbell not
to cooperate in related Whitewater matters.
</P>
<P>
   Stymied when Hubbell refused to turn over 13,120 pages of
personal documents, Starr received a subpoena in 1996 compelling
Hubbell to produce the material on the condition that Hubbell
receive ``immunity to the extent allowed by law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson ruled that Starr's application for the subpoena
expressed no intention of investigating possible tax violations by
Hubbell. Indeed, the judge wrote, Starr did not seek authority to
investigate the tax charges for more than a year after he received
the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The subpoena served on Mr. Hubbell was the quintessential
fishing expedition,'' Robertson wrote. ``The independent counsel
freely admits that he was not investigating tax-related charges
when he issued it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
