<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED KEEPS INTEREST RATES STEADY AMID SIGNS OF COOLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ECON-REPORT) 
(mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With signs of a slowing economy and increasing
evidence that the Asian economic crisis is beginning to hurt some
industries in the United States, the Federal Reserve Wednesday
decided not to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Following a two-day private meeting, the Fed said that it was
keeping the benchmark federal funds rate _ the borrowing cost on
overnight loans between banks _ steady at 5.5 percent, just where
it has been since March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other indicators were released Wednesday that
gave a picture of an economy cooling down from the hectic pace of
the past year or so. A key index of manufacturing activity, the
monthly purchasing managers' report, fell in June for the first
time in two years. This index measures manufacturing production and
its sharp decline from 51.4 in May to 49.6 in June was seen as
evidence that the Asian economic turmoil is starting to affect
American industrial producers.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department also reported Wednesday that
construction slumped 1.5 percent in May, the worst drop in more
than four years, and the Conference Board's indicator of future
economic activity remained unchanged from April to May, at 105.2.
This is the second month in a row that the Conference Board's
leading indicator stayed fixed, a sign that the economy, while
still on a positive track, is expected to be sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an economy where inflation is low and the
economy is slowing, there is no reason for the Fed to raise
rates,'' said Stan Shipley, chief economist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
``And the three indicators also released Wednesday indicate that
this economy is weakening and weakening rapidly. We think that, by
December, we may begin to see unemployment rise and retail sales
fall and then the Fed will have to vote to lower rates.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of analysts argue that the economy, after a period of
relative weakness, could well rebound in the months ahead and see
little reason for the Fed to cut short-term interest rates. Still,
Merrill Lynch's view was echoed by others. ``A good case is
building that the Fed might need to lower interest rates,'' said
James Glassman, senior U.S. economist at Chase Securities. ``The
dislocations that were caused by the Asia shock are starting to
ripple through the U.S. economy and we are beginning to see lots of
indications that economic growth is slowing down.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, the American economy has been largely insulated from
the Asian downturn. In fact, consumers have benefited in many ways
from lower prices for imported goods and lower interest rates
caused in part by the lessening of demand from Asia for capital.
That has helped curb inflation, but some domestic producers have
begun to suffer from reduced demand for American goods in Asia and
from the intense price competition.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities,
said he was particularly troubled by the drop in the index of
manufacturing activity. ``The purchasing managers' index is
something the Fed watches closely, and the numbers that came out
Wednesday were significant,'' he said. ``Our manufacturing sector
is weakening because of the problems in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has stayed its hand even though monetary policy-makers
have leaned, ever since their meeting in March, toward raising
rates in a bid to slow down what some feared was an overripe
economy. The Fed has long raised interest rates as a way of halting
inflation, and lowered them when it wanted to stimulate the
economy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But, since the beginning of the year, inflation has, if
anything, retreated even further and is now running at an annual
rate of under 1.8 percent. In addition, Fed policy-makers are
worried that raising U.S. rates could touch off more financial
turbulence in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia's misfortune is allowing us to enjoy a strong economy
here with low inflation,'' Yardeni said. ``While the Fed might see
that strong economy as a threat to reviving inflation, they
recognize that's not much of a risk right now. What's really
important in these numbers is that we are seeing a weakening price
environment for manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, many analysts expect that the hot growth rate of 5.4
percent that took place in the first quarter of the year could slow
to around 2 percent _ or even lower _ for the rest of the year as
manufacturers and retailers work off excessive inventories that
have built up in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   In light of these estimates, the Fed warned banks on Tuesday
against lowering their lending standards on business loans. In a
statement, the Fed said bankers should resist any tendency to
assume ``that the unusually favorable economic environment of the
last few years will continue indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse into the internal reasoning of the Fed may come on
Thursday when the Open Market Committee releases the minutes of its
May 19 meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
