<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ENTOURAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE DEFENDS CLINTON ENTOURAGE OF OVER 1,000 ON CHINA TRIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ When U.S. business leaders wanted to thank
President Clinton for his stop in China's commercial capital, they
presented him Wednesday with a giant ``chop'' _ an engraved stone
stamp used to formalize official papers in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the jade, tiger-headed souvenir was so big it
looked ``imperial.''
</P>
<P>
   The same might be said of the entourage that Clinton brought to
China with him _ by far the largest of any to accompany a president
on the four Sino-American summits during the past 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has about 550 U.S. government personnel _ and three
family members _ in tow. When one factors in six legislators, 150
security people, a support staff of 150 or more, military personnel
who handle communications and media people covering the trip, the
traveling party numbers more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is accustomed to criticism about its big
traveling contingent, but contends the group is needed to do all
the business on a crowded agenda that extends far beyond Clinton's
meetings with top Chinese leaders, including President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   There are trade and business deals, from farm matters to airport
construction, as well as human rights issues and education
exchanges to be explored, a White House official said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the five Cabinet secretaries and 70 other senior aides
on Clinton's trip are undoubtedly busy with sideline meetings and
negotiations, but at least one or two seem to hang around the press
center and its media-financed buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the president really needs all these folks, White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said, ``Of course not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen any presidential entourage which you couldn't
cut probably by half if you wanted to,'' said McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said critics need to ``look at all the other
moving parts behind the summit in which people are doing work,
having meetings with (Chinese) counterparts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Clinton is here is a forcing event; it forces
the bureaucracies to create `deliverables' and to come to closure
on things that have been negotiated,'' McCurry said. ``And that's
what you want to have a summit for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deliverables'' is diplo-speak for deals and agreements that
can be formally announced, sometimes with the intention of making
an otherwise uneventful get-together look fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the local U.S. government representatives have been
working for months, and McCurry said the presence of more senior
officials can nudge ``negotiations that have stalled or need a
personal push.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of stuff going on, and every single one of
these Cabinet people here represents an element of what this very
broad-based relationship is about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry pointed to an announcement in Beijing by Peace Corps
Director Mark D. Gearan that his agency's relations with China were
being formalized, after a five-year trial period, and that 40
English teachers from the United States were heading for Sichuan
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the price that we've paid to schlep everyone over here
worth that? Yes, because it tells the story to the American people
of what this relationship is about in its totality and why we are
engaged with them,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can write the obligatory (story about) too many people and
ten limos and so on. It's easy to write that story,'' said McCurry.
``I just think there is an argument that this all in the end is
worth something because this is what the strategy of engagement is
about _ bringing a whole hell of a lot of people here and getting
them to sit down and start working things out.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the China extravaganza to U.S. taxpayers is hard to
come by, although Republicans in control of Congress are certain to
make an attempt. It's a possibly embarrassing exercise that Clinton
would not face so directly if Democrats were in control of Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Government costs are spread out over dozens of departments, from
the White House to State Department and Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   When President Nixon made his breakthrough trip to China in
1972, his entourage totaled 300. President Ford brought 280 in
1975. President Reagan was accompanied by 340 in 1984. President
Bush, whose China trip in 1989 was added on to his visit to Tokyo
for Emperor Hirohito's funeral, had 300 folks along.
</P>
<P>
   The president is the only government official allowed to be
accompanied by family members on official White House trips, and
Clinton has brought first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, as well as
daughter Chelsea, on summer break from Stanford University, and
mother-in-law Dorothy Rodham of Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
