<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BUSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL COULD END SCHOOL BUSING IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a proposal that could end two decades of student
busing in Boston, the School Committee has been asked to consider
assigning students to schools with no regard to race, as one of
three new ideas for revamping the assignment program.
</P>
<P>
   If race were eliminated from the assignment process, school
statistics released Wednesday show, the racial percentages in
schools would remain largely the same as they are now, because the
district is 80 percent minority. Under the proposal to eliminate
consideration of race, students would be assigned to schools based
solely on choice and lottery.
</P>
<P>
   School Superintendent Thomas Payzant, stressing he is not yet
recommending any of the three proposals, also asked school
committee members at their meeting Wednesday to consider a
``cluster'' plan he has already publicized. It would give families
fewer elementary and middle schools to chose from, but would better
ensure they could attend schools closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Payzant also offered a third plan for consideration: drawing a
`circle' around students' neighborhoods or homes, and allowing them
to choose from the ten schools closest to them _ all but
guaranteeing them the ability to choose neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   All of the plans could eventually save the money the city now
spends on busing to achieve racial guidelines _ $17 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not recommendations. This is only the beginning of
discussions,'' Payzant said, adding he hopes they will take place
in a ``rational and thoughtful way.''
</P>
<P>
   School committee members, who received the plans for the first
time, are expected to hold public hearings through the fall before
voting for one of them in November. The earliest any plan would
take effect would be the 1999-2000 school year, said school
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The three proposals made Wednesday night grew out of a student
assignment task force that met last year.
</P>
<P>
   School committee members said they remain committed to
desegregation in the schools. Two members said they felt changes in
student assignments should not even be pursued, so the committee
can better focus on teaching and learning. Two others said the
isssue of good schools is tied so closely to parental choice and
desegregatation that it must be explored.
</P>
<P>
   Any revisions to school busing in Boston are expected to meet
with widespread opposition. Already, many minority parents have
made clear they fear that any return to neighborhood schools will
lead to wealthier neighborhoods having the best schools.
</P>
<P>
   Before busing began with a federal court order in 1974, schools
in poor, minority neighborhoods received fewer resources. Boston's
busing plan was revamped in 1989, giving students more choice while
still requiring busing to racially balance schools.
</P>
<P>
   School department officials said they simulated student
assgingments for four grades, using racial guidelines under one
simulation and no racial guidelines in the other.
</P>
<P>
   They were astonished to discover that only 15 of the city's 60
elementary sdhools had too few white students under the free choice
plan than racial balancing calls for. That represented only 196
elementary students citywide.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, schools are required to meet various racial
percentages. Elementary and middle school students choose schools
from one of three zones in the city. High school students choose
citywide.
</P>
<P>
   The pure choice plan would give parents the ability to choose a
wide range of schools within their zone _ as many as 27 elementary
schools, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The other two plans and the desegregation impact each would have
are:
</P>
<P>
   --The cluster plan, which breaks the city up into 10 clusters,
giving parents a choice of 6 to 10 elementary schools in each.
Under the plan, choice would be diminished, but parents would be
able to choose schools closer to home. However, there would be
problems with desegregation because so many Boston neighborhoods
are largely white or black. For instance, the East Boston and
Charlestown cluster would have an 8 percent increase in white
students over what that zone has now, and West Rosnbury would have
12 percent more. The plan also creates peoblems in clusters with
too many students and too few seats, including Roxbury and
Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   --The third plan makes a student's neighborhood or home the
center of a circle, increasing choice of schools over the cluster
plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
