u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-385&AMP;ADD-N     07-01 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN LEGISLATORS BEGIN TO APPROVE YELTSIN ECONOMIC PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's fractious national legislators complained at
length Wednesday about President Boris Yeltsin's newest and most
drastic belt-tightening plan for the country's faltering economy,
then began rather hastily to approve parts of it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of several days of debate over the proposal,
Communists in the Duma, the lower house of Russia's Parliament,
argued bitterly against Yeltsin's proposals for sales and
value-added taxes that would directly hit consumers. The head of
the upper chamber, the Federation Council, argued that the plan
could rob regional governments of much-needed revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Free-market supporters in the lower house who might otherwise
back the austerity measures said they opposed them anyway, because
they dislike Yeltsin's high-handed style of governing. The
president introduced the proposal nine days ago with a warning that
legislators would have to enact it or face ``other measures,''
meaning he would impose it by decree.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, no one Wednesday seemed willing to predict that
the plan will go down to defeat in the Communist-controlled lower
house, which is considering it first. In large part, legislators
were driven by fears that rejecting the measures outright would
propel the economy into genuine national chaos.
</P>
<P>
   And so the lower house gave preliminary approval to nearly half
of the 20 or so sections in Yeltsin's blueprint. They included a 20
percent value-added tax, a new flat tax on small businesses like
newsstands and gas stations, a cut in the corporate profits tax and
the repeal of a quirky provision that taxes companies forced to
sell products at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Yeltsin also proposes to impose a tax on
bartered deals, now a huge and untaxed slice of the Russian
economy, to raise land taxes, to impose a low-rate flat tax on all
citizens and to wipe out a series of Soviet-era subsidies and
unproductive government jobs. In all, experts have said the
emergency measures should bring in about $22 billion a year. The
government's forecasters have valued the package at about $16
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The government would use the money to make good on back pay to
millions of government workers and to cut its budget deficit, which
is now being financed with high-interest short-term debt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko has said that monthly debt
payments now run about 1.4 times the federal government's monthly
revenue, meaning that the government has to borrow money just to
pay for its past debts.
</P>
<P>
   Those sorts of problems have led the International Monetary Fund
to demand an economic overhaul before considering billions in new
loans that would prop up Russian finances and the ruble.
Negotiations over $10 billion to $15 billion in new loans began
last month. Foreign investors have also begun to lose confidence in
the near-insolvent economy, and Russian stocks and the ruble have
been under assault in recent weeks as the crisis worsened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
