A6723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-RUBIN-500&AMP;ADD-NY     07-01 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-RUBIN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOREA, RUBIN URGES JAPAN TO TAKE CREDIBLE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ On the last stop of his six-day
four-country sweep of Asia, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin made
his most pointed comments about a country that he did not even
visit, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese economy was clearly on Rubin's mind as he met South
Korean business, labor and political leaders for a report on the
country's economic overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed again and again the ``enormous importance of getting
Japan back on track to support growth in Korea and the region in
general.'' Rubin said he was ``deeply, deeply concerned'' about the
recent slide of the yen against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But he dodged questions about whether the United States would
again step in to prop up the yen with the standard response that
the United States would move if and when it deemed intervention was
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   And on the eve of the disclosure of Japan's latest plan to
overhaul its financial system, Rubin exhorted Japanese officials to
come up with a credible solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important key with respect to economic conditions in
Japan is to restructure its banking system in an efficient fashion
that wins the approval of the world financial markets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His decision not to include Japan on his trip, but nonetheless
to talk a great deal about it, has been a subject of intense
discussion in Asia, where Japan's inability to devise a plan to put
its economy back on track is seen as prolonging the region's woes.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin and President Clinton's detours around Japan are widely
regarded as a snub to one of the most devoted U.S. allies and have
raised wide-ranging speculation here about a realignment of
American interests.
</P>
<P>
   In his meeting Wednesday with Rubin, President Kim Dae-jung
wondered aloud whether the United States and China were forging a
``special relationship,'' a heavily veiled expression of concern
that most Asian countries have about how China's power will grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't characterize it that way,'' Rubin told Kim,
although he added that Clinton had long regarded better relations
between the United States and China as important.
</P>
<P>
   In a day capped by a somber visit to the demilitarized zone
between North and South Korea, Rubin met Kim and business and labor
leaders in hopes of improving his understanding of the issues
confronting Korea as its sweeping efforts to reform its economy
begin to bite.
</P>
<P>
   The more radical of the two labor confederations gave him a
stern lecture on the evils of the International Monetary Fund's
rescue program, which includes maintaining high interest rates and
introducing greater flexibility in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Those two factors are faulted for pushing companies into
bankruptcy at the rate of 3,000 a month and putting 1.6 million
people out of work.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the participants in the meeting understood the need
for broad-based support for reform in spite of the immediate pain.
``They were concerned that every sector of the economy bear a share
of the pain,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an attempt to assess that, he met the heads of four of the
five largest conglomerates, the Daewoo, Hyundai, Samsung and LG
groups, and a senior representative of the fifth group, SK, whose
chairman, Chey Jong-hyun, was ill.
</P>
<P>
   Government and other analysts are impatient with the large
groups' efforts to change. But in their meeting, on Tuesday, they
did express their commitment to reform, although the head of
Daewoo, Kim Woo-choong, avoided directly answering Rubin's question
about whether the groups would reduce their debt-to-equity ratios
to 2-to-1 by the end of the year, according to people at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the meeting Kim of Daewoo urged Rubin to do what
he could to further the imports and sales of Korean cars in the
United States. The Korean automobile business is running at 40
percent of capacity, because of virtually nonexistent domestic
demand and stiffer competition from Japanese manufacturers, who
have been helped by the weaker yen.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin also met representatives of small and midsize enterprises
who pleaded with him to advocate lower interest rates, according to
those at the meeting. Interest rates on corporate debt have fallen,
to 16 percent for three-year notes from highs of up to 30 percent
when the crisis hit in December.
</P>
<P>
   But small businesses generally pay much higher rates than that,
and the cost of servicing debt is driving many entrepreneurs out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin reiterated American support for South Korea, pledging to
back additional lending from international sources. But he added
that he saw no need for such additional lending, because Korea has
$39 billion in foreign currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the United States went through many of the
same painful adjustments that Korea is experiencing before it
emerged as the world's economic powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes,'' he said, ``and there's a lot to
be learned from our mistakes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
