<HEADER>
A6724 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GWTW-ESSAYS-TEX     07-01 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GWTW-ESSAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACTIONS TO ``GONE WITH THE WIND''
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A POOR BOY'S VIEW
</P>
<P>
   My people are from the South, from the mountains of Virginia and
North Carolina. ``Gone With the Wind'' it ain't.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is the same to me as to others descended from poor
whites in the rural South: It's a story of how the other half
lived. The South I know is down dirt roads and up rutted mountains.
You won't find Tara there.
</P>
<P>
   What's left of my heritage is torn-down farmhouses and overgrown
cornfields. My forebears didn't pass down silver or linens saved
from pillaging Yankees. They handed down a story of Confederate
soldiers who hid horses at the mouth of their holler.
</P>
<P>
   I have an ancestor, Elliott Bingham, who fought and died for the
Confederate cause. But I know little about him. There are no
romantic stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
   My relatives were Scottish and Irish immigrants. They worked
hard, minded their business and lived a life far removed from
belles and balls. I doubt they ever drank brandy or smoked cigars.
I do know they made moonshine and rolled cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone With the Wind'' is a wonderful story, nothing more.
Growing up watching the movie, I've seen more white-columned
mansions than my ancestors ever did.
</P>
<P>
   _ Essay by Larry Bingham
</P>
<P>
   A TEXAS GIRL'S HEROINE
</P>
<P>
   I've lost count of how many dozens of times I've seen ``Gone
With the Wind.'' The first time, as an impressionable 8-year-old,
left me swimming in images: the beautiful plantations, the fiery
Scarlett, the gorgeous Rhett. For days, I talked constantly about
it with my very Southern mother.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, and in later adolescence, the mixed messages
bombarded me: I was terrified to think I would need an 18-inch
waist for someone handsome to like me, or that I could never eat
heartily in front of men.
</P>
<P>
   It was also appalling to think that life and love were about
suffering. Would I not find the right man? Would I be too blind to
know who the right man was? It took a while for me to figure out
that Scarlett made bad choices once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   But the more important lessons from Scarlett are those I've
found to be true on my own, and were probably some reflection of
Margaret Mitchell herself. Whether Southern or not, a woman can dig
down and find strength to get through tough times by sheer will.
She can stop worrying about herself and help those who need her
strength. She can find answers to impossible questions when
survival _ even emotional survival _ is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, when all seems hopeless, family and home do perform
miracles. They can save a life, and not just in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Essay by June Naylor Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   FICTIONALLY, MY DEAR
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Mitchell may have been a good writer, but she was a
good liar, too. The ``pretty world of gallantry'' she created was
as remote from the historical reality of the pre-Civil War South as
Camelot was from the real medieval England.
</P>
<P>
   I call on the eyewitness testimony of Frederick Law Olmsted, a
journalist and agricultural expert from Connecticut who traversed
the South several times in the 1850s. A collection of his work,
``The Cotton Kingdom,'' was republished in 1953. Unfortunately,
although the novel ``Gone With the Wind'' is perennially available,
``The Cotton Kingdom'' is no longer in print.
</P>
<P>
   Olmsted describes a vast region that, in the years before the
Civil War, was constantly on the edge of economic ruin, with
widespread ecological devastation and famine. Forests and fields
were depleted and abandoned. Trains and boats ran days late. The
entire culture was hobbled by the inefficiency of the slave system,
with its absence of incentive. Children on plantations were often
isolated and uneducated; the lively social life suggested in the
opening passages of ``GWTW'' was rare indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Gallantry? Men _ slaveholders and overseers _ routinely beat
women viciously and enslaved their own children and grandchildren.
The nonconsensual sex forced on slave women was, in many ways, a
means of creating more property.
</P>
<P>
   Southern hospitality? Olmsted recounts stories of deathly ill
travelers being turned away from remote settlements and says that
he never stayed in a home in the South without being asked to pay
upon leaving. The rare inns were miserable, sometimes without
sanitary facilities. With few exceptions, Olmsted discovered an
entire population, including landowners and slaveholders,
subsisting mainly on sweet potatoes, corn bread and bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the movie and the skill and imagination that went into it.
But don't believe the underlying premise of a grand civilization
destroyed. Yes, the Civil War brought great destruction and
suffering to millions; but what was there beforehand wasn't so
great.
</P>
<P>
   _ Essay by Wayne Lee Gay
</P>
<P>
   TARA WANNABES
</P>
<P>
   Out there, on every two-lane blacktop in Texas, are two sure
things: a flattened armadillo and a Tara wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   In the country, the architectural influence of ``Gone With the
Wind'' is as pervasive as kudzu. The 2-story columns with Ionic
capitals form the gateway to the rural routes.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the columned facades are shallow facsimiles of grand
manors, 3-2s without the sweeping staircase. A self-styled Scarlett
built each one, and it is the house of her dreams. The antebellum
manse indicates social and financial success in the Wal-Mart
vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   To engage your traveling companions, hum a few bars of the
film's theme song every time you see a home belonging to the
Scarlett sisterhood, da DA da dum, da DA da de.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, usually children who have no personal ``Gone With
the Wind'' experience, say it's an extremely irritating car game.
Others find it a pleasant way to travel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Essay by Gaile Robinson
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHIN' STEREOTYPES
</P>
<P>
   Few lines from ``Gone With the Wind'' are as memorable as
Butterfly McQueen's warbling, squeaky cry: ``Lawsy, Miss Scah-lett!
I don't know nothin' 'bout birthin' babies!''
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa, Fla., native's role as Prissy, the dippy young slave,
may have been the one she regretted most. But to me, a 10-year-old
born in the South and raised in Yankee territory, she only played
dumb. Young Prissy was a welcome relief from all that syrupy
sentiment and adult chatter about ``the Wahhr.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after my sister and I were born in Virginia and North
Carolina, respectively, my Southern parents whisked us off to the
cold Midwest in search of better schools and opportunity. Prissy's
world was foreign to me.
</P>
<P>
   In time, I learned that Butterfly McQueen would never shake the
dumb maid stereotype. I also learned that many folk would love to
live in a Technicolor South.
</P>
<P>
   Not this Southerner, sugah.
</P>
<P>
   As for Butterfly, she earned a political science degree from
City College in New York at 64. Twenty years later, in 1995, she
died in a kerosene fire at her home, a few hours' drive east of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   She had long before dropped out of films. Hollywood would never
cast her in roles that showcased her talent. Now THAT'S what I call
dumb.
</P>
<P>
   _ Essay by Nichele Hoskins
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
