</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URANIUM-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: COULD URANIUM PRIVATIZATION AID NUCLEAR
PROLIFERATION? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ky.)   (bl)  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Treasury's announcement Monday that it would soon privatize
the government's half-century-old uranium enrichment plants made
waves largely because of the proposed method of sale. While an
initial public offering of shares in a government-owned corporation
is not unprecedented, it is certainly a novelty in keeping with the
spirit of the high-flying stock market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the more important news is that the Treasury is moving
forward in spite of years of warnings that the sale would undermine
a key initiative for containing nuclear proliferation. For once the
United States Enrichment Corp. is privatized, the company will have
powerful financial incentives to find a means to back away from an
agreement to import 500 tons of bomb-grade uranium from Russia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatization is a foreign policy disaster waiting to
happen,'' argued Richard Falkenrath, an economist at Harvard's
Kennedy School of government.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cold War ended and Russia was left with a potent
nuclear arsenal, Tom Neff, a physicist at MIT, had a brainstorm.
Why not buy a chunk of Russia's stockpile of bomb-grade uranium,
blend it with natural uranium to make fuel for commercial power
reactors and resell it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why not, indeed: With much fanfare, Vice President Al Gore
struck the swords-to-plowshares deal with President Boris Yeltsin
in 1993. Russia would manufacture the reactor fuel from its bombs,
and Washington would sell the fuel on world markets. Minatom, the
Russian nuclear authority, with an estimated one million employees,
would get cash to cover the wages of its impoverished nuclear
scientists. Far less bomb-grade uranium would be left lying around
Russia for someone to steal. And all this would happen without a
dime from taxpayers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Enrichment Corp., the federal operator of the plants in
Ohio and Kentucky that enrich natural uranium to commercial reactor
fuel, was assigned to put the agreement in effect. That seemed the
obvious way to go, save for one fact: In an entirely unrelated
burst of enthusiasm for privatizing government assets, Congress had
earlier decreed that the public corporation should be sold to the
highest responsible bidder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stiglitz, then the chairman of the President's Council of
Economic Advisers, pointed to the conflict of interest. A
privatized, profit-maximizing U.S. Energy Corp., he argued, would
have an incentive to buy as little Russian enriched uranium as
possible _ at least as long as the price paid to the Russians was
higher than the corporation's own (heavily subsidized) cost of
producing each extra bit of reactor fuel.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in a curious role reversal, the government's national
security establishment put the cause of reinventing government
ahead of keeping nuclear weapons out of the hands of malefactors.
The State Department, Energy Department and the president's
National Security Council all insisted that the corporation would
do the right thing because federal watchdogs would otherwise
intervene.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stiglitz was outgunned, but not outargued: There was already
tangible evidence that the business conflict was real. For even as
public servants, the corporation's managers had been caught
secretly asking the Russians to slow deliveries to allow the
corporation to sell more from its own inventory. And by Neff's
analysis, the government's will to keep the corporation on the
straight and narrow is likely to be strained again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As long as the price paid to Russia is less than the prevailing
world price, the fuel can always be resold without cost to the
government. But Neff notes that the uranium fuel market is weak _
and will probably get weaker unless the Asian economies soon
recover from their funk. Thus it would hardly be a surprise if the
government were someday forced to choose between turning a blind
eye toward the U.S. Energy Corp.'s machinations or buying up
surplus Russian uranium fuel at the taxpayers' risk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would Washington invest billions of dollars to keep the
fissionable material flowing out of Russia? In a letter to Sen.
John Glenn, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Energy Secretary
Federico Pena assured him that ``if problems arise the
administration will not hesitate to add or replace executive
agents'' _ longhand for ``yes.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Falkenrath is skeptical. ``How likely is Congress to
appropriate money to buy Russian uranium that had, in effect, been
dumped by a privatized USEC,'' he asked? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If economists believe there is trouble looming down the road, so
apparently do the Energy Corp.'s investment bankers. After
subtracting the value of uranium inventories that the corporation
will retain and adding debts it will carry, the USEC's advisers
estimated that the government would realize between $1.15 and $1.45
billion from the public offering _ just four or five years' profit,
projecting from the corporation's fiscal performance in recent
years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just how would the taxpayers be better off selling USEC at five
times earnings rather than banking the cash flow? ``It beats me,''
said a frustrated Rep. Ted Strickland, a Democrat who represents
the Ohio district where one of the corporation's two plants is
situated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
