<HEADER>
A6726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HILLARY-CLINTON     07-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HILLARY-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY WATCHES TORAH FROM U.S. SANCTIFY ABANDONED CHINESE
TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-MEDIA, CHINA-NOTEBOOK,
HONGKONG-AIRPORT) 
(JT) 
 By SETH FAISON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ There was a time, earlier this century, when
Jews flocked to this city. Though traces of their lives are mostly
buried or lost, one prominent relic was revived Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a modest ceremony timed to coincide with a visit by the first
lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, an American rabbi sanctified the Ohel
Rachel temple with a Torah carried all the way from New York,
restoring a symbol of Jewish faith that had been neglected for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi, Arthur Schneier, said it was like bringing a
synagogue back to life. Graciously thanking the people of Shanghai
for taking in so many persecuted Jews when about 20,000 of them
fled here from Europe during World War II, Schneier said he also
hoped that the synagogue would now be protected from a wrecker's
ball. Four other former synagogues have disappeared in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a beginning of Jewish life,'' Schneier said.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it is a modest beginning. The authorities in Shanghai
have not yet agreed to let the temple be used again as a place of
worship by the 200-plus members of Shanghai's expatriate Jewish
community.
</P>
<P>
   Doing so anytime soon may be difficult, because China's
government, which supervises religious worship tightly, does not
include Judaism among the five officially recognized religions. The
five are Protestant Christianity, Catholicism, Islam, Buddhism and
Taoism.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton called the restoration of the synagogue ``a very
good example of respect for religious differences and appreciation
for the importance of faith in one's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jews hold a special place in the history of Shanghai. Several
Iraqi Jewish families moved here in the late 19th century and went
on to dominate the real estate, securities and banking businesses.
Eventually, tycoons with names like Sassoon, Kadoorie and Hardoon
were among the city's most prominent residents.
</P>
<P>
   Six synagogues were built _ including Ohel Rachel, named for the
wife of Jacob Sassoon, in 1920. At the Shanghai Jewish community's
peak in 1945, it had about 25,000 members. Virtually all of them
left after the Communist Party came to power in 1949 and made
foreigners unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few months ago, Ohel Rachel was a warehouse, dusty and
unkempt from years of disuse. Efforts to restore it began only this
year, after Schneier persuaded Shanghai's mayor that it was worth
saving.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the synagogue's walls were a freshly painted white,
marble columns gleamed and crystal chandeliers hung from an arched
roof. Schneier brought the Torah from Park East Synagogue on East
67th Street in Manhattan. He is that congregation's senior rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 26 Torahs, so now we have 25,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, whose family was
originally Jewish, also visited the old synagogue Wednesday with
Mrs. Clinton. She did not comment afterward, so the loquacious
Schneier spoke for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows from personal experience about religious
persecution,'' he said. ``She has placed an enormous amount of
energy and effort into religious freedom, and I'm sure deep down it
comes from her personal experience.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-MARKETPLACE-NY     07-01 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BOEING'S OUTLOOK APPEARS TO BRIGHTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has Boeing turned the corner?
</P>
<P>
   The company's top executives all but said so Wednesday during a
teleconference with analysts and reporters. Boeing began the
monthly conferences last fall to chart the progress of an emergency
recovery plan it put in place after its commercial airplane
operations became plagued by huge and costly production delays.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the company said it delivered 61 airplanes in
June, the highest one-month total ever, and was on course to meet
its goal of delivering 550 jets this year. It also said there would
be no more monthly updates. ``The recovery portion of the plan is
now over,'' declared Boeing chairman and chief executive Philip
Condit, though he insisted that the company still faced
considerable challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing shares rose 6.45 percent Wednesday, or $2.875, closing at
$47.4375. But only last week the stock fell to a 52-week low of
$42.75 a share. Boeing is down 3 percent for the year, compared
with an 18.4 percent rise in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many analysts remain bearish, citing blistering price
competition with its European rival, Airbus Industrie, continuing
weakness in Asia and the specter of rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts and some investors contend that few on the
Street fully understand how military contractors like Boeing
account for production, saying that such accounting can
overestimate or underestimate actual earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As bad as things have been at Boeing, the way they are
accounting for them makes them look worse,'' said George Shapiro,
the aerospace analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Boeing appears to have its production problems under
control, the company's financial performance could improve rapidly,
a number of analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Because the initial cost of designing and building a new
airplane can be many billions of dollars, Boeing, along with other
military contractors, uses a system called program accounting.
Rather than absorb all the costs at once, depressing earnings,
Boeing averages them over an estimated number of airplanes it
expects to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The practice began in the 1960s with the 707, Boeing's first
commercial jet, and it has continued through the 747 jumbojet to
the 777, Boeing's newest airplane. Traditionally, the first block
equals 400 planes, even if Boeing has received orders for only as
fraction of that number.
</P>
<P>
   The practice helps smooth out earnings but it is considered
risky because there is no guarantee that all the planes in the
initial block will actually be sold. When McDonnell Douglas Corp.,
which was bought by Boeing last year, built its MD-11 wide-body
jet, it chose to average the costs over an estimated 300 airplanes.
But in 1995 the company was forced to acknowledged that it would
never sell that many planes, resulting in a $1.8 billion charge.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Boeing's new 737 narrow-body jet, however, the
opposite happened. Following its tradition, the company decided to
average the costs of the new plane over 400 units. But the
so-called Next-Generation 737 has proved wildly popular with
airlines around the world. Boeing now has firm orders for more than
800 of the planes.
</P>
<P>
   Since last fall, production problems on the 737 have forced
Boeing to take more than $1 billion in charges. The company is now
technically losing money on the airplane. But that is only because
it does not officially recognize the more than 400 additional
orders. Counting even a portion of these would immediately put the
737 in the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 737 was unique because the backlog actually exceeded the
quantity in the program,'' said Boeing controller Gary Beil. ``But
we used the same quantity as other programs, which was
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Another feature of program accounting is that it can
artificially understate earnings as more planes are produced. That
is because the first planes built are the most expensive. As the
operation gains more efficiency and the initial cost of design and
tooling are spread over more units, the costs decline.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore plane No. 400 costs considerably less to produce than
the amount carried on Boeing's books, which is equal to the average
production cost for all 400 planes. The result is more cash for
Boeing at the end of the block than earnings suggest.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where Boeing is right now with its two newest
programs, the 777 and the 737 Next-Generation. Boeing will not say
when, but it will soon have to extend the blocks on both programs,
something many investors believe will sharply increase its
financial results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you extend that block, all your fixed costs start to come
down and all of a sudden the profitability increases,'' said
Stephan J. Klaffke, who manages the equity portfolio for USAA
insurance _ which owns 1.5 million shares of Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   But others note that Boeing's performance will only improve if
it succeeds in producing its planes more efficiently _ something it
has had trouble doing lately _ and if it is not forced to sacrifice
profits to win orders away from Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors don't have perfect information because they don't in
fact know what the costs are of the airplanes from 400 to 900 and
what prices they were sold at,'' said Wolfgang Demisch, an
aerospace analyst with BT Alex Brown. ``I think they were sold at
very big discounts to the likes of American and others and so
Boeing won't make much profit on them.''
</P>
<P>
   And if economic instability in Asia spreads to Europe and North
America and if oil prices rise, putting more pressure on airlines,
some of the orders that Boeing now counts as firm may not remain
so.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said that it will not extend the block on the
737 until it is absolutely sure that its production difficulties
are behind it. But there have also been discussions within Boeing
about simply eliminating program accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that Harry Stonecipher, the former chief executive
of McDonnell Douglas who is now Boeing's president, believes that
the company is now large enough to absorb big up-front investments
in new planes and that ending the practice would give investors a
truer picture of performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things that have been evaluated and
considered,'' a Boeing spokesman said. ``But at this time there are
no plans to change it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
