<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EX-OFFICIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA WARNS EX-OFFICIAL TO STOP GIVING INTERVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-MEDIA, CHINA-NOTEBOOK,
CHINA-HILLARY-CLINTON, HONGKONG-AIRPORT) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former senior Chinese official who was jailed for
opposing the 1989 Tiananmen Square crackdown has been warned three
times by the Chinese authorities to stop talking to foreign
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The latest warning came on Sunday, only a day after President
Clinton's news conference with Chinese President Jiang Zemin. But
the former official, Bao Tong, has continued to speak out, giving
an interview on Tuesday to the Voice of America's Mandarin-language
service.
</P>
<P>
   Senior American officials said Wednesday that Bao's fate is ``a
topic of significant interest'' to the Clinton Administration. But
they added that they could not say whether Bao's case had been
raised by Clinton in his private conversations with Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   Bao, 66, is no dissident. He served as chief of staff to former
Communist Party Secretary Zhao Ziyang, who was ousted days before
the June 1989 crackdown and who remains under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Bao, who was jailed then and held for almost seven years, until
May 1996, has used Clinton's visit to speak out about the failings
of the current government. Zhao himself circulated a letter to the
party's Central Committee just before Clinton arrived, calling on
it to reverse its harsh judgment on the demonstrations in the
square, which are officially considered a ``counterrevolutionary
rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bao gave an interview to CBS News, which was taped by hidden
cameras, and televised on Monday. Bao's son, Bao Pu, said in an
interview that the security police came to his father's Beijing
apartment after the taping on Sunday, presumably because the
apartment is bugged, and spent two hours there.
</P>
<P>
   They said that Bao had violated the law by giving interviews to
foreign journalists without authorization, but Bao answered that
Jiang himself had said the day before that ``every Chinese citizen
is given freedom of speech by the Constitution,'' his son said.
</P>
<P>
   Bao also gave an interview in Beijing to The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bao's third warning from the police, who had also told
him on June 4 and June 8, nearly three weeks before Clinton's
arrival, that he must not give interviews to foreign journalists.
On June 3, The Washington Post had printed its own interview with
Bao. Bao also spoke to The New York Times for a June 25 article
about the Zhao letter; in that interview he said, ``Political
reform is the biggest issue in China today.''
</P>
<P>
   His son, Bao Pu, who lives in the United States, said Wednesday
that Bao and his family are nervous about what will happen after
Clinton leaves China this weekend, but that his father intends to
keep testing the new Chinese openness. Bao is followed by the
police wherever he goes, Bao Pu said.
</P>
<P>
   In his father's colloquy with the security police, his son said,
Bao asked whether he was guilty of any crime by speaking to
foreigners who had themselves failed to get Foreign Ministry
authorization for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police said it was a mistake for him to give any more
interviews,'' Bao Pu said, but his father responded: ``It's not
your job to tell me what's right and wrong; it's your job to tell
me what's legal or illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bao Pu said he had asked his father's judgment of Clinton's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father said, `One cannot overestimate the short-term
effect, but no one should underestimate the long-term effect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
