A6735 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHAT-WEBELIEVE-TEX     07-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-WE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE OF A SERIES ON WORLD RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
 BELIEVE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHURCH OF THE BRETHREN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEMBERSHIP: About 150,000 in more than 1,000 congregations in
the United States and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY: The Church of the Brethren developed as an outgrowth of
radical Pietism in early 18th-century Germany; in fact, much of the
group's theology and practice came from the Pietists of the 17th
and 18th centuries, who were mostly Lutherans unhappy with their
state church.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Brethren immigrated to the American colonies in the
1720s, and an American congregation was established in Germantown,
Pa., in 1723. Until the 20th century, the group's name was the
German Baptist Brethren.
</P>
<P>
   After coming to America, the Brethren were not opposed to urban
life, but most preferred farming and agricultural life. From the
1790s to the 1850s, congregations were established in Kentucky,
Ohio, Missouri, Illinois, California and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Brethren separated themselves from secular influences, opposed
slavery and wore distinctive, plain dress. The leaders they
selected were not paid and had no theological education, and all
Brethren agreed not to vote, take oaths or enter into lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Until the early 20th century, the Brethren were known as
``Dunkers'' because of their unusual practice of baptizing by
triple immersion: in the name of the Father, the Son and the Holy
Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Tension in the late 19th century caused a division in the
church, and three factions developed: the original group, ``old
order'' traditionalists and a progressive movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Brethren is one of the three historic ``peace
churches,'' along with the Mennonites and the Quakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Brethren opposed military service during the American
Revolution and Civil War; in following years, they were allowed to
avoid involvement in war efforts as conscientious objectors.
</P>
<P>
   The Brethren have made several changes this century. For the
most part, they no longer wear the plain dress they were known for,
and their leaders are now professional, salaried pastors. Women
became eligible for ordination in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEFS: The Church of the Brethren has historically resisted
creeds, but the Brethren focus on spiritual life and piety
developed through prayer, Bible study and association with fellow
believers. The church is not considered an organization that
formulates doctrine as much as it is a supportive group of people
who love God and one another.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY LIFE: The Brethren emphasize daily devotion, stewardship
and care for those less fortunate. The church opposes violence,
divorce and remarriage, as well as oath-taking, voting and
attention-getting or distracting dress.
</P>
<P>
   The love feast is the most significant feature of Brethren
worship. The communion service includes foot washing, a love meal
and the partaking of unleavened bread and wine or grape juice.
</P>
<P>
   The church is affiliated with six accredited liberal arts
colleges and a seminary in Indiana. The Brethren are best known
internationally for their relief and rehabilitation work in Europe
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Encyclopedia of American Religion and Handbook of
Denominations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-ARTS-REACT-2TA     07-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ARTS-REACT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTS SEE NO DECENCY IN RULING ON GRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision upholding a decency test for federal
arts grants has been greeted by a wave of disappointment in the
world of the arts. Performance artists directly affected by last
week's ruling vigorously condemned it, while the response of
playwrights and others ranged from the embattled to the calmly
accepting.
</P>
<P>
   All who spoke on the issue expressed confusion about the
vagueness of the court's language and the difficulty of determining
just what decency is.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member court majority (only Justice David Souter
dissented) insisted that their intention in ruling against Karen
Finley and the three other performance artists known as the NEA
Four _ Tim Miller, Holly Hughes and John Fleck _ was advisory
rather than compulsory.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the ruling did the court say that such standards
would be applied. The subject seemed to be left up in the air, with
each grant to be scrutinized individually. But even if the National
Endowment for the Arts should decide not to use taste as a
criterion in making grants, artists said, state and local officials
(in libraries, schools and theaters) might see the ruling as a
license to limit liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the strongest reaction came on the Internet. One music
student said, ``I hope those who'll be making the `decency'
decisions aren't anything like my grandpa, or else it'll be
Lawrence Welk for the rest of my life.'' Another said, ``If Jesse
Helms can decide whether or not Karen Finley can bathe herself in
chocolate on our dime, perhaps your local town council can decide
that your band is just a little too radical to play the Fourth of
July gig in the town square.''
</P>
<P>
   Mac Wellman, one of the most politically minded of American
playwrights, has had his own collision with Helms, the North
Carolina Republican senator who is a longtime foe of government
support for what he has called obscene art.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge, there is nothing about public standards of
decency in the Constitution,'' Wellman said. ``But there is a great
deal about civil liberties. This incredible decision is a victory
for those who want to control freedom of expression for their own
ends, and that's an obscenity.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from Northern Ireland, where he is working
with the Exile Theater, Wellman said: ``It's a political decision
masking as one concerned with obscenity. What it is really about is
marginalizing opinions that are different, and I think that's a
major setback for civil liberties in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellman called it shocking that poets, novelists and others
outside the theater did not seem to be taking the Supreme Court's
decision more seriously. He asked, ``Have you heard from any poet
laureates on this issue?''
</P>
<P>
   When he was contacted, Robert Pinsky, the U.S. poet laureate,
deferred comment, saying that he had not read the decision and did
not ``know enough about it yet.'' Others also responded in that
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Finley, the performance artist at the center of the storm,
said she regarded the decision as a personal affront as well as a
strike against artistic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it that the Supreme Court has decided my work is
indecent,'' she said. Through her performances, in which she is
often nude, she makes a graphic statement about the abuse of women.
She does not consider her performances to be indecent, she said,
but she does not believe that indecency should even be considered
in making grants. To her and others, the only grounds should be
artistic merit.
</P>
<P>
   After the court decision, she was besieged for comments and
decided to hold a news conference in the middle of a performance of
her current show, ``The Return of the Chocolate-Smeared Woman'' at
the Flea Theater in New York City. Emboldened by the theatricality
of that event, she said she may have more performance news
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Coincident with the decision, the House Appropriations Committee
voted in favor of financing the arts endowment. Ms. Finley's
analysis: ``The eight justices did not make a constitutional
decision. They made a decision purely based on politics. The result
was to keep the endowment, so it could continue not to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Miller recalled that he had faced charges of indecency
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both a long time ago,'' he said. ``In 1947 `All My
Sons' opened in Boston, and the Catholic Church condemned it
because of a line: `A man can't be a Jesus in this world.' They
forbade their members to see the play. When they forbade `All My
Sons,' around the corner was the raunchiest burlesque show of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second was when the Legion of Decency viewed `The Misfits'
before it was released and demanded certain changes. The main one
was the scene in which Marilyn Monroe in a fit of despair walks out
of the house and embraces a tree. That represented to them
masturbation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a continuing age-old universal argument between
decency and the human body. It goes on and on and on. This time
it's especially obnoxious. Certain kinds of art will always be
called indecent, and they need support.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   About Ms. Finley, Miller said: ``Anyone who smears herself with
chocolate needs all the support she can get. If she covered herself
in vanilla, they might not have been so outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   David Rabe, whose plays deal with challenging subjects (most
recently, in ``A Question of Mercy,'' with AIDS and assisted
suicide), said he felt uncomfortable about being represented in
this issue by performance artists, but he accepted that fact and
tried to place the decision in a larger context.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said the ruling was part of ``a juggernaut, a recent
manifestation of a fundamental hatred of art, of anything that does
not coddle the public, that is not entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not surprised by the decision: ``It's par for the
course. The whole argument is, let the marketplace decide. To
suggest that things should rise and fall on the marketplace is a
form of censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial shows that might be accused of bad taste would be
unaffected, because they do not receive public funds. Those who
would suffer are experimental artists who tackle difficult subjects
and need financial support in order to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Miller, another of the NEA Four, said that ever since the
case began eight years ago, his opportunities had decreased. He has
not been invited to perform at any university in the Southeast.
``People are cautious, and they are frank,'' he said. If they book
his show, ``they would be afraid of losing their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe suggested that Ms. Finley, as a performance artist with a
high profile, was being used as a target, but that the real aim was
far more complex and inclusive, and that many others would be
affected. These would include composers as well as authors, and
even artists from the past, as classics are brought into question.
</P>
<P>
   David Cole, the lawyer representing the four artists before the
Supreme Court, said he was disappointed in the result, but he took
a conciliatory position about the judgment. ``It's important to
acknowledge that the decision is not as bad as it appears,'' he
said. He indicated that he was heartened by the advisory aspect,
what Justice Antonin Scalia in his concurring judgment referred to
in a negative way as ``the gutting of the statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole did express his concern about the cultural and political
impact of the decision, saying: ``I likened the case to the battle
over academic freedom in the 1950s and '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright David Henry Hwang said that the chilling effect
of the decision was ``more a result of the cultural battle, the
right wing demonizing the NEA.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Cole, he took some comfort in the decision: ``All
things being equal, I would have been happy if the decency standard
had been declared unconstitutional. It's a bad decision, but it's
the one we have, and we have to figure out how to strategize. It's
important for the arts community to be vigilant. We as artists can
mitigate it somewhat by being aware of what's being turned down, on
a case-by-case basis. We can try to influence the process to make
it more favorable to artistic freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The painter Leon Golub said: ``One of the ways civilized
societies work in theory is by self-censorship. People who make the
decisions are usually sophisticated or subtle enough not to
provoke. Or if they want to provoke for political reasons, they
know how to stretch a point. Everyone knows how to play the game.
It's really pathetic: these congressmen and the Supreme Court are
responding in a frightened way to pressures being brought in our
culture by right-wing groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will make the decisions about standards of decency? Ann
Beeson, a lawyer for the American Civil Liberties Union, said she
worried that it might not even be people, but computer software.
She pointed to the proliferation of blocking software designed to
filter out pornography. It is on sale at computer stores, and more
expensive systems are available to libraries and other
institutions. These blockers are so inaccurate as to be, in her
word, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for words and images dealing with sexual matters, they
``block out certain kinds of art sites, including classic paintings
of nudes,'' Ms. Beeson said. ``They can't tell the difference
between pornographic pictures and Botticelli.''
</P>
<P>
   In what might be called Software of the Absurd, programs have
managed to block out the Quakers, the American Association of
University Women and the entire San Francisco Chronicle Web site,
Ms. Beeson said. She added that such software was sold under brand
names like Net Nanny and Surf Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Net Nanny is watching. If the Quakers are in jeopardy, what room
will there be for the Chocolate-Smeared Woman?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2026EDT &QL; 
