A6739 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHAT-WEBELIEVE-TEX     07-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-WE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE OF A SERIES ON WORLD RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
 BELIEVE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHURCH OF THE BRETHREN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEMBERSHIP: About 150,000 in more than 1,000 congregations in
the United States and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY: The Church of the Brethren developed as an outgrowth of
radical Pietism in early 18th-century Germany; in fact, much of the
group's theology and practice came from the Pietists of the 17th
and 18th centuries, who were mostly Lutherans unhappy with their
state church.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Brethren immigrated to the American colonies in the
1720s, and an American congregation was established in Germantown,
Pa., in 1723. Until the 20th century, the group's name was the
German Baptist Brethren.
</P>
<P>
   After coming to America, the Brethren were not opposed to urban
life, but most preferred farming and agricultural life. From the
1790s to the 1850s, congregations were established in Kentucky,
Ohio, Missouri, Illinois, California and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Brethren separated themselves from secular influences, opposed
slavery and wore distinctive, plain dress. The leaders they
selected were not paid and had no theological education, and all
Brethren agreed not to vote, take oaths or enter into lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Until the early 20th century, the Brethren were known as
``Dunkers'' because of their unusual practice of baptizing by
triple immersion: in the name of the Father, the Son and the Holy
Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Tension in the late 19th century caused a division in the
church, and three factions developed: the original group, ``old
order'' traditionalists and a progressive movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Brethren is one of the three historic ``peace
churches,'' along with the Mennonites and the Quakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Brethren opposed military service during the American
Revolution and Civil War; in following years, they were allowed to
avoid involvement in war efforts as conscientious objectors.
</P>
<P>
   The Brethren have made several changes this century. For the
most part, they no longer wear the plain dress they were known for,
and their leaders are now professional, salaried pastors. Women
became eligible for ordination in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEFS: The Church of the Brethren has historically resisted
creeds, but the Brethren focus on spiritual life and piety
developed through prayer, Bible study and association with fellow
believers. The church is not considered an organization that
formulates doctrine as much as it is a supportive group of people
who love God and one another.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY LIFE: The Brethren emphasize daily devotion, stewardship
and care for those less fortunate. The church opposes violence,
divorce and remarriage, as well as oath-taking, voting and
attention-getting or distracting dress.
</P>
<P>
   The love feast is the most significant feature of Brethren
worship. The communion service includes foot washing, a love meal
and the partaking of unleavened bread and wine or grape juice.
</P>
<P>
   The church is affiliated with six accredited liberal arts
colleges and a seminary in Indiana. The Brethren are best known
internationally for their relief and rehabilitation work in Europe
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Encyclopedia of American Religion and Handbook of
Denominations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
