r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASHPAY-COX     07-01 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASHPAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NationsBank launches CashPay program
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- NationsBank announced a payroll debit card Wednesday,
calling it ``a win-win proposition for all concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good deal for businesses and for the bank, because
electronic banking is much cheaper than making a transaction with a
teller.
</P>
<P>
   But it might not be such a good deal for the cardholders.
</P>
<P>
   CashPay cards are aimed at employees who don't have bank
accounts, a group that consists primarily of poor people.
Cardholders will have to pay to withdraw money, and might have to
pay charges that their employers had once paid.
</P>
<P>
   In launching the card, the Charlotte-headquartered banking
company is competing with check-cashing mills that in Georgia can
charge $5 or 5 percent of the value of the check, whichever is
higher.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank said the card makes it easier for people without
bank accounts to get their cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advantages of the CashPay debit card include 24-hour ATM
availability and the relief of employees without bank accounts from
having to provide IDs or, in some cases, fingerprints'' at
check-cashing outlets, said Julie Turner Davis, a NationsBank
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The debit cards can be used at ATM machines or point-of-sale
terminals. But each transaction costs $1.50 - and possibly another
$1.50 or more for using machines outside the NationsBank networks.
</P>
<P>
   A Consumer Federation survey of check cashers in 23 of the
largest urban areas found the average cost of cashing a paycheck
was 2.34 percent of the face value of the check, said Jean Ann Fox
of the Consumer Federation of America, based in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The range was 1 percent to 6 percent. So if you had a $320
paycheck, it would cost about $7.50 to cash the check (assuming a
2.34 percent charge),'' she said. ``And $1.50 is certainly cheaper
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox questioned why cardholders would have to pay a fee at
all to get their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the face of it, the employer should pay the cost of
delivering the paycheck, and not the employee paying the cost of
getting it, especially since the employee isn't getting any other
banking services,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this looks like is that the employer is shifting the cost
of issuing paychecks to the employee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have designed the product so that the employers could pick
up the fees if they so choose,'' said Linda Diehl marketing manager
of CashPay for NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs the government 44 cents to print, handle, and mail
federal checks,'' said Fox. ``There ought to be enough savings in
electronically delivering payroll checks, rather than printing and
mailing them, to cover the cost of access'' at an ATM machine.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, electronic banking is a big money saver. It costs banks
an average of 12 cents to do an electronic funds transfer, 20 cents
for a direct deposit, 60 cents for an ATM withdrawal, but $1.90 to
$2.30 for a teller withdrawal, said Kim Sutherland, director of
Atlanta-based Market Line Associates, a bank consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Processing electronic based transactions is certainly cheaper
than paper-based transactions,'' said James Smart, a senior vice
president at NationsBank. But he said the charges cover the costs
of direct-deposit, electronic processing, the ATM transaction, and
the cost of the account for non-bank customers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
