r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-MAIN02-COX     07-01 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-MAIN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E. coli toll hits 20
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna and Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- One additional case of infection with E. coli O157:H7
has brought the total count in the White Water outbreak to 20,
public health authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year-old boy from Cobb County who is hospitalized, but not
ill enough to require dialysis, was confirmed by lab tests as
another White Water case, said Dr. Paul Blake of the Georgia
Division of Public Health. The boy visited White Water on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a case that we had known about for a few days, but his
lab tests were pending,'' said Blake, chief of DPH's epidemiology
section.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic testing continues on the 13 cases in Georgia and 7 cases
in five other states. DNA profiles have been completed on five of
the earliest Georgia cases. State scientists hope that, when all
the genetic tests are done, they will be able to say definitively
which of the cases are linked to the White Water park, where
officials believe a child or children defecated in a kiddie pool on
June 11, 12 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   DPH personnel are also waiting for genetic fingerprints on four
other cases of E. coli O157, a potentially life-threatening strain
of a common bacteria. Those cases _ Mary Beth and Anna Dooley of
Hull, and two children from near Athens whom health authorities
decline to identify _ have no known link to the water park.
</P>
<P>
   Once the full range of tests on those cases are complete,
scientists will be able to tell whether the cases constitute a
separate cluster, or whether they are connected to the White Water
outbreak in some unexplained way.
</P>
<P>
   Among the flags that investigators will be watching for, he
said: Whether any of the infected children, in Athens or in the
White Water outbreak, have subsequently infected other children.
Because the incubation period for O157 _ the lag between infection
and the development of symptoms _ can last eight days, those cases
may be showing up in doctors' offices now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the current outbreak, six children with E. coli are
hospitalized at two metro children's hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Two girls, ages 4 and 2, are in critical condition at Scottish
Rite Medical Center, and a 3-year-old boy and a 10-year-old boy are
in fair condition, said hospital spokeswoman Kim Lathbury. And a
2-year-old boy is in fair condition and a 3-year-old boy is in good
condition at Egleston Children's Hospital, said hospital
spokeswoman Julie Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a spokesman for the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention said that even though no tainted burgers from Costco
were shipped to Georgia, consumers shouldn't be complacent.
</P>
<P>
   They still need to make sure they cook all hamburger meat until
the juice runs clear from the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger and any other ground meat from cattle should always be
cooked until the meat is no longer pink, said
</P>
<P>
   CDC spokesman Tom Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prevention goes way beyond the recall,'' he said. ``The bottom
line is they still need to cook their ground beef.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
