<SLUG> BC-STARBANK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star Banc Corp buys Firstar Corp.
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI -- Cincinnati-based Star Banc Corp. said Wednesday it
will buy Firstar Corp., based in Milwaukee, for stock worth about
$7.2 billion. The deal will create the 21st largest bank holding
company in the country, with assets of more than $38 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will have 720 branch locations (which
include branches from pending acquisitions of both companies), more
than 1,400 automated teller machines and offices in eight
Midwestern states and Arizona, plus trust operations in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after days of rumor and increased activity
on the stock market. The merger is expected to be completed
sometime in the fourth quarter, pending shareholder and regulatory
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Star Banc will shed its name and take on Firstar's name as well
as its headquarters in Milwaukee. However, consumer banking and
specialized lending operations will be based in Cincinnati. Firstar
chairman and chief executive Roger L. Fitzsimonds will become
chairman. Jerry A. Grundhofer, Star Banc's chairman, president and
chief executive will become president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Firstar shareholders will receive a tax-free exchange of 0.76
shares of common stock of the combined company for each share of
Firstar common stock, while Star Banc shareholders will retain one
share of common stock in the combined company for each Star Banc
share.
</P>
<P>
   Firstar stock (NYSE: FSR) closed Wednesday at 46, up 8 3/16.
Star Banc stock (NYSE: STB) closed at 63, down . Star Banc's
Wednesday's closing price represents a price of $48.35 for each
Firstar share in the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement Star Banc and Firstar said that ``some job
reductions are expected, primarily in headquarters and
administrative positions.'' How many Cincinnati positions will be
moved to Milwaukee, and how many overall jobs will be lost is
unknown, said Firstar spokesman Patrick Strickler. ``It is too
early for anybody to answer that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Star Banc's Community Development Initiative
would impact the new organization, Strickler deferred to another
company statement. ``Both companies are committed to achieving an
outstanding (Community Reinvestment Act) rating after the merger,''
it said.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year, $5.15 billion loan program was announced in
February to make more money available to low- and moderate-income
homeowners, small businesses and community development groups in
Ohio, Indiana and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Star Banc spokesman Steve Dale could not be reached for comment
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crabtree, an analyst with Dain Rausher in Minneapolis, said
the failure of Firstar's First Forward plan, a massive
restructuring effort, contributed greatly to the decision to merge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Firstar adopted the plan, they put themselves on the
line,'' Crabtree said. ``If they performed well and their stock
price was high, they would remain independent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Firstar fell short of its financial goals. ``The investment
community concluded since (Firstar) failed to deliver its promises
to shareholders, shareholders would demand that it be sold,''
Crabtree said.
</P>
<P>
   Star Banc and Firstar estimate that the merger will allow them
to reduce their expenses by $174 million, with half of this saving
achieved in 1999 and the remainder in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
