<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KY-SENATE-NYT &LR;      07-01 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KY-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT IN KENTUCKY SENATE RACE STRESSES CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ For years, Sen. Mitch McConnell, the archenemy
of campaign finance reformers, has insisted that their issue is
politically toothless.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the history of American politics has ever won or
lost a campaign on this issue,'' the Kentucky Republican declared
in February on the eve of the Senate vote that failed to end debate
on campaign finance legislation and probably blocked further Senate
action on the matter this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Democratic congressman is putting McConnell's view to a
stern test on his home turf.
</P>
<P>
   That Democrat, Rep. Scotty Baesler, is trying to make changes in
campaign law a central question in his race to win Kentucky's other
Senate seat in the November election. The issue has brought him to
prominence in the House this year after three terms of blending
into the back benches without much notice.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in Louisville on Monday night, Baesler told about 150
true believers that ``the most important subject in the country
today'' was campaign law that allows corporations and labor unions
to donate as much as they want to political parties and spend as
much as they please on political advertising.
</P>
<P>
   This money ``sets the agenda for Congress,'' Baesler declared.
``People who deny that have their head in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally was sponsored by Common Cause and the League of Women
Voters and was billed as a chance for Kentuckians to speak out on
campaign finance reform. All the state's candidates for the Senate
and the House of Representatives were invited, but only Baesler
showed up.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, chairman of the committee that raises money for
Republican Senate candidates across the country, who argues that
campaign finance ceilings inhibit free speech and who has led every
recent fight in the Senate against such limits, was derided as
public enemy No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler's Republican opponent in the Senate race, Rep. Jim
Bunning, was persuaded by McConnell to run this year for the seat
being left open by the retirement of Sen. Wendell Ford, a Democrat.
Bunning, a conservative Republican with a strong anti-abortion
stand, has not been outspoken on campaign finance but agrees with
McConnell that the law should remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   In response to an inquiry, Bunning issued this statement:
``Common Cause's agenda for so-called campaign finance reform is
more government and less individual freedom in political campaigns.
I believe that a healthy democracy deserves more speech, not
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Both national parties have made winning Ford's seat a top
priority this year. Party leaders here say the outcome is too close
to call, and handicappers in Washington put it in the tossup
category.
</P>
<P>
   A former captain of the University of Kentucky basketball team
and the mayor of Lexington for a decade, Baesler, 56, has been a
popular figure in this state for years. He has a country-boy
manner, an awkward gait and a quick smile. He clearly finds it
difficult to talk about himself, a trait unusual for a politician.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently his main claim to recognition in Washington
was as the only active tobacco farmer in Congress and a leading
House advocate of the cigarette manufacturers. When President
Clinton was in Lexington the day before the 1996 election, Baesler
pointedly skipped the appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's wrong on tobacco,'' the congressman said at the
time, ``and I'm very upset about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring Baesler stepped out of the pack. His opening came
when House Republican leaders structured the debate on campaign
finance legislation in such a way that no bill could pass without a
two-thirds majority and that, in any case, no vote could be taken
on one of the main bills favored by advocates of change.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler prepared what is known as a discharge petition on
campaign finance legislation, and he and his allies began
circulating it for signatures. Under the rules of the House, if
such a petition gets 218 signatures, a House majority, the issue in
question must be brought to the floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Discharge petitions are rarely successful. But this time, with
solid Democratic backing and the support of a small number of
Republicans who were embarrassed by their leadership's seeming
heavy-handedness, the number of signatures on the discharge
petition approached the magic number.
</P>
<P>
   That forced House Speaker Newt Gingrich to relent. The issue has
been returned to the floor for an off-and-on debate that began in
late May and shows no sign of conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler says that this time he expects his side will win in the
House. It is unclear whether he is right. The proponents of changes
in the law won on the first test vote, but dozens of votes on
hundreds of measures are still to come. House Majority Leader Dick
Armey has promised that the matter will be resolved by early
August.
</P>
<P>
   It is also unclear how important the issue will be in deciding
the Senate race here in November. A statewide poll by The
Courier-Journal in Louisville last year found that 4 of 5
Kentuckians believed that federal law should be changed to limit
campaign spending. But by the same proportion, those polled said
the campaign finance issue should not be a top priority for Clinton
and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally Monday night, Baesler scoffed at the idea that
voters do not care about the issue. Holding his palms a half-inch
apart, he said that ``I don't get that many letters in a month on
campaign finance reform'' but that he had not received that many
letters in a year on changing communications law, a step Congress
had managed to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the things we vote on, we don't hear from the
people,'' he said, ``but we do it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in an interview, Baesler said he was under no illusion
that the issue would sweep him to victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to make it an issue, and Mitch's central position
insures that it will be an issue,'' he said. ``But the election
won't turn on it alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
