<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALA-ELECT-ASSESS-ART-     07-01 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-ELECT-ASSESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ALABAMA'S GUBERNATORIAL RUNOFF REINFORCES SOME OLD
POLITICAL TRUTHS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ As a battle for the soul of Southern
Republicanism, the Alabama primary that Gov. Fob James Jr. won so
convincingly on Tuesday reinforced a number of truths about the
party and the region.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives still wield immense influence. Strong
stands against taxes still sell. Race still matters. And even as
Southerners take a leading role in national politics, they still
deeply resent federal intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   The results also buttressed another theme drawn from campaigns
around the country this year, including last month's spending spree
among Democrats in the race for California governor: money does not
always prevail.
</P>
<P>
   James was outspent by his opponent, Winton Blount III, a wealthy
Montgomery businessman, by more than two-to-one. By financing his
campaign heavily with loans from himself and his family, Blount
forced James to spend twice as much as the governor had originally
budgeted for the primary. But he also handed James an issue, and
the governor appealed to this poor state's populist sensibilities
by using television advertising to mock Blount's inherited wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those factors played a role in James' surprisingly
decisive victory over Blount in their hard-fought primary runoff.
With 99 percent of precincts reporting, James had 56 percent of the
vote to Blount's 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was a campaign that probed the inherent tensions in Southern
Republicanism, between the conservative Christians drawn to the
party, and James, by a deeply felt moral agenda, and the
business-oriented voters primarily concerned with the state's
economic interests. One of James' chief strategists was Ralph Reed,
the former executive director of the Christian Coalition.
Throughout the region and beyond, the primary and the ensuing
runoff became widely seen as a test of the power of the Christian
right, less than two years before the presidential primary season
begins.
</P>
<P>
   In the week before James' victory, polls showed the race to be a
dead heat. But the polls could not measure the enthusiasm of James'
support among white conservatives in rural and suburban counties.
Many of those voters were pulled to the polls by last-minute
mailings and telephone calls that emphasized the governor's
devotion to religious causes, like his protests against federal
court rulings prohibiting prayer in public schools and his defense
of a judge's decision to display the Ten Commandments on his
courtroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, for instance, the James campaign directed
three pieces of mail and three telephone calls to each of 90,000
households gleaned from lists of people who attended rallies
supporting Circuit Court Judge Roy Moore's stand on the Ten
Commandments, according to one of the governor's strategists. Many
of the fliers noted James' support from evangelical leaders like
Pat Robertson, Jerry Falwell and James Dobson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who didn't think before that religious conservatives
were not a big part of the electorate here and the backbone of the
Republican Party simply didn't understand Alabama,'' said Attorney
General Bill Pryor, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The polls also did not detect an apparent backlash against
Blount's endorsement last week by Mayor Richard Arrington Jr. of
Birmingham, a black Democrat who urged his supporters to cross over
and vote in the Republican runoff. An unusual provision allows
Alabama voters to participate in a Republican primary runoff
regardless of whether they voted or how they voted in the first
primary.
</P>
<P>
   James had pursued the mayor's endorsement himself. But when he
did not receive it, his strategists and allies encouraged the
backlash by arguing that Blount would be the captive of ``a liberal
Democratic political boss'' who had demanded a say on appointments
and spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Television advertisements and mailings produced by the James
campaign included photographs of Arrington. And a flier circulated
widely by a black newspaper publisher who supports James also
included a two-decade-old picture of an Arrington adviser, Donald
Watkins, with an Afro haircut that has long been shorn.
</P>
<P>
   James' strategists, who were jubilant about his unexpectedly
broad win, said that their ads were designed to raise questions
about Arrington's influence, and not his race. The same tactics
would have been used, they said, if Arrington were white.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of political scientists and strategists, including
many Republicans, said on Wednesday that the advertisements relied
on an implicit racial appeal and that they had worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about liberal special interest groups and run
pictures of Richard Arrington and Donald Watkins, it's pretty clear
which special interest group you're talking about,'' said Bradley
Moody, an associate professor of political science at Auburn
University. ``It's not labor unions and it's not the Alabama
Education Association.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Q. Whitfield Ayres, a Republican pollster from Atlanta who has
worked for candidates and lobbying groups in Alabama, said that the
endorsement by Arrington's Jefferson County Citizens Coalition
seemed to have increased the turnout in some Democratic precincts,
and that Blount had benefited from that vote. But he said that
those votes were more than offset by increases in rural and
suburban counties where white conservatives may have been motivated
to vote for James in reaction to the Arrington endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial indications are that the endorsement backfired,''
Ayres said. ``My sense is that Mr. Blount got on the wrong side of
a racial issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican strategist who has worked on several statewide
campaigns in Alabama put it even more bluntly. ``When you play the
race card in Alabama, it's over,'' the strategist said, speaking on
the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   James also played effectively, as he has throughout his
political life, to an almost visceral sentiment in Alabama's white
electorate _ a distaste for elites and outside authority. Several
analysts said on Wednesday that his jabs at the federal judiciary
and at critical newspaper editorial writers, whom he poked fun at
in his victory speech, appealed to his state's oft-wounded pride.
In his speech on Tuesday night, James spoke of ``a spirit that says
deep down I'm proud to be from Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Merle Black, an Emory University political scientist who has
written extensively on the Republican politics in the South, said
that James' ability to strike nativist chords was reminiscent of
former Gov. George Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the old Confederate thing of winning by losing,'' he
said. ``The important thing is making a stand against the odds.
Even if he's losing on these religious issues, it still works with
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Although concerned about the damage inflicted on James during a
prolonged and nasty primary, Republican leaders were ecstatic about
the record number of voters who were drawn to their primaries. With
few runoffs on the Democratic ballot, Tuesday's Republican race
attracted a stunning 455,000 voters, shattering the previous mark
of 359,000 Republican voters in the June 2 primary. That number, in
turn, had smashed the previous record of 215,000, set in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   James succeeded by expanding his margin of victory over Blount
in rural counties, and by minimizing his losses in cities like
Birmingham and Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's results set up a general election campaign between
James, 63, and Lt. Gov. Don Siegelman, 52, who easily won the
Democratic nomination four weeks ago. Siegelman, who has squirreled
away more than $3.5 million while James depleted his account,
wasted little time in opening a two-front offensive against the
governor on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He continued Blount's efforts to make the campaign a referendum
on James, describing him at a news conference as ``a do-nothing
governor.'' And he relentlessly promoted his plan to enact a state
lottery that would pay for college scholarships, pre-kindergarten
programs and classroom computers.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that education is by far the most important issue to
Alabama voters. But the lottery, like all forms of gambling, may be
a hard sell in a state where evangelical churches play such a
critical role in electoral politics. The governor opposes a
lottery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
