<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA SKINHEADS FACE CHARGES IN BEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - The four Lake Havasu City men taunted Carlos Durand
as a ``wetback'' in front of his three children, according to an
indictment released Wednesday. Then one of them hit Durand in the
head with a baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
   The four men, several of whom belong to a skinhead group called
Fourth Reich Skins, face federal felony charges of violating the
civil rights of Durand, a Mexican-American granted permanent
residence in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating a man with a baseball bat in front of his children
simply because he is Hispanic is vicious and inhumane,'' U.S.
Attorney Jose de Jesus Rivera said Wednesday. ``We will not
tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution of hate crimes ``is an extremely high priority for
this office,'' Rivera added.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the group accused in the January attack was Jason
Alvord, 19, who Mohave County law-enforcement officials say is
known for covering his body with tattoos, including several
swastikas and the word ``suffer.'' Alvord has been convicted of
theft in that Arizona county, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also charges Raymond Parisi, 18; Joseph Downen,
21; and Gary Wilkins, 34. Parisi and Wilkins lived in an apartment
next to Durand's at the time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Alvord and Wilkins also face state charges of aggravated assault
in the same incident. Parisi admitted participating in the attack
on Durand as part of his sentencing agreement in another case.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal indictment, Durand also endured several
previous instances of intimidation before he was clubbed, suffering
head injuries that had to be closed with medical staples. In one
instance, Alvord pointed a pellet gun at Durand and told him, ``I
have a gun right here and I ought to shoot you, wetback,'' the
indictment states.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment comes 15 months after three skinheads were
indicted on federal civil-rights charges in connection with a
cross-burning at the home of one of Lake Havasu City's few Black
families. The three later pleaded guilty and were sentenced to
federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mohave County Attorney Bill Ekstrom said Wednesday that the two
incidents do not indicate a broad pattern of racial intolerance in
his fast-growing county bordering the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have a problem of any great magnitude in the
county,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the skinhead presence, Ekstrom said, ``I think
there's some oddball group there (in Lake Havasu City). And I think
there are little, isolated groups that pick things off the
Internet.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
