<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      07-01 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS, SELES AND DAVENPORT ARE UPSET VICTIMS AT WIMBLEDON  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ It was another dry day at Wimbledon, except
for the tears shed by the three American women who failed to join
the defending men's champion, Pete Sampras, in the semifinals.
After their involuntary group exit in the women's quarterfinals
Wednesday, they put away their racquets and got out their
handkerchiefs.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of them, 18-year-old Venus Williams, also had a
screaming tantrum right on Center Court that conjured up images of
her personal hero, John McEnroe, at his boorish best. Or worst.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-seeded Williams became so furious over a trio of
suspect line calls that she added a hysterical oratory against the
umpire and officials to her usual power-hitting display. She posed
a significant threat, but ultimately failed in her bid to upset
third-seeded Jana Novotna, the 29-year-old two-time runner-up here.
Ultimately, Williams was unable to match Novotna's grass-court
experience, and found herself outserved and outvolleyed in the
ensuing tie breaker. She was vanquished, 7-5, 7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
   Novotna's net-rushing came as no surprise to her opponent. ``She
was really slicing and coming in, and basically she played the game
of someone who wants to get in to the net,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   And Williams was unapologetic about her ballistic behavior. ``If
I wasn't so dark, I probably would have turned red,'' she said,
jokingly. ``I think the crowd probably enjoyed my emotional
outbursts.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said her hysteria was not quite of McEnroe quality. ``I
don't think I would get that out of control, but I think everybody
enjoyed watching him go at it,'' she said. ``I think anyone can go
to that limit if they allow themselves to, but he would play
through it and play great tennis, and not everyone's able to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides revealing a petulant side, Williams showed she has a
future on the grass surface. But, as Novotna pointed out, it is not
here yet. ``You can imagine how desperate she was when she started
coming in even after second serves,'' Novotna said, ``and that's
what I wanted to do, be all over the net and put all the pressure
on her, because I knew that we will both be serving and volleying
and I'm sure I'll be better at that.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two Americans to depart Wednesday, second-seeded
Lindsay Davenport and sixth-seeded Monica Seles, left on quieter
notes after being upset by challengers who had had little or no
success against them in the past. The dying grass has a way of
germinating strange developments.
</P>
<P>
   After her 6-3, 6-3 loss to 16th-seeded Nathalie Tauziat, the
first Frenchwoman to reach a Wimbledon semifinal since Francoise
Durr in 1970, Davenport allowed herself a private two-minute crying
jag and then washed away her tears in the shower. Davenport had
dropped just one of her eight matches against the 30-year-old
Tauziat, but it was no coincidence that the sole defeat came here
in 1993 in their only previous meeting on grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this was her favorite surface,'' Davenport said, ``but
I didn't think she was going to be hitting her groundstrokes so
well. I got totally outplayed.''
</P>
<P>
   As did Seles. Returning for the first time in five years to the
only Grand Slam tournament she has never won, Seles was suddenly
bereft of a backhand and found herself upset, 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, by
unseeded Natasha Zvereva.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't put two points together today right from the start
of the match, and it never got better after that,'' said a
disgruntled Seles, whose best Wimbledon performance was reaching
the 1992 final. ``She rose to the occasion and I did just the
opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Zvereva used a 38-minute upset of Williams two
weeks ago at Eastbourne as fodder for her unprecedented singles
campaign here. In the second round, Zvereva, the quirky doubles
stylist, ambushed the seven-time champion Steffi Graf. Wednesday,
she reached her first Grand Slam semifinal by thwarting Seles with
a dizzying combination of slices and drop shots.
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva, who owns 20 Grand Slam doubles titles but has often
described herself as ``too lazy'' to go the distance in singles,
admitted her aspirations here were initially humble. ``I thought I
had a good shot to win the first round,'' said Zvereva, who, like
Tauziat, needed to trudge through 43 Grand Slam singles campaigns
before reaching a semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva's aspirations are decidedly less humble now. ``If I
carry on like I played today, I have a chance to win the whole
thing,'' said Zvereva, who has a 4-4 record against Tauziat. She
has already disregarded a 0-4 record against Seles and a 0-17
record against Graf.
</P>
<P>
   In the other women's quarterfinal, the defending champion,
Martina Hingis, ejected fifth-seeded Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, the
defending French Open champion, 6-3, 3-6, 6-3. The 17-year-old
Hingis expressed pleasant surprise at finding herself the youngest,
by a decade, of the four semifinalists. ``The older, the better, I
think,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, the dark-haired golden boy of Britain,
12th-seeded Tim Henman, staged the only upset, a 6-3, 6-4, 6-2
ouster of third-seeded Petr Korda. But considering Henman's
messianic sense of duty here, as well as the ankle sprain suffered
by Korda in the previous round, the result did not really qualify
as a shocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was pretty clinical in the way I took my
opportunities and never let him back into it,'' said Henman, who is
the first British man to reach the semifinals since Roger Taylor
did it 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the male losers were reduced to tears, Korda did
his share of whining. ``I couldn't move my ankle the proper way,''
he said, ``and I feel I have one of the best returns in the world,
but I can't really move, so I just gave him a lot of free points.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman, who banged in a 131-mile-an-hour serve, will face a
confident Sampras, a four-time Wimbledon champion, on Friday.
Sampras is 2-0 against Henman, and Wednesday he annihilated Mark
Philippoussis of Australia, 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 6-4, on Court One.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no complaints,'' said Sampras, who did not mind being
out-aced, 14-10, by Philippoussis. ``Everyone talks about the
serve, but the return of serve is the shot that's going to get you
to the final.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other men's semifinal, ninth-seeded Richard Krajicek of
the Netherlands and 14th-seeded Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia, two
masters of this surface, will trade aces. Ivanisevic, twice a
Wimbledon runner-up, had 29 aces in a 7-6 (12-10), 7-6 (7-5), 7-6
(8-6) decision against another Dutchman and a fellow lefty,
23d-ranked Jan Siemerink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my 11th Wimbledon, and actually it's the most fun this
year,'' Ivanisevic said, ``so maybe this is the year for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that would make Ivanisevic happier than winning
Wimbledon would be watching Croatia's soccer team win the World
Cup. ``I think the whole country would be drunk for the rest of the
year, including me,'' he said. ``I put the racquets in the
closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, the 1996 champion, advanced to his second Wimbledon
semifinal by defeating 65th-ranked Davide Sanguinetti of Italy,
6-2, 6-3, 6-4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-AD-COLUMN-600&AMP;A     07-01 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-AD-COLUMN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: LOOKING BEYOND JUNE CLEAVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miss Manners would not be amused.
</P>
<P>
   Women are buying jewelry with their own money. They are playing
professional basketball. And fewer are waiting for the wedding to
buy the house in the suburbs. To tap into this increasingly
lucrative consumer group, a growing number of companies are now
marketing directly to women products and services that were once
pitched almost exclusively to men. Companies that sell everything
from golf equipment to life insurance are more frequently using
advertising aimed solely at women to let them know they want their
business.
</P>
<P>
   Patek Philippe, the luxury watchmaker, for instance, saw a shift
in consumers' buying habits a couple of years ago when women began
to buy more of its expensive men's timepieces for themselves. That
prompted the conservative Swiss company to think differently about
how it communicated with women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in it enough to make it a focus of our advertising
worldwide,'' said Hank Edelman, the U.S. president of Patek, which
is based in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   So this year, Patek is spending half of its $15 million
marketing budget on promotions aimed at women, a 15 percent
increase from three years ago. And a primary focus of its approach
will be a print campaign focused on women for an $11,800 watch with
mechanical movement and dual time zones, features that until now
the company included only in men's watches.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which will appear in national newspapers and magazines
this fall, were created by Leagas Delaney in London. They represent
a departure from Patek's usual method of featuring jeweled watches
on the arms of the ladies-who-lunch set. In one of the new ads, a
woman in jeans is teaching her daughter to ride a bike. It carries
the slogan ``Begin your own tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at where the greatest potential growth is, and there
is a whole segment of the population that has not had an interest
in things like this that were thought of being traditionally
masculine,'' Edelman said. ``Younger women and working women have a
greater range of interests.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the 20-somethings are erasing the lines
between traditional male and female roles (think WNBA and the
Citadel). And with the aging of baby boomers comes a generation of
women now in their peak earning years who, more than ever, are
making the financial decisions in their households.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are buying houses by themselves, and women are buying
all kinds of other products that before had been sold to a dual
audience,'' said Anne Marshall, a partner at Women Trend, a
consulting firm in Washington that is part of Holman
Communications. Even so, she said, she has a sense that far too
many ads are still right out of the June Cleaver era.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not just a matter of putting women in a spot anymore,''
Ms. Marshall said. ``The point is finding messages that will
resonate with reality and are not condescending. A lot of them are
just plain rude, where they say, `You are not the bride and you are
not this.' What does that have to do with running shoes?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, nothing. But marketers are making progress, according to
Advertising Women of New York, an industry group. ``When we started
to look at what marketers were doing who were successful, we found
a number in categories not traditionally marketing to women who
were doing very well,'' said Toni Lee, a spokeswoman for the group.
</P>
<P>
   The group points to Nike Inc. and John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co., for instance. John Hancock has been focusing on
single parents and working women with two series of ads on cable
television channels.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Hancock has gone from talking to men and women in general to
talking to a very specific segment of women whose financial needs
happen to be even more critical because of their situation,'' said
Karen Kaplan, a vice president who oversees the Hancock account at
Hill, Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos, a unit of Interpublic Group of
Cos. in Boston. ``We are trying to communicate an understanding of
their unique needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency is working on a new series of ads to be added to the
campaign under the original slogan ``Insurance for the unexpected.
Investments for the opportunities.'' The new spots are expected to
hit the market in the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nike is also expanding its focus on the women's market, and
recently started a series of commercials tied to the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had a lot of `Go women,' inspirational kind of
stuff,'' said Kathryn Reith, a company spokeswoman. ``So what we
did this summer is really sort of focus on what we think is special
about the league, and that is the relationship between the players
and fans.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's spots, which began running last month on NBC, part
of General Electric Co.; Walt Disney Co.'s ESPN, and the Lifetime
cable network, will run through August and feature young girls
interacting with the league's stars. The message? ``This is what
you should be doing with your game,'' Ms. Reith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things it does is really help to continue to tie us
to performance athletic gear,'' she said of the commercials, which
were created by Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners, a unit of Omnicom
Group in San Francisco. ``Certainly we've seen a growth of the
visibility of the players, which we hope will spill over into
product sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to tap into the growing number of women taking part in
another sport, Arnold Palmer Golf Co. has created a line of women's
golf equipment called Nancy Lopez Golf. The company began a
campaign to market the product line in April, and plans to expand
the campaign this fall to include national television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company has invested significant seven figures on this
whole endeavor,'' said Cindy Davis, Palmer's president. The print
ads, created by a San Diego graphic design firm, Miriello Grafico,
are running in national women's golf magazines under the slogan
``Defining the women's game.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, ``as companies are realizing they are valuable
consumers, we are taking it more seriously both in the funding we
put behind a brand as well as the way we communicate to that
consumer,'' Ms. Davis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
