<SLUG> BC-DANCING-BARD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKESPEARE MAKES BEAUTIFUL MUSIC _ AND DANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Vernon doesn't shy away from translating other art forms
into dance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the New York-based choreographer gave local audiences
``Arc and Point,'' a ballet inspired by paintings of Vassily
Kandinsky, which were on exhibit at the time at the Amon Carter
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he has taken on Shakespeare in ``The Heart of Man,'' which
premiered in June in Fort Worth as part of Ballet Concerto's annual
outdoor summer concert.
</P>
<P>
   During the rest of the year, the small professional company
specializes in outreach performances for schoolchildren. ``The
Heart of Man'' began when Ballet Concerto director Margo Dean asked
for something she could perform in schools, Vernon explains. ``At
first, I wanted to do `Hamlet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Vernon had already choreographed versions of ``Romeo and
Juliet'' and ``Twelfth Night'' for the Eglevsky Ballet company on
Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Hamlet'' was the starting point, Vernon eventually
decided to make a less specific ballet inspired by Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The title, Vernon says, comes from a comment by Verdi that
``Shakespeare was the greatest authority on the heart of man.'' The
music for the ballet comes from Handel.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting work, about 20 minutes long, presents characters
from various plays of Shakespeare, as well as Queen Elizabeth I,
the ``Dark Lady'' of the sonnets _ and Shakespeare himself.
</P>
<P>
   There are some recognizable scenes from the plays, including a
three-minute condensation of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Several ideas from the age of Shakespeare also inspired Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck by how the acting companies of the time were
built like ballet companies of today,'' the choreographer says.
``You had certain people always doing the same sort of role: One
actor always did a prince, another always did an old person.''
</P>
<P>
   Vernon was also inspired by the acting he saw at England's
National Theater and Royal Shakespeare Company when, many years
ago, he worked there as a personal assistant. He saw, up close, the
Shakespearean performances of Anthony Hopkins _ ``before he was
famous'' _ and Laurence Olivier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done this ballet as a tribute,'' he says. ``These
performances still stick in my mind. In the right hands,
Shakespeare is still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE IN BALLET AND MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   The Shakespeare-inspired ballet ``The Heart of Man'' is only the
most recent of dozens of ballets based on the Bard. And composers
have for generations been inspired to create tone poems, operas and
musical settings of texts from the plays and sonnets. Here are some
highlights:
</P>
<P>
   ``Romeo and Juliet'' has always been a favorite, inspiring a
choral symphony by Berlioz, an opera by Gounod and the beloved
concert overture by Tchaikovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Verdi was the most successful composer of operatic Shakespeare
settings, creating a ``Macbeth'' early on in his career, followed
by two operatic masterpieces, ``Otello'' and ``Falstaff.''
</P>
<P>
   19th-century German composer Otto Nicolai had his one big
success with an operatic version of ``The Merry Wives of Windsor.''
</P>
<P>
   French composer Ambroise Thomas is remembered mainly for his
``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlioz's numerous Shakespeare-inspired works include the
oft-overlooked opera ``Beatrice et Benedict,'' based on ``Much Ado
About Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendelssohn's ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' started out as a
free-standing overture for concert performance, then was expanded
into a complete suite of incidental music for performance with the
play, then went back into the concert hall. The ``Wedding March''
from that suite was for many years the traditional recessional at
weddings in America, and the same music was the basis for a ballet
by George Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century, ``Macbeth'' indirectly inspired
Shostakovich's shocking ``Lady Macbeth of the Mtensk District,''
which drew Stalin's ire.
</P>
<P>
   British composers continued to turn to Shakespeare for
inspiration: Elgar produced a monumental symphonic poem, much
beloved by British audiences, on ``Falstaff;'' Benjamin Britten
produced an inspired operatic version of ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream;'' and Ralph Vaughan Williams composed one of the most
ravishingly beautiful of all Shakespeare-inspired works, his
``Serenade to Music,'' a choral setting of the text of the garden
scene of ``The Merchant of Venice.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``Romeo and Juliet'' inspired Prokofiev to write one
of the greatest of all ballet scores, which contains almost three
hours of music, allowing the choreographer to set virtually every
scene of the play.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
