</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-CRIME-DECLINE-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC CRIME CONTINUES TO FALL; REPORTED MURDERS AT 32-YEAR LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Violent crime in this city continued its historic
six-year decline during the first half of 1998, according to police
statistics released Wednesday, as the number of reported murders
fell to the lowest level since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the statistics for the first six months of 1997,
murders this year have dropped 24 percent. The number of reported
robberies, burglaries and other serious felonies declined less
sharply, falling 10 percent compared with the first six months of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past four years, New York City has been transformed
from the crime capital of the world to the safest large city in the
United States,'' said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani at a news conference
with Police Commissioner Howard Safir at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said there were 286 murders listed in the city
between Jan. 1 and June 30, a 24 percent decrease from the same
period last year, and a huge decline from the 1,081 homicides
reported during the first half of 1991. If crime continues at the
same pace through December, the city will record its fewest number
of homicides since 1963, when there were 549 murders reported, city
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The only major felony to show an increase in the first half of
this year was rape, which rose by 0.6 percent compared with the
first half of 1997. Safir attributed that to far more reporting of
acquaintance rapes, a category of crime that before the late 1980s
was far less likely to result in a criminal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of those rapes would not have been reported in the past
because people did not have the confidence that they would be
treated with sensitivity and anonymity,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every state and city in the nation has seen decreases in
crime during the last five years, a trend some criminologists have
attributed to changing demographics, a drop in cocaine use and
stricter sentencing laws.
</P>
<P>
   But New York's crime reduction has been steeper and more
consistent than in most other cities, notably with homicides, which
dropped to 749 last year after peaking in 1991 at 2,262. Overall,
crime began to ebb in 1992, when reported felonies fell by 15
percent, and has continued to fall ever since.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   City officials and many law enforcement officers have credited
an emphasis on more aggressive policing, begun by the previous
commissioner, William Bratton, for sustaining that improvement, and
the mayor said Wednesday that the drop in crime may now be fueling
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the police force has swelled to nearly 40,000
officers, Safir said, because of the 1993 merger of the transit and
housing police departments with the main police force and because
of the Safe Streets-Safe City tax increase enacted by the Dinkins
administration to finance additional officers. With the steady drop
in crime, those officers have been able to devote more time to
deterring the remaining lawlessness, the officials said. Detectives
were able to solve more than 83 percent of reported homicides last
year _ the highest percentage on record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more homicide detectives working on 70 percent fewer
murders,'' Giuliani said. ``That means they can be a lot more
effective in the work that they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said he planned to continue devoting police resources to
the department's anti-drug initiatives, which seek to drive out
narcotics dealers by saturating high-crime neighborhoods with city
officers and federal agents. The initiatives, which were first used
in north Brooklyn, have been expanded into northern Manhattan and
parts of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Safir also singled out the work of the Police Department's
street crime unit, which seizes illegal handguns, and said its
officers had helped reduce the number of shooting incidents from
2,500 in the first half of 1993 to fewer than 1,000 during the
first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani said the crime reductions had brought heavy
declines in crime in virtually every neighborhood, cutting across
ethnic, racial and class lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just happening in the poor sections of the city or
the middle-class section of the city or the more affluent sections,
if you want to describe it that way,'' he said. ``In fact, the
violent crime decline is happening much more dramatically in the
less affluent sections of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Although police officials faced outraged criticism on several
occasions this year when narcotics officers mistakenly raided the
homes of law-abiding citizens, the mayor said the Police Department
had no intention of reducing drug raids and might set a new record
for narcotics arrests this year. Giuliani said that when he took
office in 1994, patrol officers were not allowed to make narcotics
arrests unless a supervisor was present, and that as a result, drug
dealers operated openly in many city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we take the drug dealers off of the streets as much as
possible,'' Giuliani said, ``and it sends a very positive message
to the young people in these neighborhoods. Namely, that drug
dealers don't control the streets. Being a drug dealer is a very
bad way to run your life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
