u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-INDONESIA-S     07-01 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUHARTO WORKING TO PRESERVE FAMILY'S WEALTH, POLITICAL INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Suharto, the former president of Indonesia, is
maneuvering to re-establish a political power base to shield his
family's financial empire from scrutiny by future governments,
according to Clinton administration officials and Western
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   There is no direct evidence that the Suharto family has tried to
bribe political or military leaders, the officials say. But they
add that Suharto and his six children are offering to underwrite
the political campaigns of legislators who vow loyalty to the
family, which has a fortune in the billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and diplomats agree that Suharto does
not appear to be seeking reinstatement as president. He resigned in
May after tens of thousands of demonstrators took to the streets of
Indonesia's largest cities demanding his ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they say, intelligence reports reaching the CIA, the
State Department and the Defense Department show that he is making
use of his riches and his ties to the military to help his children
retain their businesses and their top posts in the ruling political
party, at a time when the political moorings of Indonesia are
fraying.
</P>
<P>
   Next week the party, known as Golkar, is holding a special
national congress to pick new leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto remains chairman of the party's board of patrons, and
two of his children have been appointed to the seven-member
organizing committee for the congress. Four of his children are
members of the nation's highest legislative body, the People's
Consultative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   That Suharto, 77, retains close ties to the military, the
nation's most powerful institution, was in evidence in June when he
accompanied several powerful army generals to Islamic prayers held
in military mosques in Jakarta, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suharto has been very active, rounding up support wherever he
can find it,'' said a senior Clinton administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Another administration official said Suharto ``knows that he
can't be president again, but he is going to make sure that his
kids and his cash survive whatever comes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daniel Lev, a professor of political science at the University
of Washington and an expert on Indonesia, said the Suhartos ``are
doing what comes very naturally: they have the wherewithal to buy
political support, and I suspect that is in fact what they are
trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent collapse of the Indonesian currency, the
Suharto family is still widely believed to be among the richest on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   After his resignation on May 21, Suharto went into seclusion for
a few weeks, rarely emerging from his Jakarta home and seeing few
visitors apart from his six children. He was reported to be
depressed and shocked at his ouster after 32 years of iron-fisted
rule.
</P>
<P>
   But Western diplomats in Jakarta and administration officials
with access to intelligence reports say that his isolation is over
and that he has worked aggressively behind the scenes to restore
his contacts with political, military and religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Suharto would seek a return to public life _ and
might even try to take power again as president with the help of
the army _ have swirled through Jakarta virtually since the day he
stepped down. Military leaders have been forced to make public
statements denying that they are helping him return to power.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Gen. Wiranto, the armed forces
commander, acknowledged that he and other senior military officers
remained ``close'' to Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   But Wiranto insisted that that situation does not ``imply the
existence of secret or hidden ties,'' nor the suggestion that the
military would help Suharto return to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto was succeeded by his vice president, B.J. Habibie. While
Habibie was considered a protege of the former president, it is
unclear what sort of relationship exists between the two.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks Habibie has taken some actions that appear to be
favors to his predecessor, including his decision last month to
dismiss Attorney General Sujono Atmonegoro after Atmonegoro
announced that he was organizing an investigation of the
unexplained wealth of former government officials, apparently
including Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   But other actions by Habibie appear to be snubs, including his
order this week to expel several of Suharto's closest friends from
the Legislature, including Bob Hasan, a timber tycoon who is
Suharto's favorite golfing partner and who helps manage the former
president's fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Suharto recently requested a
secret meeting with Abdurrachman Wahid, the leader of a
30-million-member Muslim society in Indonesia and the nation's most
influential religious leader. While the purpose of the meeting was
not known, the officials presume it had political overtones. Wahid
has been close in the past to Suharto's eldest daughter, Siti
Hardijanti Rukmana. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2042EDT &QL; 
