<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDMAIN-COX     07-01 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDMAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `We want to know the truth'
 &HT;    By Sophia Lezin and Doug Nurse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- On the day he buried his 3-year-old son, Woon Oh's
grief was mixed with compassion for the woman who, police say, left
the boy in a sweltering van for 2 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's suffering enough now,'' Oh said Wednesday. ``We're
trying to forgive her but we want to know the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh also said his wife, worried that the day care van had not
returned their son, Samuel, on Monday afternoon, called the center
for half an hour, leaving a message on the answering machine and
even paging the owner before she reached someone.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not questioned Eun Shin Cho, owner of Kids
and Kids Academy on Lawrenceville Highway in Tucker, because she
has been under a doctor's care since the Monday incident. Cho
reportedly had a close relationship to the child and has been
grief-stricken, said Sgt. Jeff Sligar.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators said complaints have been filed against Kids
and Kids Academy, but they have refused to disclose the nature of
the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Oh and his wife, Choonhee Kim, visited the center a month ago
and were impressed because it offered transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Before attending Kids and Kids, Samuel had been cared for by a
woman along with three other children in her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Oh and Kim thought sending the tot somewhere with more children
would improve his social skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it better to move him to the large environment (so
he could) make more friends,'' Oh said. ``He was so shy, but he was
so bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he didn't speak English well, his parents also felt
Samuel would be more comfortable at a center that catered to
Korean-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of liked the atmosphere,'' Oh said. ``We decided my
son would go to that day-care center.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first week, Samuel would cry when the center's van
arrived to take him to day care. ``But afterward, he got used to
it,'' Oh recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel would rather spend time looking at books than playing
with other children, and he could already read simple words, like
red and yellow. He especially enjoyed riding trains and playing
with toy trains. Last Saturday, Oh said he took Samuel to the
Southeastern Railroad Museum on Buford Highway in Duluth, but it
was closed when they arrived, so they went to Stone Mountain and
rode trains there.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel's intelligence was apparent to Oh's friends at Georgia
Tech, where he is pursing a doctorate in civil engineering. They
would often see the boy writing the alphabet and the names of his
friends during their visits.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from their 7-month-old son, Daniel, the couple has no
family in the area. Oh's college friends have been staying
overnight, cooking and cleaning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Samuel died, his mother was worried because the day
-care center hadn't dropped him home at 2:30 p.m., as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother fretted for an hour and stood outside waiting
for another 30 minutes before calling the day-care center. She
reached someone at 4:30 p.m., Oh said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives suspect that Samuel may have climbed onto the van
without the owner knowing, Sligar said. Day-care center workers
drive children home along a regular route every afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When his mother called, one employee looked in the van, which
was parked outside the Korean First Presbyterian Church just up the
road on Lawrenceville Highway. The center had borrowed the church
van because their own vehicle was having mechanical trouble, Sligar
said.
</P>
<P>
   The worker smashed the window with a brick to reach Samuel, and
then called 911. Paramedics and doctors worked for an hour to
revive him, but he died of heart failure brought on by heat
exhaustion, Sligar said.
</P>
<P>
   Police probably will not file any charges in the case, but when
the investigation is finished it will be sent to the district
attorney, who will decide whether to seek an indictment, Sligar
said.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Danny Porter said Wednesday that until he sees
the evidence, probably next week, he won't know whether the facts
would justify presenting it to a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The father said he had to charge the funeral on his credit card.
In the hours before the service, Oh said he and his wife are still
in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't believe it,'' Oh said. ``We feel like he's still
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
