<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUG-ANCIENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCIENT JUG MAKES ITS WAY HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GORDY HOLT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Thanks to a couple of heads-up Goodwill Industries
employees, a 3,500-year-old jug from the Middle East has worked its
way off its Seattle Goodwill store shelf and back to its keeper at
the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got it in November,'' said Randy Jones, the Goodwill
employee who found it while sorting through donations. ``It was
unloaded off a truck with a bunch of other household items. It came
in a box with a hand-written message on it that said something
like, `This is the box from 1,500 B.C.' and `Do you want it?' or `I
think you'd like it,' I forget which.''
</P>
<P>
   The name of a museum _ the University of Chicago's Oriental
Institute _ also was written on the box, along with what looked
like catalog numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that inside the box was a jug about 4 inches high
made of tan clay and wrapped in heavy cotton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put it on a shelf and kind of forgot about it,'' Jones said
yesterday, after an Associated Press report out of Chicago informed
the world that, after being missing for 55 years, the little brown
jug had been returned.
</P>
<P>
   Short on money during World War II, the museum launched a loan
program to raise money. The jug was loaned to a Seattle native,
Forest C. Dana, then a professor at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Museum registrar Ray Tindel in Chicago said Dana likely
contributed $25 to $50 to use the item. He estimated the value
today at no more $100 because many like it have been found.
However, it could provide valuable clues about life in Armageddon
3,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't sure what the juglet was used for,'' Tindel said.
``We found from that period lots of large storage jars right down
to small pieces like this one. There is some thought that the small
ones were used to dip out contents from the big ones, which were
too big to pour from.''
</P>
<P>
   What became of the jug after it was loaned is not known.
</P>
<P>
   The artifact's return to Chicago occurred several months ago
after Jones remembered what he had left on a shelf and brought it
to the attention of Dennis Grosek, who runs Goodwill's auction
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis contacted the university, and that's how we got it back
to them,'' Jones said. ``I'm kind of glad it's there now and not in
some attic or on somebody's coffee table.''
</P>
<P>
   The object's Seattle-area contributor has not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the tiny container looked as nondescript as most
bric-a-brac that floods through Goodwill's sorting warehouse daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing this one was in a box with some writing on
it,'' he said, ``or it might have gone out in the store for
resale.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the AP account, the jug was discovered by British
archaeologist P.L.O Guy on June 27, 1926, in a dig at Megiddo,
southwest of Haifa in what then was Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   Located at the crossroads of two ancient military and trading
routes, the site is frequently mentioned in the Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This report containes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
