<HEADER>
A6768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASS-TEACHERS-NYT &LR;      07-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH PASSING GRADE RAISED, NEARLY 60 PERCENT OF WOULD-BE TEACHERS
FLUNK TEST  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Flip-flopping mightily, the Massachusetts Board of
Education raised the passing grade Wednesday for teacher
certification exams and thereby flunked nearly 60 percent of the
prospective teachers who took the state's first such tests this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The vote capped two weeks of political storm that, national
education experts say, appeared to be the biggest fuss over a
state's introduction of teacher exams in years, possibly since
Arkansas tried it under a young governor named Bill Clinton in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts is not just any state, though it is tardy in
being the 44th to start testing would-be teachers for basic
competency. It prides itself on its intellectual riches and boasts
that it has the highest number of colleges and universities per
capita in the country. Moreover, Massachusetts is in the midst of a
lively campaign for governor in which educational reform already
figures as a prominent issue.
</P>
<P>
   So when word came in mid-June that only about 40 percent of the
nearly 1,800 test-takers had scored above the equivalent of a D on
the eight-hour exam, the disturbing scores prompted a
finger-pointing-fest at targets from the State House to the
colleges that train would-be teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The situation became even more charged when Frank Haydu 3d, the
state's interim commissioner of education, proposed that a lower
standard be applied that would allow 56 percent rather than 41
percent to pass, and the State Board of Education went along,
citing in part the desire to avoid lawsuits from disappointed
test-takers.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Thomas Finneran, the Democratic speaker of the
State House of Representatives, criticized what he called
``idiots'' who could not define what a noun or a verb was, or the
word ``imminent.'' Rivals accused the Republican acting governor,
A. Paul Cellucci, who is running for re-election, of abdicating
responsibility for educating the Commonwealth's children. U.S. Sen.
John Kerry, D-Mass., called the Board of Education's vote a blow to
educational reform.
</P>
<P>
   It was appalling to many that so few graduates of education
programs could answer questions like ``What is a preposition?''
Last Friday, Cellucci struck back. He announced that he would ask
the Board of Education, whose nine members are mainly appointed by
the governor's office, to reverse their decision and raise the
passing grade back to a C, meaning an additional 263 people would
flunk. And he proposed a bill that would require competency testing
not only for would-be teachers but for all current ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every parent I talked to said, `We want the high standards,'
'' Cellucci said Wednesday in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I said at the Board of Ed meeting,'' he added, ``I started
off quoting John Kennedy when he said 36 years ago: `We choose to
go to the moon and do other things, not because it's easy but
because it's hard.' And no one ever said improving our public
schools would be easy. It is hard. There will be controversy and
there will be conflict and there will be stumbles, but if we stick
with it, we'll get there, and the best way to get there is to hold
the line on standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding the line will have costs, it appears. On Monday, Haydu,
the interim education commissioner who had backed the lower
standards, announced his resignation, saying he was not cut out for
campaign-season politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm naive as to what the governor's race was all about,'' he
said Wednesday as he left the Board of Education meeting for what
he described as a long vacation.
</P>
<P>
   And opposition to the higher passing grade is still brewing, as
was evident at Wednesday's meeting, where most of the guests who
spoke before the panel's 6-to-1 vote backed the lower standards and
denounced the ``teacher-bashing'' brought on by the test results.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Balboni, a would-be teacher who took the test but, like all
the other candidates, has yet to receive his results, denounced the
board's vote and re-vote as ``based on the swing of the political
pendulum.'' He pointed out that in schools, when a whole class does
poorly on a test, the teacher assumes there was a problem with the
test itself, and grades it on a curve.
</P>
<P>
   Others cited the critical problem that teacher candidates found
out only a week before they took it that it was not just an
experiment and would actually determine whether they were
certified. And still others question whether the test is an
accurate predictor of classroom performance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some members of minority groups scored worse than
whites, which could also be the basis for lawsuits. Lawyers with
experience in issues of testing say some suits in connection with
the teacher tests are almost certain to arise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
