<HEADER>
A6770 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUS-GINGRICH-TEX     07-01 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-GINGRICH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, GINGRICH TARGET HISPANIC VOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, U.S. House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and the Republican Party courted Hispanic activists
Wednesday by stressing education, free trade and lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got a warm welcome from the League of United Latin American
Citizens; Gingrich's reception was lukewarm. Some Texas convention
delegates, saying Gingrich has never supported Hispanics, refused
to listen to the Georgia Republican's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gingrich, who are considered presidential prospects in
the year 2000, both waded into the luncheon crowd of about 1,000
but on opposite ends of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found it is much easier to work in the spirit of unity,''
said Bush, who delivered parts of his speech in Spanish. ``I can't
stand the politics of divisiveness, politics that tends to pit one
group against another.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gingrich were keynote speakers on the first day of the
national LULAC convention at the Dallas Hyatt Regency. LULAC is the
nation's oldest Hispanic civil rights organization. It has about
110,000 members in 45 states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the Republican Party are making a strong pitch for the
Latino vote in November. How this increasingly influential minority
decides to vote may help decide several crucial state and
congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   Never a monolithic voting bloc, Hispanics usually support
Democratic candidates. But they also identify with some socially
conservative GOP issues, such as the strong stance against
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on education Wednesday, Bush trumpeted a pilot program
on public school vouchers, something LULAC opposes. He stood by the
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test, which some say is biased
against Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   But on the lightening rod issue of bilingual education, Bush
advocated reviewing and repairing the state's $130 million-a-year
bilingual program, not ending it.
</P>
<P>
   English should be emphasized, but Spanish would not be expelled,
the governor said. Bush dubbed the concept ``English plus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bilingual programs serve to teach our children English,
then we ought to say, `Thank you very much,' and leave them in
place,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if the bilingual program locks someone into Spanish and
does not achieve state objectives, then we must say, `Change the
program; eliminate the program,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Distancing himself from some in the GOP, Bush advocated open
trade with Mexico and spoke out against any measure that would
effectively build a wall, including military patrols along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strong and healthy Mexico is not only good for Texas, it is
good for America. And we better make sure we do not have policy and
rhetoric that will wall Mexico off from America,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush opposed Gingrich-led attempts to make English
the nation's official language. Bush also said it's unwise not to
educate undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
   From the crowd came cries of ``We love you.'' Bush returned
their affection in Spanish by saying, ``Te Amo.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich joked that appearing at a LULAC convention is not the
first place he expected to be. He followed Bush to the podium and
praised several of his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich never directly addressed bilingual education or
immigration, although he did say that every child should graduate
knowing two languages. Instead, he portrayed the
Republican-controlled Congress' balanced budget and efforts to cut
taxes as Latino-friendly issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a moral obligation as a people to try and reach out to
every neighborhood in Texas and across the country'' Gingrich said.
``I came here today to say my door is open. We want to work with
you...''
</P>
<P>
   He also repeated a proposal to return $70 billion in federal
budget surpluses to workers in the form of rebates for payroll
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's biggest applause came when he said the United States
shares the blame for its illegal-drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in talking about bashing Mexico on drugs or
bashing Colombia ... or Bolivia on drugs,'' he said. ``The primary
problem with drugs in the world today is the American market buying
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in LULAC's Texas delegation were not happy Gingrich was
invited to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never shown the Hispanic community any kind of
support,'' said Margaret Mata of Fort Worth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
