<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-MISSILES-NYT &LR;      07-01 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MISSILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LIMITS SATELLITE WORK BY SON OF CHINESE GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-MEDIA, CHINA-NOTEBOOK,
CHINA-HILLARY-CLINTON, CHINA-EX-OFFICIAL, HONGKONG-AIRPORT) 
(th) 
 By JEFF GERTH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the Clinton administration continues to
re-examine whether to allow a $650 million satellite sale to a
Chinese-controlled company, the State Department has blocked the
son of a Chinese general from working on the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Shen Jun, the son of Lt. Gen. Shen Rongjun, is a manager in
Southern California at Hughes Space &AMP; Communications, the
manufacturer of the powerful commercial satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department issued a license in 1996 allowing the
younger Shen, a Canadian citizen, to work as an interpreter in
connection with design talks about the satellites with the
customer, a consortium with close ties to the Chinese military.
</P>
<P>
   But the license was suspended last week, while Congress presses
questions about the role of the United States in China's rocket and
satellite projects. Officials are examining Shen's role in the
project as well as the capabilities of the sophisticated
satellites, which are to be the cornerstone of a commercial mobile
phone network planned for China and 21 other Asian countries but
which also could be used to eavesdrop on thousands of phone calls
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided, for now, to suspend a munitions license for
Hughes that permits a Chinese foreign national to perform
interpretation services for Hughes in nonsensitive areas of its
civilian satellite program,'' said James Rubin, a State Department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has asked Hughes for additional information
to determine if Shen's work ``was within the scope of the
license,'' Rubin said. The license for Shen could be reinstated or
permanently revoked after the State Department completes its
review.
</P>
<P>
   Shen can still work at Hughes on matters unrelated to the State
Department license.
</P>
<P>
   A Hughes spokeswoman said the company was cooperating with the
State Department's request for information on Shen.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's close scrutiny of the satellite deal and
Shen's license has become part of a U.S. Customs Service
investigation into the help that Hughes and another satellite
maker, Loral Space &AMP; Communications, provided to Chinese rocket
experts in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of the license for Shen was partly prompted,
according to Rubin, by ``information that has recently been brought
to our attention that has not yet been published.''
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said the information came from the
Pentagon and intelligence reports.
</P>
<P>
   The current examination contrasts sharply with the cursory
review by the Clinton administration in 1996 when it approved an
earlier version of the satellite deal as well as a license for
Shen, according to officials and documents.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department was unaware of the background of Shen's
father when it issued the license in 1996, officials said. Gen.
Shen oversees his country's military satellite and rocket programs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, neither the CIA nor the Defense Intelligence Agency,
which tracks the Chinese military and usually screens export
licenses, were involved in the 1996 satellite license reviews, even
though the Hughes application listed a Chinese military entity as
one of the owners of the consortium buying its satellite, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hughes-Shen relationship dates to 1994, when Gen. Shen
visited Hughes officials in California. His son, then a computer
instructor in Canada, joined his father.
</P>
<P>
   A Hughes executive said that the company subsequently recruited
the son ``on the merits'' and by 1995 he was working in the
business development area. He is not allowed to work on any matter
that requires a federal security clearance.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996 Hughes wanted to use Shen's language skills in a
satellite deal that it had made with the consortium, Asia-Pacific
Mobile Telecommunications. The deal fell under the jurisdiction of
the State Department. The government requires companies that employ
foreign citizens on federally controlled exports to obtain a
license. In mid-1996 Hughes applied to the State Department for a
license for Shen.
</P>
<P>
   By then, President Clinton had approved the overall deal. Hughes
officials had asked the administration for an expedited decision
and the Defense Technology Security Administration, which reviews
all such licenses, did not check with the Defense Intelligence
Agency or the CIA before approving the project, according to
administration and congressional officials.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Defense Technology Security Administration
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Asian consortium's stock is held by five Chinese
state-owned entities, including one that falls under Gen. Shen's
supervision. A spokesman for the consortium, Liu Tsun Kie, said,
``Shen Jun has been responsible for input into the mobile satellite
network and business operations in China as part of the commercial
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald O'Neal, a Hughes spokesman, said that Shen, a senior
project manager, ``helps train customers to use and operate our
satellites.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Hughes submitted a new license to the Commerce
Department, which now regulates commercial satellites, after its
deal with Asia-Pacific was changed to include different equipment.
Shen ``may be used in the design review coming up'' for those
satellites once Hughes obtains federal approval, O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is being held up as a result of questions by the
State Department and the Pentagon about whether the satellites,
which contain some of the most sophisticated U.S. communications
equipment, should be sold to a company with close ties to the
Chinese military. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
