r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-JONES-COX     07-01 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-JONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge removes himself from Jones's case
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A woman who says Andruw Jones is the father of her
child is trying to negotiate a new child-support agreement with the
Braves center fielder _ and end bizarre court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquelyn Barnett of Duluth said Wednesday that DNA tests
indicate a 99.97 percent likelihood that Jones is the father of her
daughter, Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has refused to discuss the woman's paternity suit, which
is pending in Fulton County Superior Court. Jones also would not
comment Wednesday on the action by judge Joel J. Fryer to remove
himself from the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reaction,'' Jones said of Fryer's action.
</P>
<P>
   Fryer's motion to recuse himself from the case was entered June
11, according to the Fulton Daily Report, about the time he was
contacted by Sports Illustrated for an article on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The article quoted Fryer praising Jones as a player and said
that the judge ``should be wearing an Atlanta Braves jersey instead
of a jurist's robe.''
</P>
<P>
   Fryer took himself off the case ``to avoid any appearance of
prejudice or bias,'' according to the Daily Report.
</P>
<P>
   Fryer, who has been on the Superior Court bench for 24 years,
could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett said Jones' second blood test came back positive. The
case could go back to court if a compromise is not reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andruw hasn't taken any responsibility, not an inkling of
it,'' Barnett said Wednesday. ``(But) since he is not going to be
there, I have to make sure my child will be supported. I will push
the money issue out the window, I'll take it down to $10, if he
would be a father to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett, who is working out of her house for $9 an hour as a
transcriber, said that she met Jones at the bar American Pie early
last year and that they dated for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a struggle make up the difference we need in our
household,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The case went to Fryer's court in February when Barnett sought
$4,449 a month in child support. Jones, who is making $411,000 with
the Braves this season, had offered $2,500. Fryer awarded $1,500, a
temporary order contingent upon Jones taking another blood test.
</P>
<P>
   SI and the Daily Report quoted the judge as saying, ``We've got
a 23-year-old mother here who's got a wonderful education (and) who
wants to stay home until her infant becomes 18 years of age, so
long as that fat cow continues to pay. Well, I don't have great
sympathy for that. I'm going to make her starve to death if that is
what she plans on doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett, who is 24, said she was stunned by Fryer's comments.
``I felt as if I was put on the stand,'' she said. ``I was totally
judged not by just Andruw's attorneys but by Judge Fryer.
</P>
<P>
   `` I am trying to be as good as a mother as I can to Madison,''
she said. ``What was addressed was my moral character and (that)
Andruw was victimized. I am not saying he is the victim, either. It
is Madison who is the victim, if there is one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
