<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RESEARCH SUGGESTS IMMUNE SYSTEM CAN RECOVER FROM AIDS
INFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The body's immune system can recover to a large extent,
even after it has been ravaged by severe AIDS, according to
evidence reported here on Wednesday by French scientists at the
12th World AIDS Conference.
</P>
<P>
   This news helps answer a major question that has long stymied
AIDS researchers. In practical terms, it means that people infected
with HIV, the AIDS virus, would not need to take drugs to protect
against potentially deadly infections that can occur as
complications of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, scientists have not known whether the immune system
could be restored after severe infection with HIV, because there is
little precedent from other immune deficiency diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brigitte Autran, an immunologist at the l'Hopital
Pitie-Salpetriere in Paris, said her studies showed ``a tremendous
recovery'' of the immune system from AIDS. Dr. Autran's research
supports reports from other laboratories that have offered
increasingly strong evidence of the potential recovery of an
AIDS-damaged immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now providing the proof that indeed the immune system
is not dead,'' Dr. Autran said. ``It can be restored even late in
the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anthony Fauci, the head of the National Institute of Allergy
and Infectious Diseases in Bethesda, Md., observed, ``Dr. Autran's
work is among the best in showing that there is at least partial
reconstitution of the immune system.''
</P>
<P>
   The studies, which expanded on parts of Dr. Autran's previously
published research, involved a small number of AIDS patients who
had taken newer combinations of anti-HIV drugs for 24 months. The
combinations, often called drug cocktails, can drive the amount of
virus in a person's blood below levels detectable in laboratory
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery of the immune system is directly related to the degree
of suppression of HIV resulting from drug cocktail therapy, Dr.
Autran said. After therapy began, immune system cells returned at
high speed for the first two months and then increased at a slower
but steady pace, Dr. Autran said. Other cells, known as CD-8 cells,
also slowly return toward normal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Autran estimated that it would take four to eight years for
full reconstitution of the immune system to occur. This prediction
presumes that an individual is able to continue taking the drug
cocktails and that the amount of virus remains at low levels. At
this point, no one knows how long a person can tolerate the drugs
or how safe they are over many years.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of immune restoration in AIDS is not a complete
surprise, Fauci said, because immune systems that are severely
damaged from irradiation for bone marrow transplants do recover.
But it usually takes one to two years.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS cripples the immune system largely by the virus'
destruction of so-called CD-4 blood cells. When these cells drop to
low levels, an individual's risk of developing a number of unusual
infections as complications of AIDS increases dramatically. Among
such infections are pneumocystis pneumonia and toxoplasmosis. They
often are the cause of death in people who have AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Autran said that in 1996 her team began testing 303 patients
``at very advanced stages'' of AIDS. After drug therapy, 80 percent
of the participants sustained a significant increase in CD-4 cells.
Over an 18-month period, the median CD-4 counts rose to 194 per
cubic millimeter from 51. The normal CD-4 counts varies, but is
usually from 500 to 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Autran said further work was needed to determine whether
earlier or stronger treatment was required for full recovery. She
also raised the possible need for using additional strategies like
vaccines to stimulate the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Tests show that the new CD-4 cells are ``naive,'' meaning that
these newly created cells have not been exposed to foreign
substances like H.I.V. Naive cells emerged after six months and
showed a continuous increase for the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that the new cells are naive is crucial evidence for
restoring the immune system. CD-4 cells are normally produced in
the thymus gland in the upper chest. The gland is large in
childhood, but generally turns into scar tissue as it shrinks in
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the thymus is gone, what is the source of the new CD-4
cells in the recovery of the immune system?
</P>
<P>
   Presumably they come from other areas in the body that function
as a thymus, ``but we don't know where they are,'' Fauci said. He
said his team was making a large effort to find them.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the scientific interest in documenting the recovery of
the immune system is a question crucial to medical practice. Do the
new cells protect against the unusual infections that occur as
complications of AIDS?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Autran believes so. Laboratory tests of restored cells from
the participants indicated that they should be capable of fighting
off microbes that cause toxoplasmosis and other complicating
infections of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Autran and Fauci said it would take clinical trials to
determine at what point patients could safely stop taking drugs to
prevent the complicating infections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
