<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tropicana cranks up power stats
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ It was only after Tropicana Field was
mapped out that club officials realized the dimensions almost
matched old Ebbets Field in Brooklyn, a quaint fact the Devil Rays
liked to accent as they converted the world's largest
cable-supported dome into a baseball park.
</P>
<P>
   What the tenants have found after three months is hardly quaint.
And after giving up Tuesday night's twin homers to Andres
Galarraga, D-Rays left-hander Tony Saunders spoke up about
Tropicana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows this place is a joke,'' he said after
Galarraga brought to 35 the number of home runs Tampa Bay gave up
in its first 39 home games, as opposed to 25 homers on the road.
``All you have to do is lift the ball here. I mean, the only place
that's legit is to center field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trop measures 370 in the power alleys, 315 down the
left-field line and 322 to right, all easy reaches. Center field is
a cemetery, at 407 straight-away and a preposterous 415 to deepest
left-center, exactly where Chipper Jones homered Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hitters are going to like it,'' he said. ``The pitchers
are going to hate it. As long as the pitchers keep the ball up the
middle, that's the only way it plays legit. If they start hitting
balls down the lines or into the gaps, it quickly becomes a
hitter's park.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wohlers project
</P>
<P>
   After a positive first appearance with AAA Richmond Tuesday
night, closer Mark Wohlers was to pitch again Wednesday in the
R-Braves' game in Charlotte. Wohlers needed 16 pitches to retire
the side in a one-walk/one-strikeout eighth inning in Richmond's
6-0 win. The team still maintains no schedule for his return to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Simon says ...
</P>
<P>
   Randall Simon is earning his keep since arriving from Richmond.
He took over at first base Wednesday when Galarraga's left wrist
would not loosen up where he was hit by a pitch the night before.
Galarraga was able to DH. Simon has appeared in all three games
since his call-up.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko update
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko, recuperating from a Monday appendectomy, spoke with
Bobby Cox Wednesday and left his manager thinking the Braves can
get by without placing him on the DL. ``He feels fine,'' Cox said.
``Hopefully, he'll start hitting Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
