<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ANNIVERSARY-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNIST HONG KONG HAS ITS 1ST BIRTHDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-MEDIA, CHINA-NOTEBOOK,
CHINA-HILLARY-CLINTON, CHINA-EX-OFFICIAL, HONGKONG-AIRPORT) 
(mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ One year after the Union Jack was lowered here for
the last time, Hong Kong marked the anniversary of its return to
China with a restrained celebration Wednesday that suggested people
had other things on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   On a bright and breezy day that began with a ceremonial raising
of the Chinese flag at Victoria Harbor, China's president, Jiang
Zemin, said the government was ``very satisfied'' with Hong Kong's
first year as a semiautonomous city.
</P>
<P>
   But Hong Kong's chief executive, Tung Chee-hwa, captured the
dark mood of the place with a plea that people here ``summon
unprecedented courage to overcome the difficulties and open the
doors to the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of Hong Kong is not to be measured by our fortune
today,'' Tung said in a speech to 5,500 guests at a cultural
pageant Wednesday morning. ``Rather, it will be determined by our
current spirit and vitality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's economy has plowed into a wall since the handover, a
victim of the Asian financial crisis and an inflated property
market. With a deepening recession, soaring unemployment and a
crash in real-estate prices, Hong Kong has gone from being a mecca
of commerce to being just another sickly Asian economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a celebration,'' said Emily Lau, an outspoken
pro-democracy politician who was recently elected to Hong Kong's
Legislative Council. ``We are simply marking the fact that we
survived one year under Communist rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Ms. Lau marched with a small group of
demonstrators who were protesting, among other things, the
government's lack of an adequate social safety net to cushion
people from the full force of the downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a more militant protest group tried to march on the Hong
Kong Convention Center, where Jiang and Tung were attending a
banquet. The protesters carried placards calling for Jiang to
resign and a black coffin that honored the civilians killed in the
Tiananmen massacre in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   When the group was stopped short of the Convention Center by
riot policemen, the protesters tried to push the coffin through the
police line. A brief standoff ensued and the demonstrators then set
the coffin ablaze to protest being kept so far from the Chinese
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Police exerted a light hand on both rallies. Several observers
said the number of people taking part in the demonstrations was
smaller than at the handover, when police were harshly criticized
for broadcasting classical music to drown out the chants of
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang did not allow worries about the economy to dampen his
mood. Fresh from a public debate in Beijing with President Clinton,
he disarmed the audience at the pageant with a jaunty greeting in
Cantonese, then immediately reverted to Mandarin to deliver the
familiar pronouncements of a top Communist official.
</P>
<P>
   The peaceful handover, he said, ``proves Deng Xiaoping's theory
that Hong Kong people can govern Hong Kong is completely
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chinese flags fluttered from lampposts and even the
masts of sloops at the Hong Kong Yacht Club, this year's observance
was not a citywide celebration like the handover. Gone were the
spectacular fireworks and laser shows. Instead, Tung squired Jiang
to a series of tightly controlled events with select guest lists,
as the rest of Hong Kong enjoyed a day off in the sunshine.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When they stopped to talk, people had mixed feelings about
celebrating July 1. ``It's nothing special,'' said a clerk in her
30s who would identify herself only as Ms. Lau. She noted that the
biggest change in Hong Kong since China took over was the weak
economy, though she acknowledged it was not China's fault.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Lau also said China had muted Hong Kong's freewheeling
atmosphere. ``When we were under British rule, we could speak
freely,'' she said. ``Now we have to be more careful about what we
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people were quietly exultant about the anniversary. ``Being
a Hong Kong Chinese, I am proud to be here at this time,'' said
Patrick Poon, a 50-year-old employee of Dow Corning in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jiang, the Chinese leader, no longer stirs much comment
here since his visit last year to celebrate the handover. ``It's
like if you bought a house and you rent it out,'' said Chu Shu-san,
48, a newspaper vendor in Causeway Bay. ``You'd have to come down
and check it out once in a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
