<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAVPLENTY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM SHOWS `PLENTY' OF POTENTIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to overreact to a film like Hav Plenty, which is
probably why it was a Sundance Film Festival fave (or should that
be `fav'?). A romantic comedy that doesn't aim for the lowest
common denominator, its has a good nature that will win you over.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it makes you want to be won over. The movie wears
its shallow pockets on its sleeve, but it shows off its
preciousness as well, starting with the name game of its title.
</P>
<P>
   Hav is Havilland Savage (Chenoa Maxwell), a career woman who is
successful, beautiful and a little snooty. Plenty is Lee Plenty
(Christopher Scott Cherot), a blocked writer who is homeless,
handsome and easygoing. Longtime friends, they find things heating
up when Miss Savage invites Mr. Plenty _ as they're fond of calling
each other _ to spend New Year's weekend with her friends and her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Some friends; some family. The two lead characters obviously
have a thing for each other, although Hav is dating a hip-hop star
and Lee doesn't much care for her materialism. If the movie had
concentrated solely on them figuring out their attraction, things
might have been fine, but a running gag about Lee's irresistibility
to women is a little tough to buy. Sure, the guy's good-looking,
but he barely showers or changes clothes all weekend. Must be the
pheromones.
</P>
<P>
   What hurts the movie most, though, is one of its badges of
honor: its indie-film budget. This was obviously a labor of love
for Cherot, who wrote, directed and edited the film, which claims
to be based on a true story. Much about him is likable: He's
pleasant on camera, his script has some very funny moments, and his
direction largely steers clear of rookie-filmmaker
self-consciousness. But even the movie's ritzy locations look a
little too indie, as ife he had just grabbed the camcorder, and the
pacing drags _ never a good idea when you're attempting screwball
humor.
</P>
<P>
   Cherot shows enough promise to make you hope that this will lead
to bigger things for him, although he ends the movie on a rather
distressing copout (and sellout) note. Uneven as it is, ``Hav
Plenty'' deserves a chance; but even if you cut it some slack,
you'll still probably want to like it more than you really do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hav Plenty'' is rated R for frank dialogue, sexual situations
and mild violence.
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Hav Plenty''
</P>
<P>
   Score: 2 1/2 on a scale of 1 t 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Christopher Scott Cherot
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Christopher Scott Cherot, Chenoa Maxwell
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
