<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-HISPANICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONTENDERS ADDRESS HISPANIC GROUP  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLEN R. MYERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The nation's largest Hispanic political organization,
showing sharp preferences among possible Republican presidential
contenders, made Texas Gov. George Bush feel right at home
Wednesday while treating Speaker Newt Gingrich as a guest more
tolerated than welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the League of United Latin American Citizens, which
is holding its annual convention here, was divided over whether to
even invite Gingrich, in view of his opposition to affirmative
action, bilingual education, the introduction of sampling
procedures in the census and other Lulac causes.
</P>
<P>
   Belen Robles, Lulac's president, cited Gingrich's recent support
for Puerto Rican self-determination, a review of the property
claims of New Mexico's early Hispanic settlers and the restoration
of public benefits to some categories of immigrants who have not
become citizens. Officials of Lulac and other Hispanic groups said
they had agreed to thank Gingrich in speeches and publications.
Several other Lulac leaders, including the Texas delegation,
protested the invitation and left or stayed outside the hotel
ballroom where Gingrich spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt Gingrich has never done anything to help the Hispanic
community,'' said Francisco Rodriguez III, a former Lulac vice
president who is among many candidates for the group's presidency.
``For him to come before us now without offering even a token of
apology is totally against what we stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich acknowledged in his speech that he was somewhat out of
place. ``I'm a Georgian. I'm a conservative Republican,'' he said,
with a grin. ``This is not the first of five things I thought I
would get invited to today.''
</P>
<P>
   The House speaker, searching for issues where he could win
Hispanic favor without alienating Republican stalwarts,
concentrated on areas of agreement, including free trade with
Mexico. He only alluded to his support of the recently passed
Proposition 187 in California, meant to abolish that state's
bilingual education system, by saying that he favored having
students learn Spanish as well as English.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bush, support for Mexican trade was only a point of
departure for issues including bilingual education, which he has
generally supported but whose effectiveness he proposes to test.
Addressing Ms. Robles as ``el jefe grande,'' he praised her
leadership in well-accented Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Bush held a news conference before his speech, answering some
questions in Spanish. Lulac officials allowed a break in their
luncheon schedule so he could walk into the crowd for handshakes,
backslaps and hugs. Bush, running for re-election this year, has a
huge lead in the polls, overall and among Hispanic voters, over
State Land Commissioner Garry Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, following Bush Wednesday drew polite applause and left
the room immediately after speaking. As with anyone learning a
language, he has made some errors. A Spanish translation of a
statement from his office called him the ``Hablador,'' which,
instead of speaker in Spanish, means something closer to ``big
talker'' or ``braggart.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gingrich and most other Republicans are struggling with
Spanish, they do know arithmetic. From 1992 to 1996, the number of
registered Hispanic voters rose by about 30 percent to 6.6 million,
and Lulac wants to add another 2 million by the 2000. Measures that
have limited or threatened public services for resident aliens have
prodded millions of them to become citizens and to register to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   These new voters are concentrated in large states like New York,
Illinois, California and Texas. Having once hoped to draw even
among Hispanic voters, Republicans are finding that at least three
of four new Hispanic voters are registering as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
