<SLUG> BC-US-TARGET-CHINA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ANNOUNCEMENT, U.S. MISSILES HAVEN'T BEEN AIMED AT CHINA IN
YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin last
Saturday announced to a world audience the two countries have
stopped aiming nuclear missiles at one another, their statement
omitted a key fact: The Pentagon had unilaterally ``detargeted''
Chinese sites more than four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon in May 1994 completed removing targeting data from
U.S. nuclear missiles as part of a bilateral agreement with Moscow.
But the mechanics of doing so also led to the removal of Chinese
targets from the U.S. strategic missile force, spokesmen for the
Defense Department and U.S. Strategic Command said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Chinese sites have not been targeted by U.S.
missiles for four years was not noted at the Beijing summit, which
highlighted the detargeting as a sign of improving Sino-American
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Strategic Command, which controls the American nuclear
force of Trident missile submarines, land-based Minuteman III and
Peacekeeper missiles, and nuclear-armed B-52H bombers, acknowledged
the 1994 order removing target data from U.S. missiles embraced all
potential nuclear war sites _ including China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States does not target its nuclear missiles on a
day-to-day basis against any country,'' Strategic Command spokesman
Lt. Col. Phil Hutchinson said in a statement. ``The United States
formally detargeted its missiles on 30 May 1994, in the context of
a reciprocal detargeting commitment with the Russian Federation.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokeswoman Lt. Col. Queenie Byars confirmed this.
``When you say the United States detargeted ballistic missiles in
May 1994 did that include China? The answer was yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst John Pike of the Federation of American Scientists said
nuclear weapons experts were generally aware the U.S.-Russian
agreement had led to a total removal of all targeting data from
American missiles. ``They detargeted everything four years ago,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   What last week's announcement by Clinton and Jiang did signify
is that China agreed for the first time to remove American
targeting coordinates from its fleet of DF-5 intercontinental
ballistic missiles. The missiles have been deployed in ground-based
silos in central China since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 13 DF-5 missiles currently on alert can carry a
single multi-megaton thermonuclear warhead between 7,500-9,375
miles, a range that covers the entire continental United States,
Pike said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese arsenal is minute compared with the U.S. nuclear
force. The United States fields between 6,000-10,000 deployed
strategic weapons. The force includes eight Trident submarines at
Navy Submarine Base Bangor in Washington state that carry a total
of 1,536 warheads loaded eight apiece in 24 Trident I missiles per
sub.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's joint press conference in Beijing, Clinton said he
and Jiang had struck a ``mutual decision'' to remove targeting
information from each side's strategic nuclear arsenal as a step
toward improved relations and as a confidence-building mechanism
for further nuclear talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was a mutual decision we made because we felt that,
number one, if we detargeted, we would completely eliminate the
prospect ever of any kind of accidental launch,'' Clinton said.
``And number two, we would take one more step in showing mutual
confidence and trust in one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang told reporters, ``President Clinton and I decided that
China and the United States would not target the strategic nuclear
weapons under their respective control at each other. Then this
demonstrates to the entire world that China and the United States
are partners, not adversaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, asked Wednesday to comment on the Beijing
statements and the fact that U.S. missiles haven't been aimed at
China for years, acknowledged that the Clinton-Jiang agreement did
not concern itself with the time period of any previous targeting.
An administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said only that the two leaders focused on agreeing not to target
strategic nuclear weapons at each other, regardless of any actions
taken earlier.
</P>
<P>
   One congressional critic of the White House said the
Clinton-Jiang detargeting announcement was a step to ``lull the
American people into a sense of false security'' about nuclear
weapons, particularly with the high political profile put on
detargeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton and Jiang were looking for something to say''
at the summit, said Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a member of the House
National Security Committee who has frequently derided the
administration's arms control policies. ``It was a lot of pomp and
hot air and nothing of substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Blair, an expert on nuclear command-and-control systems,
told Congress last year the U.S.-Soviet detargeting accord, while
well-meaning, was ``cosmetic and symbolic'' because the targeting
data remains either loaded in the missile's own computer or in a
standby fire control database that can be reloaded into the systems
within a few seconds. In the case of an accidental missile launch,
Russian programs are set to automatically re-aim the missile at its
last target setting.
</P>
<P>
   New American systems, including the Trident I missiles, have had
all of their targeting data removed from the missile computers but
they can be reintalled within seconds, Pike said. Older Minuteman
III missiles have been re-aimed at open ocean areas _ their
computers require a specific ``aim point'' to be entered in the
missile guidance system.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether the Chinese missiles would require a
manual retargeting instruction or can be re-aimed by computer, Pike
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
