<HEADER>
A6803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-NUKE-DEFECTO     07-01 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-NUKE-DEFECTOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF-DESCRIBED PAKISTANI SAYS A NUCLEAR STRIKE WAS PLANNED ON
INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By JOHN KIFNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Pakistani claiming to be a defector from his
country's nuclear weapons program said Wednesday that Pakistan's
top military leadership, fearing an imminent Indian nuclear attack,
decided on April 25 to launch a pre-emptive nuclear strike on New
Delhi within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   That attack, however, never took place.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Iftikhar Khan Chaudhry, who is seeking asylum in the United
States, also said that Pakistan had already armed and deployed
missiles with nuclear warheads at two sites along the Indian border
and had enough fissionable material for 12 to 18 warheads.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of news conferences at the Madison Avenue office of
his lawyer, Michael Wildes, Khan told shifts of reporters that he
had seen Iranian and Chinese technicians at Pakistan's nuclear
plants and that the program received funds from Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates. A story about Khan appeared Wednesday in
USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Pakistani official said Khan had made up his story in
order to gain American citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is a total fraud,'' said Ahmad Kamal, the Pakistani
representative to the United Nations. ``He has an identity card
which is a forgery, and it's a bad forgery at that.'' Wildes had
produced a photostat of what was said to be Khan's identification
card from the Pakistan Atomic Energy Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But Kamal said the card was phony because it bore the general
crest of the Pakistani government rather than the special seal of
the Atomic Energy Commission. He added that the card also bore the
name of the Ministry of Science and Technology, whereas the Atomic
Energy Commission is a separate organization that reports directly
to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Kamal said that Pakistani authorities believed Khan might be a
man who worked briefly in an entry-level job for the nuclear
program and dropped out of sight in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Khan said that he had attended a meeting presided over by Gen.
Jehingir Karmat, the chief of the army general staff, at which
Pakistani intelligence agencies said they had information that
India was about to launch a nuclear attack on Pakistan's nuclear
development sites.
</P>
<P>
   Among the intelligence reports, he said, was word from Pakistani
radar experts working in the Arab gulf states that an Israeli plane
had been seen flying into India. The meeting he described occurred
well before India's nuclear tests on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Khan, who said he was attending the meeting as an assistant to
Dr. Altaf Hussain, the second man in the Atomic Energy Commission,
said that Karmat gave the go-ahead for a strike within two days.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he became upset by the prospect of death and
destruction in both countries and, along with four other junior
colleagues, wrote a letter to Hussain urging that Pakistan refrain
from the attack. If not, he said, they would ``go public'' with
their objections.
</P>
<P>
   Khan said he was dismissed the next day and threatened with
death. He said his wife was kidnapped and is being held by internal
security forces. Khan said he went into hiding and managed to
escape to Canada and then entered the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials in Washington said Khan's story was
being weighed with caution. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
