<HEADLINE>
GERMAN FILM ABOUT SILENCE SPEAKS VOLUMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The soft-hearted tale ``Beyond Silence,'' the Oscar-nominated
foreign film from Germany, can't help but touch you. The landscape
alone has the ability to enchant; ``Silence'' is set in a bucolic
Bavarian village in the 1800s. But we are also drawn in by the
lovely relationships among the Bischoff family and the heavy
responsibilities placed on 8-year-old Lara (Tatjana Trieb). As the
only hearing person in her family, she has become her parents'
window on the world. When she signs for them, she also rephrases
the conversations so that everyone is well-served. But she is a sly
little girl, and manages to keep a bit of herself even as she gives
her life over to her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Director Caroline Link gives the story a lovely pacing, and
takes her time in planting the seeds that may cause tension. (A
recent report on ``All Things Considered'' dealt with the
difficulty of young children in a family with disadvantaged
members, and how the children's duties within the family slowed
their own development.) This happens to Lara, whose learning is
disrupted by the burden her of role in the family. One light in
Lara's life is the aunt she idolizes: her father's sister, Clarissa
(Sibylle Canonica), who has become a clarinetist.
</P>
<P>
   When the picture leaps 10 years ahead, Lara has followed her
aunt's example, even though her father (Howie Seago) bristles; he's
resentful of his family, who never learned to sign. ``(Beyond
Silence'' is also disdainful of the German stance that lip reading
is preferential to sign language.) As Lara ponders her aunt's offer
to move to Berlin to begin her musical career, events conspire to
make her future, independent life more of a challenge than she
might have dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   Director Link works to achieve a balance, creating a strong and
loving family at the outset, one that unwittingly puts huge demands
on a child, and provokes a future in which the child might leave.
She and her writers add a romantic element when a dreamboat sign
language teacher enters the scene. But the first hour or so has an
evocative touch that becomes a little too plainspoken when Lara
grows up, although she is well-played as an adult by Sylvie Testud.
The second half of ``Beyond Silence'' is a little heavyhanded,
given that the movie is determined to teach a lesson and entertain.
But Link's smoothness in building toward the drama is understated
and calm, before she veers into sentimentality. The film is in
German, with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond Silence'' is rated PG-13 for brief adult sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Beyond Silence''
</P>
<P>
   Score'' 3 on a scale of 1 to 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Caroline Link
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Sylvie Testud, Tatjana Trieb, Howie Seago
</P>
<P>
   Length: 106 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
