<SLUG> BC-STARR-HUBBELL-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DECISION IS STINGING REBUKE FOR STARR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With STARR-HUBBELL) 
(ps) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel Kenneth Starr has taken a
lot of abuse lately, from Democrats in Congress, President
Clinton's lawyers and friends and even journalists.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday he faced criticisms of a far more serious
nature, in a carefully but harshly worded judicial opinion that
dismissed his tax case against former Justice Department official
Webster Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Judge James Robertson hit him on two fronts, saying that he did
not correctly understand his purview and used overzealous tactics
in his pursuit of Hubbell. He called the counsel's pursuit of
Hubbell a ``quintessential fishing expedition'' and called some of
his constitutional views ``scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which Starr will appeal, was a stinging rebuke for
the independent counsel. It followed other recent setbacks,
including the release from prison of Susan McDougal, another key
figure in Starr's Whitewater investigation; the Supreme Court's
refusal to grant emergency consideration of Starr's efforts to
force the testimony of Secret Service employees and White House
aide Bruce Lindsey, and the Supreme Court decision that Starr could
not pierce the attorney-client privilege between Vincent Foster,
the White House lawyer who committed suicide, and his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was also the contretemps over a magazine article by
Steven Brill, in his magazine, Brill's Content, that accused
Starr's office of unethical leaks to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's decision, though it pointedly differentiated the
pursuit of Hubbell from the case of Monica Lewinsky, was directed
more personally at Starr than the other court decisions. In fact it
is the first time a court has passed judgment on the independent
counsel's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Its effect is also more immediate than the others. In losing
this skirmish, Starr has lost, for the time being anyway, his
ability to use the tax charges as a way of pressuring Hubbell into
cooperating with the larger Whitewater investigation. The
independent counsel has long believed Hubbell has knowledge of
misdeeds by the President and Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell is a longtime friend to the Clintons, dating back to
their days in Little Rock, and a former law partner to Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Given the protracted, seesawing nature of the four-year legal
combat between Starr and President Clinton, it would be perilous to
view any single development in the complex web of the independent
counsel's investigation as decisive. And Robertson, though he wrote
a careful opinion, was challenging some contrary findings by other
judges, and is, after all, only a district judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you have to look at this kind of investigation is like
a trial where both sides have their ups and downs,'' said Theodore
J. Boutrous Jr., a litigator at the Washington law firm of Gibson,
Dunn &AMP; Crutcher. Boutrous, who was a member of former President
Reagan's legal team in the Iran-Contra investigation, added, ``It's
impossible to draw sweeping conclusions from what happens on a
particular day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Washington's cottage industry of Starr-gazing was in
overdrive as Robertson's decision began circulating among the
city's law firms and within political circles. The judge's 34-page
opinion dismissing the tax case against Hubbell gave Starr's
doubters some significant and fresh material.
</P>
<P>
   Because Hubbell had already served 17 months in prison after
pleading guilty in an earlier case brought by Starr involving
Hubbell's defrauding his former law firm, the April indictment of
Hubbell and his wife on tax charges last April was viewed by some
as overly harsh treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just days after Starr filed the tax charges against the
Hubbells, he got Mrs. McDougal indicted on three counts of criminal
contempt and obstruction of justice for failing to answer questions
from his grand jury. Like Hubbell, Mrs. McDougal had already been
severely punished, having completed an 18-month jail term for civil
contempt on the same charges.
</P>
<P>
   Given that both actions came as the Arkansas Whitewater grand
jury seemed to be was running out of time and steam, both
supporters and critics saw Starr's moves against both Hubbell and
Ms. McDougal as efforts to increase the pressure on them to provide
embarrassing information about the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both instances he seems to be wielding the hammer of Thor
to swat at mosquitoes,'' said Richard Ben Veniste, a Washington
lawyer who has represented prominent Democrats and was a Watergate
prosecutor and Senate minority counsel. ``Judge Robertson's action
will give further credence to the critics of Starr that he has been
overly aggressive in pursuing individuals who would not otherwise
be prosecuted simply to be able to get some information from them
that he can use against president and Mrs. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Ginsburg, a litigator at Patton, Boggs &AMP; Blow, disagreed.
``This is what prosecutor's do,'' he observed. `` Hubbell was a key
source of information who was reluctant to talk. It was a pressure
point that Starr was applying.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic act of defiance, Hubbell and his wife appeared
outside their modest home on the day of the indictment as Hubbell
declared, ``The independent counsel can indict my dog, they can
indict my cat, but I'm not going to lie about the president.'' Mrs.
McDougal also used strong language after her indictment on May 4,
saying, ``It is true that no man is above the law, but neither
should any man be asked to break the law in order to buy his
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   If one of Starr's points in pursuing Hubbell and Mrs. McDougal
was to win a war of wills against them, he appears to have lost.
Hubbell, declaring himself ``grateful'' for today's court decision,
is out of the independent counsel's sights for the time being. And
Ms. McDougal, enjoying a respite of freedom after another federal
judge granted her release last month on health grounds, faces trial
on the contempt charges in the fall. But she has repeatedly said
she will not tell Starr anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
