<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLATE RACING AT `NIGHTONA' PROMISES FIREWORKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking his cue from a higher power _ network TV _ NASCAR
president Bill France Jr. has said let there be light.
</P>
<P>
   And don't sweat the electricity bill at the Daytona
International Speedway this weekend. Winston Cup racing is
scheduled to go prime time from NASCAR's hometown on Saturday, when
the 40th Pepsi 400 officially becomes the first auto race broadcast
live at night by a major network.
</P>
<P>
   That is a promotional mouthful, and a fine historic distinction,
when you consider that five other Cup events are carried live at
night by cable networks. Those races, topped by The Winston
all-star event at Charlotte Motor Speedway, have proven to be
wildly popular with NASCAR's drivers, fans, corporate sponsors and
the cable carriers.
</P>
<P>
   That's because night racing is an easy sell.
</P>
<P>
   Practically every Cup driver can relate to trading paint on
Saturday night, as he did on some local bull ring at the start of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, temperatures are lower for everyone at night, even in
Florida in early July.
</P>
<P>
   Illuminated by Musco Lighting's tried-and-true electrical
system, one producing 3.5-million watts of power per hour and
reflected by 2,600 square feet of mirrors, the cars and their
flashy paint jobs typically produce spectacular theater at speeds
approaching 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is counting on it.
</P>
<P>
   But the element that will separate the Pepsi 400 from those
other night races is that wafer-thin piece of NASCAR-mandated metal
known as the carburetor restrictor plate. This is ``plate race''
No. 3 of the season, following the season-opening Daytona 500 won
by Dale Earnhardt at the 2.5-mile DIS in February and the DieHard
500 won by Bobby Labonte at the 2.66-mile Talladega Superspeedway
in Alabama in April.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona and Talladega are the only high-banked speedways on the
Cup circuit where NASCAR requires use of the plate to restrict the
flow of air and gasoline into the engine, thereby reducing
horsepower and speed. Plate racing has been part of the NASCAR
landscape since 1987. But this will be the first time that the
elements peculiar to the genre _ and its bone-breaking consequences
_ will be stirred up at night.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, there are questions about pack racing on Daytona's
steep, 31-degree banked turns, and the possible effects of shadows
at speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is everybody adjusting to being in a pack,''
said Dale Jarrett, a two-time winner of the Daytona 500. ``Even
though we race fast at a lot of other places, we're not normally in
a 30 or 35-car pack for that period of time. We usually get strung
out, but that doesn't happen at Daytona with the restrictor plate.
That's the only adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Geoff Bodine, winner of the 1986 Daytona 500, said he has
concerns after having tested under the lights at DIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were down there testing, we all ran by ourselves
because of this crazy qualifying thing we have to do,'' said
Bodine, referring to tonight's time trials. ``We still don't know
how it's going to be out there running with other cars, around
other cars, behind other cars. I'm optimistic how it's going to be.
But there were some shadows down there and the lighting people and
NASCAR said they were going to try to fix that.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip, a three-time Cup champion and winner of the
1989 Daytona 500, said shadows of any length could create a
distraction once the engines get wound up and the drivers get to
racing side-by-side.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about the other lighted tracks that we race on,''
Waltrip said, ``there certainly isn't a lot of side-by-side racing.
And there certainly isn't a lot of racing in groups like we do at
Daytona and Talladega. I'm concerned about how the cars and how the
drivers are going to react to the lights when we're eight or 10
cars deep and two and three cars wide as we're going around the
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending Pepsi 400 champion John Andretti believes the lower
track temperatures at night will eliminate the chassis setup
guesswork normally associated with this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you can probably just put the Daytona 500 setup in
there,'' Andretti said. ``Now there's little question you can stay
wide open all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least for three spectacular hours of prime time. Network
TV _ and Bill France Jr. _ are counting on it.
THE BUZZ
IRL
</P>
<P>
   The career paths of Pep Boys Indy Racing League drivers Billy
Boat and Greg Ray of Plano could be linked soon. Boat, lead driver
for Houston's A.J. Foyt, is expected to be sidelined for eight
weeks after undergoing surgery Monday for a broken left femur
sustained in a crash Sunday during the New England 200 at New
Hampshire International Speedway. Boat was reported in good
condition and walking on crutches yesterday at Methodist Hospital
in Indianapolis. Boat's recovery period, as projected by Dr. Kevin
Scheid, would keep him out of the No. 11 Conseco Dallara/Aurora for
the next four races. Boat, who also sustained a fractured pelvis,
could return for the Lone Star 500K at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort
Worth on Sept. 20. In the meantime, Ray confirmed that he has
approached Foyt about the ride. ``I spoke with A.J. and \Rteam
manager\S Tommy LaMance Monday,'' said Ray, who was on the road
Tuesday working on a sponsorship deal for 1999. ``They're trying to
figure out what they're going to do. I'd very much like to drive
for A.J. at Dover Downs \Ron July 19\S and maybe at Charlotte Motor
Speedway \Ron July 25\S. I'd like to drive, if he'd let me.'' Boat
won the True Value 500K night race at TMS on June 6 by
0.928-seconds over Ray, whose Thomas Knapp Motorsports team has
been sidelined by lack of corporate sponsorship. ``A.J. knows that
we're not in championship contention, and that we're working on a
program for next year and we've done a good job,'' Ray said. ``I
think we might be able to do something good for him.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The ``crowd'' for Sunday's New England 200 was announced at
20,000 _ or 5,000 fewer than track owner/promoter Bob Bahre said he
needed to break even financially. Bahre's three-year contract with
IRL founder Tony George ended with Sunday's race, and Bahre said he
might not renew for an event that lost title sponsor Pennzoil and
reportedly cost him $700,000. Ray, who attended the race at Loudon,
N.H., as a spectator, said dumping the event would not be a blow to
the series. ``I don't think anyone _ either the drivers or the
series _ wants to go there again, because he \RBahre\S does not
promote it,'' Ray said. ``It's apparent that he hasn't. The whole
time I was there, I saw nothing on billboards, radio, newspaper _ I
saw nothing.''
NASCAR
</P>
<P>
   Early ``silly season'' guesses on the makeup of the 1999 Winston
Cup schedule call for an addition of one race, to be awarded to the
reconfigured Metro-Dade Motorsports Complex in Homestead, Fla. That
would increase the schedule to 34 events, and nudge NASCAR
president Bill France Jr. closer to his latest cutoff point.
Speaking before The Associated Press Sports Editors annual
convention last week in Richmond, Va., France acknowledged that the
schedule ``perhaps can be expanded a small amount'' as the sport
barrels into the next century. Pressed for a maximum number of
races, France said ``36 or 37, maybe. You might be able to add a
couple, but you need to do it gradually. You don't want the
sponsorship to drop.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   France, whose appearance before the sports editors coincided
with the celebration of NASCAR's 50th anniversary season, also
floated the novel idea of two-driver teams _ each featuring
specialists on different types of courses who would alternate
behind the wheel and earn points for the team, instead of as
individuals. ``I'm not saying it's unrealistic to have two
drivers,'' said France, 65, the son of NASCAR founder Bill France
Sr. ``You have two tire-changers, two truck drivers, why not two
drivers? It would be more of a team-type championship. That would
let \Rthe main driver\S have a weekend off. You wouldn't have to
race every race. That would take a little heat off the driver.''
...
</P>
<P>
   Loy Allen is scheduled to replace Todd Bodine in the No. 35 Team
Tabasco Racing Pontiac Grand Prix at the Pepsi 400, beginning with
qualifying tonight at the Daytona International Speedway. Team
owner Bob Hancher said Bodine has not been released from his
contract, as Allen has been signed to a one-race deal. Allen won
the pole for the 1994 Daytona 500 and qualified on the outside of
the two-car front row for the Pepsi 400 that same year. Bodine has
qualified for only eight of 16 Cup races this season. ...
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Ron Fellows boosted his NASCAR stock with a victory in
the Lysol 200 Busch Grand National event on the road-course at
Watkins Glen (N.Y.) International on Sunday. A former regular in
the Sports Car Club of America Trans-Am Series, Fellows won the
Grand Prix of Dallas street race in 1994 and 1996.
FAST LAPS
Switching allegiances
</P>
<P>
   Former Texan Steve Earwood is taking Rockingham (N.C.) Dragway
back to its International Hot Rod Association roots.
</P>
<P>
   Earwood and IHRA president Bill Bader have announced that ``The
Rock'' will play host to two Snap-on Tools Drag Racing Series
events in 1999, along with one of the IHRA's World Championship
Series points meets.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Rockingham no longer will play host to the
National Hot Rod Association's Winston Invitational non-points
all-star race. That event reportedly will resurface in July 1999 at
Bristol (Tenn.) Dragway, which is being refurbished by developer
Bruton Smith, whose properties include Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Winston Invitational was a major revenue source for the
track \RRockingham\S, but it certainly wasn't the only one,'' said
Earwood, former vice president for sales and marketing at the Texas
Motorplex in Ennis. ``We feel like the IHRA series has tremendous
growth potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockingham, which Earwood purchased in January 1992, has hosted
the NHRA all-star race for 10 years. Rockingham will operate as an
NHRA-sanctioned track through the end of the season.
Nuts and bolts
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty, the 18-year-old son of Cup regular Kyle Petty and
grandson of ``King'' Richard Petty, won his first American Speed
Association race at I-70 Speedway in Odessa, Mo., on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Cup regular Ricky Craven, who has been recuperating from
post-concussion syndrome, plans to return to the No. 50 Budweiser
Chevy for the Jiffy Lube 300 at New Hampshire International
Speedway on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   New England 200 winner Tony Stewart is the second driver to win
three IRL races, joining Arie Luyendyk. Stewart also is the first
IRL driver to win twice this season.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Goodyear's second place run at NHIS at Loudon, N.H., was
his best finish of the season _ topping a fourth-place effort at
Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz Calkins is the only driver to be running at the finish of
all five IRL events this season.
Last words
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole life's been that way. Either a hero or a hobo, that's
the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Winston Cup driver Rusty Wallace on his up-and-down season.
</P>
</TEXT>
