<HEADER>
A6811 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILDEGARD-MUSIC-ART-2     07-01 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILDEGARD-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON NEW RECORDINGS, HILDEGARD, AT 900, DEFIES TIME AND THE DEVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 5)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 Cori Ellison is a singer and the dramaturg at the New York City
Opera. 
By CORI ELLISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We should all be as lively and robust in our 900th
year as Hildegard of Bingen. Unless you've been dwelling under a
rock, the name of this 12th-century German abbess should at least
sound vaguely familiar by now.
</P>
<P>
   Though never formally canonized, Hildegard, who was born in
1098, has achieved an eccentric sort of sainthood, having been
adopted as an icon by partisans of such renegade causes as Creation
Spirituality and feminism.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, her vivid prose, mystical paintings and
singular music, all conceived in visions said to have been induced
by debilitating migraines, have been whooshed from centuries of
monastic obscurity to New Age celebrity by a flurry of performances
and publications.
</P>
<P>
   The latest wave of recordings is at hand. In addition, this year
New York will see no fewer than three staged productions of
Hildegard's magnum opus, the musical morality play ``Ordo
Virtutum'' (``The Company of the Virtues''), in wildly varying
styles.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Tuesday, as part of the Lincoln Center Festival, the
esteemed medieval-music ensemble Sequentia, which is based in
Cologne, Germany, and has performed and recorded Hildegard's music
for nearly two decades, will stage ``Ordo Virtutum'' at the Church
of St. Paul the Apostle, as it might have been performed by the
women in Hildegard's convent, according to the advance publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Then, also in the festival, a decidedly downtown ``Ordo'' will
follow at Lincoln Center's Clark Studio Theater. Cooked up by the
Hildegurls, a consortium of four New York women who compose as well
as sing, it will fuse Hildegard's Latin texts and melodies with
computer-generated sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in November, the respected Camerata of the Mannes
College of Music will offer a musically orthodox interpretation in
modern dress.
</P>
<P>
   Since Hildegard's scores, consisting of single monophonic lines,
offer no tangible clues to niceties like rhythmic shape, tempo,
dynamics, vocal distribution or instrumentation (if any), much less
expression, interpreters today must make major choices. The growing
body of Hildegard recordings, ranging from the sublime to the
bizarre, demonstrates how astonishingly different those choices can
be, even when shaped by scholarship and taste.
</P>
<P>
   The latest recordings are led by two versions of ``Ordo
Virtutum,'' by Sequentia (whose earlier recording of the work, for
Deutsche Harmonia Mundi in 1982, is now on Editio Classica), and
Vox Animae, a British medieval vocal ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Thought to be the world's oldest surviving music drama, ``Ordo
Virtutum'' is essentially one of Hildegard's colorful, apocalyptic
visions described in words and music. With its cast of allegorical
characters (Humility, Charity, Fear of God and the like), it
foreshadows later medieval morality plays like ``Everyman.'' The
plot concerns a Soul tempted away from a host of Virtues by the
Devil. Ultimately, the traumatized Soul returns to grace, and the
victorious Virtues bind and cast out the Devil.
</P>
<P>
   Neither recording claims to be a historical reconstruction,
since nothing is known of the work's performance history; indeed,
it it is not known whether the work was even intended for
performance. It may have been presented by Hildegard's sisters at
the consecration of their new convent on the Rupertsberg in 1152,
some suggest, with the single male role _ the Devil, of course _
taken by the monk Volmar, Hildegard's secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Since it is known that instruments played a part in musical life
at Hildegard's convents, each of the new recordings, like
Sequentia's earlier one, uses them in some way, And both versions,
again like Sequentia's first, occasionally add rudimentary harmony,
in the form of drones or parallel lines, which were probably
improvised in Hildegard's day.
</P>
<P>
   The Sequentia release (Deutsche Harmonia Mundi 05472-77394-2;
two CDs) proves preferable for its near-perfect balance of
thoughtful scholarship, imagination and brio. It uses a small
complement of instruments _ three fiddles, a flute and a
hurdy-gurdy _ and deploys them not so much to accompany the singers
and enhance characterization as to create mood and flow.
</P>
<P>
   Over some two decades of performing Hildegard, Barbara Thornton
and her crackerjack ensemble have gained even greater nuance and
fluency, and deepened their characterizations. They offer
luminously sung, impeccably synchronized, and spirited
performances. Franz-Josef Heumannskaemper's grouchy Devil is like
the scary neighbor of every child's nightmare. Harmony is applied
liberally and cogently.
</P>
<P>
   Vox Animae's version of ``Ordo Virtutum'' (Etcetera KTC 1203;
CD) immediately feels less expansive than Sequentia's, and not just
because it clocks in at about 69 minutes as against Sequentia's 92.
It is admirably learned and attractively performed, with 20 singers
accompanied by two harps, a recorder and a tad of percussion. Yet
its variety seems more calculated than organic. Much of the work is
chanted in even tones, the rest more freely. Several choral
sections are cast in marchy measured rhythms. Instruments are used
meagerly and none too creatively, and drones and parallel motion
are added sparingly, only after the Virtues' victory.
</P>
<P>
   The vocalism is of the white, hooty, spottily blended variety
that long gave early music a checkered name. Evelyn Tubb, who
directs the ensemble with Michael Fields, contributes the most
professional and musical singing, as Humility. The Devil's speech
is stilted and singsong. The recorded ambiance is a bit
disembodied; the overall effect, rather austere and deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   Vox Animae has also released a video version of ``Ordo
Virtutum'' (Etcetera KTCV 101; VHS cassette). Taped at the Priory
of St. Bartholomew the Great in London and at Bayham Abbey in
Sussex, it shares all the musical assets and liabilities of its
audio cousin. Ferenc van Damme, the director, pulls out many
cinematic stops, busily dissolving and superimposing (never
cutting) shots of the evocative Romanesque architecture, fluffy
clouds, candles and Hildegard's illuminations, all bathed in a
golden light.
</P>
<P>
   The players amble about with earnest, glazed looks, often
breaking into stiff, hieratic semaphore. In a burst of reductive
symbolism, the Soul is tantalized by a masher of a Devil clad in a
tuxedo (complete with red tie and cummerbund), who nuzzles her and
offers her pearls, and she sheds her snow-white cassock to reveal a
skimpy black slip dress. When the prodigal Soul finally comes
crawling home to the Virtues, one of her spaghetti straps is
meaningfully askew.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Vox Animae's video is ultimately asphyxiated by its reverential
air. A group with such palpable love and respect for Hildegard
might place greater trust in the momentum of her music and the
passion of her poetry. More telling stage pictures, a more specific
facial and physical vocabulary, and more imaginative flights on the
words and music would go farther in telling her story than artsy
camera work and heavy-handed symbolism. But the video is graced
with clearly, eloquently translated and perfectly timed subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Of the steadily multiplying CD's of Hildegard's other works,
several merit recommendation. Pride of place must go to ``A Feather
on the Breath of God'' (reissued as Hyperion CDA 66039), a
pioneering album from 1981, which did much to spearhead the
Hildegard revival. The small English vocal ensemble Gothic Voices,
directed by Christopher Page, shares the bleached tone, spotty
blend, dry acoustic and sober sensibility of Vox Animae but turns
in a livelier performance; indeed, ``O Ecclesia,'' a sequence hymn
honoring St. Ursula, goes twice as fast here as in most other
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal ``O Ecclesia,'' as well as splendid accounts of 17
other Hildegard chants to St. Ursula, may be found in ``11,000
Virgins'' (Harmonia Mundi France 907200), the newest release by
Anonymous 4, a quartet of New York women specializing in medieval
music. These singers, sounding like one bionic voice, seem to have
the most instinctive grasp of Hildegard's wide-ranging, quirkily
chromatic, extravagantly melismatic music. They capture her fevered
lyricism in masterly fashion, with their characteristic
intelligence, suppleness, spontaneity and a quality that can only
be called spiritual affinity.
</P>
<P>
   Two other New York-based groups that specialize less in early
music offer honorable efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Voices of Angels'' (Delos DE 3219), by the Voices of
Ascension led by Dennis Keene, 12 women, variously deployed, give
stately but fluid, solidly blended and expressive performances of
14 Hildegard chants.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Monk and the Abbess'' (BMG Catalyst 09026-68329-2), Musica
Sacra, directed by Richard Westenburg, prefaces works by Meredith
Monk with four Hildegard selections. They use the largest forces
and the most ``modern'' approach _ 13 women producing a
full-bodied, altoish sonority at majestic tempos, with bold accents
and insistent ritards _ yet the style is surprisingly idiomatic.
</P>
<P>
   France's orthodox and austere Ensemble Organum, directed by
Marcel Peres, weighs in impressively with ``Laudes de Ste. Ursule''
(Harmonia Mundi France 901626). The group uses no instruments _
indeed, nothing but antiphony (nary a drone) to vary the texture.
Still, buoyed by an earthy, chesty yet impeccably blended timbre,
these singers are never dull.
</P>
<P>
   For the designation ``most eccentric Hildegard recording,'' the
field is getting crowded. On ``Early Music'' (Nonesuch 79457), by
the Kronos Quartet, a string arrangement of Hildegard's ``O virtus
sapientiae'' shows up in the unlikely company of John Cage, Harry
Partch, Arvo Paert, Moondog and others. The intriguing
``Oriente/Occidente'' (Materiali Sonori 90084) pairs the
world-music guru Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan with the ensemble Novum
Gaudium in music of Hildegard.
</P>
<P>
   And the popular but peculiar ``Vision'' (Angel 55246) offers the
abbess' music, straightforwardly if drably vocalized by Sister
Germaine Fritz and Emily van Evera, pureed with Richard Souther's
grotesque accompaniments, a synthesized fusion of jazz, rock and
New Age. It would doubtless have given poor Hildegard one of her
famous migraines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
