<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-PRISONERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ORDERS RELEASE OF 500 POLITICAL PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ With little fanfare, President Kim Dae-jung
ordered the release on Wednesday of some 500 political prisoners.
This appears to be all the political prisoners being held by South
Korea, if human rights groups' estimates are correct.
</P>
<P>
   The release includes those who refuse to renounce their
ideological beliefs. Just when the release would occur was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   According to local press reports, the man widely regarded as the
world's longest-serving political prisoner, Woo Yong-gak, will be
among those freed in an amnesty celebrating the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the South Korean government.
</P>
<P>
   Woo has spent almost 40 years in solitary confinement, losing
his teeth and suffering various illnesses but refusing to renounce
his commitment to North Korean doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   That commitment prevented him from being eligible for an amnesty
announced in March, which led to the release of 2,300 prisoners,
including 74 political prisoners who signed statements renouncing
their ideological beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   In total, that amnesty affected 5.5 million people, sweeping
away the records of past traffic violations and expunging notices
of demotion from the personnel files of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   Kim is a former political prisoner, so his action has a
particular resonance in a Korea that is throwing off its
heavy-handed political past.
</P>
<P>
   The government has decided to scrap the longstanding practice of
requiring all political prisoners to sign letters in which they
renounce their beliefs. The local press quoted Justice Minister
Park Sang-cheon as saying, ``Requiring violators of the National
Security Law to abandon their ideology and beliefs goes against
constitutionally guaranteed freedom of conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   But the government will still require violators of the security
law to abide by it. The law has been used to jail labor leaders and
those caught listening to North Korean radio broadcasts or
distributing leaflets about Communism.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists said that requirement undercuts the
government's amnesty plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no fundamental difference between the current policy
of denouncing one's ideological beliefs and the proposed policy of
receiving pardon by agreeing not to violate Korean laws,'' said Seo
Joon-shik, a former political prisoner who heads the Sarangbang
Group for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Seo also asserted that the government was trying to use the
release to turn attention from the nation's economic troubles,
including record rates of bankruptcy, bank closures and
unemployment, which is rising at an average rate of 8,000 people a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Woo's case had become something of a cause celebre among rights
activists. One of eight North Koreans caught in the act of
espionage, Woo has been tortured and deprived of the most basic
human necessities, including companionship, rights groups say.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to obtain a renunciation of his beliefs, the South
Korean government once allowed an uncle to visit him, but to no
avail. The uncle was Woo's only visitor during his long stay in
prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
