<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO STATES OUTLINE SANCTIONS ON SWISS BANKS IN HOLOCAUST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York and California outlined sanctions Wednesday
against two Swiss banks, after negotiations collapsed over how much
money the banks and Swiss government will return to Holocaust
survivors and heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite State Department objections, Treasurer Matt Fong of
California said his state would not do any more business with two
banks, Credit Suisse and UBS.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Comptroller H. Carl McCall and New York City
Comptroller Alan Hevesi said they would outline Thursday morning a
series of sanctions that would begin taking effect in 45 to 60 days
unless a settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions were made after all sides of the dispute had spent
a day before a committee of state and local finance officials who
had until now recommended holding off sanctions, because the talks
had appeared headed toward a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the first step is most likely to be the rejection
of bids for overnight deposits of surplus government money,
followed by banning the banks from underwriting government bonds.
Ultimately the state and city pension funds could sell their shares
of Swiss companies. The funds are the second and third largest
public employees' pension funds in the country, with combined
assets of $188 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The three officials, as well as others from Pennsylvania and
Delaware, said at City Hall in Manhattan they would recommend to
800 other state and local finance officials that they begin
applying sanctions to prod the Swiss government into joining new
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that the sides are not that far apart and
that the problem is with the Swiss government,'' Hevesi said.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse and UBS proposed last month to put $600 million in
a ``rough justice fund'' to help Holocaust survivors, in addition
to paying whatever sums a commission led by Paul Volcker determined
were due based on bank records.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs proposed last week to settle for $1.5 billion,
provided that the Swiss government and the Swiss National Bank
joined in the agreement, Mel Weiss, a lawyer from New York who
represents the Simon Wiesenthal Center, said outside the closed
session.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.5 billion is far less than lawyers for survivors and
heirs, and for charities designated to represent those who died
heirless, have been seeking. Those people were engaged in a
two-step process in which a settlement would first be made with the
commercial banks and then the talks would to the Swiss government.
</P>
<P>
   The banks and government said that sanctions were not warranted
and that imposing them would make it more difficult to settle the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will review all of our options,'' said Roger Witten, a
lawyer from Washington who is the lead negotiator for the banks.
``But a gun at our head is not conducive to progress in these
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``State and local sanctions in this matter are wrong both in
principle and practice,'' Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat
said in a statement to the officials. Eizenstat later said he hoped
that ``the parties will resume their talks as soon as possible in a
noncoercive atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi said the impasse ``gives us no choice'' but to begin
taking business from the banks to prod them and the government to
settle. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2120EDT &QL; 
