u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-HNS &LR;      07-01 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
OVERFLOWING CUP
<TEXT>
<P>
   After first 21 days, tournament filled with unforgettable
moments
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ On the 22nd day, the World Cup rested.
</P>
<P>
   It was by most accounts a well-deserved break for a tournament
that has captivated the world.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Quadrennium Madness. As the World Cup began a two-day
break Wednesday before beginning quarterfinals play Friday,
millions of fans could only step back, catch their collective
breath and marvel at a tournament that so far has been among the
most hotly contested and entertaining ever.
</P>
<P>
   The first 21 days of group and round-of-16 play ended near
midnight local time Tuesday night with an unforgettably dramatic
ending to the Argentina-England elimination match.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that had some of everything that the World Cup has
offered thus far.
</P>
<P>
   There were terrific individual efforts, numerous shots on goal,
colorful scenes in and out of the stadium, great goal play, penalty
shots, hooligans, remarkable comebacks and the ever-increasing
presence of officials pulling yellow and red cards from their shirt
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   And when Argentine goalkeeper Carlos Roa finally knocked away
England's last shootout attempt after 120 minutes of play, sealing
the 4-3 win and sending Argentine fans into a frenzy, it ended 21
days that fans should hope are matched on the way to the World Cup
final July 12.
</P>
<P>
   It was 21 days of high-flying soccer and low-life hooligans. It
was 21 days of a new, larger 32-team field bringing new, thrilling
names and games to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   The Reggae Boyz of Jamaica thrilled fans with their style and
finally got a win in their last first-round game. South Africa made
an appearance in the tournament for the first time. Croatia,
somehow, got all the way to the quarterfinals and is still kicking.
And Iran got the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It was 21 days of close games and close calls _ 152 goals were
scored, and there were plenty of names and moments to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert had the bark of a
bulldog and a biting game to match. Mexico's Luis Hernandez had his
nation's heart on a string, sending four goals into the net and
nearly carrying his team to an upset of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   England teen-age star Michael Owen had maybe the goal of the
championship so far in the Argentina game.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's Christian Vieri, with five goals in four games and his
team still alive, has lived up to expectations. Brazil's Ronaldo
has not. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   It was 21 days of some teams stunning the world and others
flopping.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland and its loyal Tartan Army of fans came within one game
of finally getting past the first round, only to be eliminated by
Morocco. Spain, a pre-Cup contender, was little more than another
face in the crowd, ousted in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia never seemed to get going. Cameroon looked old. And the
United States blew the game against Iran and a great chance to
finally capture the fancy of fans back home.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was England, often cast as a villain in the world's
eye because of the few hooligan fans who follow the team, playing a
remarkable game against the odds and a man short against Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   There was Mexico, which limped into the tournament but stood
tall on the way home after four inspired games and a near miss
against Germany. There were Chile and Paraguay making a statement
for South American soccer and surprising the experts by making it
into the second round.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the host, France, playing probably the most
consistently strong games of anyone and sailing into the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   It also was 21 days of individual moments that surely will be
remembered for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's Roberto Baggio, the once-fallen star, rose again with a
last-second penalty kick to pull out a tie and possibly stave off
elimination against Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Cameroon's Pierre Njanka wove through half a dozen Austrian
defenders to score a rocket shot that will be among the
tournament's best goals no matter what happens the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   France's Laurent Blanc, the unheralded defender, flashed through
the Paraguayan defense in the 115th minute of an elimination game
and won it with a ``Golden Goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Hernandez, just 15 seconds before the final whistle,
fought off two defenders and chipped in a game-tying goal against
the Netherlands. Four days later, Germany's Oliver Bierhoff broke
Mexican hearts with a powerful header in the 86th minute of an
elimination game that kept the Germans alive.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was England's David Beckham losing his temper in
the opening moments of the second half against Argentina. Beckham
kicked an Argentine player, and his red card got him thrown out of
the game, which severely hurt England's chances.
</P>
<P>
   It was a play that the English will remember forever, but it was
a no-brainer call for referee Kim Nielson of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several other calls over the first 21 days of the
tournament were more questionable, after international soccer
federation president Sepp Blatter early on ordered referees to
crack down on back tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Nielson made two questionable penalty-kick calls for both sides
earlier in the England-Argentina game. In other games, Cameroon
alleged racism after Hungarian referee Laszlo Vagner red-carded two
Cameroon players. Croatia advanced to the quarterfinals on a
questionable penalty call by Argentina's Javier Castrilli.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it was a memorable 21 days. There are 11 days and
eight games to go.
</P>
<P>
   France, Italy, Germany, Croatia, Holland, Argentina, Brazil and
Denmark remain alive. The Madness continues Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
