<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GESHER-THEATER-2TAKES     07-01 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GESHER-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS NOW, BUT CARRYING ON RUSSIAN FLAIR FOR FIREWORKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ Making theater in Israel would seem a
daunting task, what with a history more intense than any drama, a
potpourri of cultures that have resisted melding and a life forever
mired in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these are the very ingredients that Yevgeny Arye has
conjured to propel his Gesher Theater to a predominant position in
Israel in less than seven years, a troupe that has received raves
both inside the country and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Actors at the Gesher, initially composed entirely of Russian
emigres, performed in Hebrew before they had mastered the language
and rehearsed their first production under the scream of Iraqi
rockets. Their plays daringly grasp at the very heart of Israeli
history.
</P>
<P>
   Take the two the Gesher is taking to New York as part of Lincoln
Center Festival '98, opening on Tuesday: one invokes the Holocaust
through a circus in a madhouse in the Negev desert; the other
portrays a pioneering Jewish settlement, before the State of Israel
was proclaimed, as seen through the eyes of a youthful naif who
travels through space and time on a carousel. All this is done in
that grand Russian tradition of high passion and a swirl of light,
music and motion, and in both Hebrew and Russian to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Such heady concoctions have proved wildly popular in Israel. At
the converted warehouse in the old Arab port of Jaffa where the
Gesher performs, productions are generally sold out three months in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Success has also come abroad. In its relatively short life, the
Gesher _ the word means bridge _ has traveled, among other places,
to New York, Berlin, London and Avignon in France. Later this year,
Arye (pronounced AHR-yay) plans to take the troupe to Russia, where
he and most of his actors were born and brought up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their first show, in 1991, burst upon an astounded theater
public literally like a rocket taking off, like fireworks,'' said
Helen Kaye, the theater critic for The Jerusalem Post: ``Critics
went mad, audiences went mad, because nobody had ever seen this
kind of passionate, committed, utterly marvelous theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The commitment arises largely from the venerable Russian
tradition of a theater company as a ``personality cult'' _ to
borrow a concept from Stalin _ a collection of permanent actors
completely dedicated and subject to the vision of their director. A
theater in Russia is often inseparable from its director and is
often known by the director's name, just as the Gesher is known
among Russian Israelis as ``Arye's theater.''
</P>
<P>
   An intense, bearded man of 50 who admits that his Hebrew is
still a full third behind his Russian and English, Arye doesn't see
how a theater can be shaped any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the main difference between us and Cameri,'' he said,
referring to one of the best-known theaters in Israel. ``They're
not a company. They bring in actors and directors for each new
play, and they stage 10 to 11 new productions a year. So their
actors are not part of a theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in this at all. I believe a theater is built
on a company. The director is the leader around whose personality
the theater is built.''
</P>
<P>
   Each new play, he said, is also part of the development and
evolution of every actor and of the company. The result is the
intense realism of classic Russian theater, with each gesture, each
intonation, each pause choreographed for maximum effect and
exhaustively rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   There is no 9-to-5 here, no union hours. If Arye so demands,
rehearsals go on for 12 hours. The Gesher's first production, Tom
Stoppard's ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' in a Russian
translation by Joseph Brodsky, was rehearsed during the Persian
Gulf war, with interruptions for Iraqi rocket attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The war and the complexity of the play were something of a
baptism of fire for the actors, most of them, like Arye, recently
arrived from Soviet Russia. The complex drama, Arye said, enabled
the troupe to show what it was capable of. ``It also let us
demonstrate to the level of theatergoer for whom it was intended,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The production, presented as a kind of stylized, ominous circus,
was seen in 1992 in New York at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Arye, a graduate of Moscow University in psychology (``I was
there before the 1967 war, when they still accepted Jews''), says
he always knew he wanted to direct. After college, he went to
Leningrad to study and then work under the celebrated director
Georgy Tolstonogov.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Moscow, he applied to emigrate to Israel.
That led to a year and a half without any work. Eventually, he did
some directing at various theaters and on television, finally
leaving in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   His first stop was New York, but Natan Sharansky, the former
Soviet dissident who was then the head of a private group assisting
emigres, found some money and persuaded him to move to Israel and
form a theater. Those were years when Russian Jews were leaving by
the tens of thousands, and Arye was swamped with applications from
professional actors. He chose 15, and the Gesher was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many foes then, many people who felt that forming a
Russian theater would maintain a ghetto,'' Arye said. ``People felt
we should assimilate. I felt that forming an exclusively Russian
theater could have been fatal, so from Day 1 we provided a
translation into Hebrew. Within a year we shifted to Hebrew.''
</P>
<P>
   Of working in two languages, Arye said: ``It's a very
interesting process. The plays come out completely different in
Russian and Hebrew. I didn't realize how much a language changes
the play. The humor is different. Sometimes we even have to change
the text.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of Hebrew also brought success. Attending the Gesher
became the rage as Israeli theatergoers, culturally attuned to
temperament and passion in their theater, fell under the spell of
the intensity and professionalism of their new fellow countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   True, the oldest Israeli theater, Habimah, also descended from a
Russian-Jewish troupe of the 1920s, traced its heritage directly to
Stanislavsky. But audiences and critics now found it was no longer
innovative.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, a group of young Israeli actors had founded
the Cameri Theater to introduce a more modern, Anglo-American
tradition, establishing what remains one of Israel's major
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Haifa Municipal Theater, rebelling against the
largely imported content of the Habimah and Cameri, which worked in
the 1970s and 80s to introduce an Israeli-based repertory.
</P>
<P>
   But all of these theaters were organized around seasonal
subscribers, which required a constant flow of new productions,
with a correspondingly uneven quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tradition is very young,'' said Joshua Sobol, a veteran
Israeli playwright whose ``Ghetto'' was seen at Circle in the
Square on Broadway in 1989. Sobol's ``Village'' is one of the two
plays the Gesher is bringing to New York. ``You can say Israeli
acting and directing are based more on instinct than on acquired
professions. I believe we've had some quite remarkable
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``One difference is that the Gesher did not rely on subscribers,
but on open box-office sales. It proved that you can reach a `free'
audience, so to speak. I hope this is also a lesson for the other
theaters. It liberates the theater from a total dependence on a
captive audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite much praise for the Gesher, there have been dissenting
voices. Novel and exotic as it has been to Israeli audiences, the
Gesher is essentially an Israeli version of the classic Soviet or
Russian theater, a close cousin to the Taganka, the Moscow Art
Theater and the Maly in Moscow, whose extensive use of intense
emotion, symbol, stage gimmickry, dramatic lighting and music has
both entranced and irritated Western audiences, especially American
and British theatergoers accustomed to a more subtle approach.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Handelzalts, the theater critic and book review editor
of the Haaretz newspaper, recently created something of a storm
among the Israeli intelligentsia when he panned a Gesher production
of Chekhov's ``Three Sisters,'' the first play that Arye staged in
only one language _ Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the Gesher's popularity that Handelzalts
devoted part of his review to justifying why he dared criticize
Arye at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought a breath of fresh air to the Israeli theater
scene,'' Handelzalts acknowledged in an interview. ``They're very
talented, dedicated, well-schooled; the abilities of their
director, Arye, are very great. But if you've seen Russian theater,
you know they did not invent the wheel. They work within a very
strong tradition, but not the most exciting one. Israel is not
familiar with Russian theater, and so they assume they're God, but
they're not, which I dared say about `Three Sisters.' After the
dissenting view was published, I was looked upon as an enemy of the
people, as almost a traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The plays selected by Lincoln Center have all the ingredients
for which Arye has been lionized and criticized. Both works are
intrinsically Israeli and were created especially for the Gesher.
In that, they add a new element to the art of Arye and his actors:
an interpretation by Russian emigres of the central themes and
myths of their new homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Sobol's ``Village'' (its six performances _ in Hebrew with
simultaneous translation _ begin on Tuesday at Alice Tully Hall) is
the story of a hamlet in Israel in the 1940s, of the loves and
anxieties of its inhabitants, as witnessed by a naive youth named
Yossi.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with amorous affairs, business deals and local
arguments are echoes of major events outside: the battle of El
Alamein, the Nazi death camps, the United Nations vote creating
Israel. The central device is a rotating path, along which Yossi
leads the audience through time and space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in just such a village, in Tel Mond, in the center
of the Sharon Valley,'' Sobol said. ``I grew up in the village in
the early 40s, so the play is based on my memories. For a long time
I wanted to write a play about that period in my life, but it was
contact with Arye that triggered the writing.''
</P>
<P>
   The other play Arye is bringing, ``Adam Resurrected,'' also
deals with the past, but a far more terrible one, and in a far more
arresting and controversial manner. (The six performances begin on
July 14 under a tent in Damrosch Park; there will be four in Hebrew
and two in Russian, with simultaneous translation.)
</P>
<P>
   The production juxtaposes the Holocaust and an Israeli circus
through the mad mind of a German Jew, a former clown who survived a
concentration camp by playing the role of a man-dog for the Nazi
commandant. Now in an asylum in the Negev desert, he relives the
past through scenes that are equally grotesque, terrible and funny.
</P>
<P>
   The play is based on a book by Yoram Kaniuk, an Israeli-born
painter and writer, which was called ``Adam Son of Dog'' in Hebrew
and created a major stir when it was first published in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   As recounted by Kaniuk, 68, the production was a case study in
the integration of the Israeli book and the Russian theater. ``Arye
read the book in English, and he loved it, and he thought it would
make a good production,'' Kaniuk said. ``The only person he thought
could adapt it was a friend of his in Russia, Alexander Chevinsky,
so Chevinsky wrote it in Russian based on the English. Then it was
translated into Hebrew and I went over it. Then it was translated
back into Russian, and when it was done it was translated into
Hebrew.''
</P>
<P>
   For the director and the author, ``Adam Resurrected'' was a
plunge into a horror that neither had experienced directly but that
each had had to confront.
</P>
<P>
   Arye's major innovation was to introduce a circus tent into the
asylum where Kaniuk's action takes place. ``It's not easy to
understand,'' Arye said. ``The circus is all in the feverish mind
of a sick man.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaniuk recalled his youth. ``I worked on ships that brought
refugees here, Holocaust survivors,'' he said. ``I was a typical
young Israeli of the time, and suddenly I met the real Jews. I was
overwhelmed. There was a kind of humor they had about themselves.
They thought they survived maybe because they did something wrong.
They were talking about it all the time. I talked to young people
who grew up in Auschwitz, and knew nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, as an artist in New York, Kaniuk heard of an
instance in which a suicidal man and a boy who behaved as a dog
came together in an insane asylum and brought each other to sanity.
The theme merged with stories he had heard from survivors, and he
began work on his novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me 10 years to write,'' Kaniuk said. ``It's my best
book. The critics loved it, while people are kind of shy about
reading it. But in a play, they are mesmerized. I've seen it in
Berlin. It was the most important moment in my life. My father used
to play the violin behind the scenes for the silent movies in
Berlin, and right there they put a tent and Germans were sitting
there shaking, afraid to laugh. I love the production. Not because
it's my book _ I see it as something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still creates a problem: How can you talk about the
Holocaust in that way? But I'm not talking about the Holocaust. I'm
talking about survival. Jews always tell jokes about survival. You
laugh, otherwise you have to cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
