<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WITHOUT AN ACT DOESN'T NEED ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nomar doesn't need a tissue box, so why should you?
</P>
<P>
   Making the All-Star team is not exactly high on the list of
Nomar Garciaparra priorities. ``I really don't care,'' he insists.
``It doesn't bother me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if Player X or Player Y were to say that, it would
definitely be eye-rolling time. Most players care very much, even
if they pretend otherwise. Most players can quickly switch from
being something resembling a regular guy to what we can refer to as
their Act. Not Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar doesn't have an Act,'' says Jim Corsi. ``He's just a
regular schmoe.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure regular schmoes play a four-star major league
shortstop while slugging .534 (and climbing by the hour), but you
get Corsi's point. The Man Without An Act can live without going to
the major league All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to accept recognition when I know other
people had a lot to do with it,'' he says. ``It's a team game.
That's been my attitude growing up, my whole life. Is it just me,
or is it my teammates? That's tough to judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he belong there? Well, sure. But the three shortstops who
will represent the American League also belong there. That's life,
so get over it. Nomar already has.
</P>
<P>
   Some guys are like that. To them, All-Star Games are fluff. Dave
Cowens was like that. Larry Bird was another one. I rather like the
idea of our star shortstop thinking like those two guys.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar might feel differently about things if you could show him
just exactly what playing in an All-Star Game has to do with
winning a championship. And don't be foolish enough to mention
anything about a ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather have an All-Star ring or a World Series
ring?'' Nomar inquires. ``I'll tell you which one I want to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Nomar, I have no sense of outrage over his absence from the
1998 All-Star team, but for a different reason. Mike Hargrove was
in a lose-lose situation. He was looking at four totally deserving
shortstops, and there was no way he could take more than three.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez was the appropriate fan favorite. Next question.
New York's Derek Jeter is a great player. And then there was Omar
Vizquel, the perennial Gold Glove winner, who just happens to play
for Hargrove's Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guy who's flirting with .300, who is a tough out and
who has made one error since last Aug. 19. He's also a terrific
guy. There's nothing wrong with taking Omar Vizquel.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams understands why Omar Vizquel is on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If if it were Lou Piniella,'' says Williams, ``he'd take
Rodriguez. If it were Joe Torre, he'd take Jeter. If it were me,
I'd take Nomar. You can't go wrong with any of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Accept that it was going to be Rodriguez and Vizquel. Then it's
down to Jeter and Nomar. Who's better? Think Magic (Jeter) and
Larry (Nomar). In New York they'll always think it's Jeter (Magic).
In Boston, people will always think it's Nomar. (Take it one step
farther, and ARod is Michael). If you haven't guessed already, we
are clearly living in the Golden Age of Shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned scout extraordinaire Grover (Deacon) Jones is in town,
and his full sympathies lie with Hargrove. ``I wouldn't want to
make that choice,'' he says. ``I'd say you make it. Or else, flip a
coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar has the power edge, but Jeter is a very reliable hitter
who has made only three errors all season. It is also very possible
Hargrove felt that it was important to homor as many Yankees as
possible, since the team that could conceivably establish the best
winning percentage of all-time does not have a man in the starting
lineup. Only a serious Red Sox zealot would complain about that
line of reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   You really have no idea how little Nomar cares about this
All-Star business. The first All-Star Game he ever saw, live or on
the telly, was last year's, and the only reason for that was that
the league insisted he come as a participant. He has little
interest in seeing next Tuesday's. ``I watch a game every day,'' he
says. ``Every day. Why do I want to see another one?''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, how does anyone expect Nomar to have his mind on
baseball next Tuesday? I mean, c'mon. Tuesday will be the first
World Cup semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar is into this World Cup stuff. Big Time. He had pictured
himself in Marseilles, in person. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``How close did you come to going?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very close.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You had the flights and everything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He finally decided against it. Just too much traveling. But he
was aching to be there. On Tuesday afternoon he'll be watching the
soccer game. On Tuesday evening he'll probably be watching the
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar's not even the worst All-Star omission. How about Brian
Jordan? He's leading the National League in hitting. He's slugging
.585. He won't be in Coors Field, either.
</P>
<P>
   On a scale of All-Star omissions, Nomar's is about a 7. You want
a 10, I'll give you a 10. Try these All-Star break numbers:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HR $ RBI $ Runs $ Hits &QL;
</P>
<P>
   25 $ 100 $ 68 $ 101 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That was Detroit's Hank Greenberg in 1935. He did not make the
All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. _ The Tigers won the 1935 World Series. You think Hank
Greenberg was thinking about the All-Star Game while he was sipping
that champagne?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
