<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TECH-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISION OF ONE-STOP SHOPPING PROPELS MERGER OF PHONE, CABLE, TV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (th) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometime before the end of the century,
high-speed Internet access and low-cost phone calls alike will make
their way into American homes as streams of digital 1's and 0's
over television cables.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, as executives of AT&AMP;T and
Tele-Communications Inc. have scrambled to sell Wall Street and the
American consumer on the wisdom of their ambitious $31.8 billion
merger, one fact has become clear: The technology will tread a
costly path on its way from the laboratory into the home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $1.8 billion TCI will spend to upgrade its
one-way cable network to a two-way service capable of carrying
digital video and sound to its 10.5 million customers, AT&AMP;T will
need to persuade customers to buy advanced set-top boxes that have
connectors for video, computer and telephone, and it will have to
install a new generation of advanced Internet routers capable of
offering clear voice quality, at its own expense.
</P>
<P>
   So, beyond that first $1.8 billion, the final cost for the
entire project could run another $10 billion or more based on an
initial per-customer cost of $750. That cost could eventually fall
as low as $200 per customer sometime after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The actual amount will vary depending on what percentage of
households decide to switch service from their existing phone
company and on how quickly the cost of new Internet telephone
technology falls.
</P>
<P>
   But even assuming that the cost of the AT&AMP;T-TCI scheme allows
any real price competition on telephone calls, consumers will face
sundry logistical problems once the digital telephones arrive in
their homes. For example, most set-top boxes are in living rooms _
the one room often not wired for a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   None of this phases David Nagel, AT&AMP;T's unflappable chief
technology officer, who points out that the nation's largest phone
company has a decade's worth of experience working with the cable
industry on the challenges of digital telephony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys have crawled all over the cable networks, and the
problems are very solvable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, AT&AMP;T has been welcomed as a conquering hero by the cable
industry, which five years ago promised a future of 500 channels
and interactive television only to back off when daunting costs and
consumer apathy dulled that vision with a stubborn coating of
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if it takes five years, AT&AMP;T is going to make
this work,'' said Paul Kagan, president of Paul Kagan &AMP; Associates,
a cable industry research firm in Carmel, Calif. Alluding to TCI's
chairman _ and the cable industry's most ambitious salesman _ he
added, ``There's more here than John Malone trying to make his
stock go up.''
</P>
<P>
   While he acknowledges that a steep investment lies ahead and
several technical challenges must be overcome, others are less
sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've found with technology is that CEOs don't have a clue
about what really needs to be done,'' said Andrew Seybold, a
computer and communications industry analyst and publisher of
Andrew Seybold's Outlook, a newsletter based in Boulder Creek,
Calif. ``The problem is that the technology always takes longer
than people expect.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Seybold worries particularly about reliability, citing the
aftermath of California's North Ridge earthquake in January 1994.
While telephone service was restored in 24 to 48 hours, he said,
cable did not begin to come back for a week and in some cases two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the San Francisco region, TCI's largest service area,
with 1.5 million customers, roughly 10 percent of subscribers have
been upgraded to two-way cables. The company says that figure will
be 50 percent by the end of the year and 90 percent by the end of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   For each city it serves, the first step in an upgrade is for
engineers to cover every inch of the network on foot looking for
older, one-way amplifiers that must be replaced with two-way
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the placement of fiber nodes _ the intersection points
where fiber-optic cables meet the coaxial cables that stretch past
each home _ is adjusted to a ratio of approximately one for every
500 to 1,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   This makes the network more resistant to large-scale failures
and reduces the capacity requirements for the digital networks that
will carry data, voice and video.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, equipment will be added to the central cable plant, or
``head end,'' that will connect the thousands of homes to the
Internet and, in some cases, to traditional telephone networks.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco area, switching from today's cables to a
digital system promises significant cost savings for the network.
TCI owns a powerful fiber-optic ring that encircles the Bay Area,
which it now uses to distribute television programming. In the
future, the huge capacity of that network will make it possible for
AT&AMP;T to economically centralize its switching and routing
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Once the network is in place in each city, AT&AMP;T will immediately
be able to offer old-fashioned ``circuit-switched'' telephone
service over the cable system.
</P>
<P>
   However, by the fall of 1999, a second generation of cable boxes
should be available through consumer electronics outlets
nationwide. Based on a yet-to-be determined standard, these boxes
will permit the complete integration of voice, data and video.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of using circuit switching, which requires a
separate copper-wire path for each call, these will employ ``packet
switching,'' which allows many kinds of information, including
telephone calls, to travel down the same wire at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It is at that point, industry analysts say, that AT&AMP;T will begin
to realize the cost savings that will permit competition with local
phone companies, plus a range of new services, including CD-quality
music and distinctive ringing tones for each member of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Kagan said, the phone company has a powerful financial
weapon as it buys its way into these converged technologies: the
cable franchises will remain monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the secrets of this whole deal,'' he said, ``is that
AT&AMP;T is going to make a bunch of money offering traditional cable
television.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
