<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-STATES-LAW-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES AGAINST STATES ON PATENT SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Texas, Calif., Fla.)   (af)  
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal appeals court has ruled that a New Jersey bank can sue
the state of Florida over the state's unauthorized use of a
college-savings program, saying that states can be sued for
infringing the patent owned by an individual or a company.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington was
welcomed by some patent lawyers, who had worried that a 1996
decision by the U.S. Supreme Court could allow states to use
companies' patents without suffering any legal consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The worries escalated recently when another federal appeals
court cited the Supreme Court's decision in ruling that the
University of Houston, a state school, could not be sued for
publishing the works of an author without her permission.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the three-judge appeals court panel in
Washington ruled against Florida, which had argued that it could
not be sued by the College Savings Bank in Princeton, N.J., in
federal court. The bank owns a 1988 patent on the method it uses to
administer prepaid college tuition accounts, which allow parents to
set aside money for their children's education.
</P>
<P>
   The bank contends that the state of Florida is using the
patented method illegally in its state-run prepaid college tuition
program, which has about $2 billion in deposits and is the largest
such program in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Hubener, an assistant attorney general for Florida, said
that he had not yet seen the decision and could not comment in
detail. But he said there was a ``strong probability'' that the
state would appeal the decision to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The case had been closely watched by experts on intellectual
property and also by states, state universities and other state
institutions, which had argued in the past that they could not be
sued in federal court under the 11th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes to the heart of federalism,'' said Gerald Dodson, a
lawyer representing the regents of the University of California,
which had filed a brief supporting Florida in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision and the earlier decision that prevented an
author from suing the University of Houston, are among the first to
interpret the 1996 Supreme Court ruling that had curbed the
authority of Congress to subject states to lawsuits in federal
court. In that case, a divided Supreme Court said that the federal
Indian Gaming Regulatory Act was an unconstitutional incursion on
state sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the state of Florida relied on that 1996 Supreme
Court decision to argue that another law passed by Congress in 1992
was also unconstitutional. That law allowed private parties to sue
states for patent infringement.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's decision, the appeals court said that Congress had
acted within its power when it passed the 1992 patent law.
</P>
<P>
   ``A state found to have infringed a patent is subject to the
same consequences as a private party infringer, namely damages
subject to trebling, attorney fees and injunctive relief,'' Judge
Raymond Clevenger III wrote in his opinion for the unanimous panel.
The other judges on the panel were William Curtis Bryson and
Randall Rader.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lawyers involved in the case said that the Supreme
Court will likely have to take up the issue again because Tuesday's
ruling conflicts with that of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
earlier this year. That court found that University of Houston
could not be sued for copyright infringement by Denise Chavez, the
author of a book who claims the public university published the
book without her permission.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit panel said that Congress could not limit a
state's immunity to lawsuits involving copyright infringement
because it would be an end-run around the 1996 Supreme Court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the Federal Circuit Court of Appeals said that
the decision in the University of Houston case and a similar
decision by another court ``miss the mark.'' The court said that
the 14th Amendment empowers Congress to prevent states from taking
private property, including patent rights, without the due process
of law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision was clearly a boost for College Savings Bank
in its long-running battle with Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Peter A. Roberts, the bank's chairman, said that he believed
about a dozen states could be violating the bank's 1988 patent. But
he said that the biggest infringer was Florida and the state's
Prepaid Postsecondary Education Expense Board, which administers
its college tuition program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have made a quarter of a million dollars in profits off
our invention,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida denied that it had infringed the bank's patent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
