<HEADLINE>
A SERIES A SEASON IS ENOUGH, STEINBRENNER SAYS OF THE METS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner likes playing the Mets once a
year, but the Yankees' principal owner indicated Wednesday that he
would fight a tentative plan in which the teams would play six
games next year, three at Yankee Stadium and three at Shea. ``It's
just too much,'' Steinbrenner said. ``One series is enough. Once a
year, that's just right. If you do more than that, you're going to
dilute it. I think it should stay like it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner can express his opposition to a home-and-home
series with the Mets by voting against the 1999 schedule when it is
presented for approval at an owners meeting next week in Chicago.
But Steinbrenner is only one of 30 votes, so unless a significant
number of owners feels the way he does, he will probably be unable
to alter what now seems to be moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The players association also has to approve the 1999 schedule,
but it has not expressed any opposition to the home-and-home
interleague concept, which already exists.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees played host to the Mets in 1997, the inaugural year
of interleague play, and last weekend, the Mets played host to the
Yankees at Shea Stadium, drawing 160,740 over three days.
Steinbrenner wants to continue the current format, rather than
expand the number of interleague games, believing that it's
important to maintain the integrity of the intraleague rivalries,
against teams like Boston and Baltimore. Pursuing the World Series
should be the pervasive theme, he said, rather than just winning
city bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets blew that thing into too big of a deal,''
Steinbrenner said. ``I think they did a wonderful job promoting the
thing. They did some things maybe to embarrass me, but I accept
that. I'm happy I was able to help fill their ball park, but next
year it's my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner was not specific about how he believes the Mets
embarrassed him, but officials for both teams chortled over the
Mets' decision to ask Yogi Berra _ the former Yankee star and
manager who has said he won't go to Yankee Stadium as long as
Steinbrenner owns the team _ to throw out the first ball before the
first game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not have done anything intentionally to embarrass
Steinbrenner,'' Mets General Manager Steve Phillips said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the Yankee organization said the team has nothing to
gain by expanding the series _ other than three guaranteed sellouts
every season _ and everything to lose. The Yankees, one official
said, are the dominant team in New York right now and are expected
to beat the Mets, while the Mets would gain notoriety currently
absent from their organization if they won a series against the
Yankees, and at least temporarily altered their little brother
image. Joe Torre said before last weekend's series that he looked
forward to getting the three days over with.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said he disagreed with the Mets' decision to market
ticket packaging plans in conjunction with the games against the
Yankees. Within one limited plan, fans who agreed to buy a ticket
to the Yankees-Mets games last weekend were also required to
purchase a handful of tickets to other games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's forcing people to buy tickets,'' Steinbrenner said,
``and I just don't think that's a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
