<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORENSTAM, BACK IN STRIDE, AIMING TO REDUCE PRESSURE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Annika Sorenstam has learned to avoid mistakes.
She has also learned to grow from them.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the United States Women's Open in both 1995 and
1996, Sorenstam arrived at last year's national championship intent
on making history.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of becoming the first woman to win three consecutive
Opens, Sorenstam missed the cut, weighed down by the expectations
and the self-inflicted pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when this year's United States Open begins on Thursday at
Blackwolf Run, Sorenstam will be in the spotlight once again. She
has won her last two starts, including last week's ShopRite LPGA
Classic in Absecon, N.J. In 11 starts on the Ladies Professional
Golf Association tour this year, Sorenstam has a remarkable 10
top-10 finishes. However, after last year's humbling experience at
the Open, Sorenstam has vowed to take each day this week as it
comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot last year, so I'm just going to be calm,''
said Sorenstam, who is the most consistent women's player in the
world at age 27. ``I really wanted it badly last year and it just
didn't work,'' she said. ``It's a special week, but if I don't keep
my same routine, I won't play the same. It is easy to get too
anxious, easy to overpractice, easy to get away from the normal
things that I do at a normal tournament. I get more nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sorenstam is one of the favorites, Donna Andrews,
Liselotte Neumann, Karrie Webb and Pat Hurst are among those who
are playing well entering the third women's major of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult for this year's tournament to surpass the
drama of last year's Open at Pumpkin Ridge Golf Club in Cornelius,
Ore., when Alison Nicholas won by a stroke over Nancy Lopez, once
again denying Lopez the title she wants the most. Lopez missed a
15-foot downhill putt for birdie on the final hole that would have
forced an 18-hole Monday playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me about three months to get over it,'' said Lopez,
who has finished second at the Open four times. ``I watched the
video for a few months and just kept thinking, `What could I do
different, what did I not do right?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez will be the sentimental favorite again this year, but
there are many compelling story lines. Donna Andrews, who leads the
LPGA money list, would love to continue her best season with a
victory in a major. ``I don't think anybody has noticed I'm at the
top of the money list yet,'' said Andrews, who has won $559,407 so
far this year. ``I sort of snuck up there, and nobody was paying
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nicholas has been somewhat overlooked since her
victory last year, and has been unable to play consistently. A
chest infection hampered Nicholas for several months earlier this
year, and she would love to use this week as a springboard to
strong second half of the season. ``I don't feel that much pressure
to repeat,'' said Nicholas, a native of England. ``I have been ill
and haven't played that much. I am not expecting a great deal this
week, but I wasn't this time last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Measuring 6,412 yards, Blackwolf Run is one of the longest
courses ever to host a United States Women's Open, and it features
huge, undulating greens that should produce many three-putts and
four-putts. Nicholas' winning score last year was 10 under par, but
that will be difficult to equal this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hole has a different personality,'' Lopez said. ``This
golf course is going to take a lot of patience, probably more than
any U.S. Open course I have played in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
