<SLUG> BC-HUBBELL-STARR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ADMONISHES STARR IN DISMISSING TAX CHARGES AGAINST HUBBELL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge Wednesday dismissed tax evasion
charges against Webster Hubbell, and rebuked independent counsel
Kenneth Starr for overreaching his authority and violating the
rights of the former assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Saying Starr's prosecutors were on a ``quintessential fishing
expedition,'' U.S. District Judge James Robertson threw out the 10
tax-related charges after finding that the case was built on
records Hubbell turned over with the understanding they would not
be used to prosecute him.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's use of the documents ``violates the immunity
given to Mr. Hubbell'' and thus turned him ``into the primary
informant against himself,'' Robertson said in his ruling, the most
recent in a series of court setbacks for Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, who was appointed to the bench by President Clinton,
also dismissed related charges against Hubbell's wife, Suzanna,
accountant Charles Owen and tax lawyer Mike Schaufele.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ruled that Starr had failed to get proper
permission through Attorney General Janet Reno to investigate the
tax-related case. The charges against Hubbell ``neither relates to
nor arises out of'' the various subjects involving Clinton that
Starr had been authorized to investigate, Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed more than four years ago to investigate the
president's business dealings in Arkansas, Starr's mandate has been
expanded to include firings at the White House travel office, the
misuse of FBI files by Clinton operatives, the death of deputy
White House counsel Vincent Foster and the alleged presidential
affair and cover-up involving Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's ruling said Starr ``has identified no common
witnesses, described no similar patterns of conduct, cited no
similar applicable law'' related to his other areas of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's ruling came less than a week after a hearing at
which he voiced discomfort with the case and told prosecutors they
have a ``very scary'' view of the Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell expressed surprise late Wednesday over the quickness of
Robertson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very, very grateful and hopeful that this is the end of
a long process that has lasted five years,'' Hubbell told reporters
outside his Washington home. ``Now maybe you folks won't have to
come out here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying other court decisions conflict with Robertson's opinion,
Starr said he ``will seek prompt review of the ruling'' by an
appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton learned of the decision in China, where he is winding up
a nine-day tour. ``This decision speaks for itself, but I'm happy
for Webb and Suzy and their family, Mike and his family and Charlie
and his family,'' Clinton said through White House spokesman Mike
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, a golfing buddy of the president and former law partner
of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, was indicted in late April.
The indictment accused Hubbell of not paying taxes on ``hundreds of
thousands of dollars in consulting fees'' he had received after
resigning from the Justice Department in March 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1994, Hubbell pleaded guilty to tax evasion and mail
fraud charges and agreed to cooperate with Starr's investigation of
the Clinton's involvement in the failed Whitewater development and
their relationship to owners of Madison Guaranty Savings and Loan.
Hubbell subsequently was unable to recall details considered key to
Starr's investigation of the Clintons' business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   While Hubbell was serving 19 months in prison, Starr went after
his tax records as part of an investigation into whether Clinton
friends and supporters paid Hubbell ``hush money'' in the form of
consulting fees for little or no work so he would remain silent
about the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell argued that turning over the records, which indicate
that he underreported his income when calculating his federal
taxes, would violate his right to avoid self-incrimination. A
federal judge in Arkansas granted Hubbell immunity from prosecution
and ordered him to turn over more than 13,000 pages of documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The subpoena served on Mr. Hubbell was the quintessential
fishing expedition,'' Robertson said in the opinion issued
Wednesday. ``The independent counsel freely admits that he was not
investigating tax-related charges when he issued it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the dismissal of the tax charges against Hubbell is upheld on
appeal, Starr's inquiry into Mrs. Clinton's controversial work for
Madison Guaranty could be hampered. Also cast in doubt by this
decision is Starr's ability to go forward with his investigation
into billing practices while she was a member of the Rose Law Firm
in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's decision comes less than a week after the Supreme
Court ruled that a lawyer for Foster, the late deputy White House
counsel, does not have to turn over to prosecutors his notes of
conversations with Foster.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the high court recently refused an emergency
hearing on Starr's efforts to compel grand jury testimony from
Secret Service officers and White House counsel Bruce Lindsey in
the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a federal judge last week released from prison former
Clinton business partner Susan McDougal, who was serving time on a
contempt charge brought by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
