<HEADLINE>
HEADS OF VOLVO AND VOLKSWAGEN HOLD TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Sweden)  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Volvo AB of Sweden confirmed Wednesday that
its chief executive had discussions last Friday with the chairman
of Volkswagen AG, Ferdinand Piech, as the stock prices of both
companies jumped on speculation of a possible alliance or merger.
</P>
<P>
   But while Volvo executives discouraged suggestions that any kind
of agreement was imminent, the company has long acknowledged that
it is seeking strategic partners. And Volkswagen, which is buying
Rolls-Royce Motor Cars, has made no secret of its desire to acquire
a truck business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can confirm that Piech was here on Friday, but they have
regular meetings from time to time,'' said Stefan Lorentzson, a
spokesman at Volvo's headquarters in Goteborg, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Wednesday that Piech had
initiated the meeting with Leif Johansson and that Volkswagen's
primary interest was in Volvo's truck business.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Volkswagen and Volvo climbed on the news. VW leaped
73.50 marks, to 1,816.50; Volvo rose 19.5 kronor, to 257.
</P>
<P>
   Fortified by strong sales and $11 billion in cash and short-term
securities, Volkswagen has been on a buying spree in the last
several months. After a brutal bidding war against BMW AG, the
company struck a deal last month to acquire Rolls for $703 million.
Since then, Volkswagen has announced that its Audi unit will
acquire Lamborghini SpA, the Italian manufacturer of
high-performance sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   But Piech has also said he would like to expand in the truck
industry, and there has been speculation for months that Volkswagen
might try to reach a deal with Scania AB of Sweden, MAN AG of
Germany or Volvo. Though Volvo's biggest business is in
automobiles, trucks generated sales of 51 billion kronor, or $6.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen made about 263,000 trucks last year, a minuscule
slice of the 4.25 million vehicles it produced. In a recent
interview with a German newspaper, Piech said he hoped to add one
or two truck brands.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen already has business relationships with both Scania
and Volvo. Scania markets Volkswagen and Audi cars in Sweden. Volvo
buys engines for some of its cars from Volkswagen's Audi unit.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo executives have acknowledged that they are looking for new
partnerships, because they remain a small player in a market
increasingly dominated by behemoths. Daimler-Benz AG's agreement to
take over Chrysler Corp. for $39 billion ignited a storm of
speculation about the future of Europe's smaller car companies,
including Renault and Peugeot of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a niche player,'' acknowledged Lorentzson of Volvo,
which makes about 400,000 vehicles a year. ``We think we can
survive as an independent company, but we have said we need
partnerships with other companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Wednesday that a merger of Volvo and Volkswagen
would present few conflicts between their product lines. Although
Volvo and Volkswagen's Audi unit both produce comparatively upscale
automobiles, Volvos are marketed primarily as family cars while
Audis appeal to sportier and faster tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are competitors to some degree, but they are positioned
very differently,'' said Georg Sturzer, an automobile analyst at
Bayerische Vereinsbank in Munich. ``There isn't much overlap.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also noted Wednesday that Volvo could be more
accessible to Volkswagen than other companies. Scania is controlled
by the Swedish holding company Investor AB, which is controlled by
Sweden's Wallenberg family. Wirtschaftswoche, a German business
magazine, reported last month that Investor would not sell Scania
for less than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo stock, by contrast, is broadly distributed among investors
and is therefore more vulnerable to an unsolicited offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volvo is still very much a small player in a large pool of
sharks,'' said Stephen Reitman, an auto industry analyst at Merrill
Lynch in London. Though Volvo could once take comfort at being of
similar scale as Daimler's Mercedes-Benz or BMW, that is no longer
true. BMW has expanded through growth and its acquisition several
years ago of Rover Group of Britain. When it merges with Chrysler,
Daimler will produce more than 4 million vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is going to happen to Volvo in the next few years,''
Reitman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
