<HEADER>
A6846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-TOBACCO-2TAKES-NYT     07-01 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-TOBACCO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT ATTORNEY GENERAL SEEKS FREEZE ON TOBACCO ASSETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN RABINOVITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Seeking to sidestep months of grinding
litigation, Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal asked a
judge Wednesday to immediately rule that tobacco companies have
violated the state's consumer trade law by lying about the health
effects and addictive nature of tobacco. He also demanded that the
court freeze at least $10 billion of the companies' assets to
guarantee that they would be able to pay damages.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the action, Blumenthal requested that Superior Court
Judge Michael Sheldon in Waterbury order the companies to stop
marketing their products to teenagers, to cease selling cigarettes
from vending machines, to no longer claim that there is
``scientific controversy'' whether smoking causes diseases and to
take several other steps to reduce tobacco use.
</P>
<P>
   The move is significant, because it would be the first time that
a court would rule on the legality of the tobacco industry's past
business practices. While the industry settled four suits brought
by states for Medicaid claims in Florida, Minnesota, Mississippi
and Texas, none of those agreements affect cases in other states. A
ruling in the Connecticut case could establish an important
precedent for the 36 other states waging cases against tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Several legal experts said that the state's attempt to get this
ruling on the narrow issue of violations of trade law was
promising.
</P>
<P>
   But these lawyers cast a doubtful eye on Connecticut's bid to
freeze some industry assets, a measure no other state has
attempted, saying that a court would have trouble seeing why it
needed to take such a drastic step to insure that this wealthy
industry would have the resources to honor any future decisions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blumenthal's action comes two weeks after the tobacco industry
succeeded in derailing legislation in Congress that would have
regulated tobacco sales, restricted advertising and forced the
industry to reimburse states for millions of dollars in medical
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The motion that Connecticut filed Wednesday was a dramatic shot
across the industry's bow, signaling that the battle has once again
shifted back to the states and that the cases brought by the
attorneys general will be heating up in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives Wednesday dismissed Blumenthal's step
as little more than posturing by a politician who faces an election
in November. ``AG stands for attention grabber,'' remarked Richard
Verheij, general counsel for U.S. Tobacco Co., which is one of the
companies named in Wednesday's motions. And Gregory Little,
associate general counsel for Philip Morris, also named in the
motion, added that Blumenthal's news conference this morning was
further proof ``that the most dangerous place in Connecticut is
between Dick Blumenthal and a camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal insisted that the effort was prompted solely by the
collapse of the Congressional tobacco legislation last month and
his concern that any longer delay in this case would allow hundreds
more people in Connecticut to become addicted to cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The state does not have a trial date scheduled, though it
launched its suit against tobacco companies for Medicaid
reimbursement almost two years ago. Wednesday, Blumenthal said that
he wanted to ``fast track'' the legal process by first having the
court rule on just one aspect of the state's initial case: whether
the companies violated the State Unfair Trade Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   The state contends that the industry broke that law when it
marketed cigarettes to minors and provided inaccurate information
about the health effects of cigarettes. If the judge agrees to
consider this issue first _ to ``bifurcate'' the case _ the law
would require the judge to decide the matter without a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Under Blumenthal's plan, Sheldon would first decide whether to
order the companies to cease this behavior and begin running
anti-smoking programs. Next he would determine whether any money
was due to the state under the trade law. Finally he would convene
a jury to consider other aspects of the case, which could lead to
damages of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached a turning point in our lawsuit, now that our
hopes for a meaningful national settlement have been dashed and
prospects for Congressional action are dim,'' Blumenthal said this
morning. ``We must stop Big Tobacco from cultivating its real cash
crop _ unending fields of newly addicted children _ to preserve its
financial empire.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added that if the state could win some ``specific legally
binding judicial findings that the defendants' misconduct has
created a public health crisis in this state,'' those rulings could
establish precedents across the nation in other state and federal
courts.
</P>
<P>
   John Coffee, a law professor at Columbia University who tracks
tobacco litigation, called Connecticut's move ``eminently sensible
litigation strategy'' to quickly win the various anti-smoking
measures that were lost when the federal legislation foundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can establish in this case that the companies behaved
fraudulently, it could make all other cases a lay down slam dunk,''
Coffee added, noting that this could be the first final court
ruling on this matter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, Coffee and other lawyers said that the effort to force
the companies to put up a bond of $2 billion each was ``dubious.''
Given the extensive financial resources of the companies, they
said, there was no reason to require companies to put up such money
as security in the event that the court awarded damages.
</P>
<P>
   And the tobacco companies were even harsher in their assessment
of Blumenthal's approach.
</P>
<P>
   The case seeks to freeze some assets of Phillip Morris Inc.,
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp.,
Lorillard Tobacco Co. and U.S. Tobacco Co., and several of the
companies Wednesday issued statements that the idea was absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Blumenthal today entered the fairy tale land of Lewis
Carroll's Queen of Hearts who said, `Sentence first, verdict
afterwards,''' said Thomas McKim, assistant general counsel of R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco, noting that it made no sense ``to freeze $10
billion of tobacco company assets on the theory that his case might
hold up, if it ever reaches trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Several tobacco industry lawyers said that anti-smoking
advocates had lost recent cases, a point that their opponents
dispute, and that Blumenthal was acting desperately because of his
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   And Verheij of U.S. Tobacco said that judges would be reluctant
to break the case in half and deal immediately with the trade
practices issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bifurcation tends to be very inefficient in terms of judicial
resources,'' Verheij said. ``You end up covering a lot of the same
ground twice.''
</P>
<P>
   And he questioned why such a step was suddenly necessary.
``Blumenthal filed the case almost two years ago, and you have to
ask what is different today that you suddenly need this
extraordinary remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   And the tobacco companies were even harsher in their assessment
of Blumenthal's approach.
</P>
<P>
   The case seeks to freeze some assets of Phillip Morris Inc.,
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp.,
Lorillard Tobacco Co. and U.S. Tobacco Co., and several of the
companies Wednesday issued statements that the idea was absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Blumenthal today entered the fairy tale land of Lewis
Carroll's Queen of Hearts who said, `Sentence first, verdict
afterwards,''' said Thomas McKim, assistant general counsel of R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco, noting that it made no sense ``to freeze $10
billion of tobacco company assets on the theory that his case might
hold up, if it ever reaches trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Several tobacco industry lawyers said that anti-smoking
advocates had lost recent cases, a point that their opponents
dispute, and that Blumenthal was acting desperately because of his
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   And Verheij of U.S. Tobacco said judges would be reluctant to
break the case in half and deal immediately with the trade
practices issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bifurcation tends to be very inefficient in terms of judicial
resources,'' Verheij said. ``You end up covering a lot of the same
ground twice.''
</P>
<P>
   And he questioned why such a step was suddenly necessary.
``Blumenthal filed the case almost two years ago, and you have to
ask what is different today that you suddenly need this
extraordinary remedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
