<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AS EXPECTED, FED LEAVES INTEREST RATES UNCHANGED
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day meeting, the Federal Reserve Board, as expected,
decided not to change interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Several new economic reports indicate that the economy is
cooling, which might be the reason for the move. The National
Association of Purchasing Management index for June fell to 49.6
from 51.4 in May, the first time in two years that the level has
dropped below 50.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department also reported that construction slumped
1.5 percent in May, the worst drop in more than four years, and the
Conference Board's indicator of future economic activity remained
unchanged from April to May at 105.2.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. manufacturers have slowed production to the lowest rate of
growth since 1995, the clearest effect so far of the Asian crisis
on the American economy. Production is slowing in large part
because stockpiles of unsold goods have surged, but also because
companies are becoming worried that economic growth cannot continue
at the brisk pace of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING REPORT BOLSTERS SHARES
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Boeing rose 6.45 percent after the company gave a
glowing report on its recovery to analysts and reporters. The jet
maker said that it delivered 61 airplanes in June, the highest
one-month total ever, and was on course to meet its goal of
delivering 550 jets this year. Even so, many Wall Street analysts
remain bearish on Boeing, citing price competition with Airbus, its
European rival, continuing weakness in Asia and the specter of
rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   DOW CLIMBS BACK ABOVE 9,000
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 1.1 percent, closing above
9,000 for the first time in three weeks. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index set another record, jumping to 1,148.56.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond remained at 5.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK RALLY CONTINUES IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese stock market extended its rally for a sixth
consecutive day, logging its third-largest single-day gain this
year, on expectations that the government's plan for cleaning up
the nation's problem loans will spur an economic revival.
</P>
<P>
   STAR BANC TO ACQUIRE FIRSTAR
</P>
<P>
   Star Banc announced plans to acquire Firstar for stock worth
about $7.2 billion. The deal would create a banking company with
$38 billion in assets and outlets in 10 states, mostly in the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO CONFIRMS VW TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Volvo of Sweden confirmed that its chief executive had
discussions last Friday with the chairman of Volkswagen amid
speculation of a possible alliance or merger between the two
automakers. Although Volvo executives discouraged suggestions that
any kind of agreement was imminent, the company has long
acknowledged that it is seeking strategic partners. And Volkswagen,
which is buying Rolls-Royce Motor Cars, has made no secret of its
desire to acquire a truck business. The stock prices of both
companies surged.
</P>
<P>
   A STRONGER FOCUS ON WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of companies are marketing directly to women
the products and services that were once pitched almost exclusively
to men, because they want to let women know they want their
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
