<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EDDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARD EDDY, 77, EDUCATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Pa., N.Y., Mass., Colo., N.H.)   (bl)  
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Danforth Eddy, an educator, college administrator and
frequent commentator on women's education and educational
excellence, died June 28 at his home in South Kingstown, R.I. He
was 77.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was prostate cancer, according to the Avery-Storti
Funeral Home in Wakefield, a village in South Kingstown.
</P>
<P>
   In his last academic post, Eddy was president of the University
of Rhode Island, where he served from 1983 to 1991. Since then, he
was engaged in community affairs and served as chairman of the
Providence Blueprint for Education, or Probe, and as a catalyst for
improvements in public education throughout Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Eddy was an authority on land grant colleges. His history of
such institutions, ``Colleges for Our Land and Time: The Land Grant
Idea in American Education'' (Harper &AMP; Row, 1957), remains a
classic on the subject and was issued in French and Spanish
editions.
</P>
<P>
   He was the author of ``The College Influence on Student
Character'' (1959), a study he conducted for the American Council
on Education. Financed by the Ford and Calkin Foundations, it
concluded, essentially, that a climate of intellectual excellence
builds character.
</P>
<P>
   Eddy also wrote studies that compared private colleges in
Pennsylvania in terms of quality, costs and faculty appointments.
In addition, he contributed many articles for national
publications.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the executive board of HERS/Mid-Atlantic. The
organization, Higher Education Resource Services, promotes
opportunities for women who are college students.
</P>
<P>
   Eddy was born in Saratoga Springs, N.Y. He graduated from
Cornell University in 1944 and received a master of divinity degree
from Yale University in 1946 and a Ph.D. from Cornell in 1956. He
started his career as associate director of Cornell's interfaith
office in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   From 1949 to 1960 he was associated with the University of New
Hampshire, serving as acting president in 1954 and 1955 and as
provost and a vice president from 1955 to 1960. He then served as
president of Chatham College in Pittsburgh and as provost of
Pennsylvania State University before moving to Rhode Island in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 49 years, Mary Schurman Eddy; two
sons, Edward Eddy III of Los Angeles, and David Eddy Spicer of
Cambridge, Mass.; two daughters, Mary Eddy of Denver and Catherine
Hahn of Ashland, N.H., and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
