<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOUSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' HOUSTON GETS GOOD REPORT AFTER SURGERY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After playing through the Knicks' playoff run with a
sore left knee, guard Allan Houston underwent arthroscopic surgery
Wednesday to remove a piece of loose cartilage in order to
alleviate the minor problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' team physician, Dr. Norman Scott, performed the
procedure at Beth Israel Hospital North Division.
</P>
<P>
   Houston will begin a three- to six-week rehabilitation process
beginning Thursday at his home under Scott's guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surgery was a complete success,'' the Knicks' president,
Ernie Grunfeld, said. ``We expect a full and quick recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston will not be able to rehabilitate his knee at the Knicks'
practice facility because of the National Basketball Association
lockout. If labor peace had been reached before Tuesday's midnight
deadline and a lockout had been averted, Houston would have
probably waited to have the surgery until after the world
championships, July 29-Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was selected to the USA Basketball team, but like the
other NBA players involved, he will not participate as a result of
the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
