<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAUTION FLAGS AT THE FDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 2:
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal of two prescription drugs from the market
suggests that the Food and Drug Administration may be having some
trouble balancing political demands to speed up the drug approval
process while maintaining its tradition of rigorous safety review.
Jane Ellen Henney, President Clinton's nominee to head the FDA,
will face the tough job of improving the agency's efficiency while
resisting pressures from Congress and the drug industry that can
undermine the cause of public safety.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the painkiller Duract was removed from pharmacy
shelves after just 11 months on the market because it caused dozens
of cases of serious liver failure and four deaths in people using
the drug longer than 10 days. Earlier in June, Posicor, a drug used
to treat high blood pressure, was pulled following disclosures that
it can be lethal if taken in combination with other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both drugs, approved in 1997, underwent FDA reviews that lasted
more than a year. The agency's administrators insist that rigorous
safety standards were met, and attribute the bad results to the
failure of doctors and consumers to follow warning labels. Critics
say that pressure to get more drugs to market may be creating an
atmosphere in the agency that tilts it toward approving products
that might have been held up for more study in earlier years.
Ninety-two new drugs were approved in 1996 and 1997, compared with
50 in the preceding two years. FDA officials say the higher number
merely reflects the agency's ability to process more drug
applications due to recent increases in its staff.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the troubling spate of recent drug recalls,
including the diet drug Redux and its cousin Pondimin last
September, makes this an appropriate time for the FDA's leadership
to review agency safeguards. There is good reason to speed up
review for new drugs for cancer and other life-threatening
illnesses for which there are no substitutes on the market. But
breakthrough drugs actually account for only 20 percent of the new
drugs approved. The majority of approvals are for drugs, like
Duract and Posicor, that treat ailments for which there are other
drug therapies available. In such cases, there is little public
benefit from speedy approval of new products that might expose
consumers to harm.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA moved to take Duract and Posicor off the market because
they are not lifesaving drugs and because there are other options
that do not pose the same safety risks. That standard might best be
applied before the drugs are sold. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
