<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-PRODUCTION-SPI     07-01 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PRODUCTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING NOW TO FOCUS ON BUILDING PLANES EFFICIENTLY, BOOSTING
PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing's top brass said Wednesday they finally have a
handle on the company's commercial jet production problems and will
now shift the focus to boosting overall profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a tough nine months here,'' Boeing Chairman Phil
Condit told analysts in a conference call Wednesday. ``It is
something I never want to repeat.''
</P>
<P>
   While the company's biggest challenge the first half of this
year was to get its bottlenecked assembly lines running smoothly,
Condit said the next six months will be devoted to ``getting the
cost down and starting to return some good (financial)
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   During a progress report on the company's aircraft production
status, Boeing Commercial Airplane Group President Ron Woodard
impressed analysts by reporting 61 airplane deliveries for the
month of June, bringing its second-quarter total to 139.
</P>
<P>
   The company had been struggling for months to fill its airplane
orders on time and is still running about a month behind schedule
on deliveries. But last month's numbers show a dramatic turnaround
in both the pace of aircraft production and delivery to airline
customers.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing didn't meet its target of delivering 142 airplanes
in the second quarter, it was better than many analysts had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of this year, Boeing delivered 247 airplanes,
keeping the company on track to reach its goal of 550 for the year,
compared with 375 last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate conference call to the news media, Boeing
officials said the company has met the production goals it set last
October, when parts shortages, a lack of trained workers and other
glitches caused assembly line backups and behind-schedule
manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was forced to shut down certain assembly lines for a
month to help clear the bottlenecks. The problems hit just as
Boeing was trying to raise production to unprecedented levels to
meet rising demand from a financially strong airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly more stable than we were in October, and we
are in better shape on all fronts,'' Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors welcomed the news, sending Boeing's stock up $2.875 to
$47.44 on the New York Stock Exchange, still well below the peak of
$60.50 hit last July.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's production problems have cost the company $3 billion so
far and led to last year's loss of $178 million _ the first annual
loss in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Woodard said manufacturing improvements have been
made in all areas. Boeing's percentage of overtime hours fell to
14.1 percent in June from 14.7 percent the previous month, yet was
still shy of the goal of 13.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing officials are still closely monitoring production
of the next generation 737 models _ which has been the most
troubled assembly line _ Woodard said the number of jobs behind
schedule on those models fell to 4,751 in June from 7,767 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's companywide employment has remained relatively stable,
but the payroll will now begin to decline, Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of job cuts this year is still not known but
officials said it will most likely be lower than the 12,000
commercial division job cuts originally projected in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we get better and better on production, we will be focusing
on our headcount,'' Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to release new employment projections July
23 along with second-quarter financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Boeing's recent success in getting a high number of
airplanes built and delivered, the biggest challenge now is to
prevent 1998 from ending up as a year of ``profitless prosperity,''
said Paine Webber analyst Jack Modzelewski.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question Boeing can build airplanes quickly ... the
big question is can you build them profitably?'' Modzelewski asked
Condit during the conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Condit acknowledged that Boeing is in no position to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to be satisfied with where we are,'' he said.
``We have a lot of production efficiencies to get into our
plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing still faces a big production increase on the next
generation 737 models. The company currently produces 14 of those
models a month but will increase that to 21 in October.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're reporting good (delivery) numbers but until they get
their 737s up to the full (production) rate, I won't be
comfortable,'' said analyst Paul Nisbet with JSA Research in
Newport, R.I. ``Their costs are still not coming down.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dark cloud hanging over Boeing is the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it has 19 commercial airplanes in storage, many
of which are earmarked for Asian airlines that can't afford to take
delivery of the planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to closely watch the developments in Asia with
concern,'' Woodard said. ``If the situation continues to worsen we
can expect further softening of wide-body demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said last month it will cut production of jumbo 747s by
30 percent next year because Asia's economic slowdown prompted
airlines to delay delivery and order smaller planes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
