You take can some precautions to protect yourself from the hazards
of heat and sun when working outdoors. It takes about 15 days for
the average person to become acclimated to the hot weather. Don't
launch into a long strenuous project on the first hot, humid day of
summer; start with smaller jobs for brief periods early in the
season, then work up to larger tasks. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York
Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 1, 1998 -- BROOKLYN-ROWHOUSE, 7-1 --
Laurie Miller stands outside the little Bedford-Stuyvesant row
house that she never forgot. When her mother, a nurse, died of
cancer at 51, and the house was foreclosed upon, Laurie Miller and
her siblings, all in their early 20s, had to move out. That was in
1981. After keeping an eye on the house for nearly two decades, Ms.
Miller bought it in March Q and brought her pastor over to bless
it. ``When I actually moved in, I said to myself, If you can do
this, you can do anything,'' she says. (Don Hogan Charles/New York
Times Photo)
