Randal Vaughn, a professor of information systems at Baylor
University, uses his laptop while sitting on bench on campus.
Vaughn, who uses Pow Wow's chat to extend his reach to his students
says his three undergraduate classes tended to be large, each with
about 50 students. The computer chat has helped him reach more
students, extending his office hours by allowing him to meet with
many of them on line. (Rod Aydelotte/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SEATTLE -- July 1, 1998 -- CIR-HUMONGOUS-DAY, 7-1 --
Shelley Day, the chief executive of the Humongous Entertainment
software company, poses with a cardboard cutout of Putt-putt, one
of the characters featured in the interactive games she designs for
children. In the next few months Ms. Day's company will introduce
stuffed toys, a clothing line, a CD-ROM series based on the
Nickelodeon show ``Blue's Clues'' and a Saturday morning cartoon
show based on original Humongous characters including Putt-Putt,
Freddi Fish and Pajama Sam. (Robert Sorbo/New York Times Photo)
