</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PITCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REED AND LEITER, AT LEAST, GET GOOD NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ On a miserable afternoon for Mets pitchers, there were
at least two bright spots: Rick Reed was selected to the National
League team for next Tuesday's All-Star Game, and there were signs
that Al Leiter might be sidelined a lot less than four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, who tore a tendon in his left knee while pitching
against the Yankees last Friday night, had been hoping he could
return in fewer than the four to six weeks that doctors originally
estimated he would miss.
</P>
<P>
   At first the tear was believed to be 50 percent, and surgery was
an option. Now the Mets have been told it is closer to 15 percent,
and surgery appears unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Leiter, the Mets' best starter this season, could
rejoin the rotation next week, General Manager Steve Phillips said,
``I'm not planning on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he was injured, Leiter seemed a sure bet to be selected
for the All-Star Game. Now, Reed and catcher Mike Piazza will be
the Mets' representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' said the 32-year-old Reed, who has
gone from being a replacement player during the 1995 strike to
being named an All-Star. ``I'm looking forward to it, I'm excited
about it. It's been a long road with a lot of bumps. To be involved
in something like this, to be in the same locker room with those
guys, I'll probably just sit back in the corner and just admire
everything. Heck, that's what I do here.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Reed, who is 9-5 this season with a 2.71 earned
run average, was something of a surprise considering that he is
scheduled to pitch in Atlanta on Sunday. The National League
manager, Jim Leyland of the Florida Marlins, had indicated he would
pass over anyone throwing the day before the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought he would be able to pitch on Tuesday on
one day's rest, Reed did not hesitate. ``Heck, yeah,'' he said.
``It will be my side day. If I only face one hitter, it doesn't
matter to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2153EDT &QL; 
