<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-WILLIAMS-NYT &LR;      07-01 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS IS BACK, BUT FOR HOW LONG?  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernie Williams shook more hands in the Yankees'
clubhouse than grooms do at weddings as teammates welcomed him back
from his rehabilitation assignment in Tampa, Fla., and
congratulated him for being one of the five Yankees chosen for the
American League All-Star team Wednesday. But there are indications
that those salutations could turn into goodbyes once the 1998
season ends.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Williams' agreeing to an $8.25 million contract and
avoiding arbitration, he requested that the Yankees have no
negotiations with him or Scott Boras, his agent, during the season
and stressed that he wanted to gauge interest when his pact
expires, a person familiar with the conversations said Wednesday.
General Manager Brian Cashman confirmed that Williams explicitly
asked to be left alone and that the Yankees have honored this by
not talking with him or Boras for more than four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that he didn't want to negotiate during the season
and that he didn't want it to be a distraction,'' Cashman said.
``He told me that he wants to test the free-agent market. I told
him I could speak for myself about that, but I couldn't speak for
my owner. If he changes his mind, we'd love to talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is not likely to change his mind and Boras is
interested in getting his client on the open market to see how much
a team will pay a switch-hitting center fielder with power who hits
.300, who is two-time All-Star and who won a Gold Glove award.
Williams brushed aside questions about his free agency Wednesday
and said that ``things will take care of themselves.'' Still, it
has become more obvious that Williams is curious to see what life
is like outside of Yankeeland and the request for no dialogue is
the first step toward leaving an organization he has been with
since he was 17 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed a desire to stay here, but he expressed an
extreme desire to see what his value is on the market,'' said
Cashman, who said he would defy the no-negotiation request if
George Steinbrenner ordered him to. ``He's earned that right. We
would love to have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
