<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6871 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      07-01 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALK UP 5.3 MILLION FOR MALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ If you break down the numbers, it works out to
$530,000 per word. Or $353,333.33 per syllable. Or $132,500 per
letter.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what you get once you cut out all the legal
mumbo jumbo, the self-serving pronouncements and the half-baked
attempt at social engineering. None of that means a thing.
</P>
<P>
   What's important is the $5.3 million settlement and a 10-word
phrase that almost gets lost in the paperwork:
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is liable for the death of Edward Mallet.''
</P>
<P>
   As statements go, it's as obvious now as it was the moment
paramedics lifted Mallet's lifeless body off the pavement at a
Circle K at 27th and Campbell avenues on the hot evening of Aug.
27, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   That night, a man with no drugs, no gun and no legs was killed
for resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else is cow flop. The city's hired hands have been
spreading it thick and deep for five years, stinking to high
heaven, costing you a bundle and putting the family of a dead
25-year-old through an unnecessary ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's over.
</P>
<P>
   But at what cost?
</P>
<P>
   Getting the city to own up to a botched arrest took a lawsuit, a
five-week jury trial, court costs, lawyers fees and, finally, a
multimillion-dollar settlement.
</P>
<P>
   All that to admit a mistake everyone recognized but the police
department's arrogant top brass, the namby-pamby politicians
running city government and the by-the-hour legal gunslingers hired
to do their bidding.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a civil trial in March, during which the city's
lawyers said police had done nothing wrong, a jury awarded the
Mallet family $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our earnest hope that the findings of this jury will
have the appropriate impact on law enforcement agencies that have
the responsibility to serve and protect the diverse citizens of the
community,'' Doug Anderson, a juror from Mesa, read from a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   They had heard testimony about how the one-time gang-banger and
part-time motivational speaker was been pulled over by police that
August night.
</P>
<P>
   About how Mallet steered his fancy low-rider into a convenience
store parking lot in which another patrol car already was parked.
(Not exactly the spot a dangerous criminal would pick.)
</P>
<P>
   They heard about the shouting match between Mallet and officers
when Mallet refused to submit to arrest. About the wrestling match
that followed, and about how one officer wrapped an arm around
Mallet's neck.
</P>
<P>
   They heard that his body lay motionless on the pavement for six
minutes, and that no one bothered to check him until paramedics
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   They heard a respiratory therapist who was pumping gas at the
store say he'd offered to assist Mallet but that police told him to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   They heard, in other words: ``The city is liable for the death
of Edward Mallet.''
</P>
<P>
   Only now is the city admitting it, though, and only to whittle
down the $45 million jury award to $5.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   There are other aspects to the deal, including a $500,000 Edward
Mallet Diversity Center, which the family hopes will teach
tolerance and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   They mean well, but it's kind of place that'll most likely
attract people who already are tolerant and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Police also agreed to intensify police training and
``sensitivity to cultural diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that can only happen if the people at the top believe
in it, and in the Mallet case all they did was deny, deny, deny.
They denied responsibility so often you got the feeling they'd
convinced themselves it was true.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's an old-fashioned grade-school lesson in that kind
of stubborn repetition.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should set up a chalkboard and make the big shots most
responsible for this atrocity write on it: ``The city is liable for
the death of Edward Mallet.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 5,300,000 times. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0553 </DOCNO>
