<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-LABOR-NYT &LR;      07-01 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LABOR'S ABUSE OF THE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 2:
</P>
<P>
   The construction workers who clashed with police and tied up
midtown Manhattan for hours on Tuesday turned a lawful rally
against the use of nonunion contractors into an illegal assault on
civic life. No union, or its members, should be allowed to take the
constitutional right to protest and turn it into a license to
paralyze the city and rough up civilians and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders have issued an apology and offered restitution for
injury and property damage. But their statements seemed so grudging
and mechanical that the rank and file could easily conclude that
their leaders were really winking at their misconduct. If the
unions repeat their roughhouse tactics, arrests and heavy fines
will be warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Locally and nationally, unions are becoming more aggressive in
asserting their interests. That is all to the good in a democratic
society. But Tuesday's lawlessness pushed the issue that prompted
the rally offstage. The rally's main sponsor, the Building and
Construction Trades Council of Greater New York, believes that the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority erred in selecting Roy Kay
Inc., a nonunion contractor from Freehold, N.J., as the lowest
responsible bidder for a $32.6 million project.
</P>
<P>
   In the unions' eyes, city and state laws governing the award of
contracts on publicly financed projects to the lowest responsible
bidder fail to adequately define what ``responsible'' means. The
unions would like the city and state to adopt legislation that
would require bidders to meet new financial, safety and performance
criteria in order to be deemed responsible. They have also
submitted evidence suggesting that Roy Kay intentionally misled
state officials about safety and wage issues. Such charges should
be thoroughly investigated by responsible officials, not
adjudicated on the streets by lawless demonstrators eager to bully
city and state agencies into using only union contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue in Tuesday's demonstration was who will get jobs
on publicly financed projects. In a rebounding city economy, unions
want as many projects as possible to go to companies that use union
crews. Public agencies, most of which already rely heavily on union
contractors, want to hold down construction costs. Awarding
contracts to the lowest responsible bidders, some of whom may be
nonunion contractors, is a means to that end.
</P>
<P>
   If the unions want to change the legal requirements for a
``responsible'' bidder, they should do so through the normal
political process. Although they put plenty of energy into their
street demonstrations Tuesday, not one union raised the issue
during the authority's board meeting that same day. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0555 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PUNCHED-HORSE-NYT &LR;      07-01 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PUNCHED-HORSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE SHRUGS OFF BRAWL AS WORKER FACES CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related article, NY-WORKERS-PROTEST)  
(af) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To his handlers, he is known as Snewser, and for a
horse, he has had quite a career: riding in Yankee Stadium after
the team won the 1996 World Series, and patrolling Rockefeller
Center for ``Today'' broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could compare to his day at work on Tuesday, when,
the police said, he found himself on the wrong end of an angry
construction worker's fist. The confrontation landed the worker,
James Hornacek, in jail, and was cited by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as
a prime example of the boorish behavior of construction workers at
their rowdy demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   They were protesting the Metropolitan Transportation Authority's
use of a nonunion contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The horse could not be reached for comment Wednesday, but his
handler, Officer John Reilly, said he was recovering nicely. ``He's
due to retire this summer,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   The horse's supreme boss, Police Commissioner Howard Safir, was
similarly reassuring. ``We put a little ice on the horse,'' Safir
said. ``He's doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek, 33, of Hazlet, N.J., may not have it so easy. His
lawyers are faced with defending him against the rare charge of
attacking a police horse, a misdemeanor for which there is little
legal precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not punch a horse,'' Hornacek said. He said that he is
an animal lover who has a cat and a fish at home, and that he
helped save a runaway horse just last week at a riding stable near
his home. ``Why on earth would I punch a horse?''
</P>
<P>
   According to a criminal complaint filed in court Wednesday, a
police officer stated that he saw Hornacek ``repeatedly punching a
police horse, then stepping out of the way to avoid being kicked by
the horse, then moving back in and punching the horse again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek was arraigned on charges of attempting to kill or
injure a police animal, obstructing government administration,
disorderly conduct and reckless endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   He was released and given a court date in August, he said. But
insisting that he never struck the horse, he said he simply raised
his arm in self-defense when he found himself stuck between the
horse and the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Snewser, 19, whose given name is Daily News because he was
donated to the Police Department's mounted unit by that newspaper,
was back at his stable on West 42nd Street Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
