<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-OLDPOLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: SORRY, YOU'RE STILL TOO OLD TO JOIN THE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though starting over is never easy, Michael Rosati
said that for him the choice was easy. He had always wanted to be a
police officer and suddenly it seemed that he might have the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the advent of laser surgery, Rosati was finally able
to have his disqualifying nearsightedness corrected. At the same
time, thanks to a fight in Congress, the longstanding age limits on
becoming a New York City police officer had been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   And so, at age 44, Rosati took the Police Department's written
exam and received a high score. He proceeded to pass the background
check, the psychological exam and the physical. He was told that he
could enter the Police Academy on April 15, 1997, once he had sold
his karate school in Franklin Square, N.Y. So he sold his store.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just four days before the start of classes, he was
informed that the age limits had been reinstated. No over-age
applicants would be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like having a lottery number that wins and you lose the
ticket,'' he said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   The injustice, not to say the pathos, of Rosati's story and a
few dozen like it convinced the City Council that an exception
should be made. Earlier this year, the Council wrote a law
specifically allowing him and about 40 other older candidates their
chance to enter the Police Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Rosati showed up to try to register for the academy
Wednesday at 7 a.m., he and the other candidates over 35 were all
turned away at the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say it's humiliating, but it is
embarrassing,'' Rosati said after finding himself once again shut
out. ``It's very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosati's hopes are yet another casualty of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's rigorous interpretation of his duties or, if you prefer,
his obstinacy.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the mayor made it abundantly clear that he
did not support the cause of the over-age police officers and did
not feel an exemption should be made for them.
</P>
<P>
   Though Giuliani's own celebrated truculence has, it is said,
launched a thousand lawsuits, the mayor maintained that he was
extremely worried about opening the city to litigation. If these 40
candidates were grandfathered in, other over-age candidates would,
he insisted, use it as an excuse to bring lawsuits against the city
and overturn the age limit entirely.
</P>
<P>
   City Council members rejected his argument as legally dubious,
noting that exemptions to rules are made all the time for small
groups of people who, for one reason or another, seem to deserve
special consideration.
</P>
<P>
   While Council members said they agreed with the mayor that age
was a factor in policing, they pointed out that these candidates
had acted in good faith, giving up positions, selling businesses
and putting considerable strains on their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people changed their lives and left their jobs,'' said
Michael Clendenin, a spokesman for the City Council. ``Look, we did
this legislation because we felt it was just a question of
fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Council approved the exemption in April, Giuliani
promptly vetoed it. Last month, the Council overrode his veto by a
vote of 43-4. Three of the Council's seven Republican members broke
publicly with the mayor to vote with the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Not willing to accept this clear and apparently straightforward
legislative defeat, the litigation-fearing Giuliani sued the City
Council himself. In papers filed in state Supreme Court on Tuesday,
the mayor argues that the Council's action represents an illegal
infringement on executive authority.
</P>
<P>
   Though Giuliani did not seek an injunction, he clearly
instructed the police commissioner to lock out the slowly dwindling
group of over-age candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Rosati, Paul Agli, 42, got up early Wednesday
morning, hoping that despite the mayor's opposition he would be
allowed into the Police Academy. For his shot at joining the force,
Agli had given up a job as a research technician at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center last year and found himself
unemployed for almost 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   It was, Agli said Wednesday, a painful business to watch the
doors close in his face. And not just because he himself was being
kept out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the police violate the law is very disheartening,'' he
said. ``Either this is out of the ordinary or I am very naive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
