<SLUG> BC-MARINE-JET-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT-MARTIAL URGED FOR 2 IN MARINE JET IN SKI CABLE ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs 9th graf to change `and' to `or')  
 (ATTN: Italy, Calif., N.Y., Ind., Colo.)   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A hearing officer has recommended a court-martial
for the pilot and the navigator of the Marine jet that hit a ski
lift cable in the Italian Alps in February, a military official
said Wednesday. The Marine Corps planned to announce the
recommendation after notifying defense lawyers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Ronald Rodgers, a Marine Corps judge who conducted
seven days of hearings in May and June, will recommend that two
Marine officers in the rear seat of the plane not be charged, said
the military official, who did not want to be further identified.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers' report is a recommendation to the commander of U.S.
Marine Corps Forces on the Atlantic Coast, Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, who
could take any step, ranging from dismissing the case completely to
ordering that all four officers be court-martialed.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, an EA-6B Prowler, severed the cable, sending 20
people in a cable car plunging to their deaths. Italian officials
have urged prosecution of the jet's crew.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, an electronic warfare jet on a low-altitude training
mission, was flown by Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo,
Calif. Seated next to him in the forward cockpit was Capt. Joseph
Schweitzer, 30, of Westbury, N.Y., who had no flight controls but
functioned as the navigator and was actively involved in mission
planning.
</P>
<P>
   Two Marine aviators in the rear cockpit had no flight controls
or view out the front. They were Capt. Chandler Seagraves, 28, of
Nineveh, Ind., and Capt. William Raney, 27, of Engelwood, Colo. In
March a Marine Investigation Board recommended charges against all
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers heard testimony that the Prowler squadron kept outdated
and inaccurate information for mission planning, and that the pilot
might have brought his plane too low because of an optical illusion
created by flying from a narrow mountain valley into a broader one.
</P>
<P>
   The military official said he did not know what charges the
hearing officer had recommended. Official spokesmen for the Marines
refused to comment. The investigation board had said in March that
two charges were possible: negligent homicide, which carries a
sentence of up to three years, or involuntary manslaughter, an
offense that involves ``culpable negligence,'' and carries a
sentence of up to 10 years, which could be imposed for each victim.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Schweitzer, David Beck, said: ``If charges are
dismissed against anybody, I would think that's wonderful. If
charges are referred against anybody, we will prepare for them.''
Speaking in a telephone interview, he said he did not know what the
recommendation was..
</P>
<P>
   Pat Schweitzer, Schweitzer's mother, said in a telephone
interview that no one in her family knew, either. ``We heard it on
the news,'' she said, referring to a television report. ``We were
told we would be informed tomorrow through our lawyers. This has
been horrendous, horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, the pilot, told The Associated Press that he had not been
formally informed of the recommendation, but had heard that he
faced a court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just amazes me, the recommendation,'' he said in a
telephone interview with the news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Spinner, who represents Ashby, also said he did not know
what was in the recommendation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
