<HEADLINE>
IN UMBRIA, A WORLD OF POTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5)  
 (JT)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best way to find Mastro Paolo is to ask the attendant at the
gas station just south of Orvieto for directions. A few hundred
yards away, wedged between the highway and the railroad tracks, the
63-year-old potter Paolo Cosenza shapes and paints his bowls and
plates in a small, crumbling gray building with no air-conditioning
and a lot of noise from the passing cars and trains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in an undershirt and jeans, he is shy and unaccustomed
to visitors. His studio _ if it can be called that _ is a warren of
smallish rooms dirty with clay dust and adorned with spider webs,
old newspapers, bags of paint powder and pieces of broken pots. For
more than 40 years, Cosenza has experimented with the gray-brown
clay that he fell in love with as a child, molding it into modern
versions of ancient shapes and painting them with bands of color.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I fell in love with his shop about 15 years ago, when I lived in
Rome and visited Orvieto for the first time, and again on my latest
visit last August. After passing shop after shop displaying pottery
decorated with the traditional Umbrian designs dating back to the
Renaissance, one comes upon Mastro Paolo, as the shop is called,
across the piazza from Orvieto's magnificent Duomo. It is a welcome
change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mastro Paolo knows that he sells something original. And his
creations don't come cheap. An angular espresso cup and saucer are
$23, calculated at 1,695 lire to the dollar. But the clay he uses
is of such good quality it does not chip easily; the saucer is
really a small plate that can be put to other use, and the cup
feels just right in one's hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The modern approach to handmade Italian pottery has also begun
to seep into nearby Deruta, a semi-industrial town whose economy
depends on ceramics production. There, two sisters, Laura and Gina
Giometti, opened a shop last July that sells nothing but modern
designs _ all at terrific prices.
</P>
<P>
   At Ars Artigiana Deruta, as the store is known, are wonderfully
shaped cups and saucers for $6; a matching soup tureen in yellow,
turquoise, white and cobalt blue for $57, and dinner plates for $15
each. Simple small white plates with blue and red trim are only $3.
The shop is so small that the sisters use the gift store next door
to wrap the purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to use American designers but their prices were
astronomical and we couldn't sell them,'' said Laura Giometti. So
the sisters turned to Swedish designers who think of themselves
less as artists and more as craftsmen. ``That way we can sell our
work at about half the price _ not much higher than wholesale,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   The clientele for modern pottery is not for the most part
Italian. ``They say, `I can't eat pasta on a plate like that,'''
said Gina Giometti. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hill towns and back roads of Umbria are so clogged with
pottery stores that even the most passionate admirer gets dizzy.
The only cure is a wonderfully long and indulgent lunch on a
terrace somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of the designs here is of extraordinary variety.
Just about every child living in towns like Deruta, Orvieto and
Gubbio has painted classical figures on pieces of clay, much as
American children do poster-painting. The ubiquitous Umbrian golden
figure representing the wind can be painted from one to three times
on a coffee cup, either very well or very badly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A good way to set out on a shopping foray is to stop by the
Museo della Ceramica e Pinacoteca, a tiny museum of ceramics and
paintings in Deruta's central piazza. The museum, which doubles as
Deruta's town hall, houses some of the finest and best-preserved
examples of Umbrian pottery _ dating as far back as the 14th
century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best way to buy is not to stop in every shop but to focus on
what catches your eye in the window and turn the visit into a
chance to meet the proprietor (who many times is the potter as
well) and learn about the craft.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highest-quality and most creative shops is Deruta
Placens, a small two-story family enterprise on the edge of
Deruta's main piazza. The potter, Giovanni Mordenti, who founded
the business with his wife, Novella Nicolini, paints his bowls and
platters in a corner of the store as he waits for customers. Last
year, their 27-year-old daughter, Annalisa, decided she loved pots
more than the law, abandoned her practice and joined the family
business.
</P>
<P>
   The rich use of color and intricate patterns give the pieces
more of a Middle Eastern than Italian feel. Prices are high. The
shop's shipping slips show where the family's customers are:
Brooklyn, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Minneapolis, Denver. One
customer from Washington, D.C., had spent $1,475 on place settings
for eight, including serving platters and bowls _ and an extra $210
to ship it by air.
</P>
<P>
   GeRibi across the piazza and down the street offers sensational
ceramic tables. But my favorite items there are the whimsical,
colorful, more primitive pottery with borders of animals and
flowers taken from the designs of Vietri, 30 miles south of Naples.
American department stores have carried the now ubiquitous blue,
white and red pottery with chickens around the borders from Vietri
for years. In Deruta, the prices are slightly higher, but the
quality of the painting and the glaze is much better. A dinner
plate sells for $12. Shipping 12 plates to the United States costs
about $110. I carry mine in my hand luggage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients have seen the low prices of Vietri and we need to
stay competitive,'' said the proprietor and potter, Gerardo
Ribigini. Ribigini has his own Web site, which offers information
on designs, prices and shipping; he communicates with customers by
e-mail.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The most down-to-earth shop in Umbria is not really a shop at
all but a small, low-tech factory called Terrecotte Berti in a tiny
working-class town called Ripa Bianca, just outside Deruta. There,
for four generations, the Berti family has made large and small
decorative terra-cotta pots, fountains and other ornaments for the
garden. Now the three brothers _ Carlo, Eugenio and Remo, who still
make pots by hand every day _ run the factory.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine stumbled on the Berti brothers a decade ago
when she bought a Berti clay pot from a local merchant in the
nearby hill town of Todi. When she asked for a match, which he
didn't have, he generously sent her to his source. The second pot
cost half the price.
</P>
<P>
   The parking lot is filled with large urns and vast blocks of raw
clay sealed in plastic for indoor and outdoor pieces. The urns can
be ordered with initials, leaf or ribbon decorations and family
crests. A rounded four-foot-high planter sells for about $150. The
Bertis will crate and ship the urns _ a bit pricey, perhaps,
because it doubles the price, but then, they are big. And there are
very few places, even in Umbria, that still produce handmade garden
planters.
</P>
<P>
   Berti's also has wonderful odd bits and pieces _ small,
house-shaped clay chimneys for $72 that can be used for citronella
candles in the summer, small fountains for $60, an elegant
oval-shaped white soup tureen for $15.
</P>
<P>
   Another place that is not usually considered a pottery center by
tourists is the lovely hill town of Gubbio, where shards of shiny
black pottery and coral red vases dating back to the fourth century
have been uncovered. Here, two shops are musts. One is La Fornace
del Bucchero, which makes reproductions of ancient Greek ceramics
and Etruscan Bucchero and sells them in two locations in Gubbio
(Bucchero is a black shiny ceramic with a coal-like base). In
addition to classical designs with bronze-colored inlays of people
and animals, the Morelli family, which owns the factory and shops,
also makes Bucchero bowls and vases in angular modern shapes, from
$100.
</P>
<P>
   The other is Ceramiche Aldo Fumanti. For more than a decade, the
husband and wife team of Aldo Fumanti and Antonia Cerbella has
designed and painted pottery. Their shop, built into the side of a
13th-century grotto and opened just last August, is a brightly
lighted art gallery and ceramics store with marble floors and
spanking white walls. The copies of 16th-century pharmacy and spice
jars between 7 and 14 inches _ with the names in Italian _ are
particularly well done. They start at about $30 the pair.
</P>
<P>
   The tackiest, and most eclectic, shop in Umbria is Torretti, set
back from the main highway leading north to Deruta, next door to
the Hotel Melody. It's easy to spot: a life-size ceramic Snow White
and her seven dwarfs are cemented to the roof.
</P>
<P>
   And is it ever fun! Should you need a life-size leopard or
Dalmatian for your garden, a giant creche, or your house number in
ceramic glued to a wooden base, this is the place. I have always
loved the ceramic vegetables, although the style is definitely not
for everybody. I once gave a platter of ceramic eggplants,
cauliflowers, zucchini, mushrooms, leeks and artichokes to a friend
in Rome. He centered them proudly on his dining table. A few months
later, they were hidden away in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum is Deruta's U. Grazia, the
giant of potters in the region that overwhelms all the others in
terms of volume and clientele, shipping to major department stores
and gift shops worldwide. The Grazia family has donated so many
pieces to the pottery museum in Deruta that a booklet has been
published on them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Set behind a wrought-iron gate in an elegant stone building,
with ceramic vases set into the brick, it is a good place to find
spectacular modern designs as well as the widest variety and
biggest inventory of classical designs of any shop in Umbria. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But I have always found the shop intimidating. For one thing,
there are no prices on the merchandise. For another, there are
never enough salespeople; the few who are there _ usually members
of the Grazia family _ are not eager to answer questions and are
sometimes downright rude. They know they don't need the walk-in
trade, and a peek into the shipping room shows why: there are
scores of orders to be sent to stores and individuals around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   On my last visit, I asked one of the shop's two employees on
duty (in Italian) to tell me the price of a few pieces of a pattern
of plates I had bought years ago for a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak English,'' he replied tartly.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I have never considered my Italian _ first learned in bits
from my Sicilian-dialect-speaking grandparents _ particularly
poetic. But really.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is my Italian that bad?'' I joked (in Italian).
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he replied. ``It is.''
</P>
<P>
   He walked away without answering my question. This was not the
fun it should be. So I bought my gifts elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my favorite shops in Umbria. Most take credit cards and
traveler's checks and ship. Some give discounts for cash.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mastro Paolo,  &LR; 36 Piazza Duomo, Orvieto 05018; (39-0763)
342-892. Open daily 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. and 3 to 8 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ars Artigiana Deruta,  &LR; Piazza dei Consoli, Deruta 06053;
(39-075) 971-1148. Open daily 8 a.m. to 1 p.m. and 2 to 8 p.m.
(Cash only and no shipping option.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Deruta Placens,  &LR; 25 Via Biordo Michelotti, Deruta 06053;
(39-075) 972-277. Open daily 8:30 a.m. to 7:30 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GeRibi,  &LR; 1 Via Mancini, Deruta 06053; (39-075) 972-233. Web
site: www.geribi.com; e-mail: geribi-(AT)geribi.com. Open daily 9
a.m. to 1 p.m. and 2:30 to 7 p.m.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Terrecotte Berti,  &LR; 5 Via dei Mille, Ripa Bianca 06050; (39-075)
973-139. Open daily 8 a.m. to 12 p.m. and 3 to 7 p.m. (Cash only;
no shipping.)  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; La Fornace del Bucchero,  &LR; 10 Via Federico da Montefeltro,
Gubbio 06024; (39-075) 927-7216. Open daily 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. and
2:30 to 7 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ceramiche Aldo Fumanti,  &LR; 28 Via Piccardi (there is another shop
at 42 Via Baldassini), Gubbio 06024; (39-075) 927-6413. Open daily
9:30 a.m. to 1 p.m. and 3 to 7 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Torretti,  &LR; S.S. E/45, Deruta 06053; (39-075) 971-1342. Open
daily from about 8 a.m. to 8 p.m.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U. Grazia,  &LR; 181 Via Tiberina, Deruta 06053; (39-075) 972-018.
Open weekdays 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. and 2:30 to 6:30 p.m.; closed
Saturday afternoon and Sunday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pottery museum in Deruta,  &UR; Museo della Ceramica e
Pinacoteca,  &LR; is at 1 Piazza dei Consoli; (39-075) 971-1000. Open
Tuesday to Sunday 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. and 3 to 7 p.m. $3.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
