<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S TIME FOR THE HALL'S VOTERS TO STAND UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When news got out that John Thompson, head coach at Georgetown,
was passed over for induction into the Hall of Fame, the reaction
was less one of surprise that he hadn't made it, but that he wasn't
in already.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a no-brainer,'' said Mike Krzyzewski, head coach at
Duke and president of the National Association of Basketball
Coaches. ``If you ask people in the basketball community, they'll
say: `John Thompson? Isn't he already in the Hall of Fame?'''
</P>
<P>
   Even Jim O'Brien, the president of the Hall, in Springfield,
Mass., seemed a bit red faced Wednesday that one of the game's
luminaries had been overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave Gavitt is the chairman of the board of trustees of the
Basketball Hall of Fame,'' he said. ``I'm the president of the
Basketball Hall of Fame. John Thompson is a personal friend of both
of ours; as basketball fanatics we would both espouse that John
Thompson be in the Basketball Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Thompson's second consecutive rejection, and he has
apparently been the victim of someone's political torpedo.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be truthful, he's very close,'' O'Brien said. ``Without
question John Thompson has Hall of Fame credentials, and that over
the course of time cream comes to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``In due process, he will be elected to the Hall of Fame, but I
couldn't guarantee anyone that in a million years.''
</P>
<P>
   The screening committee can propose a nominee to the honors
committee five times. If the candidate is not elected in five
years, he or she must sit for three years and then be nominated by
the veterans committee.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches spend their careers in public; their records are out
there for the world to see. Then, at the crucial point of their
careers, they are judged by a secret panel that throws bouquets _
or darts _ at them and then hides behind a veil of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these people? Who is this gang of 24 that decides which
coach, which player, gets the final cherry on an outstanding
career? O'Brien wouldn't divulge the names, but he said everyone is
``a credible basketball person.''
</P>
<P>
   What bothers Krzyzewski is the secrecy. ``There should be
diversity but there shouldn't be anonymity,'' he said. ``Not having
to be accountable for your decisions is not a good stage. If there
are 24 people, you should know who those 24 people are.''
</P>
<P>
   How much expertise can they have if they keep John Thompson out
of the Hall of Fame? They have now done it not once, but twice.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, what kind of Hall is it that excludes a coach
who has won a national title, played for the national championship
three times and sent three outstanding centers _ Patrick Ewing,
Alonzo Mourning and Dikembe Mutombo _ to the National Basketball
Association? Can you imagine a Country Music Hall of Fame without
Willie Nelson?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Thompson has his share of critics. Some of them don't
like the position he took in 1990 when he walked off the court to
protest the increased use of standardized tests for incoming
freshmen. Some don't like the news media-unfriendly Georgetown
locker room. And some may dislike Thompson simply because he is an
African-American who doesn't seem to know his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the person gets to ballot time, subjectivity is
involved,'' O'Brien said. ``For anyone to say racism, I would vote
strongly against that because of the makeup of our classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said, ``If you said to me John Thompson is a very strong
personality and there are people out there in the media who would
take affront in one way shape or form, yeah, that could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't. The Hall of Fame is the creation of the National
Association of Basketball Coaches. Many of the first wave of
inductees were college coaches and referees. But there has recently
been a greater emphasis on professionals.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the Hall's uniqueness is that it encompasses high
school, college, professional and international. But the time has
come for each constituency to be an entity unto itself. O'Brien
said that Gavitt has set up a panel to look into the voting
process.
</P>
<P>
   Professional basketball, the women's game and the international
game have all soared in popularity in 40 years. The Hall has not
expanded fully with the times. Of its 210 male members before this
year's selections, 113 have been players, 55 have been coaches and
42 have been contributors. Twelve women have been elected.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the Hall of Fame will move into a lavish new facility in
Springfield, a facility helped greatly by coaches like Thompson,
who in 1984 became the first African-American to win a Division I
national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Progress for the Hall of Fame is essential because the game
has progressed,'' Krzyzewski said. ``But with progress, you don't
forget about the citizens who first inhabited the town. The Hall of
Fame was started by college coaches. Somehow, maybe that's been
forgotten.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
