<HEADER>
A6883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-REVIE     07-01 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYMNASTICS WITH A SERIOUS DOSE OF NEW JAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pilobolus Dance Theater is up to its new tricks in
``The Hand That Mocked, the Heart That Fed,'' a quirky and uneven
premiere choreographed to a score by the experimental jazz composer
Maria Schneider. Both music and dance were commissioned by the
American Dance Festival and the Kennedy Center for the Performing
Arts in a joint venture, the Doris Duke Millenium Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilobolus piece, which opened the company's four-week season
at the Joyce Theater on Tuesday night, is the first of six
premieres in a project, financed largely though the Doris Duke
foundation, that matches jazz composers and choreographers.
Although the company will present two other new works at the Joyce
(175 Eighth Ave., at 19th Street), ``The Hand'' is of special
interest because it is the first entry in this unusual series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hand,'' in fact, has all the earmarks of a dance work
choreographed on assignment. Jazz, even the avant-garde sort, is
not in Pilobolus' musical vocabulary and Ms. Schneider has posed a
challenge to the troupe, which is a choreographers' collective. As
a dance company, it has never been anything but experimental in its
own right. But the sophistication of Ms. Schneider's score, heard
in a recording by the Maria Schneider Jazz Orchestra, has a range
and seriousness that make Pilobolus' fun-and-games imagery look
unduly narrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hand That Mocked, the Heart That Fed'' (the title comes
from Shelley) is one of Pilobolus' narrative works without
narrative. It has a vaguely tantalizing edge and a firm structure:
The opening image recurs several times and suggests a family
portrait held askew.
</P>
<P>
   In each grouping, a dancer (but not the same one each time) is
positioned horizontally across the nape and shoulders of a standing
man while another dancer (but not the same one each time) is upside
down, supported by two others kneeling in front of the standing
man.
</P>
<P>
   The sepia tones of Neil Jampolis' wonderful lighting and
Angelina Avallone's costumes with an Edwardian tinge (petticoats
for the women and vests or suspenders for the men in trousers)
evoke a photographic style in the pose that recurs. The audience is
invited to look at an ever-changing picture.
</P>
<P>
   But Robby Barnett, Michael Tracy and Jonathan Wolken, who
choreographed the piece (with the usual credit given to
collaboration from the dancers) never fully define that picture. At
best, they offer a ghost story with Gothic touches (a woman steps
on the temple of a reclining man).
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Anderson and Tamieca McCloud spend much of their time
floating in the air, swooped up and down by the men, Matt Kent,
Gaspard Louis, Trebien Pollard and Mark Santillano. These swift
arcs create marvelous illusions of flight, and there are surreal
vignettes involving couples and trios. Toward the end, some of the
dancers take off their shoes and skate across the floor in their
socks. The women are often yanked around, and at one point Ms.
Anderson takes off into space with surprising speed.
</P>
<P>
   When the women, sandwiched between pairs of men, break out into
cartwheels, there is a liberating moment. At the end, three
characters let go of the hands of three others who sink to the
floor in squares of light: three characters who have confronted
their inner selves?
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the dance images ignore the occasional fury
or excitement of Ms. Schneider's orchestrated chaos. To work
against the music is a time-honored technique but to end this piece
with an anticlimax is a pity.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the program was solid. ``Solo,'' choreographed by
Alison Chase, had Ms. McCloud obviously bringing the knowing
mischief of her personal style to this exhilarating outburst from a
behind a paper curtain. The dancing all evening was first-rate. The
men showed off the linked and leveraged groupings typical of
Pilobolus' gymnastic style in the solemn ``Gnomen,'' choreographed
by Barnett and Wolken.
</P>
<P>
   The sudsy curtain calls (dancers propelling themselves across
watery strips of linoleum) were worth the wait after the New Age
tribal rite ``Day Two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
