</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE STOCK MARKET EXTENDS RALLY TO SEVEN DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Expands and updates earlier story.)  (lb) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese stock market extended its rally Thursday
for the seventh consecutive day, on expectations that the
government's plan for cleaning up the nation's bad loans will spur
an economic revival.
</P>
<P>
   The yen has also been rising. On Thursday morning it cost 138.15
yen to buy a dollar in Tokyo, compared with a level of 145 a couple
of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the government's plan is the use of so-called
bridge banks to take over the business of failed institutions so
that creditworthy borrowers would not be left in the lurch if their
main bank goes under.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the plan is by no means certain. But for the last
few days, investors have begun to raise their hopes that it might
actually start to chip away large chunks of the nation's mountain
of bad and doubtful debt, estimated to be at least $560 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing sense that because of world pressure the
governing Liberal Democratic Party and the government are
addressing the problem, although some of the effort is timed to
their campaigning for parliamentary elections on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's real,'' said Richard Medley, a principal of the
New York-based Medley Global Advisors, after talking with Japanese
politicians in Tokyo this week. ``These guys realize that the pain
of delaying reform is actually worse than the pain of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues rose early Thursday to
16,599.55, or 1.45 percent from Tuesday's close. The index has
risen in the last seven days, with volumes surging. Reports that
the government might also cut income taxes by nearly $30 billion
have sent investors rushing into the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happened is you've got this policy machine, and
it's working pretty well _ they've really got it together,'' said
Craig Chudler, a strategist at Salomon Smith Barney in Tokyo.
``Portfolio investors have become less negative. Instead of being
supernegative, they're just negative.''
</P>
<P>
   The bridge bank plan will give wide powers to two government
bodies, the Deposit Insurance Corp. and the Financial Supervisory
Agency, a new agency of about 400 people split off from the Finance
Ministry last month to inspect the banks. As each institution
fails, its business will be transferred to a bridge bank, which
will be set up by an umbrella holding company under the Deposit
Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Deposit Insurance Corp. will draw on public funds
from the February bank bailout of 30 trillion yen, or $217 billion,
some of which has already been disbursed to the nation's largest
banks to increase their capital.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the Supervisory Agency will play the pivotal role
in the plan. One critical question will be whether it can hire
qualified people and expand enough to accomplish the task. It will
essentially be in charge of closing insolvent institutions and
appointing new management teams to run the business of the failed
banks.
</P>
<P>
   It will also determine which loans in the failed bank are bad
and which are good. Then it will transfer the bad loans to the
Resolution and Collection Bank, another entity set up to collect
bad loans, and transfer the good loans to the bridge bank, which
then may extend loans to those borrowers as a bridge until they
find a new banker.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Critics have argued that any bailout plan will create a moral
hazard, in which private institutions have little incentive to
improve, because they think they will be rescued by the government.
Partly to prevent this, the bridge banks are expected to last about
two years, during which time they are expected to find financially
healthy banks to take on the restructured business.
</P>
<P>
   This period could be extended up to five years. After that, any
bad debt still left will be transferred to the Resolution and
Collection Bank, and the bridge bank will be dissolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
