</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-AVENA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHONY AVENA, 83, SHOESHINER WHO BECAME NYC FIXTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anthony Avena, a shoeshiner of 75 years whose shop
became a Queens institution and who successfully fought the city to
save it, died on June 22. He was 83 and lived in Whitestone,
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was bladder cancer, said Helen Avena, his wife of
nearly 58 years.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a sophomore at St. John's University in 1937, Avena
abandoned his dream of becoming a lawyer after his father, an
immigrant from Italy, died unexpectedly, leaving six young children
and the shoeshine shop. ``He had to take over the business,'' Mrs.
Avena said. ``He had to feed the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tiny shop, directly below the elevated tracks of the Long
Island Rail Road in downtown Flushing, Queens _ through two world's
fairs and four wars _ he came to know thousands of commuters and
residents. ``The heart and soul of Flushing,'' is how Brian
McLaughlin, a state assemblyman and Democrat from Flushing,
described the 200-square-foot area occupied by Avena's shoeshine
stand and the flower and key-duplicating stands he added later.
</P>
<P>
   With a lawyer's gift of persuasion, Avena talked local boys into
completing school; he got the powerful Metropolitan Transit
Authority to lower his rent, and enlisted Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
support for his case. Along with Giuliani's help came public praise
for Avena's shoeshine as the best the mayor had ever had.
</P>
<P>
   It was two years ago, during Avena's 73rd year of shining shoes,
that the MTA announced that it was raising the rent on his shop, at
Main Street and Kissena Boulevard, to more than $6,000 a month,
from $750. It was far more than he could afford, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Townsend got excited,'' said Mrs. Avena, referring to a
corporate vice president at Club Med whom Avena had persuaded to
finish high school and to go on to college. Townsend called friends
with influence in public relations.
</P>
<P>
   The news media picked up the story and a short time later Mayor
Giuliani stopped by to reassure him. ``And the MTA gave my husband
a three-year lease'' at a figure he could afford, Mrs. Avena said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won,'' she added. ``He was so proud. It was a kind of glory
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   After the deal with the MTA, a representative from St. John's
University presented Avena with a plaque, she said, and offered him
free tuition if, at 82, he wanted to complete his degree, an offer
that Avena declined.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time Avena had successfully pleaded his
case directly to a mayor. More than 50 years earlier, after the
intercession of a friend, Mayor Fiorello La Guardia ushered Avena
into his office to hear Avena's complaint: the city, which had
bulldozed the Avena family home for construction of the 1939
World's Fair, was two years late with the payment. ``La Guardia
said, `Send him right in,''' said Mrs. Avena, recounting a familiar
family story. ``In 10 minutes he had the check.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Avena is survived by a son, Michael, of
East Northport; a daughter, Geraldine Mazza of Flushing; a brother,
Gerard, of Bohemia; a sister, Grace Barone of Whitestone, five
grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Avena closed the shoeshine shop last year when he became ill,
his wife said. Family members still run the floral and
key-duplicating shops, though, and will continue to do so, it
seems. At the wake for her husband, Mrs. Avena said, Giuliani
pulled her aside and said, ``Any trouble from the MTA, you let me
know.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
