<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURNED-BOY-HNS &LR;      07-01 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNED-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS INVESTIGATORS EXAMINE NEW LEADS IN BURNING OF BOY, 8 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By PAUL McKAY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPLENDORA, Texas _ Montgomery County investigators were
examining new leads Wednesday in their efforts to determine who
doused a boy with a flammable liquid on his eighth birthday and
burned him over most of his body.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ray Middleton remained in critical condition at Shriners
Burns Hospital-Galveston as detectives in Montgomery County said
they were following up on fresh clues and reviewing statements they
have gathered since Sunday, when Robert suffered third-degree burns
over 99 percent of his body.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities would not elaborate on the new information they said
they have obtained.
</P>
<P>
   The gruesome incident occurred near the boy's rural home, a few
miles northwest of Splendora, as he was heading down a wooded trail
to a friend's house around 5:45 p.m. The boy had not gone far into
the woods before he was burned near a spindly tree, which was
blackened by the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The hard clay ground around thetree also was scorched.
</P>
<P>
   Robert ran from the woods and was found by neighbors about 40
yards from his house. A 30-year-old neighbor who rushed to his aid
told investigators that Robert had given the first name of an older
boy who he said had doused him with gasoline because he was angry
at him.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Sgt. David Moore reiterated Wednesday that the
Splendora-area teen who was named, and subsequently suspected by
some of the neighbors, had what appeared to be a solid alibi.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Moore said, the teen-ager was ``not completely cleared _
not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he was down on the San Jacinto River with a bunch of
people, including several adults, who are adamant that he was with
them,'' Moore said. ``They are adamant that they had piled into a
truck and went fishing and swimming at the river together Sunday,
and the river is nowhere close (to the neighborhood).''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that ``anything is possible,'' Moore said it
is unlikely that Robert could have somehow set himself on fire
accidentally, since no fuel containers, matches or lighters were
found around the site of the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been presumed that gasoline was poured on the
boy, Moore said soil samples are being tested to determine whether
the fuel could have been some other flammable liquid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, Robert can't tell us what happened,'' Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert, who is breathing with the aid of a ventilator, was
unable to speak by the time medics reached him in the street in
front of the home of 67-year-old Billie Reed. She said she had seen
smoke rising from the wooded trail just as she and her husband were
arriving home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The woman also claimed to have seen two teen-agers _ including
the one supposedly named by Robert _ dart into the woods after the
boy was burned.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheriff Guy Williams said late Wednesday that ``some of the
initial information doesn't appear to be right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten some other information and we're trying to put a
case together,'' Williams said. ``We're making progress, getting
calls and getting information that we're having to sort through.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could interview Robert for just two minutes we would
have it made, but that little boy is fighting for his life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The episode has left a pall over the close-knit east Montgomery
County neighborhood about 35 miles north of Houston, where
residents who are fond of the boy and his family say they are
keeping closer watch on their own children.
</P>
<P>
   Robert's parents, Bobby Ray and Colleen Middleton, both 35, work
for a glass company in nearby Kingwood. They have a daughter,
Heather, 13, and another son, Clint, 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in this neighborhood and it's a good neighborhood,
where everybody looks out for everybody else and their children,''
said Regina Tanton, 23, who noted that her 4-year-old son Joseph
was close to Robert.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a crime neighborhood; it's not a gang
neighborhood,'' said Tanton, whose husband, Billy, was the first
adult to reach Robert after the boy emerged from the woods. ``The
street is like a community where everybody is family. We're very
concerned, but there's no way we could not be concerned about
something so devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to watch our kids if they walked down to somebody
else's house. Now, we walk with them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
