NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JULY 2
</HEADLINE>
  Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and   dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-BIRTHS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 30,
about birth rates referred incorrectly to the figures given for
multiple births in 1996. The numbers represented individual babies,
not sets of them. Thus 5,298 babies were born as triplets, 560 as
quadruplets and 81 as quintuplets or in higher-order multiples.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ROCKEFELLLER-EDUC-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 30,
about the appointment of a president at Rockefeller University
misstated his given name. He is Arnold J. Levine, not Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   BC-UNDERWRITING-QUARTER-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 30,
about corporate underwriting in the first half of the year
understated the value of completed mergers and acquisitions
worldwide in the period. There were $1.36 trillion worth of deals,
not $1.36 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
