<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-YOSEMITE-LADN     07-01 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-YOSEMITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT YOSEMITE, TIME TO BE LIBERATED FROM YOUR CAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE _ Even if you were content never to leave the inside of
your car, a driving tour of Yosemite Valley would provide a
stunning profile of the world's best-known example of a
glacier-carved canyon.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't it be a shame to visit the home of such celebrated
landmarks as Half Dome, El Capitan and Bridalveil Fall without
having an (begin ital)outdoors(end ital) experience?
</P>
<P>
   Soon you may not have a choice.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, a ban on personal day-use vehicles is earmarked for
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overarching goal is to provide a more natural experience
for visitors to the valley,'' said Yosemite National Park spokesman
Al Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Yosemite Valley... it is 7 miles long and 1 to 2
miles wide. There are a finite number of places where we can put
vehicles,'' Nash said. ``Over the Fourth of July weekend, we will
have at some point in time bumper-to-bumper traffic of people
looking for a place to park. People don't come for that purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   With an average of 4 million visitors a year, including a
single-month record of nearly 722,000 in August 1997 and 60,000
last Fourth of July weekend alone, ``the Incomparable Valley'' can
take only so many cars.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, a public-transit system _ originating at the valley's
west entrance or outside the park entirely _ is planned to ship
visitors in by the busload and reduce traffic to a quarter of what
it is now.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, tighten up your bootlaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly look forward to a time when you will be even more
inclined to walk about the valley than you are now,'' said the
understated Nash.
</P>
<P>
   I guess not having cars will do that to visitors. And no time
like the present to get started on those famous footpaths.
</P>
<P>
   Following are a half-dozen Yosemite Valley ``cakewalks'' that
even those most attached to their cars can consider.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, slowly walk away from the vehicle. You can do it. So
effortless are these day hikes that you'll be back in the comfort
of your air conditioning and plush leather interior in less than an
hour, having hardly broken a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   All hikes described are wheelchair-accessible, with assistance
recommended for bumps, potholes and other inconsistencies in the
trails. Pathways with trailheads along the east valley's
shuttle-bus route are so noted with bus-stop numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Bridalveil Fall
</P>
<P>
   Starting point: Bridalveil Fall parking area.
</P>
<P>
   Distance: Half-mile round-trip.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking time: 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: A wonderful short hike to a spectacular cataract with
a spray that brought the image of a wedding headdress to mind for
early visitors. Plan on getting misted, or downright wet, at
trail's end during the height of runoff in April through June...
and, this year, well into July, due to El Nino's snowy fury.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Yosemite Fall
</P>
<P>
   Starting point: Yosemite Falls shuttle stop No.7.
</P>
<P>
   Distance: Half-mile round-trip. (Can be made into a
three-quarter-mile loop.)
</P>
<P>
   Hiking time: 20 minutes. (Half-hour for loop.)
</P>
<P>
   Comments: At 2,425 feet, Yosemite Fall is North America's
tallest _ and unparalleled when in season. The lower segment (320
feet) is easy to reach and offers refreshing summer coolness.
Extend the traditional out-and-back hike to a loop by taking the
short extension west of the fall that passes a placard flagging the
site of John Muir's first Yosemite Valley cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miwok in Yosemite''
</P>
<P>
   Starting point: Yosemite Museum; Visitor Center shuttle stop
No.6.
</P>
<P>
   Distance: Loop of less than a quarter-mile.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking time: 15 minutes, but plan at least twice that to read
interpretive signs and visit displays.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: A place to go more to learn than to walk, the
self-guided historical trail introduces visitors to a reconstructed
Miwok-Paiute encampment in the Indian village of Ahwahnee. ``We
tend to forget that the earliest people here probably lived in much
greater harmony with nature than we tend to,'' said park spokesman
Nash. ``We have the tendency to either tame the environment or to
shield ourselves from it; that is the exact opposite of the first
people who were here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Changing Yosemite''
</P>
<P>
   Starting point: Visitor Center shuttle stop No.6.
</P>
<P>
   Distance: 1-mile loop.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking time: Allow at least 45 minutes to explore.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Did you know that ancient Lake Yosemite was 5{ miles
long and, in places, several hundred feet deep? It has long since
been filled by mud, sand and rock in a natural silting process _
one of the many ways in which Yosemite Valley has been altered.
Changes in fire management, how bears are no longer fed and what a
black oak woodland will look like in 125 years are also profiled
along the interpretive self-guided trail.
</P>
<P>
   Mirror Lake and Meadow
</P>
<P>
   Starting point: Mirror Lake/Meadow shuttle stop No.17.
</P>
<P>
   Distance: 2-mile round-trip.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking time: 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: No longer environmentally correct to dredge and
artificially manage as it was until the early 1970s, Mirror Lake
has all but become a meadow, just as Yosemite Lake did. When
filled, its pretty pond offers great photographic reflections at
the base of Half Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Valley Floor Loop
</P>
<P>
   Starting point: Yosemite Falls shuttle stop No.7, but any of the
numerous vehicle pullouts along Southside and Northside drives will
do.
</P>
<P>
   Distance: Technically, a 6.5 mile half-loop and 13-mile full
loop, but only the most dedicated need make this anything but a
leisurely stroll along one or more short portions.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking time: 2.5 to 3.5 hours for half-loop, 5 to 7 hours for
full loop or as long or short as you wish.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: ``We don't necessarily look at the Valley Loop as
something that someone would do in a day,'' Nash said, ``but you
can get out and away from people and cars and traffic quickly.
There isn't a bad spot to pull out and get on a trail. Even if it's
only a few minutes, it will enhance your visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Arrive at the park early, by 10 a.m., and give yourself
enough time to complete all the trails you wish to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Yosemite Valley is 4,000 feet above sea level, the air is thin
and hikers are more exposed to the sun's rays. Use sunscreen and
drink at least two quarts of water for a day of trekking.
</P>
<P>
   There is no time limit on day-use parking, as long as you don't
sleep overnight. The two primary day-use parking areas are in the
east valley at Curry Village and near the Village Store, but any
open space is a fine place to start hiking.
</P>
<P>
   Entry to Yosemite National Park is $20 per vehicle, good for
seven consecutive days. A $50 Golden Eagle Pass is good for a year
at any national park.
</P>
<P>
   For further details about Yosemite Valley, call the park's
recorded message line at (209) 372-0200 or its information service
at (900) 454-9673; write to Yosemite Association, Box 230, El
Portal, CA 95318; or visit its Web site at www.nps.gov/yose &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
