u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAR-2000-DATA-NYT &LR;      07-01 0296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-2000-DATA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES CAN SHARE YEAR 2000 DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government signaled Wednesday that companies would
be allowed to cooperate and share information about how to fix the
year 2000 bugs in their computer systems without violating the
United States' antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department stated its policy in response to a
proposal by the securities industry to let Wall Street firms and
their computer-services suppliers share information on how to
handle the so-called millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was welcomed by the head of the President's Council
on Year 2000 Conversion as important for business in general.
``This is a significant action that is an important signal for
other industries,'' said John Koskinen, who was appointed earlier
this year as the nation's ``year 2000 czar'' by the White House.
``This removes a major obstacle to cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 problem is that on Jan. 1, 2000, millions of
computers that keep track of years as two-digit numbers will roll
over from 99 to 00 and treat the new year as 1900, not 2000. As a
result, countless day-to-day computer-based transactions, from
stock trades to the issue of Social Security checks, are in danger
of being disrupted, according to many computer-industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of using two digits instead of four for denoting
the years in dates originated in the early days of computing, when
electronic storage was scarce and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   How great a challenge the year 2000 problem will prove to be is
a matter of debate. Edward Yardeni, chief economist of Deutsche
Bank Securities, predicts that there is a 60 percent chance that
the millennium bug will precipitate a global recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
