<SLUG> BC-NJ-VIDEO-TESTIMONY-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY OF DYING MAN MAY BE TAPED, JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In a decision that could broaden the use of
technology in criminal trials in New Jersey and eventually other
states, a judge ruled Wednesday that prosecutors can videotape the
testimony of a dying medical examiner who may not survive to
testify in seven murder cases, including four in which the
defendants face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Barnett Hoffman of Middlesex County Superior Court,
said that the testimony of Dr. Marvin Shuster, who is Middlesex
County's chief medical examiner and who is terminally ill with
cancer, was ``extremely central to the cases.'' Without that
testimony on videotape, the judge went on, the prosecution would
suffer a ``manifest injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   While videotaping testimony in civil cases is routine and
eyewitnesses in criminal cases have provided taped testimony, an
expert witness has never testified on video before the start of a
trial, legal experts say. If Hoffman's decision is upheld by higher
courts, experts say it could have a far-reaching effect on evidence
introduced in criminal cases around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman based his opinion on a New Jersey criminal practice
rule, common to many states, that allows testimony to be taken in
advance of a trial if material witnesses are unable to appear in
person because of death or disability. He wrote that county
prosecutors should be permitted to videotape Shuster because he is
the sole witness qualified to give first-hand testimony about the
cause of death in the various cases, one of the most convincing
pieces of evidence to prove that a murder has occurred. The jury,
Hoffman wrote, ``should hear directly from the person who performed
the autopsy when the results are such a significant issue in the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Iacullo, a lawyer for David Serio, an Edison, N.J., man
who was charged in 1996 with shaking his four-month-old son to
death, said he would appeal Hoffman's decision on the grounds that
the coroner is not a material witness in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution has retained at least four expert witnesses
aside from Dr. Shuster to testify on Shaken Baby Syndrome in our
case,'' Iacullo said. These other witness would not only offer the
same testimony as Shuster, Iacullo said, but would be physically
present in court to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers had also argued that pretaped testimony and
cross-examination would force them to decide what defense strategy
to pursue far in advance of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one case, we're not scheduled to go to trial for almost a
year,'' said Robert Obler, who plans to appeal the decision on
behalf of his two clients, both of whom face the death penalty.
``We're going to have to guess on what cross-examination to pursue
depending on what the evidence will be like in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman acknowledged in his ruling that a capital case was ``the
most serious case a lawyer can undertake.'' But, like many defense
attorneys in murder cases, those in the cases at hand have had
their files for at least a year, he noted. ``There is no reason why
an attorney who has been assigned a murder case, much less a
capital murder case, for over one year,'' he wrote, ``should not be
able to adequately cross-examine the state's medical examiner.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
