<SLUG> BC-NY-METROCARDS-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE BILLING CITED WITH NEW YORK'S METROCARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a slap at the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority and its Metrocard system, Speaker Peter Vallone of City
Council released a report Wednesday asserting that nine out of 10
riders have problems using the electronic fare cards and that some
are double-charged when they switch to another turnstile.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Please Swipe Again, and Again, and Again and
Again,'' is based on 1,068 interviews with subway riders conducted
by City Council investigators, and showed that the vast majority
did not know they could be charged twice if, after unsuccessfully
trying to swipe their card in one turnstile, they tried it in a
second.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, who is seeking the Democratic nomination to challenge
Gov. George Pataki, accused the MTA of underplaying the scope of
the double-charging problem and said the agency, which he pointed
out is controlled by Pataki, was blaming riders for very real
problems with the Metrocard system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transit authority needs to do much more to educate people
about the Metrocard,'' Vallone said at a news conference with
officials from the City Council's Office of Oversight and
Investigation. ``Riders should be warned that they can be bilked
out of an extra fare and told how to avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials acknowledged the double-charging problem, but
said printed material and a turnstile message warned customers to
``try again'' only at the same turnstile. (The possibility of being
double-charged is not mentioned by the turnstile message, however.)
They added that 70 percent of the subway system's riders used the
Metrocard and that fewer than one in 10,000 users complained.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly, a spokesman for New York City Transit, the unit of
the MTA that runs the city's bus and subway system, said Vallone
had exaggerated the extent of the double-charging problem. He said
exact figures for the problem were not available Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with any new product, certain difficulties are expected,''
Kelly said. ``We have never blamed our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly suggested that Vallone was motivated by his political
ambitions. ``It is sad that Peter Vallone would politicize the
discount program that has saved our customers hundreds and hundreds
of dollars and has proven to be a universal success,'' he said.
``It is that time of year again; it's that season of the year to
try to win political points.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Russianoff, a lawyer for the Straphangers Campaign, a
subway riders' advocacy group, said the MTA had made strides in
correcting the problem. ``It is clear that many people have to
swipe twice,'' he said. The agency ``did manage to minimize the
problem,'' he said, by changing the turnstile message from ``Swipe
again'' to ``Please swipe again at this turnstile.'' He added that
the agency ``could do more through brochures and things like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But when unlimited-use Metrocards are available, he said, ``this
problem will evaporate for a very large percentage of riders,
because you will have unlimited swipes.'' The MTA is to start
offering those new Metrocards, at $17 weekly and $63 monthly, in
three days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   City Council investigators said Vallone was supported by an
April 1 letter from David Goldenberg, the MTA's acting senior vice
president for customer services, to Catherine McAlvey, director of
the council's investigation office, saying: ``We have not performed
a double-deduction analysis, because we do not believe that one is
necessary. Only a small percentage of the customer contacts we
receive regarding Metrocards pertain to reported double
deductions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
