<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-NOTEBOOK02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three men's biggest servers advance
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Three men with the biggest serves in the
game _ and the man charged with mending England's wounded heart _
all advanced to the Wimbledon quarterfinals in straight sets
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Top seed Pete Sampras, the only American left in the men's or
women's singles draws, defeated unseeded Mark Philippoussis 7-6
(7-5), 6-4, 6-4. Ninth seed Richard Krajicek recovered from a knee
injury to breeze past Italian Davide Sanguinetti 6-2, 6-3, 6-4,
while 14th seed Goran Ivanisevic needed three tiebreakers to defeat
unseeded Jan Siemerink of Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time finalist Ivanisevic won 7-6 (12-10), 7-6 (7-5), 7-6
(8-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult for me to play another lefty,''
Ivanisevic said. ``He is tough to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Henman might have been playing with the biggest burden.
England was eliminated from the World Cup in penalty kicks on
Tuesday night, and fans throughout the grounds were somber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think Tim will win?'' one woman asked. ''Seeing how we
lost the soccer match, we should win something.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans cheered for Henman, but still seemed in mourning. By
Friday, when he meets Sampras in the semifinals, the country should
have recovered to cheer the first British man to reach the
Wimbledon semis in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this position before, playing Boris Becker in
Germany,'' Sampras said. ``It will be tough. This event will
obviously be watched all over England and all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Seles, Davenport ousted: Top seed Martina Hingis reached the
semifinals and was joined by three players at least nine years
older than her.
</P>
<P>
   Second-seed Lindsay Davenport and emotional favorite Monica
Seles both were upset by older players Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteenth-seed Nathalie Tauziat beat Davenport easily, winning
6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I didn't play my best, but that's by far the best
she's ever played against me,'' said Davenport, who was pleased
with her best Wimbledon performance since 1994,
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried for about two minutes and then I took a shower, and I
came out and sat down. There was nothing I could do today.''
</P>
<P>
   Unseeded Natasha Zvereva upset Seles 7-6, 7-4, 6-2. Seles was
somber about the loss, saying she got tense early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't put two points together today from the start of the
match, and it never got better after that,'' Seles said.
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva and Tauziat play in the first semifinal today, followed
by Hingis against doubles partner Jana Novotna. Hingis defeated
Arantxa Sanchez Vicario 6-3, 3-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lobs: In mixed doubles, Serena Williams and Max Mirnyi
defeated Brian MacPhie and Davenport 4-6, 7-4 (7-4), 6-2, and Venus
Williams and Justin Gimelstob beat Devin Bowen and Rika Hiraki 6-3,
6-4. ... Lauren Kalvaria of Indiatlantic, who trains in Boca Raton,
lost her first-round match in girls singles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
