<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-JAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HIDING FOR METS' ROJAS IN 15-10 LOSS TO BLUE JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Last Friday night, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine walked
to the mound in the top of the seventh inning and summoned reliever
Mel Rojas. The Mets were leading the Yankees, 4-3, but there were
two runners on base, only one out and Paul O'Neill was at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough assignment, and Rojas responded by allowing a
three-run home run on his first pitch, putting the Yankees ahead
for good and leaving Valentine to endure a weekend of questions
about why he used the struggling Rojas in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Valentine tried again. With the Mets leading Toronto,
8-7, on Canada Day, he brought Rojas in to start the bottom of the
eighth. And in his first appearance since the Yankee game, Rojas
responded by allowing a three-run home run to shortstop Alex
Gonzalez that put the Blue Jays ahead for good in an eventual 15-10
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the third time is a charm, but Valentine isn't prepared to
find out. As he surveyed the wreckage after Wednesday's game,
Valentine said he would not be calling on Rojas in another key
situation any time soon, and that he had already told the
31-year-old right-hander that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until we see some better quality out of him,'' Valentine
said of a player on whom the Mets had pinned considerable hopes
this season. ``He has to re-earn his stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas faced five batters Wednesday and retired none of them,
giving up two singles, a walk, a hit batter and the home run. He
was relieved by John Hudek, who endured his own misery as Toronto
went on to score eight runs in the eighth and turn a seesaw game
into a rout.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen was supposed to be a source of strength for the Mets
(43-36) this season. But on a day when starter Hideo Nomo had to
leave after three innings because of a lower back strain, the Mets'
relievers combined to squander three leads, give up 12 runs and
reinforce the notion that the team does not have enough capable
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been a bigger disappointment in this regard than
Rojas, who was a premier reliever for several seasons with the
Montreal Expos, had a nightmarish 1997 with the Chicago Cubs and
Mets and was expected to rebound and become the dependable setup
man for closer John Franco this season.
</P>
<P>
   That, obviously, isn't what's happening. Instead, in his last
six appearances, Rojas (3-2) has allowed 13 earned runs in just
four and two-third innings, which translates into an earned run
average of 25.07. For the season, Rojas' ERA is now 5.23.
</P>
<P>
   No one on the Mets has an adequate explanation of why Rojas is
pitching so poorly, and the reliever himself didn't stay around
after Wednesday's game to talk to reporters. But it seems clear
that ever since the Mets traded the right-handed reliever Greg
McMichael to the Dodgers on June 4 as part of the deal to acquire
Nomo, there has been more pressure on Rojas to perform, and that he
has not responded well.
</P>
<P>
   It is not as if Valentine has much to choose from at the moment.
On the days his starters cannot get games to Franco, the Mets, who
have now lost four of their last five games, have usually lost. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
