<SLUG> BC-HKN-FREE-AGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARKS GRAB SUTER AS TEAMS GO ON THE PROWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers say they are still trying to sign Mike Richter, now
that their veteran goalie has become an unrestricted free agent.
But they are hedging their bets by also negotiating with Curtis
Joseph, another veteran goalie, who is a free agent from the
Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Don Meehan, the business agent for Joseph, confirmed that
conversations took place with the Rangers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk to them again tomorrow,'' he said. ``Just initial
discussions, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of those all over the map Wednesday, but only
one big deal was officially announced. It came in San Jose, where
the Sharks signed defenseman Gary Suter to a three-year contract
that will pay him about $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Suter, 34, earned $1.6 million last season with Chicago before
becoming an unrestricted Group 3 free agent. His contract is likely
to drive up the salaries of other National Hockey League veterans,
particularly other free agents who play his position.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them, Uwe Krupp and Jyrkki Lumme, are bargaining with the
Rangers. Krupp earned $1.5 million last season with Colorado; Lumme
$1.535 million with Vancouver. Krupp's agent, Roland Thompson, said
that the Rangers were among the ``six or seven'' teams that
interested Krupp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is comfortable with the management and with the coaching
staff,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Krupp played for Ranger Coach John Muckler when both were in
Buffalo in the early 1990s. As for the negotiations with General
Manager Neil Smith, Thompson said: ``Neil and I have chatted. He is
a player who fits the Rangers' needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Having played with the Islanders for three seasons after leaving
Buffalo, Krupp, 33, is comfortable with the thought of relocating
to the New York area, his agent said. But salary is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to supply and demand,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also are engaged in a bidding competition with the
Islanders and possibly other teams for Geoff Courtnall, a left wing
who earned $2.4 million last season with St. Louis and who will
turn 36 on Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Rangers have begun discussions with
representatives of the forwards Scott Fraser, Doug Gilmour and Ron
Francis. Fraser last played for Edmonton, Gilmour with the Devils
and Francis with Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, who earned $2.3 million last season as the Edmonton
goalie, reportedly turned down a multiyear offer from the Oilers
that would have paid him $4 million a season. Richter, who earned
$3.9 million last season, reportedly turned down a multiyear offer
from the Rangers that would have paid him $5 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-salaried goalie in the league is Buffalo's Dominik
Hasek, who will earn a base salary of $8 million plus a signing
bonus of $1 million next season. Hasek last week won the Hart and
Vezina trophies for the second consecutive year as the best goalie
and most valuable player in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Gary Suter's signing with San Jose had a curious wrinkle.
Although he was thought to be property of Chicago until July 1, his
rights were traded last weekend by the Blackhawks to the Sharks for
a ninth-round draft choice, a deal that was not announced. This
gave the Sharks exclusive rights to negotiate with him before the
midnight deadline. Dean Lombardi, general manager of the Sharks,
said: ``Nobody knew we had the rights to him. The league told me
that in the future they wouldn't allow this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
