<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLUSIONS TO MAYOR WILL GRACE BUSES  
 UNSUNG TALENT  
 ONO AND TIBET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ MAYOR RUDOLPH GIULIANI cannot complain that New York
magazine's latest batch of bus advertisements take his name in
vain. Unlike the ones the mayor wanted removed last year,
trumpeting the magazine as ``possibly the only good thing in New
York Rudy hasn't taken credit for,'' the new ads do not mention the
mayor. Not even by nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a need to,'' said ELLIS VERDI,
president of DeVito/Verdi, the agency that created the new ads.
``In this case, New York magazine didn't seem to need the name of
the mayor, but the ads may speak to or imply his presence.''
</P>
<P>
   That may explain the thinking behind this ad, which Verdi said
would begin appearing on buses next week: ``No dancing in bars. No
sex shops. No hot-dog vendors. So what do you do for fun around
here?'' Or this one: ``Worth jaywalking to the newsstand for.'' Or
a third: ``How a city full of know-it-alls got that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time around, the mayor and the magazine went to court.
The magazine said that the ads were an affectionate joke and that
the wording was constitutionally protected speech. Lawyers for the
city said that the use of the mayor's name without his consent
violated his privacy and was not protected by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Shira Scheindlin of U.S. District Court in Manhattan
rejected the mayor's argument, saying, ``Who would have dreamed
that the mayor would object to more publicity?''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Giuliani's press secretary, COLLEEN ROCHE,
declined comment, saying she had not seen the ads. When the one
that mentioned jaywalking was read to her, she said: ``That's not
exactly good grammar. Sounds like they need an editor.'' The
publisher of New York, AMY CHURGIN, did not return a call for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Unsung Talent
</P>
<P>
   WOODY HARRELSON, who went from playing the hapless second-fiddle
bartender in ``Cheers'' to action-oriented movies like ``The Money
Train,'' can sing too. Harrelson, a guest at a wedding reception on
Martha's Vineyard, Mass., grabbed the microphone and began a
rendition of ``Jailhouse Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He sang it like a pro in a funny, Elvis-y kind of way,'' said
JERRY BENNETT, the band leader. ``He was in tune, on time and
really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ono and Tibet
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ YOKO ONO was in the spotlight twice on Tuesday. First
she announced that she was giving $100,000 to Victim Services, a
nonprofit group that offers emergency assistance to victims of
domestic violence. She made the donation in memory of Linda
McCartney, who died in April.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ms. Ono appeared at the World Artists for Tibet benefit, at
the Day for Night Studios on the 18th floor of a building on West
26th Street, and rang a bell for peace.
</P>
<P>
   She began by facing the audience of 450 and saying that one way
to make a difference in the world was to make a wish. ``So I
brought my old wishing bell,'' she said, ``and I'll ring the bell
three times, and we will wish together.'' The crowd was silent.
</P>
<P>
   For those who preferred the sound of voices, there were
speeches. ROBERT THURMAN, a Columbia University professor who heads
Tibet House, a New York organization devoted to preserving Tibet's
culture, drew applause when he said that President Jiang Zemin of
China should meet with the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is destroying itself by destroying Tibet,'' he said.
``It can save itself a lot of money, a lot of disgrace, and Jiang
Zemin can get himself a Nobel Peace Prize if he pulls out the
military and invites the Tibetans to develop Tibet.''
</P>
<P>
   RINCHEN DHARLO, president of the Tibet Fund, which supports
exiled Tibetans, said he was thrilled with President Clinton's
China trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step is for President Jiang Zemin to reciprocate,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
