u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-N     07-01 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLONE REVISES CAMPAIGN FINANCE MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The City Council speaker, Peter Vallone, has revised
and expanded his plan to overhaul the city's campaign finance
rules, trying anew to forge a consensus after an earlier version
divided the Council's leadership and was criticized by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani as too tepid.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker is to introduce new legislation Thursday that would
lower the contribution limits for city campaigns, require
transition and inaugural committees to abide by many of the same
rules as campaign committees, and prohibit elected officials from
appearing in city-financed advertisements when they are up for
election.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone has also sought to fashion a compromise on his earlier
proposal to prohibit candidates from accepting contributions from
corporations, a measure that had been opposed by some Council
members, who said it would greatly hinder their fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Under his new plan, the city would not ban corporate
contributions, but candidates who agree not to collect them would
get extra matching funds from the city treasury for their
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration declined to comment on the plan,
saying it had not yet received it. The mayor has said in recent
months that he favors tightening the law, but has declined to say
how far he would go. But given the current enmity between the mayor
and the speaker, it is not clear whether Giuliani will support the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has set up a commission to propose revisions to the
City Charter, and commission members have said they are considering
changing the campaign finance regulations. So the mayor might be
loath to back Vallone's legislation if doing so might render some
of the work of his Charter commission unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone's legislation had stalled earlier this year, hampering
his effort to cast himself as a reformer as he seeks the Democratic
nomination for governor.
</P>
<P>
   In reviving it, he has added provisions that some advocates for
toughening the laws have long sought, including the measure that
would provide additional city financing for campaigns. If adopted,
the plan would be the biggest change in the city's campaign finance
system since it was approved in the late 1980s in response to the
municipal corruption scandals earlier in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dramatic step by Speaker Vallone and good-government
groups to make elections more accessible to the average person and
to keep undue influence out of the political process,'' said
Michael Clendenin, a spokesman for Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   The city's campaign finance system is voluntary; candidates who
take part in it receive matching funds in return for agreeing to
ceilings on their spending and fund-raising, as well as strict
disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocacy groups hailed the new plan, saying it would
encourage candidates to focus more on small donors, rather than on
wealthy individuals who might have an interest in actions by the
city government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for democracy in the city,'' said Gene
Russianoff, a senior lawyer at the New York Public Interest
Research Group who is an expert in election law.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Schrader, director of Citizen Action of New York
City, attacked the plan. Schrader, whose group is helping to
spearhead a petition effort to put a more far-reaching proposal on
the ballot in November, said the contribution limits were still too
high.
</P>
<P>
   Under Vallone's plan, for example, the contribution limit for
the three citywide offices would drop to $5,000 per donor, from
$8,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal is weak, and the $5,000 maximum is woefully
inadequate,'' Schrader said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
