<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK DETAINING MORE YOUTHS BEFORE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An increasing number of New York City youths accused
of crimes are being locked up while they await trial, causing
overcrowding at juvenile detention centers and prompting officials
to begin holding boys as young as 10 on a prison barge designed for
adult inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The number of youths in detention is growing even though
juvenile arrests have declined sharply. Juvenile-justice officials
say fewer accused youths are being released after their arrests,
because judges and prosecutors fear they will disappear or commit
new crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the city turned the hulking Vernon C. Bain
Barge, anchored in the East River a few hundred yards from Rikers
Island, into a processing center for accused juveniles and a way
station for boys awaiting transfer to upstate prisons after being
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the move was meant as a temporary solution to a
problem that was not anticipated until a few months ago: The
population in the city's juvenile detention centers has swelled to
315 in recent months and on some days to 400, from an average of
276 youths a year ago. The barge is expected to hold up to 100 boys
from 10 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   New York City has used barges before to handle periodic
overflows of detainees from its jails. Although prisoners'
advocates have complained about conditions on the barges, they have
been used for adult prisoners as recently as 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, arrests of juveniles in New York City have declined in
recent years, according to state criminal justice records, and
there has been a steep drop in prosecutions of teenagers for
robbery, assault and drugs _ the three most common offenses _ since
1995, said Peter Reinharz, the city's chief prosecutor of Family
Court cases.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Hernandez, commissioner of juvenile justice, said the
population of youths in detention is growing because judges are
increasingly declaring children ineligible for release to their
parents' supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for prisoners said the increased detention reflected a
change in attitude by both judges and prosecutors, who are taking a
harder line with accused teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   But Reinharz, who has overseen prosecutions of juveniles since
1987, said a growing number of accused teen-agers are simply
believed likely to commit more crimes, or to fail to show up in
court, if they are released.
</P>
<P>
   The recent overcrowding has complicated plans to shut the
dilapidated, 42-year-old Spofford Juvenile Center in the Bronx,
which has long been dogged by complaints ranging from abuse by
guards to vermin infestation.
</P>
<P>
   Two new detention centers, designed more than a decade ago, have
been built to replace the 290-bed Spofford center. One, in the
Bronx, opened in January; the second, in Brooklyn, is to open by
early August, when Spofford is to close permanently. But the two
have room for just 248 youths.
</P>
<P>
   To handle the overflow while the city enlarges each of those new
detention centers, the Department of Juvenile Justice has leased a
section of the 800-bed prison barge, which is managed by the
Department of Corrections. It will house up to 100 boys between the
ages of 10 and 16, said Hernandez.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He stressed that the agreement is a temporary one _ the lease
expires in 18 months _ and that children will stay on the barge for
no more than 10 days. Nonetheless, Hernandez said, the 625-foot
barge is in far better physical condition than Spofford.
</P>
<P>
   But child-welfare advocates criticized the use of a barge
designed to hold adult inmates. ``It's a prison,'' said Nancy
Rosenbloom, a juvenile-rights lawyer for the Legal Aid Society, one
of several critics who were given a tour of the barge last week.
``These cells are horrendous. You've got a heavy door clanking
shut, with a little, tiny space to look out, which will be too high
for some of the smaller children to see through.''
</P>
<P>
   From the inside of a cell, she added, ``it looks like Attica.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosenbloom said the layout of the two cell blocks being used
would make it difficult to segregate newly arrested children from
convicted youths awaiting transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that we want to say anything good about Spofford, but at
least if kids are coming into the system for the first time,
they're kept apart and treated differently from kids who have been
convicted already,'' she said. ``Imagine putting 10-, 11-,
12-year-olds who've never been in the system before, with
15-year-olds who've been convicted of very serious acts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
