<HEADLINE>
SURFERS HANG ON FORECASTER'S WORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD COUCH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON BEACH _ Sean Collins has surf forecasting down to a
science. And if his calculations are correct, Southland surfers are
in for a swell summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Seal Beach surfer and his partner, Jerry Arnold of
Melbourne, Fla., are the masterminds behind Huntington Beach-based
Surfline/Wavetrak, a surf information and prognosticating service
that provides daily wave data for surfers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   With information culled from weather service and marine charts,
satellite pictures, Navy reports, computer models, buoy readings
and a hundred surf reporters, Collins and his Surfline researchers
have set the standard in the specialized profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started off as a hobby,'' said Collins, 46, who grew up
surfing and sailing. ``I wanted to surf and travel. But a lot of
times we'd go to Mexico and there were no waves.''
</P>
<P>
   He began his first forecasting experiments in the 1970s,
compiling information from different sources. He built a reputation
and was hired by Surfing magazine, providing editorial staff,
photographers and surfers with inside information on where the best
waves were.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, he helped start up Surfline and soon realized he had
the potential to turn it into a business. And business is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Surfline services include subscriptions to Wavefax _
twice-weekly reports of specific areas via fax machine _ and
telephone lines with recorded information that is updated three
times a day. Last year more than 1 million callers paid for
Surfline reports.
</P>
<P>
   Surfline's most dynamic offering is its Web site,
www.surfline.com, which is checked out by more than 14,000 people a
day. In addition to nationwide and international surf reports,
live-video ``surf cams'' are mounted at some of the world's most
famous beaches.
</P>
<P>
   The all-weather, securitylike cameras created by Surfline
provide images of waves on both coasts of the continental United
States, in Hawaii, Mexico, Costa Rica and many other locations. The
lines of swell that one surf cam captured at Topanga State Beach in
early June were a sight to see on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's made a huge change in the way surfers look at the
sport,'' Surfer magazine editor Steve Hawk said of Surfline. ``It
used to be, 15 to 20 years ago, if I was going to go on a weekend
surf trip down to Baja, I'd hope there was going to be a swell. Now
it's turned that upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you can see things up to 10 days in advance. It's
maximized surf time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marine meteorologist Bob Burke oversees surf reporting and
forecasting for the National Weather Service in Oxnard. The Weather
Service puts out two surf reports a day for the area from San Luis
Obispo County to San Diego County. But Burke concedes that surf
reports provided by Surfline and other independent forecasters are
just as or more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean Collins does forecasting on a full-time basis,'' Burke
said. ``We put out a wider range of products and don't have one
person assigned to surf forecasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins' work is not only important to surfers. As a public
service, Collins helped some coastal cities _ Seal Beach, in
particular _ prepare for the onslaught of El Nino storms, perhaps
preventing property damage last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a leader and the pioneer in his field,'' Hawk said. ``He
invented the science and was the first to perfect combining
sources. He keeps extensive records of waves and their
characteristics. He's even trained some of the Navy's
meteorologists.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has developed remarkable accuracy, Collins has been
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes. There's an error factor,'' Collins concedes. ``There's
a ton of information out there. Each source can be different, and
it's tough for us to sort through data.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as his theories for the summer, Collins said, ``Southern
Hemisphere storms are a primary source and we're off to a good
start. There's been significant swell the past three months.
Indications show we can look forward to more of the same. We'll
also get good waves from hurricanes from the tropics off Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins went to college for two years but never imagined he
would become a scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I taught myself to be one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Current events: &UR; !off! &LR;  Baseball has its Hall of Fame in
Cooperstown, N.Y., and football honors its heroes in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing legends are hailed along the Huntington Beach Surfing
Walk of Fame, which will hold its fifth annual induction ceremony
July 30.
</P>
<P>
   The inductees for 1998, including home towns and induction
categories: the late Chuck Dent, Huntington Beach, Local Hero; John
Heath ``Doc'' Ball, 91, Eureka, Surf Pioneer; Peter ``PT'' Townend,
Huntington Beach, Surf Champion; Jack O'Neill, Santa Cruz, Surf
Culture; and Frieda Zamba, Flagler Beach, Fla., Woman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, which honors those individuals who have made
significant contributions to the sport and culture of surfing in
Southern California, will take place at 11 a.m. in front of Jack's
Surfboards on the corner of Pacific Coast Highway (1) and Main
Street in Huntington Beach. The public is invited. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
