<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-REPORTERS-NOTEBOOK-$AD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: AMERICANA DOESN'T QUITE FIT THE ENGLISH
PUZZLE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advance for release on or after July 3 
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (i) international and (k)
commentary categories.
 &HT;    By LOUIS J. SALOME 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It was three in the morning last Sept. 6, on the street
outside Westminster Abbey. Thousands of people were sitting,
standing and sleeping on the pavement eight hours before the
funeral of Princess Diana would transfix the world from that same
spot.
</P>
<P>
   An American television reporter, who had flown in for the
funeral, stood on the sidewalk rehearsing for the biggest moment of
her professional life. Later that morning, she said in a voice
dripping with drama, the ``parade'' would pass right where she was
standing before Diana's body entered the medieval cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The parade, she kept repeating, the parade, as people who had
gathered nearby listened to her practice the standup routine. Her
words grated like red, white and blue finger nails scratching on a
tidy English blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   I listened in astonishment as the American way of turning
tragedy into carnival slammed into the English demeanor of stiff,
dignified formality.
</P>
<P>
   As she practiced, the reporter finally realized the mistake and
her parade became Diana's funeral procession.
</P>
<P>
   But at that unforgettable moment in history the reporter touched
on a phenomenon that both frightens and excites the English, Scots
and Welsh, whom Americans lump together as Britons _ but of course
Britons and British are a political fiction created for imperial
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The Americanization of Britain, which the blond, beautiful and
photogenic Diana inadvertently had promoted, is speeding ahead with
all the torque that modern technology, economic power and pop
culture can generate.
</P>
<P>
   When I left Jerusalem and Middle East reporting five years ago
to become the Cox Newspapers European correspondent based in
London, the Washington-London relationship was rubbed raw. The
problems were personal and political between Bill Clinton and
then-British Prime Minister John Major.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as I leave London for Florida to become an editor of
foreign and national news at The Palm Beach Post, a Cox newspaper,
Clinton and the new prime minister, Tony Blair, are mates and the
old fault lines have evaporated. But more complex differences have
slipped to the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hidden diplomatic battles rarely exposed to public
view, Anglo-American differences are now fought on business,
technological, music and film fronts that reach from boardroom to
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Like most modern countries, Britain (the country of Great
Britain and Northern Ireland is real enough, but it's people are
not ethnically British) is caught in a crossfire between tradition
and revolution. And the United States is to some the villain and to
others the stimulus behind the changes that seem irresistible if
not always welcome.
</P>
<P>
   As many inhabitants of the British Isles rail against the
invasion of raw American commercialism, 96-channel cable television
and noisy displays of emotions, many others quietly embrace those
termites eating away at their culture, either because they realize
how inescapable those forces are or because they like them.
</P>
<P>
   The Mother Country across the pond, as the English refer to the
Atlantic, is changing whether the people there like it or not. Tony
Blair, the prime minister, is dragging his country into Paris,
Berlin, Rome, Amsterdam and Madrid because there is nowhere else
for Britain to go.
</P>
<P>
   Diana offers the most dramatic example of change. The way London
merchants and other scalawags hawk cheap Diana trinkets isn't quite
up-to-the-minute New York style, but Londoners are closing the gap.
Yet it is always helpful to remember that London isn't England
anymore than New York is the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of evolution, the monarchy is more like the Papacy than
democracy, but it too is changing to accommodate the changes in
society. And Diana in life and in death plays a large part in
awakening the royal family from its secluded slumber, and in making
society itself realize just how much it is changing.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans who visit England for the first time expect to
find an extension of the United States. They are either
disappointed or excited by the differences they find. I was excited
by all those differences, some subtle and some stark, and I always
will be.
</P>
<P>
   What bothers Americans most is money or, to be more precise, the
currency exchange and prices.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as an American hits the ground his impression of England
is prejudiced by the fact that his dollar is effectively worth 50
cents. Consumer goods cost roughly twice as much as in the United
States, so buying power is cut again.
</P>
<P>
   I have an English friend who shops at hardware stores in
Nashville when he visits a relative in Tennessee. On a recent trip
he bought a ``For Sale'' sign for $6. He said a similar sign would
have cost him about $185 in a rural area southeast of London.
</P>
<P>
   Those circumstances alone are enough to send many Americans
packing before their scheduled return to their comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   The language, so close and yet so far from Americana, is another
irritant. A pervasive kind of bureaucratic formality nettles, until
it becomes clear that this is a fraying shield which allows
institutions to control the chattel and permits people to keep
their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, what passes for English reserve is really
small-town or insular shyness. You may have to initiate a
conversation, but usually when you do you will be rewarded with
stimulating information and insights.
</P>
<P>
   The subtleties of language rather than the obvious differences
are difficult to master and to grasp them requires a good ear and
attentiveness to reactions.
</P>
<P>
   To an Englishman a dinner that is ``quite'' good isn't good at
all, but to an American that would be better than average.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to carve a niche in any foreign country. It takes
time to know people and for them to get to know you. But there is
no point in working abroad if you don't try to know and understand
the people everywhere you live and travel.
</P>
<P>
   I lived in the Swiss Cottage area of North London for two years,
and it took a whole 12 months before the newsstand owner where I
went every morning to buy newspapers would say anything more than
``hello'' or ``mornin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Cottage is filled with foreigners, people who come and go,
so the newsagent figured I would vanish in a few months. He didn't
want to waste time talking to a transient.
</P>
<P>
   Even my attempts to break down that wall of reticence were fun.
And when we finally connected, I made a friend who told me about
his life and travels and who wanted to hear about mine.
</P>
<P>
   After I moved to the Isle of Dogs, also called the Docklands, in
East London, I used to stop by the Swiss Cottage news shop whenever
I was in that area just to have a friendly conversation and find
out what was new in North London.
</P>
<P>
   It was on the southern tip of the Isle of Dogs, on the north
side of the Thames River across from the old London village of
Greenwich, where I learned to love the English.
</P>
<P>
   The Thames, with its 22-foot tidal wash on each bank, throbs
like an aorta as it pushes through London and pumps life into the
city life. At high tide it's a moving lake rushing westward from
the North Sea. At low tide, it's a modest river flowing from gentle
western hills to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that to love the English you must know them first and
that knowledge comes through their pubs, the lifeline of English
society, and for that matter of Scottish, Welsh and Irish societies
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Pubs are not simply drinking places, although for sure they are
that. They are confessionals, and homes for people whose drinking
mates are often closer than family. They are places where people
with cracks in their lives go to heal before moving on, to another
pub.
</P>
<P>
   Pubs are operated by guv'nors, or publicans, like Reg, Eliza and
their wonderful daughter, 10-year-old Emma, who live upstairs at
the Ferry House Pub on the Thames across from Greenwich Mean Time
on the Isle of Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard customers say they consider the pub the guv'nor's
front room or parlor, and anyone who starts to raise hell had
better watch out for the clientele because trouble isn't tolerated
in the guv'nor's house.
</P>
<P>
   Pubs have other rules, too, and these are understood
instinctively by everyone, except foreigners who must learn them.
</P>
<P>
   It is taboo to discuss either politics or religion in a pub. Not
even harmless discussion is permitted because, everyone agrees,
nothing about those two subjects remains harmless when suds are in
the mix.
</P>
<P>
   East London is rich in history, in language, people and trouble,
poorer in material terms, but it's the wealth that's unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Irish, East Londoners love nicknames, and irony is
their second language. ``Here's a question for the Yank.'' This is
``Lofty'' speaking at the Ferry House Pub. Lofty is excited because
he's somehow found an advance copy of the questions for Quiz Night.
</P>
<P>
   Quiz Night arrives each Monday in the winter, when teams from
neighborhood pubs travel to other pubs to engage in a formal
intellectual competition, complete with prepared questions and
answers, league standings and grub for the evening. Quiz Night is
far more popular than darts.
</P>
<P>
   Lofty wants to know which U.S. presidents are carved on Mt.
Rushmore. I tell him (you can look it up), and Lofty and his mates
applaud. I am asked all the questions about America, and when I
answer questions about English history, Lofty is so impressed he
buys me another Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Then Lofty comes up with a tough one. Who was the English poet
laureate in 1968?
</P>
<P>
   This sends everyone into deep thought. The pub is quiet for a
couple of minutes. Then Steve, the truck driver who with his mate
Richie ought to be a comedy team on television, says he has the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Cooper,'' Steve pronounces with a chuckle that makes him
bounce off his bar stool.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughs because Henry Cooper was a British heavyweight
boxer in the long ago, and everybody knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're wrong,'' says Lofty, with an air of informed wisdom.
``It was Alice Cooper,'' and everyone bursts into laughter again.
</P>
<P>
   The English can make a joke and they can take one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Why, I was frequently asked, didn't the Yanks get into the war
earlier? Why did we, the English, have to fight the Nazis alone for
so long? (The war, in England, is always World War II.)
</P>
<P>
   The question is asked with a mixture of humor and seriousness,
as if to say the United States let England down, that it was a long
time ago yet it's not entirely forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   I developed a stock answer to take the edge off, and it always
got a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   You guys, I say, weren't ready to fight with us in the big time.
You needed more training to raise the level of your game.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the worst sin you can commit in Great Britain and
Northern Ireland is to lump the English, Scots and Welsh together.
Although millions of Irish live in Great Britain, the Irish are
usually considered barely a cut above the Germans and the French.
</P>
<P>
   The Scots and Welsh have more in common with the Irish than with
the English, and they will be the first to tell you so.
</P>
<P>
   The only place you will ever hear anyone in Great Britain say
that he or she is British is among the pro-British Unionists in
Northern Ireland, and they are mostly Scottish Presbyterians.
</P>
<P>
   And the only reason the Unionists say they are British is they
don't want to be united with the Republic of Ireland, they are no
longer Scots and so in search of an ethnic identity they call
themselves British.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you travel to Great Britain or any foreign land,
go with an open mind and at least one empty suitcase that you can
fill with new ideas, impressions and cultural baggage that can be
useful anywhere and anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
