<HEADLINE>
FERRY TO GO FROM NEW JERSEY TO FOXWOODS CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 By STEVE STRUNSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ The LeFrak Organization of Queens, in New
York City, and the Mashantucket Pequot Tribal Nation have agreed to
offer a high-speed ferry from the Jersey City waterfront to a port
near the tribe's Foxwoods Resort Casino in Connecticut, officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On June 23, the Jersey City Planning Board permitted Newport
Associates, a LeFrak subsidiary, to provide ferry service from
LeFrak's sprawling Newport development along the Hudson River to
New London, Conn., on Long Island Sound, about 10 miles south of
the casino, which is in Ledyard.
</P>
<P>
   The service could begin by late this month, said Yessenia
Correa, a Jersey City spokeswoman. The service has been approved
for three years, and the Planning Board also permitted a temporary
waiting area and gangway. Ms. Correa said additional stops are
planned for Glen Cove, N.Y., and Martha's Vineyard, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Wissemann, a project engineer for Newport Associates, said
the ferry could travel up to 55 mph and would make the trip in two
and a half hours. The pier where the ferry will dock is three
blocks from the Newport PATH train station.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Pequots said he could neither confirm nor
deny plans for the service. In March, the tribe announced that it
would run a ferry from the Chelsea Piers in New York City, but New
York state officials blocked the deal, declaring it a violation of
the pier's lease.
</P>
</TEXT>
