<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Washington) _ Former President
Suharto of Indonesia is trying to reestablish a political power
base and shield his family's multi-billion financial empire,
according to U.S. officials and Western diplomats. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALA-ELECT-ASSESS (Montgomery, Ala.) _ Political analysis: As a
battle for the soul of Southern Republicanism, the Alabama primary
that Gov. Fob James Jr. won so convincingly Tuesday reinforced a
number of political truths about the party and the region.
Religious conservatives still wield immense influence. Strong
stands against taxes still sell. Race still matters. And even as
Southerners take a leading role in national politics, they still
resent federal intrusion. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT12) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-ELDERLY (Cedar Rapids, Iowa) _ With hundreds of casinos
scattered throughout 26 states, and a growing population of seniors
looking for places where they can socialize, find companionship and
be a part of something that is lively and new, casino gambling has
become a favorite pastime for older Americans. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS (Geneva, Switzerland) _ The body's immune system can
recover to a large extent, even after it has been ravaged by severe
AIDS, according to evidence reported here on Wednesday by French
scientists at the 12th World AIDS Conference. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-TEACHERS (Boston) _ There's an uproar here after 60 percent
of new teacher candidates in Massachusetts flunk the state's first
reading and writing competency test for them. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-HISPANICS (San Antonio, Texas) _ Speaker Gingrich and
Gov. George W. Bush address a big Hispanic conference and argue
that Republicans are the best party for them. A look at the
scrambling for this huge new voting bloc. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   FARMERS-LANDRIGHTS (Red Hook, N.Y.) _ RED HOOK, N.Y. _ Fraleighs
have been farming the land here ever since John Adams was
President. Yet discouraging economics and mounting debts have at
times forced Dave Fraleigh, an apple and peach grower, to ponder
some distasteful strategies. Two or three years ago, he considered
selling part of his land to suburban-style developers the way
farmers have done all over the nation. He also considered turning
the farm into an agrarian Disneyland, inviting the public to pick
their own fruit and gawk at the vanishing ways of farmers. But he
rejected that, too. Now, Fraleigh has been able to shrug off such
possibilities because a white knight in June paid him hundreds of
thousands of dollars to bind himself to farm his 125 acres until he
retires, then pass it on to another farmer. By Joseph Berger.
</P>
