<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TECH (San Francisco) _ Sometime before the end of the
century, high-speed Internet access and low-cost phone calls will
make their way into American homes over television cables. But in
recent days, as executives of AT&AMP;T and Tele-Communications Inc.
have scrambled to sell Wall Street and the American consumer on the
wisdom of their merger, it has become clear that the technology
that will make that happen is a distant _ and costly _ vision. By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Boeing says that it delivered 61
airplanes in June, the highest one-month total ever, and is on
course to meet its goal of delivering 550 jets this year. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Women are buying jewelry with their
own money. They are playing professional basketball. And fewer are
waiting for the wedding to buy the house in the suburbs. To tap
into this increasingly lucrative consumer group, a growing number
of companies are now marketing directly to women some products and
services that were once pitched almost exclusively to men. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   URANIUM-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Treasury's announcement on
Monday that it would soon privatize the government's
half-century-old uranium-enrichment plants made waves largely
because of the proposed method of sale. But the more important news
is that the Treasury is moving forward in spite of years of
warnings that the sale would undermine a key initiative for
containing nuclear proliferation. By Peter Passell.
</P>
