<P>
   RADICAL-HOUSES (Undated) _ Whatever happened to truly innovative
houses? Houses so radical in concept, so bold in execution and at
the same time so comfortable and appealing that they made people
want to change the way they lived? These days, new houses in
America seem to be more about size than innovation. Architects save
their inspiration for museums, libraries and performing arts
centers. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-PLANS (Wickford, R.I.) _ Bob Gilbane bought a dream house
by mail for $495. The ready-to-build plan of a charming, elaborate
cottage _ with columns and porches, wavy shingles and oval windows
_ was designed by one of the country's best-known architects,
Robert A.M. Stern. Gilbane liked it so much when he saw it in Life
magazine he made it the centerpiece of his new 80-acre subdivision
here. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-RENTAL (New York) _ I'm thinking of renting a summer
house. Actually, I've been thinking of renting a summer house for
about 20 years now, and I can't say that I have made enormous
progress. The problem is that every time I say to myself, ``You
must rent a summer house this year,'' my palms grow sweaty and I am
overcome with a desire to lie down. By Deborah Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   SOLAR-TECH (Undated) _ Solar-powered fiber-optics? Photovoltaic
cell-laminated tensile hyperbolic paraboloids? Today's visionary
gibberish is tomorrow's plain English. The nifty thing about
emerging technologies is the way they sneak up on you, then
transform your life overnight. ``Under the Sun: An Outdoor
Exhibition of Light'' _ a new garden installation inside the
wrought iron fence of the Cooper Hewitt, National Design Museum
until Oct. 25 _ explains how solar technology has been sneaking up
on civilization for hundreds of years. By Barbara Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOTIC-SETTINGS (Undated) _ Seeing red, white and blue this
weekend? Take off the color blinders for the rest of the summer.
After the parades pass, refresh the table with garden settings: new
green majolica plates, silk poppy napkin rings and bright orange
and pink napkins. Or with new reproductions of American classics
like a glass hobnail pitcher. They're perfectly patriotic. By
Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-ROWHOUSE (New York) _ When Laurie Miller said goodbye
to the narrow house on Quincy Street, there was still a pull chain
attached to the wooden toilet tank up near the ceiling. There was
still a clawfoot bathtub. The boiler didn't always work. It was
home, though, and had been since she was 10 years old. But her
mother, a nurse, had died of cancer at 51, and the house, in the
Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, was foreclosed upon. Laurie
Miller and her siblings, all in their early 20s, had to move out.
That was in 1981. Ordinarily, that would have been the end of it.
The old rowhouse would have been bought, sold and maybe bought
again, its fortunes dependent on the whims of strangers. But Ms.
Miller is no ordinary woman. And for close to two decades, in her
odyssey around the city, she kept her eye on Quincy Street. By
Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ELECTRONIC-BOOKS (Undated) _ Let's face it, if the printed
book had just been invented, it would probably get three stars out
of five in reviews from the computer magazines. Printed books have
been popular for five centuries, of course, and have enjoyed great
success. But that hasn't stopped recent generations of science
fiction authors, futurists, entrepreneurs and even politicians from
fantasizing about electronic and digital books. This time around,
at least three digital approximations of books are scheduled to be
introduced, beginning in the fall. By Peter H. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BOOKS-COMPARE (Undated) _ Comparing three electronic books:
Size, prices, dates of availability. none on the market yet.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CYBER-CHAT (Undated) _ At its best, chat has been a way to
waste time, the equivalent of being a teen-ager on the telephone
but with a dozen chums at once. At worst, chat has been about
cybersex, and chat rooms have been seedy locations, virtual back
alleys where pedophiles and sexual predators lurked. But chat is
changing, maturing, diversifying. By Michele Marriott.
</P>
