A7069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ALLSTARS-NY     07-01 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ALLSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS' WILLIAMS IS BACK, FOR HOW LONG? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernie Williams shook more hands in the Yankees'
clubhouse than grooms do at weddings as teammates welcomed him back
from his rehabilitation assignment in Tampa, Fla., and
congratulated him for being one of the five Yankees chosen
Wednesday for the American League All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   But there are indications that those salutations could turn into
goodbyes once the 1998 season ends.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Williams' agreeing to an $8.25 million contract and
avoiding arbitration, he requested that the Yankees have no
negotiations with him or Scott Boras, his agent, during the season
and stressed that he wanted to gauge interest when his pact
expires, a person familiar with the conversations said Wednesday.
General Manager Brian Cashman confirmed that Williams explicitly
asked to be left alone and that the Yankees have honored this by
not talking with him or Boras for more than four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that he didn't want to negotiate during the season
and that he didn't want it to be a distraction,'' Cashman said.
``He told me that he wants to test the free-agent market. I told
him I could speak for myself about that, but I couldn't speak for
my owner. If he changes his mind, we'd love to talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is not likely to change his mind and Boras is
interested in getting his client on the open market to see how much
a team will pay a switch-hitting center fielder with power who hits
.300, is two-time All-Star and won a Gold Glove award.
</P>
<P>
   Williams brushed aside questions about his free agency Wednesday
and said that ``things will take care of themselves.'' Still, it
has become more obvious that Williams is curious to see what life
is like outside of Yankeeland and the request for no dialogue is
the first step toward leaving an organization he has been with
since he was 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed a desire to stay here, but he expressed an
extreme desire to see what his value is on the market,'' said
Cashman, who said he would defy the no-negotiation request if
George Steinbrenner ordered him to. ``He's earned that right. We
would love to have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is on the disabled list with a strained right
knee, was joined on the All-Star team by David Wells, Paul O'Neill,
Scott Brosius and Derek Jeter. Wells, Brosius and Jeter are
first-time All-Stars; O'Neill made the team for the fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   Wells started against the Phillies on Wednesday night and is
scheduled to start Tuesday night for the American League.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely Williams will play in the game since he is still
strengthening his knee and since Steinbrenner would be incensed if
the 29-year-old got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who participated in batting practice and outfield
drills while wearing an elastic brace around his knee, has not
played since June 10. Cashman said the Yanks have planned for
Williams to rehabilitate at Class AAA Columbus or Class AA Norwich
on Sunday and Monday, which leaves open the possibility of
pinch-hitting in the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be really funny,'' said Williams, when asked about
the possibility of his first game back being the All-Star Game.
``But I think I probably have to get back all the way to playing
and being functional.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre said: ``I'm sure he wants to go. The first
priority is the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Williams knows the second half of the season is more
important than one All-Star Game. Whether or not Williams gets the
chance to appear in another one as a Yankee is uncertain since
there have been no telephone calls, no faxes and no formal or
informal discussions about a new contract. The Yankees offered
Williams a 5-year, $37.5 million deal before he signed for one
year. Boras wants $10 or $11 million a year for seven years. The
advantage the Yankees supposedly had in re-signing Williams by
being able to negotiate with him during this season does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, this takes the heat off us,'' said Cashman. ``I
can't talk to him. He won't let us talk to him. If he doesn't want
us to talk to him, we won't talk to him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
