u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ASSEMBLYMAN-TRIAL-     07-01 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ASSEMBLYMAN-TRIAL-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER FOR ASSEMBLYMAN SAYS ACTIONS WERE LEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lawyer for Dov Hikind, the Brooklyn assemblyman
who is on trial for charges of receiving illegal payoffs from a
social services group, told jurors in his closing argument
Wednesday that prosecutors had concocted a false case by turning
``perfectly appropriate acts by an elected official'' into supposed
criminal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their claim of benefits to Dov Hikind and members of his
family are not supported by the facts,'' the lawyer, Gustave
Newman, said at the state legislator's trial in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Newman's assessment clashed sharply with that of a prosecutor,
Elisa Liang. In her closing argument on Tuesday, after six weeks of
testimony, Ms. Liang contended that Hikind, D-Borough Park, and
another defendant, Rabbi Elimelech Naiman, had used the largely
government-financed social services group ``as their personal piggy
bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Naiman is the former employment and training director of the
group, called the Council of Jewish Organizations of Borough Park.
The council was once powerful and politically connected, and until
the case that led to the trial, it ran programs like job training,
services for businesses and immigrants, and aid to the elderly and
to children.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the council by its widely used acronym, COJO, Ms.
Liang, an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, contended that
Hikind and Naiman ``were siphoning money out of COJO for themselves
and those close to them.'' She said the money was ``supposed to be
used for aiding the poor, lifting up the needy and helping those
who could not help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument on Tuesday and Wednesday, Naiman's
lawyer, Benjamin Brafman, told the jury that there had been ``no
corrupt intent'' in any of the rabbi's activities when he was an
official of the council and ``no proof before you of any kind left
in this case that Rabbi Naiman personally benefited'' from the
council's money.
</P>
<P>
   Hikind, who has been an assemblyman for 16 years, is accused of
receiving about $40,000 of the council's money in return for
obtaining hundreds of thousands of dollars in state money for the
council. The prosecution says the payoffs to him were in the form
of payments for items like school tuition for his children and
expenses for family trips abroad and political campaign and
fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the trial judge, Charles Sifton, significantly scaled
back the case against Hikind by dismissing four of the six charges
against him: two for conspiracy and two for fraud. Sifton agreed
with the defense that the prosecution had failed to back the
charges with sufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also pared down one of the remaining charges, removing
accusations that Hikind had stolen or fraudulently obtained money
from the council. The judge retained in that charge only the
accusation that Hikind had ``misapplied'' the money.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge left untouched another major charge: that Hikind
had corruptly solicited and accepted payoffs from the Council of
Jewish Organizations of Borough Park. Conviction on that charge is
punishable by a maximum of 10 years in prison.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Liang on Tuesday had shown the jury a series of checks that
she said were evidence of payoffs. Newman, Hikind's lawyer, went
over the same checks Wednesday and challenged Ms. Liang's
characterization before a gallery packed with spectators, including
many of the defendants' Orthodox Jewish supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Newman contended, for example, that one check that Ms. Liang had
said was payment for tuition at a Jewish school for a child of
Hikind's had in fact been a permissible grant to the school that a
council employee had mistakenly listed as tuition. He held that
some of the council payments that prosecutors had said were made
for Hikind's political benefit had really been for nonpartisan
voter-registration activities that the council had been permitted
to participate in.
</P>
<P>
   Newman is expected to complete his closing argument Thursday
morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
