u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-440&AMP;ADD     07-01 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON LAWYER EMPHASIZES CIVIL RIGHTS IN BRAWLEY TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ In his summation in the Tawana Brawley
defamation case Wednesday, the lawyer for the Rev. Al Sharpton
evoked the memory of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and
described the trial here as a test of the rights of civil rights
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been here for a greater purpose,'' said the lawyer,
Michael Hardy. He told the jurors that their verdict would
influence the extent to which leaders can criticize officials as
King did and, he said, as Sharpton did a decade ago when he spoke
for Ms. Brawley. ``Rev. Sharpton's business, if you will, `` he
said, ``was the business of civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy repeatedly referred to a Supreme Court ruling, which
governs the Brawley case, that protects public criticism of
officials by making it difficult for them to prove defamation. That
decision, the landmark case of The New York Times vs. Sullivan, he
reminded the jurors, came in 1964 in the midst of the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Reverend Sharpton did was what he always does, what he has
done for a long time,'' Hardy said. ``He came to the aid of a
family in need _ a young girl in particular _ and made a call for
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff, Steven Pagones, was an assistant district
attorney when Sharpton and two other Brawley family advisers
accused him of having raped Ms. Brawley in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Pagones was exonerated by a grand jury and filed his
defamation suit against Ms. Brawley, Sharpton and the two advisers,
C. Vernon Mason and Alton H. Maddox Jr. Ms. Brawley has never
appeared in the current trial, and it is the three advisers who are
fighting the case.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, in the first of what is expected to be four days of
closing statements, portrayed Sharpton as a noble leader and
Pagones as a vengeful man bent on undermining the advisers' civil
rights work.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a characterization he has used throughout the case,
Hardy said that statements Pagones saw as outrageous slanders were
nothing more than an advocate's protection of Ms. Brawley, whom
Hardy repeatedly referred to as ``a 15-year-old girl,'' which she
was at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff, Hardy said, was trying to harm the civil rights
movement. Race, he told the jurors, had been part of the Brawley
case from the first moments when she was discovered after vanishing
for four days in 1987. And race, he said, remained in the case as
it was nearing a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about politics,'' he said. ``About Mr. Pagones'
own agenda to pay back Rev. Sharpton for having come to Miss
Brawley's aid and for having called for Mr. Pagones' arrest.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After seven and a half months, more than 100 exhibits entered
into evidence and dozens of shouting matches, the first of the
summations seemed to show that the participants are worn out by the
passions of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, who can be aggressive, was relatively subdued Wednesday,
and Pagones' lawyer, William Stanton, made few objections. Judge S.
Barrett Hickman spent most of the day deep in his swivel chair,
with his back turned to the jurors and his eyes closed. When a
court officer nudged the judge to say the jurors wanted a brief
recess, Hickman appeared startled.
</P>
<P>
   But with Sharpton sitting at the defense table, Hardy never
strayed far from the central message he has been trying to deliver
throughout the case: that this is a defamation case, not a rape
case, and that under the ruling from the Supreme Court Pagones can
win his case only if Sharpton knew that his words were false when
he uttered them or if he acted with reckless disregard of whether
his statements were true or not.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what he knew when he called for Pagones' arrest, the
lawyer said, Sharpton was ``reasonable and justified.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has done throughout the trial, Hardy sidestepped the
question of whether Pagones committed a rape. He called the grand
jury report ``questionable and in some respects a whitewash'' and
he left open the question of whether Sharpton might have been given
misinformation by Ms. Brawley's family or by the other advisers.
</P>
<P>
   One question for the jurors, he said, was ``did he know with a
high degree of probability that everything he was being told was a
lie?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
