r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-FIRE-COX     07-01 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-FIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida fires could close roads to race
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH _ The smoke that smothered the Daytona area in
recent weeks has thinned and is expected to have no effect on
Saturday night's Pepsi 400 NASCAR race.
</P>
<P>
   However, roads leading to the track could be closed with little
advance warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to speculate on when we'll get this thing
under control,'' said Dora Maxemow, public information officer for
Largo Fire Rescue in St. Pete. ``Most of the fires are south of
Daytona, below New Smyrna to the Brevard County line. I don't
believe the race will be affected by the fires, other than some
fans may not be able to get here because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fans have been here several days, their cars, trucks,
motorcycles and bicycles lined near the track, awaiting today's 6
a.m. stampede for choice spots within the 2.5-mile tri-oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't no fires and smoke going to keep us from this race,''
said Jerri Wilson, who arrived here Wednesday from Jacksonville
with 22 others in an old school bus. ``This is big, the first night
race ever here. Can't miss that.''
</P>
<P>
   The air at the track was smokey during the early morning hours
on Wednesday, track officials said, but the situation had improved
by 9 a.m. Fans are calling daily for updated information, said John
Story, the speedway's public relations director.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are calling in droves about the fires,'' Story said.
``The perception outside of Florida is that the fires are around
the track. We tell them they're not close to the track but that
there could be isolated road closings.''
</P>
<P>
   One such closing occurred Wednesday morning, a section of I-95
below New Smyrna to the Brevard County line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most serious situation, involving fires, ever in
the state,'' Maxemow said. ``The first strike came on Father's Day
weekend, and we've had a thousand people involved in this effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoke won't be a problem, although the smell is likely to remain
in the air, Maxemow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the Atlantic Ocean breezes, the smoke should drift
out of the area well before the race,'' she said. ``The smell,
though, probably will linger in this area for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR president Bill France Jr. said officials will keep close
watch on the situation, but he doesn't expect problems. And Story
said all systems are go.
</P>
<P>
   ``If race fans were in any danger,'' Story said, ``we would not
have the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
