<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0594 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARMS-LANDRIGHTS-ART-     07-01 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMS-LANDRIGHTS-ART-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO KEEP 'EM DOWN ON THE FARM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RED HOOK, N.Y. _ Fraleighs have been farming the land here ever
since John Adams was president, forming part of an enduring rustic
tapestry of grazing cows, languid country roads and trees sagging
with fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet discouraging economics and mounting debts have at times
forced Dave Fraleigh, an apple and peach grower, to ponder some
distasteful strategies. Two or three years ago, he considered
selling part of his land to suburban-style developers the way
farmers have done all over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He also considered turning the farm into an agrarian Disneyland,
inviting the public to pick their own fruit and gawk at the
vanishing ways of farmers. But he rejected that, too. ``I enjoy
growing fruit; I don't enjoy being in entertainment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fraleigh has been able to shrug off such possibilities
because a white knight in June paid him hundreds of thousands of
dollars to bind himself to farm his 125 acres until he retires,
then pass it on to another farmer.
</P>
<P>
   For Fraleigh, the instant infusion of cash will allow him to pay
off debt and buy 93 more acres. For Red Hook, it may mean something
far more valuable: one more lasting farm to help sustain a rural
sense of place far into the future.
</P>
<P>
   The white knight, in Fraleigh's case, was an environmental group
called Scenic Hudson, but similar programs have existed in 20
states for many years. Local and state governments and private
preservation trusts have been buying development rights to
farmland, permanently limiting the use of the land to agriculture,
to sustain their locales' pastoral character.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Scenic Hudson's program noteworthy is that rather
than preserving farms scattershot, the organization is spending
$2.5 million to preserve a cluster of seven Red Hook farms with
1,000 acres _ 16 percent of the town's farmland _ on the theory
that a rural area needs a critical mass of farms to resist
development pressures. Fraleigh, 44, said he would not have kept a
farm if everyone around him had sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to have a farm in the middle of suburbia,'' said
Fraleigh (FRAY-lee), who does not yet know whether his children _
Peter, 10; Steven, 8, and Sarah, 5 _ will want to farm.
</P>
<P>
   What the government and private preservationists do is have
farmland appraised for what it would be worth on the open market,
then for what it would be worth if it could be used only as
farmland. They pay the farmer the difference, sometimes more than
50 percent of a parcel's value.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if land in Dutchess County is worth $5,000 an acre
unencumbered but only $3,000 if limited to farming, then the farmer
would be paid $2,000 an acre. The farmer keeps the land, but unless
a court intervenes, the deed to the farm is restricted with a
provision that forever prohibits residential or commercial
development.
</P>
<P>
   New York state, in a program less than 3 years old, is now
spending $5 million for farmland preservation, providing grants to
selected municipalities willing to shoulder 75 percent of the cost
of development rights.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, which started its program in 1973, has spent $168
million preserving 234 farms, and Connecticut has spent $75 million
on protecting 169 farms. Some of the programs make use of a $35
million federal pot of matching funds created in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One million acres of the country's 945 million acres of farmland
are swallowed up every year, transformed into homes and malls,
according to the American Farmland Trust, a conservation group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Southern Dutchess County, about an hour and 15 minute drive from
the New York City line, was not too long ago a sleepy backwater of
milk farms and orchards. Like Red Hook farther north in the county,
it was the kind of place where, as Fraleigh's wife, Karen, likes to
say, ``I can't go into the grocery store without running into four
people I know on a first-name basis.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, the arrival of two huge IBM plants and the
emergence of corporate office parks around White Plains created a
thirst for housing, particularly in southern Dutchess. From 1969 to
1995, the last year for which figures are available, one of every
four farming acres in Dutchess vanished, leaving 615 farms with
113,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a farm has been sold, it never comes back,'' said Dave
Tetor, agriculture program leader of Cornell Cooperative Extension
in Dutchess County, which furnishes farmers with research.
</P>
<P>
   The downsizing of IBM earlier this decade gave a reprieve to
Dutchess' farmers, but the booming economy has made them brace for
the likelihood of another developer onslaught. Anticipating that
invasion, Scenic Hudson tapped $2.5 million it received from the
Lila Acheson and DeWitt Wallace Fund for the Hudson Highlands and
used it for buying development rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger generation is seeing the cards stacking up against
them,'' said Steven Rosenberg, Scenic Hudson's director of land
preservation. ``They'll say: `What am I going to do? Go into mom
and dad's farm or go to business school?' If the cards continue
stacking up the way they do, they go to business school.''
</P>
<P>
   The preservation programs have helped not only landowners like
Fraleigh, but also prospective landowners like John Hardeman.
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman, 45, owns a tiny seven-acre orchard with a roadside
produce stand just outside the village center. He could not afford
to buy substantial orchard land in Red Hook, where the prospect of
development had pushed prices above $5,000 an acre. So in 1989, he
bought land in Livingston, 15 miles north, and became what he calls
``a commuting farmer.''
</P>
<P>
   But that commuting may soon end. In June, Scenic Hudson bought
the development rights to most of the farm near the roadside stand,
173 of Dave Lown's 250 acres, reducing its value to the point that
Hardeman could afford to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Lown, 70, a fourth-generation farmer, is ready to retire and his
son and daughter have no interest in farming. He could have made
more money selling the land to a developer. But he says that he is
gratified that he can help keep the land the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather see it stay a farm,'' he said. ``I like to look at
trees and open land instead of all houses and traffic. It makes for
a nice rural area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
