<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 NETS FOCUS ON NEWARK FOR ARENA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With new ownership in place, the New Jersey Nets can turn their
attention to a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   A site has been selected in Newark that would support an arena,
said Sam Crane, president of the Regional Business Partnership, an
organization involved in the revitalization of Newark. With a 2004
escape window in the Nets' lease at Continental Arena in the
Meadowlands, Crane is confident that the city would be able to have
the arena completed by then.
</P>
<P>
   The Newark site is adjacent to Penn Station-Newark and
accessible by Broad Street and McCarter Highway, said Crane, who
scouted the MCI Center in Washington, the Palace of Auburn Hills in
Michigan, the Core States Center in Philadelphia and Gund Arena in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we looked at was the existing capacity of the streets and
rail lines to support the arena, plus other improvements that are
already funded and in place,'' Crane said. ``They don't need a new
highway, a new rail, or even new rail service. They are already
sufficient to support an arena today. They don't have to build a
new transportation infrastructure, which is a huge public cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ownership group, put together by the real estate
developers Finn Wentworth and Stanley Gale of Florham Park, N.J.,
now includes David Gerstein, who is a majority owner among the
Nets' current seven-member ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   Nets president Michael Rowe said the team will resume
discussions with the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority
concerning an extension of their lease, which runs through 2030,
and the ways that Continental Arena could be upgraded, but admitted
that the new ownership, with the support of the New Jersey
businessman and philanthropist Raymond Chambers, will pursue the
Newark site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes years to build buildings, years to locate locations,
years to finance them,'' said Rowe, who added that the arena would
likely be both publicly and privately financed. ``We're going to be
here for a while. We know the initiative of the new group is to get
a new arena. They would like one in an area with a lot of mass
transportation, that is more than just an arena. The downtown
environment fits. They'd love to have an arena in Newark.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowe's description of an ideal arena describes the plans in
place for the Newark arena and would seem to rule out Continental
Arena, which has been hampered by a lack of mass transportation. A
Hoboken site, favored by the New Jersey Devils' hockey team owner
John McMullen, is likely to need a new road structure to
accommodate the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Crane said: ``There are a lot of questions of Newark versus the
Meadowlands, but my take is that Newark is a solution to the
Meadowlands. That complex could be more successful with development
around it. The Meadowlands would still be an entertainment and
sports complex; it would just do it differently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
