<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MOOG-FOR-HALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOOG MERITS SERIOUS HALL CONSIDERATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, Andy Moog can wear a Fort Worth Brahmas
sweater to his Hall of Fame induction.
</P>
<P>
   A night like that won't come any sooner than three years from
now, but by then, Fort Worth might be that deep in the heart of the
man who is trying to boost hockey ``Where the West Begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the time between now and 2001, there will be much
debate on whether the former Stars goalie, who announced his NHL
retirement last month after 18 seasons, should go into the Hall of
Fame at all. The NHL has been nothing if not inconsistent
throughout its history, and that ``Garage League'' feeling has
caused more than just a few rifts. The fact that former league
president Gil Stein was inducted into the Hall on a controversial
vote in 1993 that later was overturned has forced the Hall to
toughen its standards, and there's a feeling Moog might get washed
out because of the stricter standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that the standards have
been toughened and that everything is being watched very closely,''
said Scott Morrison, Hall of Fame president and one of the people
who will be able to nominate Moog for entry. ``That said, I think
Andy Moog is a definite candidate who will receive a very serious
look.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog deserves at least that. In fact, he deserves to be let in
on the first vote. The numbers of the cherub-cheeked goalie from
Penticton, British Columbia, say as much. The stories behind the
numbers say even more.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Moog finished his career with 372 victories _ seventh on
the all-time list. His winning percentage of .621 is tops among
goalies who have won 300 or more games. Moog appeared in four
All-Star games, once helped his team win the Jennings Trophy for
lowest goals-against average (Boston in 1990) and three times was a
member of a Stanley Cup champion (Edmonton in 1984, '85 and '87).
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it is those Stanley Cup championships that will have
most voters turning a critical eye toward Moog's entry. In one
Cup-winning postseason (1984), he shared the goaltending duties. In
the other two postseasons, he was the backup behind Grant Fuhr. In
1985, he played in just two playoff games. In 1987, he also was
involved in just two decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Had Moog let that stand, had he finished his career as a backup
to Fuhr, then one could question his place in the Hall. It didn't
matter that he was winning more than 25 games each season if he
didn't play in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Moog couldn't live that way. Even though the NHL was pretty
much a dictatorship offering players almost no leverage, Moog found
a way to break free. While holding out between contracts, Moog
struck a deal with a grocery-store chain in Canada that paid him
$100,000 to play for the Canadian Olympic Team in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to this creative escape, Oilers general manager Glen
Sather was then forced to trade Moog to the Boston Bruins. There,
Moog helped the Bruins to the Presidents' Trophy in 1990 for the
league's best record and also helped snatch the Jennings Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Moog also posted the lowest goals-against average in the
playoffs that season at 2.21.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing preventing perfection was that the Oilers
defeated the Bruins in the Stanley Cup Finals, ruining Moog's
chance for revenge. Moog took the Bruins to the Eastern Conference
finals the next season and posted a career-best 37 victories in
1992-93. He then put together four strong seasons with the Stars,
including a career-best 2.15 goals-against average at the age of
37.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his time, Moog was always outspoken, always a leader,
always someone who looked out for the game. A vice president for
the players' association, he was instrumental in helping the
players win concessions during the 1994 lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just strikes you as a guy who really cares about hockey and
about the NHL,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, it will be the league's turn to look out for
Andy Moog. He'll probably still be down in Texas, where he is part
owner of the Western Professional Hockey League's Fort Worth
Brahmas, trying to fashion the club into a champion, or possibly
working with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   If _ no, make that when _ the Hall of Fame comes looking for
him, they know where to find him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
