<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FREE-AGENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS KEEP CARBONNEAU, LUDWIG; WOO VETERAN CLARK 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stars announced yesterday they will be keeping two of their
veteran players. And it seems only a matter of time before they add
another veteran to the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Both Guy Carbonneau and Craig Ludwig have agreed to terms for
one-year contracts with the Stars, who spent much of the first day
of unrestricted free agency yesterday wooing veteran Wendel Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau, 38, and Ludwig, 37, found fresh legs and new drive
as part of a Stars team that won the Presidents' Trophy and
advanced to the Western Conference finals before losing to the
Detroit Red Wings. The Stars are hoping they can do the same thing
with Clark, a 31-year-old who has been hampered by injuries for the
past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see in him, potentially, a guy who could get back up to
where he was, if he's surrounded by the right people,'' Stars
general manager Bob Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was drafted first overall in 1985 by the Toronto Maple
Leafs and had his best seasons with that team, scoring 34 goals in
1985-86, 37 in 1986-87 and 46 in 1993-94. After stints with the
Quebec Nordiques and New York Islanders, he returned to Toronto in
1996 and hoped to end his career with the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   However, Toronto's management told Clark, an unrestricted free
agent who made $2.3 million last season, to look around and get
back to them in a couple of weeks in hopes of getting Clark to take
a lower salary.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have decided not to re-sign either Benoit Hogue ($1.25
million) or Greg Adams ($1.55 million), giving the team money to
work with in that left wing slot. So, the thought is the Stars
would be willing to pay more for Clark than Toronto or the Edmonton
Oilers, who also are interested.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's agent, Don Meehan, said yesterday Clark is interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to talk more \Rtoday,\S but, yes, I think he has a
great intereset in Dallas,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Stars don't expect to go crazy in free agency.
While they made a call to Mike Gilles, the agent for St. Louis
Blues left winger Geoff Courtnall, it's clear the Stars are not
interested in giving the soon-to-be 36-year-old winger the
three-year contract or the $3 million per season he desires. What
the Stars likely will do is wait for Clark to decide if he wants to
leave Toronto and at the same time see if the asking price on
Courtnall goes down. Either way, Gainey sees free agency taking a
much slower pace this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems that people are being more cautious,'' he said.
``There's no impulse buying.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Sharks were the only ones to jump in the big water
yesterday, signing Chicago Blackhawks defenseman Gary Suter to a
three-year deal for $10 million. Suter made $1.6 million last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks also re-signed Bryan Marchment, ensuring the rivalry
started in the playoffs will continue next season when the Stars
move to the Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Ludwig and Carbonneau to the Stars on one-year
contracts was somewhat expected, with both performing well last
season. Carbonneau received a raise from $750,000 to $1.1 million,
while Ludwig bumped up from $750,000 to $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both had better seasons than they did the year before, and I
think that's an indication of their determination and the fact that
we as a team are fighting for a championship,'' Gainey said. ``They
both have a good grasp on what we want from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig, an alternate captain, said returning to the Stars is a
matter of taking care of unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a part of this team through all the \Rbad\S times,''
he said. ``I want to be here through the good times. With the
exception of a couple of injuries, this team was right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing a player like Clark, who has nursed various injuries
throughout his career and last season played in just 47 of 82 games
while scoring 12 goals, seems a problem for the injury-prone Stars.
But with the support of young wingers like Jamie Wright, Jason
Botterill and Juha Lind stepping up, Clark could be the veteran
goal-scorer (294 career goals) the Stars need.
</P>
<P>
   It appears clear that goal-scorer isn't Brett Hull. The
All-Star, who is being courted by the Chicago Blackhawks and
Washington Capitals, is not among the Stars' choices, Gainey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
