<HEADLINE>
SELE, WETTELAND NAMED AS ALL-STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Aaron Sele was planning to spend the All-Star
break at home in Washington state. In fact, he had already bought
plane tickets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove changed those plans, selecting
both Sele and Rangers reliever John Wetteland to the American
League All-Star team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reserves and pitchers were announced yesterday for both the
American and National leagues and Oakland outfielder Ben Grieve, a
graduate of Martin High School and son of Rangers announcer Tom
Grieve, also made the American League team. But Cubs pitcher Kerry
Wood, a graduate of Grand Prairie High, was left off the National
League team for the game, which is scheduled Tuesday night at Coors
Field in Denver. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sele and Wetteland join catcher Ivan Rodriguez and outfielder
Juan Gonzalez to give the Rangers four All-Stars for the first time
since 1989. But the Rangers were still disappointed that pitcher
Rick Helling was left off the team despite a record of 11-4 and a
4.25 earned-run average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said all along, there were going to be people not make
it who deserve to be there,'' Helling said. ``It would have been
hard for us to have five guys on the team. I'm surprised we have
four, but that shows Mike Hargrove has a lot of respect for our
team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sele is 11-5 with a 4.26 ERA, almost identical numbers to
Helling. But two factors worked in his favor. Helling is pitching
Sunday, two days before the game, and Hargrove left off both David
Cone and Chuck Finley because they're pitching Sunday as well. Sele
also had his best game against Cleveland, beating them 1-0 on May
17 when he allowed five hits and two walks in eight innings,
striking out nine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This means I'm playing for a good team,'' said Sele, who is
making his first trip to the All-Star Game. ``This is a reflection
of the team. They've played hard, scored a lot of runs, played good
defense and have hung in there against Anaheim.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time Wetteland was selected. He went to the
1996 game in Philadelphia while with the New York Yankees but did
not pitch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big,'' Wetteland said. ``I don't want to downplay it;
it's certainly wonderful. But I don't place a lot of attention on
personal performance. I pitch for the Texas Rangers and this is a
result of that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also placed four players on the 1989 team: second
baseman Julio Franco, outfielder Ruben Sierra and pitchers Nolan
Ryan and Jeff Russell. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All four are certainly deserving,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said of this year's All-Stars. ``I'm disappointed Rick didn't
get selected, but I'm tickled to death we have four.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
