<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-EXPERIMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS HOPE TO GET OK FOR AIDS TREATMENT EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ If ethics committees approve, researchers in Boston and
Geneva will soon do the crucial AIDS experiment: Stop all antiviral
drugs in a group of patients who began treatment soon after they
became infected with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
   AIDS specialists attending the 12th World AIDS Conference here
hope the experiment will show that HIV infection does not
necessarily sentence individuals to a lifetime of costly and
onerous triple-drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that these early-treated patients are cured. In fact,
scientists know that about one million AIDS viruses still lurk in
each patient's system, even though the most sensitive tests can
detect none in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of viral infection, that is a tiny amount. But it is
more than enough to kindle a raging infection if either antiviral
drugs or immune defenses cannot keep HIV suppressed to such low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to see if these patients' immune systems have revived
enough to keep the AIDS virus under permanent control, just as most
people's do with the chickenpox, Herpes simplex, or Epstein-Barr
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will see if the virus rebounds without drug treatment and
if the immune system can handle it,'' Dr. Bruce W. Walker of
Massachusetts General Hospital said in an interview here Wednesday.
``It's a question we're compelled to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker and his colleagues have identified 19 patients who were
treated soon after they acquired HIV infection, before the virus
had time to damage their immune systems irreparably. They will be
asked if they are willing to halt treatment while doctors monitor
their blood for signs that HIV has returned in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   If it does, doctors will immediately resume triple-drug HIV
treatments. Recent studies indicate that resumption of treatment
should once again suppress HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Hirschel of University Hospital in Geneva, chairman
of this week's massive AIDS meeting, said a similar group of
early-treated patients here will stop therapy if the hospital's
ethics committee approves. ``I think it will be accepted,''
Hirschel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike others, patients who started treatment during very
early infection have undetectable levels of HIV in their blood even
with tests capable of detecting as few as five copies of the virus
per cubic millimeter,'' he said. ``This suggests an essential
difference between patients treated early and those treated
later.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate set of experiments that will get under way this
summer in Boston and New York, Walker and New York AIDS researcher
David Ho will give two different experimental vaccines to patients
infected with HIV to see if they can ``tweak'' the immune system
into generating cells capable of keeping the virus under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients are lined up and we're ready to go,'' Ho said.
``We'll see if the vaccine will enhance the immune response.'' That
trial in New York will involve 10 patients who were given maximal
anti-HIV therapy within 90 days of infection and have been
successfully treated for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston vaccine experiment will enroll a different group of
HIV patients _ those who have been chronically infected but have
chosen not yet to begin antiviral drugs. After six months of potent
treatments, they will be given a vaccine invented by the late Jonas
Salk that consists of killed HIV that has been stripped of its
outer coat.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine experiments are expected to yield crucial
information about the feasibility of an HIV vaccine, both for
preventing and treating infection.
</P>
<P>
   Both sets of experiments should show if the immune responses
that successfully treated patients generate are enough to keep the
virus suppressed indefinitely. ``We don't believe it's necessary to
eradicate the virus,'' Walker said. ``But it would be profoundly
disappointing if this isn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago at the last international AIDS meeting in
Vancouver, Ho made headlines with a similar proposal to stop potent
antiviral drugs in a small group of promptly treated patients after
their virus was no longer detectable for some months by the most
sensitive tests of that day.
</P>
<P>
   Ho never did that experiment _ which was based on demonstrating
that the patients had been cured of HIV infection _ because
subsequent research showed that even the earliest and most potent
drug therapy could not rid any patient of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   New tests, capable of detecting as few as 50 copies of HIV in a
15th of a teaspoon of blood, have shown that many patients had not
really cleared the virus from their blood. Subsequent research
showed that, even when the virus could not be found in the blood,
it could be teased out from certain ``resting'' immune cells if
they were activated.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said the time is finally ripe for doing the
treatment-stopping trial because they now have proof that the
immune system eventually rebuilds itself among individuals who got
aggressive drug treatment within weeks or months of their HIV
infection.
</P>
<P>
   Other HIV-infected individuals who are not lucky enough to have
had early, aggressive drug treatment may also achieve what
scientists are calling ``immune reconstitution.'' But for now, the
early-treated patients represent the best that state-of-the-art
AIDS care can do in suppressing HIV and allowing the immune system
to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have provided proof that the immune system is not dead'' in
HIV-infected people, Dr. Brigitte Autran of the Petie Salpetriere
Hospital in Paris. ``It is capable of being restored, even late in
the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggressively treated HIV patients often show a reversal of the
decline in key ``orchestrator'' immune cells designated CD4 _ a
hallmark of the infection. But more important to immunologists is
new evidence that these reconstituted CD4 cells can recognize HIV,
and that there is eventual return of other immune cells called
cytotoxic lymphocytes (CTLs) capable of recognizing and destroying
any cells infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Autran Wednesday reported that 80 percent of several hundred
French patients could generate such ``memory'' cells capable of
recognizing HIV, including many with advanced AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most infections are dealt with by strong CTL responses,''
Walker noted. But CD4 cells, also called ``helper'' cells, must
tell them what to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
