</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-HUBBELL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES TAX EVASION CASE AGAINST WEBSTER HUBBELL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add case also being dismissed against Hubbell's wife,
accountant and lawyer; minor editing throughout.)  (See also STARR-HUBBELL-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ps) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge threw out the tax evasion case
against Webster Hubbell on Wednesday, ruling in a powerful critique
of the independent counsel's tactics that Kenneth Starr had both
exceeded his authority and reneged on a promise to grant him
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge James Robertson found that the criminal case
was too far removed from Starr's original mandate of 1994 to
investigate the business dealings of President Clinton and Hillary
Rodham Clinton in Arkansas more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ruled that prosecutors violated Hubbell's right
against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   If upheld on appeal, Robertson's decision would remove any
pressure on Hubbell, a longtime friend of the Clintons and a former
associate attorney general, to provide incriminating evidence
against them. Hubbell has long contended that he knows of no such
information.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal, embodied in strong language, will resonate beyond
the legal case because it goes to the heart of criticism by the
White House and Clinton supporters. They have contended that the
Hubbell case had come to symbolize Starr's determined pursuit of
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Served a subpoena, Hubbell had refused to turn over 13,120 pages
of records and invoked the Fifth Amendment. The independent counsel
then gave him immunity from prosecution, forcing him to turn over
the documents. But instead, the records were used improperly to
build a case against him, the judge said. Robertson called the
subpoena that led to the immunity agreement a ``quintessential
fishing expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the judge's interpretation of Starr's authority was a
major setback for the independent counsel, the judge himself noted
that his reasoning should not affect the Whitewater inquiry's more
recent expansion into the relationship between former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky and the president.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, handed up two months ago, had accused Hubbell,
his wife, Suzy, and two tax advisers of scheming in the last four
years to avoid paying taxes and penalties of more than $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had contended that much of the owed taxes stemmed
from money Hubbell had embezzled and from hundreds of thousands of
dollars in income from jobs referred by friends and supporters of
the president. The indictment said Hubbell did little work for
those jobs and suggested they might have been arranged to
discourage him from cooperating with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson ruled that the charges lodged against Hubbell in
April were too far afield from the original investigation over
which Starr was appointed to preside. Starr's original mandate was
an inquiry begun in 1994 to examine the ties of the president and
first lady to a corrupt savings association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent counsel's explanation of how this indictment
is `connected with' the original grant was a recitation spanning
six degrees of relationship,'' Robertson wrote. ``He has identified
no common witnesses, described no similar patterns of conduct,
cited no similar applicable law.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell appeared shocked and relieved by the decision to dismiss
the case against himself, his wife, his accountant, Michael
Schaufele, and his lawyer, Charles Owen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good day,'' he said at the doorstep of his home here.
``I don't know how to react. It's been five years.''
</P>
<P>
   A one-paragraph statement that was issued by the independent
counsel's office but not signed by Starr said the decision would be
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pleadings and oral arguments to the District Court reveal
our respectful disagreement with the district judge's decision,''
the statement said. ``We will seek prompt review of this ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, privately jubilant over the wide-ranging
criticism of Starr, which included a characterization of his
constitutional views as ``scary,'' were uncharacteristically
taciturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else do you say when a federal judge has used words like
`scary' and `fishing expedition?''' said Rahm Emanuel, a senior
adviser to Clinton. ``It speaks volumes about that office and the
investigation itself.''
</P>
<P>
   In China, President Clinton said that he was pleased with the
outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision speaks for itself, but I'm happy for Webb and
Suzy and their family, Mike and his family and Charlie and his
family,'' he said in a remark relayed by Mike McCurry, the
presidential press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, who had also been a partner of Mrs. Clinton's at the
Rose law firm in Arkansas, had served nearly 17 months in prison
for bilking his former law partners and clients before he was
charged in April in the tax case.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors have said that Hubbell had failed in the
first criminal case to live up to an agreement to be fully candid,
while Hubbell's supporters have said that the second indictment was
simply a further effort to pressure him unfairly into making false
incriminating statements against the Clintons. The tax indictment
suggested that some of the income he had failed to report to the
Internal Revenue Service might have been to discourage him from
being more candid with investigators, a suggestion that he had
vigorously denied.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robertson first hinted that he was leaning against the
independent counsel at a hearing last Friday when he referred to
one prosecutor's arguments on immunity as ``scary'' and was dubious
about links another prosecutor tried to make between the tax case
and Starr's original charter.
</P>
<P>
   The judge joined the bench in 1994, an early appointee of
President Clinton. He had been a seasoned corporate litigator and
partner at Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering, one of Washington's largest
law firms. While his clients included a number of large
corporations, the judge had also distinguished himself for playing
a leading role in civil rights causes in the United States and
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The central issue in his ruling on Starr's jurisdiction was the
delicate balance between the judiciary and the executive branch in
enforcing the independent counsel law and the proper role of the
special court that appoints such counsels and oversees their work.
The court, known as the Special Division, consists of three federal
appeals judges appointed by the Chief Justice of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Created by the independent counsel law, the Special Division
serves as a hybrid institution, performing some functions normally
left to the executive branch and others similar to those of the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   In January the special division, acting at the request of Starr,
issued a secret order giving the Whitewater independent counsel the
authority to investigate Hubbell's taxes. The precise question
presented by Hubbell and the other defendants was whether the
special division had the authority to expand Starr's jurisdiction
in the absence of a request by the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Two other federal district court judges ruled last year that the
special division had such authority in criminal cases brought
against peripheral defendants by the independent counsel
investigating former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy. Those judges
had written that they were reluctant to second-guess the decisions
of the special division, particularly since they are all appeals
court judges.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday Robertson said he disagreed with those district
court judges. Robertson found that although the special division
consisted of Federal appeals judges, the panel ``in fact is not a
court of appeals.'' Rather by constitutional limitations imposed
upon it by the Supreme Court, the special division performs
``essentially ministerial'' acts that can be reviewed by a district
court.
</P>
<P>
   As such, Robertson wrote, the special division ``may interpret
the independent counsel's original grant. It may not expand the
independent counsel's jurisdiction without the consent of the
attorney general.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This limitation is constitutional, and, if it is to mean
anything at all, must be enforceable upon a proper challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge noted that his reasoning ought not to affect Starr's
jurisdiction to pursue the investigation into the Lewinsky matter
because the attorney general had specifically recommended that the
independent counsel examine it.
</P>
<P>
   After finding that he had the authority to review the special
division's order conferring authority on the independent counsel to
investigate Hubbell's taxes, the judge concluded that the order was
not ``demonstrably related'' to the attorney general's application
for the original appointment of Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson rejected the independent counsel's argument that the
agreement that led to the production of Hubbell's business records
should be narrowly construed. Prosecutors had maintained that the
immunity that they had granted meant only that they could not tell
a jury that they had received the documents from Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hubbell's compelled production of documents allowed the
independent counsel to build a case against Mr. Hubbell different
in all material respects from the case for which they had been
subpoenaed,'' the judge wrote. ``Mr. Hubbell was thereby turned
into the primary informant against himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
