<SLUG> BC-RAC-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONE STAR REPORT SAYS TRACK IN WINNING FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie made
operating profits of $4.8 million last year and $3.8 million in
1996, according to a financial document the horse track filed last
month with the Texas Racing Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The financial statement, audited for the TRC by accounting firm
Ernst and Young, indicates that Lone Star has avoided some of the
startup woes of other Texas tracks. Sam Houston Race Park in
Houston and Retama Park near San Antonio, the state's other Class 1
horse tracks, had betting revenues fall far short of expenses
during their first two years of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star earned $40.5 million in pari-mutuel wagering revenue
during 1997, with listed expenses of slightly less than $36
million. Virtually all of the pari-mutuel profits associated with
the track's 1997 season came from thoroughbred racing, Lone Star
president Bob Kaminski said. The fall quarter horse live season was
only a ``break-even'' proposition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent racing executive in another state who examined the
statement for the ``Star-Telegram'' pointed out what he said were
``red flags'' in the track's current cash-flow situation. But
Kaminski said that the questionable assets vs. liabilities portion
of the Lone Star Race Park Ltd. financial report is misleading. He
said the track's cash-flow situation is actually ``very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And this year you should see an improvement over last year,''
Kaminski said. ``Our commissions for the year-to-date are ahead of
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star opened for simulcasting in May 1996 and for live
racing in April 1997. The $96 million facility was largely financed
through $65 million in bonds sold by the city of Grand Prairie and
backed by revenues from a half-cent sales tax approved by voters in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Sales tax revenues are well ahead of projections, Kaminski said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 31, Lone Star reported $5.6 million in current assets
_ more than half reserved for bond debt and racing purses _ and
$13.1 million in current liabilities, including $7 million in
accounts payable.
</P>
<P>
   Taken alone, that portion of the statement could raise some
eyebrows. However, Kaminski said some track assets are carried
under the heading of LSJC Development Corp., and still other assets
are listed under MBLS Inc., which operates concessions at the
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a true picture of all the assets and liabilities, you
would need to look at a complete consolidated picture for all three
entities,'' Kaminski said.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he said, would reflect a healthy situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a pretty strong financial position,'' Kaminski said,
``especially considering that we paid for a number of capital
expenses last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a nice market return on equity. But
without the help from the city of Grand Prairie, it would be a
marginal investment. If we had an additional $50-$65 million of
debt, it would look a lot different.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand Prairie Councilwoman Teri Jackson said yesterday that a
separate audit of the track for the city's sports corporation
raised no red flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't turn up anything that we were worried about,''
said Jackson, who chairs the finance committee for the Grand
Prairie Sports Facilities Development Corp., which oversees the
financing and operation of the track and leases the facilities to
Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   TRC executive secretary Paula Flowerday said she also went over
the financial statement with Tim Craig, the commission's director
of finance and accounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, the TRC is very pleased with Lone Star's
operations,'' Flowerday said. ``We hope that this is a signal for
continued improvement for the racing industry in the state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
