<HEADER>
A7127 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-A     07-01 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALLED TALKS CLOUD TKACHUK'S FUTURE   
 COYOTES COULD TRADE CAPTAIN TO AVOID STANDOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Imagine there's no No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy if you try, according to Rick Tocchet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you, I'll find it very hard to accept if
we end up trading Keith Tkachuk,'' said Tocchet, the outspoken
right wing for the Coyotes. ``He's too valuable of a player.
Besides, we're already thin at left wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we've got no control. I could be traded tomorrow,
too. That's just part of the business. It could happen to any one
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it could happen to Tkachuk, the Coyotes' volatile
captain who wears No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   And it could happen sooner than later if things aren't resolved
quickly regarding a contract extension for one of the NHL's premier
power forwards and goal scorers.
</P>
<P>
   A Tkachuk trade became a real possibility this week when General
Manager Bobby Smith suspended negotiations indefinitely with
Tkachuk's agent, Bob Murray, and pulled the team's latest offer
from the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to trade Keith. I want him to play on our team,''
Smith said. ``Keith has made it clear he wants to be here, too. He
hasn't said, `Trade me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, however, may have no other choice as long as
Tkachuk continues to demand a restructured deal worth $8 million
per season. The team's latest offer, which Murray and Tkachuk
rejected on Monday, would have paid him an average of $6.5 million
per year over the next five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The total package, Smith said, was worth more than the
five-year, $27.5 million contract the Buffalo Sabres gave to goalie
Dominik Hasek. Murray says goal scorers like Tkachuk, however, are
worth more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, all I know,'' Smith said, ``is Dominik Hasek was just
named last week as the Most Valuable Player in the entire National
Hockey League _ for the second straight year. He also guided his
team into the Stanley Cup semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, who never has led the Coyotes out of the first round of
the playoffs but has scored 142 goals the past three years, has two
options. He can report to training camp in September and honor the
final two years of his present contract, which is set to pay him
$2.8 million next season and $3 million the next. Or he can stage a
holdout, which he's done before.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting out for two full seasons, though, is virtually unheard
of. Neither he nor the Coyotes could afford that.
</P>
<P>
   So either the two sides try to meet in the middle, which doesn't
seem likely at this point, or the Coyotes must attempt to trade
him.
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet, one of the team's most vocal leaders, said he isn't
sure what to make of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He signed a contract and you're supposed to honor it, but
whether I agree with it or not, it's up to the individual,''
Tocchet said. ``I'm a player and I'd like to see him get his money
as much as anybody. He's a great player. My hope is that both
parties just get together and get this thing resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm selfish. I just don't want to get to another opening night
where the Coyotes and Keith Tkachuk are fighting. That happened
last year and it went on for a month. This could be worse. It
affects the whole team and creates nothing but one big
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading Tkachuk might not be as easy as it sounds. Only a
handful of teams could probably afford his salary demands, and
those teams might not necessarily have the kind of players Phoenix
would want in return.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely scenario is a straight up, one-for-one deal, such
as Tkachuk to Philadelphia for left wing and fellow 50-goal scorer
John LeClair. Or possibly Tkachuk to the Flyers for LeClair's
linemate, center Eric Lindros, a rumor that has surfaced before.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Tocchet said he only hopes it doesn't
drastically alter the Coyotes from last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is good enough,'' he said. ``With just a little
tinkering here and there, we would have beat Detroit in the
playoffs. We're pretty close. We're almost there. I just hope we
don't blow it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
