<HEADER>
A7131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHILD-ABUSE-440&AMP;AD     07-01 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-ABUSE-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE ARE HELD IN SEX ABUSE OF CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS and MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a dingy Brooklyn apartment filled with
pornographic videos and magazines, the New York City police
uncovered what they described Wednesday as a group of pedophiles
who repeatedly raped and sodomized their own and one another's
children, even while some of the children were being monitored by
the city's child-welfare agency.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested five adults, most of them members of an
extended family, on charges of abusing four children, two
8-year-old boys and two girls age 13 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   The two adolescent girls and an 8-year-old boy had been
transferred to foster care last fall after child-welfare workers
found them living in the dirty, roach-infested apartment without
any food. But after three weeks in foster care, a family-court
judge sent the girls home, despite the objections of the
child-welfare agency, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And as police investigators tried to unravel the allegations of
incest, rape, sodomy and pedophilia Wednesday, officials from the
city's Administration for Children's Services conceded that they
had been closely monitoring the household for nearly a year but
failed to uncover any sign of sexual abuse, which the police said
had occurred for years and apparently continued until June.
</P>
<P>
   The case once again raised disturbing questions about the city's
monitoring of abused and neglected children under its watch.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say casework has improved since the overhaul of
the troubled child-welfare agency two years ago, and it was unclear
Wednesday whether the family's caseworker could have detected signs
of abuse, assuming she had visited the home as required. But the
horrific allegations of severe sexual abuse renewed concerns over
whether caseworkers are conscientious in making required visits and
can adequately assess risks to vulnerable children.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the caseworker assigned to the household and the
children should have seen each child at least twice a month,
interviewing them individually to determine whether they showed any
signs of mistreatment. It was unclear Wednesday whether the
caseworker made all the required visits. City officials said they
had no hint of the ongoing sexual abuse in the home.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations came to light only when the frightened
8-year-old boy finally described the sexual assaults to a new
foster mother, who reported the allegations to child-welfare
officials on Tuesday. He had been abused in the apartment earlier
in June when he was there on a visit with his father, police
investigators said. Investigators said that the arrests were based
in part on statements made by the suspects.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the police said they were executing a search
warrant at another location where the children may have been
abused. And child-welfare officials said they were investigating
why the two girls were returned to their home from foster care and
whether the caseworker had followed up once they returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the allegations suggest extremely serious sexual
abuse of these children,'' said Nicholas Scoppetta, the
commissioner of the Administration for Children's Services. ``We
have an investigation of all the circumstances of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The case centers on an extended Brooklyn family, including
Daniel Robacker, 40, and his companion, Theresa Fremgen, 35, who
live in the apartment at 232 Linden St., in Bushwick, Brooklyn,
with their two daughters, ages 13 and 14. A close family friend,
Curtis Elam James, also lived there with his 8-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Those three adults were arrested, along with Theresa Fremgen's
brothers, Ezra, 25, and Vincent, 28, who lived nearby. But it
appears that much of the abuse occurred in the apartment itself,
which was also filled with cats, dogs and dozens of hamsters, said
an official who has worked on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Ms. Fremgen and Robacker were both
developmentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the household first came to the attention of
child-welfare workers in July 1997, when someone reported the
family to the state's child-abuse telephone line. Child-welfare
workers reported that they found a filthy house, with animal feces,
and a child with lacerations on the body.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to try to keep the household together by offering
intensive counseling services, and caseworkers monitoring the
family around the clock, starting on Aug. 27 and continuing until
Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   But officials involved in the case said the caseworker finally
ordered the three children put in foster care on Sept. 23 when it
became clear that Ms. Framgen and Robacker were not responding to
the city's help. As part of a routine medical examination, a nurse
asked each child whether he or she had ever been sexually abused.
They said they had not, a child-welfare worker said.
</P>
<P>
   And on Oct. 14, 1997, Family Court Judge Nora Freeman decided to
send the two girls home after the foster-care agency recommended
that they return, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency made the recommendation because the charge of
physical abuse had been discounted, leaving only a charge of
neglect for keeping the children in a filthy house.
</P>
<P>
   Officials working on the investigations said lawyers for the
Administration for Children's Services had urged the judge to keep
the girls in foster care, in part because they were worried about
their parents' mental state. The city, in fact, supposedly banned
such public disagreements in court last year, prohibiting the
private foster-care agency caseworkers from disagreeing with
child-welfare lawyers in open sessions. It was unclear why the
disagreement occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Freeman sided with the agency and sent the girls home.
She declined to comment when reached at home Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
