<HEADER>
A7143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUPER'S-SUPER-635&AMP;     07-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUPER'S-SUPER-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRIGUE AND DEFECTION: A TALE OF 2 CO-OPS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days after writer Joan Didion assumed the
presidency of the board of her prestigious Upper East Side co-op,
she was faced with the first crisis of her administration. The
building's superintendent, Thomas Riordan, announced that he had
been lured away by the Beresford, a larger and even more
prestigious co-op on Central Park West, home of Richard Holbrooke,
nominated as American representative to the United Nations, as well
as Beverly Sills, Tony Randall and, soon, Jerry Seinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't wait until she became president to resign,'' Riordan
said apologetically. ``It just happened that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ms. Didion was described by her husband, the writer
John Gregory Dunne, as too unhappy to come to the phone. ``There's
not a chance in the world that she will talk to you,'' said a
cheerful Dunne, who then assumed the role of Ms. Didion's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a spectacular super,'' said Dunne of Riordan. ``He
cleaned out the staff. He's got handymen who know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, members of the Beresford board responded to their
coup with more diplomatic caution than Holbrooke might have
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to be in a no-comment position at this point,''
said board vice president Mike Baker.
</P>
<P>
   But why? Isn't this an easy issue?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said soberly. ``It isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a peculiar but familiar New York story of ambition,
defection and betrayal, played out in the world of dinner parties
and best-selling books. At the center is the object of everyone's
affection, or affectations, the super super himself, who granted an
interview in his basement office at the East 70th Street
Didion-Dunne co-op last week. He starts the first week of August at
the Beresford.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, 42, seemed like a good guy, organized and just the
right kind of obsessive, with pictures of his four children tacked
onto the bulletin board alongside glossy photos of the co-op's new
roof. Two years ago, he midwifed its installation. ``It is
gorgeous,'' he said proudly, in his Irish lilt.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get to the point. Why is Riordan abandoning Ms. Didion for
the Beresford?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that they offered me huge money,'' Riordan said.
``Money is very, very important, but for me, the Beresford, at this
point of my life, I believe is a career move. It's a bigger
challenge, it's a larger building. It's the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   In the pantheon of New York buildings, the Beresford is indeed
on Mount Olympus. Riordan started in the foothills in 1981, when he
arrived in America as a licensed electrician from County Cork and
got a job mopping floors. He worked as a handyman and a doorman,
too. When his boss told him he might have an aptitude for
superintendent work, Riordan took courses and got licensed. Now he
has an air-pollution-control certificate, a No. 6 oil-burner
license, a standpipe certificate and a sprinkler certificate. He
also got management training.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're like the captain of a ship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Riordan worked his way up to superintendent. He
has been at the 70th Street co-op for nearly a decade. He has a
staff of 28 for 64 units, but at the Beresford will have 50 people
and 193 units. He seemed offended when asked if a threefold
increase in holiday tips affected his decision _ ``It really has
nothing to do with it'' _ and said he learned about the job from a
friend in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan had many opinions about what makes a good
superintendent, but they boil down to a cool head in a crisis and
constant attachment to a beeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could be sitting right here,'' he said, ``and somebody
will say, `There's water pouring out of the elevator shaft.' And
you have to know how to respond to that without running up the
street and calling for help.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The hardest part, he said, is the lack of downtime. ``You're
constantly waiting for that phone call,'' he said. Not long ago in
Detroit, where he was attending a superintendents' association
dinner-dance, he got beeped over breakfast. No hot water at East
70th!
</P>
<P>
   Riordan talked the man on duty through the problem.
``Fortunately,'' he said, ``the boiler just needed to be reset.''
</P>
<P>
   Other qualifications are people skills. ``How do you deal with a
tenant who has just stepped into concrete?'' Riordan asked. (True
story from East 70th.)
</P>
<P>
   The wrong answer is telling the person he has just destroyed the
new sidewalk. The right answer is expressing deep concern over the
ruin of the tenant's shoes, even if you want to laugh. ``But you
can't,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, never tell a reporter the names of people in your
building, or be lured into questions about difficult residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Riordan. ``They're all wonderful people.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue now is whether Riordan will keep the retiring super's
Beresford Wall of Fame, a bulletin board of autographed photographs
of Beresford celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a burning question,'' said resident Jeff Moss, the
creator of Sesame Street's Cookie Monster. ``Will we have to
reapply?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
