<DOCNO> NYT19980701.0619 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-01 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FESTIVAL-DANCE-REVIEW     07-01 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FESTIVAL-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
DANCE REVIEW: WAITING FOR A CHANCE TO TUMBLE  
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ The American Dance Festival loves to take risks,
which is why it keeps attracting dancers and audiences to its
performances on the campus of Duke University here.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, it took a big risk by offering the premiere of
``Triptych Humpty-Dumpty,'' a three-act work choreographed by David
Grenke, a member of the Paul Taylor Dance Company from 1989 to 1996
and one of this year's recipients of the festival's Doris Duke
Awards for New Work. As performed by Grenke's Thingsezisee'm
Dance/Theater at the Reynolds Industries Theater, the work was
sometimes exasperating, often compelling and always peculiar.
</P>
<P>
   Its greatest oddity was the way motionlessness became as
important as movement. For long periods, no one moved at all. And
when people did move, they didn't move much, except for moments
crammed with spasms of activity. But every outburst came to a
sudden stop.
</P>
<P>
   Although Grenke put Humpty Dumpty in his title, and Christopher
Plant's setting included a wall, there were no literal references
to that nursery rhyme character. But there were many instances of
falling.
</P>
<P>
   The taped accompaniment included a musical collage, plus new
music by Alan Lage Terricciano, played by the composer on the
piano. There were also texts by Michel Wilson Danek, Brian Frette
and two of the dancers, Mindy Cooper and Karl Herlinger.
</P>
<P>
   The first act opened with a song about suicide and murder played
while Herlinger and Grenke sat solemnly at a table and video images
by Dennis Diamond projected on the backdrop showed hands repeatedly
shifting a bottle, an ash tray and a hymnal.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Gibbons, Gina Paolillo, Elizabeth Williams and Ms. Cooper
entered, posed for long periods, then fell to the floor and rolled
like tumbleweeds. The text commented on problems of pain, loss and
the difficulties of raising children.
</P>
<P>
   The video images in the second act showed bits of the plastic
foam used to pad packages swirling like a snowstorm. The dancers
stood motionless. Yet they appeared to be expecting something.
Finally, Herlinger, keeping his back to the audience, made tiny
gestures. He scratched his brow and his neck. He raised and lowered
an arm. He crossed himself, as if in church.
</P>
<P>
   Other dancers also started moving. They slowly turned around,
tilted to the side and knelt on the ground. These deliberate
actions gave way to the tumbleweed-like rolls that were the work's
principal choreographic motif.
</P>
<P>
   While scenes of a boxing match were projected in the third act,
dancers hurled themselves at one another and against a wall or just
stood and fidgeted. And, of course, they also rolled about. The
text spoke of helplessness, the unavoidability of pain and the
death of parents.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the production, the long periods of inactivity were
disturbing. One kept wondering if anything would ever happen. When
things did happen, the actions were equally disconcerting, for the
characters now seemed rootless and adrift.
</P>
<P>
   Complete with two intermissions, ``Triptych Humpty-Dumpty''
lasted barely 90 minutes. Since that's less than many movies, one
can argue that the intermissions were unnecessary and the dance
should have proceeded without interruptions. The intermissions kept
breaking the choreographic mood, and instead of being caught up in
Grenke's visions, the audience had to keep returning to them.
</P>
<P>
   But when he successfully cast his spells, Grenke conjured up a
world in which vulnerable people eternally waited, perhaps for
Godot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-98 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
